A0362 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BK-PACERS-HNS &LR;      05-31 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
INDIANAPOLIS _ The Indiana Pacers often have been described as an
effortless bunch, able to put points on the board in the blink of
an eye.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But in the Eastern Conference finals against the New York
Knicks, the Pacers are putting a different spin on the word
effortless.
</P>
<P>
   At least Indiana coach Larry Bird seems to think so.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are a little different,'' Bird said of the Pacers.
``They play awfully well when their backs are against the wall and
they get stirred up a little bit. It seems that when they have an
opportunity to put a team away, they don't do it. It's
disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiana fans expect to see the Indy 500 on Memorial Day weekend,
but despite facing a team that couldn't even field enough healthy
bodies to do full-court drills in practice, the Pacers are bringing
them the Indy .500 _ tied at 2 with the hobbled Knicks _ for
tonight's Game 5 at Conseco Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   And Bird just doesn't get it. When Indiana came to Madison
Square Garden for Games 3 and 4 of the Eastern Conference finals
against the Knicks this past weekend, Bird thought the Pacers would
come home with a 3-1 edge _ if they didn't sweep.
</P>
<P>
   One win in New York, Bird insisted, would put the Knicks, ``in a
world of hurt,'' and go a long way toward propelling the Pacers
toward a long-awaited trip to the NBA Finals. After all, the Knicks
had not only lost the first two games in Indianapolis, but they
also had lost starting center Patrick Ewing to a foot injury.
</P>
<P>
   But the Knicks won Game 3 on Saturday, even though Marcus
Camby's knee gave out after playing just five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   And then Latrell Sprewell, who tortured the Pacers with 32
points in that 98-95 victory, woke up Sunday with a sore left foot.
An MRI exam revealed a fractured fifth metatarsal _ the bone behind
the little toe.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly that bit of bad news for the Knicks would translate
into good news for the Pacers in Monday's game. Nope. The Knicks
instead made a hurtin' call, with Sprewell playing 44 minutes and
Larry Johnson putting the Knicks on his aching back, finishing with
25 points, including a pair of back-breaking 3-pointers in the
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out and played just the opposite of what I thought,''
said Bird of the Pacers' trip to New York. ``It's very frustrating
to me because I've been in that situation many times, and the teams
I played on knew that you could probably put this team in a world
of hurt if you win a ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Pacers are hurting. Psychologically, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of beating up on them and taking the life out of them,
we gave them life,'' said Pacers forward Dale Davis. ``And, you
know, they can take a little life and make a big thing out of it.
They have a history of performing some miracles.''
</P>
<P>
   We'll see tonight if the Knicks can pull another miracle, even
though the Pacers are pointing to their 36-5 regular-season record
at Conseco as a security blanket. And with two of the final three
games at Conseco, the Pacers are confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the Knicks) took care of their home floor, and they got
a lot of credit, and they deserve it,'' said Indiana point guard
Mark Jackson. ``I feel like we're the best team in the NBA on our
home floor, and I'm planning on us holding serve. We played all
year long to have home-court advantage. We don't want to be too
overconfident, because we still have to get the job done, but the
bottom line is that they still have to beat us in our building to
move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Jalen Rose agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because we lose two games, that doesn't mean we're not
determined,'' Rose said. ``We know what it takes to get here. We
just don't know what it's like to get over this hump, and that's
what we're trying to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Rose admitted he can ubderstand if there is a sense of
doubt surrounding the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying that going home is the magic slipper,'' Rose
said. ``I'm saying that we're happy to be going home because we're
the best team on our home floor. We played awful in New York. This
is not a good feeling at this point. I would be lying to say that I
don't feel awful about the way we played these last two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, we can't allow losing two games to snowball
us into losing the entire series. We have to go home and regroup,
look at some tapes and understand the mistakes we made and find a
way to get Game 5. If we get Game 5, we're back in the driver's
seat.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
