<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO'S CONVICTIONS, SWOLLEN LIP CENTER STAGE DURING REPUBLICAN
CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ From the Kostas family restaurant with its $4.99
steak-and-egg special to the Statler Golden Ballroom, with its
$25-a-plate fund-raiser of grilled chicken, wherever Republican
Senate candidate Rick A. Lazio went Tuesday, he persevered to
ignore his swollen lip and mold his message.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's injured upper lip, the result of a fall while marching
in a Memorial Day parade, and his developing campaign platform were
likely foremost on the minds of those who sat with Lazio at Kostas
during breakfast, toasted him with ovations at the Statler during a
luncheon sponsored by Republican women, or glimpsed him at the
Republican Party convention at the Hyatt Regency here. Lazio was
shaking hands and hugging supporters, while noticeably refraining
from kissing.
</P>
<P>
   In the hours before and after his speech accepting the
Republican nomination to run for Senate in New York, Lazio made no
bold pronouncements. Instead, he repeated declarations that ``I
know I need to earn this,'' and that his positions fall in the
``mainstream'' of New Yorkers. But he tried to adapt to the
interests of upstate residents and even tried the personal touch,
with mixed results.
</P>
<P>
   At Kostas, he sat down with people like Lou Selva, who said he
owns a carpet store and is worried about the flight of businesses
and young people from the region. Lazio suggested Selva speak at a
school as a role model, advice Selva at first seemed to accept but
later told reporters he had trouble swallowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would he want me to speak at a school? What can I tell the
kids?'' said Selva, a Democrat. Still, Selva said, Lazio impressed
him and probably earned his vote for the simple fact that he did
not see Hillary Rodham Clinton, the Democratic candidate for
Senate, as a New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the 11 residents who met with Lazio at the restaurant
complained about ``brain drain'' from upstate to downstate and to
other parts of the country. Two hours later, Lazio stood on a
foot-high platform at the center of the Hyatt ballroom and told the
crowd of 700 people: ``We don't want to export any of our children
from New York state. We want them here.''
</P>
<P>
   The day had its light moments. Lazio's aides cringed both at
morning newspaper photos of Lazio on hands and knees after his
fall, and at reporters' and conventioneers' puns about a
``stumbling campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio took his injury in stride publicly, refining jokes he
tried out in appearances after the incident. Soaking in applause at
the luncheon, Lazio said, ``If you keep giving me a response like
that it's going to pop out my stitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Some, however, worried privately that the mishap reflected a
boyish, over-eager 42-year-old campaigner, a contrast to the
problem many bemoaned months ago, that the then-presumptive
nominee, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, did not have his heart in the
race.
</P>
<P>
   Many people voiced concern about Giuliani's health, but an
upbeat mood prevailed at the convention, now that Republicans had
finally settled on a nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani did not attend, having said that he did not want to
steal Lazio's limelight. But Giuliani remained on the minds of
many, who praised for civic improvements, but lamented his
reputation for divisiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Brown, president of the New York State Black Republicans
Council, acknowledged Giuliani's trouble attracting support among
black and Hispanic New Yorkers after a series of police shootings
and brutality allegations involving young black men. That is not
the case, Brown said, with Lazio, who he said was eager to attend
meetings with black Republicans and has already campaigned in
predominantly Hispanic East Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Rick Lazio is going to be Hillary Clinton's worst
nightmare,'' Brown said, predicting Lazio would ``destroy the
myth'' that blacks and Hispanics would automatically favor Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Those who are energized by Lazio's candidacy find themselves
sorting through his positions and raising questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not as abrasive and seems more flexible than Mayor
Giuliani,'' said Glory Ann Cranston, a Buffalo legal secretary who
attended the luncheon for Lazio, though she said she doubted she
would vote for him. ``He's energetic, he's great, but he's
pro-choice.'' Cranston said she would wait to see if an
anti-abortion candidate from another party emerged before deciding
what to do.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has said he favors abortion rights, but opposes public
financing of abortions, and favors a ban on late-term abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has charmed many here with moderate positions, even those
from traditionally conservative areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's more conservative than Hillary,'' said Anthony G.
Scannapieco Jr., the Putnam County Republican chairman, after
listening to Lazio outline his positions in his acceptance speech
this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In the evening, shortly after his speech, Lazio beamed as
fireworks erupted around his campaign bus, the Mainstream Express,
which he unveiled at a ball park downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``You people have enthusiasm that's contagious and it's going to
spread throughout this state,'' Lazio told a cheering audience at
the stadium. ``This is going to be a grass-roots campaign that
touches every New Yorker. We're going to be in every county, in
every community, in every neighborhood, on every street. We're
going to go door to door if we have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio climbed aboard and the bus drove off a private reception,
and then was scheduled to travel onto Syracuse to spend the night
before beginning a three-day cross-state tour.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
