<SLUG> BC-TICKETS--ONLINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANT TICKETMASTER SWALLOWS TICKETWEB  &HT;     BY TODD WALLACK
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ TicketMaster Online City Search, the gorilla of
online ticket sales, has bought TicketWeb, a smaller Berkeley rival
founded to give consumers a cheaper alternative for tickets to
concerts and other shows.
<P>
   The $35 million stock deal, announced Tuesday, already has
sparked fears that Bay Area consumers could be forced to pay
stiffer service fees for tickets to events at dozens of local
venues.
</P>
<P>
   TicketWeb, which works with partners ranging from the San
Francisco Symphony to Bottom of the Hill, an alternative rock club
in Potrero Hill, typically charges about $2 to $3 extra per ticket.
By contrast, TicketMaster charges an average of $6.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reputation is that TicketMaster's fees are very high,
which makes us concerned,'' said Jay Finney, marketing director for
the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art, which sells between 4 and 5
percent of its tickets online. ``My hope is they do not institute
the same policy of hefty commissions.''
</P>
<P>
   But company executives denied they had any plans to boost
TicketWeb's fees.
</P>
<P>
   TicketMaster Chairman Charles Conn said the companies target
different markets and, therefore, have different costs.
</P>
<P>
   TicketWeb, for instance, typically handles tickets for museums
and small independent concerts, and usually can handle all the
transactions online.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Pasadena's TicketMaster handles bigger events for
stars like Bruce Springstein and has to be able to handle waves of
telephone calls and purchases at physical ticket counters. And for
every ticket sold, Conn said the company has to handle another 10
inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   TicketWeb has about 700 venues worldwide, compared with 4,000
for TicketMaster, including high-profile names such as the Louvre
and Six Flags. But TicketWeb is especially well known in the Bay
Area, where it usually has about 50 clients at any one time and as
many as 200 total.
</P>
<P>
   The firm had sales of about $2.5 million last year, but hopes to
more than double that to $6 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   TicketWeb co-founder and Chief Executive Officer Andrew Dreskin
insisted the deal will give it the best of both worlds. He said
TicketMaster has promised to keep the company's current workforce
and name but will help it grow through access to TicketMaster's
larger sales force and Internet presence.
</P>
<P>
   Dreskin said he hopes consumers will keep an ``open mind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The brand will survive, the mission will survive, the people
will survive and the fee structure will survive,'' Dreskin said,
who owned about 20 percent of the firm. Dreskin pocketed about $7
million in the deal and co-founder Rick Tyler earned $14 million.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Benetti, a co-owner of Bottom of the Hill, said he was
initially worried when he heard about the deal. Bottom of the Hill
was TicketWeb's first customer and routinely sells out entire
concerts online.
</P>
<P>
   But Benetti said he thought TicketMaster ``comes across as a
bigger, more corporate name with much deeper fees.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Benetti said Dreskin assured him that TicketWeb would
continue as an independent business. ``I am confident that things
will remain fine,'' Benetti said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
