<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETRADE--EXPANDING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-TRADE PLANS VIRTUAL EXPANSION  &HT;     BY SAM ZUCKERMAN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
In a bid to expand its business with consumers who want help with
their investments, online broker E-Trade Group said Tuesday that it
is joining forces with accounting and consulting giant Ernst &AMP;
Young to form a financial advisory service.
<P>
   The two companies are investing $25 million each to form the
still-unnamed venture, which is set to open by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   The new company will be E-Trade's response to a dilemma facing
all electronic brokerages _ how to grow beyond those clients who
are comfortable making their own investment choices to take in the
much-larger universe of people seeking financial advice.
</P>
<P>
   Most online brokers offer a variety of Web-based tools to help
customers pick individual investments and put together a portfolio
appropriate for their circumstances and risk tolerance. Such
companies as Charles Schwab Corp. and Fidelity Investments have
gone one step further by referring clients to independent financial
advisers.
</P>
<P>
   In characteristic fashion, Menlo Park's E-Trade, the No. 2
online broker, is opting for a high-tech approach that substitutes
electronic wizardry for human interaction. Using an interactive
program developed by Ernst &AMP; Young, the new venture will walk
clients through what in effect will be virtual financial planning
sessions in exchange for a fee that hasn't yet been determined.
</P>
<P>
   The program will ``reproduce the experience of meeting with a
personal financial adviser face-to-face,'' said Ernst &AMP; Young Vice
Chairwoman Beth Brooke in a briefing.
</P>
<P>
   In case that is not enough, E-Trade customers willing to pay a
higher fee can arrange to meet with one of Ernst &AMP; Young's nearly
1,000 financial planners.
</P>
<P>
   There are many online financial advisory services, but few offer
such a combination of electronic and human advice.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade already has a relationship with one such online advisory
service, DirectAdvice.com. Officials of the online brokerage said
they are abandoning DirectAdvice because it doesn't have enough
advisers on staff who can step in when customers want human
contact.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade's foray into investment advice is part of its larger
transformation from an electronic stock trader to an Internet-based
provider of a broad array of brokerage, banking and other financial
services.
</P>
<P>
   The company's goal is to persuade customers to entrust it with
their assets, not just use it as a cheap way to trade stocks. It
badly lags in that race. Its 2.6 million customers kept $65 billion
in assets with the company at the end of March. Schwab's 6.9
million clients had some $823 billion deposited with the firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``For E-Trade to gain a greater share of consumers' assets, they
need a way to give customers advice,'' said Robertson Stephens
analyst Scott Appleby. ``This is a low-cost way to do it.``
</P>
<P>
   Dispensing advice electronically is consistent with other steps
E-Trade has taken to broaden its appeal.
</P>
<P>
   For example, responding to criticism that it lacked branches,
E-Trade earlier this year said it would install hundreds of kiosks
in widely scattered locations around the country where customers
could carry out routine banking transactions.
</P>
<P>
   In every case, E-Trade has opted for an automated, electronic
approach, which keeps costs down. Whether customers will accept
such alternatives remains to be seen, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
