</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW--COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU'RE NEVER TOO YOUNG FOR GOOD IDEAS 
 &HT;     BY PETER SINTON
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Dot-com entrepreneurs don't have to wait for high school or college
to get started.
<P>
   Take Ben Casnocha, for example. The sixth-grader at Town School
for Boys in San Francisco came up with an idea for an online
service where local residents could complain about issues, like
tardy garbage pickup, and have their problems directed to the right
authorities for resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Casnocha and nine of his classmates have registered the domain
name Complainandresolve.com and are developing the site as part of
an elective technology course taught by teachers Anthony More and
Kirk Lorie.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is complaining more than ever now, so we feel this is
the prime time to launch,'' says Ben, who received an iMac for his
12th birthday two months ago and does some Macintosh repairs in his
free time.
</P>
<P>
   He sees Complainandresolve.com as a useful ``one-stop site''
akin to KGO's ``Seven on Your Side'' TV reports, where citizens can
post their problems and get them resolved.
</P>
<P>
   The students are using Town School's server and are building the
service with various Web site development tools. Ben and his team
used Register.com to reserve their domain name. They recommend
BBEdit Lite for writing code and use Fireworks 3 to create some
flair such as ``Java script rollovers and navigation bars.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many other dot-com startups, Ben and classmates are not
sure how their site might make money. The main impetus for the
project _ besides learning, of course _ was ``to give something
back to the Bay Area,'' says Ben, who lives in Cole Valley and is
the son of an attorney. But, he adds, ``As we kids become smarter
and more intelligent with computers, we feel like we can turn this
into a profitable business.''
</P>
<P>
   STUDENT PRIZES: Besides Phi Beta Kappa, magna and summa cum
laude and other academic awards, college students these days also
are seeking financial prizes. They want lucre as well as lux.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the latest examples, more than 600 college teams
representing more than 2,000 student entrepreneurs entered the
first National Student Business Plan Competition sponsored by
Garage.com.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, four doctoral students at the University of
California at San Francisco won the $150,000 grand prize for their
Quicksilver Genomics. Their post-genomic drug development venture
would create technology to let pharmaceutical, biotechnology and
academic researchers rapidly discover patentable compounds from
unclassified gene sequences.
</P>
<P>
   During Memorial Day weekend, team members Rey Banatao, Jose
Haresco, Sean Mooney and Sandra Waugh went to Lake Tahoe to
celebrate and deliberate what to do next. Do they each take their
$37,500 and buy new computers and pay off loans? Do they pool the
winnings and pursue their venture, perhaps even dropping out of
graduate school or taking a leave of absence?
</P>
<P>
   Banatao says it is a nice problem to have. The Quicksilver team
also entered the University of California at Berkeley Business Plan
competition that last month awarded $70,000 in cash and prizes.
That contest, in its second year, attracted 182 teams, but
Quicksilver didn't make the cut to the final eight.
</P>
<P>
   Quicksilver was not the only winner in the contest sponsored by
Garage.com, the Palo Alto online venture capital company, and other
backers such as Charles Schwab and Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   Kwaish, a Stanford University team helping businesses leverage
the power of wireless handheld devices, won $50,000. So did
co-first prize winner KnowHow, a University of California at Irvine
team that is developing a smart notification service that
prioritizes e-mail and other messages by their importance.
</P>
<P>
   Two teams won $25,000 second-place prizes: RedFolio.com, a
Purdue University team that is developing artificial intelligence
engineering software; and Fluid Bandwidth, a University of Texas at
Austin team developing networking solutions for midsize companies.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH COURSES: UC Berkeley Extension is offering six crash
courses in ``Entrepreneurship and Innovation'' from July 10 to
August 2. They range in price from $215 to $795 and subjects
include crafting the e-business model, Internet startups _ legal
issues, how to be your own financial planner, entrepreneurship and
innovation, Web commerce post-launch challenges and solutions, and
successful Internet marketing. For more information, check out &LR; 
www.unex.berkeley.edu &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Send comments, tip and questions to
entrepreneurs &LR; sfgate.com
</P>
