<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH--COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES GOING PUBLIC WILL ENDURE AN IPO DROUGHT THIS SUMMER  &HT;     BY KATHLEEN PENDER
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Somebody call Roto Rooter!
<P>
   The IPO pipeline is getting seriously backed up, with only a
handful of deals trickling out, and yesterday's market rally is not
expected to do much to unclog it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be a long dry summer,'' says Steve Bishop of RS
Investment Management. ``It's going to take a few weeks (of
consistent gains) before we get things going.''
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 400 deals in registration, a record number,
according to Jeff Hirschkorn, senior market analyst with IPO.com.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are three high-profile Bay Area companies that are
having a bit of trouble with their offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Handspring, which makes the popular Visor electronic
organizer and was started by the people who developed the Palm,
scaled back its planned offering for the second time. The company
now hopes to sell 10 million shares at $17 to $19, down from its
previous offering range of $19 to $21.
</P>
<P>
   When Handspring (HAND) filed for its IPO on March 31, it hoped
to raise as much as $300 million. That was cut to $220 million
earlier this month. The current plan would raise $180 million and
value the company at about $2.25 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Handspring is falling in sympathy with Palm, which has dropped
to $24 from a high of $95, reached shortly after it went public
March 1 at $38 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Handspring, ONI Systems, a San Jose maker of fiber-optic
gear, enlarged its offering, but then the deal mysteriously drifted
into limbo land.
</P>
<P>
   After New Focus, another optical networking company, pulled off
a successful IPO on May 17, ONI raised its offering range to $21 to
$23 per share for 8 million shares, up from $14 to $16.
</P>
<P>
   But on May 22, the company (ONIS) delayed the offer for a day,
then postponed it again. Some news reports said it would debut
yesterday, but as of last night it still hadn't been priced.
</P>
<P>
   One source in the investment community heard the deal was hung
up by ``minor problems'' the Securities and Exchange Commission had
with the deal. Another source heard the SEC was concerned with the
company's compensation package.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can't get it worked up by the end of this week,
they're going to have to tell institutional investors what's going
on,'' Hirschkorn says.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, TheStreet.com reported that Williams Communications,
ONI's biggest customer, and Williams Chief Technology Officer
Matthew Bross &UR;  &LR; owned options in ONI that together would be worth
about $40 million after an IPO.
</P>
<P>
   Though legal and apparently common in the fiber-optics world,
the story questioned whether the arrangement would color Williams'
product-buying decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ONI did not return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   That brings us to CrossWorlds Software (CWLD), the Burlingame
company that gained national attention when its former CEO, Katrina
Garnett, appeared in ads for the company in a low-cut black dress.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of PENDER31 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  CrossWorlds was scheduled to go public Friday but postponed it
until this week, Hirschkorn said.
</P>
<P>
   The firm, which makes software for integrating business software
from multiple vendors, was the subject of several news analyses
over the weekend that questioned whether it is lagging competitors
such as Tibco Software, Vitria and Active Software, which all had
the good fortune to go public before tech stocks went kerblooey.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschkorn says CrossWorlds ``has some good clients including
Siemens and US West. And it's developing partnerships with IBM and
SAP.''
</P>
<P>
   He expects the IPO ``will have an initial pop. If ONI doesn't
get done, I expect this to be the deal of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER SLUMP REDUX: In a column Friday on the summer stock
slump, I ran a chart showing what would have happened if you
followed a seasonal strategy for investing in tech stocks between
1979 and 1999. That prompted an e-mail from one enterprising reader
who figured out what would have happened under a buy-and-hold
scenario.
</P>
<P>
   The chart, from Ned Davis Research, set up two scenarios:
</P>
<P>
   In the first, an investor puts $10,000 in a group of tech stocks
on May 1 of each year and sells on October 31. The investor does
nothing during the intervening six months. On May 1 of the next
year, he reinvests the $10,000, plus accumulated profits (or minus
any losses), in the index for another six months, then sells again.
</P>
<P>
   The second scenario is identical except the investor buys
November 1 of each year and sells April 30.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the 20 years, the investor would have $10,921 if
he owned stocks between May and October of each year, compared with
$109,390 if he owned from November through April.
</P>
<P>
   E-mailer Craig Willms responded: ``I took the data from the
chart, pasted it in Excel, and ran the calculation of what would
have happened if the investor were to have just left the money in
the stock, rather than attempting to time the market. I came out
with $119,579 as the end result.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might have been wrong in my calculations. However, if I was
correct, this seems like the better strategy, especially when taxes
are included. I realize that leaves out the obvious of being able
to place the money in other investments during that time.''
</P>
<P>
   I checked Craig's buy-and-hold number with Larry Winer from Ned
Davis Research, who came up with a number that was quite close:
$109,430.
</P>
<P>
   However, Winer added, ``if one switched into commercial paper
during the weak seasonal period (May to October) one would have
ended up with a total profit of $111,882.
</P>
<P>
   ``Granted this is not much of a gain over the buy-and-hold
numbers, and does not take into account the cost of making the
trades or tax liability. However, once again, I must stress that we
do not recommend someone use this (seasonal switching) strategy for
trading. It is meant to be used for perspective to show that most
of the gains ... have come from the seasonally strong periods.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
