<HEADER>
A0370 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     05-31 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS' MISTAKES ARE COSTLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND -- The Angels signed shortstop Kevin Stocker Tuesday,
apparently because Ozzie Smith was not available.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have fallen into a rut defensively the past couple of
weeks, and it couldn't have been more evident than in their 6-1
loss to the Cleveland Indians Tuesday night before 42,910 at Jacobs
Field.
</P>
<P>
   They made three errors in the game -- two by shortstop Benji
Gil, who figures to lose his starting job to Stocker by the end of
the week. Third baseman Troy Glaus is in no danger of losing his
job, but he also made a costly error in the game and wasn't happy
to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think we enjoy making errors?'' Glaus said. ``You get
pissed. You get (expletive) pissed. If we didn't think we could
make every play, we shouldn't be out there. I made an error. You
saw it, I saw it, everybody saw it. I made an error I shouldn't
have made.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Mike Scioscia saw it, but wasn't so hard on
Glaus.
</P>
<P>
   ``He takes so much pride in his defense, that's why he's such a
tremendous ballplayer,'' Scioscia said. ``He is one of the premier
third baseman in the game and he'll continue to improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a passion for the game; he has a burning desire to
succeed and he will. But you have to be careful with Troy to make
sure his emotion doesn't turn to frustration. He expects a lot from
himself both in the field and at bat. When he doesn't meet that
level, we have to make sure it doesn't become a situation of
frustration.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Glaus' 13 errors this season (tied with Gil for the most on
the club), eight have come in the past 15 games. But Scioscia wants
Glaus and all his players to move forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be errors made,'' Scioscia said. ``These
guys are going to make an error that will lose a ballgame. It's
what you do in the next one, how you turn the page. It's not a good
feeling when you let the ballclub down, but it's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Scott Schoeneweis (5-3) easily could have become
frustrated by the game's turn of events. But he pitched well after
the Indians scored three unearned runs in the pivotal second
inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians had a runner at first with one out in the inning
when Alex Ramirez hit a grounder to Gil at shortstop that should
have been a double play. Instead, Gil booted it for an error.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis got another potential double-play ball when Richie
Sexon grounded to Glaus at third. But Glaus' throw to second
baseman Keith Luuloa sailed wide right and went towards the
right-field corner, allowing both baserunners to score and Sexson
to reach third.
</P>
<P>
   Sexson scored on Sandy Alomar's single to give the Indians three
unearned runs in the inning and set the tone for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I was a strikeout pitcher and could strike guys out in
that situation,'' Schoeneweis said. ``Unfortunately I don't throw
95, so I just try to get another ground ball. ... I just wish I
could pick up my teammates a little better. They pick me up all the
time, I'd like to return the favor. They bailed me out by scoring a
lot of runs when I gave up runs. When something like (the errors)
happen, it's my job to put zeroes up there and I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Gil made a throwing error later in the game, giving the Angels
48 this season, second worst in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we've paid a lot of attention to,'' Scioscia
said of the defense, which has gradually slipped from among the
best in the league to among the worst. ``Obviously it's something
we need to tighten up. A lot of the errors have been on routine
plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to make errors, you just can't make 'em the way
we have the last couple of weeks. We'll be all right, we'll clean
that up.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, even perfect defense might not have made a different
Tuesday because Indians starter Dave Burba (5-1) pitched well. He
gave up one run and six hits in seven innings, the only run scoring
when Bengie Molina tripled home Garret Anderson in the fourth
inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
