<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0372 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-HKN-STARS-DEVILS-HNS &LR;      05-31 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-DEVILS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT KAISER  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ This isn't how the Dallas Stars wanted to
begin their defense of the Stanley Cup.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seemingly a step slow all night, the Stars were handed a 7-3
whipping by the New Jersey Devils in Game 1 of the Stanley Cup
Finals before a raucous 19,040 at Continental Airlines Arena on
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils' kid line of Petr Sykora, Jason Arnott and Patrik
Elias combined for 11 points as they outdueled the Stars' top line
that features Mike Modano and Brett Hull. Hull has more playoff
goals (86) and Modano more playoff points (98) than the combined
age (72) of the Devils' young bloods, but experience was no help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they were dominant, but they moved the puck
well and skated as well as I've seen them all year,'' Devils coach
Larry Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Stars goalie Ed Belfour, who allowed only 13 goals in seven
games in the Western Conference finals against Colorado, was lit up
for six goals on only 18 shots before being pulled for former Aero
Manny Fernandez with 16:58 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my decision to pull him,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock
said. ``He hasn't had too many nights like that.''
</P>
<P>
   On top of Belfour's misery, captain and top defenseman Derian
Hatcher suffered a hyperextended knee midway through the third
period and didn't return. Hatcher, who led the Stars with five
hits, provided the only consistent physical presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's minor,'' Hitchcock said of Hatcher's injury. ``I think
he'll be a player in Game 2.''
</P>
<P>
   The only positive the Stars might take from this embarrassment
is they are in familiar territory. The defending champs also lost
Game 1 of the Stanley Cup Finals to Buffalo last year, but a big
difference is they played Game 2 at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``For whatever reason we've played games like this before, but
the difference between 7-3 and 4-3 was Belfour,'' Hitchcock said.
``This puts pressure on us, but we know we'll play better.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock also might have to consider what defensive tandem he
puts on the ice against the Devils' kid line as Darryl Sydor and
Sergei Zubov were victimized three times. Sydor and Zubov were on
the ice for the Devils' first five goals overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole group really struggled with their quickness,''
Hitchcock said. ``We haven't seen that kind of quickness from three
lines like that all year, and we made a lot of mistakes because of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils allowed only one shot in the first 10 minutes and
jumped out to a 1-0 lead at 7:22 of the first period. Elias started
the play as he skated behind the net and tried a wraparound Belfour
stopped, but Sykora picked up the rebound and dropped a
behind-the-back pass to Arnott, who had beaten Joe Nieuwendyk to
the front of the goal and deflected the puck in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just did a little cycle, and we kind of know where each
other is,'' Arnott said.
</P>
<P>
   Sydor tied the game at 13:13 on a slap shot from the top of the
left circle. Mike Keane did the dirty work as he fought for
possession of the puck behind the net and fed Jere Lehtinen, who
slipped the puck back for Sydor's one-timer that beat a screened
Martin Brodeur.
</P>
<P>
   The turning point of the game came midway through the second
period after Ken Daneyko had given the Devils a 2-1 lead. Modano
streaked down the left side and fired a rocket on Brodeur, who gave
up the rebound in front of the goal. Hull was right there, but
Brodeur robbed him with a sparkling glove save while on his back.
Seconds later, Sykora scored off a behind-the-back pass from Elias
to make it 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game really swung there,'' Hitchcock said. ``Brodeur made
a great save on Hull, and that play behind the net (by Elias) was a
great one.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
