<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOG-FEE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LEGISLATURE OKS SMOG FEE REFUND _ DAVIS TO SIGN  &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ After months of wrangling, the Legislature sent two
bills to the governor's desk Tuesday that will refund the $300 smog
impact fee to residents who moved into the state.
</P>
<P>
   About 1.7 million Californians over the past decade paid the fee
when they moved here and registered their vehicles. But a state
appeals court ruled it unconstitutional last year, and Gov. Gray
Davis said he would refund the money.
</P>
<P>
   Despite agreement in the Legislature that the money should be
refunded, disputes about details have kept the bills stalled in
committees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four months after a meeting of the minds on this issue, we are
finally returning the money we had no legal right to take in first
place,'' Assemblyman Tom McClintock, R-Northridge, said during
debate on one of the bills last week.
</P>
<P>
   McClintock had originally sponsored a bill to refund the money,
but it was killed and the task divided into two bills by Democratic
lawmakers in tough re-election battles, Sen. Betty Karnette and
Assemblyman Alan Lowenthal, both of Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has said he will sign the bills and put $650 million in
his budget to pay for the refund.
</P>
<P>
   Once he does, anyone who has paid the $300 fee can expect to
receive notice that it will be refunded.
</P>
<P>
   The bills call for the checks to be issued by the Department of
Motor Vehicles, a technicality that allows Davis to reap the
publicity of signing the checks if he chooses. State checks are
usually signed by Davis' rival, state Controller Kathleen Connell.
</P>
<P>
   McClintock warned that the state is wasting more money every day
of delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition to the moral delay, we are losing $14.5 million in
interest,'' he said.''
</P>
<P>
   Several lawmakers warned against making similar errors in the
weeks ahead. When the smog impact fee was passed at the end of a
legislative session more than 10 years ago, the Legislature's own
lawyer warned that it was illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we think about voting on legislation over the next week,
let's make sure that we don't do another dumb mistake like the bill
in 1990 _ one that takes 10 years to undo,'' said Assemblyman Bill
Leonard, R-Rancho Cucamonga.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly bill passed 79 to 0, and the Senate bill passed 38
to 0.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 0038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0375 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-ALASKA-AIRLINES-SFCHR     05-31 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-AIRLINES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 2 ALASKA AIRLINES PILOTS FACE DISMISSALS OVER SAFETY  &HT;     By HENRY K. LEE 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alaska Airlines said Tuesday that it plans to fire two pilots
for continuing a flight from Portland, Ore., to San Jose in March
with oxygen masks deployed after they failed to pressurize the
Boeing 737 jet.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots jeopardized the lives of passengers and should have
turned back to Portland when the problem began only 30 minutes into
the flight, an airline safety expert said.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Michael Alan Reese, 56, of Long Beach, Calif., and First
Officer Vincent Emile Danet, 38, of San Diego were told of the
airline's ``intent to terminate'' them at a hearing that capped an
extensive airline investigation, Alaska officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The action will not be made final for 30 to 45 days under a
collective bargaining agreement between the airline and the pilots'
union, the Air Line Pilots Association.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration also is investigating
whether the pilots, who could not be reached for comment Tuesday,
should have their licenses suspended.
</P>
<P>
   When they took off from Portland, the pilots allegedly failed to
activate cockpit switches to pressurize the plane.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Wallin, 49, a man from Portland, Ore., who was on the
flight, said the first sign of something wrong came just a
half-hour into the 90-minute trip. He said his ears popped and the
oxygen masks then came down.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a collective gasp in the plane,'' Wallin recalled
Tuesday. ``I thought that was my last day, and I think that
sentiment was shared by just about everyone for awhile.''
</P>
<P>
   An aviation expert said Tuesday that while forgetting to
pressurize the plane ``does happen,'' the pilots made a far greater
mistake _ and jeopardized passenger safety _ by continuing to San
Jose, because half of the passengers' oxygen canisters were empty
by the end of the flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never run into that before,'' Bill Waldock, a professor
at Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University in Prescott, Ariz., said of
the pilots' decision to continue. ``If there's no oxygen in there,
you might do OK with somebody that's in good health. But if you
have people with heart or other health problems to begin with, you
could kill them.''
</P>
<P>
   Reese and Danet have been on paid administrative leave since the
incident, the latest in a spate of problems that have plagued the
Seattle-based airline this year, beginning with the January crash
of Flight 261 off the Southern California coast, which killed all
88 people aboard. The crash investigation has focused on mechanical
problems with the airplane's stabilizer.
</P>
<P>
   According to the airline, Flight 506 left Portland at 7:30 a.m.
on March 25 with five crew members and 92 passengers _ including an
infant riding on an adult's lap and former Oregon Gov. Neil
Goldschmidt cq  &LR; _ aboard a new Boeing 737-700.
</P>
<P>
   As the plane headed south, ``somewhere between 10,000 and 14,000
feet, horns sounded in the cockpit,'' Alaska officials said,
without elaborating on the plane's location. At 14,000 feet,
emergency oxygen masks automatically dropped from the ceiling, and
passengers were told to put them on.
</P>
<P>
   After descending to 10,000 feet to pressurize the cabin, the
pilots decided to continue to San Jose at a 41,000-foot cruising
altitude despite requests by flight attendants to return to
Portland, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The airplane landed in San Jose without incident, said Alaska
spokesman Greg Witter. ``I understand some passengers were somewhat
upset by the situation, but I don't believe anyone needed to be
hospitalized,'' Witter said.
</P>
<P>
   The plane then was flown without passengers to Alaska's Seattle
maintenance facility to replenish the oxygen system.
</P>
<P>
   The incident came two months after the crash of Flight 261, amid
ongoing investigations into allegations that Alaska mechanics
falsified safety records.
</P>
<P>
   Allegations by John Liotine, 37, of Pittsburg, Calif., who
formerly worked as a lead mechanic at the airline's Oakland
facility, helped spark in 1998 a federal grand jury investigation
of airline records that earlier this month grew to include the
Flight 261 jet, an MD-80.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, John Young, a mechanic in Seattle, was placed on
leave after speaking to the media about maintenance problems. He is
expected to return to work Friday, Witter said. Both mechanics were
placed on leave to avoid disruptions in the workplace, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
