<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WOMEN DRIVERS, MEN DRIVERS  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Two women drove in the Indy 500 Monday, a
historical first.
</P>
<P>
   On lap 74 the women collided, knocking them both out of the
race.
</P>
<P>
   So naturally all the funny guys are calling and sending e-mails
about how the two women drivers were probably putting on makeup or
talking on cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody mentions the accident-free 73 laps. Or the fact that race
drivers have become such rich, pampered multimedia stars that the
men are just as likely as the women to be putting on makeup while
driving.
</P>
<P>
   Some stereotypes are true, but I'm not sure which would be
worse: Having your car get nudged over the railing of the Bay
Bridge by a woman driver putting on makeup, or by a man driver
putting on his game face _ bringing his hostility and
aggressiveness to a boil to prepare for his day of being a guy.
</P>
<P>
   THAT GIANT Coke bottle at Pac Bell Park, it turns out, is a
metaphor.
</P>
<P>
   The big bottle is empty, and so were the Coke machines at the
Fan Center under the Big Bottle. Gerald White says the machines ran
out Saturday and stayed dry Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of kids paying $1 for a Coke in the Fan Center, they
had to go to a regular snack stand and pay $3. Why nobody thought
to transfer some of the sacred Cola to the Fan Center is anybody's
guess.
</P>
<P>
   SOMETIMES I'M right, and when that happens it's important to
point it out.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of e-mail has arrived on a recent reference here to the
bandito in ``Treasure of the Sierra Madre'' saying something about
``any stinking badges.''
</P>
<P>
   Readers pointed out that the bandito said, ``We don't need no
stinking badges.''
</P>
<P>
   I would like to mention that most people who write to inform me
of an error do so with utmost courtesy. Like, ``I love your column,
it is the high point of my day, indeed your prose makes my life
worth living. However, I feel it is important to let you know that
Thomas Jefferson was never a Heisman Trophy winner.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is with the utmost courtesy that I point out that
sometimes famous movie lines become famous and oft-quoted even
though they were never uttered in the movie. In ``Treasure,'' here
is the exact exchange between Humphrey Bogart and the bandito:
</P>
<P>
   Bandito: ``Oiga (listen), senor, we are the federales. You know,
the mounted police.''
</P>
<P>
   Bogie: ``If you're the police, where are your badges?''
</P>
<P>
   Bandito: ``Badges? We ain't got no badges. We don't need no
badges. I don't have to show you any stinking badges.''
</P>
<P>
   After a couple of grammatical mistakes, the bandito caught
himself and got back to his proper English, and history should not
forget that.
</P>
<P>
   BAD HOLIDAY HERE. And as a reader service, consider that if you
order a Gardenburger at an amusement park near closing time, and
the counter kid says, ``Wow, first one of the day,'' that while
that item was sitting around all day waiting for Mr. Nutrition, it
may have been taking on microorganisms until it looked like an
overbooked hayride.
</P>
<P>
   HOW DO you build a competitive baseball team in a ``small''
market like San Francisco?
</P>
<P>
   Doug Wilkins heard Giants' General Manager Brian Sabean, on
KNBR's Ralph &AMP; Tom show, say that the Giants are ``trying to strike
a delicate medium.''
</P>
<P>
   No word of protest yet from the Fortune Teller's Union.
</P>
<P>
   THIS COLUMN is on the record as being in support of cell phone
use in public, as long as certain rules are followed.
</P>
<P>
   No bellowing or theatrical gesturing. No cell conversations
during movies or plays, at church, or during major surgery (this
goes for doctor  &UR; and  &LR; patient).
</P>
<P>
   Add one more cell no-no: Jenefer Bickers heard from a friend who
was on a romantic gondola ride in Venice when the gondolier took a
cell phone call and held an extended conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, woe is mio.
</P>
<P>
   WHO'S GOT TIME for culture these days?
</P>
<P>
   But Carroll Collins and his wife were in Albuquerque and saw a
listing for a play that sounds perfect for the busy dot.commer
hoping to soak up lotsa culture pronto: ``Cat on a Streetcar Named
Iguana.''
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER BIGGIE for Jerry Springer. The Chronicle's TV listings
capsulized Tuesday's Jerry: ``A wife says she wants to break a
world record by sleeping with 2,000 men in one day.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk is cheap, but seldom  &UR; this  &LR; cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Wonder if Mr. 2,000 will receive a special gift, other than,
obviously, the pride.
</P>
<P>
   And will hubby get in on the, uh, festivities?
</P>
<P>
   Alice Barnes comments, ``I bet she won't be tired after getting
all that sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   TODAY'S STUMPER: If a serial ax murderer sneezes, should you say
``Bless you?''
</P>
</TEXT>
