<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACBELL-TAXBREAK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PACIFIC BELL WILL GET $13 MILLION TAX BREAK  &HT;     By GREG LUCAS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Democratic state Controller Kathleen Connell cast
the deciding vote Tuesday to give Pacific Bell a $13 million break
on the phone giant's property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The move by the state Board of Equalization means less property
tax revenues for public schools and cities and counties where the
company has facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you give this type of reduction, there is also a
reduction in service for schools and fire and police protection in
parts of the state where this company has a presence,'' said Johan
Klehs, a board member opposing the lower valuation for Pacific
Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``A utility shouldn't be getting a break when residential
property owners aren't getting a similar one,'' Klehs said.
</P>
<P>
   Connell said she voted in favor of the tax break because
deregulation of the telephone industry requires the board to change
its way of assessing Pacific Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The previous way of calculating value was done in a regulated
environment. Today, the industry is deregulated, and so the old way
of assessing value is no longer valid,'' Connell said.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Bell's tax boon came as part of the board's annual
determination of the value of each utility operating in California.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is what factors the board should consider in
calculating value.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 10 years, that formula has been set by a court
settlement that expired last year.
</P>
<P>
   Now the board can use whatever formula it chooses to set the
values of Pacific Bell, Pacific Gas and Electric Co. and other
major utilities.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of the board, including Connell, favors setting value
based only on the replacement cost of a utility's physical assets.
</P>
<P>
   The board's staff argued that value should also be based, in
part, on the income generated by a fair market sale or rental of a
utility's property.
</P>
<P>
   The board's staff recommended a value of $14.1 billion for
Pacific Bell. Pacific Bell wanted a value of $12.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Connell joined two GOP members of the board in backing the lower
valuation, which will save Pacific Bell about $13 million in
property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were seeking consistency and fairness. We think the
valuation from the board is fair and treats us like other telecom
companies in the state,'' said Bill Mashek, a Pacific Bell
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Mashek said the lower property tax bill for Pacific Bell would
not lead to a rate reduction for customers because the state Public
Utilities Commission, which regulates Pacific Bell, does not use
company costs as a factor in setting rates.
</P>
<P>
   Connell was also the swing vote on a disagreement with PG&AMP;E and
other energy utilities over whether cash reserves to pay federal
tax liability should be partially or totally excluded from the
property tax value of the company.
</P>
<P>
   The board's staff argued that roughly 56 percent of the reserves
should be excluded.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E and other electrical utilities, including Southern
California Edison and San Diego Gas and Electric, contended that
all the reserves should be totally excluded or the companies would
be overvalued.
</P>
<P>
   Connell agreed with the board staff, eliminating a $4.9 million
property tax break for PG&AMP;E and a $5.4 million tax break for
Southern California's three largest utilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
