<HEADER>
A0378 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-EAGLES-BIGSUR-SFCHRON     05-31 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EAGLES-BIGSUR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA'S BALD EAGLES COMPETE WITH DEVELOPERS FOR
REMAINING  HABITAT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By GLEN MARTIN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE NACIMIENTO, Calif. _ Life can be pretty sweet if you're an
eaglet in Central California.
</P>
<P>
   When things go right, you spend your days lollygagging in a
comfy nest as big as a king-size bed, rousing yourself occasionally
to accommodate the gobbets of fresh fish your parents are always
trying to cram down your gullet.
</P>
<P>
   But there can be downsides. Like when your nest lies in the path
of development. Or your more aggressive sibling kicks you out of
the nest and you tumble 100 feet through the canopy of a gray pine,
landing in a heap on a mud bank with a broken leg and two busted
wings.
</P>
<P>
   Both scenarios are playing out here by this sprawling reservoir
in the hills between Highway 101 and the southern Big Sur coast.
And while initially discouraging, both _ in this particular case,
at least _ have happy endings.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, a pair of bald eagles hatched two young in a
lakeside nest they have been using annually since 1995, one of only
seven active bald eagle brood sites in Central California. For the
first two months, both eaglets seemed to prosper.
</P>
<P>
   Then last week, one gave the other the old heave-ho,
demonstrating once again that while nature is very often beautiful,
it is not necessarily pretty.
</P>
<P>
   ``That happens quite a bit, actually,'' said Sal Lucido,
president of the Ventana Wilderness Society, which sponsors
preservation programs for California birds of prey. ``Two or even
three eaglets may hatch in a nest, but often only one makes it to
maturity.''
</P>
<P>
   Happily, the injured eaglet was rescued by local rangers and
rushed to the San Francisco Zoo. It has already undergone one
operation on its leg, and attending veterinarians hope it may
eventually be restored to the wild.
</P>
<P>
   But the larger drama involves more than avian fratricide; it is
about the long-term protection of the bald eagle and its
increasingly fragmented wild habitat in the face of California's
population and development boom.
</P>
<P>
   As in other parts of the state, bald eagle nests in the Big Sur
area were established by releasing birds captured in Alaska and
Canada. These eagles eventually found mates during their annual
migrations to the northern part of the continent; they then
returned to California to nest.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1986, 70 bald eagles have been released in Central
California. And 35 eaglets have been raised to maturity by these
transplanted raptors, creating some optimism for the future of the
species in the central state.
</P>
<P>
   Eagles were nearly eradicated throughout most of North America
in the mid-20th century by gunfire and the widespread use of
pesticides such as DDT, which weakened their eggshells.
</P>
<P>
   DDT was subsequently banned, and not too many people are taking
potshots at eagles anymore; that set the stage for a recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Their comeback during the past 30 years has been so successful
that President Clinton proposed removing them from the federal
endangered species list last year. A final decision on the
delisting is expected in July.
</P>
<P>
   Still, bald eagles have been slow to return in force to
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before this program, the last time an eagle nested in this
area was in 1934,'' said Lucido. ``We're making some progress in
bringing them back. We just have to make sure we don't blow it a
second time.''
</P>
<P>
   But what ultimately made a comeback possible, said Jim Davis,
executive director of the society, is something that has long been
reviled as an environmental horror: artificial reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
   Reservoirs may destroy salmon runs and riparian forests, but
eagles love them, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have everything that bald eagles need,'' said Davis.
``There are perfect nesting trees right next to the water, and the
reservoirs are full of the fish and waterfowl that the eagles like
to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean California's bald eagles are out of the woods
yet.
</P>
<P>
   They may like reservoirs _ but so do people. Lake Nacimiento is
experiencing a development boom. Vacation homes are sprouting like
pink stucco fungi along the shoreline. Jet skis and cigarette boats
roar across the lake's limpid surface.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the eagles are handling it with equanimity, but it's
obvious they are going to need some long-term protection.
</P>
<P>
   Boaters regularly motor to within a hundred yards of the nest
and are only nominally dissuaded from getting closer by a boundary
line of buoys. And the parade of new homes continues to march up
the shore.
</P>
<P>
   But conservationists are joining with a local rancher to do
something about it.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Irving's family has ranched this land since the 1930s. He
owns 413 acres around the nest, including more than a mile of
shoreline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm not a Los Angeles-style environmentalist, but I've
always considered myself a preservationist,'' said Irving, who has
the soft manner of speaking and deft movements typical of someone
who has spent his life working with large livestock.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who are moving up here don't really have the
respect for the land and the sense of community that the old
families had,'' Irving said. ``It's important to me that we save
what we can.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Irving is negotiating with the Ventana Wilderness
Society and the Big Sur Land Trust to sell the land around the nest
with long-term conservation in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, Irving has given the two groups a long-term option to
buy the land, which has a current market value in excess of
$900,000.
</P>
<P>
   The land trust, which has preserved 19,000 acres of land in and
around Big Sur since 1978, will bring the legal expertise needed to
close the deal, while the society will handle restoration and
management plans.
</P>
<P>
   Nikki Nedeff, director of conservation for the land trust, said
she is optimistic the necessary money can be raised to buy the
property.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is actually a little far afield from our primary mandate,
which is preserving land along the Big Sur coast,'' Nedeff said.
``But bald eagles are a historic part of the Big Sur ecosystem, and
it's essential to protect their nesting sites.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, said Nedeff, wildland such as that encompassed by
Irving's ranch is becoming increasingly rare in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of habitat _ upland chaparral with mixed hardwoods
and conifers _ is terribly threatened,'' said Nedeff. ``It's
becoming fragmented, particularly by vineyards and housing tracts.
Eagles thrive in it, but so do a tremendous number of other
wildlife species. We always welcome the chance to save some of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lake Nacimiento's lone remaining eaglet is doing its
part to bolster its species _ by growing like a weed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only been eight weeks since it hatched, but it's already
fully fledged and big as an adult,'' said Davis. ``In another few
weeks, it will be out of here. In a few months, it will have
migrated north, maybe as far as Great Slave Lake in Canada. As long
as we give them the few basics they need, they'll do just fine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
