<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0379 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OZONE-HOLE-SFCHRON &LR;      05-31 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OZONE-HOLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OZONE HOLE FOUND OVER NORTH POLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clouds of ice and acid high in the stratosphere disrupted the
Northern Hemisphere's protective ozone layer this past winter, and
scientists say the ozone loss poses potentially serious health
problems for humans if it repeats in coming winters.
</P>
<P>
   An international team of researchers detected the unusually cold
ozone-destroying clouds in the stratosphere over the Arctic last
winter, and the team's leaders reported their findings Tuesday at a
meeting of the American Geophysical Union in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The findings are surprising because scientists had expected that
the protective ozone layer would recover after ozone-destroying
chemicals known as chlorofluorocarbons, or CFCs, were banned by
international treaty four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But that has not happened, the team of nearly 200 scientists and
technicians found. Instead, the same phenomenon that has opened a
growing ``ozone hole'' over Antarctica each winter for more than 10
years is occurring over the Arctic Circle as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ozone levels over the Arctic have been dropping for the past
four to five years,'' said Brian Toon, an atmospheric scientist at
the University of Colorado and a leader of the team. ``As a result
the stratosphere over the Arctic is beginning to look a lot like
the Antarctic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time, in fact, that we've seen the polar
clouds lasting long enough to affect the ozone layer
significantly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ozone loss in the Southern Hemisphere is already causing
health problems for many people in Australia, New Zealand and
elsewhere in the South Pacific because the sun's damaging
ultra-violet radiation is no longer blocked by the layer of ozone.
</P>
<P>
   The same could happen in populated areas of the United States,
Canada and Russia if the Northern Hemisphere's ozone layer
continues to thin, the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   Using an array of satellites, weather balloons and high-flying
aircraft, the scientists found that polar stratospheric clouds made
of ice particles and nitric acid were larger and lasted longer than
researchers had found in previous years.
</P>
<P>
   The clouds, known as PSCs, generally form about 13 miles above
the poles each winter when temperatures drop to 110 degrees
Fahrenheit below zero, Toon said.
</P>
<P>
   This past winter, he reported, instruments on satellites,
balloons and two high-altitude aircraft all showed that ozone
concentrations in some parts of the stratosphere declined as much
as 60 percent between November and March.
</P>
<P>
   The complex chemistry that caused the loss begins with the
presence of chlorine atoms. Chlorine was released into the
atmosphere for many years in the form of CFCs, which were once
widely used for refrigerators, air-conditioning equipment and many
industrial products.
</P>
<P>
   CFCs were banned in 1996 by a treaty known as the Montreal
Protocol, but they are expected to linger in the upper atmosphere
for many more years, scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   Highly reactive chlorine can destroy ozone molecules on contact,
and it is the nitric acid in the polar clouds that transforms
normally inert chlorine into the form that tears the ozone apart.
This past winter, the researchers found, nitric acid ``drizzled''
down from clouds high up in the stratosphere and turned even more
chlorine than usual into the ozone-destroying form.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what the international team discovered was also
predicted in computer models developed by a separate group of
scientists led by Azadeh Tabazadeh, am atmospheric physicist at the
NASA Ames Research Center in Mountain View, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The arctic atmosphere is not nearly as cold as it is over
Antarctica, but it has been growing colder over the past 20 years
by more than four degrees Fahrenheit per decade, Tabazadeh said in
an interview last week. Because of this, she said, this past winter
should in fact have seen colder than normal temperatures over the
Arctic, leading in turn to larger and longer-lasting polar
stratospheric clouds.
</P>
<P>
   That is precisely what happened this past winter, and as a
result the nitric acid compounds high in the stratosphere dropped
down to turn the lingering chlorine atoms into ozone destroyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our model is correct and if our estimate of the cooling
rate in the stratosphere is correct, than we predict that by 2010
ozone in the (arctic) stratosphere will be decreased by up to 30
percent,'' Tabazadeh said.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the situation is made worse by heat-trapping gases
that have been linked to global warming.
</P>
<P>
   Toon said the ``greenhouse gases'' in Earth's upper atmosphere
that continually trap heat at the Earth's surface, also act like
radiators to lower temperatures in the stratosphere. As a result,
the icy polar clouds this past winter grew larger and colder and
lasted longer than expected, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the clouds of ice and nitric acid particles form high
in the stratosphere directly over the Arctic, their influence on
the protective ozone layer extends far south each spring as they
drift over densely populated areas of the United States, Canada and
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   It is these regions that could see increases in skin cancer
rates and other damaging effects from solar ultraviolet radiation
if the ozone layer thins during future winters as it has now, the
researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Kiruna, Sweden, this past winter, the international
project was the largest in a series of annual efforts known as the
Stratospheric Aerosol and Gas Experiment. , or SAGE. This winter's
version was termed SOLVE, the SAGE III Ozone Loss and Validation
Experiment. The project included researchers from Canada, Russia,
Japan, and the United States, as well as from several European
organizations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 0100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0380 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-STARS-DEVILS-TEX     05-31 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-DEVILS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOPPED-UP BELFOUR CAN'T STOP NEW JERSEY IN OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Stars goalie Ed Belfour crouched down in
goal, his face expressionless. Only his eyes showed life, shifting
sideways towards Dallas' bench, where seconds later he began to
skate toward.
</P>
<P>
   A little less than 18 minutes remained in Game 1 of the Stanley
Cup Finals but Belfour's portion of Tuesday night's 7-3 humiliating
loss was done. The rest of the Stars weren't so lucky. They had to
wade through the mess they made.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just say the Stars, much like Belfour, had seen better
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very embarrassing,'' Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor said.
``We didn't give (Belfour) a good game. That's the bottom line.
It's not Eddie Belfour that lost the game. It's us. We let him
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was just one of those nights for the defending
champions. Whatever hadn't already gone wrong, they found a way to
screw up. After a solid first period that ended knotted at 1-1, the
meltdown began for the Stars. They allowed six goals in a span of
22 minutes and 21 seconds of the second and third periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty simple,'' Stars forward Joe Nieuwendyk said. ``We
got outplayed in every area. They played positionally sound as they
always do. We just did not compete for pucks and they took it to us
and we didn't respond.''
</P>
<P>
   How did they get outplayed? Let us count the ways.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively. The Stars usual strength failed them. Sydor and his
defensive partner Sergei Zubov were on the ice for all but one of
the Devils goals.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively. The Stars aren't usually the
light-up-the-scoreboard types, but their impact players practically
disappeared during the stretch where New Jersey scored all of its
goals.
</P>
<P>
   In goal. Dallas usually doesn't allow seven goals in two games
much less two periods. In fact, Colorado failed to score more than
a pair in any of the seven Western Conference Finals games.
Belfour, who brought a 1.81 goals-against average into Tuesday
night's game, allowed six goals on 18 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour said he had been fighting a bit of a cold bug and felt
his decongestant maybe effected his play.
</P>
<P>
   When did he realize the medication was a problem?
</P>
<P>
   ``After six goals,'' Belfour deadpanned. ``It was 6-1, and
things weren't going our way and I think Hitch maybe realized that
it was time to get me out of there. It wasn't going my way and with
the score 6-1 in the third period he decided to get me out of there
and rest.''
</P>
<P>
   And ABC execs were fretting that Devils-Stars lacked
goal-scoring appeal?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice for some of our guys to start scoring some goals
because they've been hard to come by,'' Devils coach Larry Robinson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some goals? Hard to come by?
</P>
<P>
   The Devils couldn't miss Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey had talked about needing a good start which Devils
forward Jason Arnott provided with his goal seven minutes and 22
seconds into the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   After the Stars tied it with a goal by Sydor at 13:13 of that
period, their problems began.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils didn't waste any time jumping ahead of the Stars in
the second period either. Defenseman Ken Daneyko squeaked his first
playoff goal in at 2:52 of the second period on a shot that hit the
inside of Belfour's right thigh bounced to his left thigh and in.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw from the start we didn't have that passion and emotion
for some reason. Why? We don't know,'' Stars winger Mike Keane
said. ``They got a goal and a second goal then a third goal then
things started snowballing.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than 30 seconds after Martin Brodeur's spectacular glove
save on Brett Hull midway through second-period action, Petr Sykora
scored on Belfour to stretch New Jersey's advantage to 3-1. Devils
forward Patrik Elias had a failed breakaway yet passed back to
Sykora.
</P>
<P>
   Follow that aforementioned snowball roll from that point on.
</P>
<P>
   Devils defenseman Scott Stevens scored. After a 17-minute
intermission between periods, New Jersey picked up right where it
had left off. A Sergei Brylin goal followed by another Sykora goal
which led to Belfour's departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my decision to pull him,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock
said.
</P>
<P>
   And while Belfour got pulled, all 19 of the other Stars felt his
pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``For sure,'' Sydor said. ``We can't let so many scoring chances
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnott scored his second and New Jersey's seventh against Stars
backup goalie Manny Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars hadn't allowed that many goals in a playoff game since
Game 5 of the Western Conference Finals last season, and the pride
started hurting as they were skating around under a scoreboard that
read 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played games like this before and the only difference
between 7-3 and 4-3 has been Belfour,'' Hitchcock said. ``We've had
a couple of performances like this and we've always bounced back.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas' started that long bounce back by getting two goals in a
12-second span later in the third period. Obviously, Kirk Muller's
and Jon Sim's additions were too little, too late. But the Stars
have a lot of pride and they say that's just the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils believe it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going to come out hard, flying and playing dirty
hockey,'' Arnott said. ``No question about it, Eddie Belfour is
going to come out rock solid and I think we got to worry about what
we are going to do out there.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Stars managed to find a silver lining to the cloud
hanging over them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The positive is we're only down by one game,'' Stars winger
Scott Thornton said. ``They didn't get two games for that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
