<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0383 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-LIDDY-AZR     05-31 1415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIDDY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOM LIDDY RUNS FOR CONGRESS BUT NOT FROM DAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KRIS MAYES 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spend any time at all with Tom Liddy, one of four Republicans
scrambling for a foothold in the race for the 1st Congressional
District, and you quickly realize that his father, former Watergate
figure G. Gordon Liddy, is never far from his side.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not literally. The G-Man lives only part time in
Scottsdale and does his nationwide radio show mostly from Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   But there he is in the photographs in the candidate's Tempe
campaign office, standing next to family friend Waylon Jennings.
</P>
<P>
   The Harley-Davidson and Corvette that the 37-year-old sometimes
drives to his fund-raisers are his dad's _ complete with H2O-GATE
license plates.
</P>
<P>
   G. Gordon makes frequent mentions of his son's candidacy, Tom's
first bid for office, on his syndicated radio show, aired on 290
radio stations nationwide, six in Arizona. Tom also runs political
ads on his father's show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of my parents,'' the younger Liddy said recently
while campaigning in Ahwatukee. ``They wanted my father to testify
against people during Watergate, but he preferred to remain silent.
And for that silence he was sentenced to 21 years in prison. The
guy doesn't lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Liddy, a lawyer for a Phoenix firm, left his post as legal
counsel to the Republican National Committee in Washington, D.C.,
and moved to Arizona in 1998. He moved to Chandler and the 1st
Congressional District nine months ago. &QL; 
In most other states, Liddy might be labeled a carpetbag ger. But
like New York, a state where Hillary Rodham Clinton's campaign has
caught fire despite her newcomer status, Arizona is a place where
being from someplace else is almost a political advantage. John
McCain was one of the first candidates to prove that in 1982 when
he targeted the 1st Congressional District, moved there and won.
</P>
<P>
   Although Liddy has an uphill battle in a race that features
three other skilled Republicans _ former think tank director Jeff
Flake, cable TV executive Susan Bitter Smith and former Phoenix
City Councilman Sal DiCiccio _ experts do not discount Liddy's
candidacy. And they say if Liddy does win the heavily Republican
district, he will have his name to thank.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would seem like Flake is probably the institutional
favorite, but there isn't any reason to think that in an Arizona
Republican primary that the name recognition of someone who is
closely associated with the right wing of the party couldn't pull
an upset,'' said Zachary Smith, a political science professor at
Northern Arizona University. ``Tom Liddy could be a complete
unknown and still win this thing because of the name recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there can be a downside to being the candidate whose
father, however charismatic, is an avatar of the Nixon era.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent candidates forum, perennial GOP candidate Bert
Tollefson rose to denounce Liddy's lineage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your father was a burglar!'' Tollefson yelled.
</P>
<P>
   Liddy was also faced with a dicey question from a reporter
recently when it was discovered that the candidate's campaign Web
site was linked to his father's, which featured an advertisement
for a calendar of scantily clad women brandishing guns. ``Stacked
and packed!'' the ad read. ``America's most beautiful heavily armed
women.'' Within days, the advertisement for the calendar was
discreetly taken down.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gordon Liddy is unapologetic about his past and says it has no
bearing on his son's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's absolutely right,'' the elder Liddy said of Tollefson's
remarks in an interview last week. ``But the fact that I was a
burglar does not mean that Tom is. I don't see how that affects
Tom. Suppose I was a neurosurgeon. Would that make Tom a
neurosurgeon?''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Liddy, who from time to time has acted as his father's
lawyer and continues to represent him in an ongoing lawsuit filed
against him by fellow Watergate figure John Dean, speaks openly
about his father's imprisonment and the effect it had on him, Tom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a time for my brothers and sisters and I to really rely
on each other for closeness and strength, and it was a time of
great suffering for my mother,'' Liddy said. ``We were impoverished
_ not Ethiopia impoverished, but we ended up $300,000 in debt and
didn't have any new clothes for five years. It humbles you and
makes you grateful for what you have got.''
</P>
<P>
   His father's time in the spotlight may have deprived him of a
father and new clothing for five years, but it gave Tom Liddy a
deftness for dealing with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (CNN anchor) Bernard Shaw comes into your living room
when you are 12 years old and you are shaking hands with Barbara
Walters, you are not awed by the media circus,'' Liddy said. ``I am
media savvy, as they say.''
</P>
<P>
   Being the son of Gordon Liddy has been beneficial in other ways
as well.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gordon Liddy has lent his name to several of his son's
fund-raisers, and many of Gordon's friends, including Oliver North
and the late Richard Kleindienst, have helped out. In July, the
candidate will travel to Virginia, where Gordon Liddy and rocker
Ted Nugent will headline a Tom Liddy fund-raising event.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, most of Tom Liddy's fund-raising apparatus is outside
Arizona. According to an analysis by The Republic, 58 percent of
Liddy's contributions have come from donors outside the state,
tying Liddy with Bitter Smith for the title of biggest out-of-state
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   After the most recent campaign finance reporting period, Liddy
reported having only $31,000 in cash on hand, even though he had
raised more than $212,000. By contrast, Flake had raised $237,755
and had more than $200,000 in the bank by mid-April. More than 50
percent of Liddy's campaign donations have flowed to consultants.
</P>
<P>
   Liddy has developed a base of support in the state that includes
McCain's state director, Larry Pike, and his wife, Nicole Bidwill,
the daughter of Cardinals owner Bill Bidwill.
</P>
<P>
   The senior Liddy talks as though his son were the front-runner
in the race rather than a newcomer who has never held office in
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Tom has only one serious opponent. It's a race between
him and Jeff Flake,'' Liddy said, referring to the East Valley
Republican and former director of the Goldwater Institute. ``Jeff
Flake strikes me as one of these intellectual types. . . . There is
nothing wrong with being an intellectual, but this fellow seems to
think he is just entitled to it because he worked for the Goldwater
Institute.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By the way, he's a hell of a good shot,'' Gordon suddenly
interjected about his son. ``I saw him take a .45, and with one
shot, he took the head right off a snapping turtle.'' (Upon hearing
of his father's comments, Tom remarked dryly, ``Oh, great, that's
going to help me with the women's vote in Tempe.'')
</P>
<P>
   Tom Liddy's accuracy with a deadly weapon and his time spent in
the Marines aside, on the campaign trail the candidate is all
compassionate conservative. At every opportunity, he trumpets the
need to raise teachers salaries and his own experience teaching
seventh grade, which he hopes will help set him apart from his
competitors on what is the defining issue in the suburban
congressional district.
</P>
<P>
   And as he campaigns door to door, Liddy courts Independents, who
will be eligible to vote for the first time in the Sept. 12
Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   Liddy also appears to be borrowing a page from McCain, talking
about the need for campaign finance reform and a kind of
lay-it-all-out style of governance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a guy who, if he will do anything, will talk straight,''
Liddy said during a recent candidate forum.
</P>
<P>
   And talk tough. At a recent forum, Liddy was the only candidate
who was willing to criticize an opponent whose salary from a
non-profit organization had been paid, in part, by a tax-deductible
donation from his campaign finance chairman.
</P>
<P>
   At a forum in Phoenix two days before Flake relinquished the
post, Liddy used time reserved for his own introduction to take on
Flake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows there is an elephant in this room, and we're
going to talk about it tonight,'' Liddy said.
</P>
<P>
   At another forum hosted by gay Republicans, Liddy noticed that
Flake was absent from the controversial group's meeting and sensed
another opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is Jeff Flake?'' Liddy asked loudly as the group
assembled. ``Has anybody seen Jeff Flake?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 0111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0384 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r n BC-GONZALEZ-SHOOTING-LAD     05-31 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GONZALEZ-SHOOTING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAPD STEPS UP MANHUNT IN GONZALEZ SLAYING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LISA VAN PROYEN, ALEXA HAUSSLER AND JASON KANDEL 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Amid expressions of shock and grief across the
city, detectives widened the manhunt Tuesday for the killer of
Chief Bernard C. Parks' granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   The brazen slaying of 20-year-old Lori Gonzalez on Sunday has
rocked members of the Parks family, as they gathered at his home to
mourn. Vice President Al Gore called to offer his condolences.
</P>
<P>
   As Parks made funeral arrangements, at least a dozen elite
detectives from the Robbery-Homicide Division fanned out across the
city in search of the gunman, described only as a heavy-set
African-American in his early 20s, 5 feet 10 inches to 6 feet tall,
with a long face and black, oily hair.
</P>
<P>
   A video surveillance tape from a nearby gasoline station could
provide needed clues as to who walked up next to Gonzalez's car
about 10 p.m. Sunday and fired at a passenger, missing him and
killing her instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We firmly believe that she was not the intended target,'' said
LAPD Cmdr. Dave Kalish. ``This is a situation where we had a
beautiful young lady who had nothing to do with crime.''
</P>
<P>
   At a makeshift memorial, residents and friends placed a rag
doll, and flowers, and left written eulogies where she was slain,
in front of the Popeyes Chicken restaurant at La Brea Avenue and
Jefferson Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez had been visiting friends and her mother, Felicia, in
Los Angeles after leaving Saddleback College in Mission Viejo where
she majored in English.
</P>
<P>
   Police identified the passenger as a 20-year-old longtime
acquaintance of Gonazlez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's obviously pretty devastated by the incident. The
interviews with him have been pretty slow,'' said department
spokesman Lt. Horace Frank. ``We're not ruling anything out.''
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Nate Holden announced he would seek a $25,000 reward
to help track the killer but backed away at the urging of police.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought a reward being noted at this time would interfere
with the investigation,'' Holden said. ``They were pretty emphatic
about it. I got the impression that they were onto someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators urged anyone with information to call a tip line.
Some residents of the neighborhood said they already have told
police about seeing the attack and hearing shots.
</P>
<P>
   A 16-year-old girl who lives near the restaurant said she saw a
man run from the scene of the shooting shortly after hearing
several gunshots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him run up to the car,'' said the teen-ager, who asked
that her name be withheld because she fears retaliation. ``Then I
heard gunshots. I couldn't really see his face. He was wearing dark
clothes. But I saw him run into the alley. It was scary.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she called 911 to report the attack and spoke with
detectives Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Another woman said her teen-age son was in the area when
gunshots erupted, so she bolted out the door to find him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him down the street,'' she said. ``He was waving his
arms and saying, `Here I am. I knew you'd come after me ...'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time he steps outside, I'm like, Oh gosh, I hear
something,'' she said. ``I'm tired of doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez was fatally shot just a day after someone stabbed to
death a 90-year-old community leader, Albert Patton, and his
85-year-old wife, who uses a wheelchair, in their home a few blocks
away.
</P>
<P>
   According to Los Angeles police statistics, violent crimes in
that neighborhood have risen about 6 percent this year over last.
As of May 21, there were 13 homicides in the Southwest Division,
identical to the same time period last year. But rapes, robberies
and aggravated assaults have all risen this year over last.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Ken Deasy of St. Agatha's Parish Family Church, several
blocks away from where the shooting took place, said he was
disappointed because he and community members have been working to
make the streets safer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had two years of cultural exchange repairs, gangs have
gone down, blacks and Latinos are getting along, and we're getting
more whites to come in to live here,'' he said. ``Then this
happens. I really see this as disappointing. I hope no one from our
area (did) ... this.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles police homicide Detective Brian Carr said extra
detectives were assigned to the case because of the number of tips
generated by the prominence of the victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``That generates a lot of leads. It's not playing favorites for
the chief. If Joe Schmoe got the same media attention, we'd do the
same thing,'' Carr said.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles City Council adjourned its meeting in memory of
Gonzalez, and council members offered their sympathy to the police
chief and his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very hard-hitting loss, not only to the family and the
people who knew her, but for the rest of the city to realize that
these kinds of tragedies can occur to anyone,'' said Councilwoman
Laura Chick.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Protective League, which has gone head to head at
times with Parks, sent a letter of condolence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no secret that we have differences of opinion with the
management style of LAPD, but ... when a tragedy like this occurs,
we set everything aside to grieve with the grieving family,'' said
Ted Hunt, president of the league.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral services are tentatively set for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Parkses are a very close family, a loving family. They are
together now. This is a real tough time for them,'' Kalish said.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives ask that anyone with information about the slaying
call them at (213) 485-2129 or (213) 485-2504 after hours.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 0113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
