<P>
   Gonzalez had been visiting friends and her mother, Felicia, in
Los Angeles after leaving Saddleback College in Mission Viejo where
she majored in English.
</P>
<P>
   Police identified the passenger as a 20-year-old longtime
acquaintance of Gonazlez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's obviously pretty devastated by the incident. The
interviews with him have been pretty slow,'' said department
spokesman Lt. Horace Frank. ``We're not ruling anything out.''
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Nate Holden announced he would seek a $25,000 reward
to help track the killer but backed away at the urging of police.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought a reward being noted at this time would interfere
with the investigation,'' Holden said. ``They were pretty emphatic
about it. I got the impression that they were onto someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators urged anyone with information to call a tip line.
Some residents of the neighborhood said they already have told
police about seeing the attack and hearing shots.
</P>
<P>
   A 16-year-old girl who lives near the restaurant said she saw a
man run from the scene of the shooting shortly after hearing
several gunshots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him run up to the car,'' said the teen-ager, who asked
that her name be withheld because she fears retaliation. ``Then I
heard gunshots. I couldn't really see his face. He was wearing dark
clothes. But I saw him run into the alley. It was scary.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she called 911 to report the attack and spoke with
detectives Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Another woman said her teen-age son was in the area when
gunshots erupted, so she bolted out the door to find him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him down the street,'' she said. ``He was waving his
arms and saying, `Here I am. I knew you'd come after me ...'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time he steps outside, I'm like, Oh gosh, I hear
something,'' she said. ``I'm tired of doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez was fatally shot just a day after someone stabbed to
death a 90-year-old community leader, Albert Patton, and his
85-year-old wife, who uses a wheelchair, in their home a few blocks
away.
</P>
<P>
   According to Los Angeles police statistics, violent crimes in
that neighborhood have risen about 6 percent this year over last.
As of May 21, there were 13 homicides in the Southwest Division,
identical to the same time period last year. But rapes, robberies
and aggravated assaults have all risen this year over last.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Ken Deasy of St. Agatha's Parish Family Church, several
blocks away from where the shooting took place, said he was
disappointed because he and community members have been working to
make the streets safer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had two years of cultural exchange repairs, gangs have
gone down, blacks and Latinos are getting along, and we're getting
more whites to come in to live here,'' he said. ``Then this
happens. I really see this as disappointing. I hope no one from our
area (did) ... this.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles police homicide Detective Brian Carr said extra
detectives were assigned to the case because of the number of tips
generated by the prominence of the victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``That generates a lot of leads. It's not playing favorites for
the chief. If Joe Schmoe got the same media attention, we'd do the
same thing,'' Carr said.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles City Council adjourned its meeting in memory of
Gonzalez, and council members offered their sympathy to the police
chief and his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very hard-hitting loss, not only to the family and the
people who knew her, but for the rest of the city to realize that
these kinds of tragedies can occur to anyone,'' said Councilwoman
Laura Chick.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Protective League, which has gone head to head at
times with Parks, sent a letter of condolence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no secret that we have differences of opinion with the
management style of LAPD, but ... when a tragedy like this occurs,
we set everything aside to grieve with the grieving family,'' said
Ted Hunt, president of the league.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral services are tentatively set for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Parkses are a very close family, a loving family. They are
together now. This is a real tough time for them,'' Kalish said.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives ask that anyone with information about the slaying
call them at (213) 485-2129 or (213) 485-2504 after hours.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
