<HEADLINE>
FEDS HOPE TO EASE FOREST FIRE THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDD SLIVKA  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal officials may close thousands of acres of Arizona
national forest as soon as next week to reduce the chances of a
disastrous fire season.
</P>
<P>
   The affected forests would be those on or close to the Mogollon
Rim _ the Apache-Sitgreaves, Coconino, Kaibab, Tonto and Prescott
national forests, all of which have had active fires in the past
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the `Yes, but when and where?' part now,'' Conny
Frisch, supervisor of the Kaibab National Forest, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're asking, `Do we have the money to do this?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Forest officials said that June 7 is their target date for
closures, but that they may leave areas of &QL; 
pinon-juniper open to the public because they don't burn as quickly
as the ponderosa pine at higher elevations.
</P>
<P>
   The closures could rival 1996, when nearly 4 million acres in
national forests were closed to the public because of fire danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to explore with other forests going for statewide
closures,'' Frisch said. ``We'd like to all do it at once.''
</P>
<P>
   A decision should be made by Thursday, she said. If the closure
does not encompass all forests _ the rainless winter has left
little grass to burn in the lower elevations _ individual forest
management can decide if and how much to close.
</P>
<P>
   There already are fire restrictions at all national forests and
on state and federal lands. Parts of the Apache-Sitgreaves, Kaibab
and Tonto national forests have been closed to the public for
several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the public out of wild lands is neither easy nor cheap,
officials said. But it becomes a human-resources battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the point now where the entire nation is tipped
towards the Southwest,'' said Karen Malis-Clark, a Coconino
spokeswoman. ``Anyone who supports firefighting activity in the
country is coming to New Mexico and Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the state's firefighting resources are nearly tapped out. On
the Kaibab, two large fires have sucked up many of the area's
resources.
</P>
<P>
   At the Coconino, the now-extinguished ``Clover'' fire took up
resources, and when that fire was mostly contained, many of the
engines and crews fighting it were transferred to the Kaibab fires.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Vultee'' fire near Slide Rock State Park this past weekend
strained resources still more, and although that fire is mostly
controlled, the personnel and equipment originally assigned to it
are now being sent to a fast-growing blaze north of Pecos, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   Widespread closures, officials say, would cut down on new
blazes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to limit the human starts,'' Frisch said. ``We
know that we get some lighting starts, but we know that there was
no lightning in Sycamore Canyon and Oak Creek Canyon (sites of two
recent fires). So we're trying to limit that part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially after the holiday weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had people in the forest lighting fires all weekend,'' she
said. ``Our fire-prevention people had their hands full.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling even more attention to Arizona's cotton-dry, brush-heavy
conditions Tuesday, Gov. Jane Hull kicked off a daylong session
among the state's fire managers by alluding to the four major fires
in New Mexico so far this year _ and categorically stating Arizona
is next.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever is raging in New Mexico will soon be raging here,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Holding her arm above her waist, Hull said, ``I'm not the expert
you are, but I know when there is brush up to here, we have a
tinderbox.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
