<HEADER>
A0387 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     05-31 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S SIMPLY NO EXCUSE FOR STARS' FAILURE TO COMPETE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Of all things that might have happened,
and for all the wrong reasons, the Dallas Stars were guilty of the
absolute worst Tuesday night. They failed to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Lifeless lumps in uniforms did show up and go through the
formality of a Game 1 defense of that prized possession they earned
a year ago _ the Stanley Cup. But it was 60 minutes of mere
pretending. That was obvious.
</P>
<P>
   This was not about losing a game. This was all about a failure
to compete at the same energized level as the New Jersey Devils,
leading to rampant national embarrassment and disgrace for the
Stars. And speaking of embarrassment, how about those fretting
folks from such networks as ABC and ESPN, who made no secret of
their displeasure with these two teams being in the Stanley Cup
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Worried over ratings, the TV types were forecasting two weeks of
boring, low-scoring, defensive struggles. At least the Stars'
dismal performance shut up the talking heads.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this 7-3 shocker had plenty to do with Eddie Belfour coming
apart in goal, which more than anything that happened Tuesday night
will privately rattle the confidence of the Stars. But there were
certainly a multitude of Dallas witnesses to the Belfour wreck,
including defensemen Sergei Zubov. who had an upclose view of
Eddie's sudden crackup.
</P>
<P>
   Zubov was on the ice for five of the six goals given up by
Belfour before Ken Hitchcock benched his goalie three minutes into
the third period.
</P>
<P>
   If New Jersey is this dominant, particularly the No. 1 line of
Petr Sykora-Patrik Elias-Jason Arnott, then this series will be
over in four games. Speed-wise, the Stars were no match for that
threesome. ``But it wasn't just the Sykora line,'' added Hitchcock.
``As a group their forwards gave us more speed and quickness than
we've seen this season from any team.''
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Hitchcock was not in an angry mood afterwards. Neither
was general manager Bob Gainey, who watched every second from the
press box, calmly waited for the celebrating Continental Airlines
Arena crowd to dance out of the building, then said on departing,
``we've got 48 hours to recapture our energy and try to come up
with a new game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Hitchcock shrugged and said, ``We've had these
kind of games before this (in the playoffs), but the difference in
4-3 and 7-3 has been Belfour. Tonight, Eddie didn't have a good
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone mentioned to Hitchcock that his team didn't seemed to
have recovered from the grueling series against the Avalanche,
particularly the Game 7 win on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this being an extension from Game 7 is irrelevant,''
answered Hitchcock. Amen.
</P>
<P>
   There are no excuses for opening a Stanley Cup Finals and
failing to compete on the same level as the opposition. Unless, of
course, the Devils are this much better than the Stars, which would
shock the hockey world and all odds-makers in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to the Stars on Tuesday night was a duplicate of
Game 3 of the Western Conference Finals, which the Avalanche won,
2-0. Except Belfour played outstanding in holding the score down.
The remainder of the team did the lifeless-lump impersonation that
night. The Game 3 in the Edmonton series was much the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen this,'' repeated Hitchcock. ``We were flat and a
step late, and some of our best people were the ones who were late.
Then the game turned on the third goal (by New Jersey).''
</P>
<P>
   Truthfully, the Stars quit after the Devils made it 3-1 in the
second period. There was a bang-bang-bang sequence in the period
when a quick whistle took away a goal by Guy Carbonneau that would
have tied the game at 2-2. Then Devils goalie Martin Brodeur
rescued his team with a fine save on a Mike Modano wrister,
followed quickly by a terrific glove save as Brett Hull attempted
to slam home the rebound on the Modano shot.
</P>
<P>
   With no penalty whistles through almost two periods, the
end-to-end action went the other way, but this time Elias set up
Sykora for that third goal as Belfour failed to close off the side
of the net. At 3-1, the Stars appeared to be waiting on Thursday
night's Game 2. They promptly retreated.
</P>
<P>
   The optimist _ if he's really drunk _ will say the Stars now
have the Devils right where they want them. Within a year, the
Stars have lost four straight Game 1s in the Western Conference
Finals and the Stanley Cup Finals. But they have yet to lose a
series.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, no comparing the other three to Tuesday
night. This was a failure to compete. This was even their goalie
folding up. This was, by far, the worst and the most troubling.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
