r s BC-HKN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-T     05-31 0343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDDIE THE ANGEL'S NIGHT OFF TOO UNUSUAL TO WORRY ABOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ And before the seventh goal, Eddie
Belfour rested.
</P>
<P>
   And we saw that this was good. Real good. Almost merciful.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody ever said, of course, that the Angel Eddie was
infallible. For months he has been the rock that the defending
Stanley Cup champions have leaned on.
</P>
<P>
   But what in the Devils' name was this?
</P>
<P>
   Belfour stood there, alone in his team's end, while the New
Jersey Devils celebrated and the arena howled. He had just given up
his sixth goal of the night, and there wasn't a teammate defenseman
or a hotel security guard to put a headlock on.
</P>
<P>
   His shoulders slumped a little, and there was no need to argue
with what was about to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my decision to pull him,'' coach Ken Hitchcock said,
after the 7-3 lashing that his Stars had just absorbed. ``He hasn't
had too many nights like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Into the game came Manny Fernandez, who, rumor has it, is the
Stars' backup goaltender. Belfour's night ended with almost 17
minutes still to play.
</P>
<P>
   Through 17 previous playoff games, Belfour had allowed only 31
goals _ less than two per game. He had stood up to the likes of
Doug Weight, Owen Nolan and Peter Forsberg.
</P>
<P>
   He had survived jeering, chanting audiences in Edmonton, San
Jose and Denver. And he had stood tall amid the pressure of a Game
7 against the Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   But the Stars themselves already know all that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie didn't have a good night,'' Hitchcock assessed, grimly.
``He's had great nights throughout the playoffs. I know he'll
bounce back.''
</P>
<P>
   You'd think so. Hitchcock knows that recent history is on his
side. The Stars sleep-walked through the finals opener a year ago _
losing at home, even _ yet bounced back to win four of the next
five. There were too many guys in dark jerseys Tuesday night _ guys
with Stanley Cup rings _ having too ghastly of a night.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcocy%l+W: B%M
</P>
</TEXT>
