<SLUG> BC-KOFI-WAKES-UP-OPED-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. FORCES SHOULD BE GIVEN TOOLS TO DO THE JOB  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Editorial)  (This 450-word ``separate-buy'' editorial is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This editorial has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By THE EDITORIAL BOARD OF THE INDEPENDENT  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   He is right, of course. It is just a shame that it took so long
for the obvious to be said out loud.
</P>
<P>
   In an exclusive interview with The Independent, Kofi Annan, the
United Nations' secretary general, pointed to the undeniable fact
that, too often, U.N. troops need a tougher mandate and better
hardware.
</P>
<P>
   It is too easy for U.N. peacekeeping troops to be used by the
world's politicians as mere fig leaves, covering up the fact that
nobody wants to do anything serious at all.
</P>
<P>
   During the war in Bosnia, U.N. peacekeeping troops were
permitted to do little except smile sweetly _ even if crimes were
committed under their very noses _ unless they themselves were
being shot at.
</P>
<P>
   It was a recipe for disaster _ as, for example, at Srebrenica,
where 6,000 people were massacred while Dutch U.N. troops, hampered
by lack of international support, stood by.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations can only take tough action if the powerful
Security Council votes in favor. Thus, huge responsibility lies
with the permanent members of the Security Council, most notably
the U.S., France and Britain, each of which can ensure that action
is blocked.
</P>
<P>
   But the secretary general's leadership is important, too.
Annan's predecessor, Boutros Boutros-Ghali, was notoriously more
interested in playing office politics in New York than in helping
to right the wrongs of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Annan, by contrast, has taken on some of the trickiest
diplomatic tasks imaginable _ successfully negotiating, for
example, with the Iraqi dictator, Saddam Hussein, and with his
Libyan counterpart, Colonel Muammar Qaddafi _ while continuing to
ensure that the U.N. conceals an iron fist in its velvety glove.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Leone has proved a humiliation for the U.N., with 500 of
its troops being taken hostage by the lawless rebels of the
Revolutionary United Front. The bandit force made a mockery of the
theoretically powerful U.N. force.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of well-equipped British troops has made things
better for the moment, though Annan is understandably wary lest
Britain pull out again soon. He noted the core problem
internationally: ``The capacity is out there; but the will is not
there to go in.''
</P>
<P>
   This soft-spoken Ghanaian is aware that to stand by while Sierra
Leone spirals downward into violent chaos merely paves the way for
a repeat performance elsewhere in the not very distant future.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, a line must be drawn. For that, the U.N. needs the
support of the major Western powers. Annan says: ``We will test
them.''
</P>
<P>
   For everybody's sake, we must hope that they pass the test. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 450-word editorial from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper
in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
