<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEARABLE-LAPTOP-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LAPTOP YOU CAN WEAR?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (This quirky 375-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By CHARLES ARTHUR  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ You've heard of a laptop keyboard but how about
making your lap into a keyboard?
</P>
<P>
   Wait a year or so: Electrotextiles, a British company, has
developed a way of including conductive fibers in cloth to produce
a keyboard that can be rolled up or even knitted into clothes, with
the bonus of ties that can act as a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   The company, based in Buckinghamshire, England, is speaking to a
number of companies in Europe and the U.S. about developing the
system, which with the advent of mobile computing could be the
ideal way to carry a keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasts suggest the number of handheld devices will explode
over the next five years, but with voice recognition still
requiring too much computing power, and keyboards taking up too
much space, the devices could have limited potential for data entry
away from computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need a keyboard which is at a human scale to use with
those devices,'' said Tim Butler, Electrotextiles' sales manager,
who reckons the cloth keyboard could be in production before next
March. ``The cost won't be a commercial impediment; it's just
deciding how much functionality you actually want built into the
cloth.''
</P>
<P>
   The company was started 18 months ago by two art college
graduates who realized the potential of weaving conductive fibers
into insulating material such as nylon, which makes it washable,
ironable and shockproof.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capital companies have expressed interest in funding the
start-up. Among potential applications are an aircraft seat which
could sense too great a pressure build-up at a particular point,
and adjust itself, or a hospital bed which could sense continuous
pressure which might lead to bed sores.
</P>
<P>
   But the first _ and busiest _ market is likely to be for people
on the move who want to have a flexible data entry system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can make a tie act as a mouse when it's moved over the
keyboard,'' said Butler. ``Or, using the software which decides
what various inputs actually mean, we can reprogram it so the
keyboard just turns into a device where you can draw, and the
drawing will be captured by the computer.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this curious 375-word article from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
