<HEADER>
A0394 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v PM-BUDGET-NYT     05-31 1615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, May 31:
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NKOREA (Yanji, China) _ Like hundreds of thousands of
hungry North Koreans have sneaked into neighboring China to find
food, escaping a deadly famine in their homeland. But now, Chinese
police have sharply increased their efforts to expel the North
Koreans living undercover in China, creating a climate of fear
along the border and fueling a potentially explosive international
refugee crisis. The number of ``food migrants'' sent back has at
least doubled this year, up to about 2,000 a month, aid groups on
the border say. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-HEZBOLLAH (Bint Jbail, Lebanon) _ After liberating
southern Lebanon with rockets and bombs, the Hezbollah militia is
back here in force _ this time with an army of doctors, nurses,
veterinarians, bulldozers, agronomists and engineers. One week
after the last Israeli soldiers retreated from the rocky hillside
villages that they controlled for nearly 18 years, the business of
keeping the water pumping and the hospitals running for an
estimated 75,000 Lebanese civilians has been taken on by Hezbollah.
By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-MASSACRE-DAILY (Clarksville, Tenn.) _ Edward Daily seemed
to have the resume of a true American hero. When the Associated
Press began investigating reports that the unit he said he was with
had massacred hundreds of South Koreans nearly 50 years ago, Daily,
69, seemed an ideal guide. The story led to a Pulitzer for the AP
and the unmasking of Daily. As the Army and other reporters began
to study the records, it became clear that Daily was neither the
war criminal nor war hero he claimed to be. He was never at the
scene of the massacre or even with the unit. And interviews with
veterans show that Daily, while developing his books, may have
airbrushed himself into their memories of the war. By Michael Moss.
</P>
<P>
   GEOGRAPHY-GENDERGAP (Undated) _ No girls were finalists in the
National Geographic geography contest last week, leading to
conflicting opinions among researchers about a gender gap in the
study of geography. By Kate Zernike.
</P>
<P>
   NY-COWS-COPYRIGHT (New York) _ Remember those painted fiberglass
cows that will soon be distributed around New York City? They have
brought charges of copyright theft and corporate espionage. And
they have turned into a major embarrassment for the Swiss
government. By Chris Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NICE-BOSSES (Undated) _ Remember Chainsaw Al? Being a tough guy
might have worked a decade ago, when corporate America was
downsizing and laying off workers by the millions. But the day of
the chief executive who boasts about how many jobs he cuts to
bolster his company's stock price is over. With unemployment at a
30-year low, bosses realize that they have to do more than pay good
salaries and lavish perks on their employees if they want to keep
them. They also have to be nice to them. By Amy Zipkin.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo _ NYT16 _ has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-INSURANCE (Shanghai) _ Sy Sternberg, the chairman of New
York Life Insurance, was in China this week trying to figure out
whom to meet so as to ensure that his company is next among the
dozens of insurers who have applied for a license to do business in
China. In China's murky business world, where market access depends
on whom you know and how happy you have made them _ though no one
will tell you who those people are. Instead, chief executives like
Sternberg operate on supposition and hearsay to identify the hidden
decision makers and cultivate ``top of mind,'' which means making
their company the first that Chinese leaders think of when
considering foreign supplicants from their industry. By Craig S.
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   BARCLAYS-AD-COLUMN (London) _ Barclays PLC, the British bank, is
in the midst of a very big cost-cutting program that at the very
least will make the 300-year-old financial institution smaller; it
just closed 172 branches. Matthew Barrett, the bank's new chief
executive, is hoping that by having a big brand, with the big reach
of the Internet _ where he thinks most consumers will bank in the
future _ he can counter the effect of the branch closings. The new
ad campaign, which was created by Leagas Delaney in London, was a
challenge because of the traditionally staid image of British
banking. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   APOLLO-HIP-HOP (New York) _ When a group of rap legends and
Harlem-based artists announced last month that they would be
mounting a Broadway-style musical in the landmark Apollo Theater,
the show was presented not only as an indicator of Harlem's
economic and cultural renewal, but as the birth of a virtually new
theatrical genre: the hip-hop musical. But nothing is ever simple
when it comes to exploring an embryonic artistic form, or, for that
matter, stretching the borders of artistic expression in Harlem. By
Nina Siegal.
</P>
<P>
   TONYS-POLITICS (New York) _ Contenders for the theater world's
Tony awards are jockeying for position. By Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
<P>
   KINGS-MEN (Undated) _ A Critic's Notebook on the enduring
greatness of ``All the King's Men,'' Robert Penn Warren's 1946
novel based on the career of Huey Long. By Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   MARIJUANA-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Grass,'' director Ron Mann's
punchy and enjoyable new documentary on the history of marijuana in
the U.S. during the 20th century, begins with the creation of
marijuana as a part of institutionalized racism, starting with laws
invented to make the substance illegal in the Southwest as a way of
persecuting Mexicans. Reviewed by Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BODIES-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Bodies in Motion and at Rest,''
by Thomas Lynch (Norton). Reviewed by Richard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   TV-BEAT-REVIEW (Undated) _ On PBS, American Masters special:
``The Source: The Story of the Beat Generation.'' Reviewed by Julie
Salamon.
</P>
<P>
   TV-LYNCHING-REVIEW (Undated) _ On Cinemax, ``The Tulsa Lynching
of 1921: A Hidden Story.'' Reviewed by Julie Salamon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Maureen Dowd writes about Rick Lazio
and his race for the U.S. Senate against Hillary Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Paul Krugman on Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN (East Rutherford, N.J.) _ Sports of The
Times column on Game 1 of the Devils-Stars, focusing on the two
goalies, New Jersey's martin Brodeur and Dallas's Ed Belfour. By
Dave Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN (Purchase, N.Y.) _ Sports of The Times column
on the Knicks' Chris Dudley, who provides some comic relief, some
thoughtful analysis and a little bit of help for a depleted Knick
team. Underappreciated but scrappy, he is emblematic of the Knicks
themselves. By Ira Berkow.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING (Moved in ``d'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-FOOD-SCIENCE (Bray, England) _ At the Fat Duck, a
restaurant 35 miles west of London, science joins art in the
endless search for better flavor. Chef Heston Blumenthal has allied
himself with Peter Barham, a physicist, with remarkable results. In
only a few years, the Duck has waddled to the top of several lists
of England's best restaurants. The first in a series of four
articles under the rubric: En Route England. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-ABSINTHE (Undated) _ On the bar scene in London after
the legalization of absinthe. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   BEETS (New York) _ Joan Hamburg, the WOR radio talk show host,
had not eaten beets since she was a child before she encountered
them a few weeks ago at Blue Hill in Greenwich Village. ``Some
people have phobias about bridges, some about elevators,'' she
said. ``I had a beet phobia.'' Yet when she didn't recognize her
nemesis hidden in a beet raviolo with her braised cod, she ate it
and discovered: ``It was spectacular. I may have gotten over my
phobia.'' That kind of conversion is not so unusual lately as a
vegetable generally perceived as a winter staple actually comes
into season, and in colors, sizes and shapes that beet phobics
reared on the canned kind could never imagine. By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: Compound butter _ how to
gild a simple skirt steak, with a primer on variations. By Mark
Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Florence Fabricant reviews ``Paris
in a Basket'' and ``The Greenmarket Cookbook.''
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (Undated) _ The column: Pineapple tart. By Wylie
Dufresne.
</P>
<P>
   ANCHOVIES (Undated) _ Anchovies, in fillet and paste form: Love
or hate them, they're an invaluable resource for any cook who wants
lots of flavor without a lot of work. By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Undated) _ The Wine Talk Column: So powerful a force
are Duboeuf wines in the Beaujolais market, and so distinctive is
their style, that most wine drinkers assume that all Beaujolais
tastes like Georges Duboeuf's ubiquitous Beaujolais-Villages. That
assumption is not far from wrong. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
