<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0397 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-BLAZERS-LAKERS-NY     05-31 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLAZERS-LAKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAIL BLAZERS DEFEAT LAKERS, 96-88 
</HEADLINE>
   By TOM SPOUSTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Using desperation as their sixth man, the Portland
Trail Blazers surprised the Los Angeles Lakers, 96-88, on Tuesday
night at the Staples Center and forced the Western Conference
finals to a Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers followed the lead of their two stars, Scottie
Pippen and Rasheed Wallace, who combined to hit the Lakers with a
tenacity that wasn't there while Portland fell behind, three games
to one, in the four-of-seven-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen scored 22 points and had 6 steals and 4 blocked shots.
Wallace had 22 points and 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I set the precedent of being aggressive early, I knew my
teammates would follow,'' said Pippen, who bruised his hand while
landing on the court after a collision with Robert Horry. ``It was
just a matter of making sure we stayed steady and continued that
throughout the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers turned back every Laker rally and fiercely
protected the 80-67 lead they held through four quarters. Los
Angeles came within 9, at 87-78, with 6 minutes 18 seconds to play,
but got no closer as the Lakers lost for the second time at home in
this series.
</P>
<P>
   With a chance to reach the National Basketball Association
finals for the first time since 1991, the Lakers fell flat on their
jump shots, making only 38 percent. Shaquille O'Neal led Los
Angeles with 31 points and 21 rebounds. Kobe Bryant, playing with
five fouls for most of the fourth quarter, had 17 points.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Rice and Robert Horry combined for 4-of-19 shooting. The
Lakers also made only 6 of 27 3-point attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shot too may 3-point shots,'' Lakers Coach Phil Jackson
said, ``and ended up standing on the perimeter too much trying to
get the ball to Shaq and not finding a way. You have to give
Portland credit for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland shot 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense has been strong this series, except for a few
lapses,'' said Trail Blazers Coach Mike Dunleavy. ``Tonight, we
really didn't have any for a few lapses. Tonight, we really didn't
have any breakdowns. It made a big difference for us.''
</P>
<P>
   After fighting off a 10-point surge by O'Neal, the Trail Blazers
broke down the Lakers late in the third quarter. They finished with
an 8-0 run, sparked by Steve Smith's jump shot and Wallace's two
free throws, before Detlef Schrempf ended the scoring with a layup
and two free throws with 1.3 seconds left following a foul by Rick
Fox.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers threatened to blow out the Lakers midway
through the third quarter, three times taking 9-point leads. But
O'Neal took charge, scoring 10 straight points and making a
full-court pass to Horry to pull the Lakers within 5, at 70-65,
with 2:30 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers made a quick 10-5 run early in the third quarter
after Arvydas Sabonis' jump shot gave Portland a 57-47 lead. Bryant
hit a 3-pointer, O'Neal had two baskets and a free throw, and Ron
Harper sank a jumper to pull the Lakers within 5, at 62-57.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers shot 50 percent in the first half, yet managed
only a 53-45 lead. Pippen, who led Portland with 15 points in the
half, took only one shot in the second quarter, a 3-pointer that
beat the horn and set up a familiar situation for the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Lakers played a mediocre first half, this time
missing 31-of-45 attempts to shoot only 31 percent. Once again,
they stayed within striking range, this time by making 14-of-15
free throws. O'Neal scored 15 points and Bryant had 8 points
despite hitting only 1-of-7 shots. Horry was 0 of 6 and Rice was 1
of 4.
</P>
<P>
   A dunk by O'Neal and two free throws by Bryant cut the Trail
Blazers' lead to 48-45, but a basket by Wallace and Pippen's late
3-pointer lifted Portland's lead back to 8 points. Wallace had 11
points and 7 rebounds in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   As they did in the first halves of Game3 and 4, the Trail
Blazers seized the momentum, and they took an early 10-point lead.
Bonzi Wells hit a 3-pointer and Sabonis followed with a jump shot
to put Portland ahead by 40-30 with 7:21 to play in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal continued his smooth touch at the free-throw line, making
3-of-4 attempts in the first half to go with 9 of 9 from Game 4.
From the field, O'Neal was 6 of 14 with 9 rebounds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pippen played a near-flawless first quarter, scored 12 points to
help the Trail Blazers take a 26-24 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
