<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0400 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     05-31 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LOS ANGELES _ It was the very spotlight under which he has always
felt so uncomfortable, but for a night it bathed him, caressed him,
made him look brighter than all of the Hollywood stars at
courtside.
</P>
<P>
   On this night when the Trail Blazers were fighting for their
playoff lives, it was Scottie Pippen in complete control, a vision
of dogged determination and sleek, fluid athleticism. He was a
velvet hammer, a running, jumping picture of poise, suffering no
mental meltdowns while showing the world all of the talent that is
inside of him in a 96-88 victory.
</P>
<P>
   It was an incredible touch of irony that Pippen should choose
this game and this night to step up and display all of the
leadership skills that Phil Jackson had said it would take for
Portland to triumph. Of course, the Lakers coach had said it in a
goading manner before the start of the series, hoping to put the
pressure on Pippen and then watch him collapse from it.
</P>
<P>
   So Pippen comes out with the Blazers teetering on the brink of
elimination to collect 22 points, six rebounds, six steals, four
blocked shots and three assists. But those are just numbers, and
Pippen was about more than numbers. He was about calm, confidence,
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   In a setting where so many members of the hipster audience
choose to wear their sunglasses indoors, it was Pippen who right
from the start always looked like the coolest cat in the Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   He had been fined $10,000 prior to the game for an elbowing and
forearm-exchange incident with the Lakers' John Salley in the final
minutes of the Game 4 loss in Portland. But rather than complain,
Pippen seemed to use that as a motivator, a sign he was willing get
down and dirty, do whatever it takes.
</P>
<P>
   After losing back-to-back games on their home floor and losing
second-half leads both times, the Blazers faced considerable
questions about their pedigree as real title contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after letting an opportunity to close the deal slip through
their hands, the questions will be asked of the Lakers. The
presumed heirs to the throne got 31 points and 21 rebounds out of
Shaquille O'Neal. But the fresh prince of LA, Kobe Bryant,
struggled all night and shot just 4-for-13 before fouling out with
4:45 to play.
</P>
<P>
   It was another game in which the Blazers jumped out fast, and
you always had the feeling the Lakers would make another run. They
did, but they could never get the play that put them over the top.
</P>
<P>
   And through it all, you could never take your eyes off Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   There he was running the Portland offense, pushing the ball up
the court in the transition game, getting it to the proper scorers
in the sets. He knifed through defenders to make tough layups, and
he pulled up in the face of the LA defense with steely nerves to
make clutch jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   There he was at the center of a stellar Blazers defensive
effort, cutting off the passing lanes for his half-dozen steals and
playing spectacular help defense to block his four shots.
</P>
<P>
   There he was diving on the floor for loose balls, even
dislocating a finger on one fall to the floor and never missing a
beat.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of big-game performance that fans of the Chicago
Bulls dynasty were used to seeing from Michael Jordan. And maybe
somewhere on the other side of the country, Jordan was watching and
smiling. After all, he had seen much of this before over the years
from Pippen but rarely all together like this and never when all of
the burden was upon him.
</P>
<P>
   Surely Jordan, like the rest of us, watches with interest to
find out if the ultimate second banana on those six NBA
championship teams can pull the wagon by himself. For despite all
of his contributions, those Bulls were always Jordan's team first
and then Jackson's team, never Pippen's.
</P>
<P>
   His track record shows he has played big games before. But what
makes one question whether he is great or just very good has been
an inability to deliver them night after night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scottie was a warrior out there,'' said Blazers coach Mike
Dunleavy. ``He kept us going in the direction we needed to go and
wouldn't let us waver.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the kind of game and the kind of situation Portland
wanted him for, to hold up the Blazers when their legs were wobbly
and to help Dunleavy dissect the famed triangle offense of the
Lakers that had been brought in from Chicago. To lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just did what I had to do,'' Pippen said.
</P>
<P>
   Which on one evening of desperation was enough to make him the
brightest star in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   His legacy without Jordan will depend on what happens next.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
