<SLUG> BC-BKW-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORM READY TO WRITE ITS OWN CHAPTER IN SEATTLE SPORTS SCENE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The final practice before showtime for Seattle's
newest pro sports franchise was the stuff of Army boot camp.
</P>
<P>
   It was tough to tell Tuesday whether Storm coach Lin Dunn was
trying to prepare her players for the inaugural season or kill 'em.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't really matter if we're ready,'' Dunn said,
unrelenting in her forward charge into history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going.''
</P>
<P>
   That's right, Seattle's WNBA expansion team opens its season
Wednesday night in Sacramento, a team loaded with so much talent
there's talk that the Monarchs could knock off the three-time
defending champions from Houston.
</P>
<P>
   We'll wait and see on that one.
</P>
<P>
   Then, ready or not, the Storm make the quick turnaround back up
the coast for Thursday night's home opener in KeyArena against the
Comets.
</P>
<P>
   It may be especially memorable that the Storm will cut its baby
teeth on the likes of Yolanda Griffith, Ruthie Bolton-Holifield and
Ticha Penicheiro of the Monarchs.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's best that when the lights, cameras, action and hype
kick in at KeyArena in front of what should be a sold-out crowd of
12,969, it's with Sheryl Swoopes, Cynthia Cooper and Tina Thompson
in the house.
</P>
<P>
   Women's basketball turns another page in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in general it's a great opportunity, another stride,
another step forward for women's basketball, especially here in the
Seattle area,'' said Storm guard Jamie Redd, the all-time scoring
leader from the University of Washington who will make her pro
debut with the Storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fan-based city. They really support sports here,
especially women, and I think it's a great opportunity for this
city, for this team. For me to be a part of it is a great
feeling,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   We all know the first chapters of the women's basketball story.
</P>
<P>
   It started at the University of Washington, where former coach
Chris Gobrecht and her Huskies were reliably compelling enough to
pack Hec Ed.
</P>
<P>
   We were watching when some of that love and loyalty carried over
to the short-lived reign of the Seattle Reign of the American
Basketball League.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of the Bay area, which does not have a WNBA franchise
despite the league's expansion to 16 teams, and outside of
Knoxville (University of Tennessee) or Storrs, Conn. (the OTHER
Husky women), no place in America has been quite so rabid for quite
so long as Seattle is for women's hoops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seattle is deserving of this, the fans and everything,'' Storm
assistant coach Kathy Anderson said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A former assistant with the UW women's program, Anderson helped
with stats during Reign games and later became an assistant to
Phoenix Mercury head coach Cheryl Miller.
</P>
<P>
   So Anderson has a keen sense of why this Storm debut is
something for the city to champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seattle was one of the first major cities to make women's
basketball go. It may have been the first. I can't think of another
place where women's basketball was accepted in a major city that
did it before Seattle did it,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, I'm very excited to see all the people who were such a
part of that, who are having the opportunity to see professional
women's basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that this is an entirely Pollyanna-esque proposition.
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA is here because of the NBA's muscle. The ABL was
prevented from expanding its sponsorship and broadcast base by the
strong-arm tactics of the NBA. The grass-roots, player-owned ABL
was squashed by the corporate Goliath that decided it, too, wanted
to field a women's league.
</P>
<P>
   There is some upside to this turn of events _ events that still
taste sour to some Reign fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think where (the WNBA is) different (from when the ABL was
operating) is that the best are all in one league now. So I think
you're going to see the best competing against each other,''
Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, there's a lot of versatility, especially in the post
players. You're going to see a lot of post players come out and
play out on the perimeter and be active out there. There are lot of
players, whether they're American or European, who have played over
there, so the international style might be more apparent. So in
some ways that brings a little more versatility, a little bit more
of a spread-out, wide-open game.''
</P>
<P>
   The new chapter opens with this sort of promise.
</P>
<P>
   What remains to be seen is whether ABL fans can forgive and
forget.
</P>
<P>
   What remains to be seen is whether the Storm can be an
entertaining alternative to a night at Safeco Field, where the
perfect Northwest summer weather is a draw regardless of how the
Mariners are faring.
</P>
<P>
   What remains to be seen is whether the Storm can carve an
identity for themselves _ separate from being the kid sisters to
the Sonics and something more than summertime filler for the people
who run Full House, owners of the Sonics and Storm.
</P>
<P>
   These things could seem like obstacles for a fledgling team like
the Storm.
</P>
<P>
   But given the history of women's basketball in Seattle, the
future surely holds some good times to be had by all.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
