r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-SIDEBAR-LA     05-31 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-SIDEBAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIPPEN FINALLY TAKES CHARGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Some Laker fans unfurled a banner high up in
Staples Center on Tuesday, probably too high for Scottie Pippen to
see.
</P>
<P>
   It said: ``Pippen + Jordan  &QC;  Ring. Pippen - Jordan  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   The sentiment still might be proven true. But for this night,
Pippen, playing most of the night with two dislocated fingers on
his left hand, proved he could be an impact player without his more
famous partner.
</P>
<P>
   In leading the Trail Blazers to a 96-88 Game 5 victory, Pippen
did it all: brought the ball up the court, signaled instructions to
his teammates, exploited Lakers' foul troubles and led the team in
scoring.
</P>
<P>
   And this was after he was fined $10,000 for hitting John Salley
late in Game 4. The penalty came down earlier Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be aggressive,'' said Pippen, who broke Jordan's
all-time playoff record for career steals with 380. ``We know in
our minds and hearts we can beat this team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Scottie's a warrior,'' Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy said.
``He's out there, giving his best. ... He just really wanted it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen also whined and complained a little, but this time, he
rose above it and scored 22 points, six more than he has averaged
this series. That included a perfect 6-for-6 first half from the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen attempted just one second-period shot, a 3-pointer at the
buzzer, and made it to give Portland a 53-45 lead.
</P>
<P>
   His other numbers - six steals, three assists, four blocked
shots and neutralization of Ron Harper (14 points but 1 of 5
3-pointers) - further illustrated his worth.
</P>
<P>
   So back to Portland for Game 6 they go.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an all-around player,'' Detlef Schrempf said of Pippen.
``He's been around. He knows what it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Schrempf has been around, too, having won the NBA Sixth Man
Award in 1990-91 and 1991-92. But, of course, he doesn't have the
six championship rings Pippen has.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's flashed me the gold a couple of times,'' Bonzi Wells
said. ``He blinded me with the diamonds. But that's Scottie. He's
here to give us a taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen had been averaging 15.8 points, third-highest on his
team. But with elimination on the line, Pippen decided he needed to
make sure his team went home today - and take the Lakers with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's more aggressive, he's focused, and he's setting a good
example for everyone else,'' Schrempf said.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen seemed a step quicker Tuesday, driving the lane, making
some flashy passes, swatting away Shaquille O'Neal, that it offset
his whinier moments - making a dunk and wanting the call,
complaining when being called for a charge.
</P>
<P>
   But like the Pippen of Chicago days, he came to play and
inspired his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Wells referred to his ``offensive intensity, defensive
intensity. Doesn't matter. Scottie's a real vocal leader. He talks
to on the court in a way that's respectable. He doesn't belittle
anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, anyone not wearing an NBA referee's shirt. But the fact
remains, Portland is alive today because the man called upon to
lead did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
