<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-SEATTLE-STORM-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRACTICE TIME OVER FOR STORM; REAL DEAL STARTS IN SACRAMENTO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MEREDITH BAGLEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It's the moment they've all been waiting for. After
months of planning, building, practicing and waiting, Seattle Storm
players and coaches realize their WNBA dream Wednesday night at 7
when the Storm visits the Sacramento Monarchs.
</P>
<P>
   For head coach Lin Dunn, the process of starting a team from
scratch has been a whirlwind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like just yesterday that I was dribbling a ball
through Seattle to sell tickets, and we were getting our logo and
name,'' she said as the Storm closed training camp Tuesday. ``All
of a sudden it's tipoff time.''
</P>
<P>
   Facing the powerful Monarchs, led by 1999 MVP Defensive Player
and Newcomer of the Year Yolanda Griffith, Dunn wouldn't mind a bit
more preparation time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like another week of practice since we're so young, but I
think a lot of teams wouldn't mind that,'' Dunn said. ``It doesn't
matter if we're ready _ it's time to go.''
</P>
<P>
   After their first franchise victory over Los Angeles on Friday,
the Storm players feel confident they can pull off a similar upset
in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beating L.A. was a tremendous morale boost for us,'' Dunn
said. ``We'd seen progress all week in practice, but to go into
their building and win was a real boost. It shows things are
working.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle put the pieces together to top the Sparks 75-69, finding
an inside scorer in Simone Edwards (18 points, seven rebounds) to
complement Edna Campbell's deadly perimeter game.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, who scored a career-high 25 in Los Angeles, finished
the preseason as the league's leading scorer.
</P>
<P>
   The Storm also cut down on turnovers and fouls against the
Sparks and shot over 40 percent from the field for the first time.
Dunn knows her team will need that kind of all-around effort to
dethrone the Monarchs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will try to balance our scoring like we did in L.A.,'' Dunn
said. ``We also need to be patient and take the air out of the ball
a bit. We need to break them down and hold the ball a bit longer
than other teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle will depart from its usual uptempo style in response to
the potent Sacramento attack. The league's second-highest scoring
team last year, the Monarchs haven't slowed down, posting a 4-0
preseason record with two 20-point victories.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Tangela Smith leads Sacramento in scoring with 14.3
average, while the 6-foot-3 Griffith is averaging 12.5 points and
8.3 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   All-Star point guard Ticha Penicheiro led the league in assists
last year, with 7.1 per game, and Olympic team member Ruthie
Bolton-Holifield gives the Monarchs another All-Star threat on the
outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``As talented as Los Angeles was, Sacramento may be even
better,'' Dunn said. ``Yolanda Griffith is the premier power
forward in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffith, also Olympics-bound, led or ranked in the top three in
five major statistical categories last year, despite missing
several games late in the season to a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't shut down Yolanda,'' Dunn said. ``We will try to
limit the time she touches the ball and make her give it up when
she does get it.''
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Seattle must continue to score inside to take the
pressure off Campbell, and play solid defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is defense,'' Storm point guard Sonja Henning said.
``They have great athletes who can score a lot, and we need to slow
them down and make it a half-court game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Monarchs are candidates to unseat Houston as WNBA champion
this year, a prediction not lost on Henning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sacramento is one of the best, if not the best, teams in the
league this year,'' she said. ``We know that, and this game will be
a great opportunity to show us where we are and where we need to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose, one outcome is for sure for Seattle's new WNBA
team: it's game time.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Meredith Bagley can be reached at 206-448-8211
</P>
<P>
   or meredithbagley &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
