<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 02:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0410 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-ROCKIES-HN     05-31 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-ROCKIES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
DENVER _ If Astros manager Larry Dierker starts wearing sunglasses
at night games, it won't be because he's trying to make a fashion
statement. It's just that he might do anything to shade his view of
what has been happening on the field night after night.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Astros let another victory slip through their grasp Tuesday
night, losing 10-7 to the Colorado Rockies at Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   What was shaping up as an uplifting come-from-behind victory
ended like so many other losses this season. The Astros dug
themselves a four-run hole after three innings but took the lead in
the eighth, only to watch the comeback go to waste.
</P>
<P>
   Easy come, easy go.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies scored four runs in the bottom of the eighth,
sending the Astros to their 11th loss in their last 15 games. The
Astros fell 11 games behind National League Central
Division-leading St. Louis, matching the most games they have been
out of first place this season.
</P>
<P>
   Yorkis Perez's bases-loaded walk to Todd Helton forced home the
decisive run, but the Astros were left to wonder if the eighth
inning might have played out differently if not for Craig Biggio's
throwing error on a ground ball by Jeff Cirillo with one out,
runners at first and second, and the score tied at 7.
</P>
<P>
   One out was a given, and a potential inning-ending double play
for reliever Marc Valdes (1-1) seemed like a possibility, although
it wasn't a sure thing. Biggio attempted to get an out at second
base, but his throw to shortstop Julio Lugo was off the mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think we were going to get two (outs) on that play,''
Biggio said. ``But we should have gotten the one out. I didn't have
a good grip on the ball, and it ended up being costly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a lot of mistakes. When you're having the kind of
season we're having, every mistake is costly. There always seems to
be something happening during the course of a game that costs us.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, it was another sloppy game for the Astros, who were
charged with two errors and failed to make at least that many other
plays. The baserunning also was suspect, particularly that of Mitch
Meluskey, who was picked off after leading off the third inning
with a walk and got caught in a rundown after driving in the
go-ahead run in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the inconsistent defense that has made Dierker cringe
the most. The Astros are on a pace to commit 124 errors, which
would be their highest total in three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game was not about Todd Helton,'' Dierker said. ``This
was about catching the ball and not playing good defense. When you
play in a park like this, you have to play good defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get the single out on the Biggio play, there's a base
open, and we walk Helton. You have to make the plays here, and we
didn't make the plays. If we make the plays, we can hold the score
down to a level we need to win games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't even seem like the team that we've seen for the
past three years. We're kicking the ball around, and it's hard to
watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, the Astros couldn't wait to get out of
Houston to escape Enron Field. Now, they can't wait to go back.
Tuesday's loss was their eighth in a row on the road and the 13th
in their last 16 games away from Enron.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros wasted a balanced 12-hit attack, led by Bill Spiers,
Ken Caminiti and Richard Hidalgo, who had two hits apiece. Lance
Berkman chimed in with a career-high four RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti left the game after his sixth-inning single because of
a mild strain of his right hamstring. His status will be evaluated
daily.
</P>
<P>
   Astros starter Scott Elarton would have liked nothing more than
to pick up a victory in front of the 60 family members and friends
who made the trip from Lamar, Colo., to watch their favorite son
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies scored four runs off Elarton over the first three
innings and had nine hits and six runs during the righthander's
six-inning performance, which was better than the pitching line
indicates.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably the best I've felt since the surgery,'' said
Elarton, referring to the offseason procedure on his right rotator
cuff. ``I felt like my pitches had good action on them. They hit
quite a few good pitches. I made my share of mistakes, but they did
a good job of situational hitting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies scored two runs in the first inning, one on Helton's
sacrifice fly. Helton, who ranks among the league leaders with 51
RBIs, has driven in 10 runs in five games against the Astros this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado added another run in the second on Tom Goodwin's
double, and Jeffrey Hammonds' RBI single in the third pushed the
lead to four runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros finally joined the scoring in the fourth inning on
Berkman's three-run homer off Rockies starter Kevin Jarvis. Berkman
has homered in three of the last four games, and the Astros have at
least one homer in a club-record 17 consecutive games. Since being
recalled from Class AAA New Orleans on Friday, Berkman is hitting
.375 with nine RBIs and six runs in five games.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies added two more runs in the fifth on a single by
Darren Bragg and a sacrifice fly by Brent Mayne, who has driven in
four runs in the first two games of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti led off the sixth inning with a single up the middle
but was lifted in favor of pinch runner Lugo. Hidalgo's double to
left gave the Astros runners at second and third with nobody out.
</P>
<P>
   Lefthanded reliever Brian Bohanon replaced Jarvis after
Hidalgo's two-base hit. Berkman and Daryle Ward each drove in a run
with groundouts, trimming the Rockies' lead to 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   Meluskey's two-run single in the eighth gave the Astros their
only lead, but it was short-lived after the Rockies turned the
tables, scoring four runs (one earned) off Valdes, who was making
his second appearance with the Astros since being acquired in a
trade with Tampa Bay last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
