<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS SEE OPPORTUNITY SLIP AWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When aggression gave way to duress, when momentum
was surrendered to desperation, and when precision disappeared in a
cloud of dust and a crowd of bodies in the lane, the Lakers' steady
charge toward the NBA Finals stopped with a thunderous thud,
accompanied by a repetitive clanging sound.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen charged, and the Lakers bowed.
</P>
<P>
   Rasheed Wallace attacked, and they deferred.
</P>
<P>
   And jump shot after jump shot after jump shot bounced and banged
and dropped harmlessly away as the Lakers lost a chance to clinch a
Finals berth, falling 96-88 to the Portland Trail Blazers on
Tuesday before a subdued 18,997 at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Momentum belonged to the Lakers after a two-game sweep at
Portland over the weekend. But the night belonged to Pippen, whose
22 points and masterful play at both ends of the court took the
Lakers off balance, and gave Portland new life in the Western
Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers take a fragile 3-2 lead into the Rose Garden on
Friday for Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be ticked,'' said Glen Rice. ``We had an opportunity
to close it, and it was here on our home court. But now we've gotta
realize that we've got to regroup and be ready to go to war
Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   And they'll have to remember to pack instructions to assembling
the triangle offense.
</P>
<P>
   For most the evening, the Lakers alternated between standing
around, waiting for Shaquille O'Neal to free himself up, and
settling for perimeter shots. In a game they never led, the Lakers
attempted an eye-popping 27 shots from the 3-point arc, making just
six, and shot 30 for 79 (38 percent) overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to play smarter,'' O'Neal said. ``We need to
stick with what got us the wins.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal used a late charge to get to 31 points _ his high this
series _ and added 21 rebounds, but he also committed five
turnovers, and no one else could contribute consistent offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a disappointment for us,'' said coach Phil Jackson,
``but it's not a surprise. We didn't shoot the ball well, we shot
too many 3-point shots. And we ended up standing on the perimeter a
lot in this ballgame, trying to get the ball in to Shaq but not
finding a way, and you have to credit Portland for some of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers also get some credit for destroying the Lakers'
ability to play defense. Kobe Bryant was dogged by early foul
trouble, as were fellow guards Brian Shaw and Ron Harper, most of
that damage done by Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   No one criticized the officiating, but the Lakers clearly were
befuddled by some early tough calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing, because depending upon how the referees
call a ballgame in a night (determines) what kind of defense you
can play in this game,'' Jackson said. ``And we like to play good
individual defense, and suddenly all our players are in foul
trouble _ Shaw, Harper and Kobe. Then we have to end up rotating
and start running around playing junk defense. ... Scottie created
a foul situation. That's what happened to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant couldn't accomplish much offensively either, going 4 for
13 from the field for 17 points, balanced out by six turnovers in a
wild performance reminiscent of the old Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   And Rice, coming off a 21-point breakthrough in Game 4, went
silent again, finishing with 4 points on 1-of-8 shooting, going 0
for 5 from the arc. Robert Horry added a 3-for-11 line off the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than abandoning our offense tonight and not being able
to play the aggressive defense to stop their big guards, that put
us in a hole,'' said Rick Fox. ``And we got not passive, but a
little back on our heels again.''
</P>
<P>
   The defeat dropped the Lakers to 2-4 in closeout games in this
postseason, proving they still have a few things to learn about
becoming champions. As he has in the past, Jackson spun this as an
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to take a little more time to win this
series,''Jackson said, ``and I think it's really good for us as a
basketball team. This team has not grown enough to understand some
of the subtleties of what we're trying to do. And it's a good
measure for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Holding to form in this series, the Lakers sputtered early and
fell to a double-digit lead. And after shooting 31.1 percent in the
first half, they were fortunate to be down only eight points, 53-45
at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen hit the floor with fire shooting from his fingertips,
once again becoming a force at both ends of the floor to lead the
Blazers' charge. By the end of the first quarter, he already had 12
points, a steal and three blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   By halftime, he also had a dislocated left ring finger, but
still had a team-high 15 points and had upped his steals total to
three.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers never trailed, hitting 50 percent of their shots _
including a buzzer-beating 3-pointer from Pippen to close the half.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, just maybe, the Lakers got a little comfortable with
their 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were obviously looking to go home tonight with our minds on
preparing for the next round,'' Fox said, ``but that wasn't the
case.''
</P>
<P>
   And an odd series in which each team has won twice on the
other's homecourt stuck to its pattern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, you all don't listen to me when I talk,'' Portland
coach Mike Dunleavy said. ``I told you from the very beginning that
I didn't think there was a home-court advantage in this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that either team was capable of winning every game
on the other team's home court, that it was going to come down to
how you play every night, and that's been the key.''
</P>
</TEXT>
