<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-WEST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTLAND PUTS LAKERS' CORONATION ON HOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This time, there was no second-half scoring
drought. The crucial free throws from an unlikely source did not
materialize. And the Portland Trail Blazers never lost their
composure.
</P>
<P>
   In other words: A coronation proclaiming the Los Angeles Lakers
as kings of the Western Conference was put on hold.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers knew they needed a royal performance Tuesday night
in the Staples Center, and they crowned the Lakers 96-88 in Game 5
to extend the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Once demoralized, the Blazers can force a Game 7 here Sunday by
winning Game 6 Friday in the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know in our minds and hearts we can outplay this team,''
said Scottie Pippen, who led the Blazers with 22 points, six
rebounds, six steals and high intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've outplayed this team throughout the series. We just
haven't finished them off (in games).''
</P>
<P>
   Now trailing the best-of-seven series 3-2, the Blazers exorcised
every demon that plagued them in back-to-back home losses. They
pressured the Lakers on both ends of the floor, got major
production from their key players and won their second straight
game on the road in this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to go down very easily,'' Portland coach Mike
Dunleavy said. ``I wouldn't expect any less.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers had won just two of their previous 11 road games in
the conference finals. But they knew they could win in the Staples
Center, as one of those victories was a 106-77 thrashing of the
Lakers here in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's game took on similar characteristics, considering the
Blazers were crisp and the Lakers were cold offensively. Los
Angeles shot 38 percent, including a dismal 6-for-27 from beyond
the 3-point arc.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in a hole. We're still trying to fight out, and we
still have to take it one game at a time,'' said Blazers forward
Rasheed Wallace, who matched Pippen's 22 points and added 10
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers have reclaimed the momentum, if not planted a seed
of doubt in the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to take a little more time to win this
series, and it's good for us,'' Lakers coach Phil Jackson said.
``This team has not grown enough to understand some of the
subtleties of what we're trying to do, and it is a good measure for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Jackson's way of saying his team played out of control,
without focus and would not know killer instinct if it came wrapped
in purple and gold.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles is now 2-4 in potential series-ending games during
this postseason run. The Lakers had a 3-0 lead against Phoenix in
the Western Conference semifinals but lost Game 4 before winning
Game 5. They were up 2-0 against Sacramento and went the distance,
finally securing Game 5 in that first-round series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an opportunity missed,'' said center Shaquille O'Neal,
whose 31 points and 21 rebounds made him the only productive Laker.
``There is an old basketball saying: `You live by the jump shot and
you die by the jump shot.' We shot 27 threes and only made six. I
thought we played pretty good defense, but we didn't put the ball
in the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   The poise Portland displayed didn't help, either.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of going into a complete funk in the third quarter, the
Blazers, ahead 72-67 with 1:53 left in the third, closed out the
quarter with an 8-0 run.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Pippen, the Blazers' entire lineup remained in attack
mode.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fought that third quarter. The last two games they kicked
our (butts) in the third. But we fought hard this time,'' Wallace
said, his voice booming as he talked about his teammates'
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal had little help. Laker guard Kobe Bryant finished with 17
points but missed 9 of 13 shots. Glen Rice misfired on 7 of his 8
attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to be a championship team, we're going to have
to face adversity,'' Bryant said. `` ... Without stress, there's no
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of those Laker misses were bricks, some _ particularly
in Bryant's case _ due to poor shot selection. There was also just
too much Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   With 9:20 left in the third quarter, Bryant picked up his fourth
foul while guarding Pippen, who made up for passive performances in
Games 3 and 4. Pippen took the ball right at Bryant and the rim
from the opening tip.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen did not miss until 5:47 was left in the third. He sank
his first six shots, including a 3-pointer that put Portland ahead
53-45 as the first half ended.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen took turns tormenting Bryant, Brian Shaw and Ron Harper _
all of whom played with foul trouble. Jackson argued that the
situation forced the Lakers to play ``junk'' defense, utilizing
double-teams when they would rather play straight up.
</P>
<P>
   Portland, the more active team, took advantage and kept making
shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when it started to get rough out there, we continued to
go with it,'' Blazers forward Brian Grant said. ``We didn't blow
up, lose our cool or do anything to hurt the team. Now we can go
home.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
