NYT-05-31-00 0241EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 02:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0415 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      05-31 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABBOTT GOOD, BUT NOT GOOD ENOUGH AGAINST WHITE SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM CAPLE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ On the other hand, Paul Abbott avoided being hit by
any broken bats, baseballs, batting helmets, shin guards, water
jugs, Moose antlers or other assorted dangerous projectiles.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott also pitched very well in his first start since getting
hit in the face with a broken bat last week _ just not as well as
Chicago White Sox starter James Baldwin. Abbott allowed two solo
home runs in seven innings, Baldwin held the Mariners to one run
and that was the difference in Seattle's 2-1 loss to the White Sox
at Safeco Field Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a loss, so it wasn't good enough,'' Abbott said. ``I gave
up seven runs against Oakland (two weeks ago) and the result is the
same. James Baldwin was just excellent tonight, and I gave up one
run too many.''
</P>
<P>
   Abbott, who has been dogged by injuries throughout his career,
had a scary moment in his previous start last week in Baltimore
when Harold Baines' bat broke and sailed into the pitcher's face,
literally knocking him out of the game with cuts, a broken nose and
a black eye. As Jamie Moyer said, if the bat hit him slightly
differently, it could have been the end of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the bat could have missed him entirely as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake and watched it again last night. I probably
shouldn't have done that,'' Abbott said. ``The first time was all
right, but the second time ... I went to bed thinking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Abbott said his close encounter with the bat didn't bother him
once he got on the mound Tuesday night, and he certainly pitched
like it didn't.
</P>
<P>
   With the area around his right eye bruised blue and green (``To
match the uniform,'' he said), Abbott pitched what was easily his
best game of the season, and one of the better games of his career.
He threw his pitches for strikes and kept the hitters off-balance
with his outstanding changeup. He walked none, struck out seven and
allowed only four hits in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Abbott, two of those hits were home runs.
Carlos Lee slammed a pitch well over the center-field fence for a
game-tying home run in the fifth inning and Ray Durham lined a 3-2
pitch just over the wall in left, giving Chicago the lead in the
sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the first one, I caught too much of the plate and he
hammered it, like he's supposed to do,'' Abbott said. ``I had
Durham behind 0-2 and had him on the defensive, but he fought back.
I didn't want to walk him.''
</P>
<P>
   Durham's home run spelled the difference, thanks to Baldwin, who
is 8-1 with a 3.09 ERA, off to the best start of his career. A
notoriously slow starter, Baldwin is 16-5 since last year's
All-Star break. He's pitching so well that ESPN called for a
postgame interview, which Baldwin did while standing in the dugout
in his underwear.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin limited the Mariners to one run and four hits in seven
innings, even cooling down league batting leader Edgar Martinez,
who was held hitless for just the second time in the past 27 games.
</P>
<P>
   The only run Baldwin allowed was driven in by his old roommate
and good friend, Seattle center fielder Mike Cameron. The two
roomed together in the minors and Cameron's rookie year in the
majors, but had never faced each other until Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin struck out Cameron in the first inning, but the
outfielder fared better in the third when he gave Seattle a brief
lead, singling home Rickey Henderson from second base. That was all
Seattle could manage against Baldwin, while the White Sox scored
just enough against Abbott to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt my presence and I felt his,'' Cameron said. ``He
pitched us pretty tough tonight. He kept us off-balance, and made
some good pitches when he had to. He's throwing all his pitches for
strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the loss, the Mariners remained in first place in the
American League West, where just 1{ games separate Seattle from
last-place Oakland. Chicago maintained its surprising first-place
lead over Cleveland in the AL Central.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Caple can be reached at 206-448-8006
</P>
<P>
   or at jimcaple &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
