<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS LOSE IT IN NINTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Another day, another Dodger injured. Or two.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Todd Hundley and reserve outfielder Geronimo Berroa both
left in the sixth inning with injuries. Hundley strained a rib cage
muscle on his right side and Berroa suffered a contusion on his
left foot.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the troubles of the night was a blown save by Jeff
Shaw as the Mets rallied for six runs in the ninth, including a
grand slam by Todd Pratt, to beat the Dodgers 10-5 Tuesday at
Dodger Stadium in a game than lasted more than four hours.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers entered the ninth leading 5-4, but Shaw failed to
record an out before being replaced by one-time Chicago Cubs closer
Terry Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza led off the ninth with a single to left and was
replaced at first by Jay Payton. Robin Ventura walked on four
pitches and Todd Zeile singled to center to score Payton, tying the
score 5-5 and chasing Shaw. It was Shaw's fifth blown save in 16
chances, and he fell to 2-3.
</P>
<P>
   Adams struck out pinch-hitter Joe McEwing for the first out, but
he walked Kurt Abbott, who was hitting .194, to load the bases.
Adams struck out Joe Nunnally, but then walked Melvin Mora,
recalled earlier in the day to replace Rey Ordonez, to force in a
run and give the Mets a 6-5 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt then hit Adams' 1-2 pitch over the fence in left field to
give the Mets a 10-5 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Making it potentially worse is the loss of Hundley, who's added
another dimension to the lineup because of his health. He has 13
homers and 33 RBI, and was providing offense as a left-handed and
right-handed hitter,as well as depth to the middle of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley doubled to lead off the sixth off Mets starter Bobby
Jones. Pinch-hitter Kevin Elster singled to center off reliever
Dennis Cook, but Hundley was held at third by coach Glenn Hoffman.
Hundley apparently injured the intercostal muscle of his rib cage
while stopping suddenly. He was replaced by Chad Kreuter, who
scored on Berroa's single.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hollandsworth struck out, but Mark Grudzielanek gave the
Dodgers a 5-4 lead with a single to left off Pat Mahomes to score
Elster. But on the play Berroa aggravated his injury, which he hurt
when he fouled a pitch off his foot during his at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Berroa was diagnosed with a left foot contusion and was having
precautionary X-rays taken.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley will be re-evaluated today, but it didn't look good. He
needed help walking down the dugout stairs and was in obvious pain.
</P>
<P>
   If Hundley's injury forces him to the disabled list, he'll be
the fifth starter to be there this season. Currently, center
fielder Devon White and third baseman Adrian Beltre are on the
15-day disabled list. Elster and right-hander Kevin Brown spent
time on the disabled list earlier this season. Pitchers Gregg Olson
and Jeff Williams are also on the disabled list, and right-hander
Mike Fetters spent three weeks on the disabled list before
returning Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers right fielder Shawn Green singled to score Todd
Hollandsworth with two outs in the third to tie it 1-1 before Eric
Karros unloaded on Bobby Jones' 2-1 pitch for his 14th homer of the
season. It went deep into the left-field seats and gave the Dodgers
a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The homer also pulled Karros within three of Ron Cey's Los
Angeles Dodgers record of 228 career homers.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets chipped away at the Dodgers' two-run deficit in the
fifth inning when Edgardo Alfonzo led off with a double and scored
on Mike Piazza's singled to right. That was the last batter starter
Eric Gagne faced.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Herges relieved and got out of the inning without further
damage, but the dependable rookie had trouble in the sixth after
striking out the first two batters. Melvin Mora singled, Derek Bell
followed wiP,th an infield single to third and the runners moved up
a base on third baseman Dave Hansen's throwing error. Alfonzo gave
the Mets a 4-3 lead with a two-run single to left.
</P>
</TEXT>
