r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     05-31 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH LESSON FOR SHAQ, KOBE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Rewind ``Pomp and Circumstance,'' hold the
commencement speeches. Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant have one
more test to pass before they complete their advanced course work.
</P>
<P>
   You know, toward their NBA degree.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, O'Neal and Bryant fell eight points short of a
passing grade in ``Clinching 300: The Art of Closing the Deal.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a tad troublesome that this one last class has caused them
such consternation. After all, everything they've learned to this
point was supposed to prepare them to ace it.
</P>
<P>
   We fully expected them to matriculate to the NBA Finals without
further delay, especially considering they've spent the past year
learning at the knee of the professorial Phil Jackson, the most
esteemed educator in their field of study.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, it would have been gratifying if O'Neal and Bryant
had been able to lead the Lakers past Portland in five games in
their best-of-seven Western Conference final.
</P>
<P>
   They gave no indication in the days leading up to this test that
they would suffer a panic attack and just freeze right there in
front of 18,997 people at the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   We were sure they'd be completely comfortable flaunting
everything they learned when Sacramento took them to five games in
the first round of the playoffs and Phoenix foiled their sweep in
the second round.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, their 96-88 loss to the Trail Blazers was a setback.
</P>
<P>
   But now is not the time to panic. Bryant and O'Neal have another
chance to pass this test on Friday. If they require it, Game 7 on
Sunday is out there like an ultimatum.
</P>
<P>
   This latest setback notwithstanding, O'Neal and Bryant remain on
schedule to graduate in four years from the L.A. satellite campus
of the School of Hard Knocks.
</P>
<P>
   They enrolled as Lakers together in the fall of 1996. Bryant
came straight out of high school while O'Neal transferred in from
the satellite campus in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, 28, got his first advanced NBA degree as a member of the
Magic, leading the team to the Finals in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Magic lost to the Houston Rockets, O'Neal felt
pretty confident he'd have a wall full of these advanced degress by
the time he turned 30.
</P>
<P>
   But his learning curve seemed to hit a glass ceiling in L.A.
Bryant, meanwhile, had a lot of catching up to do.
</P>
<P>
   He had to learn how to co-exist on the court with other highly
skilled players, for one thing. Bryant, 21, also had to figure out
how to dispense all of his energy equally between defense and
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant and O'Neal flunked plenty of tests before they finally
succeeded. There was their four-game loss to Utah in the 1998
Western Conference finals. They looked pretty unprepared for that
test.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was their four-game exit in the second round last
year to eventual NBA champion San Antonio. O'Neal looked like he
was winging that one.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Bryant was the one guilty of improvising as he went
along. He missed six of the first seven shots he tried against the
Trail Blazers and bore little resemblance to the composed player
that nailed the shot to beat Phoenix in Game 2 of that series,
blocked the shot to keep the Trail Blazers beaten in Game 3 of this
series and distributed a game-high seven assists in Sunday's Game
4.
</P>
<P>
   A single sequence in the waning seconds of the second quarter
perfectly captured Bryant's plight on this night. Bryant had the
ball with 15 seconds remaining and was looking to cut the Trail
Blazers' lead to three. But he lost the ball - one of his game-high
six turnovers - and ended up looking at Scottie Pippen drain a
three-pointer at the other end to put the Trail Blazers ahead 53-45
at the half.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal missed eight of the 14 shots he tried in the opening 24
minutes. But if he had trouble finding his rhythm, there was a
reason. Instead of working the ball inside to their seven-footer,
the Lakers obdurately launched quick shots from the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, who ended up fouling out with 4:45 left to play,
accounted for three of the Lakers' 27 three-pointers. That was four
more than they tried from beyond the three-point arc in their
29-point loss in Game 2 and about a dozen too many.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an opportunity missed,'' said O'Neal, who finished with
31 points and 21 rebounds. ``We shot 27 threes and only made six.
You live by the jump shot and you die by the jump shot.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one lesson learned. We trust Bryant and O'Neal also are
wiser for having let this opportunity slip away. We're sure they
know it's best to matriculate to the NBA Finals without further
delay. They're much too advanced to be held back another year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
