<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T WORRY, IT'S JUST A SETUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What the Lakers need now, like NBA playoff losers
throughout the television age, is a good conspiracy theory.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for their bruised egos, the best theory we can
come up with does not include the referees or the clock operators
or the schedulemakers or anybody with the power to tip the outcomes
of games and series to help the league's favorite network make more
money.
</P>
<P>
   This theory does not offer an excuse for the Lakers after their
latest clunker, a 96-88 loss at Staples Center to the Portland
Trail Blazers, who stayed alive in the Western Conference finals by
controlling Game 5 from start to finish.
</P>
<P>
   This theory has the Lakers going Grassy Knoll on themselves.
</P>
<P>
   How else do you explain how a team capable of brilliant
performances like Sunday afternoon's in Portland can turn in
efforts like Tuesday night's at home?
</P>
<P>
   How else do you explain how a team that can dominate the Trail
Blazers the way the Lakers did in Game 1 is capable of losing by 29
points in Game 2?
</P>
<P>
   How else do you explain how the Lakers keep finding ways to make
their postseason so fan-tastically exciting, just when they should
be putting opponents and TV audiences to sleep?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not one of those things where you can just give a reason;
it happens. There's a lot of circumstances that come into play,''
said A.C. Green, with tell-tale vagueness.
</P>
<P>
   Green added: ``I can't pinpoint one or two things. You could
pinpoint a hundred things. All of them would probably be right.''
</P>
<P>
   We imagine a cabal of 12 tall men, speaking in hushed tones in a
locker room, before the game where they could have completed an
opening-round sweep of the Sacramento Kings. After which they lost
two games in a row to force a do-or-die Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   As with any conspiracy theory, it (begin ital)could(end ital)
have happened.
</P>
<P>
   It could have happened before the game where they could have
completed a second-round sweep of the Phoenix Suns. After which
they were blown out in Arizona and had to come home to wrap up the
series.
</P>
<P>
   It could have happened Tuesday, as they stood on the verge of
beating Portland 4 games to 1 and going to the NBA Finals for the
first time since the era of Magic Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making it look too easy,'' they might have said to each
other.
</P>
<P>
   They might have realized that great teams are measured by the
adversity they overcome and their response to critical tests.
</P>
<P>
   After so sublime a regular season - for instance, Kobe Bryant
was the only starter to get hurt, and he returned to action Dec. 1
- maybe they're just setting up tests for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   They lose playoff games by margins that should embarrass a team
with 67 regular-season wins. And when they win, they do so by
coming from behind, trailing by double-digit margins in their two
victories in Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they're like the rich men who race cars or climb
mountains. They like to put themselves in danger. For the thrill of
it, not just the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes they lose control of games early and they can't
get it back.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened Tuesday. The Blazers took their usual lead
in the opening minutes. The Lakers nibbled away at the lead but
never drew even.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant, perhaps limited by a foot sprain, had his worst
night in weeks. The Lakers deserved all those fouls for letting the
Blazers take the ball to the basket early and often.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers made it a 10-point game early in the second quarter.
The Lakers kept firing up errant 3-point shots.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of postseason trends held. The Lakers shot 38 percent
and lost for the fifth time in six games where they've shot less
than 43 percent. They lost for the fifth time in eight games where
they've allowed 96 or more points.
</P>
<P>
   You'll hear from some hand-wringers that the Lakers are in
trouble now. Game 6 is in Portland on Friday and the Blazers will
be the ones with nothing to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers fans, relax. Game 5 was just a case of the Lakers living
dangerously again.
</P>
<P>
   They'll win this series and they'll go to the NBA Finals against
the New York Knicks or Indiana Pacers. Then they'll be expected to
win that series in four or five games.
</P>
<P>
   NBC bean-counters, relax. The Lakers will find a way to make the
Finals interesting. For you, and for themselves. In these playoffs
they always find a way to do that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 0322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
