r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-SIDEBAR-LA     05-31 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-SIDEBAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH NIGHT FOR KOBE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ These are not the nights that make superstars, not
that in the end any one needed to point it out to Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant was hardly the only Laker who struggled in their
disappointing 96-88 loss to the Blazers in Game 5 of the Western
Conference Finals on Tuesday night, but if only by status, he was
the most visible.
</P>
<P>
   He opened the game 1-for-8 from the field, before finishing
4-of-13. He had six turnovers. He was scorched for most of Scottie
Pippen's 22 points. The first-team, all-defensive standout did not
have a steal. And then as a final ignobly to his sorry night, he
fouled out with 4:45 to play.
</P>
<P>
   All and all, not the playoff game of his superstar dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant finished with 17 points -- eight coming from the
free-throw line -- five rebounds and four assists.
</P>
<P>
   That's as much good news as he could muster.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the night, he found lanes closing quickly. He found
hands in his face. He found a ball that wouldn't stay in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   The player who almost single-handedly kept the Lakers in Game 3
before they could rally to pull out the victory, suffered through
an overall miserable night, often resembling the young guard who
played a little out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little bit?'' repeated Lakers coach Phil Jackson. ``He got a
lot out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers said Bryant sprained his right foot in the first
half. X-rays take n after the game were negative, and he is
scheduled to have it re-examined today.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant didn't blame his foot for his play, though he described
it a little more favorably than Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was shaky,'' Bryant said. ``I just have to take what the
defense gives me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to get to the basket, taking what Portland gave
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, it wasn't much.
</P>
<P>
   The officials also hardly treated Bryant with superstar status
with some of the borderline fouls they called against him.
</P>
<P>
   But after he traveled for his sixth turnover, Jackson sat him
with 7:05 to play in the fourth quarter, the Lakers down by 11 and
desperately needing offense to mount a charge.
</P>
<P>
   Did this ever happen to Michael Jordan?
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, though, has never been one to lack belief in himself and
he wasn't about to let Tuesday's performance impact his confidence.
``You just keep going,'' he said. ``Without stress, there is no
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Lakers joined Bryant in the off-shooting night -- Glen
Rice was 1 for 8, Robert Horry 3 for 11, Rick Fox 1 for 5, Derek
Fisher 2 for 6 - - but after Shaquille O'Neal, it is Bryant the
Lakers turn to for production.
</P>
<P>
   And are not used to seeing play brickmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you can do is stay aggressive, and hope you get some
calls,'' Bryant said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 0338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 03:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0426 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU     05-31 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING BUT BAD NEWS FOR DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Another day, another Dodger injured. Or two.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Todd Hundley and reserve outfielder Geronimo Berroa left
in the sixth inning with injuries. Hundley strained a rib cage
muscle on his right side and Berroa suffered a contusion on his
left foot.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the troubles of the night was a blown save by Jeff
Shaw as the Mets rallied for six runs in the ninth, including a
grand slam by Todd Pratt, to beat the Dodgers 10-5 Tuesday at
Dodger Stadium in a game than lasted more than four hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hundley felt a little burning sensation in there and then
cramped,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``It's possible he
could have pulled something in there or torn an oblique muscle.
He's not doing good right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers entered the ninth leading 5-4, but Shaw failed to
record an out before being replaced by one-time Chicago Cubs closer
Terry Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza led off the ninth with a single to left and was
replaced at first by Jay Payton. Robin Ventura walked on four
pitches and Todd Zeile singled to center to score Payton, tying the
score 5-5 and chasing Shaw. It was Shaw's fifth blown save in 16
chances, and he fell to 2-3.
</P>
<P>
   Adams struck out pinch-hitter Joe McEwing for the first out, but
he walked Kurt Abbott, who was hitting .194, to load the bases.
Adams struck out Joe Nunnally, but then walked Melvin Mora,
recalled earlier in the day to replace Rey Ordonez, to force in a
run and give the Mets a 6-5 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaw, I'm going to have to stay off him for a while,'' Johnson
said. ``He needs a little rest. I'm going to have to play (the
closer's role) by ear. I probably might do a little committee. I
have a few guys with experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Pratt then hit Adams' 1-2 pitch over the fence in left field to
give the Mets a 10-5 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bad stretch,'' said Shaw, who admitted he was feeling
tired but was not in pain. ``I'll do what (Johnson) says. I
understand his thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Making it potentially worse is the loss of Hundley, who's added
another dimension to the lineup because of his health. He has 13
homers and 33 RBI, and was providing offense as a left-handed and
right-handed hitter, as well as depth to the middle of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley doubled to lead off the sixth off Mets starter Bobby
Jones. Pinch-hitter Kevin Elster singled to center off reliever
Dennis Cook, but Hundley was held at third by coach Glenn Hoffman.
Hundley apparently injured the intercostal muscle of his rib cage
while stopping suddenly. He was replaced by Chad Kreuter, who
scored on Berroa's single.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hollandsworth struck out, but Mark Grudzielanek gave the
Dodgers a 5-4 lead with a single to left off Pat Mahomes to score
Elster. But on the play Berroa aggravated his injury, which
occurred when he fouled a pitch off his foot during his at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   X-rays on Berroa's foot were negative and he's listed as
day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley will be re-evaluated today, but it didn't look good. He
needed help walking down the dugout stairs and was in obvious pain.
</P>
<P>
   If Hundley's injury forces him to the disabled list, he'll be
the fifth starter to be there this season. Currently, center
fielder Devon White and third baseman Adrian Beltre are on the
15-day disabled list. Elster and right-hander Kevin Brown spent
time on the disabled list earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers Gregg Olson and Jeff Williams are also on the disabled
list, and right-hander Mike Fetters spent three weeks on the DL
before returning Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
