   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MINORITY-PILOTS (San Antonio) _ Calvin Allen, dapper in a crisp
black uniform with attached pilot wings, always turns a few heads
as he makes his way through busy airports. The 47-year-old Delta
pilot and one of the airline industry's few black pilots is among
those hoping to recruit more women and minorities to the cockpit.
By JOHN GUTIERREZ-MIER.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-SHOOTINGS (Brackettville, Texas) _ Ranchers and residents
say the growing number of Mexicans who illegally cross the border
trample fences, slaughter small livestock, cut water lines and
break into homes. Some of these Americans are accused of taking
justice into their own hands, leading to shootings are creating
consternation in Mexico. By LISA SANDBERG.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SENATE (Buffalo, N.Y.) _ Pop quiz: The U.S. Senate candidate
wants to boost public education, protect the environment, wire up
schools to the Internet and protect health benefits for the
disadvantaged. Oh, and no mudslinging on the campaign trail. It's
all about issues. Who's the candidate? Rick Lazio, the new GOP
contender, or Democratic nominee First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton?
Answer: Both. By LARA JAKES.
</P>
<P>
   GRAY-DAVIS (Sacramento, Calif.) _ After a year and a half in
office, the administration of California Gov. Gray Davis was summed
up with just two words: Ka-ching! ``Gray Davis will be known as the
California governor who actually had a tip jar on his desk,'' said
Senate Republican leader Jim Brulte. That was the start of a long
litany of jokes about Davis and his record-breaking fund raising
during an annual roast sponsored by Capitol Focus, a nonprofit
group that teaches school kids about state government. By ROBERT
SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Business consultant and author
Tom Peters writes in the May 22 issue of Time magazine that he
believes ``90 percent of white-collar jobs in the U.S. will be
either destroyed or altered beyond recognition in the next 10 to 15
years.'' By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   GE-LABOR (Schenectady, N.Y.) _ When labor officials sat across
from General Electric Co. executives in New York City to begin
negotiations on a new three-year contract, their primary goals were
not be much different from what they were the last time at the
bargaining table. But with stable employment and healthy sales,
this round of talks is likely to lack the fervor of the last talks
in 1997. By KENNETH AARON.
</P>
<P>
   HOTEL-COMPCIERGES (San Francisco) _ Room service at some hotels
means more than dinner and drinks. It now means computer help for
business travelers who rely on their sometimes troublesome laptops.
By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   DIRT-CLEANER (Fort Edward, N.Y.) _ A company with facilities in
New York and New Hampshire can turn contaminated land into a
playground in about 20 minutes. Using a ``shake and bake
technology,'' the process is gaining popularity among businesses
and government agencies seeking to clean up sites. By DINA
CAPPIELLO.
</P>
