<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Save Our Scraps! Art lovers unite to preserve the Cathedral of
Junk
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A group of Austin artists, high-tech people and
other yard art lovers has formed a nonprofit folk art foundation to
save a South Austin tower of junk known as the Cathedral of Junk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outpouring is pretty incredible,'' said Bill Narum, an
Austin Web page designer, video game maker and former Armadillo
World Headquarters poster artist who is leading the move to
preserve the 32-foot-tall stack of coffee makers, bicycles,
urinals, McDonald's Happy Meal toys, blenders, riding mowers, bed
springs and what-all created by artist Vince Hannemann. ``Not only
the public was so interested in the preservation of it, but the
artists were behind it. So far, it's been unanimous support from
the local artists.''
</P>
<P>
   Narum says he even has the support of Billy Gibbons of ZZ Top.
</P>
<P>
   Others involved include fellow Armadillo artists Jim Franklin
and Micael Priest, Austin artist Bob ``Daddy-O'' Wade, TV producer
Jessica Thomas and Gary Fortin of the broadband Internet
infrastructure provider Aperian. They have been meeting to plan how
to save the tower in the back yard of Hannemann's little South
Austin rent house on Lareina Drive.
</P>
<P>
   The person they're trying to save the tower from is Hannemann
himself. Even though the sometimes-cranky Hannemann spent 11 years
wiring the items in the tower together, he is tired of dealing with
people coming to visit the structure and had begun taking it apart.
To preserve the tower of skateboard parts, pinball machines,
crutches, carburetors and just about any piece of junk you can
imagine, Narum and friends have created a nonprofit organization
called the Austin Folk Art Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, Narum said, intends to raise money to buy the
house where Hannemann lives and to pay Hannemann $10,000 for the
sculpture so that he will move out and go away. One idea is to hire
another artist to live in the house and give tours of the junk.
Hannemann has said he wants to move to a small town and build an
even larger tower of junk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that Johnson City is too close for Vince,''
Narum said.
</P>
<P>
   Fortin, Aperian's vice president of marketing, is talking about
putting up some of his own money to save the junk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Austin's first significant piece of folk art that is in
jeopardy of being torn apart,'' he said. ``I think it's a great
opportunity for the high-tech community _ the multimedia cluster _
to come over to the south side of the river and make a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Narum estimates the asking price for the small house will be
about $45,000, and the group needs an operating budget to maintain
the site. ``We don't want to buy it and just let it rot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Narum says the group already has enough money pledged to cover
the sculpture. His biggest problem has been Hannemann. When members
of the folk art foundation stopped by Hannemann's place for a tour
on a recent weekend, they discovered Hannemann was still taking his
piece apart. Narum, who had thought Hannemann had stopped
dismantling the tower, says he went ballistic on Hannemann and a
shouting match began. Only in South Austin would people argue over
junk preservation. Narum says he even used the ``A'' word on
Hannemann.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to blow up on him,'' Narum said. ``I got in a screaming
match with him with a bunch of supporters over there.'' Narum added
that the situation ended amicably when Cathedral of Junk supporters
gave Hannemann $500 to leave his artwork alone, until the full
$10,000 payment can be raised. ``After that we shook hands and made
up,'' Narum said.
</P>
<P>
   Hannemann says he had told Narum he was going to take down the
tower until he got some earnest money. ``Yeah, we had a little
misunderstanding; let's put it that way,'' Hannemann said. ``I had
been up front with him that I was going to dismantle it until they
gave me some money.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, who has produced shows for the Austin Music Network,
thinks the Austin Folk Art Foundation could save other folk art
around town. ``Who knows what's out there and hasn't been talked
about?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So if you have a pile of trash at the end of your street, give
me a call and maybe we can find it a docent.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso can be reached at jkelso(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
