<HEADER>
A0529 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN01-COX     05-31 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cincinnati and pigs: Pure ham
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe you had to have been there, back in the Great Flying Pig
Debate of 1988, to get such a kick out of the fiberglass pigs
roaming the streets of Cincinnati. The Big Pig Gig boasts 375 pigs,
to be precise, designed by local artists a la Chicago's Cows on
Parade. (A tuxedoed pig at Music Hall; Pigasso at the Art Museum _
you get the idea.)
</P>
<P>
   I don't know if this says more about me or about Cincinnati, but
the pigscapade was my favorite controversy in all my years as a
reporter in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody got hurt. But boy, was there ever a spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   It all started with artist Andrew Leicester's plans for a public
sculpture in Sawyer Point Park. The four pink, red-winged pigs atop
riverboat smokestacks were intended as a whimsical tribute to
Cincinnati's 19th-century status as Porkopolis.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal drew the ire of some city officials _ notably once
and future Mayor Charlie Luken and future Congressman Steve Chabot
_ who felt the swine presented a less-than-dignified image of their
city.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy went national. ``Why would a city with a team
like the Bengals be worried about flying pigs?'' quipped Bryant
Gumbel on the Today show.
</P>
<P>
   Things came to a head at a raucous public hearing of
Cincinnati's Urban Development Committee. A local DJ strolled City
Council Chambers cuddling a Butler County pig named Arnold,
announcing, ``We're pro-pig and we want the world to know it.''
Artists linked arms and sang, ``All we are sa-a-a-y-ing is give
pigs a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of the five committee members donned felt pig hats.
Council member Arn Bortz donned a pig snout.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was expected to drum up public opposition to the
pigs and the ``elite arts community.'' Instead, it turned into a
lovefest for the pigs.
</P>
<P>
   Chabot was roundly booed when he declared, ``I am neither
pro-pig nor anti-pig.'' (Being one of the House managers in the
impeachment trial must have been a breeze by comparison.)
</P>
<P>
   Beneath Luken's chair hung a Magic-Markered poster of
Charlotte's web with those immortal words, ``Some pig.''
</P>
<P>
   In all the clamor you could hear a battle for the city's image.
Were we a laugh-at-ourselves, whimsical city, or the stodgy,
repressive place the rest of the world liked to imagine us?
</P>
<P>
   Ever since then, Cincinnati has embraced its porcine heritage,
hosting the annual Flying Pig Marathon and Bockfest Pig Parade.
</P>
<P>
   Pig pride has never been so rampant in Cincinnati. (Check them
out in person through Oct. 31 or visit them online at
www.bigpiggig.com.) Make the acquaintance of ``Hogwarts,'' a hammy
Harry Potter, complete with spectacles and broomstick. ``Pigs were
Cincinnati's original waste management system,'' artist Liz
Duquette told The Cincinnati Enquirer. ``That's why we asked Rumpke
to be our sponsor.''
</P>
<P>
   What does it take for one individual to admit, in public, ``I
was wrong?'' Plenty, it seems, any more, when such a statement
seems tantamount to an admission of weakness.
</P>
<P>
   What does it take for an entire city to admit, ``I was wrong?''
When will that happen?
</P>
<P>
   In Cincinnati, the answer appears to be, ``When pigs fly.''
</P>
<P>
   You can e-mail Mary McCarty at marymccarty(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
