<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0530 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN01-COX     05-31 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Standardized tests a fair way to assess skills for all students
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's illogical, unfair and wrong to compare standardized tests
used to measure academic achievement in public schools with Jim
Crow tests used to discriminate against African Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Crow tests were used by racist southern officials to deny
blacks their constitutional rights. They were shameful barriers to
minority equality.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the NAACP Legal Defense and Education Fund has
compared standardized tests used in many public schools with racist
tests used to keep blacks from voting or getting into traditionally
white schools or professions.
</P>
<P>
   The standardized tests used in Texas, and especially in Waco,
are designed to tear down barriers to educational equality,
particularly for minorities and economically disadvantaged
students.
</P>
<P>
   Tearing down barriers to achieve equality can hardly be compared
to erecting barriers to deny equality.
</P>
<P>
   The reason NAACP officials complain about standardized tests is
because the tests are showing that many African Americans are
scoring behind white students on scholastic achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the tests are racially or culturally biased, there is no
reason to blame the tests for the results. Most widely administered
standardized tests are painstakingly vetted to be as free of racial
or cultural bias as humanly possible.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that school children across the nation have been let
down by public school systems that substituted sensitive, feel-good
gimmicks for the hard work of teaching, testing and learning.
</P>
<P>
   Students most hurt by the social promotions and politically
correct edubabble that dominated America's education community for
30 years were minority and economically disadvantaged students.
</P>
<P>
   Until recent efforts to ensure that public school students can
once again read their diplomas and obtain the skills needed to hold
down decent jobs, public schools studiously ignored accountability
at all levels of the educational process.
</P>
<P>
   Parents were not held accountable for their responsibility to
oversee their children's educational progress.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers were not held accountable for their responsibility to
teach their students enough to succeed in a higher grade.
</P>
<P>
   School administrators and trustees were not held accountable for
their refusal to hold anyone in their school districts accountable
for the downward spiral of public education.
</P>
<P>
   Out of fear of traumatizing students, the curriculum was watered
down, tests were dumbed down, grading was based on intentions, not
results, and students were promoted to higher grades when they had
not learned the material in their current grade.
</P>
<P>
   Hurt the most by more than a generation of social promotions
were minority and economically disadvantaged students.
</P>
<P>
   Students from middle and upper-income families with a heritage
of educational attainment were least hurt.
</P>
<P>
   NAACP officials would be more on target if they blasted the past
three decades of slacker education for the current testing gap
between minorities and whites.
</P>
<P>
   Standardized tests should be based on grade-level curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   Promotions should not be based on standardized test results
alone. Attendance and classroom work also should be considered.
</P>
<P>
   School districts need to be committed to fund and staff extra
classes to keep students from falling behind. These extra classes
must be conducted during the school year as well as during the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Standardized tests and accountability measures must be directed
at preventing children from falling behind, not increasing academic
failures.
</P>
<P>
   There is no reason to blame or get angry with standardized
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Standardized tests simply measure learning. We need them the
same way motorists need to measure how fast they are going or how
much gas they have in their tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Standardized tests can always be made better, but they are not
the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is the senior editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald. E-mail him at rnethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
