<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 11:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0533 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS1-01-CO     05-31 1448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS1-01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    Eds. 1 of 2 files. RUNS WITH NEWS-QUESTIONS2-01-COX
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent article contained a statement from someone who said
it was ``impossible for my brother to defend himself against these
Kafkaesque proceedings.'' What is meant by that?
</P>
<P>
   A: Derived from the name of Czech writer Franz Kafka
(1883-1924), ``Kafkaesque'' means surreal, nightmarish persecution.
</P>
<P>
   Kafka's works, written in German, combine a realistic, sometimes
grotesquely exact description of details with an overall atmosphere
of fantasies, dreams and nightmares. People find themselves trapped
in inexplicable, confusingly complex situations in which there is
no way out. The word conjures up the confusion, anxieties and
alienation of modern man. The article you saw reported on a case
involving the 1996 anti-terrorism act, which gives the Immigration
and Naturalization Service the authority to arrest, detain and
deport non-citizens based on secret evidence not revealed to the
defendant.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When and where was the first shopping mall built in the
United States?
</P>
<P>
   A: The book ``Famous First Facts'' lists it as Country Club
Plaza, on the outskirts of Kansas City, Mo. Construction began in
November 1922, and the first tenant moved in in March 1923. The
center occupied 40 acres and had 150 stores, a 2,000-seat
auditorium, and a parking lot for 5,500 cars.
</P>
<P>
   The first shopping plaza in which the stores faced in toward a
promenade, rather than out toward an access road, was the Highland
Park Shopping Village in Dallas, built in 1931.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported last fall that an elephant inThailand needed
a foot amputation after she stepped on a land mine. Is any update
available on her condition?
</P>
<P>
   A: At last report, veterinarians at Thailand's leading pachyderm
hospital said Motola, the injured elephant, was in good health and
eating 600 pounds of food a day.
</P>
<P>
   A five-man surgical team amputated the 38-year-old animal's left
front foot after it stepped on a mine while hunting for food on the
rugged border between Thailand and Myanmar (formerly Burma).
</P>
<P>
   The animal's plight garnered worldwide attention and offers of
help, including more than $120,000 in donations. Motola's survival
was in doubt for weeks after the amputation in August, but by
December her condition had improved to the point that she was moved
from her pen to an area where she could practice walking.
</P>
<P>
   Veterinarians said fitting her with a prosthesis was being
considered. An American firm, Riecken's Orthotic Laboratory in
Evansville, Ind., has offered to make a prosthesis.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why is San Diego's weather always so beautiful, in the low
70s all year long, while just to the north, in Los Angeles,
temperatures sometimes soar over 100 degrees?
</P>
<P>
   A: Actually, both cities _ which are about 125 miles apart _
have remarkably similar weather.
</P>
<P>
   The climate in both is termed Marine or Mediterranean. The
primary moderating influence is the Pacific Ocean, with coastal
mountain ranges acting as a buffer against extremes of summer heat
and winter cold to the east.
</P>
<P>
   A high over 100 is quite the exception in either city. Los
Angeles averages only five days a year with temperatures of 90 or
higher; San Diego averages three. It's possible, by the way, for
temperatures to top 100 in San Diego, primarily in the eastern
sections of the city, when dry easterly winds blow for several
days. But it's rare.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does either city have extremes of cold. There are no days
with temperatures of 32 degrees or below. Both cities also average
relatively little annual precipitation (12 inches in Los Angeles,
9.9 inches in San Diego), and average humidity levels are about the
same (69 percent in San Diego, 71 percent in Los Angeles).
</P>
<P>
   As the Weather Almanac notes, pronounced differences in
temperatures can occur in both cities within fairly short
distances.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know that George W. Bush was released early from the
National Guard to attend Harvard Business School. But did he, in
fact, receive a degree?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. He received his MBA in 1975. He received his
undergraduate degree from Yale in 1968, and enrolled at Harvard
after getting out of the Texas Air National Guard in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I saw an article the other day concerning a possible advance
in the treatment of diabetes, specifically transplantation of human
pancreatic islet cells. Where can I get more information?
</P>
<P>
   A: The American Society of Transplantation says information can
be found online at www.transplant2000.org.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneering work on the process, in which eight patients were
liberated from insulin injections by having pancreas cells from
dead donors transplanted into their livers, was done by
British-born surgeon James Shapiro of the University of Alberta.
Shapiro described his work at a recent meeting in Chicago of the
American Society of Transplant Surgeons and the American Society of
Transplantation.
</P>
<P>
   The cells that produce insulin are called the Islets of
Langerhans. In those who develop diabetes as children, the islets
are destroyed. Attempts have been made to transplant islet cells,
or in the entire pancreas, but have had limited success and
involved lengthy hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   In the new approach, the islets are injected into veins, a
simple procedure not requiring a surgeon and involving, at most, an
overnight hospital stay. Getting a sufficient supply of islets is
seen to be a problem, but may be overcome in the future by cloning
techniques.
</P>
<P>
   If the technique continues to prove successful in further
research, demand for the treatment _ and costs _ are expected to be
high.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The move to disbar President Clinton brings to mind Richard
Nixon. Was he disbarred from the practice of law after his
resignation as president?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. On July 8, 1976, Nixon was disbarred by a New York
court, marking the first time the former president had been found
guilty by an official body of charges relating to Watergate. That
action meant he could not practice law in any form in New York and
could not appear as a lawyer before any court or agency, or give
legal advice, in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon, who previously had said he never intended to practice law
again, already had resigned from the bars of California and the
U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The court sustained five charges brought by the Association of
the Bar of the City of New York that Nixon had obstructed ``the due
administration of justice'' and thus violated the Code of
Professional Responsibility, a set of rules that all lawyers are
required to observe. The charges weren't contested by Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   In its 4-to-1 opinion, the court, which had admitted Nixon to
practice law in New York in 1963, found that the charges were
substantiated by documentary evidence, such as the tapes of Nixon
himself, excerpts of testimony of individuals given to various
congressional committees, and affidavits.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who is credited with writing the song ``Happy Birthday''?
</P>
<P>
   A: Facts on File Encyclopedia of Word and Phrase Origins
explains that it was written in 1893 by Patty Smith Hill
(1868-1946) and Mildred Jane Hill (1859-1916) as part of their
``Song Stories for the Kindergarten.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the background on Atlanta Braves rookie shortstop
Rafael Furcal? A recent article described him as a candidate for
rookie of the year.
</P>
<P>
   A: To start at the beginning, Rafael Antoni Furcal as born Aug.
24, 1980, in Loma de Cabrera, Dominican Republic, where he still
lives in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   He was signed by the Braves as a free agent on Nov. 9, 1996. In
1998, he played on the Appalachian League's Danville, Va., team,
where he had a ``standout campaign,'' as the Braves put it. He
batted .328 in 66 games and stole a league record 60 bases. He was
named Danville's player of the year that year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999 he was named the Braves' top minor league prospect by
Baseball America after compiling a ``sensational campaign'' with
Class A Macon and Class A Myrtle Beach while being converted from
second base to shortstop. He led all of minor league baseball with
96 steals in 126 attempts and was named the South Atlantic League's
top prospect after leading the circuit with 73 steals in only 83
games.
</P>
<P>
   Furcal's biography and statistics can be viewed online at
www.atlantabraves.com/.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
