<HEADER>
A0535 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS2-01-CO     05-31 1433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS2-01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    Eds. 2 of 2 files. RUNS WITH NEWS-QUESTIONS1-01-COX
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: When a Postal Service truck is pulled over to the side of a
street to put mail into a mailbox, are other motorists expected or
required to yield to them? Or do they have to yield to the other
traffic?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are no specific U.S. Postal Service policies governing
the behavior of motorists while in the vicinity of postal delivery
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   However, given the growing amount of traffic congestion on
Atlanta-area streets and roads, motorists certainly can increase
the comfort level of letter carriers by watching out for them and
yielding to them when they're making deliveries to roadside
mailboxes, said Postal Service spokesman Michael Miles.
</P>
<P>
   Q: At a recent state dinner, South African President Thabo Mbeki
presented President Clinton with a set of 24-karat gold coins
produced by the South African Mint. What happens to such gifts, and
who or what agency oversees the handling of them?
</P>
<P>
   A: The State Department Protocol Office physically handles the
exchange of gifts between heads of state, according to the White
House. Those received by any U.S. president are forwarded by the
State Department to the White House to be put on display in the
Oval Office or elsewhere in the ceremonial rooms of the White
House. The White House Gift Unit oversees placement.
</P>
<P>
   After that, gifts and other materials given to the president by
visiting heads of state go to the National Archives, where they are
held until a presidential library is built. At that point, they go
on display on an official basis.
</P>
<P>
   In the case you're inquiring about, Mbeki presented to Clinton a
limited edition legal tender proof coin set, the Natura Prestige
Set 2000. It consists of four 24-karat coins from the 2000 ``The
Sable-Queen of the Antelope'' collection, which is second in the
South African Mint's ``The Monarchs of Africa'' series.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki's wife, Zanele, presented to Mrs. Clinton a 12-piece set
of ``Afrisilver'' napkin rings, each napkin featuring a different
animal found in Africa, including a lion, elephant, leopard and
buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Henry Aaron hit 755 lifetime home runs, making him the
all-time home run leader ahead of Babe Ruth and Willie Mays. How
many times did Aaron hit 50 or more homers in one season?
</P>
<P>
   A: None. Aaron's single-year home run top was in 1971, when he
hit 47. Ruth's top year was 1927, when he hit 60 homers; in 1921,
he hit 59; in 1920 and 1928, 54. Mays' top year was 1965, when he
hit 52; in 1955, he hit 51.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is Johnny Mathis still living? If so, what has he been up to
in recent years? I never hear anything about him any more or see
him on TV.
</P>
<P>
   A: He's very much alive, and when he isn't singing or cooking _
he's a gourmet chef of considerable renown _ usually can be found
on a golf course, playing for his own enjoyment or participating in
golf-related charities. Mathis, 64, lives in a Hollywood Hills
mansion built by Howard Hughes. He cherishes his privacy, and has
described himself in the past as ``a loner, but not lonely.''
</P>
<P>
   He has performed at five U.S. presidential dinners and has
appeared in numerous royal command performances in England. His
appearance on A&AMP;E's Grammy-winning ``Live By Request'' series in
1998 captured the series' highest ratings to date.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most enduring figures in popular music, Mathis has
recorded more than 100 albums, including many that have become
milestones in 20th century popular culture. He has garnered more
than 60 gold and platinum album awards since his arrival on the
music scene in the mid-1950s.
</P>
<P>
   His latest CD is ``Mathis on Broadway,'' a collection of
contemporary show tunes released recently by Columbia Records. It
features duets with Broadway award-winners Betty Buckley, Nell
Carter and Forever Plaid, and is Mathis' first collection of
theater tunes since the ``Rhythms and Ballads of Broadway'' album
in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A recently discussed the motto ``In God We Trust'' on
coins. How did that start?
</P>
<P>
   A: Although it was used by Francis Scott Key in a slightly
different form when he wrote ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' in 1814,
it originated as an inscription for U.S. coins during the Civil
War.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 13, 1861, when Union morale had been shaken by
battlefield defeats, Rev. M.R. Watkinson of Ridleyville, Pa., wrote
to Treasury Secretary Salmon P. Chase. ``From my heart I have felt
our national shame in disowning God as not the least of our present
national disasters,'' Watkinson wrote, suggesting ``recognition of
Almighty God in some form on our coins.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase ordered designs prepared with the inscription ``In God We
Trust'' and endorsed coinage legislation authorizing use of the
slogan. It first appeared on some U.S. coins in 1864, and
disappeared and reappeared on various coins until 1955, when
Congress ordered it placed on all paper money and all coins.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Articles about polls always refer to a margin of error. Can
you explain what that means, and how it was developed?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Gallup Organization explains that over the years,
statisticians have developed quite specific ways of measuring the
accuracy of samples _ as long as the fundamental principle of equal
probability of selection is adhered to when the sample is drawn.
</P>
<P>
   For example, with a sample size of 1,000 national adults
(derived using careful random selection procedures), the results
are highly likely to be accurate within a margin of error of plus
or minus 3 percentage points. Thus, if it is found in a given poll
that a president's approval rating is 50 percent, the margin of
error indicates that the true rating is very likely to be between
47 and 53 percent. It's very unlikely to be higher or lower,
according to Gallup.
</P>
<P>
   To be more specific, Gallup says the laws of probability show
that if the same survey were conducted 100 times, asking people in
each survey to rate the job a president is doing, in 95 out of
those 100 polls the rating would be between 47 and 53 percent. In
only five _ because of chance error _ would the rating be higher or
lower than that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was told that Walt Disney World is located on property that
formerly was the site of McCoy Air Force Base. Can you confirm?
</P>
<P>
   A: Wrong site. McCoy became the site of Orlando's airport, not
Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy Air Force Base was closed in 1974. The following year, the
surplus land was deeded to the City of Orlando for airport facility
use, and the Greater Orlando Aviation Authority was created by
special legislative act. In 1976 it received international airport
status and was renamed Orlando International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney World site is southwest of Orlando, off I-4 near Lake
Buena Vista. The airport is southeast of Orlando, off the Beeline
Expressway.
</P>
<P>
   And now, incidentally, you know why the airport designator code
for Orlando International Airport is MCO. It's derived from McCoy.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know the word kamikaze came into the language when Japanese
pilots staged suicide attacks in World War II, but what is the
literal meaning?
</P>
<P>
   A: It comes from the Japanese kami (god or deity) and kaze
(wind): thus, ``divine wind.'' It is traced to 1281, when a typhoon
_ hence, ``wind of the gods'' _ wrecked a Mongol fleet invading
Japan. Since World War II, the term has been used in English for
anyone or anything displaying recklessness.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is known about mouth and throat cancer from smoking
cigars and pipes?
</P>
<P>
   A: The American Lung Association and the American Health
Foundation say cigar and pipe smokers face risks of lung, larynx,
mouth and esophagus cancer; chronic pulmonary disease; and heart
problems, including those caused when nicotine is absorbed into the
bloodstream.
</P>
<P>
   Even passive smoke from cigars and pipes can be harmful to
others, according to health researchers. Because cigar and pipe
tobacco burn at a lower temperatures than cigarette tobacco, the
smoke they release may contain higher concentrations of carbon
monoxide and cancer-causing substances such as nitrosamine.
</P>
<P>
   Health experts also refute the oft-held idea that risks are
lessened if people switch from cigarettes to pipes and cigars,
thinking they won't inhale. This is a myth, the experts say,
because the habit of inhalation is likely to continue.
</P>
<P>
   More information online: www.lungusa.org/ (American Lung
Association); www.ahf.org/ (American Health Foundation).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
