<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0572 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CUBA-ART-$ADV04-COX     05-31 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ART-$ADV04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CUBAN ARTIST SHEDS LIGHT ON MYSTERIOUS SANTERIA RELIGION
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., June 4, and Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA, Cuba _ It's a sweltering Sunday afternoon, the
temperature fueled by a blazing Caribbean sun and the scorching
African rhythms floating skyward from a narrow alley tucked in an
otherwise nondescript corner of this capital city.
</P>
<P>
   Drummers pound an incessant beat on tall wooden drums,
triggering waves of swaying, hypnotic dance in the crowd of some
200 people jammed into the sweaty space. A young Afro-Cuban woman
wearing a skin-tight body stocking festooned with bright flowers
shimmies, her body rolling with rhythm, while two tall, blonde
European women gently rock to the beat, faces entranced by the
spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   A young American backpacker clad in sandals, shorts and T-shirt,
his chin darkened by a scraggly goatee, rolls his head, eyes
closed, as the drums crescendo.
</P>
<P>
   The throng somehow parts as tall, bearded Salvador Gonzalez
Escalona strolls calmly through the midst of an event he created.
Never breaking a sweat, he smiles as he speaks to acquaintances and
accepts handshakes from strangers, glowing with the energy of a
weekly gathering that has become a cultural and tourist magnet here
in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to Hammel Alley,'' he tells a visitor in Spanish. ``We
are celebrating our African roots.''
</P>
<P>
   His arm swings out to encompass the two-story buildings crowding
the alley, which are covered with wild, flowing murals Gonzalez has
painted over the past decade to celebrate Cuba's mystical
Afro-Caribbean religion, Santeria.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our religion is very different from yours in the United
States,'' he said. ``It is a philosophy of the forces of nature. My
work responds to the codes and values of our African ancestors.''
</P>
<P>
   The murals incorporate swirling circles, bright orange eyes,
geometric shapes, crosses, scribbled poems and homilies, densely
packed bodies and intriguing faces. Gonzalez is also a sculptor who
recycles the objects of everyday life: an ancient cash register
stands on a pedestal; an old black manual typewriter is nailed to a
door; a bathtub on wheels is welded to a frame arching over the
street, a scrap-iron seahorse towing the tub with metal traces.
</P>
<P>
   Fidel Castro may have outlawed religion as the enemy of his
communist state, but Santeria still thrives in Cuba, and Salvador
Gonzalez has become one of its most visible advocates.
</P>
<P>
   He began his mural project in the early 1990s, when as a
struggling artist the idea of taking his paintings to the street on
a grand scale might have seemed risky. Cuba was _ and still is _
ruled by bureaucrats who often issue official decrees as to what
artistic forms and expressions are acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, 52, simply started painting. His neighbors loved his
work, and helped him scrounge paint supplies. They helped him build
scaffolds, and set up lights at night to let him work as late as
his muse provided inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the official types mostly overlooked him, then
gradually became fans. News of the growing mural spread by
word-of-mouth and it soon became a popular stop with the trickle of
tourists who began showing up in Cuba in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   By the late '90s, the mural was mostly finished, and Gonzalez
had carved out a spot as a hip representative of Cuban art and
culture. With tourism flourishing, he has become one of Cuba's most
notable artists. Magazine articles and press coverage led to
commissions overseas. He has painted a water tower in Germany, a
huge building in Caracas a homeless shelter in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   His subject is the mysterious world of Santeria. The religion
stems from the Yoruba people of West Africa, who kept their beliefs
when they were brought to the New World as slaves. Forbidden by
their masters from practicing their religion, they hid it by
incorporating the Catholic saints as representatives of each of the
Yoruban gods, called orishas.
</P>
<P>
   The orishas rule over every aspect of life and nature, from
relationships to the weather, to mountains, trees and the ocean.
Priests _ or babalawos _ instruct the faithful through sacrifice
and offerings, sometimes tossing pieces of coconut shells seeking
divination, or instructing their adherents to follow intricate,
secret rituals to chase away evil spirits or ensure good luck in
business or love.
</P>
<P>
   The religion also incorporates rhythmic drumming, dance and
trances. Followers can be seen swooning in religious ecstacy, their
bodies apparently possessed by fervor and spirits.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has brought Santeria from Havana's back alleys into the
light of international attention, earning respect from art lovers
and the admiration of Santeria believers for preserving and
furthering a vital part of Cuban culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of life and music in his art,'' said Jacqui
Guillard, who visited Gonzalez's Sunday afternoon gathering
recently on a trip from Switzerland, where she is an artist. ``It's
fascinating and really shows the allure of Cuba _ it's such a
mysterious destination.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez clearly thrives on the attention, but insists his real
purpose is to keep alive the religion that has flourished in Cuba
for hundreds of years. He's happy that his art has provided a means
for people outside Cuba to understand a little more about Santeria.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am only a channel for the values of my ancestors,'' he said.
``My art is in homage to them, to their beliefs, to our culture.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Williams may be contacted at: MikeW(at)Coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more on the artist:
</P>
<P>
   http://marina.fortunecity.com/greenwich/227/salvador/ (This site
is in Spanish).
</P>
<P>
   For more on Santeria:
</P>
<P>
   www.iac.net/(tilde)moonweb/NOSVT/VoodooResources.html
</P>
<P>
   www.religioustolerance.org/santeri.htm.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
