<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 11:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0602 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-FATHERHOOD01-COX     05-31 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FATHERHOOD01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FATHERHOOD SUMMIT MOVES FROM TALK TO ACTION
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The First National Summit on Fatherhood was
convened in 1996 to ``wake up America'' to the tragedy of absentee
dads. Two years later, the second summit showed how the problem
affects all of society. This week, the third summit will issue a
call for community action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're now in a position to give people concrete things they
can do,'' said Wade Horn, president of the National Fatherhood
Initiative, a non-partisan advocacy group that promotes
``responsible fatherhood'' and sponsors the summits.
</P>
<P>
   The organization was formed in 1994 to dramatically declare that
dads matter _ especially in a nation where 40 percent of the
children, a total of 24.7 million, live in a home without their
biological fathers.
</P>
<P>
   Although the movement has focused attention on the importance of
fathers, Horn said, the problems have hardly lessened. Either
through out-of-wedlock birth or divorce or separation of their
parents, nearly 2.5 million children will join the ranks of the
fatherless this year.
</P>
<P>
   The previous summits helped establish a ``thriving fatherhood
movement,'' Horn said. ``This event is designed to equip
community-based organizations with the tools they need to help
bring dads back to their children.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important that we mobilize communities,'' said Horn, a
child psychologist and former Commissioner for Children, Youth and
Families in the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   This Third National Summit on Fatherhood will bring hundreds of
politicians, local activists and academicians _ and a few celebrity
dads _ to Washington on Friday and Saturday. Country music star Tim
McGraw, former Buffalo Bills quarterback Jim Kelly, and Detroit
Lions defensive end Robert Porcher are scheduled to receive awards
as ``Fathers of the Year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We use these awards to tell a compelling story about
fatherhood,'' said Horn. ``These celebrities are deserving dads.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with his wife, Jill, Kelly co-founded the Hunter's Hope
Foundation in 1997 after their son, Hunter, was diagnosed with
Krabbe disease, an inherited, often fatal, affliction of the brain
and nervous system that strikes young children.
</P>
<P>
   After spending his early life absent from his biological father,
former major league pitcher Tug McGraw, Tim McGraw sought him out
and worked to establish a close relationship. Married to country
music singer Faith Hill, McGraw is also a devoted father to their
two children, Horn said.
</P>
<P>
   Porcher is among the NFL's biggest advocates for responsible
fatherhood, appearing on ESPN and other sports media to promote the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   The celebrity recipients will be joined by a fourth Father of
the Year, Joe Jones, the founder of Baltimore's Center for Fathers,
Families and Workplace Development, which helps low-income fathers.
</P>
<P>
   One goal of this year's summit is to ``mobilize whole
communities'' in the movement to find absentee fathers and help
them become meaningful parts of the lives of their children, Horn
said.
</P>
<P>
   The people attending the summit work with organizations in
prisons, schools, churches, businesses, entertainment and
neighborhoods around the country. The sessions include ``Working
With Incarcerated Fathers,'' ``Serving Hispanic Dads,'' ``Working
With At-Home Dads,'' ``Serving Fragile Families,'' ``Legal Issues
for Fathers,'' and ``Whatever Happened to Daddy's Little Girl?''
</P>
<P>
   The third summit starts a new action-oriented phase of the
fatherhood movement _ getting more dads to act responsibly, its
organizers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important battles are still before us,'' the NFI said
in a issues paper. ``Achieving attitudinal change may be hard, but
behavioral change is even harder. And that is what our children
need most of all.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.fatherhood.org
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
