<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0607 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-MINORITY-PILOTS-HNS &LR;      05-31 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINORITY-PILOTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PILOTS WANT MORE MINORITIES TO ASCEND TO THE COCKPIT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN GUTIERREZ-MIER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Calvin Allen, dapper in a crisp black uniform
adorned with pilot wings, always turns a few heads as he makes his
way through busy airports.
</P>
<P>
   Allen doesn't attribute that to his good looks. He is one of the
very few African-American pilots for commercial airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about our comfort level,'' said Allen, 47, a Delta
Airlines captain who lives in San Antonio. ``People are used to
seeing white airline pilots, but if you're black, female or some
other minority, that's something people aren't used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 2,000 pilots from across the country will gather here Aug.
7-13 for the Organization of Black Airline Pilots' annual
convention. Members hope the convention will entice women and
minorities to consider a flying career.
</P>
<P>
   That is a difficult task, admits Allen, who is helping to
coordinate the event.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, there were 122,053 licensed pilots in the United
States, according to the Federal Aviation Administration. Of that
total, 5,366 were women. Federal law prohibits the agency from
tracking pilots by race or ethnicity, said Roland Herwig, an FAA
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   (OBAP, as the Atlanta-based airline pilots' organization is
called, has 1,400 members. The organization also includes
Hispanics, Asians and whites. It was formed in 1976, when
African-American commercial pilots numbered only about 80.)
</P>
<P>
   The actual number of pilots whose livelihood depends on flying _
for national and regional airlines, cargo companies, air charters
or air taxis _ is closer to 77,000. About 6 percent are women, 3.5
percent are Hispanic and 2 percent are black, according to the
Atlanta-based Air Information Resources Inc., a career service for
pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, a former Air Force pilot and 1976 graduate of the Air
Force Academy, said African-Americans have a long history in
aviation, but discrimination and glass ceilings have traditionally
kept them and other minorities out of the cockpits of many
commercial airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The all-black Tuskegee Airmen of World War II fame, for example,
received segregated training at the Tuskegee Institute in Alabama.
Their unit was disbanded after the war, but their air combat record
over Europe shattered racial stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, career barriers _ such as height requirement for
pilots that put females at a disadvantage _ have been chiseled away
by lawsuits targeting some of the nation's largest airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Patrice Clarke Washington, the first African-American woman to
serve as a captain for United Parcel Service, remembers the days
when she was the sole black female pilot flying big jets across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started training in 1979 and entered the market in 1982 at a
time when it was difficult to do because the industry was so
stagnant,'' said Washington, whose husband, Ray, is a pilot for
American Airlines. They live in St. Charles, Ill., a Chicago
suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Washington said co-workers were surprised to see a woman flying
the plane. Even today, she is often mistaken for a flight
attendant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that women know that they can do anything they
want,'' she said. ``Unfortunately, there are still too many young
women who don't know they can achieve their wildest dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaime Pacheco, a pilot with Federal Express in Memphis, Tenn.,
and a longtime member of OBAP, said the organization has opened
industry doors for many.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't enough minorities out there, but there's a lot of
pressure to have a diversified work force,'' said Pacheco, a former
Navy pilot who also lives in San Antonio. He lamented the fact that
no similar organization exists for Hispanic pilots.
</P>
<P>
   ``OBAP is promoting the same things I want. Although the
pinnacle would be to become a pilot, the organization is there to
provide opportunities for engineers and mechanics as well,''
Pacheco said.
</P>
<P>
   The organization also works closely with military recruiters and
encourages them to actively seek minorities to enlist as pilots.
Allen said there were more black military pilots flying during
World War II than there are today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike their white counterparts, the black pilots were not
allowed to fly commercially'' after the war.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 12,100 Air Force pilots, 10,976 are white males,
according to the Air Force Recruiting Service Headquarters at
Randolph Air Force Base in San Antonio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
