<SLUG> BC-GE-LABOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GE, UNION TALKS LESS TURBULENT THAN LAST ROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KENNETH AARON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. _ When labor officials sat across from General
Electric Co. executives in New York City to begin negotiations on a
new three-year contract, their primary goals were not be much
different from what they were the last time at the bargaining
table.
</P>
<P>
   Job security, increased pension benefits and health care issues
are the major concerns of the Coordinated Bargaining Committee of
GE Unions, which represents 14 labor groups and 37,000 workers of
the Fairfield, Conn.-based company.
</P>
<P>
   The fervor, though, may have subsided since the 1997 go-round.
Then, with bloodletting at Schenectady's GE Power Systems in
mid-flow, a fiery rally preceded the days before talks started.
Union bigwigs from Washington, D.C., trucked up to the Electric
City to stir the troops in the days before negotiations started.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the local job picture is stable and is expected to remain
so. Power Systems sales are projected at $14 billion this year, a
39 percent increase over last year's results. Instead of noise in
Schenectady, IUE rallies leading to the negotiations have been
scheduled for Indiana, Ohio, Pennsylvania and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business is very good here in Schenectady. We're doing very
well _ people are making some good money,'' said Bob Santamoor,
business agent for the 2,000-member IUE Local 301.
</P>
<P>
   The current contract, ratified in 1997, expires June 25.
Negotiations on a new contract began Tuesday. If history is an
accurate crystal ball, negotiations will continue to the wire.
</P>
<P>
   The last set of talks yielded an 8.75 percent raise over the
three-year contract, an extra holiday and commitment by GE to
replace certain workers who take early retirement.
</P>
<P>
   The company is expecting talks to bear fruit, and on time.
``We're cautiously optimistic,'' said company spokesman Gary
Sheffer.
</P>
<P>
   Santamoor said pension issues remain the key concern of
Schenectady union members. With the average age of the Schenectady
union member at 52, retirement issues loom large.
</P>
<P>
   Convincing GE to award an annual cost-of-living increase to
pensioners, as well as other adjustments in the pension formula,
may be a tall order.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether we can get everything we've been asking for is going
to be tough,'' Santamoor said. ``GE just doesn't want to seem to
bend.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffer said the company periodically boosts pension payments.
It did so earlier this year, and an increase in pension payouts is
fairly guaranteed anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every contract negotiation, there are always some
increases, some improvements,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But if GE grants the request for an annual inflation adjustment
for retirees, it won't be plowing any new turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fairly common in union pension plans to have some kind of
annual increase,'' said Richard Hurd, a professor of labor studies
at Cornell University in Ithaca, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Increases typically are tied to the Consumer Price Index, a
federal gauge that shows the relative cost of a big basket of
items.
</P>
<P>
   The company maintains that it cannot boost pension payments on a
regular basis because it wants to make sure funding is sufficient
for future workers. The unions maintain that GE wants to hold on to
the money because the surplus in its pension fund is reflected in
the company's net income: Last year, more than $1 billion of GE's
$10.7 billion in profits came from the pension fund.
</P>
<P>
   There are other issues, too. Job security is a big one. While
Schenectady employment has been consistent of late, the Coordinated
Bargaining Committee continues to seek assurances that GE will not
outsource its work and also wants to improve the process of
contesting the shipment of jobs elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of different approaches, and we've proposed all
that we can think of,'' said Lauren Asplen, an IUE spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffer said GE will not embrace any strategy that shackles its
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   As far as health care goes, Asplen said early indications show
that GE wants to put a heavier share of insurance costs on workers.
The Coordinated Bargaining Committee is ready to refute arguments
that the company's costs in that arena are up significantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might not be true to the extent that they're claiming,''
she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
