<SLUG> BC-HOTEL-COMPCIERGES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAPTOP TROUBLE? JUST CALL FOR ROOM SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDs: Eirik is CQ)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For many business travelers, the failure of a
laptop computer can be the ultimate nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   But if you are staying at the right hotel, there is nothing to
fear. Just pick up the room phone, call the desk and ask for the
``compcierge.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Ritz-Carlton in San Francisco, a 15-member team of
technology butlers works around the clock to fix modems, repair
printers, debug circuit boards and explain the inexplicable
software of guests' portable computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The requests run the gamut, from `I'm having trouble getting
on the Internet' to `I'm having trouble opening a Word document' to
`My laptop won't boot up,''' said Eirik O'Neal, head of the
technology butler team and systems manager at the Ritz-Carlton.
</P>
<P>
   The service began in January 1999. So far, it has served between
400 and 500 customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 60 percent of our guests travel with their laptops; we
really are a business hotel,'' said Ritz-Carlton spokeswoman Angela
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The technology butlers don't just fix computers. They also have
wrestled with cranky cell phones and dotty Palm Pilots, Jackson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a guest who lost his entire Powerpoint presentation,''
she said. ``One of the butlers went up to the room and re-created
the entire presentation for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The service is free and customers love it, technology butler
Paul Savarino said. ``Everyone I deal with is just head-over-heels
happy. They're amazed that such a service exists.''
</P>
<P>
   Another hotel chain, Toronto-based Four Seasons Hotels and
Resorts Inc., began offering its compcierge service two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw that more and more guests were traveling with their
laptops,'' said Susan Maier, spokeswoman for the Chicago
Ritz-Carlton, which is managed by Four Seasons. Over a six-month
period, ``we saw computer-related calls go from about two a week to
about two per day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago hotel's compcierge service has four employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I carry a cell phone, and I've been awakened at night, say, by
requests from guests who need to print a document for a morning
meeting,'' said Joe Cardinal, who heads the Chicago Ritz-Carlton's
service. ``Most guests' problems involve connectivity, like trying
to get their e-mail or to get on the Internet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
