A0610 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-BORDER-SHOOTINGS-HNS &LR;      05-31 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-SHOOTINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     KILLINGS HEIGHTEN TENSION ALONG THE MEXICAN BORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LISA SANDBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRACKETTVILLE, Texas _ They trek across this harsh terrain by
the thousands, dirt-poor Mexican migrants in a quest for jobs in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Hungry, thirsty and exhausted, they are accused of trampling
fences, slaughtering small livestock, cutting water lines, breaking
into homes _ enraging the ranchers and other property owners who
for years have watched helplessly as the numbers grow.
</P>
<P>
   The rage has grown to the point where some Americans have taken
justice into their own hands _ shooting and, in two cases, killing
Mexican nationals. These cases have exacerbated the uneasy ethnic
and class tensions that have long existed here and threatened to
draw the United States into a dispute with its southern neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, two illegal immigrants have been killed and
three others wounded by landowners. All five were shot from behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are taking the law into their own hands,'' said
the Mexican consul in San Antonio, Juan Jose Martinez. ``Some of
(the victims) weren't even on the men's property when they were
shot. We are very concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Lee, the district attorney for a three-county area west of
San Antonio where the five shootings occurred, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people here want to make a cause celebre out of these
shooters and think that we can just turn our back. ... `He was
trespassing and therefore I had the right to shoot him' doesn't cut
the mustard,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the United Nations opened an investigation into the
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   A Washington law firm, hired by the Mexican government, is
seeking damages from the U.S. property owners for the victims or
the survivors of those killed.
</P>
<P>
   While the landowners say they do not condone the violence, they
understand the fear and frustration that may have led to it.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent shooting occurred May 13 on a 50-acre parcel of
land near Brackettville, a town of 1,800 people 130 west of San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Blackwood, a 74-year-old property owner, was charged with
murder. He is accused of using a handgun to shoot a 23-year-old
Mexican migrant named Eusebio de Haro from a distance of 100 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting occurred in the late afternoon just after de Haro
and a companion, exhausted and dehydrated after a four-day journey
by foot through this rugged country, approached Blackwood's home
and begged for water.
</P>
<P>
   Their request denied, the companions apparently were obeying
orders to leave the property when de Haro was shot once in the rear
upper leg.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the sheriff arrived 45 minutes later, de Haro had
bled to death.
</P>
<P>
   His companion, Javier Sanchez, 28, is in the custody of U.S.
marshals facing a felony charge of illegal entry following a formal
deportation.
</P>
<P>
   Sympathy for Blackwood, who was been released on $150,000 cash
bond, runs deep among property owners in this desertlike expanse of
terrain along the Edwards Plateau.
</P>
<P>
   Residents, who complain the intruders have grown more
destructive over the years, have established a fund to help pay for
Blackwood's defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the man done it on purpose,'' said Harry White,
59, the manager of a 10,000-acre hunting ranch teeming with exotic
animals which, like Blackwood's property, is located along Farm
Road 674. ``The last thing he wanted was to kill one of them. I can
promise you that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kinney County Sheriff Leland K. Burgess said that while
Blackwood may have acted ``recklessly,'' he said others share blame
for the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand why the ranchers don't get together and sue
the Mexican government for failing to keep their people home,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Migrants are not the only new faces in this remote region.
Attracted by this area's inexpensive and starkly beautiful terrain,
retirees from around the United States have flocked here to
purchase sprawling tracts of land, many of which were once part of
vast ranches.
</P>
<P>
   The newcomers are less tolerant of the Mexican trespassers,
longtime residents say.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just don't know what these aliens are going to do,''
White said.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities agree, noting that all four of the suspects
involved in the five shootings are non-native Texans.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions run particularly high along a 5- to 6-mile stretch of
the Rio Grande near Del Rio, where dozens of riverfront residents
on the Vega Verde subdivision say they are virtually under constant
attack from organized Mexican thieves.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they rob you and go across the river, you're out of luck,''
said Bonnie Rosser, an Alabama native who insists bandits scout her
property from across the river. ``We worked hard for our property,
and these people don't come looking just for food and water, they
want the TV and the VCR.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An interview with Rosser about recent burglaries turned into a
community gathering as a dozen neighbors arrived to tell their
stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``You call the sheriff when you're being robbed and someone
shows up two to three hours later,'' said Virginia Ferguson, 36, a
New Jersey native who said she and her grandfather have been
burglarized eight times in recent months. On one occasion, thieves
cut through the side of their house and stole $8,000 worth of
valuables, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson's neighbor, Patrick Bordelon, is accused of shooting
and killing a 16-year-old Mexican in November after the teen-ager
and a group of friends may have tried to burglarize his home.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lee, the district attorney, Bordelon chased Luis
Armando Chavez Vaquera off his property and shot the boy in the
back of the head as the teen was swimming back to Mexico. His
decomposed body was discovered 12 days later.
</P>
<P>
   Released on bond, Bordelon awaits trial for murder.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez Vaquera's grieving parents say Texas' reputation for
harsh justice appears less punishing when the victim is Mexican.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say over there the laws are very strict, but I don't
believe it,'' a tearful Maria del Carmen Vaquera Morrillon said
from the family's dirt-floor shack in Ciudad Acuna, the city across
the river from Del Rio. ``How can you kill someone and get out on
bond? Right now, those people are laughing at the (Texas)
authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   She said her son deserved to be punished for burglary, not
killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said he wanted to steal. We would have paid for those
things,'' she said, sobbing and holding a framed picture of her
son.
</P>
<P>
   Eloy Padilla, a Del Rio attorney with Texas Rural Legal Aid,
said no matter how much support Bordelon enjoys on the U.S. side,
Texas laws frown on people being shot from behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a guy's walking away and you shoot him in the back, even if
it is in your house, that's murder in the state of Texas, period.
... Just because they are burglars doesn't mean it's an open season
to kill,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Lisa Sandberg's e-mail address is
lsandberg(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 1157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
