<HEADER>
A0621 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-DIRT-CLEANER-HNS &LR;      05-31 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIRT-CLEANER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COMPANY TOUTS SIMPLE PROCESS TO DECONTAMINATE DIRT  
 &HT;     (ATTN: N.H., N.Y.) 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DINA CAPPIELLO  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORD EDWARD, N.Y. _ It can turn a brownfield into a playground
in 20 minutes flat.
</P>
<P>
   That is about how long it takes Environmental Soil Management of
New York LLC to zap pollution out of contaminated dirt, using a
shake-and-bake technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only treatment option that can prove and guarantee
destruction of contamination,'' said Bob Manz, president of the
company.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, a host of private businesses and government
agencies flock to the 7.5-acre property located in Fort Edward's
Energy Park industrial complex with their tainted dirt. For $25 to
$40 a ton, ESMI's thermal treatment process virtually erases the
liability associated with owning contaminated sites by recycling
the soil.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which employs 24 people at its location in upstate
New York and another 22 at a similar facility in Loudon, N.H.,
specializes in hydrocarbons _ the long chains of carbon atoms that
constitute gasoline, oils and PCBs, or polychlorinated biphenyls.
</P>
<P>
   The cleaning process is relatively simple: Contaminated dirt is
sorted and screened before being ``baked'' in a large cylindrical
oven that breaks the molecular bonds of contaminants. After 15
minutes of baking, the soil is done.
</P>
<P>
   With other cleanup methods _ such as landfilling, capping and
trapping tainted soil in nonreactive materials like cement _ there
is always the risk that the landowner will be responsible for
contamination coming back to threaten either human health or the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put it in a landfill, you're moving a spill from point
A to point B, but your liability stays the same,'' said Mike Craft,
owner of MC Environmental Services, a cleanup company based in
Glens Falls that has taken contaminated dirt to ESMI since it
opened five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can offer our customers a certificate of treatment which
reduces their liability to the level of contamination that
originally existed in the soil,'' Craft said.
</P>
<P>
   ESMI does not have permits to treat hazardous or highly polluted
solid waste.
</P>
<P>
   Manz said soil investigations are commonplace in business today
as commercial property is transferred from one company to another.
``The majority of the time, some contamination is uncovered and
most likely it's petroleum,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ESMI spun off from parent D.A. Collins Construction Co. around
the time the federal government enacted a law mandating the upgrade
of all underground gasoline storage tanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw that there was a great demand for environmental
cleanups,'' Manz said.
</P>
<P>
   Since it opened in New York in 1995, the company has seen gross
revenue of about $6.5 million annually. Most revenue comes from the
cleanup of contaminated soil and the rest comes from selling the
dirt after it is clean.
</P>
<P>
   On average ESMI generates 10,000 to 12,000 tons of fill each
month in the form of top soil, sand and stone _ an amount
equivalent to what comes out of a mine. The price ranges from 75
cents to $11.75 per ton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 1211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0626 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-WHOLESOME-$ADV04-COX     05-31 1464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHOLESOME-$ADV04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AFTER 94 YEARS, MEANING OF 'WHOLESOME' FOOD STILL DEBATED
 &HT;    1020&AMP;add. For release Sunday, June 4.
 &HT;    By ELLIOT JASPIN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a long tale of horrors, it was among the worst.
</P>
<P>
   A workman slips and falls into a huge vat of meat being rendered
into lard at a packing plant. His bones are fished out, but his
body dissolves and is eventually packaged into ``Durham's Pure Leaf
Lard'' bound for America's kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   This scene from ``The Jungle,'' Upton Sinclair's 1906 novel
about conditions in Chicago's meat-packing industry, shocked the
nation. The U.S. Department of Agriculture launched an
investigation to find if such a thing had actually occurred (it
had), and Congress called hearings to placate a public angry that
it had practiced accidental cannibalism.
</P>
<P>
   The House Agriculture Committee, which convened on June 6, 1906,
was soon embroiled in a debate on what should be covered by a bill
to reform the meat industry.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone agreed that meat ``unfit'' for human consumption should
be banned. But a dispute arose about how the bill should deal with
something that might not hurt a person, but might be ``offensive to
his ideas as to what he will consume.'' The bill said food should
be ``wholesome,'' a term meat industry executives tried but failed
to have removed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite nearly a century of investigations, exposes, regulations
and legislation, the debate that began that June day 94 years ago
is still very much alive. While Congress was clear in 1906 that it
was regulating both the safety and quality of meat, the Agriculture
Department's new science-based inspection system
</P>
<P>
   may be tampering with that mandate.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new inspection rules, which the government started
enforcing in January 1998, traditional ``poke and sniff''
inspections were replaced with a series of tests intended to
monitor critical points in the production process after birds and
animals were slaughtered. Now the same science-based inspection is
being applied to inspections made at the time of slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   While these new experimental rules may protect consumers from
food that will kill or sicken them, the regulations against what
was termed ``loathsome food'' in 1906 have been weakened.
</P>
<P>
   Under the traditional inspection system, federal inspectors
viewed each carcass and culled diseased birds. To make absolutely
certain only healthy birds were used, samples were taken after the
first round of inspections. If a single lesion was found on a
sample, it immediately triggered additional testing. If more
defective birds were discovered, the government clamped
successively stricter controls on the plant.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the experimental regulations say a certain
percentage of birds can have defects such as sores and scabs and
still be shipped to consumers. That is because the regulations
distinguish between health hazards such as fecal contamination and
flaws such as sores, scabs, pus and tumors which, while repugnant,
the government says are safe to eat.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the type of defect, the government may or may not
take action. The new regulations say, for example, that 52 percent
of the birds sampled can have sores.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that the people who framed the original laws
governing meat and poultry were concerned about not only with the
safety, but the quality of their food.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture Department officials issued a report in 1906 that
said their inspectors condemned cattle which, while not diseased,
had ``repugnant conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Flesh showing any unusual condition is always a source of
apprehension to the American public who do not care to eat meat ...
should it present an offensive appearance,'' the report declared.
</P>
<P>
   At the Agriculture Committee hearings, food industry executives
were less squeamish.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas E. Wilson, a meat packing executive, tried unsuccessfully
to weaken the language in the bill by replacing the words
``unsound, unhealthful, or otherwise unfit for human food'' with a
simple admonition not to use carcasses ``unfit for human food.''
</P>
<P>
   As Wilson explained, ``it might be possible for an animal to be
found in some particular unsound, and yet fit for food.''
</P>
<P>
   The suggestion caused an uproar.
</P>
<P>
   One perplexed legislator told Wilson, ``if it is unfit for human
food, it should be condemned. If it is unsound and unhealthful, of
course it is unfit for human food. I do not see why you object to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Samuel Cowan, representing Texas cattle ranchers, tried a
slightly different tack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the term 'wholesome' I would take out entirely,'' Cowan
told the committee. ``I would not have that in the bill, because a
thing that is wholesome to you might not be wholesome to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowan argued that federal inspectors could hamstring business by
interpreting ``wholesome'' any way they wished.
</P>
<P>
   When the bill was debated on the House floor 13 days later,
legislators paid little heed to the meat packers' objections. Words
such as ``wholesome'' stayed in because outside the industry, one
legislator noted, ``no one objects to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a century later, Agriculture Department officials still
say they are responsible for making sure that food reaching the
consumer is wholesome. But as recently as last February,
whistle-blowers inside the Agriculture Department said the
government was allowing diseased chickens to be turned into chicken
nuggets at a Gold Kist Inc. poultry plant in Guntersville, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Following the inspectors' disclosures several school systems
refused to use the chicken nuggets, and a debate ensued on what was
meant by ``wholesome.''
</P>
<P>
   The inspectors at the Gold Kist plants readily acknowledged that
the chicken nuggets would not hurt anyone, arguing instead that
they were not wholesome. To several states such as Ohio, the idea
of ``wholesome'' seemed synonymous with safety because they tested
the product for pathogens. Federal officials would not respond to
repeated requests to explain what they meant by wholesome, but
their press releases emphasized that the Gold Kist products were
safe.
</P>
<P>
   John Bekkers, Gold Kist president and chief operating officer,
said in a statement, ``As we have assured our customers all along,
Gold Kist Farms brand chicken products are safe, wholesome and good
to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   To critics, the Gold Kist case shows that the idea of
wholesomeness has become more flexible.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its program to implement its science-based inspection
methods, the Agriculture Department introduced its experimental
inspection program last October at the Gold Kist plant. While the
plant was supposedly chosen because it processed mostly young,
healthy birds, farmers in the area said the flocks they were
sending to the plant had been ravaged by disease for the past
several years.
</P>
<P>
   As one federal official later noted ruefully to investigators,
``When the Guntersville plant receives birds free of disease, the
(experimental inspection program) works very well. When there is a
high incidence of disease, complaints are raised.''
</P>
<P>
   Because they are supposed to prod the company into policing
itself, federal inspectors said they were ordered not to take
diseased chicken off the production line. That was the company's
job, they said. But the inspectors said that if the company didn't
do its job, nothing much happened.
</P>
<P>
   After the inspectors complained to Cox Newspapers in February
about diseased poultry being sold to consumers, plant records show
there was a dramatic change. Just before news leaked out, the
company condemned about 5 percent of its carcasses on any given
day. Afterwards, the number skyrocketed to 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the testimony of their own inspectors as well as plant
records, the Agriculture Department maintains that food leaving the
Guntersville plant was and is ``safe and wholesome.''
</P>
<P>
   In press releases and public meetings, department officials went
to great pains to point out that their new science-based inspection
prevents anything harmful to humans from slipping through.
</P>
<P>
   But as Nicols(cq) Fox, who has written extensively on the food
industry, pointed out, ``Unquestioned is whether science is even an
appropriate standard for food. It is certainly not the way most
people decide what to eat and what to avoid. Science might tell us
that a cooked fly in our soup isn't dangerous or that sterilized
manure is a safe protein ingredient in corn flakes, but neither
would be acceptable to most of us.''
</P>
<P>
   One the Web: www.goldkist.com
</P>
<P>
   Elliot Jaspin's e-mail address is elliotj(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
