<HEADER>
A0628 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CONLEY-SPELLING-HNS &LR;      05-31 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONLEY-SPELLING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SEAN CONLEY WINS 3 SPELLING ROUNDS, HEADS FOR FINALS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND   
 &HT;     c. 2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sean Conley, a deliberate and reserved
seventh-grader from Newark, Calif., correctly spelled nyctalopia,
discomfiture and floppety at the 73rd National Spelling Bee
Wednesday, hurtling him in Thursday's finals.
</P>
<P>
   Sean, 12, who is schooled at home, hopes to top his tie for
ninth place last year. The San Francisco Examiner is sponsoring him
in the bee.
</P>
<P>
   Sean was among 248 contestants in the bee, many of them
fidgeting and twisting in their chairs upon hearing a dreaded bell
that signals mistakes. While dozens of them went to the so-called
``comfort room'' to regain their composure after losing, Sean
calmly tapped his fingers on his thighs as if playing the piano,
awaiting his next turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just tapping,'' he said during a break in the contest.
``I'm getting bored. I've seen all these words before. There's no
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Each time Sean's turn came up and he faced the word pronouncer
at an imposing black podium beside the red-curtained stage, he
asked for the word's meaning, its origin and its use in a sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just ask a lot of questions because it gives me time to
think,'' Sean said. ``I want to make sure I don't say the wrong
letters.'' He added: ``Some kids race right through and sometimes
they accidentally say a wrong letter.''
</P>
<P>
   The first word was a cinch: Nyctalopia, a Greek word that means
unable to see at twilight. Then came discomfiture, which means
frustration or confusion. Sean knocked that one off too.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he nailed floppety, which means soft and flexible.
</P>
<P>
   During the break, Sean said he was confident because he had
prepared thoroughly. ``I've been studying from lists of words
they've used in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he hopes to have a computer job when he grows up. Sean's
father, Mike Conley, is an Apple Computer software engineer, said
he had one main objective: ``I want him to learn a little poise _ a
little grace under pressure.'' Conley, however, admitted that he
himself was not cool on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat there and bit my fingers just waiting for that bell to
ring,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Conley said Sean started reading at 18 months old. At age
two he was spelling, using plastic refrigerator magnet letters.
</P>
<P>
   Bry Conley, his mother, said Sean likes ``puzzles and
competitions and competing and winning.'' She added that she hoped
he would make friends at the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of these absent-minded-professor types.'' She also
noted, however, that her son, whom she teaches at home through the
Tri-City Homeschoolers program, has ``worked really hard for it (a
victory) for so many years.''
</P>
<P>
   The spelling bee, sponsored by E.W. Scripps Co., offers the
winner prizes that include $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
</P>
<P>
   Judy &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 1254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
