<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sean Conley, a deliberate and reserved
seventh-grader from Newark, Calif., correctly spelled nyctalopia,
discomfiture and floppety at the 73rd National Spelling Bee
Wednesday and advanced to Thursday's finals.
</P>
<P>
   Sean, 12, who is schooled at home, hopes to top his tie for
ninth place in last year's bee. His entry is sponsored by The San
Francisco Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Sean was among 248 contestants in the bee, many of them
fidgeting and twisting in their chairs upon hearing a dreaded bell
that signals mistakes. While dozens of them went to the so-called
``comfort room'' to regain their composure after losing, Sean
calmly tapped his fingers on his thighs as if playing the piano,
awaiting his next turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just tapping,'' he said during a break in the contest.
``I'm getting bored. I've seen all these words before. There's no
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Each time Sean's turn came up and he faced the word pronouncer
at an imposing black podium beside the red-curtained stage, he
asked for the word's meaning, its origin and its use in a sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just ask a lot of questions because it gives me time to
think,'' Sean said. ``I want to make sure I don't say the wrong
letters.'' He added: ``Some kids race right through and sometimes
they accidentally say a wrong letter.''
</P>
<P>
   The first word was a cinch: Nyctalopia, a Greek word that means
unable to see at twilight. Then came discomfiture, which means
frustration or confusion. Sean knocked that one off too.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he nailed floppety, which means soft and flexible.
</P>
<P>
   During the break, Sean said he was confident because he had
