<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0644 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-WRESTLING-GRAPEVINE01     05-31 0305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-GRAPEVINE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GRAPEVINE: News, notes and gossip from the wrestling industry
 &HT;    By John Allen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's start off with our own rumor killer and this comes
straight the horse's mouth. ``I was reading on the Internet, 'Dusty
leaves ECW, returns to WCW,' usty Rhodes said. ``What happened is
that Turner South came to me _ Turner South _ and they wanted me to
host a WCW Classic show. And I said, `cool.' And the show is going
to be hot, and they'll probably show it ten times a day, so I'll
become the new Andy Griffith,'' Rhodes said. ``But I'm still with
(ECW executive producer) Paulie (Heyman). (After being fired at
WCW) Paulie called and said, 'Dream are you OK, you need anything?
.. . You're never too old for me. Why don't you come up here, no
contract, I'll give you this much money, just come up here, right
now, as long as I'm here.''
</P>
<P>
   That made me feel good. I went, respected the guy's show and I
remembered how much I had missed it. If he calls me, I'll be
wherever he needs me. And if you don't see me for three or four
months, you'll see me because out of sight out of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Bet you didn't know, Dusty Rhodes was the youth football coach
of the year in the Atlanta area for 1999. Rhodes coached his son
Cody's eighth-grade team to the conference championship. ``It was
the highlight of my career, even with all the places I've been,
it's my biggest thrill,'' Rhodes said.
</P>
<P>
   Do you think this is the end for Ric Flair? He has a career
match at the June 11th ''Great American Bash'' against his son
David, but as we have seen at previous pay-per-views, losing a
match that forces you into retirement doesn't mean you have to stay
retired. Right Kevin Nash?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
