<HEADER>
A0674 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-CHICKEN-SFCHRON &LR;      05-31 5352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICKEN-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Romancing the Chicken: Just when you thought your affair
with  America's most popular bird was over, 10 chefs show you how
to 
 rekindle the flame   By Tilde Herrera  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Chicken and I have been on the rocks for years.
<TEXT>
<P>
   I used to be a devout chicken-lover, always eager to include it
in casual and special meals. I found it so satisfying that it edged
beef, fish and other proteins from my diet and I ate it nearly
every day.
</P>
<P>
   But awhile back, I realized my romance was faltering. I became
disillusioned with chicken. It was too accessible, too mainstream.
My interest started to wane.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, carne asada replaced grilled chicken tacos. Ahi
tuna salad became too tempting to pass up. And then, the ultimate
betrayal _ I opted for seared ostrich loin instead of roasted free
range chicken.
</P>
<P>
   The honeymoon was over, the excitement long gone. Chicken had
become boring.
</P>
<P>
   I tried to salvage my relationship by asking some of the Bay
Area's top chefs what they do to keep chicken interesting. Johnny
Alamilla, chicken enthusiast and executive chef of San Francisco's
Ch &LR; e &LR; , uses spices and marinades to perk up his chicken dishes. He
loves the way the neutral meat reacts to countless flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Ben de Vries, of Ristorante Ecco in San Francisco, caramelizes
the skin by searing it to add a new dimension to the sweet flesh.
He also adds simple accompaniments, like fresh herbs and flavored
oils, to let the chicken's simple flavor shine through. De Vries
emphasizes that using good quality chicken is essential to a
satisfying meal.
</P>
<P>
   To help reignite my &LR;   &LR; affair with chicken, Alamilla and de Vries
came up with unique, easy chicken recipes I could cook at home,
using ingredients and techniques reflective of their specialities.
A host of other top notch chefs did the same.
</P>
<P>
   They'll work for you, too, if you've tired of chicken for
dinner, day in and day out. Most of these recipes can be made in a
short time. Some need to marinate overnight, but the actual cooking
is a breeze.
</P>
<P>
   These tips from the experts are just what I needed. If your
romance with chicken has been at a low lately, give these recipes a
try. They just may help you turn your ho-hum date with America's
most overused bird into an affair to remember.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Handling Chicken &QL;  &LR; 
Chicken, like any raw meat, can harbor salmonella and other
potential disease-causing organisms, so storing and handling it
properly are essential to reducing the risk of contracting any
illness.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Refrigerate.  &LR; After purchase, refrigerate chicken on the
bottom shelf (generally the coldest part) of the refrigerator for
up to two days. Keep chicken refrigerated until ready to use. Store
chicken wrapped in loose wax paper or in loose plastic wrap. Place
it on a plate or dish to prevent the juices from dripping onto
other foods and surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Freeze.  &LR; In the freezer, chicken should be kept in a tightly
sealed container or heavy duty freezer bag for up to six months.
Its quality will be best if it's used within two months.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Defrost.  &LR; Defrost chicken on the bottom shelf of the
refrigerator. It is important that the chicken is defrosted evenly;
otherwise, parts of the flesh that are still frozen before cooking
may not reach the temperature required to kill salmonella bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Cook.  &LR; The U.S. Food and Drug Administration recommends that
chicken be cooked to minimum internal temperature of 165 to kill
salmonella and other bacteria. For a whole chicken, insert a meat
thermometer into the thickest part of the inner thigh area near the
breast without touching the bone. For a single breast, insert the
thermometer into the thickest part.
</P>
<P>
   After cooking, let the chicken rest about five minutes for
single breasts and 10 minutes for whole birds to let the juices
redistribute before carving.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Clean up.  &LR; Wash your hands thoroughly with soap and water
before and after handling raw chicken. Always use a separate
cutting board for chicken if preparing other meats or vegetables
simultaneously to avoid cross-contamination. Wash utensils and
cutting board in hot, soapy water and sanitize immediately.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good idea to keep a sanitizer on hand to spray on
counters, utensils and cutting boards after use. Simply fill a
spray bottle with water and add a splash of bleach (about 1/2
tablespoon to 1 quart of water). Shake to combine. Be sure to label
the bottle and keep it out of reach of children.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Facts About Chicken &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Americans remain smitten with chicken, according to the National
Chicken Council and the U.S. Poultry and Egg Association. On May 1,
the two trade organizations released results from their latest
survey that shows nine out of 10 households consume chicken at
least once a week, while three out of 10 households consume chicken
three or more times per week. About 11 percent of those surveyed
declared they expected to eat even more chicken in the next year.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bill Mattos, president of the California Poultry
Industry Federation, Americans consume more chicken than any other
meat _ 81 pounds per person annually. That's five pounds more per
capita than last year. Meat and pork lag behind at 69 pounds and 52
pounds, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE CHEFS AND THEIR RESTAURANTS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Johnny Alamilla.  &LR; Ch &LR; e &LR; , 320 Third St. (at Folsom), San
Francisco; (415) 546-3131. Lunch weekdays; dinner Monday-Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Jean Alberti.  &LR; Evvia, 420 Emerson St. (near Lytton Avenue),
Palo Alto; (650) 326-0983. Lunch weekdays; dinner nightly. Also
Kokkari, 200 Jackson St. (at Front), San Francisco; (415) 981-0983.
Lunch weekdays; dinner Monday-Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ John Beardsley &LR; . Ponzu, 401 Taylor St. (at O'Farrell), San
Francisco; (415) 775-7979. Breakfast and dinner daily.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Curt Clingman.  &LR; Jojo, 3859 Piedmont Ave. (near Rio Vista),
Oakland; (510) 985-3003. Dinner Tuesday-Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Khai Dong.  &LR; Ana Mandara, 891 Beach St. (at Polk Street, in
Ghirardelli Square), San Francisco; (415) 771-6800. Dinner nightly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Donald Link.  &LR; Mojo, 543 Emerson St. (at Hamilton Avenue),
Palo Alto; (650) 323-7700. Dinner nightly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Julia McClaskey.  &LR; Dine, 662 Mission St. (near Third Street),
San Francisco; (415) 538-3463. Dinner Monday-Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Daniel Patterson.  &LR; Elisabeth Daniel, 550 Washington St.
(between Sansome and Montgomery), San Francisco; (415) 397-6129.
Lunch weekdays; dinner Monday-Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Benjamin de Vries.  &LR; Ristorante Ecco, 101 South Park (between
Second and Third streets, Bryant and Brannan), San Francisco; (415)
495-3291. Lunch weekdays; dinner Monday-Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Seiji Wakabayashi.  &LR; Ondine, 558 Bridgeway, Sausalito; (415)
331-1133. Dinner nightly; brunch Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; MOJO'S CHICKEN &AMP; DUMPLINGS
</P>
<P>
   Donald Link, who is the executive chef of San Francisco's Elite
Cafe and Palo Alto's Mojo, says this recipe was inspired by his
grandfather. The level of heat can be adjusted by adding more _ or
less _ cayenne pepper. For faster preparation, substitute a
preroasted whole chicken, available at most grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   The Chicken
</P>
<P>
   1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   4 fresh sage leaves
</P>
<P>
   One 21/4- to 3-pound chicken
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Cayenne to taste
</P>
<P>
   Paprika to taste
</P>
<P>
   The Sauce
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup diced onion
</P>
<P>
   1 cup diced celery
</P>
<P>
   1 cup diced carrot
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped fresh sage
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Cajun seasoning + more to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon hot sauce (Link uses Christal Chili Sauce)
</P>
<P>
   The Dumplings
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced onion
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh sage
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   Instructions: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; To roast the chicken: &LR;  Preheat oven to 450 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Cut 2 thin slices from the lemon. Insert 1 lemon slice and 2
sage leaves under the skin on each chicken breast. Season the
entire chicken generously with salt, pepper, cayenne pepper and
paprika.
</P>
<P>
   Roast the chicken for 35 to 40 minutes, or until done.
</P>
<P>
   Let chicken cool and remove meat from bones.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the sauce and assemble the dish:  &LR; Melt 1 tablespoon of
the butter in a skillet. Add the vegetables, herbs, Cajun seasoning
and salt. Cook until the vegetables are soft, about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the remaining 3 tablespoons butter. When the butter melts,
whisk in the flour. Cook, stirring constantly, for a couple of
minutes until the mixture takes on a ``nutty'' aroma. Slowly stir
in the wine, cream, broth, lemon juice and hot sauce. Simmer for 10
minutes, stirring occasionally. Add the chicken pieces and simmer
for 10 minutes, stirring occasionally. Taste and adjust seasoning
as needed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the dumplings:  &LR; Melt the butter in a small skillet; add
the minced onion and saute slowly until it softens and turns
translucent. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the flour, sage, mustard, salt and cayenne in a mixing
bowl; stir to blend.
</P>
<P>
   Mix together the milk, eggs, baking powder and sauteed onion.
Add to the dry ingredients and stir until just incorporated.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer chicken mixture to a 9 x 9-inch baking dish. Drop big
spoonfuls of dumpling batter about 1/2-inch apart on top. Cover and
bake for 10 to 15 minutes. Uncover and bake for an additional 5
minutes, or until the dumplings begin to brown.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 to 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 388 calories, &LR;   &LR; 23 g protein, 26 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 20 g fat (10 g saturated), 142 mg cholesterol, 994
mg sodium, 2 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; CHE'S HAVANA-STYLE CHICKEN
</P>
<P>
   An airline chicken breast has the first half of the trimmed wing
bone still attached. Even if a boneless chicken breast is used,
make sure that the skin is still intact. Also, make sure the
plantains are ripe for this recipe, otherwise they will not absorb
enough flavor from the marinade. Chef Johnny Alamilla recommends
serving this dish with fresh or sauteed greens, such as spinach or
chard.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   The Marinade
</P>
<P>
   2 cups freshly squeezed orange juice (about 4 oranges)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups freshly squeezed lime juice (about 9 limes)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh oregano
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup chopped fresh Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoon chopped garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 Fresno chiles, seeded and chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground coriander seeds
</P>
<P>
   The Chicken and Plantains
</P>
<P>
   6 chicken breasts, wing bone attached (``airline breast'')
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil as needed
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1/2 lime
</P>
<P>
   3 ripe plantains, peeled and sliced lengthwise, then cut in half
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine all marinade ingredients and let stand for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Rinse each chicken breast and pat dry, then add to the marinade.
Chicken may marinate overnight (in the refrigerator) for a bold,
citrus flavor, or for 1 hour at room temperature (if marinating for
only an hour, give the chicken a squeeze of lime before serving for
extra zing).
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Remove the chicken from the
marinade and pat dry. Season with salt and pepper. Add enough olive
oil to a heavy cast-iron skillet to coat the bottom. Place over
medium heat. When hot, add the chicken skin-side down and saute
until browned. Flip the chicken breasts and place the entire
skillet in the oven. Roast for 7 to 8 minutes, or until the chicken
is three-quarters cooked (timing will depend on size of chicken
breasts).
</P>
<P>
   Remove the skillet from the oven and transfer the chicken to a
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Add the lime juice to the skillet. Add the plantains and toss
them in the pan drippings until coated. Return the skillet to the
oven, and bake for 5 to 8 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Return the chicken breasts to skillet and roast for 10 minutes
longer.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 311 calories, &LR;   &LR; 31 g protein, 16 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 14 g fat (4 g saturated), 92 mg cholesterol, 93 mg
sodium, 2 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. The calories and other nutrients absorbed from
marinades &LR;   &LR; vary and are difficult to estimate; therefore, the
marinade is &LR;   &LR; not included in the analysis. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SAUTEED CHARD
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   1 shallot, minced
</P>
<P>
   4 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 jalapeno pepper, seeded and minced
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches red chard, stemmed, washed and leaves cut into large
pieces
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in a large skillet over medium-high heat.
</P>
<P>
   Add the butter and heat until it is melted and frothy.
</P>
<P>
   Add the shallot, garlic and jalapeno and saute for 1 to 2
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the chard and cook until just wilted and tender.
</P>
<P>
   Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 82 calories, &LR;   &LR; 2 g protein, 6 g carbohydrate, 6
g &LR;   &LR; fat (2 g saturated), 8 mg cholesterol, 147 mg sodium, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
VIETNAMESE LEMON CHICKEN SKEWERS
</P>
<P>
   These flavorful skewers may be served with a green salad or
rice. Be careful not to marinate the chicken too long or the highly
acidic marinade will start to ``cook'' it. From Khai Dong at Ana
Mandara.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 scallions, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   Zest of 1 lemon, grated
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   3 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Asian fish sauce (nuoc mam)
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   4 boneless, skinless chicken breasts
</P>
<P>
   12 bamboo skewers
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the scallions, lemon zest, lemon juice, garlic, pepper,
sugar, fish sauce and oil in a medium-size bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Slice the chicken crosswise on the diagonal into wide strips.
Place in the marinade, cover and refrigerate for at least 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Soak the skewers in warm water for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat broiler or grill.
</P>
<P>
   Thread the chicken strips onto the skewers. Broil 5 inches from
the heat source for about 4 minutes per side, or until done.
Alternately, grill the chicken for about 4 minutes per side.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 129 calories, &LR;   &LR; 27 g protein, 0 g carbohydrate,
1 &LR;   &LR; g fat (0 g saturated), 68 mg cholesterol, 76 mg sodium, 0 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. The calories and other nutrients absorbed from marinades &LR; 
 &LR; vary and are difficult to estimate; therefore, the marinade is &LR; 
 &LR; not included in the analysis. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; KOKKARI'S GRILLED CHICKEN SOUVLAKI
</P>
<P>
   Colorful and light, these Mediterranean skewers from chef Jean
Alberti make a great grilling option on warm, summer nights. The
tangy lemon vinaigrette is wonderful drizzled over the skewers, and
can also be tossed with fresh greens on the side. Complete the menu
with a wild rice pilaf.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  The Marinade
</P>
<P>
   3 cups plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh oregano
</P>
<P>
   3 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fresh orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   The Chicken
</P>
<P>
   6 boneless, skinless chicken half-breasts
</P>
<P>
   6 bamboo skewers
</P>
<P>
   3 green bell peppers, deribbed and cut into 1-inch squares
</P>
<P>
   3 red bell peppers, deribbed and cut into 1-inch squares
</P>
<P>
   1 red onion, cut into 1-inch squares
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Oregano sprigs for garnish
</P>
<P>
   The Vinaigrette
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped fresh oregano
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons minced shallot
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Mix together all marinade ingredients in a glass container.
</P>
<P>
   Cut each chicken breast into 5 or 6 pieces and place in the
marinade.
</P>
<P>
   Cover and refrigerate for 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the vinaigrette: &LR;  Mix together the parsley, fresh and
dried oregano, the shallot, garlic, lemon juice and salt and
pepper. Slowly whisk in the oil.
</P>
<P>
   Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To cook the chicken:  &LR; Soak the bamboo skewers in warm water for
1 hour. Preheat grill.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the chicken from marinade. Thread the chicken and
vegetables onto the skewers alternating about 5 pieces of each per
skewer.
</P>
<P>
   Brush each skewer with olive oil and season with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Grill until done, about 8 to 10 minutes per side.
</P>
<P>
   Garnish with fresh oregano sprigs and drizzle with the
vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 479 calories, &LR;   &LR; 28 g protein, 7 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 38 g fat (5 g saturated), 68 mg cholesterol, 79 mg sodium, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. The calories and other nutrients absorbed from marinades &LR; 
 &LR; vary and are difficult to estimate; therefore, the marinade is &LR; 
 &LR; not included in the analysis. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
JOJO'S PROVENCAL CHICKEN
</P>
<P>
   This earthy, Provencal-inspired dish, by Jojo's Curt Clingman,
requires a minimum of preparation and tastes fabulous. Clingman
specifies using quality olives like Picholine or Lucques. They
should not be pitted, Clingman says, because the pits add a
wonderful nutty quality to the dish. Be sure to warn your guests
before they start to eat. Serve with rice, lightly oiled pasta or a
loaf of country-style French bread.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt + salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon pepper + pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   6 chicken legs, drumsticks separated from thighs
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup pure olive oil
</P>
<P>
   6 spring onions, cut in half lengthwise
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   4 branches fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   4 branches fresh savory
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   6 small carrots, peeled and cut into small pieces
</P>
<P>
   Peel from 1/2 organic orange, removed with a vegetable peeler
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Picholine or Lucques olives (see note)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons imported Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Mix together the flour, salt and pepper. Dredge the chicken
pieces in the flour mixture, shaking off excess.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in an oven-safe skillet. Add the chicken and
fry until lightly browned, turning once. Remove the chicken from
the skillet and set aside. Add the onions cut-side down to the
skillet and saute until lightly browned; remove and set aside.
Drain the grease from the skillet. Add the wine and cook over high
heat until reduced by half. Tie the thyme and savory together with
kitchen string. Add the chicken broth and the thyme and savory.
Season with salt and pepper. Bring to a boil, return the chicken
and onions to the skillet, add the carrots and simmer for 5
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Loosely cover the skillet with a piece of parchment paper or
foil and place in the oven. Bake for 45 minutes. Check after first
15 minutes to be sure the liquid is simmering slowly.
</P>
<P>
   When the chicken is done, remove the pan from the oven. Give the
herb bundle a shake to free the leaves into the sauce. Discard the
stems. Skim the fat from the sauce. Add the orange peel and olives,
cover and let steep for 20 minutes. Stir in the mustard and bring
everything back to a simmer. Adjust seasoning. Garnish with
parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with rice or pasta.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note: &LR;  Do not pit the olives. The pits add a wonderful nutty
flavor to the dish. However, be sure to warn your guests before
they start to eat.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 577 calories, &LR;   &LR; 32 g protein, 9 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 41 g fat (8 g saturated), 138 mg cholesterol, 1,644 mg sodium, &LR;   &LR; 2
g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; PONZU'S CHICKEN WINGS WITH CARAMEL-BLACK PEPPER GLAZE
</P>
<P>
   These addictive chicken wings, by Ponzu's John Beardsley, make
an exciting appetizer or light entree served with steamed jasmine
rice. The quick and easy preparation also makes this dish ideal for
last-minute entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   12 chicken wings
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 quarts vegetable oil for deep frying
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon water
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup Asian fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Cut the chicken wings into 2 pieces, cutting at the joint.
Remove the wing tips and reserve for stock, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a large pot to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Add the chicken wings and fry for about 10 to 15 minutes, until
golden brown and crispy. Remove the wings to paper towels to drain.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the sugar and water in a small saucepan; place over
medium-high heat until the sugar turns a light caramel color, about
7 minutes. Remove from heat and add the fish sauce. The sauce will
boil vigorously. Return to medium heat and cook until slightly
thickened, about 30 seconds to 1 minute. Stir in the pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the chicken wings with the sauce and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 3.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 485 calories, &LR;   &LR; 27 g protein, 35 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 24 g fat (7 g saturated), 114 mg cholesterol, 1,851
mg sodium, &LR;   &LR; 0 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
OVEN ROASTED CHICKEN STUFFED WITH PARMESAN ORZO ON SAUTEED RAINBOW
SWISS CHARD WITH PAN JUS
</P>
<P>
   Perfect for a weekend dinner, these stuffed chickens, by Dine's
Julia McClaskey, make an impressive presentation. The preparation
can be time consuming but the end product is spectacular _ and it's
basically a one-dish meal. Cutting the whole stuffed chickens in
half during the roasting process is the trickiest part.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   The Chickens
</P>
<P>
   6 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 bunch chives, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 bunch rosemary, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 bunch thyme, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 two-pound chickens
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Parmesan Orzo
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces orzo
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh sage
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup freshly grated Parmigiano-Reggiano cheese, plus 6
tablespoons for topping
</P>
<P>
   The Jus
</P>
<P>
   4 cups chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup butter (optional)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   The Chard
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 shallot, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch rainbow Swiss chard, rinsed and chopped
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The chickens:  &LR; Mix the garlic, chives, rosemary and thyme with
the olive oil in a large bowl. Coat chickens with the mixture, then
season with salt and pepper. Cover and refrigerate for at least 6
hours, or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Cook the orzo according to instructions on package, until al
dente. Rinse with cold water and drain. Toss with the olive oil and
combine with the sage, 1/2 cup of the cheese, and salt and pepper
to taste. Stuff the chickens with the orzo mixture, tie the legs
together and place on a rack in a roasting pan.
</P>
<P>
   Roast for 60 minutes. Remove the chickens from the oven.
Increase the oven temperature to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Carefully cut each chicken in half. Place the halves
stuffing-side up on a greased baking sheet. Top with the remaining
cheese. Bake for 10 minutes, or until the topping is browned.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The jus:  &LR; While chickens are roasting, prepare the pan jus and
chard. Pour the chicken stock into a saucepan and cook over medium
heat until reduced to 2 cups. Add the optional butter, the lemon
juice and parsley. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The chard:  &LR; Melt the butter in a large skillet. Add the garlic
and shallot and cook until slightly browned. Add the chard and
cook, stirring, until wilted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To serve: &LR;  Make a bed of the chard on a warmed serving platter.
Arrange the chicken halves on the chard, then spoon the pan jus
over the chickens.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 1,049 calories, &LR;   &LR; 88 g protein, 52 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 53 g fat (16 g saturated), 241 mg cholesterol, &LR;   &LR; 748
mg sodium, 3 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
POLLO AL MATTONE (CHICKEN COOKED UNDER A BRICK)
</P>
<P>
   Ristorante Ecco's Benjamin de Vries updates this classic Italian
entree with the addition of Yukon Gold potatoes, wild mushrooms and
fragrant porcini oil, available at specialty food stores and
Italian markets. Controlling the heat is the most important part of
this dish. By cooking the chicken in a preheated pan, the natural
juices are sealed in and the skin caramelizes for extra sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   The Chicken
</P>
<P>
   4 sprigs oregano, chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 sprigs thyme, chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 sprigs rosemary, chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 sprigs sage, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup pure olive oil + olive oil for skillet
</P>
<P>
   1 small chicken (about 2 pounds), split and backbone removed
</P>
<P>
   The Potatoes &AMP; Mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 large Yukon Gold potatoes, rinsed and cut into 1-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   10 cipollini onions, peeled and halved
</P>
<P>
   1 pound assorted wild mushrooms, sliced (porcini, hedgehog and
chanterelles are recommended. If not available, shiitake and oyster
mushrooms may be used)
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons chopped fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces porcini oil
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons pepper
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the herbs and olive oil in a small bowl. Place the
chicken in a shallow pan and pour the olive oil mixture over it.
Turn the chicken in the marinade, rubbing it into all the nooks and
crannies, until the chicken is completely coated. Cover and
refrigerate for at least 2 hours; overnight is even better.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To prepare the potatoes and mushrooms:  &LR; Preheat oven to 350
degrees. Heat the olive oil in a 12-inch roasting pan or a 14-inch
Dutch oven over medium heat. Add the potatoes and onions and saute
until lightly browned. Add the mushrooms and thyme and cook for an
additional 5 minutes. Drizzle with 2 ounces porcini oil, sprinkle
with the salt and pepper, and place in the oven. Roast until the
potatoes are cooked through, about 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cooking the chicken:  &LR; While the vegetables are roasting, place
two 14-inch cast-iron skillets over high heat. When the pans are
very hot, add enough olive oil to one pan to coat the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Place the chicken breast-side down in the hot oil (careful, it
will splatter). Place the second skillet on top of the chicken and,
using oven mitts, press down firmly. If the top skillet does not
seem heavy enough, weight it down with a brick.
</P>
<P>
   Reduce the heat to medium. Fry the chicken, turning it every 5
minutes and replacing the top skillet each time, for about 25
minutes, or until done. Remove chicken from skillet and let rest
for 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To Serve:  &LR; Cut each chicken half into 2 pieces, dividing
between the breast and thigh/leg.
</P>
<P>
   Portion the vegetables onto warmed serving plates. Top each
portion with a chicken quarter. Drizzle each with an equal amount
of the remaining 2 ounces porcini oil.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 872 calories, &LR;   &LR; 41 g protein, 35 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 64 g fat (12 g saturated), 134 mg cholesterol, 943
mg sodium, 6 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. The calories and other nutrients absorbed
from &LR;   &LR; marinades vary and are difficult to estimate; therefore,
the &LR;   &LR; marinade is not included in the analysis. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; ROASTED CHICKEN WITH ASPARAGUS, FENNEL &AMP; POTATOES
</P>
<P>
   This homey, hearty dish is the type of casual meal that
Elisabeth Daniel's Daniel Patterson prefers to make on one of his
rare days off. Quality ingredients should be used because of the
recipe's straightforward nature. All of the ingredients, except the
aged sherry vinegar, usually can be found at the San Francisco
Ferry Plaza Farmers' Market (Saturday mornings). Patterson
specifically recommends using chicken from Hoffman Gamebirds,
organically grown vegetables and olive oil from Davero or Nick
Sciabica &AMP; Sons.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 chicken, 4 to 5 pounds
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 pound small Yukon Gold potatoes (creamer size)
</P>
<P>
   2 fennel bulbs
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons green (also called Fall harvest) olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 pound asparagus
</P>
<P>
   1 cup low-sodium chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon aged sherry vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced chives
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The chicken:  &LR; Season the chicken generously, inside and out,
with salt and pepper. Place the chicken breast-up in a roasting
pan. Roast for about 1 hour, or until done. Transfer the chicken to
a platter and let rest for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The vegetables: &LR;  Place the potatoes in a saucepan. Fill with
water to cover by 1 inch; add a generous amount of salt. Bring to a
gentle boil, then simmer for 5 to 10 minutes, or until a sharp
knife can easily pierce the potatoes. Drain. When cool enough to
handle, peel the potatoes and cut into quarters. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Quarter the fennel bulbs lengthwise. Cut out the core, then cut
the fennel into 3/8-inch strips.
</P>
<P>
   Heat 1 tablespoon of the olive oil in a large skillet over low
heat. Add the fennel and gently saute until tender, about 30
minutes. Season with salt and pepper. Remove from heat and set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Trim the tough ends from the asparagus and cut the spears into
2-inch lengths.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the asparagus with 2 tablespoons of the olive oil and a
little salt in a oven-proof saute pan. Place pan in the oven and
roast until the asparagus is tender, about 10 to 15 minutes,
tossing every few minutes. Remove from oven and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; After chicken is done:  &LR; Combine the asparagus and potatoes in
the skillet with the fennel. Keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Pour off the fat from the roasting pan, reserving a few
tablespoons. Add this reserved fat to the vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Add the chicken broth to the pan and bring to a boil, scraping
up the browned bits from bottom of the pan. Boil until the liquid
has reduced by one quarter. Strain the liquid into a bowl. Add the
sherry vinegar and remaining 2 tablespoons olive oil. Add any
accumulated juices from the chicken. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To serve: &LR;  Mound the vegetables in the center of a serving dish
and pour the sauce over them. Place the chicken on top and garnish
with chives.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 578 calories, &LR;   &LR; 41 g protein, 32 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 32 g fat (7 g saturated), 109 mg cholesterol, 165
mg sodium, 4 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; ROASTED GARLIC &AMP; MISO MARINATED CHICKEN BREASTS WITH SESAME-SOY
CHARD
</P>
<P>
   This is another excellent grilling option from Ondine's Seiji
Wakabayashi. The roasted garlic and miso nuances are accented by
the tanginess of the Asian-inspired chard. The chicken also would
be terrific incorporated into a Chinese chicken salad.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   The Chicken
</P>
<P>
   2 heads of garlic
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup red miso (Miso Master Brand is suitable)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup white miso
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup hot chile oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   4 boneless, skinless chicken breasts
</P>
<P>
   The Chard
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sesame seeds, toasted
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 shallot, minced
</P>
<P>
   4 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches red chard, stemmed, leaves rinsed and chopped
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Marinade: &LR;  Preheat oven to 450 degrees. Slice the top off
of the garlic heads, keeping the cloves intact. Remove the outer,
papery skins. Brush the heads of garlic with olive oil and wrap in
aluminum foil. Place in the oven and roast for 45 minutes to 1
hour, or until the cloves are completely softened.
</P>
<P>
   Squeeze the roasted garlic cloves from their skins and place in
a blender. Add the red and white miso, hot chile oil, chicken broth
and salt. Blend until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the marinade into a bowl; add the chicken breasts and turn
to coat. Cover and refrigerate for from 8 to 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Chicken:  &LR; Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Place the chicken in
a baking dish and bake for 25 to 35 minutes, or until done.
Alternately, grill the chicken for about 8 minutes per side.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Chard:  &LR; Combine the sesame seeds, soy sauce and sugar in a
blender and puree. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in a skillet. Add the shallot and garlic and
saute until softened, about 1 minute. Add the chard to the skillet
and cook, tossing occasionally, until just wilted. Add the sesame
seed mixture and toss to distribute evenly.
</P>
<P>
   Portion the chard onto warmed serving plates, then place a
chicken breast alongside.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 339 calories, &LR;   &LR; 33 g protein, 17 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 16 g fat (3 g saturated), 73 mg cholesterol, 1,388
mg sodium, 3 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. The calories and other nutrients absorbed
from &LR;   &LR; marinades vary and are difficult to estimate; therefore,
the &LR;   &LR; marinade is not included in the analysis. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
