<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Mushroom Magic Awaits Those Who Dare to Hunt   By Kim Severson  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Wild king boletes and rumple-headed morels can
sell for $45 a pound or more in Bay Area markets _ a prospect that
makes gathering your own an attractive alternative.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finding your own fungus in the woods is particularly sweet in
the spring, when mythic morels appear for just a handful of weeks
and the first bold, chunky king boletes (call them porcini or
cepes) are just starting their march through the forest.
</P>
<P>
   To the uninitiated, how and where to search _ and even what to
hunt for _ remains as much a mystery as the morels themselves. But
for those dedicated enough to camp out in the woods and tromp
through old burns and slag in search of springtime mushrooms, an
organized foray is the way to go.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonoma-based Wild About Mushrooms Sierra offers a series of
camps throughout the year that teach novices how find and cook wild
mushrooms. Longtime fungus freak Charmoon Richardson runs the two-
and three-day events, which cost around $100 depending on the trip,
and often serves as head chef when a visiting kitchen professional
isn't along.
</P>
<P>
   Charmoon, along with David Campbell, one of the Bay Area's
leading experts on identifying edible mushrooms, usually scour the
mountains a week or two before their forays to make sure campers
will find enough. They arrange a group campsite and alternative
lodging for people who don't want to stay in a tent.
</P>
<P>
   The first priority on a foray is to pick enough mushrooms to
feed the camp. Large morels, which take well to smoke, might get
stuffed with sheep's milk cheese, rolled in butter and grilled.
King boletes are sliced, dipped in a winey marinade and cooked on
the grill until crisp. A main course will feature morels paired
with smoked salmon and sour cream in a sort of stroganoff.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, more mushrooms might be scrambled into eggs
over the propane stoves set up at camp.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever's left is divided among the group, allowing campers to
go home with enough bounty to cook with at home.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  The next Wild About Mushrooms camp is June 9-11 ($90). &LR;   &LR; Other
classes, food events and mushroom walks are also offered &LR; 
 &LR; throughout the year. Call (707) 887-1888 for more information, &LR; 
 &LR; or log on to  &LR; www.wildmushrooms.qpg.com &LR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  The Mycological Society of San Francisco also holds &LR; 
 &LR; mushroom-related events throughout the year. Call (415) &LR;   &LR; 759-0495
or log on to the online calendar at  &LR; www.mssf.org &LR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
COL. 2 of MORELS 5 (92669 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
