</P>
<P>
   DRUG-PRICES (Washington) _ More and more in recent years,
private insurance has been picking up the cost of prescription
medicine. Only about one-quarter of the total drug costs of
Americans are now paid out of pocket. That explains why there is no
general political uproar, even though drug prices in the United
States have been rising by as much as 15 percent a year, the
pharmaceutical manufacturers are among the most profitable
businesses in the world and many new drugs in Canada and Europe
cost a fraction of what they do here. Imagine the political swivet
Americans would be in if that were the case with gasoline or some
other staple of daily life. The elderly, of course, are up in arms.
Those who are completely dependent on Medicare, which does not
cover the cost of outpatient prescriptions, bear the brunt of the
skyrocketing prices. But most Americans never face these high drug
prices. They pay no more than $5 or $10 for each prescription. By
David E. Rosenbaum. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   MINN-WELFARE (Washington) _ Large-scale study of Minnesota
welfare reform finds extremely positive effects: higher earnings
and income, less poverty, an increase in marriage rates and marital
stability and improvements in children's behavior and school
performance _ a combination never seen before. By Robert Pear.
