million Americans, and about 30 companies have psoriasis drugs in
clinical trials. While none of the drugs are expected to cure the
disease permanently, early test results show that some could be
safer and effective for longer periods than existing drugs. But
some analysts caution that psoriasis is deceptively hard to treat
and that one company after another has failed in its treatment
efforts. Another drawback is that since psoriasis is not considered
to be a very serious disease, the Food and Drug Administration
might set tougher standards for drug approval. By Andrew Pollack.
