<SLUG> BC-POTPOURRI-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics. 
 
 Wine Potpourri: Champagne Deserves More than `Special Occasion' 
 Status  By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Champagne has always been associated with the
finer things in life, a connection that has been both a blessing
and a bane to Champagne producers. Although Champagne is celebrated
around the world, many Champagne houses have looked to the United
States as one of their major export markets.
<P>
   Given the adult population of the United States, the potential
here for huge sales is great, even though Americans consider
Champagne and other quality sparkling wines as special occasion
drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Alain de Polignac, of Champagne Pommery, would like
Americans to think of Pommery Champagne as an art. He says that
from 1858, when the young widow Louise Pommery decided to take over
her husband's business, Pommery has strived to create a luxury
product with a unique style. In 1860, Madame Pommery established a
direct marketing campaign, including the appointment of an export
manager, a position previously unknown in Champagne.
</P>
<P>
   Prince de Polignac has continued the tradition, maintaining that
the art of Pommery lies in its ``uniqueness of flavor, light and
brightness, which sparkles like the light.'' Perhaps a bit over the
top, but Prince de Polignac believes that all Champagne, and
especially Pommery, reflects ``the art of wine making and the art
of living.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Pommery produces a line of Champagnes in one of the most
visually stunning properties in Reims, Champagne. The
Elizabethan-style architectural complex, built in 1866, is
surrounded by 61 acres of vineyards and stands rests on top of an
11-mile network of chalk aging cellars, dating from the Roman
Empire. But the heart of Pommery lies in the vineyards, 741 acres
of the highest rated vineyards, planted in seven ``grand cru''
villages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything starts with Brut Royal,'' says Prince de Polignac.
``Brut Royal, a blend of one-third each Chardonnay, Pinot Noir and
Pinot Meunier, is the heart of the Pommery style'' Pommery Brut
Royal ($35) is fresh and lively with lifted fruit, a touch of
toasted nuts, and a long balanced finish.
</P>
<P>
   For more depth and complexity, there's Pommery Brut Royal
Apanage ($40), a cuvee that leans heavily on Chardonnay. The
bouquet is fresh, fruity and lively and the full-bodied flavors are
richly textured. This blend of wines from 12 crus is distinct and
bold.
</P>
<P>
   Pommery Brut Rose ($40), a delightful blend of Pinot Noir, Pinot
Meunier and Chardonnay, is a tasty wine with good structure, layers
of sweet fruit, crisp acidity and a long luscious finish.
</P>
<P>
   Moving up the scale in complexity and depth is Pommery Brut
1992, $60, with its fresh fruit flavors, creamy texture, crisp
acidity and just a touch of warm bread yeast in the finish. Vintage
Champagne often shows a little oxidation, but Prince de Polignac
says that oxidation is not the Pommery style.
</P>
<P>
   Pommery's crowning achievement is the 1990 Louise, $100, a rich
and creamy Champagne with focused fruit flavors, excellent acidity,
great finesse and charm. Louise first appeared on the market in
1986 and quickly took its place among the best of Champagnes grand
marques.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Heidsieck Mis en Cave &LR;
</P>
<P>
   An American beer company gives the consumer freshness
information by putting a ``born on'' date on every can of its beer,
and now Champagne Charles Heidsieck has adapted the same concept to
its non-vintage Champagne.
</P>
<P>
   Heidsieck's winemaker, Daniel Thibault, calls the innovative
concept, ``Mis en Cave,'' which means ``laid down in the cellar.''
The year on the bottle refers to when the Champagne began its aging
in the cellar, not the vintage year.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Charles Heidsieck Mis En Cave 1996 ($45) began its aging
in 1996. The wine aged on the yeast lees for three years and was
disgorged in 1999, a longer time on the lees than many non-vintage
Champagnes. Heidsieck also has Mis en Cave 1995 ($47) and Mis en
Cave 1993 ($50).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Learning to Love &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Winemakers trying to crack the huge market for wine in China are
either amused or horrified by what they often see there in
restaurants. Wine is not a traditional part of Chinese culture, so
the Chinese treat wine like any other beverage.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the quality or value of the wine, many Chinese mix
white wine with Coca Cola and red wine with Sprite.
</P>
<P>
   On one of my recent trips to Australia, a winemaker friend told
me about his efforts to place his wines in Beijing, Shanghai and
Canton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in Canton participating in a big wine tasting at a
hotel,'' he said. ``The night of the tasting, I walked into the
room and found the Chinese pouring my reserve Shiraz into a large
glass and filling it with Sprite. I went outside to calm down, then
realized that if that's the way we're going to get into the bloody
market, so be it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 1359EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
