<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0678 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-LEARN-TOAST-SFCHRON &LR;      05-31 0453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEARN-TOAST-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Every other week, The Chronicle features ``Learning
to Cook'' by Marion Cunningham, a cooking teacher and cookbook
author best known for her revisions of the Fannie Farmer cookbooks.
This column is intended for novices in the kitchen. &HT;     
 Learning To Cook: Make Brunch Special With James Beard's French 
 Toast  By Marion Cunningham  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Somehow my vote for the most satisfying of all
meals is the late Saturday or Sunday breakfast often called
``brunch.'' Companionable, indulgent and lazy, it turns the clock
back to when life was slower and simpler.
<P>
   In case you thought, like I did, that the word ``brunch'' was
coined in the U.S. late 1940s, it turns out that brunch was a term
in England in the 1900s.
</P>
<P>
   James Beard, one of the outstanding American cooks and cookbook
authors of the 20th century _ he wrote 28 cookbooks _ introduced me
to his favorite brunch recipe, J.B.'s French Toast. He told me that
they used to serve this in the dining cars on the Santa Fe
Railroad. The crumbled cornflakes give every bite a crisp crunch
that is mighty good.
</P>
<P>
   This will make a memorable meal with the addition of a lightly
sugared bowl of strawberries during the spring and summer. During
the winter, serve it with grapefruit halves.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; J.B.'S FRENCH TOAST
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cornflakes
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons (1/2 stick) butter
</P>
<P>
   6 slices thick white bread (1/2- to 3/4-inch thick)
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; Prepare the batter:  &LR; Crack the eggs into a bowl. Add the
milk, nutmeg and salt and stir briskly so the mixture is blended
well and all one color. Using a shallow bowl makes it easy to dip
and coat the bread slices.
</P>
<P>
   Crumble the cornflakes slightly (to make each flake about half
of its original size) and spread them in a layer on a piece of wax
paper.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 225 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Prepare the Bread:  &LR; Dip (don't soak) both sides of each slice
of bread into the batter. Press each slice of bread on both sides
into the cornflakes to coat the bread well.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Fry the French toast:  &LR; Melt 2 tablespoons of the butter in a
12-inch skillet over medium heat. Add 3 slices of the bread and fry
until golden on each side. When done, sprinkle about 1 tablespoon
of sugar on top of each slice and keep the toast warm in the oven.
</P>
<P>
   Fry the remaining 3 slices in the remaining 2 tablespoons of
butter. Serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 283 calories, &LR;   &LR; 7 g protein, 36 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 12 g fat (6 g saturated), 129 mg cholesterol, 550 mg sodium, 1 &LR;   &LR; g
fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
