<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0679 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-BESTBURGER-SFCHRON &LR;      05-31 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BESTBURGER-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: The Chronicle regularly features ``Best Way'', a
column in which the Food staff tries to establish the most reliable
way to cook many of our favorite foods. 
 
 Best Way: Preparing Hamburgers   By Andy Lax 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; As millions of people roll their dusty Webers from
garages, we decided to test the ultimate of all barbecue delicacies
_ the all-American hamburger.
<P>
   Stripped of its bun and condiments, a great burger must be able
to stand alone. After a battery of tests, we found the best method
for preparing burgers that will make your neighbors envious of the
aromas drifting over the backyard fence.
</P>
<P>
   All the tests used 1/3-pound of hamburger seasoned with 1/4
teaspoon each of salt and black pepper. All were cooked to medium.
</P>
<P>
   We tested for fat content first. We compared 73 percent lean, 80
percent lean, 90 percent lean and 93 percent lean. Both the 90
percent and 93 percent were dry. Though some liked the meaty taste
of the leaner burgers, the ones with more fat were juicier.
However, the 73 percent lean meat, though suggested by many
butchers, was too mealy for some tastes. The 80 percent lean struck
the best balance between the requisite fat and a good, meaty
texture.
</P>
<P>
   Next, we determined the best way to season hamburger patties. We
seasoned three identical patties with 1/4 teaspoon each of salt and
pepper. We mixed the seasonings into one patty, sprinkled them on
both the top and bottom of the next, and both mixed them into and
sprinkled them on the third. Surprisingly, the panel prefered the
burger with the seasonings sprinkled on it. Though some bites were
saltier than others, the surface seasonings made a nice crust when
seared in the pan.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the seasoning test went on to round three _
hamburger patty formation. The first burger was packed together
into a dense disc. The other was formed into a patty with minimal
handling. Though the tightly packed burger was more aesthetically
pleasing, the result was mealy, dense and lacked bite. The loosely
packed burger stayed firm and meaty and was the hands-down winner.
</P>
<P>
   Next, we tested cooking methods using a nonstick pan, a
cast-iron pan, a grill pan and a charcoal grill. The cast-iron pan
gave off a somewhat unpleasant metallic taste and was the least
favorite among the tasters. While the nonstick pan performed well,
it was neither a match for the grill pan nor the grill. The grill
produced a moist burger that was meaty, juicy and had a good smoke
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   However, the grill pan was the biggest surprise. This burger
also had a good smoke flavor and grill marks for visual appeal.
While there is no replacement for the grill in the hearts of most
Americans, the grill pan offers a fine alternative for those of us
driven indoors by San Francisco's chilly nights.
</P>
<P>
   Not content to let our winning burger rest on its meaty laurels,
we pitted it against the ultimate of all San Francisco hamburgers _
the Zuni Cafe burger. The secret of chef/owner Judy Rodger's
success is salting large strips of chuck overnight and then
grinding it. The only change we made to Zuni's recipe was to use a
food processor to grind the meat, pulsing it in chunks to the
desired consistency. The Zuni burger was voted superior by
unanimous decision. While it did not have the salty crust, the meat
was far juicier and of superior quality.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEST WAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Use 21/2 pounds of good quality chuck, cut the meat into long
strips. Sprinkle with 11/2 teaspoons of fine sea salt, cover and
refrigerate overnight. Using a meat grinder or a food processor,
grind meat to desired consistency. Handling the meat as little as
possible, form into patties of desired size. Using either a grill
or a grill pan over medium high heat, cook the burger to desired
doneness, about 3-4 minutes per side for a medium burger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AN APPEALING ALTERNATIVE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If grinding your own meat doesn't appeal to you, the following
method produces a fine burger. Handling the meat as little as
possible, form 80 percent lean ground beef into patties. Sprinkle
both the top and bottom with salt and pepper to taste. Using either
a grill or a grill pan on medium-high heat, cook the burger to
desired doneness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
