 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
 Taster's Choice: Two Ricotta Brands Stand Above the Rest   By Robin Davis  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Whole milk ricotta cheese is wonderful in so many
recipes like lasagne, or on its own served with fruit or crackers.
Italians have been making it for years, but now many American
cheesemakers have gotten into the act.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's panel tasted five whole milk ricotta cheeses, many made
in California. They ranged in price from $2.89 for 15 ounces to
$9.95 per pound. The panel found distinct differences between them,
with two coming out far ahead of the others.
</P>
<P>
   First place went to  &UR; Mozzarella Fresca &LR;  (15 ounces, $3.99 at
Whole Foods). Panelists described the flavor as wholesome, clean
and sweet; one thought it would work particularly well in recipes
calling for whole milk ricotta and another thought the cheese had a
pleasant nuttiness. Two panelists called the texture a bit grainy.
Four would buy it; one might.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bellwether Farms &LR;  ($9.95 per pound at Draeger's) came in
second, although three panelists picked it as their favorite. Two
tasters particularly liked the creaminess. Others noted the nutty,
clean fresh milk flavor. Four would buy it; one would not.
</P>
<P>
   Third place went to  &UR; Polly-O &LR;  (15 ounces, $2.89-$3.99 at many
supermarkets). Three panelists thought the texture was too thin and
watery, although most liked the sweet flavor. One would buy it, one
might buy it and three would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lioni Latticini &LR;  ($4.99 per pound at Rainbow Grocery) came in
fourth. Most panelists particularly liked the texture, though one
found it chalky and dry. One thought the texture resembled cream
cheese more than ricotta. Some also thought the cheese tasted too
tangy. One would buy it; four would not.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also tasted Formaggi di Ferrante, but it scored too
low to rate.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Shelley
Handler, consultant and food writer; Roland Passot, chef-owner of
La Folie in San Francisco and Left Bank in Larkspur and Menlo Park;
Kim Severson, Chronicle staff writer; and Kirk Webber, chef-owner,
Cafe Kati, San Francisco. All products are tasted blind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 1400EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
