 CHRON  
 Cook's Books: Grilling Is Really Quite Simple  &HT;       
 By David A. Steinberg 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; I'm sure I'm not the only person to have
experienced Pittsburgh-style grilled chicken _ charred on the
outside, raw on the inside. Or how about chowing down on a batch of
barbecued chicken ``chips'' that could easily be mistaken for the
tiles used as heat shields on the space shuttle.
<P>
   Maybe it's a testosterone thing, but most guys I know who
erroneously profess to be ace grillers refuse to get the help they
so obviously need. It's sort of like asking for directions. To be
fair, however, it's not just a guy thing. Some women I know are
just as territorial around the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of gender, if you like to grill outdoors or know
people who do (especially if they keep serving up hockey pucks
masquerading as burgers) then ``Pacific Grilling,'' by Denis Kelly,
is a great book to have on the shelf.
</P>
<P>
   Most of its premise revolves around using the best ingredients
and careful attention to preparing the fire, be it gas, charcoal or
wood.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes are short and, as a whole, very simple to follow. As
a result of their simplicity, the main ingredient in each recipe is
often the star flavor; Kelly eschews complex, multilayered sauces
that are often just overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   This approach is evident in the recipe for Grilled Lamb Chops
With Rosemary-Garlic Paste. Just the title alone covers half of the
ingredients; the rest are salt, pepper and olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere have I found a simpler or quicker recipe that yields
results worthy of any type of dinner party _ from homey to elegant.
The paste-rub highlights the flavors and tenderness of the lamb.
But be warned: This is no recipe for inferior meat. Any flaws in
the lamb will be more than obvious after grilling. And as with all
lamb dishes, trimming off every bit of fat is essential to success.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another recipe where the quality of the meat is paramount is
the Seared Tuna With Togarishi Pepper and Wasabi Mustard Sauce.
Once again, the recipe title says most of it. But the catch is yet
another hit to the wallet: The tuna has to be sushi-grade _ not
just because the flavor comes shining through, but because, as the
title suggests, the center is basically raw, and any lesser grade
may jeopardize your intestinal constitution, if not your health.
</P>
<P>
   But Kelly does have more than a few recipes that use sauces a
little more forcefully, such as Michael's Grilled Duck Breasts with
Berry Pinot Noir Glaze, a recipe from Michael Wild, the owner and
chef of Oakland's Bay Wolf restaurant. Not only does this recipe
use one of my favorite spices _ juniper berries _ but it also does
a wonderful job at rendering out most of the fat from the duck
breasts without overcooking the meat. The recipe could easily be
adapted to boneless chicken thighs.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, a native Californian who lives in Oakland, does a nice
job of offering both a wide range of recipes and some techniques on
the art of grilling. He also includes a short appendix listing
sources of accessories, specialty foods and ingredients _ Tokyo
Fish Market in Berkeley, for example, is an excellent resource for
sushi-quality tuna.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly has done an excellent job at reintroducing us to the
simplicities of grilling. So fire up!
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Pacific Grilling,'' by Denis Kelly (Sasquatch Books; 239 &LR; 
 &LR; pages; paperback; $18.95). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MICHAEL'S GRILLED DUCK BREASTS WITH BERRY PINOT NOIR GLAZE
</P>
<P>
   Michael Wild is the owner of Oakland's Bay Wolf restaurant.
Every year he travels up to Oregon to cook at the McMinnville Pinot
Noir Festival, where his duck and lamb dishes go beautifully with
the fragrant Pinot Noirs from the surrounding region. The trick
with grilling duck is to render the fat from the skin over a
medium-low fire. Serve this with fresh corn and green beans sauteed
in a little rendered duck fat or olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   6 boneless duck breasts
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons juniper berries, toasted and ground in a spice
grinder
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon coriander seeds, toasted and ground in a spice
grinder
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup duck or chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   1 basket raspberries or other similar berries
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup Pinot Noir or other dry red wine
</P>
<P>
   1 shallot, minced
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the fire for direct grilling. Spray or rub the grill
with oil.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle the meat side of the duck breasts lightly with juniper,
coriander, salt and pepper. Reserve any leftover spices for the
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Grill the duck breasts skin side down over medium-low heat until
the skin is browned and crisp and the fat is rendered, about 20 to
30 minutes. Move the duck to a cooler part of the grill if
flare-ups occur. Turn the duck breasts over to seal the meat side
and cook for 1 to 3 minutes more until medium-rare to medium, about
130 degrees to 135 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the duck breasts from the heat, cover loosely with
aluminum foil, and let rest for 10 to 15 minutes while you make the
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   In a small saucepan, simmer the stock, raspberries (reserve 1/4
cup for garnish), Pinot Noir, shallot and remaining spices for 10
minutes, stirring constantly. Strain the sauce through a stainless
steel sieve and reduce over high heat until it is thickened and
glossy.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the sauce over the duck breasts and garnish with the
remaining berries.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 251 calories, &LR;   &LR; 34 g protein, 5 g
carbohydrate,8 &LR;   &LR; g fat (2 g saturated), 120 mg cholesterol, 226 mg
sodium, 1 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
