<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH ROW FACTS VS. FICTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some of these death penalty opponents must have nothing to do
but fret over the fate of convicted killers and respond to
newspaper columnists who disagree with them.
</P>
<P>
   I have some advice for these folks: Get a life.
</P>
<P>
   That may take a while, so while we're waiting, I'll take a
moment to address the anti-capital punishment crowd's indignation
over civilized society's cold-hearted audacity in demanding the
ultimate punishment for the ultimate crime. If I may paraphrase
Oliver Stone's corporate raider in ``Wall Street:'' Capital
punishment is _ for lack of a better word _ good.
</P>
<P>
   But that's a piece of logic that escapes the death penalty
opponents. We're talking about a mind-set that consistently devises
mindless criticisms of capital punishment _ and of those who
support it. The latest rebuke directed at me is one of my all-time
favorites.
</P>
<P>
   In reply to my contention that innocent people are not being
executed in this country, the anti-execution folks have been
telling me that I need to check my ``facts.''
</P>
<P>
   And just exactly what facts do they offer to refute my
assertion?
</P>
<P>
   None. Zero. Not any.
</P>
<P>
   What they offer instead is the well-worn information that the
state of Illinois recently discovered that a number of its Death
Row denizens may have been innocent of the crimes for which they
were condemned to die. They offer this as evidence that innocent
people are being executed.
</P>
<P>
   I beg to differ. What the Illinois situation actually shows is
that innocent people are not being executed.
</P>
<P>
   It is unacceptable, no doubt about it, if defendants are being
wrongly convicted and sentenced to death for crimes they didn't
commit. But that doesn't mean there's a problem with the death
penalty; it means there's a problem with the process that leads to
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Defendants who are convicted of capital offenses and sent to
Death Row are afforded ample opportunity to prove that they are
innocent or that they didn't receive a fair trial or that there is
some mitigating circumstance that should spare them the just
punishment assigned them by a jury of their peers.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, the state so often derided as the capital punishment
capital of the world, a Death Row convict is awarded an appeal _
regardless of whether the inmate wants it. Condemned killers who
beg to be executed often find it difficult to get their wish
because so many do-gooders are scrambling to shield them from the
lethal needle.
</P>
<P>
   Multiple slasher/mutilator Larry Keith Robison was subjected to
one last competency hearing even after he pleaded with his
partisans to file no more appeals on his behalf. There was no
question about his guilt. He understood his fate and desperately
wanted to get on with it _ but the bleeding hearts insisted on
prolonging this brutal murderer's disgusting life.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, thank goodness, Robison got the injection he
deserved _ and justice was served.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate process in death penalty cases can drag on for 10
years, 15 years, 20 years. That should be more than enough time for
an innocent convict to prove his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   It was more than enough for those Death Row inmates in Illinois.
It was enough for confessed serial killer Henry Lee Lucas, whose
death sentence was commuted to life in prison because he may not
have committed the one murder for which he was sentenced to die.
</P>
<P>
   Facts? The fact is, there is plenty of evidence that people who
are wrongly convicted don't get executed. If the anti-capital
punishment lobby has a list of people who were executed and later
proved to be innocent, please send me the list as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   I'm talking about people who were actually innocent, you
understand, not hideous vermin like Gary Graham, who has evaded the
death chamber for darn near 20 years by means of frivolous appeals
and outrageous delays. When this animal is finally executed _ soon,
if all goes well _ some folks will offer up his fate as evidence
that innocent people are being executed.
</P>
<P>
   Ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 1427EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0702 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     05-31 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE US LINK, GLOBAL MARKETS HAVE ROOM TO GROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Nasdaq Composite index is down 15 percent for the year. The
Mexican stock market is down 16 percent, Brazil 12 percent, Great
Britain 15 percent, Spain 15 percent, Japan 17 percent, and Hong
Kong 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Raise your hand if you detect a pattern here.
</P>
<P>
   The global village has turned into the global stock market.
Practically everywhere you turn, stocks are down roughly in line
with the decline in US stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The worldwide sell-off has made life difficult for US investors
who ventured offshore in search of something better or at least
something different. More significantly, the tight link among
markets raises a question: Is international diversification dead?
</P>
<P>
   Investors have long been encouraged to keep a portion of their
money in overseas markets on the theory that those markets will
rise and fall at different times than US markets. If we just have
one big market today, does it still make sense to leave home?
</P>
<P>
   Most money managers say yes. ``We definitely feel international
diversification is still a viable strategy,'' said Steven Norwitz,
an executive with T. Rowe Price. Research at T. Rowe Price shows
that over long periods of time _ say three to five years _ American
markets and international markets move in very different patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Over shorter time frames, especially during difficult times,
however, the differences can disappear. ``You get a quick Pavlovian
reaction,'' said Allen Sinai, chief economist at Primark Decisions
Economics. ``If the US goes down, everyone goes down.''
</P>
<P>
   Market strategists say the worldwide drop in stocks this year
can be attributed to the confluence of three separate forces. The
three are:
</P>
<P>
   --Technology. When the United States fell in love with
technology stocks last year, the rest of the world was not far
behind. Internet companies, telecom companies, and software
companies had a worldwide rally and just as they did here, many
stocks soared to unsustainable heights. When the prices of American
tech stocks started to crumble, investors everywhere got nervous.
Softbank, a popular Japanese Internet stock, is down 70 percent
since February. Some money managers say that when it comes to
technology, there really is just one big stock market. ``You are
talking about an industry that is already globalized,'' said Lisa
Svensson, manager of Putnam's Global Growth fund. It remains to be
seen how tight that link will prove to be over time.
</P>
<P>
   --Currency. Most European stock markets this year are not doing
all that badly measured in local currencies. But when you factor in
the steep decline in the euro versus the dollar, the numbers look a
lot worse. If the euro rallies, as it has done for the last few
days, European markets may look better going forward.
</P>
<P>
   --Economic links. In large measure, US stocks are down because
investors anticipate a slowing in the US economy. Should that come
to pass, other countries will feel the impact. That economic link
explains why some markets, Mexico's for example, fall in sympathy
with ours. Syl Marquardt, research director of John Hancock Funds,
points out another economic tie. In many emerging markets, both in
Latin America and Asia, the governments link their currencies
tightly to the US dollar. When the United States raises interest
rates, those countries too must raise their rates and suffer the
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this year's synchronized sell-off, money managers
continue to believe overseas markets are appealing. In fact, most
expect Europe and Japan to outperform the United States over the
next few years.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Moore of State Street Research uses a baseball analogy to
explain why. The United States, he says, is in the eighth inning of
its economic expansion; Europe is in the fifth or sixth inning;
Japan only the second or third.
</P>
<P>
   In nonbaseball terms, that means both Europe and Japan have more
room to grow without bumping up against their limits or worrying
about inflation. What's more, both places are not as far along as
the United States in the deregulation of their industries or the
penetration of technology in their societies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside the US there is still a lot of good news to come,''
said Allen Sinai.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line from money managers: The world may be getting
more homogenous, but we aren't all the same just yet.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Breakaway Solutions, a Boston-based e-consulting
firm, decided to scrap its plans for a secondary stock offering
because the market for technology stocks was deteriorating.
</P>
<P>
   But Breakaway has found another way to raise money. On Tuesday,
the company announced that it sold 1.5 million shares to Putnam
Investments in a private placement. The money _ $39 million _ will
be put up by four Putnam mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a perfect world, we wouldn't be selling at this price,''
said Gordon Brooks, Breakaway's chief executive. ``But this isn't a
perfect world, and this way if the markets don't turn around, we
have a cushion.''
</P>
<P>
   Breakaway's stock closed at $22.50 Tuesday, down from a peak of
$79 in March.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks said Putnam approached him and actually wanted to buy
even more of the company. When the deal goes through, Putnam will
own 8.8 percent of Breakaway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
