<HEADER>
A0713 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-T     05-31 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGGING DEEP FOR HISTORY OF BARBACOA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is just now the end of May, and already the temperature has
gone well above 100 in many parts of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   We're looking for a hot summer.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the way we'll deal with the debilitating heat is to
leave our air-conditioned homes, go out in the back yard and start
open fires on which to cook our meat.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly that only makes it hotter, but you are allowed to
drink all the beer you want. Besides, many Texans believe that the
Lone Star State is the birthplace of barbecue and that we have an
important tradition to uphold.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Flemmons, the Fort Worth Star-Telegram writer who
considered Texas chauvinism to be a high calling, once wrote that
``Texas foods, jazz, jeans and Elvis souvenirs are the only true
American art forms, recognizable around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas food he was referring to was barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there are only three Texas foods anyway. The other two
are fried and Tex-Mex.
</P>
<P>
   Like most devout Texans, Flemmons understood the state's
emotional ties to barbecue. It is not only a cooking method, but a
challenge. Texans believe that they can barbecue anything they can
clean, but they prefer to barbecue beef.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmons was certain the word barbecue came from the Spanish
word barbacoa. Some people say it is a Spanish word, others say it
is Indian. In either case, it isn't exactly what most people
consider barbecue. Flemmons figured the old chuck-wagon cooks tried
it, mispronounced it, and therefore claimed it as their own. He
might have been right, but nevertheless, it is not uniquely Texan.
</P>
<P>
   Barbacoa is a festive kind of dish generally reserved for
special events, or at least weekends. In ``Homestyle Mexican
Cooking,'' Ida Romo writes, ``Pits are used as ovens in many parts
of the world. Mexico has the barbacoa.''
</P>
<P>
   In this variation, the large leaves of the maguey or agave plant
are used to line a pit, and a pig, calf or lamb is cooked in it.
Barbacoa is an ancient method of cooking that is still popular in
some parts of Mexico for large fiestas and family gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbacoas are held most often in the state of Mexico,'' Romo
writes, ``but also in the Yucatan, where banana leaves are used to
wrap the meat.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the United States, where the other leaves are hard to come
by, use corn husks or aluminum foil instead.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago chef (but native Oklahoman) Rick Bayless pretty much
agrees, but in his book ``Rick Bayless's Mexican Kitchen,'' he
leaves beef out altogether: ``When barbacoa is the featured fiesta
food, the party is usually in a rural setting. Traditionally,
barbacoa consists of a fresh-slaughtered pig, goat or lamb that's
marinated or not, wrapped in aromatic leaves and cooked in a
wood-fired pit in the ground _ a cross between steaming, roasting
and smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   Texans kind of liked the idea, all right, but they wanted beef.
It was just a little awkward trying to wrap a whole cow in leaves
and then dropping it in a pit. So, they just did the head.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Texas Cookbook, Culinary &AMP; Campfire Lore from the Lone
Star State,'' by Arthur and Bobbie Coleman, the instructions are
straightforward:
</P>
<P>
   ``Dig a hole three feet deep. Build a fire in it and let the
fire burn down to coals. Cover the coals with three inches of dirt.
While the fire is burning down to coals, prepare the calf's head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leave the hide on the head, and leave enough skin on the neck
to cover the cut portion. Remove the windpipe and wash the opening
thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wrap the head in a tow sack. Put the wrapped head in another
tow sack which has been thoroughly soaked with water. Place in the
hole. Cover with three inches of dirt. Build a fire on top of the
dirt, and let the head bake for 15 hours. When done, it will feed
about 6 hungry cow hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Pretty darned simple, but admit it, not what you consider
barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   To try it for yourself, here's a more contemporary version done
in an oven. You can buy a ``cabeza,'' or beef head, at local
Hispanic markets, but you might want to use eye of round or brisket
or any beef roast.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BARBACOA CABEZA
</P>
<P>
   1 cabeza, brisket or roast (See note)
</P>
<P>
   4 onions, quartered
</P>
<P>
   3 heads garlic, separated
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches cilantro, separated
</P>
<P>
   Corn or flour tortillas
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Place first four ingredients in a large baking bag; the kind
used for roasting a large turkey. Put the bag in a baking dish on
the bottom rack of a 200-degree oven. On another rack place a
heat-proof container with water. It will help keep the meat moist
during the long cooking period. Cook the beef for 5 hours,
occasionally checking the water level.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the cooking period, allow the meat to cool
slightly, then shred it with a fork. The meat should be moist, but
if not, add drippings from bag as needed.
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste and serve with tortillas.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Lamb, pork or goat can be substituted. Chicken doesn't
stand up well to the long cooking.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes on food for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Write to him at: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web Site:
www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 1440EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0714 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      05-31 1314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEWARE OF TRYING TO OUTGUESS THE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Problem: Allocating 401(k) assets; funding IRA through day
trading
</P>
<P>
   Income: $31,000 annually
</P>
<P>
   401(k) balance: $22,000
</P>
<P>
   Contributions: 6 percent of earnings, plus 3 percent match
</P>
<P>
   401(k) options:
</P>
<P>
   Putnam OTC Emerging Growth fund
</P>
<P>
   Templeton Foreign fund, Class A
</P>
<P>
   George Putnam Fund of Boston
</P>
<P>
   MFS Research fund
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard Institutional Index fund
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard Extended Market Index fund
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch Global Growth fund, Class A
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  My 401(k) is merging into a new plan with a new set of
investment choices. I want to invest aggressively for the next five
years and am planning to increase my contribution to the 401(k) to
10 percent of my earnings. I am also planning to shelter about
$2,000 a year in an IRA _ this money will come from day trading in
stocks. How do you suggest I allocate my 401(k) money?
</P>
<P>
   J.S., West Roxbury, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A &LR; . Despite your desire to take an aggressive stance, I
nonetheless suggest you begin with a core position representing
half of your current balance and half of your contributions in
Vanguard Institutional Index fund. As you may learn in day trading,
trying to outguess the market is a very risky business, and you're
best off putting the largest investment in the broad index
represented by Vanguard's Institutional Standard and Poor's 500
fund.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest you then divide the remainder of your 401(k) money and
contributions among Putnam OTC Emerging Growth, Templeton Foreign
fund, and MFS Research fund, although I would watch the latter
fairly closely. By its name you would likely infer that the fund
takes heavy positions in health care and technology stocks, but the
current portfolio presented by Morningstar Mutual Funds shows very
little concentration there. Aside from underweighting utilities,
durables, and staples and overweighting in energy stocks, the fund
does not stray far from the makeup of the Standard and Poor's 500
Index.
</P>
<P>
   I think the idea of supplementing the 401(k) with an IRA is
solid, although I think your plan of funding it through the profits
from day trading is problematical. If you use a traditional IRA,
the account is tax-deferred rather than sheltered _ you'll owe
taxes on the money when it is withdrawn later on. If you use a Roth
IRA, you are basically prepaying the taxes by funding it with
after-tax dollars. In that case, any gains you achieve in such an
account are indeed permanently sheltered from taxation.
</P>
<P>
   If you do plan to fund the IRA with profits from day trading, I
suggest you adopt one strict discipline, which is not to tap into
the IRA in the event that your day trading ventures end up where
most of them do _ in losses. If you have to tap either a
traditional or Roth IRA prematurely _ before age 59 1/2 in both
cases, and before five years have elapsed for the Roth _ you will
face penalties for early withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, I would be happier if you decided to fund your
IRA with regular contributions of $166 a month from your earnings
and keep any profits _ or losses _ that day trading might generate
in a completely separate account.
</P>
<P>
   Since there is no offering within the 401(k) that concentrates
on the field, I suggest you put your IRA money in Vanguard Health
Care fund.
</P>
<P>
   Problem: Should I cash out and invest my retirement plan?
</P>
<P>
   Retirement account: $8,500 invested in a money market account
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  I built my $8,500 balance in a tax-deferred retirement
account while working for a former employer. The plan offers no
other investment beyond the money market account, which is bringing
me $340 a year. I am thinking of cashing it in and investing the
proceeds fairly aggressively in mutual funds, where I would hope to
achieve 10 percent average annual returns. I would face a 10
percent penalty plus federal and state taxes, all totaling $2,630,
but if the returns on the remaining $5,870 are as projected, I
would soon enough catch up. What do you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   J.P., Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You would be much better off if you moved the money to a
rollover IRA, which would let you both avoid the penalties and
continue to defer the taxes. In addition, with a rollover IRA you
will have the option of adding the balance to a future qualified
retirement account, such as a 401(k) if you desire to (although
this option evaporates if you add to the account).
</P>
<P>
   The procedure for creating a rollover IRA is to go to the mutual
fund family you choose and have them receive the money directly
from your old employer's retirement plan. By that means, the money
does not enter your hands and thus the taxes and penalties are not
triggered.
</P>
<P>
   If I were making the move, I would simply move the funds to
Vanguard Index 500 fund, thus putting your reliance upon the 500
dominant American companies.
</P>
<P>
   Problem: Should new options mean investment changes?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  I am a postal employee and expect to retire in about 20
years. I am fully invested in the C fund of the Postal Services
Thrift Savings Plan, which is managed to track the Wells Fargo
Equity Index. Other current options are the G fund, invested in
short-term US Government securities and the F fund, which tracks
the Wells Fargo US Debt Index. In October there will be two new
options: the S fund, tracking a small-cap index and the I fund,
which will track an index of international stocks. Do you think I
should make any change?
</P>
<P>
   C.D., Billerica, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  Even though small-cap and international stocks are my least
favorite categories to index, I think the broader portfolio
diversity that these offerings provide merits their inclusion in
your portfolio. In both cases, I think a broadly diversified but
managed fund is likely to turn out better results than an index
fund in the long term. If these are the only way that you can get
exposure to these market segments, I would use them. My suggestion
would be to leave 60 percent of your accumulation in the C fund,
and to put 20 percent each into the new offerings, directing that
your ongoing contributions be similarly apportioned.
</P>
<P>
   Problem: Newsletter says no to Vanguard Windsor II
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  The April issue of Louis Rukeyser's Mutual Fund Newsletter
said it no longer considered Vanguard Windsor II to be an
appropriate long-term core holding. Because it is a core holding in
my portfolio, I was distressed. Do you agree with his opinion, and,
if so, what do you consider an appropriate alternative?
</P>
<P>
   W.C., San Diego &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  No, I do not agree with Rukeyser. One of the virtues of
Vanguard Windsor II is that it is a disciplined fund, seeking out
large cap stocks that fall into the value category _ with low
prices relative to their book values. The fund has been pursuing
this discipline since it was formed in 1985, and pursuing it
through markets that have been both good and bad for value-oriented
stocks. This can be seen in its portfolio price-to-earnings ratio
of 22.5, in its price-to-book ratio of 4.0, and in its 2.96 percent
yield. It also can be seen in its year-to-date total return of 2.96
percent, hardly a number to get excited about but comforting at a
time when most stock mutual funds are in the red for 2000. And its
discipline to stick by its mission can be seen in its low turnover
ratio of 26.
</P>
<P>
   If I were you, I would stay with Windsor II. But if you have
become disillusioned with value investments in general, I would go
no further than moving to Vanguard Index 500, which holds a
portfolio that represents a blend of both growth and value stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box
2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378. His column, The Adviser, also appears
on Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
