<SLUG> BC-SOC-LILLY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LILLY IS A LEADING LIGHT AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILTON, Conn. _ Those who favor the phrase, ``You can't go home
again,'' have to bite their tongues around Kristine Lilly. The
``Welcome to Wilton'' sign boasts that it's the former US women's
national soccer team member's hometown. The high school soccer
field is named in her honor. The locals welcomed her with parades
after the team won the Olympic gold medal in 1996 and the World Cup
last year.
</P>
<P>
   She made the townfolks especially proud in the World Cup final
when she stopped a shot by China after goalie Briana Scurry was
beaten on the play. Now, Lilly has them beaming with pride again,
as she is set to further etch her name into American soccer
history.
</P>
<P>
   Lilly is one of several former national team members who will
play in the newly formed (and much-anticipated) women's soccer
league _ the Women's United Soccer Association. She will be the
marquee player for the Boston franchise, one of eight WUSA teams
that will begin play next April.
</P>
<P>
   Scurry, a former standout at the University of Massachusetts,
also will play in the league, as will Brandi Chastain, Mia Hamm,
Michelle Akers and Julie Foudy. Other WUSA teams will be fielded in
Washington, New York, Atlanta, Orlando, Philadelphia, the San
Francisco Bay Area, and San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am delighted for the USA world champions and all the elite
players in America,'' said former national team coach Tony DiCicco,
who will serve as the league's acting commissioner. ``They finally
have a league of their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Lilly said the inception of a women's professional league means
girls like those who play on the soccer field named after her won't
see their careers end at the amateur level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the greatest thing that has happened to soccer because
basically the national team was all we had to play for,'' said
Lilly via a telephone interview from New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to take anything away from the national team,'' Lilly
added, ``but players who didn't make the national team had nothing
else to play in. I always wanted to play for the national team, but
I love to play professionally. I'm excited about being in Boston, I
think it's going to be great.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, WUSA was formed by major US media companies and
individual investors. The group was organized by John S. Hendricks,
chairman and CEO of Discovery Communications Inc., the parent
company of the Discovery Channel and The Learning Channel, who will
also oversee the WUSA.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday, Major League Soccer Commissioner Don Garber and
Hendricks announced that the two leagues have agreed to work
together to maximize growth and visibility. Until recently, MLS had
sought to organize the women's league itself.
</P>
<P>
   The formation of the league culminates a dramatic upsurge of
interest in women's sports in general and women's soccer in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer now is following the lead of women's basketball which
boomed when the US team captured the gold medal in 1996. That led
to the formation of two women's basketball leagues, the now-defunct
American Basketball League and the Women's National Basketball
Association, which kicked off its fourth season this week.
</P>
<P>
   As with women's basketball, talk of a women's soccer league went
on throughout the 1990s. Now that the league is coming to fruition,
players like Lilly aren't bemoaning how long it took.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started at the lowest point, with just a hundred fans a
game,'' said Lilly. ``And then everything escalated. First, the
World Cup was a turning point at the national level, and I knew
(the league) would never happen in 1996. It was not the right time.
But when people like John Hendricks got involved, everyone saw how
passionate people are about women's soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the league has been formed, folks are anticipating
former teammates battling against each other, players like Hamm and
Chastain attempting to fire shots past Scurry. Lilly, who said the
group has been together for eight years, is looking forward to the
next step as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the US soccer team is unique in that there is no other
sport at the national level where the players have been together so
long,'' she said. ``We have all been a part of the whole movement
of women's soccer, and it's been great to be a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Klem ``Whitey'' Budreckas, Lilly's former soccer coach at Wilton
High School, said the league will only get better because the
talent level of teenage players nationwide is greater than when
Lilly was in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I coach 17-year-olds right now,'' he said, ``and when you look
at those girls play, it's amazing how far they've come. Nothing
against Kristine and when she played, but right now the girls are a
lot closer talentwise. It's amazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always said it (a major league) would be great to have, but
in the back of our minds, no one dreamed of a professional league.
The women's national team brought forth recognition in the World
Cup and the Olympics. It's great for soccer and for young kids to
follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Budreckas said his only regret is that the WUSA didn't field the
New England team in Connecticut, which he said is now one of the
primary hotbeds for women's amateur soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame we didn't get one. I remember when you used to
talk about the talent in girls soccer, people talked about Maryland
and Virginia. Now, Connecticut is right there on top,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
