<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN'T TELL 'EM APART WITHOUT A SCORECARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A recent evening found me hobnobbing at the Canadian Women's
Club, whose members are not necessarily women, nor exclusively
Canadian. That is where I met John Cusack.
</P>
<P>
   This was the same John Cusack who alerted me to the existence of
the Minnie Driver shrine in Cambridge (May 12 column), but not the
downbeat dreamboat John Cusack, who has starred in 44 movies. Like
me, my John Cusack is a huge fan of his Chicago-born namesake. And
he's a fount of Cusack-iana, not only concerning former flame
Driver, but also on family lore.
</P>
<P>
   I had incorrectly assumed that John was related to the veteran
Irish actor Cyril Cusack, and was the brother of acting sisters
Sinead, Sorcha, Niamh, and Catherine. In fact, John is the brother
of acting sisters Joan, Ann, and Susie. Joan and Susie, along with
their father Dick, have roles in the wonderful recent release
``High Fidelity,'' a hilarious and poignant full-employment plan
for the Cusack family.
</P>
<P>
   My John then made a startling assertion about movie star John,
intended as a compliment: ``He's never been bad in a bad movie.''
It's true that Cusack somehow survived ``Pushing Tin,'' but ``Con
Air''? ``Chicago Cab''?
</P>
<P>
   Enough about them. It is time once again to chide parents for
failing to differentiate their children one from another. This is
hardly a recent problem. You will recall in Shakespeare's ``Julius
Caesar,'' the mob chases Cinna, shouting ``tear him to pieces; he's
a conspirator!'' But when the man proves to be Cinna the poet, not
Cinna the politican who has plotted against Caesar, the crowd
cries, ``Tear him for his bad verses!''
</P>
<P>
   A faithful reader has been logging William McDermotts for me and
filed this report: ``The number one Big Mac in my estimation is my
pal Bill McDermott of ML Strategies, a Dukakis-era Economic Affairs
functionary. Because lawyer Bill is from Dorchester originally, he
is often confused by the unwitting with William McDermott of Savin
Hill, one of the handful of Massachusetts lawyers expert at
election law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both are unlikely to encounter in court the William McDermott
who is a well-known Brookline police officer, who is often quoted
when there is trouble with protests at Brookline abortion clinics.
I don't believe Officer McDermott is a member of the Harvard Club,
which is presently presided over by another William McDermott, this
fellow easily distinguished from the rest because he commonly and
wisely employs his Shavian middle name (Shaw). And then there is
the good Dr. William McDermott, yet another denizen of the Harvard
Club, former president of the Mass. Medical Society, now known also
for his World War II exploits following a recent Globe article.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just when I thought I had exhausted my supply of William
McDermotts, a nice-looking truck drove by the other day, the side
panel emblazoned with the legend _ William McDermott, Painter.
Quality Work. Reasonable Rates.''
</P>
<P>
   If you need a program to keep track of the McDermotts, how about
the three Jayson/Jason Williams playing basketball? Or the
father-son Don Nelsons coaching the Dallas Mavericks? (The boy
spells his first name Donn.) You probably remember when the
Baltimore Orioles tried out two pitchers for spring training named
Michael Anthony Smith. Happily for scorekeepers, only one made the
team. But the inevitable happened almost a year ago today: the
Colorado Rockies' lefthander Bobby Jones went up against the New
York Mets' Bobby Jones. The Gotham hurler surrendered 10 hits and
lost 8-5.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, we have the two Michael Goldsteins who are both
Kennedy School graduates and school reform entrepreneurs. And there
are the two Barbara Lees, who were sisters-in-law, and both donate
pots of money to worthy causes. Not long ago, I received an e-mail
from Tim O'Brien, and sycophantically inquired if he was the Tim
O'Brien _ the talented novelist who always poses in a Red Sox cap
to hide his bald pate. The answer came back . . . yes and no. ``No,
I'm just a Tim O'Brien, not the famous author nor the reporter for
ABC News, nor the (former) reporter for the New York Times.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Tim, you're my reader _ you will always be the Tim O'Brien
to me.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
