<HEADER>
A0720 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-31 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CAREER LESSONS FROM `SPORTS NIGHT' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Business consultant and author Tom Peters writes
in the May 22 issue of Time magazine that he believes ``90 percent
of white-collar jobs in the United States will be either destroyed
or altered beyond recognition in the next 10 to 15 years.''
</P>
<P>
   He cites a variety of factors to back up what he calls his
``apparently bizarre'' prediction, but his article begs the
question: Where are those 10 percent of jobs that won't change? My
guess is they're with companies that will react so slowly that they
seem to be oblivious to this monumental change in the world
economy.
</P>
<P>
   So your career has two potential paths: the job headed for
oblivion or the company whose heads are oblivious. It's not a
pretty choice.
</P>
<P>
   The season finale of ``Sports Night'' this month on ABC included
some great workplace irony. As the fictional cable sports channel
on the show is about to be sold, the executive producer meets a man
in a bar who tells her how he became wildly successful, even though
he failed far more than he succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each time I fail,'' he tells her, ``I get my people together
and say, `Where are we going?' and it starts to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   She scoffs at his simplistic advice, until she finds out that
he's the man buying the cable channel _ and that he plans to keep
the fictional ``Sports Night'' on the air. After all, he says,
``Anybody who can't make money off `Sports Night' should get out of
the money-making business.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC, however, apparently can't make money off the real ``Sports
Night.'' Even though the show was a critical success, the network
canceled it.
</P>
<P>
   It's ironic, too, that although ABC can kill off that fictional
cable channel, cable television channels have been slowly killing
network TV for years. And as the Internet keeps getting faster,
network TV edges closer to oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Peters' forecast is not as outrageous as it might
appear. Network television hasn't changed all that much in 15 years
_ except, of course for The Philbin Factor _ but its jobs have been
altered dramatically because there is so much more competition.
Just as the network bosses are not exactly loyal to quality shows,
workers and viewers are not exactly loyal to the networks.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I also realize it's ironic to write about this in a
newspaper, the product of another dying industry. (I also realize
I'm using the word ``ironic'' way, way, way too much, and promise
not to do it again until they bring ``Sports Night'' back.) It's an
industry that clings to the status quo, and although there are some
great newspapers, none has a reputation as a great employer.
</P>
<P>
   So are there no great employers because it's a dying industry _
or is it a dying industry because there are no great employers? I
don't know, but I think we'd all be better off working for the guy
on ``Sports Night.''
</P>
<P>
   Where are we going? Just because your company is oblivious
doesn't mean you should be.
</P>
<P>
   In one way or another, we're all in dying industries. Innovative
grocers and microwave ovens can wipe out restaurants, just as
Amazon.com and Barnes &AMP; Noble can eliminate local bookstores. But
good restaurants and independent bookstores manage to stay in the
money-making business.
</P>
<P>
   Even though technology in general is thriving, companies fail
all the time. And just as many blue-collar workers lost their jobs
to foreign competition, techies could well see more jobs outsourced
to places like China and India.
</P>
<P>
   So, assuming Peters is right, how do you protect yourself? Find
smart people and hook up with them, as a partner or as a boss or as
a follower. Think about whether your company's vision for the
future looks out far enough to suit your future. A status quo
company might be just what you want at 55, but not at 25.
</P>
<P>
   Is your company a good employer? This isn't just a warm and
fuzzy question, but a practical one. As baby boomers reach
retirement age, the competition for talent will intensify. There
are exceptions, of course, but companies with a reputation as good
employers also tend to do well financially. That is not a
coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   Are you failing enough? Certainly you want to build up a pattern
of success, but often you learn more from your failures. If all you
have are successes, maybe you're not pushing yourself hard enough
to try new things.
</P>
<P>
   Have you tried moonlighting in another career or thought about
starting your own business? Do you push for challenging
assignments? Can you honestly say that you work with people who are
smarter than you? If you had to take a temporary step down to move
to a competitor with a more promising future, would you do it?
</P>
<P>
   Have you ever thought that your career is demanding such long
hours that you're cheating yourself out of a life? Sometimes the
best career ideas come out of your leisure time.
</P>
<P>
   Careers used to follow logical paths, and industries took
decades to evolve. Now everything operates on microwave time, and
you can get burned before you know it.
</P>
<P>
   Having a comfortable job used to be the American workplace
dream, but now that comfort is deceiving. Those who don't take
risks may be more likely to get microwaved than those who do.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't really matter which came first: the chicken employee
or the employer who laid an egg. All that matters is that
everyone's future will be scrambled.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
