   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JACKSON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Since two can play pie-in-the-sky,
taxpayers should not be shy about what they get for their $275
million that the Red Sox want for a new $627 million Fenway Park.
By Derrick Jackson. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) -- Of all the women in the Bible, few
have a poorer image than Eve. But a careful reading of Scripture in
the original Hebrew _ not in an English translation _ clearly
debunks these views, a professor says. By Michael Paulson. By
Michael Paulson. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   NOLAN-COLUMN (San Francisco) -- A word is passing out of the
American language. ``Gentrification'' once described a lifestyle
and complaints about it. Its linguistic replacement is ``housing
crisis.'' By Martin F. Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: David Nyhan is writing on a local topic today.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLE (l) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BEAM-COLUMN (Undated) -- It is time once again to chide parents
for failing to differentiate their children one from another. By
Alex Beam. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-CLERKS (Undated) -- Jerks and smirks not enough
</P>
<P>
   to float the animated series ``Clerks.'' By Matthew Gilbert. 400
words.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-WOIWODE (Undated) _ ``What I Think I Did,'' by Larry
Woiwode, is a book about the development of a writer before a
career takes off. It is also necessarily a book about the
development of a person. By Richard Dyer. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINE-REVIEW (Undated) _ To mark the 150th anniversary of
Harper's, Lewis Lapham &AMP; Co. have thrown a high-minded party in
print that reminds us how indispensable the magazine is. By Don
Aucoin. 900 words.
</P>
