<HEADER>
A0728 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CANCERDRUG-LAWSUIT-BO     05-31 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCERDRUG-LAWSUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ILLINOIS LAB ACCUSES CANCER EXPERT OF PATENT FRAUD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAJA MISHRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ An Illinois pharmaceutical company has sued Children's
Hospital and its star cancer researcher, claiming that Dr. Judah
Folkman and his team of doctors falsely took credit for a medical
breakthrough that could lead to the development of drugs that
starve malignant tumors to death.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed Tuesday in US District Court in Boston, does not
affect any of the high-profile clinical trials of tumor-starving
drugs, called angiogenesis inhibitors, underway at various
hospitals around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit highlights the intense competition and complexity
surrounding the recently accelerated race to find a cure for cancer
and other diseases, where a patent on a single molecule can be
worth billions of dollars in royalties.
</P>
<P>
   In the 21-page complaint, Abbott Laboratories says Folkman
``fraudulently'' told US patent reviewers that he discovered the
tumor-inhibiting properties of a small section of an angiostatin
protein known by scientists as Kringle 5. Abbott scientist Donald
Davidson made the actual breakthrough and Abbott is the rightful
owner of the patent, the complaint states. In 1995, Folkman and his
team took Davidson's research and, in violation of a
confidentiality agreement, sought to profit from it without
Abbott's knowledge, Abbott maintains.
</P>
<P>
   Folkman responded: ``This dispute comes down to Children's
Hospital wanting to protect its patent rights and Abbott wanting to
avoid paying any royalties. I have no personal interest in this
matter and hope that Kringle 5 continues to test well and
progresses from the laboratory to further stages of development so
that it can eventually benefit patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Abbott is asking the court to transfer the credit and patent for
the discovery to it. The company also wants assessment of $10
million in punitive damages and compensation for any other losses
incurred because of the alleged fraud. Abbott also wants the
licensing rights for any drug that results from the discovery, a
right that now belongs to EntreMed Inc., a Rockville, Md., company
that has exclusive rights to 24 patents based on the work of
Folkman and his colleagues at Children's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides have been trying to settle the case for three
years, and were in negotiations as recently as Friday. Children's
Hospital requested that a third-party arbitrator be allowed to step
in, but Abbott resisted, according to a source familiar with the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Abbott said: ``Abbott has thoroughly
investigated this issue and has attempted to reach a settlement
with the defendants. Unfortunately, the parties could not reach a
resolution. We intend to vigorously pursue this case.''
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for EntreMed said the suit is a routine patent
dispute that will nonetheless receive much attention because of
Folkman's high profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question here is: Who was the first inventor? These are
not uncommon types of lawsuits,'' said Atlanta-based patent
specialist James D. Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   EntreMed and Children's Hospital are expected to file their
responses within 20 days.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy is an outgrowth of Folkman's watershed 1971
insight that cancerous tumors might be vulnerable if their ability
to siphon blood from arteries were somehow crippled. Tumors release
substances that ``grow'' new blood vessels to the tumor from
existing blood vessels _ a process called angiogenesis. This allows
them to thrive and spread.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Folkman and his colleagues filed a patent application
claiming that a protein named angiostatin prevents angiogenesis.
Angiostatin is part of a larger protein called plasminogen, which
helps blood clot. Plasminogen, at that time, was known to contain
five regions, consisting of danish-shaped structures dubbed
Kringles. Folkman found that Kringles 1 through 4 stopped
angiogenesis. Whether Kringle 5 had similar properties was unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson, a Notre Dame-educated specialist on plasminogen and
Kringles, began researching tumors for Abbott in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   According to court documents, shortly after Folkman's patent of
angiostatin, one of his colleagues, Dr. Yihai Cao, called Davidson.
He requested help in Kringle research. He also wanted hard-to-get
plasminogen to conduct tests with. He called the right man:
Davidson was skilled at the difficult process of separating Kringle
sections, and his employer had one of the few stockpiles of
plasminogen in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson and Abbott agreed to help, according to the documents.
In 1995, Abbott got Folkman to sign a confidentiality agreement
because some of the research Davidson was sharing had the potential
to benefit Abbott.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Davidson had a breakthrough of his own,
according to the court documents: He was able to create a new form
of Kringle 5 that showed greater tumor-starving potential than any
of the other Kringle sections. An excited Davidson told Folkman,
whose lab was able to confirm the discovery.
</P>
<P>
   According to court documents, Folkman congratulated Davidson's
supervisor and advised him that Abbott should file for a patent. In
personal notes from Dec. 1, 1995, Folkman even chided himself for
having ``overlooked'' Kringle 5, according to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   But 12 days later an attorney for EntreMed, which works with
Folkman, filed a patent application for Kringle 5. It was approved.
Abbott was never told, according to the lawsuit, and instead ``the
defendants kept their scheme to patent Abbott's Kringle 5 invention
secret from Abbott.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kringle 5 discovery has no part in the much-watched test of
angiostatin that began in April at the Thomas Jefferson University
Hospital in Philadelphia. That drug involves only Kringles 1
through 3. The test, which is expected to conclude this summer, is
simply to see if the drug is safe to take before more extensive
patient tests can be conducted. Another, more promising, drug
derived from Folkman's work, endostatin, has already entered the
more extensive testing phase.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the Kringle 5 discovery is not being tested in
drugs currently does not mean it is valueless, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because we don't have that in our drug candidate doesn't
mean we won't be able to use it down the line,'' said EntreMed
attorney Johnson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
