<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIJI-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PACIFIC, ANOTHER ETHNIC CONFLICT WITH ROOTS IN IMPERIAL AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nationalistic racism can rear its head anywhere, as conflicts
from Europe to Africa to Asia have demonstrated time and again in
recent years. And the struggles are not limited to white-on-black
violence, as upheavals from the Balkans to the Middle East to the
current convulsions in the Fiji Islands illustrate.
</P>
<P>
   What is generally consistent about these episodes, as seen
clearly in Fiji, is that the trouble has roots in the Age of
Imperialism and that outbreaks occur when a group seems to be
gaining economic and political power at the expense of another
group that has been on the disputed turf for a longer period.
</P>
<P>
   That is precisely what is happening in the Republic of the Fiji
Islands, a southwest Pacific archipelago.
</P>
<P>
   To the extent that the country of 813,000 people, mostly
subsistence hunters and fishers, is known to the outside world at
all, it is as a scuba diver's paradise. But Fiji has been
struggling with simmering racial resentments since its emergence
from British colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
   Indigenous Fijians are descendants of Melanesians from southeast
Asia and Polynesians who migrated through Indonesia. For millennia,
these groups blended in the Fiji archipelago and evolved
distinctive customs, language, and religion.
</P>
<P>
   What the Fijians did not develop was a united country. Spread
across more than 300 islands, about 100 of which are inhabited,
they were ruled by local chiefs who continued to fight with one
another as first Dutch, then British, explorers came into view.
</P>
<P>
   In 1871, one powerful chief, Cakobau, was able to subdue the
clan warfare; in 1874, he asked the British to make Fiji a crown
colony as a strategy to avoid outside interference. This appeared
to work, as the British ruled through local chiefs and brought in
indentured servants from India to do grunt work on the sugarcane
plantations they established.
</P>
<P>
   Fiji remained a colony until, at its own request, it was granted
independence within the Commonwealth in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fiji's birthday present from the United Kingdom was an
enduring problem that the country is still trying to come to terms
with,'' said Michael Brown, a professor of international politics
at Georgetown University who specializes in the study of ethnic
conflict. ``The British completely changed the demographics in a
permanent way.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time of independence, there were, by many accounts, more
Fijians of Indian descent than of Melanesian heritage. Most of the
real estate was in the hands of the indigenous residents, but
modern business was the realm of ethnic Indians.
</P>
<P>
   A backlash against the Indians set in, similar to the Sinhalese
reaction against Tamils in Sri Lanka. It erupted in violence in
1987, when an election led to the first government in the young
country's history in which a majority of ministers were of Indian,
rather than Melanesian, descent.
</P>
<P>
   First a coup, then racial violence, occurred. Politicians forged
a compromise, but before they could put it in force, indigenous
nationalists staged a second coup. Fiji was ejected from the
Commonwealth, and the country was ostracized internationally until
civil government was restored. That was accomplished under a set of
arrangements that attempted to guarantee Indian Fijians their
rights while preserving a special sensitivity to the indigenous
Fijians.
</P>
<P>
   ``What that meant was never clear,'' said Robert Rotbert of
Harvard's Kennedy School of Government. While the nation settled a
bit after 1989-90, the underlying problem was not resolved.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, racial tensions rose as political leaders struggled
over a new constitution, but last year, after Fiji's first vote in
which seats in parliament were determined without regard to
ethnicity, there was hope that a corner had been turned.
</P>
<P>
   ``People hope that (Mahendra) Chaudhry's election (as prime
minister) meant indigenous Fijians had come to terms with the
ethnic realities,'' Brown said, ``and accepted power sharing.''
</P>
<P>
   Those hopes have died in recent weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
