<HEADLINE>
REVISITING TREATMENT OF WOMEN IN THE BIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the women in the Bible, few have a poorer image than Eve,
the first woman mentioned in the Old Testament. Through the
centuries, popular culture, whether literature or art, has depicted
the Eve of Genesis as a sinner who seduces Adam and precipitates
the fall of man.
</P>
<P>
   But a careful reading of Scripture in the original Hebrew _ not
in an English translation _ clearly debunks these views, according
to Carol Meyers, a professor of archeology and biblical studies at
Duke University.
</P>
<P>
   And Eve, Meyers asserts, is not the only woman in the Bible who
has not received fair treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Meyers is part of a growing body of scholars whose intense study
of the Bible is yielding new information about female figures in
Scripture, challenging conceptions _ and, in some cases,
misconceptions _ about women that have been used to justify biases.
</P>
<P>
   Now Meyers has brought together the work of about 80 scholars to
produce an unprecedented reference book, ``Women in Scripture.''
</P>
<P>
   Divided into three sections, the volume provides entries on more
than 200 named women in the Bible, more than 600 entries on unnamed
women, and 49 articles about nonhuman females, including feminine
deities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a lot of distortion and misunderstanding
about biblical figures, both men and women, as a result of 2,000
years of biblical interpretation,'' said Meyers, who served as
general editor of the reference book.
</P>
<P>
   ``This interpretation, when it comes to women, has almost always
been done by men,'' she said. ``I'm not sure it's meant to be evil,
but there are biases and I'm hopeful the book will serve to correct
some biases and misconceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyers and the rest of the book's contributors are quick to
point out that they did not set out to produce a polemical volume,
but rather a work based on thorough academic research.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, Meyers said the book is meant to be
accessible to general interest readers and not simply to scholars.
And, indeed, a perusal of the book offers articles easy to
understand even if you don't have a background in biblical
scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want this to be a coffee-table book,'' Meyers said.
``We want people to use it, whether it be pastors preparing Sunday
sermons, women in Bible study groups, or students in a college
course _ anyone who is interested in finding out about women in the
Bible and what scholars think about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyers, who has written extensively on Eve, contributed a piece
on Eve that attempts to refute popular interpretations of the first
woman of the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   While Eve is commonly associated with sin, Meyers points out
that she is not called a sinner and that, in fact, the word sin
does not appear in the Old Testament until the story of Cain and
Abel.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Eve does not seduce Adam with an apple. The fruit is not
an apple and Eve simply gives it to Adam, Meyers notes. And,
contrary to popular belief, God does not curse Eve; God curses the
serpent and the ground underneath it. Finally, the Eden story is
often described as the fall of man, but this is a Christian
application of views put forth by Plato.
</P>
<P>
   And, Meyers writes, ``The Hebrew word `adam' can indeed mean a
male and even be the proper name Adam; but it can also be a generic
term for a mortal or a human being.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
