UNDATED: cool completely. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Place chicken in shallow non-aluminum container; cover with
marinade and turn thighs to coat. Cover and refrigerate overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Piri-piri butter:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons finely minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon plus 2 teaspoons dried red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Heat butter with garlic in small saucepan over low heat until
melted. Heat olive oil until very hot (use preceding instructions)
in small saucepan over medium heat. Remove from heat and add red
pepper flakes and cool for 10 minutes. Add garlic butter, then
lemon juice and salt.
</P>
<P>
   Let chicken come to room temperature. Heat grill or broiler.
Remove chicken from marinade and sprinkle lightly with salt. Grill
or broil for 5 to 6 minutes, basting once or twice with piri-piri
butter. Turn and cook until juices run clear when thigh is pierced
with skewer and skin is golden and slightly crisp, about 5 minutes
more.
</P>
<P>
   Serve chicken with remaining butter in ramekins and accompany
with fried potatoes and sliced tomatoes sprinkled with a little
chopped mint or cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 790 calories, 65 grams fat, 5
grams carbohydrates, 46 grams protein, 212 milligrams cholesterol,
748 milligrams sodium, 74 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Mediterranean Kitchen'' by Joyce Goldstein (Morrow, $16)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BAKED APPLE AND ALMOND CRISP A LA MODE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons light olive oil, divided
</P>
<P>
   4 medium tart baking apples, peeled, cored and cut into thin
slices
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup packed brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon ground allspice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sliced almonds
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla ice cream
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 350 degrees. Lightly brush 2-quart baking dish with
oil. Arrange apples in rows in baking dish.
</P>
<P>
   In another bowl, combine brown sugar, flour and allspice. Add
olive oil and almonds. Stir until blended. Sprinkle mixture evenly
over the apples. Bake 30 minutes or until apples are tender and
crust is golden brown.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving with 1/2 cup ice cream: 348
calories, 17 grams fat, 47 grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 30
milligrams cholesterol, 65 milligrams sodium, 45 percent of
calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Carapelli
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   HOW MANY BOTTLES OF OIL ON THE WALL? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paula Wolfert, author of ``The Cooking of the Eastern
Mediterranean,'' among other titles, says cooks should use olive
oil from the country of the cuisine they are cooking. Making
moussaka? Use Greek olive oil. Making paella? Use Spanish olive
oil.
</P>
<P>
   Faith Willinger, author of ``Red, White &AMP; Greens: The Italian
Way With Vegetables,'' says American cooks have it all wrong. She
uses extra-virgin olive oil in all her cooking. To do otherwise,
she says, is akin to frying a fish in margarine and then laying a
pat of butter on top.
</P>
<P>
   The home cook should have a couple kinds of olive oils in the
pantry but, culinary divas aside, a battalion of different bottles
is not necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Have a good bottle of extra-virgin on hand for drizzling on
summer ripe tomatoes or for jazzing up pieces of toast and calling
them bruscetta. A pleasing-to-your-palate, medium-priced olive oil
is fine for everyday cooking. And if you'd like to adjust your
baking to use olive oil as a replacement for more conventional
fats, buy a light olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, don't buy more oil than you'll use in a reasonable
length of time. Those huge tins of oil look great, but if you don't
use much oil, it can turn rancid before you see the bottom of the
tin.
</P>
<P>
   Store olive oil out of sunlight and away from the stove or any
other heat for the longest shelf life. Refrigerating olive oil will
dull the flavor. However, if you've made a marinade or dip and want
to save it before serving, refrigerate and then let it come to room
temperature before serving.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   WHAT PRICE FLAVOR? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A classic Turkish dish is Imam Bayildi, or ``the imam fainted.''
</P>
<P>
   One story goes that the eggplant/tomato/onion dish got its name
because it was a favorite of a Muslim cleric. When he found out how
much olive oil was used in the recipe, he swooned from the excess
of the expense.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BETCHA DIDN'T KNOW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Olive trees have been around since 3000 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   Each tree lives between 300 and 600 years. When an olive tree
dies, new shoots emerge around the base and grow into a new tree.
</P>
<P>
   The average tree yields 40 pounds of olives a year. It takes 10
pounds of olives to make 1 liter of olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MARINATE YOURSELF
</P>
<P>
   After you get finished putting olive oil on your salad at the
picnic, rub some on your skin. Virgin olive oil, applied to the
skin after sunbathing, could protect against skin cancer, ``New
Scientist'' magazine reports. According to researchers at Kobe
University School of Medicine in Japan, a study concluded that the
oil slowed tumor growth in mice used in cancer experiments.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
