<HEADLINE>
FEEL A PRESSING NEED FOR A SPECIAL OIL? CHANCES ARE THAT YOU CAN
FIND IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY and RENIE STEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time was when the adventuresome cook took off to the
supermarket, ``Mastering the Art of French Cooking'' in hand, and
scoured the shelves looking for olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Except in cities with a sizable Italian or Greek population, the
cook of yesteryear most likely had one lone brand to choose from.
The conical bottle of Pompeiian Olive Oil was the one that went
home to become an ingredient in the Julia Child production of the
week.
</P>
<P>
   But now, thanks to world travel and new nutritional information,
the most ancient of oils is hot again.
</P>
<P>
   Americans now know that there's more to Italian food than pizza.
There's pesto and bagna cauda, the obnoxiously named ``Italian
butter'' at Macaroni Grill. And we also now know that there's a
world of food to the east of Italy:
</P>
<P>
   Greek salad and Lebanese tabbouleh and Turkish meze spreads.
</P>
<P>
   And just as we were tucking into these food finds in the
culinary explosion of the 1980s, the American Heart Association
announced that olive oil was _ welcome news for once _ good for us.
A monounsaturated oil, olive oil beat out the grain- and seed-based
oils Americans had been downing for 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   In good American free-enterprise tradition, the grocery shelves
got loaded with different brands and variations of olive oil. We
got virgin olive oil, we got extra-virgin olive oil, cold-pressed
olive oil, flavored olive oil and lite olive oil. We got olive oil
spray. And organic olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   And now, it appears we're about to get even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The olive oil industry in California is where the California
wine industry was 20 years ago,'' says Bruce Beauchamp, owner of
Capay Olives in Orland, Calif. Olive growers, Beauchamp says, are
turning to making ``boutique'' oils that sell for a premium.
Beauchamp himself is working with making kalamata olive oil, saying
the flavor is ``like kissing God.''
</P>
<P>
   And this summer, American consumers will experience another oil
onslaught from Italy. Carapelli, that country's leading
extra-virgin olive oil producer, is bringing four varieties of oil
to a supermarket near you. Looks like it's time to make more room
on the shelf.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   TUSCAN SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried Italian seasoning
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 head romaine lettuce, cut into 1/2-inch strips
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sliced cucumbers
</P>
<P>
   1 cup crumbled feta cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup pitted kalamata olives
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup roasted sweet peppers, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup thinly sliced red onion
</P>
<P>
   In medium bowl, whisk together olive oil, vinegar, garlic,
Italian seasoning, salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   In large bowl, combine remaining ingredients. Add dressing and
toss well.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 277 calories, 28 grams fat, 5
grams carbohydrates, 3 grams protein, 17 milligrams cholesterol,
438 milligrams sodium, 91 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Carapelli Olive Oil
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BAKED RICE-STUFFED EGGPLANT
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   2 small Italian eggplants, about 8 ounces each
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped ham
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon pine nuts
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cooked white rice
</P>
<P>
   1 plum tomato, halved, seeded and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely chopped flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Cut eggplants in half lengthwise.
Score cut side at 1/2-inch intervals, brush lightly with 1 teaspoon
of the olive oil and place cut side down on baking sheet. Bake
until browned and eggplant is tender when pierced with skewer,
about 15 minutes. Reduce oven temperature to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, combine onion and remaining olive oil in large
skillet. Cook, stirring until onion is tender, about 5 minutes.
Stir in rice, tomato, ham, pine nuts, parsley and salt and pepper
until blended. Remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   Using a spoon, carefully remove eggplant flesh, leaving a
1/2-inch-thick shell intact. Chop flesh and add to rice mixture.
Pack rice mixture into the scooped-out eggplant shells. Sprinkle
with Parmesan. Arrange on baking sheet, cover lightly with foil and
bake 20 minutes. Uncover and bake until tops are browned, about 10
minutes more.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 143 calories, 4 grams fat, 2
milligrams cholesterol, 4 grams protein, 24 grams carbohydrates, 43
milligrams sodium, 25 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bertolli
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   GRILLED CHICKEN WITH PIRI-PIRI HOT SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   Marinade:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dried red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   4 large garlic cloves, crushed
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 pounds chicken thighs
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in small saucepan over medium heat until very hot but
not boiling. Drop in 1 red pepper flake; if it skips to the surface
of the oil and bubbles, the oil is the correct temperature. If the
pepper turns brown or black, oil is too hot and you will have to
let it cool awhile. If pepper sinks and doesn't bubble, oil is not
hot enough. Keep heating and testing until you've got it right.
When oil is correct temperature, remove from heat and add remaining
pepper flakes. They will sizzle and bubble on surface of oil a few
minutes. When action subsides and oil turns a pale orange color,
add lemon juice, garlic and ground pepper. Let cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
