<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEERNUT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST A TAD SHORT OF WONDERFUL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL BOURGEOIS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Zambezi is a solid, well-made but undistinguished beer that
falls firmly into that great class of beers that are merely good.
</P>
<P>
   It is by no means bad, but it is not wonderful either.
</P>
<P>
   Zambezi produces a very nice, effervescent head, if that means
anything to you, but it subsides quickly.
</P>
<P>
   We found Zambezi a tad astringent, almost citrusy. Still, it had
a freshness about it, and a pleasant gold color, but not much depth
of flavor.
</P>
<P>
   The finish was a little bitter, but should you find yourself
tromping through the African bush in the dead of summer, do not
turn Zambezi down.
</P>
<P>
   It was refreshing but without the complex layers of taste and
aroma that we crave. Zambezi is a good beer, but for the money you
can do better, despite its fine and educational label.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very enlightening beer,'' said The Norm, a
self-styled know-it-all who lives in my back yard, but who insists
that he is homeless.
</P>
<P>
   If it weren't for beer labels, The Norm wouldn't read at all,
but he's determined to get on ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   He had planned to strike it rich as an inventor, but he said the
military seems uninterested in a helicopter that only flies upside
down.
</P>
<P>
   So now he's studying for his big break with Regis, and he found
the Zambezi label helpful.
</P>
<P>
   On it we learned that the beer is named for the Zambezi River,
the ``greatest river in Africa''; and that the river cascades over
Victoria Falls, which ``is one of the seven wonders of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, we weren't sure about this wonder business, so we checked
and it seems there are several sets of wonders. There's the ancient
wonders; the modern wonders; the Middle Age wonders; the natural
wonders, which includes Victoria Falls; and the Forgotten Wonders,
which are wonders that failed to make any other ``wonder'' list.
</P>
<P>
   But none makes any mention of beer, so here are our Seven
Wonders of the Beer World.
</P>
<P>
   1) Lite beer. The big wonder is why? It isn't real beer, and
``lite'' isn't a real word.
</P>
<P>
   2) Fruit-flavored beer. Again, we wonder. If you have to eat
fruit, eat a fried pie and wash it down with a Schlitz, but don't
mix them first. It's gross.
</P>
<P>
   3) Genuine draft in a bottle? Listen up, people, if it's in a
bottle, it isn't draft.
</P>
<P>
   4) Coors. A waste of good water.
</P>
<P>
   5) Coors Lite. It IS water, only with a metallic taste.
</P>
<P>
   6) Designer beer. Designers are guys who don't like women and
make them wear goofy clothes that nobody, least of all a beer
drinker, would buy. Brewers make beer, not designers.
</P>
<P>
   7) Nonalcoholic beer. This is a tough one. We are sympathetic to
those who for whatever reason can't drink real beer. But the idea
of calling this stuff beer is like yanking the engine from an F-16
and calling it a plane. This just don't fly.
</P>
<P>
   (Paul Bourgeois is beer critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
