<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW URBAN LANGUAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A word is passing out of the American language.
``Gentrification'' once described a lifestyle and complaints about
it. Its linguistic replacement is ``housing crisis,'' with adverbs
and adjectives trailing: ``ridiculously high rents'' and ``amazing
home prices'' in ``a crazy market.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gentrification'' blossomed in the Reagan era, after recession
and inflation in the 1970s had depressed the urban housing market.
The American Heritage Dictionary in 1982 called it the
``restoration of deteriorated urban property, especially in
working-class neighborhoods, by the middle and upper classes.'' The
Oxford American Dictionary added a political spin: ``movement of
middle class families into urban areas, causing property values to
increase and having secondary effect of driving out poorer
families.''
</P>
<P>
   Poorer families suffered, especially from federal cutbacks in
housing in the Reagan era, but early gentrifiers benefited and
accumulated political clout. The scene in this city's neighborhoods
is familiar elsewhere. An organic-food store has replaced the
bodega, the old tavern is now a brewpub, and the luncheonette has
become a coffee parlor. OK, perfect, nobody else come unless you
want to be branded an Outsider and a Gentrifier.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one in the '60s or '70s worried about gentrification,''
recalls Barney Frank, who has grappled with housing problems in the
Massachusetts Legislature and now in Congress. ``We have to deal
with expiring Section 8s,'' a federal program aiding renters. ``You
can not prevent gentrification, nor should you. What you can do is
to offset the consequences. It's the same overall with capitalism
and globalism. It's what Franklin Roosevelt would do: Set aside
some money, slow things down, yes, but not antigentrification.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent study showed that 40 percent of San Francisco renters
pay more than a third of their incomes on housing and that 20
percent pay half of their salaries. With job growth outpacing
housing starts, the average one-bedroom apartment now rents for
$2,000 monthly.
</P>
<P>
   The board of education proposes a teachers' apartment complex
near the planned Dianne Feinstein Elementary School. The city also
hopes to build high-rise clusters near transit stations. More
federal and state money is needed, but a severe political problem
is local. Even though the city has been zoned for high-rise housing
in some areas for decades, neighborhood opposition stalls projects
for years. And who are the fiercest opponents? Not the families
whose roots go back generations, but those who hopped aboard the
vessel of prosperity in the '80s and '90s and now propose pulling
up the ladder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gentrification'' has faded as a menace because early
gentrifiers won and have mostly prospered, these several ``greed
decades'' later. Many now own instead of rent, but still cherish
the anti-Reagan, anticapitalist stance of chic urban pioneers. They
oppose ``luxury housing for the rich,'' even though such housing
relieves the gentrifying pressure on rental housing for others. The
early gentrifiers do not believe that a rising tide lifts all
boats. Nor do they believe in the law of supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
   They were once called yuppies (young urban professionals), a
name they still don't like. They swiftly adapted to another
acronym, NIMBY: ``Not In My Back Yard,'' they say in this city and
others. They say no to new housing, to a new ballpark, to anything
new, though they're fairly new themselves.
</P>
<P>
   They chatter about a ``housing crisis,'' they no longer
experience themselves. They combine liberal views on social and
sexual issues with a robustly conservative defense of the economic
status quo. They intimidate politicians with NIMBY manifestos and
storm City Hall to protest outsiders who might lengthen their latte
line. The early gentrifiers have gone beyond NIMBY and gone
BANANAs: ``Build Absolutely Nothing Anywhere Near Anything,''
simple as that.
</P>
<P>
   Martin F. Nolan's column appears regularly in the Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 1511EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0756 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-SURVIVOR-LEDE-COX     05-31 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURVIVOR-LEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How to survive 'Survivor'
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   They slept dangerously close to poisonous snakes. Roasted rats
for dinner. Hiked for hours along treacherous, bug-infested trails.
</P>
<P>
   Is this any way to win a million bucks?
</P>
<P>
   It was for 16 adventure-seeking _ some might argue insane _
castaways on Survivor, CBS' bizarre reality series/game show
premiering tonight (8 p.m., WPEC-Channel 12). Combining elements of
The Real World, Gilligan's Island and Who Wants To Be A
Millionaire, Survivor is TV's latest ratings stunt in which people
are more than willing to humiliate themselves in front of a
prime-time audience for the sake of money and 15 fleeting minutes
of fame.
</P>
<P>
   And you thought it couldn't get any worse than Rick and Darva.
</P>
<P>
   This Truman Show meets Lord of The Flies one-hour series, hosted
by Jeff Probst (VH1's Rock and Roll Jeopardy!), is scheduled to air
for 13 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by a similar Swedish game, the Survivor concept is
relatively simple. Sixteen people _ ranging in age from 22 to 72 _
are dropped on a tropical Malaysian island for 39 days with minimal
supplies. Actually, they're forced to jump off a ship and swim
about a mile to their temporary home. Among the eight men and eight
women are a housewife, a neurologist, a biochemist, a river guide,
a musician and a retired Navy SEAL. Round-the-clock camera crews
hidden behind coral reefs and palm fronds follow their every move _
from trekking two hours for water to participating in a live
worm-eating competition.
</P>
<P>
   In this modern-day Robinson Crusoe adventure, the castaways are
forced to work together to build shelter (makeshift huts) and hunt
for food (they made bamboo spears to catch fish). The contestants
also gather every third day to compete in various games (diving
contests, treasure hunts) for such luxury items as chocolate bars
and flashlights. But every third night, the castaways hold a secret
ballot to boot one of the contestants _ probably the weak link or
loudest snorer _ off the island. When two survivors are left, a
panel of seven expelled participants will choose the $1 million
winner. The winner's identity won't be revealed until the final
episode _ if no one blabs before then, that is.
</P>
<P>
   So, while teamwork and cooperation are important, so is the
ability to be a deceitful back-stabber.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best and worst of office politics,'' notes Mark
Burnett, Survivor's executive producer. ``Very few people rise up
in organizations by being 100 percent on the straight-and-narrow
path. I gained enormous respect for some people and their
duplicity. At times this was an interesting mirror on life.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnett says he was surprised at how competitive the contestants
became. After one period of nonstop rain, for example, the
survivors were extremely hungry. So, Burnett gave them a map to
find fruit. ``They were offended,'' he recalls. ``They said, `Screw
you! Keep your map!' Most of these people didn't want to talk about
the money. They said they would've paid us for the experience.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were concerns. A few years ago, a contestant who
played the game in Sweden committed suicide a month after getting
kicked off the island. To keep that from happening on CBS' version,
two psychologists were hired to counsel exiled contestants. But
they didn't have much to do, Burnett says. ``It was boring for them
because we chose the people so well,'' he says. ``The psychologist
was like, `Can I have a beer?'''
</P>
<P>
   So, was there any hanky-panky on the island? After all, there
were manly studs and young college girls romping around the jungle
in skimpy bikinis. Burnett says he's sure one male and female
hooked up. ``But that wasn't a big factor in the show,'' he
explains.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, there were several tense moments. Some of the
castaways genuinely disliked each other. But most of those moments
occurred when someone was voted off the island. ``For most human
beings, not being liked is the most painful thing they can
endure,'' Burnett says. ``But most of them took it on the chin and
said, `OK, it was just a game.'''
</P>
<P>
   And there was a lot of interest in the game. CBS says it
received more than 6,000 applications and videotapes _ many from
Florida. In one video, a Floridian was seen shimmying up a palm
tree to show off skills he thought would be helpful on a tropical
island.
</P>
<P>
   Burnett had one major criteria for a Survivor contestant. ``We
didn't want to choose the kind of people you might see on The Jerry
Springer Show,'' says Burnett, who also produces Discovery
Channel's Eco Challenge. ``We went out of our way to choose people
who were very balanced.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Les Moonves, CBS' president and CEO, got in on the
five-month casting process when the field was narrowed to 50
Survivor wannabes. ``It was more interesting that any pilot we've
ever done,'' Moonves points out. ``Seeing these 50 people and
trying to put together a puzzle ... was fascinating.''
</P>
<P>
   But why did CBS want to do it? Well, that's easier than Regis'
first question.
</P>
<P>
   Survivor could help older-skewing CBS attract younger viewers.
Moonves adds that networks can experiment more in the summer, when
the ratings stakes aren't as high. ``This show will call attention
to the fact that CBS is not closed for the summer,'' Moonves says.
``There's a fascination with seeing average guys in unusual
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   We are, it appears, a nation full of thrill-loving voyeurs.
Everything from The Real World to Internet sites with 24-hour
cameras are extremely popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``Network TV has been looking for the next good idea for a long
time,'' says Robert Thompson, director of Syracuse University's
Center for the Study of Popular Television. ``Sleazy as it may be,
this may be the next big idea. TV and voyeurism were bound to
unite. The formula is one that clearly works. TV can let us be
peeping Toms without going to someone's window.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson believes we'll see more reality specials because they
are cheap, low-risk ventures. In fact, Big Brother, a CBS series in
which 10 people who have never met live in a house under total
surveillance, debuts in July. CBS says it's already preparing
another Survivor series if this one does well. (Such locations as
Tibet, the Australian Outback and Africa are being considered.)
Even stodgy PBS is joining the fray with The 1900 House, in which a
family spends three months in a house without modern-day
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, 1984 author George Orwell must be smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of him is saying, `I told you so,''' Thompson says. ``But
part of him was all wrong. This is not a state apparatus that's
being imposed upon us to keep us docile. We're doing it to
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   kevinthompson(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL
</P>
<P>
   The rules of the game:
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen castaways are marooned on a tropical island in the South
China Sea for 39 days and divided into two teams.
</P>
<P>
   With minimal supplies, the contestants work together to build
shelter and hunt for food. On the last day of each three-day cycle,
the castaways form a tribal council. At the meeting, each person
casts a secret ballot to boot one fellow castaway off the island.
</P>
<P>
   When only two survivors remain, the seven most-recently
eliminated contestants return to decide who the final survivor will
be.
</P>
<P>
   The winner takes home $1 million. Consolation cash prizes will
be awarded to the other castaways based on their order of
elimination. Those prizes will range from about $2,500 for the
first castaway ousted from the island to about $100,000 for the
runner-up to the final survivor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
