<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0760 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-SURVIVOR-HASKELL-COX     05-31 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURVIVOR-HASKELL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: Runs with SURVIVOR-LEDE
 &HT;    Rats! What are we going to eat here?
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine eating a fried rat. Colleen Haskell says it's not that
bad.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the 16 Survivor contestants left on a tropical
Malaysian island for 39 days, it wasn't like the 23-year-old Miami
Beach resident had many fancy dining options.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were so many rats and we had nothing else to eat,''
shrugs the bubbly Haskell. ``We were killing them left and right,
after a while, we said, `What are we going to do with all of these
dead rats?' So someone just threw them in the fire. ... I took a
leg and said, `Whatever.'''
</P>
<P>
   Haskell, who admits she's a bit ``spacey,'' answered an open
casting call last year in Miami to become a Survivor contestant.
The Bethesda, Md., native says she was shocked after being
selected. Her parents, quite naturally, thought she was nuts.
``They said, `This isn't in the parental handbook,''' says Haskell,
giggling like a high schooler. ``They still don't know what to do.
My mom's a wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   While riding on the plane for the 12,000-mile trip to the remote
island in the South China Sea, even Haskell wondered if she did the
right thing. ``We (the contestants) weren't allowed to talk to each
other, but I was looking at this person and what they were wearing
and I was thinking, `What am I going to do living with this person?
Why did I sign on the dotted line?''' she recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Haskell, a student at Miami Ad School, calls her Survivor
experience ``amazing.'' Spending more than a month with 15 other
strangers in less than ideal conditions leaves a lot of time for
serious introspection. ``I learned a lot about myself,'' says
Haskell, who hopes to land a job in creative advertising. ``Being
23, everyone my age goes through insecurities about what they're
doing and where they're headed, but this experience put everything
in an isolated period. I had to set a goal and achieve it.... that
was in my face every day.''
</P>
<P>
   And the toughest part?
</P>
<P>
   Why, swimming across a muddy lagoon, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``The water was thicker than mud,'' she recalls. ``It was awful,
awful, awful.''
</P>
<P>
   Haskell also wasn't too happy about the frigid night
temperatures, constant bug bites and lack of flavor in food.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't realize how important flavor is in food,'' Haskell
says. ``Sometimes it tasted like the most disgusting thing you ever
ate.''
</P>
<P>
   The contestants, Haskell says, often got antsy during the many
down times when there wasn't anything to do. ``You had nothing else
to do but wonder if something was wrong with you,'' she says.
``Someone would go, `This cut is really infected' and everyone
goes, like, `Yeah.' I think everyone thought they were going to die
at some point.''
</P>
<P>
   So, would she do it again?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it was fun,'' Haskell says excitedly. ``It was like I
went to summer camp and now I'm on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   On TV ... eating rats.
</P>
<P>
   kevinthompson(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
