<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0776 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      05-31 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
  
 HARPER'S MARKS 150th; A CASUALTY OF WAR  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To mark the 150th anniversary of  &UR; Harper's,  &LR; Lewis Lapham &AMP; Co.
have thrown a high-minded party in print that reminds us how
indispensable the magazine is.
</P>
<P>
   Mining gems from the 19th century, the June issue offers, among
many other things, Mark Twain's hilarious spoof of the full
disclosure required of presidential candidates (which could be
written today, if only there were a Twain around to write it); a
surprising list of words that first appeared in 1850 (among them
buddy, employee, heartbeat, pornographer, sonny, wavelength); and a
stirring letter to the London Times from Frederick Douglass,
thanking the newspaper for editorializing against a racist assault
on him.
</P>
<P>
   Back here in the present, Tom Wolfe weighs in with another
scathingly stylish essay upbraiding the lefty intelligentsia. The
white-suited one evidently has no intention of mellowing as he
approaches his 70th year (of Susan Sontag, Wolfe writes that she
``spent her life signing up for protest meetings and lumbering to
the podium, encumbered by her prose style, which had a handicapped
parking sticker valid at Partisan Review'').
</P>
<P>
   But the issue's high point for this reader is the series of
short stories and essays written by present-day authors from the
vantage of 1850; more than a nod to the past, this amounts to a
genuinely searching look. The best of them is ``P.T. Barnum and My
Great-Great-Granddad's Slaves,'' in which Allan Gurganus turns his
ancestor's trip to see a Barnum roadshow (with family slaves in
tow) into a lyrical meditation on slavery. Who were the real
freaks, Gurganus asks, Barnum's bearded ladies and the other
hapless ``curiosities,'' or the people who actually felt they had
the right to own other human beings?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Given the facile contempt so much of the public feels for ``the
media,'' it's worth noting that 34 journalists were killed doing
their jobs in 1999. One of them was Myles Tierney, a 34-year-old
producer for Associated Press Television who made a career of
bringing TV cameras into places others feared to go, right up to
the day he was machine-gunned by a rebel in Freetown, the capital
of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Tierney's brief life is the subject of an excellent piece by his
colleague and sometime lover, Dianna Cahn, in the June  &UR; Brill's
Content. &LR;  This thoughtful, self-questioning account of the hazards
faced by foreign correspondents makes clear the price some
journalists are willing to pay in order to tell a story they think
the world needs to know _ even if, in the case of the civil war
that tore apart Sierra Leone and caused unspeakable suffering for
civilians, much of the world seemed indifferent.
</P>
<P>
   But the risk-loving, fearless Tierney seemed born for a war zone
and would cross enemy lines if that's what it took. ``He liked
covering wars and was good at it; he thrived on the commotion, the
negotiation, the adrenaline,'' writes Cahn. ``For him it was always
a chase, a story that needed to be told.''
</P>
<P>
   For Cahn herself, Tierney's death brought not just grief but a
deeper understanding of the strange kinship between war
correspondents and the desperate people they cover. She learned
that ``we go into these places knowing we can leave any time we
choose. We have lives outside. But in death, a very real part of
war, the difference is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Salon columnist Cintra Wilson rails entertainingly _ but, of
course, futilely _ against the American obsession with fame in
 &UR; Utne Reader. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Fame is a perverse deformity, an ego swelling as ludicrous as
an extra sex organ . . ., '' Wilson writes. And: ``Celebrity is a
virulent killer of fundamental human values, and the only way to
control it is to quit believing in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's essential point is that the cult of fame and celebrity
is a pernicious trap for us, the gawkers, since it keeps us from
Getting a Life. She might be right, and it's certainly refreshing _
with the magazine stands clotted with odes to celebrity worship _
to see someone turning a rhetorical blowtorch on the whole
business.
</P>
<P>
   But there's another way to look at it. In an excerpt from Tyler
Cowen's ``What Price Fame?'' juxtaposed against Wilson's screed,
Cowen argues that the quest for fame has produced ``many of the
triumphs of contemporary culture'' in the arts, in business, and in
science, ``all achieved at relatively low cost.'' Cowen concludes,
depressingly but probably rightly, that ``false beliefs can be very
useful for society.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To be a parent is to experience the deepest joy available to
human beings and also the deepest anxiety and confusion.
</P>
<P>
   It's a vast emotional territory, one that Alec Wilkinson
affectingly traverses in an essay about his 6-year-old son, Sam, in
the June  &UR; Esquire. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Sam has a sensory disorder that makes him extra-sensitive to
sound and touch and complicates the act of speaking. That makes the
act of raising him more challenging, but the feelings Wilkinson
touches on are universal: the desire to fill your offspring's life
with as many happy moments as possible, the virtual end to other
forms of recreation (movies? what are movies?), and the bedrock
realization every parent has, Wilkinson writes, that your love for
your child makes you a ``hostage to the unfolding of the
universe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
