<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE GENDER-BIAS WARPATH AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pamela Martens' voice carries remnants of her Virginia
upbringing as well as a ring of frustration that's hard to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all the women (in this case) knew what was going on, they
would be angry, too,'' said Martens, who helped launch the
so-called ``Boom Boom Room'' gender-bias lawsuit against Salomon
Smith Barney four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Martens is on the warpath again. This time the 54-year-old
Long Island stockbroker has launched a nationwide e-mail campaign
to focus attention on the case and protest a two-year-old court
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Martens, who is seeking a jury trial, withdrew from the larger
class-action lawsuit in 1998 because the settlement did not give
brokers with discrimination claims the ability to take their cases
to court. Rather, the settlement says civi-rights claims may be
resolved before an independent arbitrator.
</P>
<P>
   As part of their employment, stock brokers are required to
register with the National Association of Securities Dealers and
sign a so-called U-4 securities arbitration form mandating that any
dispute or claim against their employer be submitted to
arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   Many employees, particularly women and minorities, have argued
that the system denies them the right to present evidence to a
diverse panel of peers. Instead, they say, the mediators are older
white males with ties to the financial services industry.
</P>
<P>
   On May 16, a day after US District Court Justice Constance Baker
Motley of New York tossed out the individual complaints that
Martens and Judith Mione filed against the firm last year, Martens
fired off a string of e-mails protesting the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Motley dismissed the claims after finding that over a 15-month
period the pair ``neglected their individual claims and, instead,
devoted substantial efforts to derailing the class settlement. . .
. The court now concludes that Martens' and Mione's failure to
advance their individual claims stemmed not from confusion but from
inexcusable delay sufficient to dismiss those claims . . . for
failure to prosecute,'' wrote Motley.
</P>
<P>
   Enraged, Martens took her concerns to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been creating massive e-mail lists,'' Martens said.
``Over time, I've gathered the e-mails for all the human-rights
groups, for all the members of NOW in New York City, for all the
members of the Business and Professional Women's Association, and
for certain women's activists online. I think people ought to know
exactly what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally from Appalachia, Martens arrived at Smith Barney in
1985 hoping to garner access to the wealth she'd never had.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son was 5 years old,'' she said. ``I started to look at
what it would take for me and my husband to educate him. I said `I
need to move on and find out how to manage and save money.' So I
entered a Smith Barney training program.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten years after her arrival, Martens received a ``big bronze
plaque for a decade of loyal and dedicated service.'' Yet, she
said, her branch manager in Garden City, Long Island, frequently
criticized female and minority brokers, oftentimes using
disparaging epithets behind their backs.
</P>
<P>
   She said the manager of her office invited male brokers to a
golfing club, but noted at the time that he had not planned to
invite any of the women. ``He also turned a storage room in the
basement into a bar and he had a toilet bowl and rusty bike hanging
from the ceiling,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the PA system, he would invite all brokers for drinks in
the Boom Boom Room. The one time I went he had a black garbage can
with a (plastic) liner in it and a soup ladle to serve Bloody Marys
to brokers.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, after a group of female clerical workers were told they
must volunteer some of their personal time to their supervisor's
charity or lose raises and time off, Martens protested. She says
her anger increased when the manager insisted that stockbrokers
contribute money to his charity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I laced . . . into him,'' Martens said. ``I said, `What you
have done  &UR; today &LR;  is extortion and it calls into question your
competency as a manager.' He said, `I'll toss you out of this
office and we will throw a party.' ''
</P>
<P>
   After Martens complained to a company official, her supervisor
told stockbrokers in the bond room that he would ``snap my neck if
anything happened to him,'' she said. ``He'd stroll around the
floor waving a baseball bat. I shut my door and tried to stay away
from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Martens hired a lawyer in January 1995, and was fired nine
months later for failing to attend a required meeting. ``They had
never fired anyone for not attending a meeting. Instead,'' she
said, ``people got, as a standard practice, a fine, but even that
was not enforced.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, she filed a lawsuit against her employer. Four years
later, Martens is still up in arms.
</P>
<P>
   But whether she will be able to rally a significant wave of
support is another matter. The New York division of NOW is backing
her and so is a national student group. But NOW's national office
has backed the court settlement hammered out by the Chicago law
firm, Stowell &AMP; Friedman. In all, some 23,000 current and former
stockbrokers at Salomon Smith Barney will be impacted by the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 14 and later 15 of the 25 original plaintiffs say they
wanted to move ahead with the settlement,'' recalled attorney Mary
Stowell of Stowell &AMP; Friedman. ``We sent out hundreds of copies of
settlements to the women, and we told them to check a Web site
(www.classactionsb.com) where the settlement has been posted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also notified people of the class-action lawsuit of their
right to opt out and pursue individual claims,'' she continued.
``We had two fairness hearings where the judge wanted to see better
goals and timetables established for the hiring and promotion of
women and minorities. The judge also wanted to maintain
jurisdiction over that. . . . It is too bad Pamela Martens is
angry. We did a fabulous job for many in the class.''
</P>
<P>
   In making her decision last week, Motley noted that in removing
themselves from the class, Martens and Mione forfeited the right to
involve themselves in the affairs of the class. In other words,
once you're out, you're out.
</P>
<P>
   Martens disagrees, and she intends to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Martens's 1994 complaint against Salomon Smith Barney, now a
unit of Citigroup Inc., sought not only monetary damages but also a
declaratory judgment against the investment firm, the New York
Stock Exchange, and the NASD, stating that mandatory arbitration of
employment discrimination and harassment charges violates federal
law.
</P>
<P>
   Diane E. Lewis can be reached at 617-929-2069, by e-mail at
work(at)globe.com, or at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box 2378, Boston,
MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
