<HEADLINE>
HERE'S THE DRILL: BRISKET IS SOMETHING YOU GRILL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the not-from-around-here category, we received a letter
from a reader in Trophy Club, Texas, who was confused about
brisket.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband went to the grocery store for me last week and
tried to buy a beef brisket. He's not that familiar with cooking,
so he asked the person working in the meat department to help him
find a beef brisket.
</P>
<P>
   ``The woman in the meat department sent him home with a corned
beef brisket. I told my husband I thought there was a difference
between a beef brisket for barbecuing and a corned beef brisket. He
said the woman said they were the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My cookbooks list them as two different cuts, but I can't find
any explanations between the differences. Can you help me figure
this out? Can a corned beef brisket be prepared in the same way?''
</P>
<P>
   My clue that the reader is a newcomer to Texas is that beef
brisket is often not even sold in the rest of the country. And when
it is, it is sold ``corned'' in the British tradition (meaning in
brine in a heavy plastic bag). That's also how we see corned beef
here.
</P>
<P>
   But in Texas, what is a trash cut of beef to most of the country
is the apple of the barbecuer's eye. It was German butchers in the
Texas Hill Country who turned brisket, a cut taken from the breast
section under the first five ribs of the steer, into a thing of
beauty. In an attempt to market this very tough cut that no one
would buy, the butchers began smoking them in the backs of their
shops. Yahoo. Texans fell in love.
</P>
<P>
   Beef brisket can be found in every supermarket in Texas in the
beef section. It will be packaged in Cryovac (heavy plastic wrap)
or simply plastic-wrapped on one of those foam trays. The
vacuum-wrapped briskets are ``packer-trimmed,'' meaning that it's
the entire brisket and the fat is not trimmed. The ``market trim''
is usually a portion of the brisket, either the point cut or the
less fatty flat. I think you need the fat for flavor, so I
generally buy the entire brisket and freeze any leftovers that
don't go into weekday sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   Starting around Easter, and lasting through Labor Day, brisket
is very attractively priced (some stores have it for as low as 57
cents a pound at this time of year) because stores use it as a lure
for Texas grillers.
</P>
<P>
   Do not, and we repeat, do not use a corned beef on the grill.
You'll end up with a soggy mess. A corned beef is best cooked in a
slow cooker or on the stove top.
</P>
<P>
   In the ``Food Lover's Companion,'' Sharon Tyler Herbst says,
``Brisket requires long, slow cooking and is best when braised.''
We'll excuse Tyler Herbst _ she's not from around here, either. The
best way to cook a brisket, any Texan will tell you, is in a smoker
or on a grill. And here are instructions from the Weber Grill
folks.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS BEEF BRISKET
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8-10
</P>
<P>
   5- to 6-pound beef brisket, untrimmed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup rub for beef
</P>
<P>
   1 bottle beer
</P>
<P>
   Wood chips or chunks, optional
</P>
<P>
   Rub brisket liberally with rub up to 1 day in advance and
refrigerate. Prepare coals or turn on gas grill. If using a
charcoal grill, place a drip pan between 2 piles of coals. In a gas
grill, place the drip pan under the grate between flames. Pour beer
into drip pan.
</P>
<P>
   Place brisket, fat side up, in center of cooking grate over drip
pan. Place wood chips that have been soaked in water for 30 minutes
directly on coals or in smoker box in your gas grill. Grill 3 to 4
hours or until meat thermometer registers 180 degrees. When done,
remove from grill and let rest 10 minutes. Slice thinly and serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Be sure to add coals each hour to keep heat constant if
using a charcoal grill.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 412 calories, 22 grams fat, 0
carbohydrates, 51 grams protein, 158 milligrams cholesterol, 119
milligrams sodium, 47 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   A treat from 1187: Beatrice Thomason loved the salad dressing
she sampled at Cafe 1187 on Easter Sunday. Chef-owner Michele Tezak
was glad to share the recipe inspired by her mother, Jodie. Her
mother made the salad dressing at least 20 years ago, and Michele
simply adapted it. At Cafe 1187, the dressing is served on a simple
salad of crisp romaine and tomato wedges.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CAFE 1187 RED ONION SALAD DRESSING
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 2 cups
</P>
<P>
   1/4 red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried basil
</P>
<P>
   1 medium red onion, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   3/4 to 1 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   Place all ingredients, except oil, in blender. Turn on blender
and process until mixture is pureed. While blender is running,
drizzle oil in a continuous thin stream through the hole in the
lid. Make sure to do this slowly so the dressing will emulsify, or
combine into one ``unit.'' You have used enough oil when the hole
in the middle of the onion mixture, caused by the blender's
mechanism, has disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   This dressing can be turned into a seasoned mayonnaise by simply
adding more oil. Tezak suggests using a food processor instead of a
blender if you're making mayonnaise.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per tablespoon: 50 calories, 5 grams fat, 1
gram carbohydrates, trace protein, 7 milligrams cholesterol, 76
milligrams sodium, 95 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
