<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIAN PRISONERS IN ISRAEL END HUNGER STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Palestinian prisoners in Israeli jails ended a
month-long hunger strike Wednesday, averting a further round of
street protests that many here had feared could derail peace talks
between Israel and the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   In a compromise forged by the authority's Ministry for
Prisoners' Affairs, Israel granted the inmates more liberal family
visitation rights and moved five prisoners out of solitary
confinement, among other concessions. Some 500 prisoners who had
been on a liquid diet for the past 31 days called off the protest,
though they continued to demand that other inmates be freed from
solitary confinement.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrations in the West Bank and Gaza in favor of the
prisoners erupted into violence last week, leading to a suspension
of peace talks and to gun battles with the Israeli military that
left six Palestinians dead.
</P>
<P>
   The peace talks, which had been held in Stockholm, are to resume
in an unannounced location in the Middle East as soon as Thursday,
according to Israeli state radio. President Clinton and Prime
Minister Ehud Barak are to discuss the talks Thursday in Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials hailed Wednesday's deal as a belated
Israeli recognition of the extreme sensitivity of the issue of the
prisoners. But they repeated demands for the release of some 500
Palestinians who have been held in Israeli prisons for crimes of
political violence since before the the May 1994 start of
land-for-peace negotiations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not fully satisfied, but the significant thing is that
this was a clear message from the Palestinian people that the
prisoners' cause is fundamental and needs to be resolved,'' said
Qadoura Fares, a Palestinian legislator who helped negotiate the
compromise. ``I believe the Israelis understood the message.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hundreds of protesters camped for the past month in plazas
throughout the Palestinian territories had also been fasting in
support of the striking prisoners. The protests were called off
Wednesday, Issa Qarake, a chief organizer, said in Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The solidarity activities in the street helped the prisoners
to achieve their main demands,'' Qarake said
</P>
<P>
   Among the concessions extracted by Palestinian negotiators was
the right of young children to visit with imprisoned parents
unimpeded by barred barriers. Prisoners will also now be allowed to
telephone their families on special occasions like weddings and
funerals, and to pursue studies with Palestinian universities,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Israel released some 360 long-term prisoners over the past year
in accord with agreements negotiated with the Palestinian
Authority. Palestinian negotiators are asking Israel to release
another 230 pre-1994 prisoners who they say were not directly
involved with fatal attacks against Israelis _ the key Israeli
criterion for their possible release.
</P>
</TEXT>
