<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-U.S.-CHINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE BEAT U.S. WOMEN, 1-0, IN SOCCER REMATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The audience and the temperature had fallen precipitously since
their last meeting, but the United States and China played a
riveting rematch in women's soccer in Canberra, Australia early
Wednesday. Again, the match was decided by a penalty kick, this
time in regulation. And this time, China prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Four minutes from the end of regulation, the Chinese forward Sun
Wen got tangled with defender Danielle Slaton, and the two fell
down in the penalty area. China was awarded a penalty kick, and Sun
calmly placed her shot in the upper right corner for a 1-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The last time these teams had played, July 10, 1999, they had
drawn the largest audience ever to watch a women's sporting event _
90,185 at the Rose Bowl for the final of the Women's World Cup. The
rematch, held in the first round of the Pacific Cup tournament in
the Australian capital, was played Wednesday before an estimated
550 fans. And those summer temperatures that had risen above 100
degrees on the Rose Bowl turf last July had dipped to freezing in
the Southern Hemisphere's late autumn.
</P>
<P>
   Playing on a field made choppy from rugby matches and missing
three vital starters _ goalkeeper Briana Scurry (shin splints),
midfielder Michelle Akers (shoulder surgery) and defender Carla
Overbeck (knee surgery) _ the Americans outshot China by 10-5 but,
as in the World Cup, could not manufacture a goal during
regulation. Mia Hamm did not play one of her better games, and she
was replaced by Nikki Serlenga in the 81st minute.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes later, after miscommunication in midfield between
Julie Foudy and Cindy Parlow, the ball bounced free in the penalty
area. Slaton attempted to shield it from a charging Sun, protecting
it for the sliding American goalkeeper Siri Mullinix, but Slaton
and Sun collided and the referee signaled a penalty kick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a marginal call; nonetheless we weren't going to win
the game without scoring,'' Coach April Heinrichs said in a
telephone interview from Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Last July, after two overtime periods, the Americans had
prevailed 5-4 in a penalty kick shootout on Brandi Chastain's
famous shot. In the rematch, the Americans missed three point-blank
chances to score in regulation, Heinrichs said. In the 90th minute,
Milbrett ran onto a pass from Parlow and angled a shot from the
left side of the penalty area that beat goalkeeper Han Wenxia but
sailed just wide of the right goal post.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played well at times, but it would be misleading to say we
dominated, and it would be misleading to say the game was anything
more than a 1-0 game, with both teams having the possibility to
win,'' Heinrichs said. ``I don't think there was melodrama around
the big rematch.''
</P>
<P>
   With the captain Overbeck unavailable, Heinrichs moved Joy
Fawcett into central defense and started Christie Pearce at right
back. Lorrie Fair replaced Akers in defensive midfield, and
Mullinix continued to play capably at goalkeeper, aggressively
coming off her line. Sun, voted the most valuable player in the
World Cup, was muzzled for the first 85 minutes, until she broke
free to gain a penalty kick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very pleased how we played in the back,'' Heinrichs
said.
</P>
<P>
   China made one key change, replacing longtime goalkeeper Gao
Hong with Han. Gao, who has uncertain hands, had played poorly in a
3-0 loss to Norway at an important tournament in Portugal in March.
The entire Chinese team had seemed lethargic and overtrained in
Portugal, only to appear reinvigorated for the rematch against the
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They looked tired, uninvested in Portugal,'' Heinrichs said.
``Tonight, they were invested.''
</P>
<P>
   The teams are expected to play a handful of times this year,
including again in Australia at the 2000 Summer Olympics in
September. Five consecutive matches between the United States and
China have been decided by one goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of those games is going to be excruciating,''
Heinrichs said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
