<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0787 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-YOUNG-WORKERS-$ADV04-     05-31 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-WORKERS-$ADV04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN BOOM TIMES, SOME NEW GRADS HOLD OUT FOR FULFILLMENT
 &HT;    With YOUNG-DATA. For release Sunday, June 4.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE PARK, Md. _ A computer sciences graduate recently left
his Ivy League university straight for a newly formed software
company. Starting salary and benefits package: $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Class of 2000 has it made. The college graduates, 1.2
million of them, are entering the job market in a soaring economy,
with corporate America hungry for new workers.
</P>
<P>
   Show them the money _ but show them more. Mere mega-salaries and
stock options fail to impress many of these twentysomethings, whose
college careers have coincided with the nation's longest peacetime
economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Many are in no rush to begin chasing their first million. In
opinion polls and interviews, they rate job satisfaction, corporate
values and family life over personal wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just sitting in a room and writing (computer) code didn't
appeal to me,'' said Joel Martinsen, 22, a mathematics graduate
from the University of Maryland at College Park.
</P>
<P>
   His roommate took a job with IBM, which offered a signing bonus
and a $55,000-a-year salary.
</P>
<P>
   Martinsen, of Rockville, Md., leaves in late June for China,
where he'll work in the remote northern province of Jilin as an
English teacher for two years, and teach himself to speak Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not exactly a high-tech, high-paying job, but it's a
chance for me to learn. And who knows, with the China trade
agreement maybe it'll be useful for me when I'm looking for a job
down the road,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is almost counter-revolutionary amid the dot-com
revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is the ultimate indulgence amid America's boom times,
the luxury to be picky about a job or to defer a career altogether.
Whatever the reason, the current crop of graduates seems less
materialistic and more concerned with their quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've reached this turning point in my life where every job
I've had so far has been monkey work. A trained chimpanzee could do
my job,'' said Erica Lapidus, 28, of Plainview, N.Y., who works for
a corporate head-hunter. When she finishes her master's degree in
international business management this fall at Nova Southeastern
University in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., she wants a fulfilling job in
marketing that allows her to travel the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me miserable just to roll out of bed in the morning.
I want a job that I love,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   More than four-fifths of men and women in their 20s said that
having a flexible work schedule that allows them time with their
families was more important than a status job or making a high
salary, according to a recent poll by the Radcliffe Public Policy
Center.
</P>
<P>
   According to a survey of more than 3,000 students conducted late
last year by Jobtrak.com, an online career-placement service, money
ranked a distant second to ``balancing work and personal life'' in
a listing of career values. Flexible work hours, the ability to
telecommute and living in a specific region of the nation were more
important than income level or signing bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Adjusted for inflation, the average wage in America has actually
dipped slightly since 1964. The figures do not reflect non-salary
compensation such as stock options and other benefits now being
used to lure new workers.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from the robust economy, wage stagnation and the
decline in mutual loyalty between workers and employers could be
two possible explanations for the new lifestyle-over-money attitude
among college grads.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems, the software giant, has more than 3,100 jobs
to fill. A special Web site targeted to prospective workers
reflects the new reality of what students want, and includes a
come-on that offers something for everyone: ``Stick your neck out.
Get your hands dirty. Lose yourself in the work. Pick your hours
(and your attire) to suit your style.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Scott's words (CEO Scott McNealy), ``Kick butt, and have
fun.'' That means we expect 110% from everyone, but also honor and
support a balanced life. Our many perks can help with many personal
time-management challenges, the rest is up to you. Does this kind
of environment appeal to you? If it does, you could really thrive
here.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, college graduates with high-tech degrees in computer
sciences and engineering are in high demand, commanding average
starting salaries of about $50,000. About half of the 1.6 million
tech jobs available this year will go unfilled due to a lack of
qualified and trained candidates, according to the Information
Technology Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   But the need for skilled workers cuts across nearly every field,
with demand up this year for marketing and management grads and
liberal arts majors such as communications and psychology.
</P>
<P>
   Jobtrak.com, which monitors job-posting data at U.S. colleges
and universities, reported that there was a 40.8 percent increase
in the number of available jobs last April compared to a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate recruiters have scrambled to woo new workers,
including forays onto college campuses that have begun targeting
not only seniors, but also students in their junior year.
</P>
<P>
   They've also begin making stops at the traditional spring break
beaches. Along with the thousands of revelers in hot spots like
Panama City, Fla., and Myrtle Beach, S.C., last spring were scores
of corporate recruiters holding job fairs among the beer bashes.
</P>
<P>
   In Silicon Valley, the California bastion of the high-tech
economy, the recruitment frenzy is so wild that gimmicks include
raffles in return for resumes. Apply for a job, and qualify to win
a new BMW or a trip to Cancun.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen or more Web sites specialize in marrying recruiters with
potential workers, allowing students to post their resumes
electronically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is a factor, obviously. But it is a mistake to assume
that it is the end-all,'' said Monica Feid, spokeswes have jobs or
job offers by the time of graduation. This year, more than half
have found work.
</P>
<P>
   Many have job offers, but are choosing to postpone a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Hogan, 23, of Philadelphia, an engineering grad, is
weighing offers from private firms, or may take a lower-paying job
with the state of California's transportation department for the
chance to live the West Coast lifestyle. He'll decide soon, but for
now his mind is on an upcoming summer trip to Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel, 'I'll get a job after I graduate and I've traveled
or done some other enriching things.' They don't feel pressed for
time,'' said Camille Luckenbaugh of the National Association of
Colleges and Employers in Bethlehem, Pa. ``The economy is that
good.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics, employment projections for
1998-2008 and the Occupational Outlook Handbook for 2000-2001 at
www.bls.gov/emphome.htm
</P>
<P>
   National Association of Colleges and Employers, an association
of college career centers and U.S. businesses: www.naceweb.org
</P>
<P>
   Jobtrak.com, a for-profit online career placement and
resume-posting service: www.jobtrak.com
</P>
<P>
   CollegeHire.com, a for-profit online career placement and
resume-posting service: www.CollegeHire.com
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's e-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
