<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0788 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-NY-SENATE-HNS &LR;      05-31 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CLINTON, LAZIO BATTLE FOR UNDECIDED VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LARA JAKES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Pop quiz: The U.S. Senate candidate wants to
boost public education, protect the environment, wire up schools to
the Internet and protect health benefits for the disadvantaged. Oh,
and no mudslinging on the campaign trail. It's all about issues.
</P>
<P>
   Who is the candidate? Republican Rick Lazio or Democrat Hillary
Rodham Clinton?
</P>
<P>
   Both.
</P>
<P>
   For all of the talk of the stark differences between Lazio and
Clinton in the race for Senate, the four-term congressman from Long
Island is espousing many of the same themes that the first lady has
embraced in her 10 months on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   And while he lashed out at Clinton for engaging in political
mudslinging, Lazio said his campaign is aimed at ``bringing people
together and building a stronger New York through unity, not
through division'' _ rhetoric that closely resembles that of the
first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our campaign tactic is going to be to unite New Yorkers _ it's
about positive changes,'' Lazio told a packed ballroom at a women's
luncheon Tuesday afternoon. ``We have 150 days as the world looks
at us to prove who we are. This campaign is going to be about
inspiration and bringing people together and not going down the
dark path of division and hate.''
</P>
<P>
   Compare that to Clinton:
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be the kind of leader who lifts people up, not
pushes them down,'' Clinton said on a recent campaign swing, asking
her crowd to ``reject the politics of division, revenge and
retribution.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there are some distinct differences between the two.
Since Lazio entered the race last month when New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani abandoned his campaign, Clinton's camp has compared the
congressman to former House Speaker Newt Gingrich, the stridently
conservative politician who pushed through the Contract with
America in the historic 1994 Republican takeover of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio voted in favor of the contract in his first term and was
personally aided by Gingrich in winning two prominent committee
assignments.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio is also eager to point out differences between him and the
first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you talk about what's mainstream and what's not, I think
most people in New York would consider tax relief as an important
issue,'' Lazio said, ticking off what he says are the three top
issues that set them apart. ``Most people would look at health care
and say, `Yeah, we need to extend prescription benefits for
seniors; we need to do it in a responsible way.' We don't want to
turn over our health care system to the federal government, to this
faceless bureaucracy. On the environment, one person can talk about
(protecting) it and one person's been doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of differences between Mrs. Clinton and
myself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But with a small number of New Yorkers who have yet to decide
between Clinton and Lazio, neither candidate wants to be portrayed
as anything but mainstream and conciliatory to avoid alienating any
voters. Recent polls show Clinton and Lazio already locked in a
statistical dead heat, with as few as 6 to 10 percent of voters
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Even Clinton spokesman Howard Wolfson indicated he was surprised
at Lazio's relative restraint on a day ripe for red-meat Republican
rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds as though they've been reading her speeches,'' he
said. ``The difference is, one person has been saying it for a
year, and one person's been saying it for a day. These are the
themes Hillary Clinton has been campaigning on over the last
year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
