<HEADER>
A0793 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-`FINKS'-HEZBOLLAH-IND     05-31 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`FINKS'-HEZBOLLAH-INDEPENDENT-FISK-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEZBOLLAH BRINGS REVENGE ON `COLLABORATORS'  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 875-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   TAIBE, SOUTHERN LEBANON _ In the government hospital in Nabatea,
Abbas Koussan's battered face and body are a mark of shame on his
country; on the Hezbollah militia who liberated his village of
Taibe, on the U.N. troops who failed to protect him, on the
government security men who refused him permission to tell his
story even in his hospital bed, on the Israelis who tried to
blackmail him into collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   And on his neighbors in the pretty little Shiite Muslim hamlet,
some of whom _ convinced that he was (italics: was) a collaborator
_ beat Abbas Koussan insensible in the center of the village after
looting his little shop.
</P>
<P>
   I happen to know Abbas. I don't believe he was a fifth columnist
or an informer. The Israelis and their proxy militia tried to
intimidate him and blackmail him and they tortured him because they
thought he worked for the Lebanese army.
</P>
<P>
   They even asked him about my own movements in southern Lebanon.
But he was no spy. It didn't save him.
</P>
<P>
   There was no Lebanese government to protect him _ any more than
there was a government force to save the life of the Christian
civilian in Rmeich who was shot dead by an Amal gunman in a dispute
Sunday afternoon. For these are increasingly dangerous days in
southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Abbas Koussan knows it all too well. Having endured months of
harsh imprisonment in the notorious Khiam jail, he thought he was
safe running his store below the old Israeli gun position, selling
jackets and knives and sunglasses to Finnish U.N. soldiers,
drinking cups of coffee outside with his brothers Mohsen and Bilal
and sister Dalal.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Saturday morning, at 10 o'clock, at least 30 armed men
drove up to the shop, many of them carrying rocket-propelled
grenade launchers and Hezbollah flags. They said they were from
Hezbollah and they tore down pictures of the rival Amal flag and of
President Emile Lahoud of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Then they went into the house, ransacking every room, seizing
two legally owned pistols and a hunting gun and then thieving their
way through the shop below.
</P>
<P>
   The men knew the names of the intruders. There were Nehme Abbas
and Mohamed from the Souli family and Reda and Hassan Marmar who
lived just down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``They screamed at us that we were dogs and bitches and they
said they were going to kill Abbas,'' Dalal said Sunday. ``He was
put in a car with two other men and taken into the village. They
opened fire everywhere _ into the house, the shop, around our feet,
over our head. They beat the rest of us, even the children. A car
came back later and Abbas's unconscious body was tipped out onto
the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought he was already dead because there was so much
blood,'' Dalal said. ``We got him into the house and the U.N. came
and gave medical assistance. It was about the only thing the U.N.
did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was half and hour before the U.N. soldiers got to the
house, and turned up at the stagnant village pool _ known to the
U.N. as `Cholera Pond' _ where Abbas and two other men, Assad Souli
and Mohamed Musri, were beaten with rifles and clubs. The U.N. who
would have been outnumbered 30 to 12, have an observation post 30
seconds walk from the pond.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Cholera Pond Sunday, the crowd were all ignorance.
``Nothing happened here,'' an old man with a white beard lied to
me. And when I asked to talk to Ali Rislan, one of the local
Hezbollah leaders, he repeated the same story.
</P>
<P>
   With sunglasses shading his face and dressed from head to toe in
black, he was a little taken aback when I contacted Hezbollah
headquarters by phone _ and when a Hezbollah official in Beirut
asked him to cooperate with my enquiries. ``Wait here,'' Rislan
said.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, a young man in the local mosque apologized for
Rislan's absence. ``He got a very bad toothache and we had to take
him to a dentist,'' he said. ``Can you imagine what it's like
trying to find a dentist around here?'' I could.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened,'' the young man continued, ``was that some of
the local people _ not Hezbollah, you must understand _ were very
angry at some collaborators who lived in the village. They took
three of them to the pool here and beat them. Even some women were
doing the beating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abbas Koussan _ you know there was a photograph we saw of him
yesterday eating a meal with the head of Israeli intelligence at
Metulla or somewhere. Yes, he was in prison but he was a
stool-pigeon.''
</P>
<P>
   I didn't believe that, I said. He had spoken with deep enmity of
his country's occupiers and had always told me the truth about
events in the occupation zone.
</P>
<P>
   Why had the gunmen looted the shop and stolen the family jeep
and mobile telephone? Why could Hezbollah not stop such acts of
anarchy in a village which they controlled? &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
