<HEADER>
A0795 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-DYING-LANGUAGES-INDEP     05-31 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DYING-LANGUAGES-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST OF WORLD'S LANGUAGES `WILL VANISH BY 2100'  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (This 625-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By STEVE CONNOR  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Most of the world's 6,000-plus languages will have
died out by the end of the century, experts predicted Monday.
Linguists issued fresh warnings about the perilous position of the
thousands of languages spoken mainly by adults but increasingly
rarely by their children and grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   They said the continuing drive for the young to communicate in
one of the three most popular tongues _ English, Spanish or
Mandarin _ threatens to destroy a key ingredient of humanity's
cultural heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists estimate there are 6,000 to 8,000 identifiable
languages in the world and that most are spoken by less than a few
thousand individuals, making them especially vulnerable to
extinction.
</P>
<P>
   In areas where native languages are well studied _ notably North
America and Australia _ it is estimated that up to 90 percent will
be lost in the next few generations.
</P>
<P>
   Extrapolating the findings to the wider world, linguists
estimate that at least half and probably nearer three-quarters of
languages spoken today will be lost forever before the century is
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety percent of languages today are each spoken by less than
100,000 people. With most languages being spoken by a small number
of individuals, that makes them very vulnerable,'' said Steve
Levinson, of the Max Planck institute for psycholinguists at
Nijmegen, in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Only 200 to 250 languages are spoken by more than a million
people, with English, Spanish and Mandarin expanding faster than
any of the other popular tongues, Dr. Levinson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless something amazing happens, the estimates for the rate
of loss are probably right. We're losing our natural laboratory of
variation, our Galapagos,'' said Dr. Levinson, referring to islands
where Darwin studied the diversity of life.
</P>
<P>
   Matthias Brenzinger, of the University of Cologne in Germany,
who for the past year has led an investigation aimed at rating the
degree of danger faced by languages, said the scale of the problem
is immense. ``Most of the currently receding languages will
disappear without even being recorded,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Papua New Guinea, which boasts the richest diversity of
languages in the world, many young people prefer to communicate in
``tok psin,'' which literally means ``talk pigin'' English, than
the language of their elders, Dr. Levinson said. ``We know of many
cases of language replacement taking place wholesale,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   English is growing in popularity because many people believe
their children will be better off as a result. Spanish and Chinese
are growing largely for demographic reasons _ as a result of
expanding populations, Dr. Levinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Languages can also be lost more dramatically through war and
ethnic genocide, as well as mass migrations and cultural
imperialism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should we be worried? For all sorts of reasons, including
sentiment. We will have lost the products of human creativity and
the extent of language variation gives us insight into the nature
of ourselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   South American children who speak the Mayan language Tzeltal,
for instance, learn how to distinguish between north and south when
they are as young as four as a result of the way their speech
inherently relates the geographical position of objects being
discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Only rarely is a dying language saved. One of the most famous
examples is the Mohawk language spoken by the indigenous people who
live in the Quebec region of Canada. Linguists began working with
Mohawk-speakers in the early 1970s to codify spelling conventions
and syntax.
</P>
<P>
   Mohawk lessons were offered as part of the curriculum of
elementary schools in Quebec and now hundreds of children have
learned a language that would probably have died out by now. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 625-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
