</P>
<P>
   Matthias Brenzinger, of the University of Cologne in Germany,
who for the past year has led an investigation aimed at rating the
degree of danger faced by languages, said the scale of the problem
is immense. ``Most of the currently receding languages will
disappear without even being recorded,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Papua New Guinea, which boasts the richest diversity of
languages in the world, many young people prefer to communicate in
``tok psin,'' which literally means ``talk pigin'' English, than
the language of their elders, Dr. Levinson said. ``We know of many
cases of language replacement taking place wholesale,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   English is growing in popularity because many people believe
their children will be better off as a result. Spanish and Chinese
are growing largely for demographic reasons _ as a result of
expanding populations, Dr. Levinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Languages can also be lost more dramatically through war and
ethnic genocide, as well as mass migrations and cultural
imperialism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should we be worried? For all sorts of reasons, including
sentiment. We will have lost the products of human creativity and
the extent of language variation gives us insight into the nature
of ourselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   South American children who speak the Mayan language Tzeltal,
for instance, learn how to distinguish between north and south when
they are as young as four as a result of the way their speech
inherently relates the geographical position of objects being
discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Only rarely is a dying language saved. One of the most famous
examples is the Mohawk language spoken by the indigenous people who
live in the Quebec region of Canada. Linguists began working with
Mohawk-speakers in the early 1970s to codify spelling conventions
and syntax.
</P>
<P>
   Mohawk lessons were offered as part of the curriculum of
elementary schools in Quebec and now hundreds of children have
learned a language that would probably have died out by now. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
