<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIBURN-AMATEURS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMATEUR PIANO COMPETITION TAKES HEART _ AND BRAINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Van Cliburn has been a professional musician
virtually all his life, having been trained by his mother for a
performing career. But the renowned Fort Worth-based pianist is
also an amateur in at least one respect: He practices music that he
will never perform in public, such as the sonatas of Schubert and
the keyboard music of J.S. Bach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play music that I don't perform to hear the sounds from my
own fingers,'' he says. ``I play something that's close to my
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing music from the heart is what inspires participants in
the Cliburn Foundation-sponsored International Piano Competition
for Outstanding Amateurs,
</P>
<P>
   which begins Monday and runs through June 10 at Ed Landreth
Auditorium on the Texas Christian University campus in Fort Worth.
And Cliburn is fully in tune with the spiritual and emotional
aspect of playing for the love of music.
</P>
<P>
   Cliburn sees the amateur competition as reaffirming the appeal
and durability of classical music. ``Those whom we call amateurs
live their lives as missionaries for classical music,'' he said in
a recent telephone interview. ``That's terribly important. And it
proves that the future is secure for great music.''
</P>
<P>
   The missionaries participating in this year's amateur
competition represent a cross section of society and are a
remarkably accomplished group, numbering medical doctors, lawyers
and academics.
</P>
<P>
   James S. Catterall, a cognitive scientist and professor of
education and information studies at the University of California
at Los Angeles, says this isn't an accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get a lot of people over 35 who are accomplished
pianists, you're going to find that they are pretty accomplished at
other things, too,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   What may be surprising _ and certainly relevant, given the
credentials of many of the competitors _ is that playing the
keyboard has a stronger link to intelligence than any other form of
music-making, according to Catterall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The keyboard has a prominent geometry,'' he says. ``It is the
best for spatial, temporal reasoning _ ordering things in space and
time. It's lots better than computer training for this sort of
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four percent of the participants are professors of
medicine or health-care professionals at the doctoral level.
Attorneys, engineers, scientists and college professors are also
represented in substantial numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hawley, for example, is a professor of media technology
at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. He says that he is
energized when he is performing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, when I started practicing piano after not playing
for four years, I noticed how much more creative I was in all of my
work,'' Hawley says. ``And how out of balance I was when I wasn't
practicing.''
</P>
<P>
   Cliburn does not need statistical evidence to second Catterall's
view that music can be significant in the development of the mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a mental stimulus, in addition to its spiritual
aspect,'' Cliburn says. ``Music is one of the essential academic
subjects.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he adds: ``The great works are to be played by everyone.
There is a responsibility for everyone to know about great music.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though his training was focused on a professional career,
Cliburn says that music appreciation need not have an ulterior
motive.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a young person studies music, it should be approached not
from the standpoint of becoming a performer, but from the direction
of learning the depth of the music,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   This year's amateur event is the second in what will become a
biennial competition in Fort Worth. Last year's amateur inaugural
was so successful that it was decided to have the contest every
other year. To fit the competition into the Cliburn's quadrennial
cycle, and take advantage of the local and national interest,
Cliburn Foundation executive director Richard Rodzinski decided to
have the second amateur competition this year before switching to
every other year.
</P>
<P>
   This year's competition will demonstrate a number of
enhancements. The first-prize winner will be presented in recital
at the Hirshhorn Museum in Washington, D.C., on June 18, a little
over a week after the end of the competition.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to prizes of $2,000, $1,000 and $500 for the top
three winners, the best performances of baroque, classical,
romantic and modern works will win $250 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the basic concept of having an amateur contest is to
reward people who are dedicated to music, more awards means more
opportunities to reward,'' Rodzinski says.
</P>
<P>
   TICKET &AMP; SCHEDULE INFO:
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary round: Two sessions daily, 1 and 7:30 p.m.
Monday-Thursday
</P>
<P>
   Admission: $10 per session, $45 for the entire preliminary round
</P>
<P>
   Semifinal round: 1 and 7:30 p.m., June 9
</P>
<P>
   Admission: $20 per session, $35 for the entire semifinal round
</P>
<P>
   Finals and awards ceremony: 3 p.m. June 10
</P>
<P>
   Admission: $30
</P>
<P>
   The subscription price for all sessions is $105. All events are
at Ed Landreth Auditorium, University at Cantey on the campus of
Texas Christian University. Call 335-9000.
</P>
<P>
   PRIZES:
</P>
<P>
   First prize: $2,000
</P>
<P>
   Plus, a recital engagement at the Hirshhorn Museum in
Washington, D.C., on June 18.
</P>
<P>
   Also, tickets for the finals and official guest status at the
11th Van Cliburn International Piano Competition, June 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Second prize: $1,000
</P>
<P>
   Third prize: $500
</P>
<P>
   Press jury award:
</P>
<P>
   100-volume compact-disc set of ``Great Pianists of the 20th
Century''
</P>
<P>
   Audience award: 1 pair of Justin boots and a western hat
</P>
<P>
   Best performance of works from the baroque, classical, romantic
and modern eras: $250 each
</P>
<P>
   (Wayne Lee Gay covers classical music for the Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
