<HEADLINE>
LAS VEGAS PROVIDES REFUGE FOR DISSIDENT WRITERS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (This 425-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ANDREW GUMBEL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Las Vegas has a colorful history of offering
refuge _ to scam artists, mobsters, racketeers and the criminally
insane, for a start.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that explains why the city has been so ready to offer a
helping hand to an altogether different category of fugitive:
writers under threat from oppressive foreign governments.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas has just been named North America's first ``City of
Asylum'' _ the political sort of asylum, that is _ under a program
run by the International Parliament of Writers.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the largesse of local gambling moguls and other
private donors, authors and intellectuals persecuted in Sudan, say,
or Iran, or Serbia, will be able to live in the Nevada desert free
of charge for a year.
</P>
<P>
   What they will make of a city where it is almost impossible to
find a bookshop, much less a vibrant literary culture, remains to
be seen.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme was dreamed up by Wole Soyinka, the Nigerian Nobel
laureate and president of the International Parliament of Writers,
who received an honorary degree from the University of Nevada at
Las Vegas last year.
</P>
<P>
   He floated the idea past Richard Wiley, an English professor at
UNLV, who in turn contacted a chum who runs the Mandalay Bay casino
resort.
</P>
<P>
   Soon they had raised enough money to invite the first writer to
take up residence this autumn. The name of the recipient will be
announced soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The writer is rare who's never written purple prose. And Las
Vegas is purple prose, writ large,'' Soyinka said wryly as the
program was unveiled a few days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a rather perverse way, Las Vegas actually echoes or mirrors
the predicament of the writer. The writer creates, in effect, a
virtual society, a virtual community. If ever there was a virtual
city, it is Las Vegas.''
</P>
<P>
   The City of Asylum idea grew out of Salman Rushdie's predicament
in the shadow of the Iranian fatwa. Strasbourg offered Rushdie
asylum in 1993, an offer that was turned down but which
nevertheless led to other cities _ Barcelona, Venice, Berlin and
Mexico City _ making similar offers to other writers.
</P>
<P>
   If Las Vegas has been quick to embrace the idea, it is partly
because it is seeking respectability and a reputation that goes
beyond gambling and whoring.
</P>
<P>
   Not all its citizens approve, however. Lou Piccinnetti, a
security guard, told a local newspaper he thought traffic fines
should be reduced for low-income residents before money was
lavished on foreigners. ``What about the persecuted people here?''
he asked. ``Who's going to help us?'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 425-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
