<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-SALES-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HOME SALES DROP 5.8 PERCENT IN APRIL 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN VAMES   
 c. 2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sales of new homes dropped sharply in April to the lowest level
since November, echoing other evidence that have shown slowing home
sales across the country as mortgage rates continue to rise.
</P>
<P>
   New home sales fell 5.8 percent in April to a seasonally
adjusted 909,000 annual rate, the Commerce Department reported
Wednesday following an upwardly revised 5.8 percent pace in March.
Sales in April were significantly lower than the 3.2 percent drop
to a 937,000 annual pace that economists had been expecting,
according to a Reuters poll.
</P>
<P>
   While the data indicates that housing markets are feeling the
pinch of higher interest rates and the sell-off in technology
stocks, home sales continue to remain near historically high
levels. March, which has been revised from an originally-reported
4.5 percent pace of new home sales, was the second highest on
record.
</P>
<P>
   The news is likely to comfort economists and policy makers, who
have been looking for signs that the economy is slowing in response
the Federal Reserve's year-long effort to raise interest rates. But
anecdotal evidence indicates that the demand for homes in some of
the hottest U.S. markets is still outpacing supply, and that home
prices in those markets are still rising, even as sales are
slowing.
</P>
<P>
   But the new home sales data Wednesday provide some of the first
evidence that home prices may be moderating in response to slowing
sales. The Commerce Department also reported that the median sales
price for a new home dipped to $161,400 in April from $165,000 in
March.
</P>
<P>
   Most economists say higher mortgage rates are having the largest
influence on the slowing housing market, quelling demand as the
cost of financing goes up. According to mortgage giant Freddie Mac,
the Fed's most recent increase in short-term rates on May 16 pushed
mortgage rates sharply higher. The rate for a typical 30-year
fixed-rate mortgage stood at 8.62 percent last week, compared with
an average 8.15 percent for April, and 7.15 percent in May 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Other data Wednesday indicated that interest rates are also
having a broader effect on the economy. The Conference Board, a
private business research group, said its index of leading economic
indicators, a grouping of economic data designed to forecast future
economic activity, dipped 0.1 percent in April, following a 0.1
percent increase in March and a 0.3 percent decline in February.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
