<HEADER>
A0802 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ARAFAT-EMBARRASSED-IN     05-31 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARAFAT-EMBARRASSED-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARAFAT FIGHTS `LOSER' IMAGE AFTER HEZBOLLAH'S VICTORY  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (This 750-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By PHIL REEVES  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Almost a week after Israel's troops beat a hasty
retreat from Lebanon, Yasser Arafat has publicly acknowledged that
he faces growing political pressure to emulate the success of
Hezbollah's guerrilla forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hezbollah are being portrayed as heroes in the Arab world,
while the Palestinians look like losers,'' he reportedly told an
Israeli minister, Dalia Itzik, at a meeting in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   His remarks were made two weeks after more than a week of bloody
unrest _ the so-called ``Days of Rage'' _ in the West Bank and
Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   The unrest began as a protest over prisoners in Israeli jails
but grew to reflect deep frustration among young Palestinians over
the failure of Arafat and his team to secure sufficient results in
six years of peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   According to Israel's Ma'ariv newspaper, Arafat's comments were
unusually forthright. ``You have to understand what sort of
pressure is being placed on me by the public,'' he told Itzik, the
Israeli environment minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``My public perceives Hezbollah to be heroes who succeeded in
getting the IDF (Israel Defense Forces) out of Lebanon and believe
that that is the route we should take as well.'' He also stressed
that he was also under pressure from the Arab world to follow
Hezbollah's example.
</P>
<P>
   ``My situation is not simple,'' Arafat added, ``The pressure
being applied on me is coming from every direction. The Palestinian
people want to see results in terms of the release of prisoners. In
practice they see that nothing is moving.''
</P>
<P>
   This may be a ploy to bounce Israel into offering more
concessions during talks, due to be transferred back to the Middle
East from Stockholm. In this, the message is clear: If Ehud Barak,
Israel's premier, and his team continue to play hard ball, then the
process could collapse as the Palestinian public will not tolerate
more long delays and feeble results.
</P>
<P>
   The Jerusalem Post reported Tuesday that the Palestinian leader
has written to Bill Clinton complaining about the state of the
talks _ which he said were in an impasse _ and asking the U.S.
president to push for progress.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will have a chance of relaying these sentiments when he
meets Barak Thursday in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   But, while the Palestinians are unlikely to return to an armed
struggle to end the Israeli occupation of the lands, Arafat has
real cause to be worried about hardening public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that the TV pictures from Lebanon of Hezbollah
celebrations at the end of Israel's 22-year occupation _ watched
joyously both by Palestinians in the occupied territories and
Israel's 1.2 million Arabs _ were embarrassing to him and his team.
</P>
<P>
   His dilemma has been deepened by being the target of criticism
from Hezbollah's leader, Sheikh Hassan Nasrallah, who told al-Wasat
newspaper that he believed ``that the Palestine Question can't be
settled in the way matters are being dealt with at the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The struggle of the Palestinian people has been going on for
more than 50 years,'' he said, ``Fifty years is a long time;
leaderships may grow tired. If so, they must stand aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``But only yesterday,'' he continued, ``we saw on TV how the
youths of Palestine were confronting the Israeli soldiers with
stones. This is a generation that is prepared for sacrifice; a
generation that has not been exhausted despite the difficult and
harsh conditions it is living under.''
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations with Israel have limped along _ another deadline
next month is sure to be missed _ producing few results that
satisfy Palestinian demands.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has proved a master at presenting himself on the
international arena as a peacemaker, but Jewish settlement building
has continued on the West Bank. He tends to characterize any offers
to the Palestinians as ``concessions.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has not found Barak easy to deal with, as another remark
to Itzak revealed. ``Oh, how I miss Yitzhak Rabin. With him, a
fight was a fight, and spat was a spat, a date was a date and a
word was a word.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the example of Hezbollah looms over him, life is harder
still for the aging Palestinian leader. In the past, Arafat _ who
has some 17 security organizations attached to his Palestinian
Authority _ has ruthlessly cracked down on internal dissent. From
now on, it may not be quite so easy. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
