<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-VOTEBUYING-0601-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WILL WELFARE BE USED TO COERCE KEY VOTES IN HISTORIC MEXICAN
ELECTION?
 &HT;    (550&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A month before the most bitterly fought
presidential election in Mexico's recent history, the ruling party
is under increasing fire for using federal welfare programs to lure
or coerce votes for its candidate.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo told farmers in
Morelos state that subsidies and other assistance ``get to where
they need to get, to your hands, without intermediaries,
bureaucrats or political manipulation.''
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo's comments seemed designed to quell complaints that some
bureaucrats are threatening to withhold subsidies to the poor
unless recipients pledge to vote for Mexico's 71-year-old
Institutional Revolutionary Party, the PRI, on July 2.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Zedillo's speech, however, a top campaign advisor
to the PRI's candidate bluntly said in a national magazine article
published last Sunday that the PRI is ``at war'' and will use those
programs to fight to keep power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, federal social programs are carried out by the PRI, and
their aim is to win the presidency,'' said veteran PRI politician
Manuel Bartlett, who joined the campaign of PRI candidate Francisco
Labastida Ochoa shortly after it was widely perceived that
Labastida had lost a nationally televised debate in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no reason to deny it . . . ,'' Bartlett told Milenio
magazine. ``We are at war and if the public employees there are PRI
sympathizers they should defend the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett, a former Puebla state governor, ran unsuccessfully
against Labastida in a PRI primary election last year. He is
considered one of the old-fashioned PRI strongmen called
``dinosaurs.'' Although Bartlett denies it, he is widely suspected
of using his position as a cabinet member in charge of elections in
1988 to engineer fraud on behalf of the PRI's then-presidential
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI, which has controlled Mexico's presidency for seven
decades, has a history of doling out gifts of food and building
supplies to the poor before elections.
</P>
<P>
   This year's race comes in the wake of democratic reforms to make
elections fairer and cleaner. But opposition parties say they are
still concerned about PRI activists in remote areas attempting to
coerce votes by threatening to cut government subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 percent of Mexican voters live in rural areas, which
are a stronghold of PRI support.
</P>
<P>
   One program under scrutiny is Progresa, a family welfare program
started by Zedillo in 1997 that offers cash payments to poor
mothers who keep their children in school.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2.6 million families _ 14 million individuals _ are
enrolled in the program. Several publications in Mexico have
reported complaints by women in rural Veracruz and Chiapas states
that program promoters are warning them to vote for the PRI or
their benefits will be cut.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida aide Javier Trevino challenged critics to prove that
manipulation of social programs has really happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't stop investing in social programs,'' he said, just
because an election is about to happen.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Labastida campaign's position is that ``we don't
need any kind of support of activities outside the law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe what (Bartlett) was referring to is that the government
of President Zedillo has made a commitment to the Mexican people
with these programs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Recent surveys have found that about 40 percent of recipients of
federal subsidy and welfare benefits identify them with the PRI and
not the government.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, opposition politicians in the state of Mexico
discovered a storage area rented by a local PRI-dominated
government that was filled with construction materials a PRI
candidate was handing out to poor farmers in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to that, the PRI was fined $125,000 because its mayoral
candidate, Jesus Silva-Herzog, a former ambassador to the United
States, was handing out government-owned milk in containers with
his photo and the party emblem.
</P>
<P>
   Silva was not found personally guilty because the incident
occurred in February before he had officially registered his
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' e-mail is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.wola.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
