<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Many students entering college are being warned that their
personal computers must have ISA/PCI Ethernet adapters and that
networked PC's must be equipped with 10Base-T Ethernet adapter
cards, cables and communications software. What do these terms
mean?
</P>
<P>
   A. Many of those terms relate to networking _ specifically, to
getting the computer onto the university network.
</P>
<P>
   Although standards vary, most major colleges and universities
have Ethernet networks, which provide much faster connections to
the Internet than does access through a typical dial-up Internet
service provider.
</P>
<P>
   Ethernet is a local area network protocol that was first
developed in the 1970s and is now one of the most common networking
methods used by corporations and colleges. Many types of computers
can use it, including Windows PC's and Macintosh machines.
</P>
<P>
   Ethernet can transmit data at up to 10 million bits per second,
which is much faster than a 56K (56 kilobits per second) modem.
</P>
<P>
   The term ``10BaseT'' refers to the specific type of Ethernet
network and the cables it uses to connect the computer to that
network. Newer versions, called Fast Ethernet, can transfer data at
speeds up to 100 million bits per second and are also referred to
as 100BaseT networks.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to connect to Ethernet networks is not standard in
some computers.
</P>
<P>
   Most new Macs come with built-in Ethernet capability, but
computers running Windows usually need an Ethernet adapter card
installed. Some computer manufacturers will sell you a machine with
the card already installed, or you can buy an adapter card from a
computer store.
</P>
<P>
   ISA/PCI refers to the slot on the computer's motherboard that
the card snaps into.
</P>
<P>
   Older computers usually have ISA slots, but the PCI standard has
become the norm in newer machines. The Ethernet card should come
with the software that will let the PC communicate with the
network. You can also find the proper Ethernet cables at your local
computer store. The cable packaging may refer to the cables as
having ``RJ-45'' connectors, which is just a reference to the plug
type on each end.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the communications software requirements, these will
probably vary even more depending on the particular college and the
computing platform (Windows or Macintosh). Most colleges will
provide on request the specific information for what they prefer.
</P>
<P>
   You might try looking at the college's Web site for the
preferred standards, as well as at a Frequently Asked Questions
section focusing on hardware and software standards. If your future
freshman doesn't yet have a computer to take to school, you might
also ask if the campus bookstore or an affiliated outlet sells the
approved equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is there any way I can tell what Web sites do with the
personal information I give them?
</P>
<P>
   A. Most commercial Web sites that ask for personal information
have a link to their privacy policy at the bottom of the home page,
which should tell you what the site is doing with your data and who
the site might share the information with.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is not a complete record of all the Web sites out
there, Enonymous.com's analysts have a database rating privacy
practices of 30,000 sites at www.privacyratings.org.
</P>
<P>
   The site offers a directory of sites that have high privacy
ratings, and you can check to see if a particular site has been
rated by typing its URL into a box on the Privacy Ratings page.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of good sites for general information on
online privacy, including legislative measures.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to keep up on the issues, try the Electronic Privacy
Information Center (www.epic.org), the Online Privacy Alliance
(www.privacyalliance.org) or Americans for Computer Privacy
(www.computerprivacy.org).
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd St.,
New York, N.Y. 10036-3959, or by e-mail to Q&AMP;A(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
