<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PICKING TILES AND PLANNING CAREFULLY TO REPLACE COUNTER TOPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One way to refinish a kitchen countertop where the plastic
laminate is worn is to resurface it with ceramic tile.
</P>
<P>
   First, check the condition of the laminate carefully. The
surface must be flat, relatively smooth and firmly bonded to the
counter. Once you have determined that the laminate bond is secure,
you can pick out the tiles you want for the counter. Avoid choosing
unglazed, porous tiles or tiles with a high-gloss glaze. Unglazed
tiles stain easily and will be hard to maintain. High-gloss tiles
will scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Ceramic tiles are available in a wide range of sizes and colors.
Most do-it- yourselfers will find that the standard
four-and-a-quarter-inch square ceramic tiles are easiest to work
with because they are a convenient size and they have spacing tabs
to ensure uniform grout joints. To determine how many tiles you
need, calculate the area of the counter top, including the
backsplash, and add 15 percent to cover cutting mistakes, breakage
and spares for future repairs.
</P>
<P>
   You will also need a latex or acrylic thin-set adhesive to bond
the tiles to the counter, and an unsanded grout to fill the gaps
between the tiles. Consult the specifications on the packages to
determine the required amounts for each, or check with the dealer
at the tile store.
</P>
<P>
   It is likely that you will have to cut some tiles and shape
others to fit around the sink opening. You will need a tile cutter
and a nibbler for these tasks. These can be rented from the tile
dealer or from a tool rental store. You will also need a notched
trowel and a grout float.
</P>
<P>
   Start by removing the sink and fixtures. First, shut off the
water supply to the faucets. Then disconnect the supply lines and
remove the fixtures. Loosen the sink tailpiece and the retaining
clips under the sink, then lift the sink from the counter.
</P>
<P>
   Wash the counter top with a mild detergent to remove all dirt
and grease, then sand the surface with 120-grit sandpaper. The
sanding will roughen the laminate surface and create a ''tooth''
for the tile adhesive to bond with. Use a damp cloth to clean all
dust from the surface.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest part of any tile installation is planning the layout
so the tiles will look symmetrical. Since the sink is the focal
point of the counter top, the layout should be centered on it. Lay
a row of tiles along the front edge of the sinkhole, making sure
the row is centered on the sinkhole.
</P>
<P>
   Use a pencil to place a mark on the counter at one end of the
row. This will be the starting point for the layout. Use a framing
square to extend the mark to the backsplash. Lay a row of tiles
along this new line, then repeat this operation on the other side
of the sinkhole.
</P>
<P>
   Next lay a row of tiles around the perimeter of the sink. If
they extend over the sinkhole, mark the overlapping material on the
underside of each tile, then cut them to fit the opening. Use the
tile cutter to cut straight pieces and the nibbler to break away
small portions to fit the corners. You may also have to cut the
tiles that fit against the backsplash.
</P>
<P>
   When all the tiles are cut to size, you can begin the
installation. First, nail a temporary wooden straightedge, called a
batten, to the edge of the counter. This will serve as a guide for
aligning the first row of tiles. Mix the adhesive according to the
package directions, then let the mixture stand for about 15 minutes
to develop stronger bonding power.
</P>
<P>
   Spread the adhesive with the flat side of the trowel, then flip
the trowel over and use the notched side to comb the adhesive in a
uniformly rigid pattern. Begin setting the tiles at the front edge,
starting at your pencil mark; then continue to tile the entire
counter. When you place the tiles along the backsplash, be sure to
align them with the rest of the counter tiles. After all the tiles
are in, place a piece of plywood (about 12 inches by 12 inches) on
top of the tiles and tap the board with a rubber mallet. This will
seat the tiles firmly in the adhesive.
</P>
<P>
   Allow at least 24 hours for the adhesive to set before applying
the grout. Mix the grout according to the package directions and
spread it across the face of the tiles with the grout float. Hold
the float at a shallow angle to force the grout into the gaps
between the tiles. Let the grout set for about 15 minutes, then
wipe away any residue with a damp cloth. When the grout has had
time to dry completely, apply a grout sealer with a small artist's
brush.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 1559EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
