<HEADLINE>
EARTHBOUND KITE IS A SOARING LEGACY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARY ROGERS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Manny Estrada made his way happily through
the tables in the ballroom at the Best Western Inn. It was prom
night, so Manny wore a tuxedo and a proud smile. He carried an
impressive bouquet of red roses wrapped in green paper.
</P>
<P>
   Almost shyly, he stopped here and there to hand a long-stemmed
blossom to each of ``his girls.'' Manny is the only man in the
Masonic Home and School's Class of 2000. There are six young women
graduates, and Manny had a rose for each of them, but the flowers
were not the only remembrance he would present that Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   At that early hour, Manny still possessed the treasure: a box
kite with no string attached. He had safeguarded it for months, but
before the banquet ended and the dancing began he would pass it on,
just as others before him had done for 25 springs.
</P>
<P>
   This small kite has become a touchstone for the young men of the
Masonic Home and School, a century-old facility on Fort Worth's
south side that offers shelter and a sense of family to more than
100 youngsters from ages 4 to 19.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, during the annual Junior Senior Banquet, the kite is
handed from a senior man to a junior man. It is a reminder that
each is expected to climb high, to fly with no strings attached,
never tethered to the hurts of yesterday. ...... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The wooden dowels are painted red now, and the brittle paper
once singed by a dormitory fire has been replaced by sheer cloth.
Each junior man who receives the kite keeps it through the year.
Then, just before graduation, he attaches his senior card to the
thin fabric and gives it away to a friend or a brother.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the young men who attended this year's banquet and prom
didn't know that the kite was flown only once, and then but
briefly, but Dan Cloud knows very well.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, Dan was a senior at the Masonic Home and School. It
was, he remembered, a time when ``50 cents was the whole world.''
He built the kite because he didn't have one _ and because he likes
to build things.
</P>
<P>
   Dan, now of Granbury, used dowels ``liberated from the wood shop
and butcher paper from the school cafeteria;'' when he was
finished, the kite looked perfect but was too heavy to fly.
</P>
<P>
   Try as he might, Dan could not make the kite lift into the air.
It remained earthbound, its destiny never fulfilled _ until one
stormy afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   A malignant wind boiled across the sky. Weather-watchers
predicted tornadoes. The heavens turned an ominous green.
</P>
<P>
   The kite was the perfect match for the swirling gusts of wind.
Dan held the string and the little box kite raced erratically into
the stormy sky, dipping and twisting, riding briefly on the gale
like an eagle riding the updrafts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't last long, but it did fly a short distance,'' Dan
recalled. He laughed, a small rumble of delight rising through
layers of memory.
</P>
<P>
   That year, at the Junior/Senior Banquet, Dan presented the kite
to his brother and the next year his brother passed it to another,
and so it has been each year since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder how many of those boys have tried to fly it,'' Dan
mused. After years of civil engineering courses, time in the
construction industry, a job producing filter elements for
industrial use; after marriage and children; disappointments and
successes, Dan knows why the kite wouldn't fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was too much wing for the mast,'' he explained. He
needed more paper to lift the heavy burden of wood. Dan knows that
now, but then he knew only that the kite seemed married to the
soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I built it today, it would fly,'' he said, echoing an
oft-repeated lesson of life.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
