<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0861 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-N     05-31 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON A SHOE QUEST FROM CLICKS TO MORTAR 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I am not going to waste anyone's time here with a
long theoretical discussion about the relationship of new shoes to
self-esteem. I think we can agree that the right pair will really
improve your life, at least for a day or two. That is why I got so
excited a few weeks ago in Bloomingdale's, where I saw these really
adorable Tommy Hilfiger blue plaid sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   I believe that the industry term for this style of shoe, which
resembles a bedroom slipper because it has no back, is ``mule.''
(Am I kidding? I know very well the technical term for this and
every other style of shoe ever invented, and I would be happy, if
called upon, to talk extemporaneously for a couple of hours about
the subtle differences among mules and slides and thongs.)
</P>
<P>
   Picture these plaid sneakers with denim capri pants. I did, as I
caressed one _ I mean, tested the quality of its stitching. Then I
tried to flag down one of the 50 million salesclerks stampeding
through the shoe department as though they were all late for a
Bruce Springsteen concert in another state.
</P>
<P>
   Years of shopping for shoes in Bloomingdale's have trained me to
persevere. Sure enough, after about 10 minutes, a clerk reluctantly
met my gaze. No matter what he may say later under oath, I did not,
to the best of my recollection, tap him forcefully on the shoulder
with the display sneaker to get his attention. I admit, however,
that I may have used an ``urgent'' tone to persuade him to help me.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it didn't matter: my size was sold out. In the past
I would have accepted that bleak verdict, and after a period of
mourning I would have tried to forget the feelings I had for the
sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   But I knew that somewhere in the world was a pair of those blue
plaid sneakers in my size. A complicating factor was that I have
long counted myself among the majority of Internet shoppers who say
they are reluctant to buy clothing online because they cannot see
or touch or try it on first. But in the tug-of-war between the
sneakers and my long-held shopping convictions, the sneakers won.
</P>
<P>
   So I went right to Nordstrom.com, which claims that its
collection of 20 million pairs is the ``largest selection of shoes
on earth.'' (That may well be true, but if there isn't one pair
among the 20 million that is the right one for you, who cares?)
</P>
<P>
   A search for ``Tommy Hilfiger'' yielded a red sneaker-mule
hybrid that looked familiar. I clicked on it, and learned that it
came in many colors, including ``multi.'' A quick call to the
toll-free customer service line at Nordstrom.com confirmed that
multi meant blue plaid. So I ordered the shoes, which cost an
amount that my husband, if he is reading this, need not bother to
look up online.
</P>
<P>
   Would they fit? With the sweet rush of a highly successful
shopping experience coursing through my veins, I decided that it
didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, I visit online retailers that I know, retailers
with real stores where I can return unwanted items. I ordered six
T-shirts (on sale) from Gap.com and a pair of denim capri pants
from Jcrew.com.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, packages started arriving. The plaid sneakers fit
(we are inseparable). Ditto the capri pants. The T-shirts I
returned to a Gap store three minutes away.
</P>
<P>
   The convenience reminded me of something I hadn't thought of
since childhood: Ruby's Department Store. In the Midwestern town
where I grew up, a van from Ruby's would pull into the driveway
every autumn. Inside was a selection of potential ``school
clothes'' for me and my three brothers. My mother, who was too
smart to take four small children into a real store, kept whatever
fit and sent back the rest.
</P>
<P>
   That level of personal service did not seem unusual back in the
1960s, a decade when dry cleaners and butchers and fruit sellers
stopped weekly at the homes in our middle-class neighborhood. But
in the inflationary years that followed, such deliveries became a
luxury. Most vendors gravitated in one of two different directions,
either providing a high level of customer service or low prices.
</P>
<P>
   But now the Internet makes it possible to get both. For one
thing, you can quickly compare prices online. ``But at the same
time it is a customized medium,'' said Joseph B. Pine, co-author of
``The Experience Economy'' (Harvard Business School Press, 1999).
``Anything you can digitize, you can customize how a product is
presented. You can even customize the product itself.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not naive enough to think that I will shop for all my
clothes online in the future. Kathryn Olson, executive vice
president of marketing at Nordstrom.com, predicted that it would
depend on my mood. Some Nordstrom customers, she said, browse first
in a store, then go home and order several sizes of an item online.
They try the clothes on at home at their leisure, then return
unwanted apparel to the store.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you may shop online for convenience,'' Olson said.
``Other times you may want the in-store environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, I got both. I considered a pair of pale green silk
shantung ballet flats at Talbots.com. My size was sold out, but the
Web site offered 10 percent off another style. Instead, I used the
online chat function to pester the site _ I mean, ask nicely _ to
find out if I could have the discount if I ordered the ballet flats
in a slightly larger size. Yes, a customer service representative
wrote back.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that it would break my heart if they did not fit, I
jumped up and drove five minutes to a nearby Talbots store, tried
on the flats (the only color in the store was a less attractive
beige) and found that the larger ones in fact fit better. So I
drove home and ordered them online.
</P>
<P>
   The flats are back-ordered and will not be shipped before June
9, luckily. By then I may be ready to betray the sneakers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
