<HEADER>
A0863 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      05-31 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LESLIE LAND    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Embrace of the Lespedeza
</P>
<P>
   Q. Two years ago, I planted two small bush clovers (Lespedeza
thunbergii). Last summer, they grew well over six feet tall and
produced gorgeous purple blossoms in August and September, drowning
a rose bush next to them. This spring, all those branches are dead
and new growth is coming up from the base. Will it be just as huge
this summer? If so, should I move the rose bush or can I trim back
the lespedeza?
</P>
<P>
   A. With any luck, your plants will indeed be just as large this
year. Or maybe a bit larger. Other than that, expect the same
performance. Whether it's too big a show for the rose depends on
the rose and on your appetite for crawling around at the base of
the lespedeza.
</P>
<P>
   If the rose bush is small or prone to fungus, it should be
moved. If it's medium to large, and robust, it probably won't
suffer long-term harm from a late lespedeza embrace, especially if
those loving arms are fewer than nature intended.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the lespedezas should be thinned rather than
trimmed. Remove up to a third of the shoots from each clump,
cutting them off right at the base. If the cut shoots keep growing,
cut them again. The less-dense lespedezas will still be tall and
weep gracefully over their neighbor, but they'll be too light and
lacy for any serious smothering.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, the words bush clover can terrify anyone
familiar with your plants' evil cousin, the highly invasive Chinese
lespedeza (L. cuneata). L. thunbergii isn't worry-free, but it's
usually less threatening to the surrounding countryside. It's also
inclined to be more tender than generally advertised, though
individual plants have survived as far north as Maine.
</P>
<P>
   L. thunbergii is available from Plant Delights Nursery, 9241
Sauls Road, Raleigh, N.C. 27603; (919) 772-4794. Catalog: 10
postage stamps or a box of chocolates. It's also available from
Avant Gardens, 710 High Hill Road, North Dartmouth, Mass. 02747;
(508) 998-8819. Catalog: $3, refundable with order.
</P>
<P>
   Mulch, Rain and Rot
</P>
<P>
   Q. Our vegetable garden in the upper Hudson Valley suffered
badly in last summer's drought, so this year we mulched the lettuce
and peas with straw as soon as they came up. We also put a thick
layer of it around the peppers and tomatoes. But now we're afraid
all the recent rain will lead to problems with rot. Should we take
the mulch off again and allow the garden to dry out a bit?
</P>
<P>
   A. Think about straw mulch the way you're supposed to think of
stock funds: Apply the money wisely, then leave it alone.
</P>
<P>
   Cool-weather crops like lettuce and peas should be mulched
early. The insulating layer of straw will keep the soil around
their roots nicely chilly. Hot-weather crops like tomatoes and
peppers, on the other hand, don't like cold feet. They should not
be mulched (or ideally, even planted) until the soil is thoroughly
warmed. If you have to set them in cool soil, mulch with a thin,
dark, porous weed barrier, ideally a biodegradable one.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange straw around tomatoes, peppers, eggplants and okra after
the soil is well warmed but before it's hot. If you used a barrier
at planting time, just pile the mulch on top.
</P>
<P>
   Once the mulch is in place, close to but not touching the
plants, don't mess with it unless you see rotting stems, moldy
leaves or an invasion of slugs. You put it on to help hold that
spring rain in the ground. If you move it to let the garden dry
out, that's just what the garden will do, and when the rainless
weeks of summer come, you will be sorry you didn't stay the course.
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 West
43rd Street, New York 10036, or by e-mail to
gardening(at)nytimes.com. Those of general interest will be
published. Unpublished questions cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
