<P>
   For Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GRANDPARENTS-RIGHTS (Undated) _ With the divorce rate climbing
and social problems such as drug abuse shattering families, more
than 2.5 million grandparents in the United States now find
themselves raising their children's children. But there are also
numerous grandparents fearful of losing their grandchildren when
parents split, resulting in a burgeoning rights movement. By KIM
COBB.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-PARDON (Austin, Texas) _ Gov. George W. Bush pardons
convicted rapist A.B. Butler, who spent 17 years in prison before
DNA tests showed him innocent of the attack. By EVAN MOORE and JOHN
GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-OIL-WELLS (Austin, Texas) _ A report prepared by energy
industry representatives and large landowners urges Texas to
toughen its oversight of oil and gas producers. The report says lax
oversight has let too many companies abandon wells without properly
plugging them, threatening aquifers and leaving the state to deal
with the orphaned wells. By RUSSELL GOLD.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-EMISSIONS (Austin, Texas) _ The Texas Natural Resource
Conservation Commission approves adopting auto emission standards
favored by the auto industry. The decision goes against the
standards advocated by Gov. George W. Bush and environmentalists,
who sought tougher California emission standards. By BILL DAWSON.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-EUROPE (Lisbon, Portugal) _ President Clinton says he is
willing to share missile defense technology with friendly nations,
a message he will take to his first meeting with Russian President
Vladimir Putin. Clinton also discusses Middle East peace prospects
with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-MENTAL-HEALTH (Washington) _ Vice President Al Gore and his
wife Tipper unveil a mental health care initiative. Mrs. Gore has
suffered from depression and is a mental health advocate, and the
vice president is trying to convey a mellower image in response to
criticism that he has attacked George W. Bush without making
significant counterproposals. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-NUKES (Undated) _ Even as he considers reductions in the
nuclear arsenal, George W. Bush says that as president he would
urge Congress to increase spending on defense research and
development by $20 billion over the next five years to develop the
``peacekeeping'' weapons of the future. By CLAY ROBINSON.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HERSH-MCCAFFREY (Washington) _ Pulitzer-Prize winning journalist
Seymour Hersh defends his controversial New Yorker article in which
he alleges that retired Army Gen. Barry McCaffrey ordered an
unprovoked attack against retreating Iraqi soldiers two days after
a cease-fire was announced in the 1991 Persian Gulf War. The
article also alleges that U.S. forces under McCaffrey's command
opened fire on some 380 Iraqi prisoners. The Army denies both
allegations and the White House has attacked the article. By ERIC
ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   CONLEY-SPELLING (Washington) _ Sean Conley, 12, a reserved
seventh-grader from Newark, Calif., advances to Thursday's final
rounds of the 73rd National Spelling Bee here after correctly
spelling nyctalopia, discomfiture and floppety. By JUDY HOLLAND.
(1stLd-Writethru already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CRAIG-SPELLING (Washington) _ Vicki Craig, 14, an eighth grader
at Bradley Middle School in San Antonio competes on the opening day
of the 73d National Spelling Bee. Vicki will have to spell three
words correctly to make it to Thursday's final rounds. By AUSTIN
ZALKIN.
</P>
<P>
   MOORE-SPELLING (Washington) _ Michael Moore, 12, a sixth grader
at Crockett Elementary School in Midland, Texas, tries his luck in
today's National Spelling Bee, hoping to make it to Thursday's
final rounds. By AUSTIN ZALKIN.
</P>
<P>
   MILLER-SPELLING (Washington) _ Alison Miller, 14, a
home-schooled student from Niskayuna, N.Y., outside Albany,
competes this afternoon in the National Spelling Bee, seeking to
make the finals on Thursday. By AUSTIN ZALKIN.
</P>
<P>
   MARTINEZ-SPELLING (Washington) _ Christy Lynn Martinez, 13, an
eighth-grader at the Crossroads Christian Institute in Laredo,
Texas, says she is excited about entering the 73rd National
Spelling Bee. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
</TEXT>
