<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0866 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-FARMS-TOURISM-BOS &LR;      05-31 1325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARMS-TOURISM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGRI-TOURISM TAKES ROOT IN VERMONT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Vt. - Bill Adams was 4 when he took the job of
shifting gears on a tractor. He was a teenager when he took control
of the family farm and 45 when he despaired of it, selling off his
herd of milk cows and ultimately hoisting his powerful farmer's
body into the cab of an 18-wheeler.
</P>
<P>
   And he was 55 before he was reborn as talent.
</P>
<P>
   But here he was, in a John Deere cap and overalls, regaling
visitors from a Baltimore senior center with stories about killing
frosts and hired hands. Astride a tractor, hauling a dozen tourists
in sun visors and crepe-soled shoes, he extinguished his cigarette
on a rotating tire with two enormous
</P>
<P>
   dirt-caked fingers.
</P>
<P>
   He has been photographed chewing on a piece of hay. His daughter
Jill, who pays him by the hour to accompany tourists around the
farm, said her father has adjusted well to his new role as an
entertainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a couple of years doing sleigh rides, I think my dad's
accent thickened a little,'' said Jill Adams, who greets tour buses
in a checked apron with a baby on her hip, introducing herself as
the farmer's daughter. ``His accent thickened, and his body
language became a little bit more pronounced, and then he became
this Vermont character.''
</P>
<P>
   Six generations after purchasing this land, the Adams family has
become a pioneer of ``agritourism,'' or, as it is known in some
states, ``agri-tainment.''
</P>
<P>
   In Vermont, whose constellation of small dairy farms has
struggled to survive &UR;  &LR; in an age of more efficient corporate
operations, some are looking to
</P>
<P>
   agritourism as one of the last hopes for preserving the state's
quintessential &UR;  &LR; landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, legislation written by Representative Bernard
Sanders, the &UR;  &LR; Vermont Independent, doubled the nation's agritourism
program to $2 million, &UR;  &LR; with assurances that at least $500,000 of
that will go to Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   And a growing number of venturesome farmers are swapping ideas
from their &UR;  &LR; agritourism wish list - a Napa Valley-style Cheese
Trail, corporate &UR;  &LR; agricultural retreats, statewide distribution of
decorative outhouses, &UR;  &LR; cornfields shaved into eye-catching
patterns, and the mobilization on the &UR;  &LR; front porches of hobby farms
of genuine, out-of-work, cranky Vermont farmers.
</P>
<P>
   It's all right with Bill Adams, who sees public relations as
just another &UR;  &LR; of the sidelines required to make ends meet on this
rocky land, like his &UR;  &LR; father's sawmill and his great-grandfather's
sap-gathering tub.
</P>
<P>
   ``The simple old life is gone. It don't fit in today's world,''
he said. ``Our &UR;  &LR; crop is fleecing the city folks.''
</P>
<P>
   It was about 80 years ago that expanding rail links and an
Eastern longing &UR;  &LR; for frontier experiences came together to form a
new kind of recreation: the &UR;  &LR; dude ranch. Agritourism's proponents
say 21st-century consumer culture has &UR;  &LR; planted the seed of a new,
but equally potent, longing - the desire to stay on &UR;  &LR; or visit a
farm and learn where food comes from, to handle the earth, and
to &UR;  &LR; touch live animals.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Southern Maine's Mark Lapping, who has
researched &UR;  &LR; agri-tourism as a route to rural development, sees a
potential for deep &UR;  &LR; relaxation as urbanites ``adapt to a different
calendar and a different &UR;  &LR; expression of time.'' They rise at 4 or 5
a.m. and fall into bed at 8 p.m., and &UR;  &LR; the time in between is
marked not by the clock but by chores.
</P>
<P>
   When Adams Farm first opened its doors to day-trippers eight
years ago - &UR;  &LR; last year the number rose to 35,000 - it took Jill
Adams a few seasons to &UR;  &LR; realize that for city dwellers, the daily
rhythms she grew up with carried the &UR;  &LR; allure of the exotic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought people would want to come see the baby
animals,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``I had no idea they would find our life and our family
fascinating. It's just &UR;  &LR; been a process of listening - of people
coming up to you and touching you and &UR;  &LR; looking at you with a deep
longing in their eyes and saying, `I wish I could &UR;  &LR; do this.' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``But even with federal funds disbursed for physical
improvements like &UR;  &LR; bathroom facilities and milking-parlor viewing
stands, the fledgling hybrid of &UR;  &LR; farming and tourism has met with
skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, New England farmers are typically stretched to
their limits &UR;  &LR; with physical labor, and ``the last thing you want to
do is be nice all the &UR;  &LR; time,'' said Bob Townsend, who has pushed
agri-tourism for the past seven years with the University of
Vermont extension service.
</P>
<P>
   Others wonder whether the most vigorous, well-meaning urbanites
could integrate themselves into the life of a real farm - and if
they could, whether it would feel like entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not terribly sure,'' Lapping said, ``that there is enough
happening on a farm to keep contemporary Americans really happy for
oodles and oodles of time.''
</P>
<P>
   But at Adams Farm, as at agri-tourism ventures across the state,
there's an urgent, almost desperate message behind the down-home
showmanship. Vermont is home to 1,700 of New England's remaining
3,000 dairy farms, and many of those businesses are driving
themselves into debt, fighting for survival. Vermont's
</P>
<P>
   Washington delegation has battled to save the Northeast Dairy
Compact, which sets minimum prices for milk in an effort to keep
farms afloat financially.
</P>
<P>
   On an individual level, Vermont dairy farmers feel a passionate
need to communicate to city dwellers that they should take an
interest in where food comes from and who spends their lifetimes
producing it. As the Baltimore tourists gazed up at him from the
wagon on a recent afternoon, Bill Adams told the story of the year
he gave up his herd in a government buyout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It finally dawned on me, there's got to be a better way to
make money than to lose $100 a day,'' he said. ``Now I do what
comes naturally to me: Nothing. I'm not part of the milk surplus
problem today.''
</P>
<P>
   The tourists laughed.
</P>
<P>
   When his daughter watches him riff about the years he has spent
trying to make a living, she sees a man whose heart has been broken
by the price of milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up, milk was liquid gold to him. Now he's trucking
this fancy produce - that's what he calls it - the strawberries
that are six to a container. These are precious, precious things
right now,'' she said. ``He'll say, `Over there in the corner, all
the milk is stacked in a heap. You don't even waste your time
counting it. It's not worth anything.'''
</P>
<P>
   While farmers wait for a national initiative to save the family
farm, Sanders said, Vermont should take another route,
acknowledging the contribution that farmers already make to
tourism, the state's second-biggest industry. When National
Geographic listed 50 must-see spots recently, Vermont was the only
entire state designated - largely, Sanders said, because of the
picturesque working landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for agri-tourism is accommodating and attracting a
large number of tourists without destroying the authentic quality
they so admire. Restrooms are a major problem, for example, as are
parking lots. And many tourist attractions, like the salaried
appearance of old-time farmers, require the artificial ratcheting
up of quaintness.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell Rasor, a Falmouth writer at work on a book about
landscapes called ``Twisted Pastoralism,'' compared the agritourism
idea to Maine's ``beauty strips'' - 100-foot stands of trees that
keep daytripping canoers from seeing
</P>
<P>
   the clear-cut forests behind them.
</P>
<P>
   But then tourism, Mark Lapping observed, has never been about
gritty truth-telling.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad, who is the certainly the smartest man I've ever met,
will put on a very thick Vermont accent because you're going to pay
a dollar more a gallon for maple syrup,'' said Lapping, who grew up
on a dairy farm in Jericho. ``It's like so much in life. It's
marketing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
