<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MONDAY NIGHT' TALENT SEARCH IS STALLED BY A LACK OF STAR
ANALYSTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the 10 weeks since Boomer Esiason was fired from ``Monday
Night Football,'' ABC has offered no information about
replacement(s).
</P>
<P>
   Don Ohlmeyer, the producer, has cheerfully refused to stoke
speculation. When last seen, Howard Katz, the president of ABC
Sports, was waving the starter's flag at the Indianapolis 500 on
Sunday, leading to speculation that he was interviewing Bobby
Knight for Esiason's job.
</P>
<P>
   Current rumors have Rush Limbaugh out, Sterling Sharpe of ESPN
in and Dan Fouts, an ABC college football analyst, being
considered. Ohlmeyer said: ``We've talked to a lot of people and
auditioned a good number of people.'' Is the Star Search over?
``Maybe not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Who besides the play-by-play announcer Al Michaels is in? Well,
Hank Williams Jr., who sings ``Monday Night's'' theme song.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably,'' Ohlmeyer said.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's post-Esiason search has been vexed by the absence of
available superstar analysts, and the inability to find escape
clauses in the contracts of big names like Fox's Terry Bradshaw,
Howie Long and Cris Collinsworth, whom Fox made action figures of
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They contacted my representatives, but I'm under contract,''
Long said. He said he would have difficulty leaving Fox ``even if
there were an out in my contract'' because of loyalty to the sports
division's top executives, David Hill and Ed Goren. ``I know where
the rudder is in my shop,'' he said. ```Monday Night' is a
tremendous stage, but I don't know where it's going.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohlmeyer is on target for a mid-June announcement of his
analyst(s). ``I'm doing hard-core planning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a ton of different pieces to pull together.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``We're focused on details like the logo, where to
shoot our openings and the number of cameras.''
</P>
<P>
   LORD STANLEY'S FINALS ON ABC
</P>
<P>
   In Year 1 of its National Hockey League contract, ABC has a
chance to carry up to five games in prime time, starting with Game
3 Saturday. During its five-year tenure with the NHL, Fox reached
its maximum of three once, last year.
</P>
<P>
   But the Devils-Dallas series offers a problem for ABC: a
possible fifth game on June 8, a Thursday, would pre-empt ``Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursdays during the recently concluded prime-time season,
``Millionaire'' averaged a 17.5 Nielsen rating, while the finals
never achieved more than a 4.0 rating on Fox. Last season, Fox
averaged a 3.4 for the finals.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's lowest-rated show this season, ``Wasteland,'' averaged a
3.8.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Hyams, ABC's vice president of audience analysis, smoothed
over the coming precipitous fall of its June 8 rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though ABC's prime-time number would be lower with
hockey, we are exposing the Stanley Cup finals to a much larger and
broad-based audience than those who would watch it on Saturday or
Sunday afternoons,'' Hyams said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that benefit accrues more to the ratings-starved NHL than
to ABC. ``If hockey does well, it helps ABC,'' Hyams added.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's postseason 1.5 rating is the same Fox had through the same
stage of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   EXTENSION PERIOD TO EXPIRE
</P>
<P>
   The exclusive period for NBC and Fox to extend their deals with
Major League Baseball expires on June 5. But baseball is unlikely
to get the maximum until it opens bidding to all comers when the
period ends.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball clearly wants a major jump above the combined $950
million Fox and NBC will have paid since 1996 when their contracts
expire after the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN's new six-year deal _ three very expensive years added to
the last three years of the previous contract _ pays baseball an
average of $135.8 million annually, nearly four times more than the
1999 fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Show me a negotiation where anybody pays less, and we'll have
a headline,'' said Ed Goren, the president of Fox Sports. In his
view, ESPN is paying so much because its previous deal was
undervalued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see the NBC and Fox packages as being undervalued,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   KNIGHT GETS OFF EASY
</P>
<P>
   ESPN's hourlong interview with Bob Knight on Tuesday night was
riveting as the embattled Indiana basketball coach challenged
nearly every question about his anger put to him by Roy Firestone
and Digger Phelps. But by not showing Knight the tape of him
choking a former player, Neil Reed, during a practice in 1997, ESPN
failed viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN said it planned to show Knight the tape, but five minutes
before air time an Indiana official called to say that the
university believed the tape would not be aired. ``That wasn't our
understanding,'' said Josh Krulewitz, the spokesman. Why did ESPN
give in? It is reasoned, rather lamely, that it had used the tape
to introduce the show. Knight couldn't see it, rendering it
useless. What if ESPN had defied Indiana?
</P>
<P>
   ``He could have walked out,'' Krulewitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Not showing the tape lessened the program and Firestone's
ability to challenge Knight when he said he hadn't watched the tape
``because I didn't have to look at it to know that I didn't choke
anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   But Firestone was in a bind. He inexcusably admitted that he
hadn't seen the tape _ just freeze frames _ so he couldn't dispute
Knight's insistence that Reed's allegation was not fully upheld by
the tape.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
