<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCCER-SQUEEZE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING FIELD IS MORE LEVEL, BUT CROWDED 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW PURDY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEDFORD, N.Y. _ Mauricio Auricio Alejos has spent his life on
grass. He played on two national championship soccer teams during
the 1980s in his native Guatemala. When his career dipped, he left
professional soccer and came to the United States, where he now
owns a landscaping business. Making his living on suburban lawns,
he's noticed something about his great love.
</P>
<P>
   ``The houses where I go, mowing the lawns, planting flowers, 10
years ago you never saw a soccer ball,'' he said. ``Now you see one
in every back yard.''
</P>
<P>
   He is delighted that the youth of America have discovered
soccer. But the question for Alejos is, where does that leave the
men from Latin America?
</P>
<P>
   Around 7:30 Sunday morning, about 40 Latino men were traipsing
across the dew-soaked grass behind the Fox Lane High School,
heading for the first of the day's five adult soccer games in the
Mount Kisco Soccer League. Like golfers who sleep in their cars to
beat the crowds at public courses, the soccer players rose early
partly to satisfy a passion, but mostly because it was the only
time the grass was theirs.
</P>
<P>
   The fight for space in the suburbs comes in many guises _
monster mansions vs. town houses, SUV's vs. minivans, big box
stores vs. malls. But the competition for fields of competition has
turned feverish with youth soccer still mushrooming and the
formation of more and more adult leagues, many made up of Latino
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Children, because they are children, come first. But immigrant
men, mostly Latino, have a cultural claim on the fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our dream,'' Alejos said, watching his Kisco United
team defeat the Crow Hill Capitals. For some players, Alejos is
both coach and employer. ``I try to give a job to the guys and then
they play for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Alejos also trains young players and has seen the difficulty of
getting fields from two perspectives. ``We have no problem with the
kids,'' he said. ``But for the adults, it's very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Soccer's boom is sometimes compared to the 1970s tennis craze or
the growth of ice hockey, but soccer stands out for its cultural
passion. Mount Kisco's adult league began three years ago after
town officials settled a federal lawsuit alleging discrimination
against the town's growing Latino population. Men complained that
they were not being allowed to play soccer in Leonard Park, an
expansive park in Mount Kisco.
</P>
<P>
   With 10 adult teams, officials in Mount Kisco and the Bedford
Central School District (which serves Mount Kisco and three other
towns) are trying to accommodate them while an endless list of
other sports beg for fields, from youth soccer and baseball to
lacrosse and field hockey.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same elsewhere. White Plains, with 50,000 people, has
about 400 adult players in three leagues and about 800 youth
players. ``In our leagues we have every South American country
represented,'' said Joseph Davidson, the city's commissioner of
recreation and parks. ``Soccer is their national sport and they
want to play it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gladys Buitron, the president of the White Plains Scorpion
Soccer Club, said city officials made many demands before allowing
adults field time for soccer four years ago. Finally, Buitron said,
a local Hispanic leader called officials and said, ``Let my people
play.'' More than 400 people showed up for opening day.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the Hispanics who are coming to the county have very
few ways of socializing,'' said Robin Bikkal, chairwoman of the
county's Hispanic Advisory Board. ``The one bond they all have,
other than the language, is soccer.'' A recent board report called
for more soccer fields, and the county is considering five new
ones, but the soccer players keep on coming.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Salter, the president of the Westchester Youth Soccer
League, said he does not see youths and adults in competition.
They're all desperate for fields, he said. Look at his numbers.
About five years ago there were 4,500 young players in the county.
Now there are 9,000.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Alvarado, who came here from Mexico just 13 years ago,
remembers how different it once was. He used to travel to Staten
Island, Long Island, even Connecticut, just to find players for a
game. Now there are too many players, not enough fields. But he'll
go where he has to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you,'' said Alvarado, 33, lacing his cleats and
tying back his long black hair early Sunday morning, ``When you
have the love of this game, you'll go anywhere to play.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
