<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0872 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-CHILD-CARE-ART-NYT     05-31 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHILD-CARE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILD WELFARE TURNS NIGHTMARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT11 of 5/30 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In October 1998, Cynthia Marquez was suspected of
child abuse after her son Juan, a 10-year-old who takes six pills a
day to temper his behavioral problems, pummeled a younger brother,
leaving bruises on his arms. School officials called in a complaint
to the state hot line, and a city child welfare investigator
appeared at her Brooklyn apartment, inspecting her kitchen
cupboards and questioning her children.
</P>
<P>
   Nine days later, after the charges had been declared unfounded,
the case was closed. But the memory lingered.
</P>
<P>
   And so one recent evening, after Juan started misbehaving again
_ screaming, hurling things in the apartment, pushing his younger
siblings _ Marquez considered dialing 911, but stopped. What if,
she wondered, the police call the welfare agency on her for failing
to protect her other children?
</P>
<P>
   She called no one. Juan calmed down. But the disquieting choice
that Marquez, 26, faced that evening underscored a larger,
complicated fact of family life in Bushwick and other neighborhoods
like it across the city. There, where the Administration for
Children's Services is regarded as a potent, ubiquitous presence,
there is a real everyday fear that a momentary crisis can become
something worse. That a parental mistake can lead to an
investigation. Or that in the nightmare case, a difficult child can
be taken away.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, Marquez says, she worries about the consequences of
her troubled boy's temper tantrums and horseplay. ``Problem is, you
call 911, and BCW is coming to take your other kids away,'' she
said, referring to the agency, like most other parents here, by its
old name, short for the Bureau of Child Welfare.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of fear _ whether well founded or excessive _ is the
product of a tangled mix of circumstance and public policy. There
is, after all, a very real problem of child abuse and neglect in
this and other poor neighborhoods, where drug abuse, violence and
the everyday stresses of poverty have taken a heavy toll on family
life.
</P>
<P>
   Today, 20 out of every 1,000 children in Bushwick are in
protective custody, a rate 10 times as high as it is in the Upper
East Side of Manhattan and seven times what it is in solidly
middle-class section of Bayside, Queens, according to city figures.
And in Bushwick, there were 1,413 investigations of neglect or
abuse complaints in 1998, the most recent year for which statistics
are available, while there were only 109 on the Upper East Side.
</P>
<P>
   If the stakes are high for Bushwick parents, so, too, are they
for the city. The next flawed investigation could be the next
high-profile tragedy, and the city, which has stepped up
enforcement in recent years, has been alternately criticized for
sometimes failing to spot children in grave danger and at other
times for removing children far too rashly.
</P>
<P>
   That combustible combination of children at risk and an
oversight agency under pressure not to slip up can create an
atmosphere in which a wide range of parents _ some good, some bad,
some in between and stressed out _ alter their conduct, color their
conversations and have the frankest of strategic conversations with
their children, all because they worry about their first or next
encounter with the child protective agency.
</P>
<P>
   Parents in Bushwick talk with dread about the possibility that
missing eyeglasses or a broken arm could result in accusations of
child abuse. Some carry documents clearing them of child abuse
charges in case they find themselves being questioned by a
caseworker. They tell one another to always have a doctor's note
for school absences. They warn their children about what can happen
if they tell tall tales at school.
</P>
<P>
   Marquez keeps receipts showing that she has been to the food
pantry when her cupboards run bare. ``I have to protect myself,''
she said simply.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, anywhere from two-thirds to three-quarters of the
tens of thousands of reports of possible neglect or abuse
investigated by the city's child welfare agency every year turn out
to be unwarranted. And while parents in Bushwick say vigilance in
reporting concerns is a good thing, they feel they are living out
every parenting move under suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   Such suspicions and fear that abound in a neighborhood like
Bushwick do not make things easier for the agency's caseworkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In poor neighborhoods, people get reported more often,'' said
Faye Moore, a former child protective worker in Brooklyn and now a
vice president for Local 371, the union that represents the city's
caseworkers. ``In neighborhoods where there are more reports, there
is mistrust of the agency. We walk in knowing we're not trusted.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting along the Brooklyn-Queens border, Bushwick is among the
city's poorest neighborhoods. Nine out of 10 children in the school
district here live below the federal poverty line. A majority of
residents are blacks and Latinos, and growing numbers are newcomers
from Mexico and the Dominican Republic, with little or no ability
to communicate in English.
</P>
<P>
   In the neighborhood's schoolyards and bodegas, on tenement
stoops and in community meetings, parents trade tales about their
own encounters with the agency. Some are true; others are bits of
scary folklore. All, while hard to definitively confirm, stoke the
very real emotional stress of the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Marquez says she has heard of a mother who was reported for
neglect because her son's school uniform was not properly pressed.
</P>
<P>
   Nieves Padilla, 43, a single mother of four teen-agers in the
Hope Gardens housing project, had a social worker arrive at her
door, she says, because she refused to sign papers authorizing her
daughter to be placed in special education. The charges, brought in
1991, were ultimately dropped, according to papers that Padilla
still takes with her to school meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Nery Mejia said her daughter, then 5, suffered a gash below her
eye during a squabble over a stuffed toy several years ago. Mejia
wound up with a child abuse case against her after a school
official reported it to the state central register.
</P>
<P>
   The city cannot confirm or deny either Mejia's or Padilla's
version of events because they both occurred at a time when charges
ultimately deemed to be unwarranted were expunged from the record.
Under a new law passed after the 1995 killing of 6-year-old Elisa
Izquierdo, case files are now maintained even if charges are
dropped. Elisa was beaten to death by her mother, whom the city had
long suspected of child abuse and neglect.
</P>
<P>
   By Mejia's account, she spent months after the investigation
sleeping at her daughter's side, reassuring the child, and
apparently herself as well, that nothing would come between them.
``I was scared one day they'd come and take my daughter,'' she
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Padilla, 43, wondered aloud whether there was a financial
incentive for calling in a complaint to the state child abuse
register. ``I don't know if the teacher gets some money!'' she
suggested, rolling her eyes to the sky.
</P>
<P>
   They do not.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
