<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKIEO-BIOGRAPHIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKIE GETS THE HARSH-LIGHT TREATMENT TWICE MORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GAILE ROBINSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Jacqueline Bouvier Kennedy Onassis: A Life''
</P>
<P>
   by Donald Spoto
</P>
<P>
   Biography
</P>
<P>
   St. Martin's Press, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   ``Jackie, Ethel, Joan: Women of Camelot''
</P>
<P>
   by J. Randy Taraborrelli
</P>
<P>
   Biography
</P>
<P>
   Warner Books, $25.95
</P>
<P>
   What makes it OK to turn the spotlight on Jacqueline Kennedy
Onassis again?
</P>
<P>
   This spring, there are two new books on the former First Lady:
``Jacqueline Bouvier Kennedy Onassis: A Life,'' by Donald Spoto,
and ``Jackie, Ethel, Joan'' by Randy Taraborrelli, about Jackie's
relationship with the wives of Robert and Ted Kennedy. Both turn
over JFK-era rocks and poke at the squirmy, icky things underneath
_ the stuff no one should want to touch, look at or hear. That
period has been filed under ``National Tragedy,'' and the staining
of memories with additional details offered by Taraborrelli and
Spoto ought to leave readers swimming in a cesspool of
self-loathing.
</P>
<P>
   Taraborrelli's book is slimy with hot, sticky gossip. Even
though the pages are sandwiched between hard covers, they read like
clippings from the cheesiest of tabloids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jackie loved to gossip, and always had. However, when the
gossip was about her, she didn't much like it,'' Taraborrelli
writes.
</P>
<P>
   After slogging through Taraborrelli's chapters on betrayal,
assassination, infidelities, assassination, manipulation, and
tragedy, tragedy, tragedy, readers might fear a karmic comeuppance
for having touched these books.
</P>
<P>
   Even Spoto's work, which attempts a higher road, is tainted with
tell-all.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was required only to be and to appear at the proper place
and time, smiling, waving, an ambassador of what-you-will. She did
not have to accomplish anything of significance. People required
only that she look magnificent,'' Spoto writes. ``She had perhaps
no alternative but to offer the public a kind of mask and to
retreat into her deserved privacy behind that mask. She was not a
cold woman, but her image became that of someone predictable in her
elegance and almost immutable in her character.''
</P>
<P>
   He avoids the seamier moments of the Kennedy and Onassis
marriages, and expands on Jackie's third act, as an editor for
Doubleday, a period of great satisfaction for her.
</P>
<P>
   She wanted a simple life with a happy family. She was raised to
be a trophy wife by a mother who cared more for social standing and
wealth than emotional well-being. Jackie tried to please everyone,
and in doing so became the tragic queen of Camelot.
</P>
<P>
   Our longtime allegiance is with Jackie; yet, with these and
previous books about her, we've forged a retail covenant with
gossipy writers. The paradox would have trapped her, too.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
