r e BC-SUMMER-READING-TEX     05-31 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-READING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR SUMMER SURPRISES BY UNKNOWN AUTHORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The summer blockbuster books are about to descend upon us.
Beginning in early June with ``Portrait of an Artist, as an Old
Man'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $23), Joseph Heller's posthumous,
near-autobiographical final novel, and finishing in late August
with ``The Bear and the Dragon'' (Putnam, $28.95), another Jack
Ryan multipager from Tom Clancy _ with J.K. Rowling's ``Harry
Potter and the Doomspell Tournament'' (July, Levine/Scholastic,
$25.95) in between _ many of modern literature's biggest names will
compete for your vacation and/or poolside reading dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, it's easy to forget that this summer's books will, as
always, include wonderful work by authors whose names aren't so
familiar. For those who'd like to alternate titles by favorite
writers with books by newcomers, here are several suggestions for
near-guaranteed summer reading pleasure:
</P>
<P>
   Above all, try ``World of Pies'' by Karen Stolz (June, Hyperion,
$18.95). A creative-writing teacher in Austin, Stolz utilizes a
striking approach to fiction in her first novel: Each chapter
chronicling the life and times of small-town Texas girl Roxanne
involves some sort of recipe, which is faithfully printed at
chapter's end. That approach could quickly become too cute and
stale, but Stolz is such a skillful writer that it seems entirely
natural that her characters would use food as a sort of emotional
lighthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman bakes a little piece of herself into a pie,''
Roxanne's mother says.
</P>
<P>
   By book's end _ when the once-semirebellious Roxanne moves back
to the quaint town of Annette so her daughter can experience the
pleasures of small-town life _ readers will want to move there,
too, and gobble some lemon meringue pie or Dutch crumb cake.
``World of Pies'' is likely to garner rapturous reviews and
gradually increasing sales.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not ``Sorority Sisters'' (Villard, $19.95) is a
bestseller, Tajuana Butler and her novel provide perhaps the most
heartwarming story of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Butler originally self-published ``Sorority Sisters,'' a salty
tale of several vastly different young women who become friends and
soul mates in college. Last year, after months of peddling the book
at flea markets and garage sales, Butler attended Book Expo
America, the publishing industry's annual national trade show, and
forced a copy on an associate editor from Villard. The editor
reluctantly agreed to read ``Sorority Sisters:'' one day later, she
purchased it.
</P>
<P>
   And with good reason; Butler's characters glimmer with
multidimensional charm, even while pondering seemingly
insignificant things, like whether the paraphernalia table should
be where the hors d'oeuvres table is, as they arrange a room for a
sorority mixer.
</P>
<P>
   It is rare for a self-published writer to have book rights
purchased by a major publishing house, and then go on to become a
famous, bestselling author. The best recent example? None other
than John Grisham.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Sherman Alexie was selected by ``The New Yorker''
magazine as one of the best American fiction writers under age 40.
That honor was based on Alexie's short-story collection ``The Lone
Ranger and Tonto Fistfight in Heaven.'' The Spokane/Coeur d'Alene
Indian always creates fascinating scenarios featuring American
Indians, and his latest series of stories, ``The Toughest Indian in
the World'' (Atlantic Monthly Press, $24), is no exception.
</P>
<P>
   There is, perhaps, one major difference here between Alexie's
usual protagonists and those populating ``The Toughest Indian in
the World.'' This time, he has chosen to depict American Indians
who have achieved at least middle-class success. They still have to
be wary of the white world, though. As one character in the title
story notes, ``Love you or hate you, white people will shoot you in
the heart.'' Enemies may now substitute innuendo for bullets, or
social repression for physical assault. But the result, Alexie
believes, is the same: ``We could have been a thousand vestigial
reproductions of a single organ, all of us struggling to find a
purpose, a place to stand and breathe, enough room to function
within the large body of a thing, a person, a crowd called
Indian.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is Jim Knipfel's ``Quitting the Nairobi Trio''
(Tarcher/Putnam, $23.95) _ the title comes from a regular sketch on
the old ``Ernie Kovacs'' TV show _ a book that ought to be
dismaying, if not downright off-putting, but isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Knipfel, now a staff writer for the ``New York Press,'' writes
candidly about his 1987 stay in a Minneapolis mental hospital after
a failed suicide attempt. Most chapters are obviously based on
actual experience. But several, which are never presented as
different from the others, describe Knipfel's hallucinatory
episodes. These, he notes in a foreword, ``are as real to me as
lunch. They may have been simple hallucinations. They may represent
what my doctors later called a `psychotic break.' Or as I believed
for some time afterward, I may have died after that overdose and
gone to Hell for a few days.''
</P>
<P>
   Every page of ``Quitting the Nairobi Trio'' will make readers
uncomfortable. The topic of mental illness, Knipfel notes almost
gleefully, makes ``most people get creepy and nervous ... I
understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   But what he has to tell us _ not only that the mentally ill are
people, too, but that they're interesting people we should study
instead of compulsively ignore _ is important. Where ``I Never
Promised You a Rose Garden'' and ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's
Nest'' were primarily entertainment, ``Quitting the Nairobi Trio''
is more read-and-learn, with occasional amusement as a side
benefit. It's powerful and, frankly, wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDRV/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 1636EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
