<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0879 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-31 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A PRESCHOOL IS SPARED, FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``Don't mess with parents,'' Kathy Jones said.
``It's like that old rule about not coming between a bear and her
cub.''
</P>
<P>
   The Carmel Companies, the new owner of the Parkmerced housing
development, walked into the middle of the parents and the 50
children of the Montessori Children's Center, and found itself
thoroughly clawed.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Carmel gave the 24-year-old preschool 50
days' notice of eviction, with no time for parents like Jones to
get their kids into any other school in the fall. Carmel became
villain-of-the-month in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Carmel's attorney, Joe Bravo, was brave enough to
venture into a meeting of outraged and tearful parents and do a
little back-pedaling. He said Carmel will not evict the school for
at least a year, and will engage in good-faith mediation with the
school.
</P>
<P>
   Bravo received some polite applause, but also some questions
about why the school ever has to leave, and what will happen to
teachers given a year's notice. Parents also wanted to know why
Carmel suddenly was willing to give the school a year's stay of
execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pressure, that's why,' yelled someone in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   It was a crowd that did remarkably little yelling, considering
they were parents faced with a big corporation coming between them
and their children. It was a crowd that knew how to bring San
Francisco-style moral suasion to bear on an outside corporation.
</P>
<P>
   They raised hell. They went to newspapers with the ultimate
eviction story, the story of big-bucks developers evicting an
excellent school and its students.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., wrote a letter offering to serve as
mediator. The Board of Supervisors issued a resolution, by
Supervisor Mabel Teng, urging Parkmerced do everything it can to
keep the school alive.
</P>
<P>
   You had to wonder how Carmel was dumb or arrogant enough to walk
into this public relations disaster. Tuesday night's meeting was
attended by two news crews and representatives of Supervisors Tom
Ammiano and Leland Yee and Assemblyman Kevin Shelley.
</P>
<P>
   You also have to wonder, as parent Kent Dauterman did, what will
happen in four or five months, or a year, if the media loses
interest.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to stop a big corporation from doing what it wants
with its property, and it may be naive to ask for some humanity in
the greedy marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the Montessori Children's Center are acres of open space
suitable for development, some of it slated to be a day care
center, but not a school, according to Carmel's lawyer. The
Montessori Children's Center occupies street-front property, and
could be in the way of something big.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember that these children do not see themselves simply as
students at school,'' Dauterman wrote last week in his letter of
protest to the Carmel Companies. ``They are young enough that this
school is their entire world.''
</P>
<P>
   What does that little world mean? Ask Caan Nguyen, who came to
this country in 1975 from Vietnam, learned how good the Montessori
Children's Center is, and when he had children sent two of them
there.
</P>
<P>
   His oldest son, Alexander Nguyen, went on to kindergarten at
West Portal Elementary School, and has won first prize in a
district-wide essay contest for kindergartners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he didn't get it from me,'' Nguyen said. ``He got it
here, at this school.''
</P>
<P>
   The little school is neat as can be, with fresh paint, clean
floors and teaching materials stacked by the eight staffers who
stand to lose their jobs in a year, or whatever length of time is
mediated.
</P>
<P>
   A watercolor of the school, painted by Robert Flynn, husband of
school director Judith Flynn, hangs in the entrance next to
paintings of mothers with children by Raphael and Mary Cassatt. The
school glistens with care and pride.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the management of Parkmerced says the school has to go
because the building isn't up to some not-quite-specified ideas of
snuff. Bravo, Carmel's attorney, says the building is too old and
wasn't designed as a school.
</P>
<P>
   One of the school's founders, Rebecca Cherny, listed dozens of
schools, modest and glamorous, that are in old buildings not
designed as schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-four years ago, my daughter opened the doors of this
school, and now she's a third-year med student at Stanford _ that's
what good early childhood education did for her,'' Cherny said.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Deets is a parent of another of the school's graduates
who went on to Stanford. ``My daughter wants to go into foreign
service, be a diplomat. How many kids graduating out of Stanford
want to do that?'' Deets said. ``It's because they're teaching
values here.''
</P>
<P>
   Judith Flynn, the school's director, said that last summer she
was at a meeting of an international group called Educators Without
Borders, and jokingly said the frontiers for children may not
necessarily be in places like Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little did I know,'' she said, ``that my frontier would be in
my back yard.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
