<HEADER>
A0891 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-TV-E!-FICTION-SPI &LR;      05-31 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-E!-FICTION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW `OFF-RAMP' A FUN-FILLED RIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the star-driven world of tellytainment, the anthology series
is up there with pyorrhea on the list of items generally not wished
for when blowing out the birthday candles.
</P>
<P>
   Even a story-driven show like ``Law &AMP; Order,'' famous for its
revolving-door casting, could never have made it to a 10th season
without some semblance of year-to-year stability. Be honest. Would
you tune in every week if you knew Jerry Orbach wasn't returning as
Det. Lennie Briscoe, or if Angie Harmon was never again to make an
appearance as A.D.A. Carmichael?
</P>
<P>
   This absence of star power makes ``Hollywood Off-Ramp'' the most
likely candidate for best new series you won't remember next year.
But enjoy it while it lasts. Beginning with a Sunday night premiere
and then moving to Mondays at 10 p.m. on E! Entertainment
Television, ``Hollywood Off-Ramp'' looks to be the Chee-tos of
cable: salty, not very good for you, lots of fun.
</P>
<P>
   True, this would define most of the programming on the E!
channel. But when placed alongside ``Wild On ...,'' ``Howard
Stern'' and the latest ``Sexy Swimwear'' installment, ``Off-Ramp''
actually offers some fiber. OK, maybe it's more like the stringy
filament from a celery stalk, but we're talking E! Entertainment
Television here, not PBS.
</P>
<P>
   Hosted by Brian Unger, ``Hollywood Off-Ramp'' borrows
shamelessly _ correction: steals shamelessly _ from ``The Twilight
Zone.'' Unger, a former correspondent and fill-in anchor on ``The
Daily Show'' at Comedy Central, writes his own wry intros and exits
for each half-hour episode.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's premiere, which centers on a producer's frantic
efforts to woo a reclusive actor to his next film, Unger intones
with Rod Serling-like seriosity: ``A truly great actor chooses to
work once every 10 years, creates a definitive role, then retreats
_ with the cash _ back to the ashram, where he slowly bloats up
like a tick.''
</P>
<P>
   After episode three, which follows the activities of a 1940s-era
gossip columnist, Unger allows that the appetite for entertainment
dish is even more insatiable today. He adds: ``That's why these
days celebrities pay managers and publicists, who protect them by
making sure their clients' names appear with mind-numbing frequency
in every gossip column on the planet, no matter how much they have
to lie to get it there.''
</P>
<P>
   Shot in Vancouver, B.C., the stories that play out between
Unger's pithy prose are crafted stylishly with black humor and
brick-subtle satire. Each has a ``Twilight Zone'' twist at the end,
which will encourage regular viewers to tune in and guess how
things turn out. Some make sense, some blur the line between fact
and fiction. Either way, ``Hollywood Off-Ramp'' is a refreshing
throwback to an earlier age, when television was more interested in
content _ and so were the people who were watching.
</P>
<P>
   Episode Two, which airs Monday at 10 p.m. in the show's regular
time period, puts it in beautifully succinct perspective when a
famous actor, tired of starring in slasher films, tells his
director and his manager that he wants to be an artist, not a hack.
The director replies: ``You are better than an artist. You are a
pop-culture icon!''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Off-Ramp. Half-hour anthology series satirizing the
antics of people in show business. Series premiere Sunday at 10
p.m., E! Entertainment Television. Show moves to its regular day
and time Monday at 10 p.m. Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
