   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PHONE-CHARGES (Washington) _ The Federal Communications
Commission and most of the nation's leading telephone companies
announced Wednesday a sweeping reshuffling of the telephone rates
that should reduce costs for all businesses and consumers.
Officials said the reductions amounted to the largest rate cut in
the history of federal telephone regulation and that they would
have their biggest impact on the poor and those who use their
telephones the least. For tens of millions of Americans who make
few or no long distance calls each month, the government estimated
the rates would be reduced by as much as 50 percent. By Stephen
Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Microsoft files its reply to
the government's amended remedy filing on Friday. The document
comes soon before the judge issues his ruling on the remedy, widely
expected to be the breakup of the company in two. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-TOUR-BUSES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Nine days after a double-decker
tour bus killed a pedestrian at a Midtown intersection, Gov. George
Pataki on Wednesday shut down the tour company, New York Apple
Tours, for at least two weeks, and said he will try to put them out
of business permanently.
</P>
