<P>
   NY-ACTOR (New York) _ After nearly 25 years in the business,
Randolph Walker knew better than to bank on an audition. Still,
when he headed home last week after trying out for a bit part in a
movie called ``Dummy,'' he could not help feeling a little hopeful.
There is a difficult combination of realism and optimism that life
as a New York actor demands, and Walker had perfected it, scraping
by on the odd bits of work that define daily existence for so many
people in the profession. It was on his trip home that Walker was
fatally struck by a double-decker tour bus, setting off a wave of
outrage against its operator, the problem-ridden New York Apple
Tours. The reaction in theater circles was more than anger or
sadness; New York's acting rank and file, who live the rare highs
and relentless lows of the city's performing arts, had lost one of
their own. By Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
