<HEADER>
A0905 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-SOCSEC-COMMENTARY-TEX     05-31 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCSEC-COMMENTARY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T MAKE A MESS OF SOCIAL SECURITY SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JACK Z. SMITH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Social Security is the single most successful program in
government history. Without it, more than half of all seniors would
live in poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   _ George W. Bush, in Rancho Cucamonga, Calif., May 15. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dear Gov. Bush:
</P>
<P>
   I certainly agree with you that Social Security has been a
splendid program.
</P>
<P>
   But I've read in the papers that you want to make a big change
in it. I hear that you want to partly ``privatize'' it.
</P>
<P>
   You were pretty doggone vague when you announced your
privatization ``plan'' for Social Security two weeks ago. But you
said enough to make me antsy about what might happen to ``the
single most successful program in government history'' if you land
in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   You said you want to let people invest part of their Social
Security payroll taxes in individual retirement accounts. They
could put the money in stocks or other investments that might earn
a higher rate of return than Social Security funds invested in
government bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why your strategy bothers me:
</P>
<P>
   For every dollar a person earns up to $76,200, 6.2 cents is
deducted for Social Security payroll taxes. The employer kicks in a
matching amount, for a total of 12.4 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Under your plan, an employee could keep a portion of the payroll
tax _ perhaps 2 cents of each 12.4 cents _ and put it in an
individual retirement account.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, Social Security is a pay-as-you-go program.
About 90 percent of payroll taxes go to pay current Social Security
benefits. If workers divert money into individual accounts, that
will sharply reduce the amount of incoming payroll taxes devoted to
paying current benefits.
</P>
<P>
   To make up for this shortfall, you'll probably have to cut
benefits, since you're opposed to raising payroll taxes. Or you
might try to find some highly questionable source of supplemental
funding, such as those projected long-range federal budget
surpluses that may never materialize.
</P>
<P>
   Your plan also would diminish the progressive nature of the
Social Security system, which has historically given low-income
people retirement benefits that represent a higher percentage of
their lifetime wages than the benefits that high-income earners
get.
</P>
<P>
   Unselfish Americans have long viewed this progressive feature as
social insurance that provides a decent floor of retirement
benefits for the less fortunate among us.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to raise Social Security's rate of return, why not
preserve the present system but have Congress change the law to
allow a limited portion of Social Security trust funds to be put
into potentially higher-yielding investments such as stock funds?
</P>
<P>
   By the way, AARP, the leading U.S. senior citizens'
organization, likes that approach much more than your privatization
scheme. With such an approach, payroll tax revenues would be
sufficient to pay current benefits. And the investments would be
pooled nationwide, reducing administrative costs and making them
less risky than individual retirement accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security should be just one leg of a personal retirement
plan. And it should be the ultrasafe, secure part, not some Las
Vegas crap shoot based on dicey investments. If you want to pour
money into highly speculative stocks, you can do it on your own or
through vehicles such as a 401(k) plan.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody should be concerned about projected future Social
Security deficits. But the system is not expected to come up short
in paying benefits for 30-plus years, even if no changes are made.
</P>
<P>
   We'll probably need to increase the payroll tax modestly over
time and gradually raise the amount of income taxed, because people
are living longer and the ratio of workers to retirees is falling.
</P>
<P>
   But, Governor, please don't jeopardize what you call ``the
single most successful program in government history.''
</P>
<P>
   Sincerely,
</P>
<P>
   Jack Z. Smith &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jack Z. Smith is a ``Star-Telegram'' editorial writer and
columnist. He can be reached at (817) 390-7724 or
jzsmith &LR; star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 1652EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0170 </DOCNO>
