<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-NKOREA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREAN LEADER REPORTED TO HAVE VISITED CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Beijing was buzzing Wednesday with reports that North
Korea's reclusive leader, Kim Jong Il, made a secret visit to
Beijing this week to consult with China's leaders on the upcoming
summit meeting between North and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The story first appeared Wednesday morning in a South Korean
newspaper, which said that Kim stayed at China's state Diaoyutai
Guest House from Monday to Wednesday and was returning to Pyongyang
by train Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The report could not be independently confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   The visit would be Kim's first overseas trip since succeeding
his father, Kim Il Song, who died in July 1994, and a significant
sign that he is interested in reducing his country's diplomatic
isolation, experts here said.
</P>
<P>
   The trip was not announced in either North Korea or China, and
an official at the North Korean Embassy here denied the reports.
</P>
<P>
   But Sun Yuxi, a Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman, was more
cryptic, saying, ``I do not confirm or deny that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese have long encouraged Kim to visit Beijing, and
Foreign Ministry officials have predicted that he would come later
this year, perhaps following an exchange of visits by other senior
officials. Kim made an unusual visit to the Chinese Embassy in
Pyongyang several months ago, in what was seen as a prelude to such
a trip.
</P>
<P>
   A number of previous invitations by Beijing were rebuffed, or,
more commonly, never answered, Chinese officials say.
</P>
<P>
   But many experts were skeptical that Kim himself was in town
this week, since China's leaders have been busy entertaining
President K.R. Narayanan of India.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   An official at the train station in Shenyang, in northeast China
near the North Korean border, said that a special train bound for
North Korea had passed there Wednesday afternoon, but he did not
know if Kim was on board, according to Reuters. But Wednesday
evening dispatchers there said they knew of no such train.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's Kim and South Korean President Kim Dae Jung are
scheduled to meet in the North Korean capital of Pyongyang on June
12-14.
</P>
<P>
   Although China and North Korea are old political allies, and
fought side by side during the 1950-53 Korean War, China has also
cultivated ties with South Korea in recent years and is strongly
supporting the upcoming bilateral talks, eager to avoid renewed war
so close to its border.
</P>
<P>
   But also, the Chinese government is clearly becoming impatient
with North Korea's unwillingness to undertake reforms that might
help rescue its economy and end years of desperate food shortages.
</P>
<P>
   Those problems spill over into China in the form of hundreds of
thousands of North Korean migrants who cross illegally into China
in search of food and other necessities.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials say they have been encouraging North Korea to
follow their economic example: scrapping a command economy for
market-driven reforms. And there have been signs that Kim is
considering that possibility, for example, by tolerating the growth
of small private produce markets.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's government has also shown signs recently of
relaxing its hostility toward Western countries, particularly the
United States. In recent months, it has established diplomatic
relations with several countries, including Italy and Australia.
And the U.S. State Department announced ``progress'' in talks
between U.S. and North Korean officials this week in Rome, which
dealt mostly with security issues on the Korean peninsula.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 1653EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0907 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS01-COX     05-31 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD mini-reviews
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray, Eric Sundquist, Mandi Albright, Scott Walton,
Yolanda Rodriquez
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  CONTEMPORARY GOSPEL
</P>
<P>
   ``Thankful''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Mary. Columbia / C2 Records. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The rapping (``I Sings''), stomping (``Can't Give Up Now'') and
hand-clapping (first single ``Shackles'') might make it hard to
believe that there's actually serious praising going on here. But
this R&AMP;B-sounding debut doesn't hide its inspiration in ambiguous
lyrics. And while the vocal mettle of this duo only weighs as
heavily as the similar-sounding Mary J. Blige in the lower
registers, those yearning for more youthful and earnest female
voices in this sub-genre should still be ``Thankful'' for these
sisters' arrival.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Mary Mary, Columbia and C2 Records:
www.mary-mary.com, www.columbiarecords.com, www.c2records.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Smile''
</P>
<P>
   The Jayhawks. American Recordings / Columbia.13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   The Jayhawks' second CD without former frontman Mark Olson,
``Smile'' lacks the freshness of the band's rough-and-real,
format-bending work from the Olson era. ``Smile'' comprises mostly
slick, familiar-sounding pop. For that kind of thing, it's not bad;
Gary Louris, who wrote or co-wrote all the tunes on the album, can
turn out a ballad with a hook that'll stick with you. The title
track, for example, has a catchy sound reminiscent of regional pop
fave the Connells.
</P>
<P>
   _Eric Sundquist
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on the Jayhawks: www.thejayhawks.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Engines of Creation''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Satriani. Epic. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   Say it ain't so, Joe.
</P>
<P>
   That's the lament ``Engines of Creation'' should invoke en masse
among longtime fans of guitar virtuoso Joe Satriani. A postmodern
pastiche that meshes break beats, techno and industrial stylings,
Satriani's latest release proves a disjointed, misguided effort.
``Until We Say Goodbye'' and ``Clouds Race Across the Sky'' sound
most like the Satriani of old; driving guitar solos and deft
fingerwork ring out clearly over seemingly misplaced beats and
loops. If Satriani was going for a concept album, he's got one.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the concept apparently involved using all
available studio gimmickry rather than time-tested talent.
</P>
<P>
   _Mandi Albright
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Joe Satriani: www.satriani.com/
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SOUNDTRACK
</P>
<P>
   ``Mission: Impossible 2''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   16 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Here's one for the headbangers. And the Tori fans. And even
lovers of Brazilian folk. That's the beauty _ and the ugly _ of
this patchwork quilt of music from (and inspired by) ``M:I 2.''
There's something here for just about everyone, but nothing that
really holds it all together. New music from Metallica, Chris
Connell, Tori Amos and Latin-guitar sensation Heitor Pereira make
the album worth the price of admission. And Limp Bizkit lands a
direct hit with ``Take a Look Around,'' a blistering metal-rap
retread of Lalo Schifrin's famous ``Mission: Impossible'' theme.
But the rest of the disc is a wildly inconsistent mishmash of
mostly unmemorable metal.
</P>
<P>
   _Nick Tate
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B: More on ``Mission: Impossible 2,'' Hollywood
Records: www.hollywoodrecords.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  POP-ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Farmhouse''
</P>
<P>
   Phish. Elektra. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   The one bright spot on this otherwise middling effort is that
nothing here remotely resembles the Grateful Dead-style space jams
that have (often unfairly) drawn comparisons to Jerry Garcia and
Co. Most tracks are more poppy than trippy short songs that build
on Trey Anastasio's spare fretwork and vocals _ a far cry from the
extended live cuts on last fall's six-disc box set. Now for the bad
news: Phish also seems to have thrown out its usually consistent
songcraft with the jams. And the result isn't exactly fillet. A few
tracks are worth a listen, such as the elegant acoustic
guitar-driven ``Sleep'' and ``The Inlaw Josie Wales.'' But the rest
is Phish filler _ or bait.
</P>
<P>
   Phish plays June 23-24 at Lakewood Amphitheatre.
</P>
<P>
   _Nick Tate
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B: More about Phish: www.phish.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
