<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0909 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HOME-POOL01-COX     05-31 1622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-POOL01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Multifunctional settings blend pools with the landscape
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jim and Edie Duane had a shopping list of features
when they set out two years ago to create an outdoor living space
in their back yard. Not all of them were in sync.
</P>
<P>
   Jim, who swam competitively in his youth, wanted a pool for
exercise. Edie, an avid gardener, didn't want a big aqua rectangle
to overpower her landscape.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted a detached home office. She had her heart set on a
guest house that would double as a cabana.
</P>
<P>
   Through careful planning, the Duanes created a versatile setting
behind their home that meets all their needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned you can have your cake and eat it too, as far as
having all the aesthetics and being practical at the same time,''
Edie said.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of others are opting for pool-centered environments as
they extend their homes to outdoors, where they can exercise,
relax, garden and entertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to feel like they're creating their own little
resort in their back yard,'' said Richard Fricker, owner of
Specialty Pool &AMP; Spa of Alpharetta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   The best designs are in the details.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people, whether (they desire) formal or informal, are
going with pools nestled in an area that gives them yet another
reason for going outside _ additional seating, cabanas, outdoor
chimneys,'' said Phillip Cates of Lifescapes/TruGreen LandCare, a
Canton landscape company.
</P>
<P>
   That total package, including pool, structures, decking and
landscaping, can cost six figures, depending on amenities. Yet
unlike a simple swimming pool, these oases can greatly enhance a
home's resale value.
</P>
<P>
   ``If done well, with a little creativity a pool can make a
property pop and sizzle,'' Fricker said.
</P>
<P>
   These days, ``creativity'' includes finishes that make the pool
look like a pond. Decking that blends the pool into the landscape.
Water features that add soothing sound. Lighting and sound systems
that set a mood. Plants that soften a pool in a garden. Structures
that lend the conveniences of indoors.
</P>
<P>
   Planning makes perfect
</P>
<P>
   The Duanes carved their retreat out of woods on their rural
property near the community of Crabapple in Ga. Until then, their
only outdoor amenity had been a deck.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted more of a mountain pond than a swimming pool, very
secondary to everything else,'' Edie said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time Jim, a real estate appraiser, was planning a
home office for his second job as a builder.
</P>
<P>
   So the couple decided to first build a guest house at the rear
of their property with a basement that included an office, exercise
area and dressing rooms for their future pool. Jim Lesty of
Lifescapes designed a setting that links the guest house to the
house via a series of hillside terraces that include a pond, pool,
gazebo and garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted them to take a 17-year-old ho-hum back yard, make it
into paradise and then border it with a Garden of Eden,'' Edie
said.
</P>
<P>
   Specialty Pool &AMP; Spa created a free-form, or abstract-shaped,
pool with a medium blue surface that complements the surrounding
rust tones of crab orchard stone decking. Short stacked-stone
retaining walls provide natural seating areas, behind which Edie
planted annual and perennial beds that spill with color. On the
highest terrace, a waterfall splashes into a goldfish pond.
</P>
<P>
   The pool's clover-like shape didn't leave Jim much room for
doing laps. He solved the problem by installing a Super Swimmer, a
harness contraption that provides resistance while swimming in
place.
</P>
<P>
   The pool is still large enough for when the Duanes' teenage
daughter hosts a swim party for friends. ``That's one reason we
built this area _ so that we could meet the kids and their
parents,'' Edie said. ``They all love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Follow your garden's style
</P>
<P>
   The Duanes chose a free-form pool with natural stone decking
because they wanted an informal setting.
</P>
<P>
   Choices in a pool's shape, color and materials should be based
on the landscape's design, designers said.
</P>
<P>
   Formal landscapes typically call for rectangular pools, not
those that are kidney-shaped.
</P>
<P>
   Medium blue or gray tones give the pool's surface a
sophisticated feel, bright blue, aqua and white lend a more casual
Caribbean look, while dark tones make for a natural lagoon look.
(Light bottoms reflect the sky, while darker ones absorb the
light.) One popular finish is Pebbletect which contains an
aggragate that disguises the mottling effects of plaster.
</P>
<P>
   For decking, the top choices are limestone, bluestone and crab
orchard stone, said Graham Pittman, an Atlanta landscape architect.
</P>
<P>
   Water features are another must. ``Their sound is undeniably
therapeutic because it provides a sense of tranquility that makes
people want to kick back and relax,'' Fricker said.
</P>
<P>
   Spas and fountains are among the mainstays, but for today's
large pool environments, waterfalls and vanishing edges (also known
as negative edges) are popular. Rock-laden waterfalls help create a
natural setting surrounding a free-form pool, while vanishing edges
most often are used in formal, terraced ones containing rectangular
pools.
</P>
<P>
   In Morgan and Mary Lee Pridemore's northwest Atlanta garden, the
pool extends perpendicular to the rear of their house. At the far
end, water cascades over the vanishing edge, spilling into a trough
on a lower terrace and creating the illusion that the pool is
overflowing.
</P>
<P>
   Carl and Pat Hartrampf love living on the edge _ so much that
they designed their pool so that its spill can be enjoyed from the
front instead of the back. From a statue and fountain, water gushes
into a square pool, then glides over the edge several feet into the
main pool and finally a trough at the base. The effect, when viewed
from their Buckhead house, is a multi-tiered waterfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a ribbon of water,'' Pat said.
</P>
<P>
   Those little extras add up!
</P>
<P>
   Creating a pool environment is like designing an interior: It's
all in the details.
</P>
<P>
   If the pool will be used for entertaining, lighting _ both task
and ambient _ becomes a must. Suddenly, the transistor radio
doesn't do the job so a sound system seems necessary. Depending on
the purpose of the area, structures such as cabanas, gazebos and
pavilions figure into the package, too.
</P>
<P>
   For Calvin and Cindy Thompson, the challenge was to integrate a
number of structures, including a house, detached garage and tennis
courts, around the pool outside their country home in Dallas, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our design criteria included a unique pool area with
waterfalls, water gardens, outdoor fireplace/barbecue area and
gathering areas that could accommodate large parties on a frequent
basis _ all while providing our clients with an intimate,
comfortable surrounding,'' said Cates, whose company developed the
site's master plan.
</P>
<P>
   Lifescapes made the pool area private by lowering it 2 feet and
hauling in tons of boulders to retain the soil and create a
dramatic waterfall. Drainage proved a challenge, so an intricate
system was designed to avoid buildup in the planting areas.
</P>
<P>
   Plants are crucial for blending a pool into the landscape. ``A
pool without landscaping is a concrete hole in the ground,'' Cates
said. ``Landscaping accentuates it and frames the views of the
pool.''
</P>
<P>
   Flower beds were once believed off limits to poolsides because
of chlorine's harmful effects, but advances in nonchlorination
systems allow plants to dangle over the water's edge.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Pat Hartrampf, who insisted on maintaining a dogwood tree
when Superior Pools installed her pool. ``They said you cannot put
a pool under a dogwood, but it was already here and I wanted it,''
she recalled. ``It looks great.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, the pool, which is enjoyed by their eight
grandchildren, is only one element in their garden.
</P>
<P>
   It's that mix of features in a pool environment that comes with
a price. An average 20-by-40-foot pool costs about $40,000 to
$80,000, depending on its bells and whistles, Fricker said. Decking
and hardscaping can cost as much as the pool. Add in structures,
furnishings and landscaping, and projects totaling several
hundred-thousand dollars aren't that unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the amenities that add up because it's like building an
outdoor park in your back yard,'' he said. ``But for many this is
becoming the way of the land _ whether they swim or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Before you dig
</P>
<P>
   Careful planning is the key to creating a pool environment. Here
are some points to consider:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Determine why you want a pool, how you'll use it and how
often. Lifestyle in part dictates the design of the pool and its
surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Consult a landscape designer for developing a master plan for
your property before adding a pool. A professional can help you
site the pool according to views from both indoors and out.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Determine restrictions on construction. Most cities require
fencing to ensure safety and, because pools are considered an
accessory structure, a permit as well, said Bret Benninghoff of
Superior Pools. Some community covenants also address pools.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Avoid starting a project in spring, when most pool contractors
and landscape designers are busiest. It takes an average of eight
weeks to construct a pool depending on the amenities, Benninghoff
said. ``A day of rain can cost you two or three on a job.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For information: The National Spa &AMP; Pool Institute offers
consumer guidelines on planning a pool and selecting a contractor.
Call 1-800-323-3996 or visit its Web site at www.nspi.org.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
