<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Locate hard to find itemsBy Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to help you
locate it. But because of the volume of mail, we cannot track down
every request. Readers whose queries are answered in the column
will receive a blue-and-cream canvas Buyer's Edge tote bag. Write
us at Buyer's Edge Find It,The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us at buyersedge(at)ajc.com
(please include your name, the city you live in and daytime phone
number); or call 404-582-7642.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Could you please tell me where Oxiclean is sold locally?
</P>
<P>
   _ Ardie McDaniel, Alpharetta, Ga.,
</P>
<P>
   A: This concentrated cleaner can be used for removing such
stains as mildew, algae, juice, pet messes and odors and tile grout
stains. Or simply add a scoop to a load of laundry. Or use it to
clean your dentures, coffeepot, wood deck and ice chest. Pick up a
16-ounce tub of Oxiclean ($9.99) at Linens &AMP; Things in the Peach
Shopping Center, 2900 Peachtree Road N.E., 404-816-2700. For
cleaning purposes, you might consider a $19.99 starter kit (shown)
from manufacturer Orange Glo International. It includes a 16-ounce
tub of Oxiclean and a squirt bottle; a 16-ounce spray bottle of
Orange Glo wood cleaner and polish; a 20-ounce spray bottle of
Orange Clean multipurpose cleaner; and a synthetic chamois cleaning
cloth.
</P>
<P>
   Q: For several months, I have been trying to find Campbell's
Chunky Manhattan Clam Chowder (tomato based). I had been buying it
at Publix, but they appear to no longer carry it, and I can't find
this soup anywhere else in the Atlanta area. I would appreciate
your help in finding this item.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steven Levy, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: New Yorkers might have an easy time finding this soup, but we
in the South do not. Publix no longer carries the soup, says
spokeswoman Leslie Spencer. However, the soup can be ordered at any
Publix store, at customer service. A 19-ounce can is $2.19.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've been trying to locate a picture of two little boys in
overalls walking down a dirt road. One of them looks at the other
and says, ``You been farming long?'' I can't remember if this is on
a sign or if it's a poster. Can you please help?
</P>
<P>
   _ Angie Thornton, Cumming, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: These ``Little Farmers'' will never grow old. You can
purchase a poster (18 by 14 inches, $4.95) exclusively through the
Country Store catalog: 1-800-558-1013. Or order it on the Internet
at www.countrystorecatalog.com. A plaque is also available _ the
company mounts the poster on a wood base and seals it with acrylic
for a glossy finish ($14.95).
</P>
<P>
   A California woman took the picture of her twin sons in 1978.
(She won third place with the photo at the San Luis Obispo, Calif.,
fair.) Over the years it was used in farm advertising until Roy
Reiman of Reiman Publications obtained the picture for posters.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have been trying to find DuBarry's cleansing cream. I have
used it for years; it gives my skin such a soft feeling. I had a
source, but they no longer carry it. Help me, please.
</P>
<P>
   _ Carlie Davis, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: In 1903, Richard Hudnut created the DuBarry Co., one of the
first cosmetics giants in the United States. It was named in honor
of Comtesse Jeanne duBarry, who reflected ``the essence of
beauty.'' The products were especially popular in the '40s and
'50s, but fans have remained loyal to this line, which contains all
types of skin-care products. We found an 8-ounce jar of DuBarry's
Cleansing Cream ($10.95) at Barwick's Pharmacy, Briarcliff Shopping
Center, 2724 Clairmont Road N.E. (404-634-3361). Ingredients
include mineral oil, deionized water, beeswax and paraffin.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Recently, I heard that bison meat is reported to be lower in
fat than beef. Is this true and, if so, where can I find it in the
Atlanta area?
</P>
<P>
   _ Brian Eilertson, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: A bison burger or a hamburger? Which should you eat if you
are watching your fat and calorie intake? Bison is the winner. A
4-ounce serving of bison has 124 calories and 2 grams fat while a
4-ounce serving of beef tenderloin has 179 calories and 8 1/2 grams
fat.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy bison at Whole Foods Grocery, 2111 Briarcliff Road
(404-634-7800). Ground bison ($5.99 a pound) is carried all the
time. The store also stocks bison steaks around holidays such as
July Fourth, Thanksgiving and Christmas. Steaks are $18-$19 a
pound.
</P>
<P>
   Harry's Farmers Market, 1180 Upper Hembree Road, Alpharetta
(770-664-6300) carries bison around holidays, including July
Fourth, Thanksgiving and Christmas. Ground is $4.99 a pound; ribeye
and New York strip steaks are $16.99 a pound. Customers can also
special order bison at other times. Call meat buyer Joe Illescas
(770-664-6300, Ext. 3331). Kroger will also special order bison for
you through its meat departments.
</P>
<P>
   _Contributing: Michelle C. Brooks and Marcia Langhenry
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
