<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thandie Newton was on scene before ``M: I-2''
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For many mainstream moviegoers, Thandie Newton, Tom Cruise's
co-star in ``Mission: Impossible 2,'' may be a relatively new face.
But there are those of us who've known about _ and pretty much
worshipped _ her for almost a decade. Born in Zaire and raised in
England, Newton has a combination of focus, grace and daring that's
unique among today's young actresses. After you fall for her in
``M: I-2,'' check her out in these pictures.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Flirting'' (1991): Set in two prep schools in rural
Australia in 1965, this film has become best known for featuring a
young, pre-Tom Cruise Nicole Kidman. However, Kidman's role as the
school trophy date is actually secondary (though she does stand
out). The real star is Newton who plays a smart, self-possessed
daughter of an African diplomat forced to endure ugly schoolgirl
``witticisms'' about jungles. When she becomes involved with
another outsider _ a weedy white boy who loves Sartre _ their
relationship poses every imaginable threat to their close-minded,
thick-headed schoolmates. ``Flirting'' was Newton's movie debut.
She was all of 16.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Journey of August King'' (1995): The journey in this
underappreciated movie is mostly a spiritual one. Almost biblical
in its 'tis-a-gift-to-be-simple spareness, the picture reunites
Newton with her ``Flirting'' director, John Duigan. It's set in the
mountains of North Carolina in the early 1800s. Jason Patric plays
a farmer who's lost his wife _ and, with her, his sense of who he
is and why he is. Then, reluctantly at first, he helps a teenage
runaway slave (Newton) escape her brutish, vengeful owner (Larry
Drake looking like he fell off the Ugly Tree). Patric, who's done
some scenery chewing in his time (``Speed 2''), gives a lovely,
restrained portrayal. But Newton is the movie. Resisting P.C.
revisionism _ as she did in a similar role as Sally Hemings in the
flawed ``Jefferson in Paris'' _ she never condescends to her
character. It's a performance as breathtakingly delicate as it is
complex.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Besieged'' (1998): This is not director Bernardo
Bertolucci's (``The Last Emperor'') finest hour. Nor is it British
actor David Thewlis' (``Naked''). However, Newton manages to escape
unscathed from this moody fable of a rich, reclusive musician
(Thewlis) who falls in love with his African housekeeper (Newton),
a proud exile who mops by day and studies pre-med by night.
Actually, the film is more bothersome than bad and, being a
Bertolucci work, it can't help but have a few exquisite touches.
The most exquisite, of course, is Newton who, yet again, raises a
problematical role to the level of art. She later said her accent
and gestures were modeled after her mother.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Beloved'' (1998): Maybe it was people had OD'd on Oprah
Winfrey (she was on every magazine cover short of Consumer
Reports). Or maybe it was the three-hour length. Whatever the
reason, ``Beloved'' failed to catch fire at theaters. That's too
bad because this adaptation of Toni Morrison's Pulitzer
Prize-winning novel is a passionate powerhouse of a picture. Think
``Roots'' crossed with ``Poltergeist.'' Winfrey, who produced,
stars as a former slave living in post-Civil War Cincinnati. She
shares her modest house with her shy daughter (Kimberly Elise), her
lover (Danny Glover) and a troubled spirit. ``It ain't evil,''
Winfrey insists. ``Just sad.'' The haunt goes quiet when a
beautiful, childlike creature calling herself Beloved (Newton)
mysteriously shows up and forms an attachment to Winfrey that's
touching and very dangerous. Harmonic convergence note: Newton's
real first name, Thandiwe (she used it in ``Flirting''), means
``beloved'' or ``loved one'' in Zulu.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
