<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kid-friendly sites to inspire future Emerils
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   More and more people are realizing that a lot more goes on in
the kitchen than just eating and preparing food. When kids are not
shooed out of the way but allowed to make a real contribution, a
new world of learning that goes way beyond washing and drying
dishes can open up. Reading, math, chemistry, science, physics,
biology, nutrition, history, geography, botany, art and social
science are just some of what kids will be exposed to as they make
their way around the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   A little hands-on kitchen duty can also lead to increased
self-esteem, personal responsibility, creativity, communication and
just the plain fun and satisfaction of preparing food and having
others enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   Supervision is the key. By taking the time to supervise your
kids in the kitchen, you will be giving them a rich experience that
will likely stay with them for the rest of their lives. And who
knows? You may even launch a future Emeril or a million-dollar
Pillsbury winner.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is loaded with sites geared to kids in the kitchen
and parents who want to get the most out of the experience. Here
are a few:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SAFETY FIRST
</P>
<P>
   First things first. The kitchen is not a playground. There are
fire, electricity, hot surfaces, boiling pots, sharp knives and
implements and any number of accidents waiting to happen. Here are
some sites that every parent should go over.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hurts and Hazards Kids, Kitchen Accidents and Safety at
www.ext.vt.edu/pubs/preschoolnutr/348-655/348-655.html is put
together by the Virginia Cooperative Extension Service, helping
even the youngest child identify potential hazards.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Along the same lines but geared to older kids is Kids in the
Kitchen Without Catastrophe at
www.familyfoodzone.com/cooking/tip.html. Learn good kitchen habits
early and keep them for life. This site provides common-sense
kitchen guidelines for any age.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  HOW OLD?
</P>
<P>
   Just how young can you start introducing your child to the
kitchen? According to some sites, there are a number of activities
that even a pre-K child can handle.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  About.com's Kids in the Kitchen
</P>
<P>
   at
//busycooks.about.com/food/busycooks/library/weekly/aa032999.htm
offers topnotch info for parents as well as kids. Click on Cooking
Skills for Kids for age-appropriate activities for those as young
as 3. For instance, ages 3 to 6 can easily stir ingredients in a
bowl, wash fruits and vegetables, tear lettuce to make salad and
add ingredients to bowls. Ages 6 to 8 can fill and level measuring
cups and spoons, set the table and beat ingredients with a wire
whisk. Ages 8 to 10 can use a microwave. By ages 10 to 12, kids are
ready to use the oven, use a knife with supervision and use a
grater to shred ingredients. By the time they are 13 to 16, they
are ready to prepare recipes independently. The real payoff begins
when you hear the magic words from your offspring: ``You can relax
tonight, I'll make dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Incredible Edibles' Kids in the Kitchen at
www1.sympatico.ca/healthyway
</P>
<P>
   /HEALTHYWAY/archive/reckid.html is a must for parents who want
to do it right. Along with kid-friendly recipes like Pizza by the
Yard and Bunny Hop Salad, there's information on matching tasks to
skill levels, safety tips and the importance of supervision.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More excellent age-appropriate kitchen activities are at
Cooking with Children at www.nncc.org
</P>
<P>
   /Curriculum/fc46cook.kids.html. Even a 2-year-old can break up
bread for stuffing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cooking with Kids at www.weeklyreader
</P>
<P>
   .com/features/cookwka.html sets out instructions for parents on
how to introduce kids from pre-K to first grade to the kitchen.
Easy recipes include sandwich checkerboards and peanut butter
rolls.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For ages 6 to 8, Familyplay at www
</P>
<P>
   .familyplay.com/activities/korner.html provides some excellent
parental tips to get kids involved in meal planning, reading
labels, shopping and preparation.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jell-O Kids Cooking Fun at www.kraftfoods
</P>
<P>
   .com/html/features/jello.html offers great recipes and is an
excellent learning site that includes Cooking Words to Know, where
kids learn such words as boiling, blend, chill, crumble, dissolve
and thaw. Rules of the Kitchen lays out good kitchen habits that
can last a lifetime, including: washing hands with soap and water
before beginning; reading the whole recipe first; collecting all
ingredients; and not skipping steps. One section identifies kitchen
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  JUST FOR KIDS
</P>
<P>
   The internet is a virtual amusement park of food sites just for
kids. Many food companies sponsor food-related sites with contests,
fun stuff, recipes and clubs just for kids who have gotten the
cooking bug. Here are some.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kitchen Kids at www.techedlab.com
</P>
<P>
   /techkids/cooking.html has lots of recipes and links. Kids Food
Cyber Club provides activities for kids from third to fifth grade.
</P>
<P>
   Kelloggs' Kids Kitchen at www.pilotonline
</P>
<P>
   .com/kids/kitchen.html provides a summer's worth of kid-friendly
recipes week by week, along with kitchen tips.
</P>
<P>
   Candy and kids. Go to www.kidscandy.org
</P>
<P>
   /kkitchen.html for some candy recipes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Canadian Living magazine devotes a whole issue to kids in the
kitchen. At www.canadianliving
</P>
<P>
   .com/features/food/kids-in-kitchen/ you'll find great recipes,
especially for older children.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kids Cooking Corner at www
</P>
<P>
   .kidscookingcorner.com/ is loaded with recipes, jokes, games and
a chance for pint-size chefs to talk to each other. Tons of other
related links.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kids Cooking Club at www.kidscook.com
</P>
<P>
   /ABOUT.ASP offers a membership program designed to teach
children all about good food, kitchen safety, nutrition and basic
cooking skills.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Azteca offers a cooking club and kid-size south-of-the-border
recipes at www.aztecafoods.com
</P>
<P>
   /kidrec.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
