<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0918 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-BROADWAY-SEASON-SPI &LR;      05-31 2058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADWAY-SEASON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TONYS A TIME TO LOVE, HONOR, DISOBEY RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFFREY ERIC JENKINS  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the odd marriage of commerce and art that is
Broadway theater, June brings the joy of the season. For theater
people, ordinary rites of passage pale in comparison to the
infighting, oddsmaking and lobbying that surround the Tony Awards.
</P>
<P>
   With the broadcast of the first hour of the ceremony Sunday on
PBS, and the final two hours on CBS, the Broadway theater community
looks back over the past 12 months to honor those who make magic in
the 37 theaters that comprise the Great White Way.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Tony broadcast has seen its audience decline
during the past two decades, it remains the only consistent
national exposure for theater in America. Rosie O'Donnell, whose
syndicated talk show is practically a Broadway-musical worship
service, returns to host the telecast after a hiatus in 1999.
Co-hosting is Broadway veteran Nathan Lane.
</P>
<P>
   Broadway may be the financial pinnacle to which theater artists
can aspire (royalties for writers and composers can run to tens of
thousands of dollars a week), but it is not always the artistic
zenith of the stage. Mainly concerned with musical entertainments,
Broadway has seen plays gradually migrate to off-Broadway _ a
thriving industry of comfy jewel-box theaters with fewer than 500
seats.
</P>
<P>
   Following recent practice, the Pulitzer Prize in drama and the
New York Drama Critics Circle Award for best new play each went to
plays ensconced in off-Broadway houses. Donald Margulies received
the Pulitzer for his hilarious and affecting ``Dinner With
Friends,'' which was directed by former Seattle Rep artistic
director Daniel Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   August Wilson's 1979 play, ``Jitney,'' although hardly new,
received the drama critics' nod for a work that amply shows the
promise of a developing writer. It also features one of the most
powerful acting ensembles in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   The single biggest news item to emerge from Broadway this year,
though, wasn't the dearth of plays, the development of two separate
musical versions of Joseph Moncure March's epic poem, ``The Wild
Party,'' or even Elton John and Tim Rice's glitzy new musical for
Disney, ``Aida.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the announcement that ``Cats,'' which opened in 1982 and
has been the long-run champ since 1997, would close on June 25. The
announcement created a bump in ticket demand and caused the show's
producers to extend the run. On Sept. 10, the fat kitty will sing
one last time and ``Cats'' will fade into memory (let's hope) with
a record 7,485 performances.
</P>
<P>
   SOMETHING OLD
</P>
<P>
   Revivals have long been part of the commercial theater tradition
and this season is no exception. Interesting, though, was the Tony
committee's decision to confer ``new play'' status on Sam Shepard's
20-year-old ``True West.''
</P>
<P>
   While it's true the current production is the first on Broadway
_ and the committee made a similar decision regarding the
playwright's ``Buried Child'' in 1996 _ Shepard's best-known play
had two earlier runs off-Broadway. This time, starring independent
film demigods Philip Seymour Hoffman and John C. Reilly, ``True
West'' certainly has easier competition than it would in the
play-revival category.
</P>
<P>
   The play itself is better than the current production, which is
a slick, facile, go-for-the-obvious-laugh approach. Kurt Beattie's
1997 production at the Seattle Rep was much stronger and more
deeply felt. Closing two weeks after the Tonys and sporting four
nominations, ``True West'' is likely to score none.
</P>
<P>
   A play revivals go, this season has been a lively one. A
high-profile production of Eugene O'Neill's ``A Moon for the
Misbegotten,'' also directed by Sullivan, received positive notices
and has performed nicely at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   However, a British production of Tom Stoppard's meditation on
love and art, ``The Real Thing,'' cruises to success on the
strength of David Leveaux's taut direction and finely crafted
performances by Stephen Dillane and Jennifer Ehle. Look for the
revival Tony to go to the O'Neill play and for ``Real Thing''
actors Dillane and Ehle to be honored.
</P>
<P>
   The Tony Award possibilities turn rosier when it comes to
musical revivals. Leading the parade is ``Kiss Me, Kate'' with 12
nominations, including three actors vying in one category. Giving
``Kate'' a run for its best-musical statue is ``Meredith Willson's
The Music Man'' with eight nominations. While there isn't a thing
wrong with Susan Stroman's direction of ``Music Man'' _ it's the
sort of show that gets you to smile and won't let you stop grinning
_ its homespun, apple-pie Americanism doesn't have the appeal it
once did. ``Music Man'' is a delight, but it misses the emotional
nuances offered by ``Kate.''
</P>
<P>
   The other nominees in the musical-revival category, ``Jesus
Christ Superstar'' and ``Tango Argentino,'' are mere window
dressing to fill the group. ``Superstar,'' which opened Easter
week, is a dreadful failure on every level except one: at the box
office. Roundly and deservedly panned by the critics, this revival
of the 1971 Andrew Lloyd Webber and Tim Rice musical seems ignorant
of progress made in recent years, particularly between Catholics
and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   SOMETHING NEW
</P>
<P>
   Broadway's burdens are nowhere clearer than in the categories of
best new play and best new musical. It is always easier to reach
back in time and revive something that has already succeeded. Far
more difficult is the expensive and adventurous process of
developing new work.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Tony voters have tough choices in the ``new''
categories _ for both plays and musicals. In addition to ``True
West,'' the plays include Arthur Miller's ``The Ride Down Mount
Morgan,'' Claudia Shear's ``Dirty Blonde'' and Michael Frayn's
British import ``Copenhagen.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller's entry in this group means that he has plays nominated
in both the new and revival categories (``The Price''). Originally
staged in England nearly a decade ago and then at off-Broadway's
Joseph Papp Public Theater in 1998, ``Mount Morgan'' surveys the
thought process of a bigamist who believes that it suits everyone _
his wives, his children and himself _ if he is ``true'' to himself
by having two distinct lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mount Morgan'' is an oddity for Miller, who spent years
instructing his audiences about the role of morality in society.
Here the playwright cloaks a fantasy of middle age in clever
arguments that rely on the lead actor's charisma.
</P>
<P>
   Since Patrick Stewart has charm in spades, the production shifts
uncomfortably between a repellent point of view and the utter
delight the character (and we) take in his roguish behavior.
Without Stewart's presence, this piece cannot sustain its specious
argument and that's not a good sign for a play. But touts can never
discount a living playwright of Miller's longevity and success.
</P>
<P>
   Shear's ``Dirty Blonde'' is a plausible candidate to snare the
best new play award. With a simple set and three actors playing a
variety of characters, the playwright attempts to unearth the dark
impulses that fed Mae West's lust for stardom. Shear portrays both
West and an actress much like herself in scenes that shift from now
to the distant past when tough-gal Mae trod the boards.
</P>
<P>
   The production is not without its pleasures, but its great
weakness is Shear's portrayal of West. The only time she truly
captures the essence of the great sex symbol is when West has sunk
into her decrepitude. Shear as the young West lacks the necessary
warmth and earthiness that lurked beneath the legend's exterior.
</P>
<P>
   The great discovery in ``Dirty Blonde,'' however, is journeyman
actor Kevin Chamberlin who plays an obsessed film historian with a
fetishistic secret. His performance shows what the play could be if
a more sympathetic performer handled the female role. Playwright,
fire thyself.
</P>
<P>
   In the musical arena, the choices aren't much easier.
``Contact'' is a dance-play; more ballet than musical, it uses
recorded songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``James Joyce's The Dead,'' which won the critics' prize for new
musical, is a play with lots of music. A lovely and haunting work,
``The Dead'' has already begun to tour and may sneak a win as best
musical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swing!'' probably cannot win due to its revue style _ but at
least the music is live.
</P>
<P>
   Michael John LaChiusa's ``The Wild Party,'' which was unloved by
the critics, may have a slim chance. LaChiusa has toiled in the
musical vineyard for years and has earned a reputation for noble
failures. The drawback for ``Wild Party'' is that a much better
version appeared off-Broadway a month or so before the Broadway
production. LaChiusa also competes with himself for best book and
best score of both ``Wild Party'' and ``Marie Christine.''
</P>
<P>
   Written by Andrew Lippa, the earlier version of ``Wild Party''
closed before attempting a Broadway run when reviews were seen as
too weak. After LaChiusa's Broadway production, though, the critics
seemed to wish they had given more support to Lippa's musical.
</P>
<P>
   SOMETHING BORROWED
</P>
<P>
   In these days of a global economy, it probably doesn't pay to
get worked up over productions that originate in London. Actor's
Equity, however, begs to differ. As with any union, Equity's
mission is to protect the jobs of its membership. Therefore,
whenever a producer wants to bring a member of British Equity to
these shores for a Broadway run, there must be an exchange that
takes an American to London.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, a number of British performances snare headlines and
positive reviews, which leads to more American paranoia. However,
of the 84 nominees this year, only a dozen or so are England-based
and just a handful are expected to win.
</P>
<P>
   A leading candidate for best new play is the British import,
``Copenhagen.'' There are points in this play to make the most
engaged listener glaze over, but the actors battle with passion for
our attention. Although Frayn's play bears more than a passing
resemblance to Sartre's ``No Exit,'' in which three characters
torture one another over the ``truth'' of their existences, the
main attraction of the piece is its intellectual aspiration.
</P>
<P>
   The playwright focuses his tale of love, friendship and betrayal
through the lens of physics. We watch as Niels Bohr and Werner
Heisenberg enact and re-enact a crucial meeting in the 1940s that
has been interpreted again and again in the years since. Bohr, who
provided important assistance to the making of atomic weaponry in
the United States, does a kind of moralizing dance with Heisenberg,
who headed the failed German attempt at creating an atomic bomb
during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   It is interesting, engaging stuff, but almost guaranteed to be a
hard sell on the road. Even with all of the reviews and awards to
date, a recent week saw only 70 percent of the seats filled. Will
it play in Peoria? If it wins best play, the tour operators _ who
are the largest bloc of Tony voters _ will have said, ``Yes.'' The
bet here, though, is, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   SOMETHING BLUE
</P>
<P>
   Pity poor ``Saturday Night Fever.'' A top draw since its bow
last fall, the musical failed even to earn one nomination for its
Broadway run. Lambasted and dismissed by the critics, the show
circumvented its naysayers and built a healthy advance. The past
few weeks, however, have seen attendance figures drop by 30
percent. It may finally demonstrate that audiences won't be fooled
forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lion King'' director Julie Taymor's latest production is an
adaptation of Carlo Gozzi's ``The Green Bird.'' Performed by a
terrific cast who wear Taymor's trademark masks, ``Green Bird'' is
another play that has so much music it might easily be considered a
musical. Cleverly updated by Taymor and Eric Overmyer, the play
seems to be missing something at its core. Awe-inspiring and
beautiful in its theatricality at times, the piece lacks the warmth
and humanity that marked her work for Disney.
</P>
<P>
   So what, finally, is a musical? What is a play? Those
definitions will continue to evolve as Broadway tries to move with
the times.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, it's time to celebrate the pleasures of the
past season and enjoy watching the winners waltz down the aisle
like freshly minted June brides and grooms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 1701EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
