<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0921 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-GRANDPARENTS-RIGHTS-H     05-31 1551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRANDPARENTS-RIGHTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WITH PROBLEMS SPLITTING FAMILIES, GRANDPARENTS SEEK RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KIM COBB  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Tommie Granville and Brad Troxel separated in June 1991,
Tommie was pregnant with their second child. They had never
married, but their Seattle-area family broke into pieces just like
the divorced ones do.
</P>
<P>
   Troxel moved back in with his parents, and Jenifer and Gary
Troxel began enjoying the regular weekend visits of his two
daughters. Then Brad Troxel killed himself in May 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Granville said she was worried about the stress on the girls
when she began trying to limit their visits with their paternal
grandparents. The Troxels hired a lawyer, and almost seven years
later their attempt to force overnight visits with little Natalie
and Isabelle is before the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, whatever the court's decision is we'll be able to
mend fences,'' Jenifer Troxel said. ``I just wanted to be a part of
their lives when they're young because they're so much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The Troxels' battle with their grandchildren's mother is not
uncommon due to the shaky status of the American family. As the
divorce rate has climbed in recent decades, and social problems
such as drug abuse have derailed or destroyed parents, more than
2.5 million grandparents now find themselves raising their
children's children, according to the U.S. Census Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side are people such as the Troxels who fear losing
their grandchildren when parents split, and a burgeoning
grandparents' rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   All 50 states have laws that allow grandparents to petition for
visitation with their grandchildren, largely due to the lobbying
efforts of the AARP. But the Troxel case out of Washington is the
first to test grandparent visitation law before the Supreme Court,
which is expected to rule on the case by July.
</P>
<P>
   Passions run high in these intense family fights.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Mehring of Illinois has been jailed at least part time for
the past six months rather than consent to a court order forcing
her to turn her 7-year-old daughter, Jenna, over for visits with
the girl's paternal grandmother. The parents' rights movement has
turned Mehring into a hero _ the ``P.O.W. Mom.''
</P>
<P>
   And groups such as the American Academy of Matrimonial Lawyers
(AAML) believe much of this issue boils down to the rights of
children, rather than those of the parents or grandparents _ their
right to have relationships with extended family members.
</P>
<P>
   ``As our generation ages there are going to be many, many more
grandparents,'' said AAML attorney Sandy Ain. ``And because divorce
has become so common, these confrontations are becoming more common
and more litigated _ which is in some respects a sad commentary on
our society.''
</P>
<P>
   Every divorce or death of a parent creates a family situation in
which moms or dads are no longer related to the same family as
their child, said Richard Victor, founder of the national
Grandparents Rights Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``So how should we define family _ through the eyes of the
adult, or the eyes of the child when we make decisions pertaining
to family rights?''
</P>
<P>
   Groups such as the American Civil Liberties Union fear that the
very concept of grandparents' rights implies a weakness in
nontraditional families such as single parents and gay and lesbian
couples. In most states it is difficult if not impossible to sue a
legally married couple for visitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our concerns was the possible impact (of a Supreme
Court decision) on gay and lesbian parents,'' said Michael Adams,
associate director of the ACLU gay rights project. ``But our
broadest concern was this was a case about parents' rights vs. the
rights of the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most fundamental issue of this case is that decisions
about children have to be made all the time,'' Adams said. ``Who's
going to make those decisions, the parent or the government?''
</P>
<P>
   The mother doing jail time in Illinois has refused to discuss
the specific nature of the disagreement with her daughter's
grandmother. But Mehring told the St. Louis Post-Dispatch that she
considers her incarceration _ eight hours a day, after which she's
allowed to return home _ a ``mother's sacrifice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to remind people this isn't an argument between two
people. This is about the government going over a parent's head,''
Mehring said. The Washington law being scrutinized in the Troxel
case is broader than the grandparent visitation statutes in other
states, and provides that anyone, whether related or not, can
petition for visitation rights to serve the best interest of the
child.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is so broad, it opened the door for a myriad of
parties with competing agendas to file friend-of-the-court briefs
on how and when the government should be allowed to weigh in on
decisions made for children by their parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been many petitions to the Supreme Court on this
issue, but we were the first case to hit all the issues squarely,''
said Troxel attorney Mark Olsen. ``We had a constitutional issue, a
very broad-based statute, so any ruling would apply to virtually
all the states.''
</P>
<P>
   Victor is frustrated that the Supreme Court is testing the issue
of grandparents' rights in a law unique to the state of Washington.
The clause that allows ``any person, at any time'' to sue for
visitation is simply bad law, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you test a law in an attempt to make public policy, you
really should have a law that is generic, or at least reflective of
the rest of the country,'' Victor said.
</P>
<P>
   The high court could simply strike down the ``any person, any
time'' language as unconstitutional, Victor said, a ruling that
would have no effect in any state but Washington and on no
grandparents other than the Troxels.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What parents' rights groups and the ACLU are seeking is that the
court change the burden of proof most commonly used in grandparent
visitation cases to one that requires the grandparents to prove
that a child would be substantially harmed if they are not allowed
to visit. ``It's a nearly impossible burden of proof,'' Victor
said.
</P>
<P>
   The prevailing standard in most states leaves it up to the
individual judge to determine if court-ordered visitation by
grandparents is in the ``best interest of the child.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the nine Supreme Court justices considering the Troxel case,
six are grandparents. Justice Clarence Thomas was raised by his
grandparents. Jenifer and Gary Troxel believe that their
granddaughters will be harmed emotionally by separation from their
grandparents. But they have no complaint with how their
granddaughters are being raised, only the amount of time their
mother allows them to spend with the girls.
</P>
<P>
   Jenifer Troxel said she thinks that she and her husband serve as
a reminder of a life the girls' mother wants to leave behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she thought she had made a mistake by having a
relationship with our son,'' Troxel said. ``She wanted to begin a
new life.''
</P>
<P>
   The girls' mother, Tommie Granville, married Kelly Wynn shortly
after the district court judge first ordered grandparent
visitation. Wynn adopted the girls in February 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like she thought we were going to hinder her
relationship,'' Troxel said. ``And all we want to do is know our
son's girls.''
</P>
<P>
   In an open letter seeking help with legal expenses before the
Supreme Court heard arguments in January, Kelly Wynn and Tommie
Granville Wynn wrote, ``The Troxels were upset by visitation
arrangements we asked them to accept during a very stressful period
in the girls' lives. At the time, Natalie was 3 and Isabelle was 18
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Troxels wanted to have overnight visitation every other
weekend and holidays and part of the summer,'' according to the
Wynns. ``We asked them to begin with one Sunday a month and hoped
we could begin to build on that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Troxels filed suit, and won court-ordered visitation of one
weekend a month, one week in the summer, and four hours on each
grandparent's birthday. But the Wynns appealed, and the Washington
Supreme Court ultimately ruled that the law allowing ``any person,
any time'' to petition for visitation was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The Troxels then appealed that verdict to the U.S. Supreme
Court, which heard arguments in the case in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having experienced the reality of unnecessary court
intervention in our personal family, we believe that this
interference is completely wrong,'' the Wynns wrote.
``Grandparents' support is always welcome, but court-ordered
visitation is not supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   Troxel said they were still seeing the girls at the time that
she and her husband filed suit, but felt like those visits were
getting fewer and farther between. They decided they had better sue
before the visits disappeared altogether, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the Troxels and the Wynns are strained, at
best, the grandmother said. She said she sends Natalie and Isabelle
cards and letters, but she and her husband have not seen the girls
in more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we just have to start out with a couple of hours,
we're willing to try anything,'' Troxel said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
