<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV18-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., JUNE 18, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: I have to cut some rectangular openings for electric outlet
boxes in the middle of a sheet of plywood.
 &HT;    I've done this by first drilling a starting hole for the blade
in each corner of the outline, then using a small tapered handsaw
to cut around the outline.
 &HT;    However, I now own an electric sabre saw and have been told that
there is no need for drilling a starting hole _ the blade can start
its own hole if properly used.
 &HT;    I tried this but broke the blade.
 &HT;    Can you tell me the right way to get such a cut-out started
without having to bore any starting holes first?
 &HT;    A: Tip the saw's base all the way forward so that its front end
rests on the plywood with the tip end of the blade not quite
touching the wood along one side of the penciled outline.
 &HT;    Turn on the saw and slowly tilt it back down onto the plywood
and allow the reciprocating blade to start scratching the surface.
 &HT;    Keep lowering the base of the saw until its blade cuts through
the plywood and the saw's base is flat against the surface of the
wood, then proceed to cut along all four sides of the outline.
 &HT;    You can make angled cuts from one side of the outline to the
other when necessary to cut out square corners without having to
make any more starting cuts.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Our old bedroom dresser which is covered with mahogany wood
veneer has a bad cigarette burn on the top.
 &HT;    Stain will not cover up this black scorch mark and the veneer is
burnt off in a small area.
 &HT;    Is there any way you know of that I can cover up or patch the
veneer in order to make the stain less noticeable?
 &HT;    A: The best way would be to cut out the damaged section of wood
veneer and then fill in with another piece of matching wood veneer.
 &HT;    Since finding a matching piece of veneer is not easy, your best
bet would be to use a razor blade and metal straightedge to cut out
a small piece of the original veneer from an inconspicuous surface
on the same piece of furniture _ along a hidden side or near a back
corner.
 &HT;    After cutting out a rectangular patch, lift it off carefully by
sliding the razor blade under the veneer.
 &HT;    Place this piece on top of the damaged section and move it
around until its grain pattern lines up with that of the veneer
under it.
 &HT;    Then tape it down and use the razor to cut through both layers
of veneer at one time _ that is, the new patch and the damaged
veneer under it.
 &HT;    Lift off the top piece and peel out the piece of damaged veneer,
then glue the new piece down in the cut-out just made.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Our house has a crawl space instead of a full basement and
this space has an uncovered dirt floor.
 &HT;    There are signs of mildew showing up on the exposed floor joists
in this crawl space, and there is a musty odor that is starting to
seep up into the house.
 &HT;    What can I do to correct this condition?
 &HT;    A: The dirt floor should be completely covered with sheets of
heavy plastic to keep moisture from seeping up into the house.
 &HT;    The sheets should overlap at least 6 inches where they meet, and
bricks or stones should be put on top to hold the seams in place.
 &HT;    The plastic should also lap up onto the foundation walls by 6
inches on all sides and you should make sure there is adequate
ventilation of the crawl space to avoid condensation problems.
 &HT;    Vents are needed in the foundation walls on all four sides.
These should be large enough to provide at least 1 square foot of
unobstructed opening for every 300 square feet of floor space (if
vents have louvers and screens they must be twice as large).
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: The main sewer pipes inside our basement are made of PVC
plastic.
 &HT;    They make a lot of annoying noise each time we flush one of the
upstairs toilets.
 &HT;    The plumber says that we have a proper vent system that is not
plugged, so there is really nothing he can do.
 &HT;    Can you suggest anything?
 &HT;    A: The noise you hear is the sound of water rushing through the
drain pipes each time the toilet is flushed. This is not unusual
with plastic drain lines that are exposed.
 &HT;    The only suggestion I can offer is to ``box in'' or enclose
these pipes by first wrapping them with acoustical insulation and
then enclosing them with plywood or drywall panels.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NOTE: Drawing captioned ``MAKING A POCKET CUT'' goes with this
column.
 &HT;    CAPTION: Tilting sabre saw, as shown, when starting cut will
enable blade to cut into and through plywood without having to
drill a starting hole first.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
