<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0940 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CLINTON-EU-0601-COX     05-31 1414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EU-0601-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON WARNS OF 'URGENCY IN MIDEAST, SUPPORTS SHARED OF MISSILE
DEFENSE
 &HT;    (600&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LISBON, Portugal _ Trying to press Palestinian and Israeli
leaders toward a long-sought peace accord, President Clinton warned
Wednesday that Israel's surprise withdrawal from Lebanon last week
has added ``a new sense of urgency,'' to the search for peace in
the troubled Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   ``It changed the landscape,'' said Clinton, who spoke by
telephone Wednesday with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and was
to meet Thursday here with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It both turns the tension up in all camps, and increases the
overall price of not reaching an agreement fairly soon,'' Clinton
told reporters. ``It changes everything, in a way that both
increases the pluses and increases the potential minuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Clinton said he supports sharing the benefits of a
proposed national missile defense system beyond U.S. borders, to
American allies and other nations that are committed to controlling
the spread of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said such benefits could even extend to Russia, adding
that it would be ``unethical'' to deny the protections of advanced
missile defense technology to countries that see eye-to-eye with
the United States on nuclear nonproliferation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always said that ... every country that is part of a
responsible international arms control and nonproliferation regime
should have the benefit of this protection,'' said Clinton.
``That's always been my position.''
</P>
<P>
   His remarks were made in response to questions at a news
conference following a summit here with Portuguese Prime Minister
Antonio Guterres and European Commission President Romano Prodi.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments on national missile defense came a week after
Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential
nominee, said a U.S. missile shield should be far more
comprehensive than the system Clinton has proposed, adding that it
should also protect Israel and other U.S. allies from a rogue
missile attack.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, though, said he had long favored protection for other
countries, and not only U.S. allies. Further, he suggested that the
same was true for Vice President Al Gore, on track to become the
Democrats' presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that we could ever advance the notion that we
have this technology designed to protect us against a new threat
... to other civilized nations who might or might not be nuclear
powers, but were completely in harness with us on a
nonproliferation regime, and not make it available to them,''
Clinton said. ``I think it would be unethical not to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's always been my position and I think that is the
position of everyone in this administration,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing in the gardens of Portugal's stately Palacio Nacional
de Queluz, Clinton, Prodi and Guterres all hailed the strength of
U.S-European relations. They announced a host of low-octane
agreements, mostly reaffirming previous policies such as support
for stability and democracy in the Balkans, implementation of an
earlier accord protecting American companies from data piracy on
the Internet and a determination to work out trade disputes through
the World Trade Organization (WTO), rather than engaging in
tit-for-tat transatlantic trade skirmishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided also that megaphone diplomacy will be replaced by
telephone diplomacy,'' Prodi said. ``It is more constructive, even
less sexy.''
</P>
<P>
   There was agreement, also, on a broad U.S.-E.U. initiative to
combat AIDS, malaria and tuberculosis in poor countries and a
strengthening, the three leaders said, of the security ties binding
the two continents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a business-as-usual summit,'' Guterres said. ``It
was a stragetic summit.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-European summitry was overshadowed, however, by the two
most ambitious foreign policy challenges Clinton is likely to face
in his remaining months in office _ the question of whether to
build a national missile defense system and the search for an end
to half a century of enmity and war in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is weighing whether to build a limited national missile
defense system that would help defend the U.S. from a ballistic
missile attack from so-called ``rogue states,'' unpredictable and
considered a potential danger to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon plans to test the key technology _ using a U.S.
missile to intercept and destroy an incoming enemy missile _ in
July and to make recommendations to Clinton, probably by September,
as to the advisability of installing a powerful set of radar
stations in Alaska, along with 100 interceptors. At a cost
estimated at between $26 billion and $60 billion, that system would
be able, supporters claim, to protect the entire United States from
a trans-Pacific missile attack of limited order.
</P>
<P>
   The matter will be near the top of a crowded agenda when Clinton
travels to Moscow Saturday for two days of summitry with Russia's
new president, Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Russia opposes the missile defense system, which it regards as
undercutting the deterrent value of its own nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he hopes to explain to Putin that such a system
could be a tool for stability and even added security for both
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done a lot of information sharing already with the
Russians,'' Clinton said. ``We have offered to do more, and we
would continue to.''
</P>
<P>
   The administrations of Putin and Clinton agree that a missile
defense system would require changes to the Nixon-era
Anti-Ballistic Missile (ABM) Treaty, which restricts defense
shields of both nations as a way to deter systems that could fuel
an arms race.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders are also in the opening stages of talks over a
third Strategic Arms Reductions Treaty (START), with Russia
favoring deeper cuts than the United States is so far prepared to
accept.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he didn't expect to resolve either issue during
this weekend's visit _ his first with Putin since the former KGB
officer was elected president two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be surprised if we resolved all of our differences on
the question of missile defense, although we might make more
headway than most people expect,'' said Clinton. ``Sometimes it's
most important to be talking when there's still unresolved
differences.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is hoping, on a separate front, to help bridge
differences between Israelis and Palestinians. With negotiators
from both sides set to meet in Stockholm Thursday to resume
working-level peace talks, Clinton is hopeful that he can host
Barak and Arafat for a face-to-face summit in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The two Middle East leaders are working to resolve their
outstanding land-for-peace issues _ including such tough matters as
the future of Jerusalem, the question of Palestinian statehood and
the right of Palestinian refugees to return to Israeli-held lands _
by September 13.
</P>
<P>
   Recent Israeli-Palestinian violence in Gaza and the West Bank
have raised doubts about the men's ability to make that deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's surprise decision last week, though, to pull Israeli
troops out of southern Lebanon, ending an 18-year occupation, has
sharply shifted the dynamic, said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The move was ``a daring one, which creates both new challenges
and new opportunities,'' said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also imposes a much greater sense of urgency,'' he said.
``I think the consequences of inaction are now likely to be more
difficult because of this move.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton telephoned Arafat immediately after his press
conference, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said, then Clinton
dashed off for a round of golf on a course 20 minutes outside of
Lisbon.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to meet with Barak in Lisbon Thursday
morning, before journeying to Berlin, stop two on a week-long swing
that takes him to Russia this weekend. On Monday he travels to the
Ukraine before returning to Washington late that night.
</P>
<P>
   Barak had originally planned to meet with Clinton in Berlin, but
Clinton said an Israeli holiday would prevent that.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
