<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0941 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0601-COX     05-31 1923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0601-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Focusing on the military . . .
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush promoted his plan today to increase military
weapons research as a way to boost the morale and firepower of
American forces. ``The best way to keep the peace is not to match
every conceivable threat weapon for weapon or division for
division, but to redefine war on our terms,'' he said, standing
next to new Marine recruits and graying military veterans at the
New Mexico Veterans Memorial Park. ``That means giving United
States troops the technological superiority that they need to
prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   . . . ESTABLISHING LEADERSHIP CREDENTIALS . . .
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, in leading the Republican charge against the
Clinton-Gore record on military matters, is attempting to step out
from the shadow of John McCain, a Vietnam POW and his former
primary foe. Bush, by focusing on defense issues just ahead of
U.S.-Russia arms talks, also is hoping to counter his lack of
foreign policy experience compared to Democratic opponent Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   . . . AND RAISING MORE MONEY
</P>
<P>
   All the stops on George W. Bush's four-day trek through the West
will prove fertile _ with money. Bush reaped an estimated $100,000
at a luncheon in Denver, and another $300,000 for the Republican
National Committee and $125,000 for the New Mexico Republican Party
at a reception in Albuquerque. By week's end, after visits to
Arizona and Nevada as well, Bush should collect $350,000 for his
own campaign, $200,000 for state GOP organizations and about $2
million for the national committee, campaign officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A PUSH ON MENTAL HEALTH . . .
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual joint campaign appearance with wife Tipper today
in Chevy Chase, Md., Al Gore proposed requiring insurance companies
to cover mental health services for children under the same
co-payments and deductibles used for other health benefits. He also
called for special mental health training for all new teachers and
promised to fight for strong patient rights to privacy. Gore said
his child-only insurance proposal, like his plan for universal
health insurance for children, would help build momentum for what's
called ``parity'' in benefits for all patients.
</P>
<P>
   . . . AND PLAYING UP THE PERSONAL
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's campaign schedule is reflecting an attempt to
highlight the personal stories of his life. Today, he and wife
Tipper discussed mental health and Mrs. Gore talked about the
depression she suffered in 1989 after her son, then 6, was almost
killed in a car accident. On Thursday in Atlanta, Gore will speak
out for the privacy and treatment rights of people with cancer,
which killed his older sister in 1984. Friday's topic, in
Washington, is fatherhood. On Memorial Day, he told veterans about
his decision to enlist in the Army and volunteer for Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   POP QUIZ
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Senate candidate wants to boost public education,
protect the environment, wire up schools to the Internet and
protect health benefits for the disadvantaged. Oh, and no
mudslinging on the campaign trail. It's all about issues. Who is
the candidate? Republican Rick Lazio or Democrat Hillary Clinton?
Both. For all of the talk of stark differences, the congressman is
espousing many of the same themes that the first lady has embraced
in her 10 months on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   CO-OPTING THE CENTER
</P>
<P>
   Starting a first full day of campaigning aboard his ``Mainstream
Express'' bus today, Republican Rick Lazio said his race against
Hillary Clinton was ``a struggle between somebody on the far left
and somebody in the center.'' The Long Island congressman, the
unanimous pick of his party's state convention, said he had given
the bus its nickname ``to reinforce my record in the House, which
is a mainstream record, which is, I think, where the vast majority
of New Yorkers are.''
</P>
<P>
   MCAIN LIKING WHAT HE SEES IN BUSH . . .
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's recent statements on arms-control policy,
missile defense and trade with China have drawn hearty praise from
John McCain. In a Wall Street Journal opinion piece, McCain
applauded Bush for embracing internationalist positions that
benefit America's interests. Now, McCain lamented, if only more
Republicans in Congress would follow Bush's lead. McCain is
shunning Bush's three Arizona fund-raisers today, though, because
of those ``soft money'' donations he's campaigned against.
</P>
<P>
   . . . AND SPREADING HIS MAGIC IN CALIFORNIA
</P>
<P>
   John McCain is endorsing Tom Campbell for Senate in California,
a move Campbell hopes will boost his appeal to fellow Republicans
and non-Republicans alike. McCain and the GOP congressman from
Silicon Valley were appearing together today for the announcement.
Campbell is aiming to unseat second-term Democratic Sen. Dianne
Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   BUT IT'S BUSH'S STATE, ANYWAY
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party, with its roots in the presidential campaigns
of Dallas billionaire Ross Perot, will not be on the statewide
ballot in November. The party notified the state's elections
division that it would not file a petition to place its candidates
on the ballot. Kelly Abt, a member of the party's national
committee from Texas, said the two major parties made it too
difficult for his party, which has never been on the ballot, to get
on this year.
</P>
<P>
   A ROLE FOR MADISON AVENUE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush is turning to an executive of one of the nation's
best-known advertising agency, Young &AMP; Rubicam, for creative
suggestions on TV spots. Jim Ferguson, the ad agency's chief
creative officer, has accepted an unpaid, advisory role in the
campaign, said Stuart Stevens, a Republican consultant and a member
of Maverick Media, the advertising arm of the Bush campaign.
Stevens said Ferguson will assemble an informal group of people in
New York who may be asked to help write Bush's TV ads.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA CLUB RESERVATION . . .
</P>
<P>
   A Sierra Club board member wrote colleagues six months ago to
urge they not endorse Al Gore, arguing the vice president had a
``tawdry environmental record'' and left natural resources
``hostage to the highest bidder. With this legacy, no real
environmentalist could ever endorse Al Gore,'' Michael Dorsey wrote
in an internal e-mail copied to Gore. The message was released by
the Republican National Committee. Six months after the e-mail, the
Sierra Club is airing $250,000 worth of ads criticizing George W.
Bush for his environmental record in Texas, but has not endorsed
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   . . . AND THE SENTIMENT IS SECONDED
</P>
<P>
   A pioneer in the environmental movement joined Sierra Club board
member Michael Dorsey in criticizing Al Gore's ``tawdry
environmental record.'' David Brower, the club's executive director
in the 1950s and1960s, said that when he resigned from the board
earlier this month he urged that they support Ralph Nader. ``The
other two (presidential) candidates are really the same color'' on
environmental issues, and ``it's too bad,'' the 87-year-old Brower
told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   CLOSE TO THE VEST ON VEEP
</P>
<P>
   For all the speculation, George W. Bush says only two other
people know what's going on in his thinking about a running mate:
his wife, Laura, and Dick Cheney, who is heading the search. Asked
about the process, Bush scoffed and said, ``Total gossip.'' He said
his wife is simply interested in the process, while he and Cheney,
a former secretary of defense, speak regularly to plot strategy.
Bush suggested that some of the speculation is fueled by the way he
reacts to suggestions: ``I say, `I appreciate that piece of
advice,' and all of a sudden that becomes `inside information.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ANYBODY SEEN BRADLEY?
</P>
<P>
   After withdrawing from the presidential race March 9 and
offering Democratic rival Al Gore his support but not his outright
endorsement, Bill Bradley has disappeared from the national stage.
There have been no public comments or events, no fund-raising or
campaigning for congressional candidates. And there has been no
get-together to make peace with the man who pummeled him in the
primaries. Bradley aides said the former senator is still living in
Montclair, N.J., getting ready to close his campaign office and
trying to figure out what to do with his life.
</P>
<P>
   READ HER LIPS: NEW TAXES
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire Gov. Jeanne Shaheen said she plans to run for a
third term _ but won't renew her pledge to veto an income tax.
Failing to take the pledge to veto broad-based taxes historically
has been a kiss of death in New Hampshire. But there's a changed
landscape this year: an education funding crisis triggered by a
1997 court ruling that demanded they find a fairer way to pay for
schools, and other candidates are campaigning for an income tax as
the means to do it.
</P>
<P>
   MOSCOW ON THE HUDSON?
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Senate hopeful Jim Florio lashed out at Democratic
rival Jon Corzine for using private detectives in their primary
campaign. Florio claimed operatives hired by Corzine's attorney
called several of his staff members asking for personal information
about him, his family and key advisers. Florio, a former governor,
said the investigators were involved with the campaign against
tobacco company informant Jeffrey Wigand. ``It sounds like the
KGB,'' Florio said. Corzine, an ex-Wall Street executive, said he
was unaware his attorney, Stanley Arkin, had hired the sleuths.
</P>
<P>
   PRETTY PRICY CHEAP EATS
</P>
<P>
   For the famished at the Republican convention in Philadelphia,
$165 will buy a ``Snacks and Junk'' basket, with a dozen Tastykakes
and a dozen soft pretzels, a bag each of Oreos, chocolate chip
cookies and potato chips, and six Hershey's chocolate bars and six
bags of peanut M&AMP;Ms. For the really hungry, $249 will fetch a
2-foot-long Italian hoagie, plus a quart each of pasta and potato
salads, a dozen Tastykakes and a dozen pretzels. Aramark, the
exclusive caterer, also will feed Democrats at their convention in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ACROSS THE CANADIAN BORDER, THEY'RE CHEAPER
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Slade Gorton (R-Wash.) formally began his re-election
campaign with a five-day bus tour of the state. Gorton, 72, vowed
to make the rising cost of prescription drugs a centerpiece of his
campaign. He's introduced a bill that would bar drug manufacturers
from charging Americans more for prescriptions than they charge
patients in other countries. A September primary will determine
Gorton's Democratic opponent, either state Insurance Commissioner
Deborah Senn or former Rep. Maria Cantwell, now an Internet
executive.
</P>
<P>
   WATCH OUT! HERE COMES THE WEASEL
</P>
<P>
   Rep. George Nethercutt (R-Wash.), who can thank the term-limits
movement for helping him unseat House Speaker Tom Foley in 1994, is
running for a fourth term despite his promise to serve only six
years. Cartoonist Garry Trudeau dubbed Nethercutt ``Weasel King''
in ``Doonesbury'' last year, and since then George the Weasel King,
a costumed, crowned animal character sponsored by U.S. Term Limits,
follows Nethercutt around, taunting him. U.S. Term Limits says
Nethercutt is one of three members of the congressional class of
1994 who broke term-limits pledges. The others: Marty Meehan
(D-Mass.) and Scott McInnis (R-Colo.).
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
