<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0942 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WOMEN-FILMMAKERS-$ADV     05-31 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-FILMMAKERS-$ADV04-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLIMPSES INSIDE A WORLD BARELY IMAGINED BY MEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 4) 
 By MOLLY HASKELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Love is a minefield, but women would rather blow up than be
single,'' says the unflappable heroine of ``Love and Sex,'' Valerie
Breiman's romantic comedy (opening in August) that could be the
female response to ``High Fidelity.'' Kate (Famke Janssen), the
movie's Don Juanita, casts an eye over the loves of her life,
affectionately sending up the pretenses of men as she surveys
sexual warfare in the trenches from a survivor's-eye view. She has
emerged bloody but unbowed, having withstood even a traumatic
childhood passion which in the film's hilarious opening flashback
locates the love-hate roots of screwball comedy squarely in the
playground.
</P>
<P>
   Two 12-year-olds are mutually smitten, but only one of them _
the girl, of course _ can admit it. To protect her beloved's
reputation as an officially girl-hating male, little Kate allows
Bobby to call her names and shove her in public so that his
tough-guy buddies won't know he's in love.
</P>
<P>
   She then loses him when her own best friend rats on her and
reveals the couple's trick. ``Among the many differences between
man and woman when it comes to love,'' the now older and wiser Kate
says ruefully, ``is women's need to tell the world every little
detail.''
</P>
<P>
   The need to discuss love and sex from a female point of view
coupled with a new freedom to do so would seem to be the launching
pad of a gaggle of women-directed movies, many of them first films,
that take us behind the scenes to a world barely imagined and
perhaps not entirely welcomed by men. It's a world of whispers and
confidences and giggles and tears, a great many gradations of
sensuality, from the barely understood to the actively carnal,
along a wide spectrum of appetites and longings; a portrait of sex
that differs from the male variety in being both sadder and more
humorous. Colette Burson's ``Coming Soon,'' a female
rite-of-passage and right-to-orgasm film that opened last month,
might be the ``she said'' version of the ``he said'' teen picture
`American Pie,'' or a prep school prequel to HBO's ``Sex and the
City.'' A trio of seniors, best friends, discuss orgasms, boys and
getting into college, trying to sort out their relative importance.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Virgin Suicides,'' Sofia Coppola's recent magical
adaptation of Jeffrey Eugenides' 1993 novel, the five Lisbon
sisters share such an intense togetherness in their feverish,
cloistered adolescence that they are like a single organism.
</P>
<P>
   Not only the attitudes, but the actresses in these made-by-women
movies defy conventional male and Hollywood criteria for
seductiveness and sex appeal. The heroines aren't always the
glamour pusses of movie-star gloss or men's wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Kirsten Dunst, as the sexually precocious 14-year-old Lux
Lisbon, is lovely, but closed off and opaque in her bafflement, and
the other three sisters (after the death of the youngest, Cecilia)
are appropriately blurred, almost indistinguishable. Where a male
director might have selected five ready-for-my-close-up babes for
the roles, Sofia Coppola has managed to cast and direct them as a
collective, girls whose tragedy is precisely that they never had a
chance to become remarkable or individual.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Coming Soon'' (with a screenplay by Burson and Kate Robin),
Stream, the main character, is played by the freckled and often
scruffy Bonnie Root. She is less stunning than one sidekick _
Tricia Vessey, a comically depressed beauty who becomes a model _
but more straightforward than the third member of the trio, Gaby
Hoffman's unhappily overweight sexpert who mingles lies and bitter
truths in a defensive response to the constant and combined
pressures of college entrance and orgasmic ecstasy. In her
determination to find out what the fuss is all about, Stream is no
shy blossom waiting to be plucked but an intrepid explorer, testing
her reactions against the alleged experiences of her friends; nor
does she suffer the consequences that once lay in store for good
girls who strayed from the straight and narrow.
</P>
<P>
   Famke Janssen's Kate in ``Love and Sex,'' a writer and editor at
a women's magazine, is model-tall but real-woman funny, a
lay-it-on-the-line type of heroine who shows the disadvantages of
being a string bean among peas and butter beans. As the little girl
who conspires in her oppression on the playground, she's 6 inches
taller than the swaggering tot boyfriend she worships, and the guys
never catch up.
</P>
<P>
   On their first date, the artist (Jon Favreau) who becomes the
love of her life says, ``You're the tallest woman I've ever
known,'' then has the gall to ask her shoe size.
</P>
<P>
   The two connect with the spacey, goofy eroticism of a Woody
Allen-Diane Keaton couple, and Janssen and some of the other odd
enchantresses of recent women's movies _ Hilary Swank and Chloe
Sevigny in Kimberly Peirce's ``Boys Don't Cry,'' Kate Winslet in
Jane Campion's ``Holy Smoke'' _ represent a new type: attractive
enough to make demands, but neither coy nor narcissistic. ``This is
what I want. What do you want?'' they seem to say.
</P>
<P>
   French movies, which have always found sexiness and fascination
in a wider range of women, have recently featured such offbeat
stars as Sandrine Kiberlain and the versatile, dark-haired,
pale-skinned Karin Viard, who is mesmerizing in two women's films,
Solveig Anspach's ``Haut les Coeurs'' (shown at Rendez-Vous with
French Cinema at Lincoln Center in March), where she plays a woman
struggling with breast cancer, and Catherine Corsini's ``La
Nouvelle Eve'' (at Rendez-Vous last year), in which she's a
terrorista of love.
</P>
<P>
   The girls in ``The Virgin Suicides'' range in age from 13 to 17,
roughly the equivalent of the boys across the way whose narration,
in book and film, charts the girls' brief lives and mysterious
deaths. Yet despite a strict upbringing in which their repressed
and domineering mother (a brilliant Kathleen Turner, tight-lipped
and inscrutable) has isolated them from any socializing outside of
school, the girls are nevertheless, and typically, light years
ahead of the stumbling, gawky guys who adore them from afar. Yet
their poise and maturity are in some sense a sham, a mask or at
least a veneer, intimidating to the boys, but only on their home
ground where they form a united front.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Their family is collapsing from within, a plant poisoned at its
roots. Lux, the only one who does get out, who speaks for herself
or who asserts her desires, gets violently punished, and her
sisters along with her. In the '70s, when the story is set, a woman
who is free with her favors is branded a tart. Just how different
is it today? This question and its implications serve as the
thematic motif of most of the teen films, whether guy or chick
oriented.
</P>
<P>
   But where guy films hinge on a binary system as rigid as a
computer, the women's films take a more nuanced approach to sex and
its permutations, and the varying degrees of enthusiasm for it.
They refuse to be pinned down by the coitus-or-bust philosophy, or
the either-or vision of women as tarts or virgins, straight or gay,
lusty or prudish. In Gil Junger's ``Ten Things I Hate About You''
(1999), one of the few male-directed teen films that allows its
heroine to talk back, Julia Stiles brazenly ridicules the
monomaniacal and hormonally indiscriminate male. ``Oh, yeah, let's
do it in the back seat right now!'' she says, her sarcasm letting
the guys know just how charming their idea of nirvana is to her.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a common enemy in these films, it's not the men but
the cheerleader view of sex perpetrated by the women's magazines.
In ``Coming Soon,'' Stream memorably lashes out at the very idea of
the Cosmo girl, and at the other extreme, in ``The Virgin
Suicides,'' Lisbon has banished all such magazines from the house.
As Eugenides writes, ``Mrs. Lisbon had never given the girls beauty
tips, and forbade women's magazines in the house (a Cosmo survey,
`Are you multiply orgasmic?' had been the final straw).''
</P>
<P>
   In their relentless and mechanistic focus on sexual
satisfaction, these magazines have put women on the spot, ratcheted
up the pressure to experience constant and fulfilled sex lives.
``What about liking the guy?'' the girls in ``Coming Soon'' wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Burson's ``Coming Soon'' had a hard time finding
a distributor, almost got an NC-17 rating (with behavior far less
sexually graphic than that of ``American Pie'') and seems to have
earned unusually hostile reactions not only from men in the
industry but from male critics who complain of its
``amateurishness.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearing women talk about sex makes men nervous, like those
giggling groups of girls in high school _ and high school hovers
over the proceedings like a bad dream; having constructed an
identity that passes as adult, confident in the world, we don't
want to revisit the trauma of anxiety and rejection. It was one
thing for guys in movies to tell dirty jokes in the locker room,
compare notes on the sexual attributes of various girls, take bets
on getting some and rate girls on a scale of one to 10.
</P>
<P>
   But they didn't bargain for the reverse, for getting rated in
return. The idea of the sexually insatiable woman was a delirious
fantasy that in reality posed only terror for the man who might not
be able to satisfy. Hence the pathologizing of female promiscuity
as nymphomania _ a term that, as Carol Groneman points out in her
fascinating new book on the subject, ``Nymphomania,'' has undergone
almost comical permutations according to each of the anxieties and
misogynies in society's ever-changing view of acceptable female
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Decline of the American Empire' (1986), the Canadian
director Denys Arcand's wonderfully even-handed and now-classic
dark comedy of the sexes (he also wrote the screenplay), the
endlessly voluble and confessional women discuss their affairs with
each other, just like their husbands and lovers.
</P>
<P>
   When the moment comes, a woman knows just how to drive her man
crazy: ``Jean, I love you; with Jacques it's nothing but sex ...''
Women were supposed to be the sweeter sex, the redeemers _ or, if
sexual, the entrappers, responsible for man's downfall.
</P>
<P>
   Male anxiety over independent women often translates into a
demonizing of the sexually spirited female. In ``Fatal
Attraction,'' Glenn Close comes on to poor Michael Douglas like a
harpy in heat, and more recently in the Danish film ``Mifune,'' in
a gratuitous and surprisingly nasty scene, the hero is stunned on
his wedding night by his bride's unbridled lust.
</P>
<P>
   There have been films over the years that give us glimpses of
that once taboo subject _ young women's sexual initiation _ but the
predominant view of the mating experience, especially in the
hormonally driven teen-age years, has been male. A notable
exception was Amy Heckerling's ``Fast Times at Ridgemont High''
(1982), a funny, poignant adaption of Cameron Crowe's story about
surfers and make-out artists in Southern California which showed
the holy grail of sexual initiation as something more shadowed and
equivocal where the girls were concerned. As in Heckerling's
glorious ``Clueless'' (1995) and her forthcoming ``Loser'' (with
Jason Biggs and Mena Suvari), the director exhibits a genius for
getting into the heads and libidos of a whole gamut of high school
types, male and female, nerds and royalty.
</P>
<P>
   Eugenides, the novelist, shows in ``The Virgin Suicides'' the
same extraordinary ability to imagine life from both sides of the
fence in his portrait of five girls who baffle and entrance a group
of boys. Looking at them from across the street, collecting
mementoes when they are gone, the guys probe, pry, spy and try to
imagine the lives of human beings so close to them and yet so far,
and finally realize the very limits of understanding. In a line
lifted directly from book to film, ``We felt the imprisonment of
being a girl, the way it made your mind active and dreamy.'' In her
astonishingly subtle evocation of that bevy of sisters, Coppola
(who wrote and directed) captures both the mystery and the
yearning, and finally the sense of the hiddenness of all lives, of
differences and similarities between male and female which make the
struggle to understand both so difficult and so endlessly
compelling.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly the movie's most charming and revealing scene occurs
when the boys and girls go on a group date to the prom _ the Lisbon
sisters' first and only social outing. All crammed into the same
car, the boys are stunned to hear the girls talking about
everything from one neighbor's house improvements to another's
rumored Nazism. That these creatures who existed only in pantomime,
wafting lyrically and mysteriously behind glass windows, were in
reality chatterboxes who had looked out just as the boys had looked
in, radically alters the voyeuristic equation. The awesomely
unknown, silent Female of romantic illusion suddenly and
confusingly mutates into four living and breathing girls, voluble,
idiosyncratic, full of opinions, human beings not so different from
themselves. That is, until the sisters merge again in death, and
are once again silenced, now by the deep freeze of memory: forever
young, forever fair, virginity intact.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
