<HEADER>
A0946 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-POWER-FAILURE-NYT     05-31 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-POWER-FAILURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFTWARE TO PREDICT POWER NEEDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By IAN AUSTEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If nothing else, most American computer users have been able to
count on one thing: electricity to run their machines. But high
demands for electricity this summer could produce power shortages
like those in parts of the country last year.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study led by the Sandia National Laboratories, however,
concludes that one remedy for the nation's overburdened power grid
may be rethinking the software that oversees it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very difficult time for the electrical industry,''
said Mark Ivey, principal member of the technical staff at Sandia
and a co-author of the study for the Department of Energy. ``A lot
of people out there are just running to stay ahead of the next
emergency. They don't have the time to sit back and think.''
</P>
<P>
   The study, with the unwieldy title ``Grid of the Future White
Paper on Accommodating Uncertainty in Planning and Operations,''
suggests that utility planners and operators begin using software
that judges the probability of risks to the power system.
</P>
<P>
   Ivey compares the programs to the Eight Ball toys, which contain
a floating polygon with different predictions printed on each of
its facets. When the ball is tipped over, only one prediction is
revealed at a time through the window on the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Risk assessment software involves inserting scenarios of
everything that can go awry on the power grid into a computer,
rather like putting the predictions inside the Eight Ball. Then,
using a variety of factors, sophisticated software could calculate
how frequently and under what circumstances each of the scenarios
would pop up.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations use probability predicting software to manage
production, but Ivey said that most of it was not sophisticated
enough for the extremely complex power grid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The grid is sufficiently specialized that it's going to take a
directed, concentrated and expensive effort to get something that's
useful,'' Ivey said.
</P>
<P>
   Many players in the power grid that serves more than 400 million
people in the United States, Canada and Northern Mexico have not
modified the software they use to plan and control the network, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Ivey, who is also working on a climate change research project,
said that he was concerned by the way power companies use weather
data from the past 10 years and data on the past year's electricity
demands in determining future power needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The planner at one utility told me that to forecast future
demand she takes last year's numbers and adds a factor to them,''
he said. ``That kind of backward looking approach is getting people
into trouble. With the changing complexity of the grid, we're
heading for a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Even small miscalculations in forecasts can mean trouble. A
difference in demand of 1 percent for most parts of the grid (it is
broken into several segments across the continent) could represent
the entire output of a major generating station, Ivey said.
</P>
<P>
   One starting point being explored at Sandia, a Department of
Energy laboratory that is operated by a subsidiary of Lockheed
Martin, is software that is currently used to analyze the
reliability and maintenance of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But Ivey said that any software would encounter major
statistical problems without some changes in industry habits. A
competitive utility market has made many electrical companies
reluctant to part with statistics for fear the data will be used by
competitors. And much of the data that they do release proves to be
outdated or inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just getting information is a challenge,'' Ivey said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
