<HEADER>
A0949 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-LANDSCAPE-STONE0601-C     05-31 1361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANDSCAPE-STONE0601-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Classic Rock
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Written in stone. Solid as a rock. Resting on
bedrock.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing says permanent, substantial and dependable like stone,
so it's no wonder that people seeking to shape the landscapes
around their homes often turn to natural or manufactured stone.
</P>
<P>
   Local landscape designers and home-improvement materials
suppliers say various kinds of landscape timbers are still in use,
but stackable concrete blocks have become the first choice where
walls are needed to hold and shape the earth.
</P>
<P>
   Walls serve several functions in landscaping. They can prevent
the erosion of a hillside and turn a steep slope into a series of
level terraces for gardening. They can provide an elevated area
within a flat landscape for special treatment such as a rock
garden. They can define spaces and provide visual interest. And a
wall can provide protection, creating a sturdy, solid barrier near
driveways or other traffic areas.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Walsh, owner of the landscape design firm Garden Images,
said one reason for the increasing popularity of stone walls is
that much of the land being used for home building in recent years
is not as flat as traditional housing land.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, housing development in the Dayton area has occurred
on former farm fields that are generally level. Now that much of
that kind of land has been consumed, housing developers are forced
to use land with more ravines, hills and other dips and rises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I see a hillside on a property that is very steep,''
Walsh said, ``I always think of a concrete block wall. They're
great at stabilizing the land and preventing erosion.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she favors natural stone where the grade is not as
severe. It's harder to build a wall of natural stone, but Walsh
said the results can be very attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh worked with Springboro homeowners Ginger and John Kennedy
to create a two-tiered limestone wall that looks almost like a
naturally occurring stone outcropping.
</P>
<P>
   Ginger Kennedy said she and her husband had their Springboro
house built about five years ago, and her husband built a stone
waterfall and pond with a stone border in their small back yard not
long after. John Kennedy gathered the stones for the waterfall and
pond border from around the subdivision, which was still being
developed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the yard landscaped, but we were never really happy
with it. It was just kind of boring,'' Ginger Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said her husband contacted Denise Walsh, and their ideas
for a system of retaining walls in the small, sloping yard meshed
perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   To create a wall that looked natural took lots of planning and
preparation, Walsh said. Building a stone wall involves a lot more
than stacking rocks on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The garden wall is made of irregularly shaped slabs of
limestone, some of them about 3 feet across and weighing up to half
a ton. And almost half the stones in the layout are buried out of
sight.
</P>
<P>
   As with all walls, construction started with excavation. The
plants in the Kennedy landscape were removed and set aside for
reuse, and trenches were dug where the two wall sections were to be
installed.
</P>
<P>
   While her crews were digging the lower trench, Walsh said,
ground water that had been trapped under the Kennedy's patio gushed
into the hole, creating a little pond. She had to add a drainage
system including a buried well to catch the excess water that
tended to pool near the patio.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kennedys said the soil near their patio had always been
soggy,'' Walsh said. ``One thing you never want to do is try to
build a wall in a mud hole.''
</P>
<P>
   After digging and providing an outlet for the ground water, the
next step was providing a level base of porous gravel under the
wall. Gravel under the wall improves drainage and eliminates the
freezing-and-thawing cycle that can deform a wall over time.
</P>
<P>
   The final step was setting the stones themselves and adding the
right combination of small stones and dirt to make the wall stable.
Like most stone walls, the Kennedy project was built without
mortar. Gravity and the surrounding soil keep the wall in place.
</P>
<P>
   With a wall of regularly shaped concrete blocks, positioning is
fairly simple. Positioning irregular stones is an art form.
</P>
<P>
   ``Building this kind of wall is like working on a puzzle,''
Walsh said. ``I had the guys working with me lay out a few stones,
then pick some up and try a different arrangement. It's very time
consuming and labor intensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Petrosino used concrete blocks for the area around his
backyard swimming pool. But he said the work on the 150-foot
retaining wall was still back-breaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make sure you've got a good pair of work gloves on if you try
something like this,'' Petrosino said. ``I was sore all over; my
thighs were bruised from bouncing blocks against my legs. Not only
were we wrestling with those 60-pound blocks, but we had to shovel
about 20 tons of gravel.''
</P>
<P>
   Petrosino bought his house six years ago and has been adding
features one at a time for years. He first installed a swimming
pool, then he added a large deck and gazebo. This year the
retaining wall goes in, and next year it's to be a picnic shelter
followed by final landscaping.
</P>
<P>
   ``My neighbors kid me that I never do anything small,''
Petrosino said.
</P>
<P>
   The Petrosino house and pool are elevated somewhat from the land
behind the house, and Petrosino is using the retaining wall to
divide the property into zones of differing heights.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the slope of the yard, some portions of the wall are
four blocks high while others are only one block high. But the top
of the wall is level from end to end.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way I could have laid it out on my own and had it
come out right,'' Petrosino said. ``I had an architect plan it, and
Judd Powell used the plan to design the actual wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell owns Tom's Mulch, and he worked with Petrosino on the
project. Petrosino did ``a lot of the grunt labor,'' while Powell
did the planning and the detail work.
</P>
<P>
   The detail work included cutting away portions from the backs of
some blocks so they could be fit into curves.
</P>
<P>
   Petrosino said he bought about 600 blocks and the company
delivered the blocks on skids of about 50 that were scattered
around his yard. He said he drove a forklift to move the blocks
around.
</P>
<P>
   Concrete stacking blocks are designed to be stacked in staggered
rows, side by side in a straight line. Generally the underside of
each block is made with protrusions or grooves that make it sit
firmly on top of the blocks underneath. The protrusions also make
each row of blocks sit slightly further back than the row
underneath.
</P>
<P>
   To create curves, the builder often has to chip away part of the
protrusion and cut the sides of the blocks into angles.
</P>
<P>
   As with the Kennedy project, Petrosino said the trickiest part
of the job was not placing the blocks but preparing the ground. A
series of trenches had to be excavated and leveled, and the work
was especially tricky at the points where the level of the wall
changed from two blocks thick to three blocks thick, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Powell said he used a base of ``chips and dust'' under the wall.
Chips and dust is a combination of small pebbles and chips of rocks
surrounded by loose dry dirt. He said the dust helps create a firm,
level surface while the pebbles provide drainage.
</P>
<P>
   Petrosino said that after each level of the wall was installed,
the area behind it was filled with gravel. The blocks are partially
hollow, and the gravel flows into the spaces in the blocks to help
anchor the wall.
</P>
<P>
   The last step of the construction was the addition of a row of
decorative capping stones.
</P>
<P>
   Petrosino said he's pleased with the project now that it's
nearly complete, but he said it has been a lot of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did most of the lifting and placing blocks on a Saturday,
and the next day it rained so we couldn't work,'' he said. ``I was
never so glad to see a rainstorm in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
