<HEADER>
A0950 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SALAD-GREENS0601-COX     05-31 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALAD-GREENS0601-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A rich bounty of salad greens
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ June is somewhere between asparagus and green
beans.
</P>
<P>
   It's a month best-known for fruit, with an abundance of local
strawberries and raspberries. A few peas show up at farm markets,
but not enough for dinner for all of us.
</P>
<P>
   What June does offer to meet our need for green vegetables is
salad greens. And this year, after a cool May, the crop is
bountiful.
</P>
<P>
   We've come a long way since a green salad meant just lettuce.
When Guy Ashmore takes his salad greens to the Saturday Waynesville
Farmers Market, he may include peppery arugula, lemony sorrel,
vibrant Russian red kale and frilly mizuna in the mix.
</P>
<P>
   At the Yellow Springs farm market, Doug Siebert of Peach
Mountain Organics sells bagged mixes that change from week to week.
They may include exotica such as tiny leaves of Bright Lights
chard, Bull's Blood beet greens, pretty leaves of red orach or
small green leaf amaranth, snow pea tendrils and salad burnet.
Radicchio, two kinds of endive and frisee add a contrasting bitter
edge.
</P>
<P>
   Siebert rattles off the crops, mentally walking through his
fields, which also produce red and green Russian kales, and
sometimes Italian broccoli raab. An organic farmer in a constant
battle with bugs, he may be able to harvest peppery broad leaf
cress, Japanese mizuna and spoon-shaped tatsoi. Arugula is a staple
addition, and herbs such as flat leaf Italian parsley, celery-like
lovage and feathery bronze fennel have a place in the mix. He even
tucks in brightly colored nasturtium flowers and the plant's
peppery leaves as well, and a scattering of petals from the orange
yellow calendula blossom.
</P>
<P>
   All of which means salad has moved light years beyond a wedge of
iceberg lettuce, or, at its spring best, a bowlful of tender leaves
clipped from a back yard patch of Black Seeded Simpson leaf
lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   These days salad greens are multicolored. And the farm market
combinations are the trend-setters that have moved beyond the
mesclun mixes sold routinely at every supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   The attraction is the variety of taste and texture _ and a
pumped-up nutritional profile.
</P>
<P>
   Eating iceberg lettuce is about the nutritional equivalent of
drinking a glass of water. The darker the greens, the more
nutritious they are in terms of vitamins, minerals, fiber and
phytochemicals.
</P>
<P>
   The colors of these ``greens'' range from deep burgundy to
blue-black. The tastes are often assertive, which is why they are
usually mixed with milder lettuce such as heirloom varieties of
Speckles and Freckles or crisp Green Ice. Mixtures can pack
surprises with each bite, making salad an adventure.
</P>
<P>
   But the season is limited. Many of the varieties can't stand
heat of midsummer and disappear from markets until fall. So enjoy
the salads this month. Pretty soon it will be time for beans.
</P>
<P>
   Putting a dressing such as blue cheese or Thousand Island on the
tender leaves of a farm market mesclun mix is too heavy-handed.
There are lighter dressings that complement the sometimes delicate
leaves. Vinegar and oil vinaigrettes are the best choices, but
there are lots of ways to add flavor to that basic mix.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few choices.
</P>
<P>
   BASIC VINAIGRETTE
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1/2 cup
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon kosher or coarse sea salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon freshly squeezed lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 to 1/2 extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Crush the garlic and salt in a mortar with a pestle (or mash
with a fork in a small bowl). Add the pepper, lemon juice and
vinegar. Whisk in the oil.
</P>
<P>
   This is a good dressing to use when adding shavings of Parmesan
cheese, crumbles of blue cheese, nuts or slivers of smoked meat to
the salad.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Dijon mustard not only adds flavor but helps
emulsify the dressing. When using mustard, remember to blend the
mustard with the vinegar before adding the oil. If you add the
mustard last, the dressing will not be smooth.
</P>
<P>
   LEMON-MUSTARD VINAIGRETTE
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1/3 cup
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   juice of 1/2 lemon
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Combine the mustard, vinegar and lemon juice. Whisk in the oil.
Add salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   _ From ``The Gardener's Table `` by Richard Merrill and Joe
Ortiz (TenSpeed, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   When the rest of the dinner has an Asian accent, this take on
salad dressing keeps the theme.
</P>
<P>
   SESAME VINAIGRETTE
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons toasted (Japanese) sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons rice vinegar
</P>
<P>
   salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   In serving bowl whisk the oil and vinegar. Add to four big
handfuls of mesclun greens and mix well to coat. Sprinkle with salt
and pepper and toss again.
</P>
<P>
   _ From The New York Times
</P>
<P>
   This is more elaborate variation of Asian dressing.
</P>
<P>
   ASIAN-STYLE VINAIGRETTE
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3/4 cup
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Asian sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup low-sodium soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup freshly squeezed lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup corn oil
</P>
<P>
   Combine all the ingredients except the oil in a lender. With the
machine running, gradually add the oil.
</P>
<P>
   _ From ``The Gardener's Table `` by Richard Merrill and Joe
Ortiz (TenSpeed, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   This mesclun dressing incorporates sweet roasted red bell
peppers.
</P>
<P>
   RED PEPPER DRESSING
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 cups
</P>
<P>
   6 roasted red bell peppers, skins and seeds removed
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sherry vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cups canola oil
</P>
<P>
   3 shallots, finely minced
</P>
<P>
   salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   Add the roasted peppers, vinegar and both oils to a blender.
Blend until smooth. Pour into a bowl and whisk in shallots by hand.
Season with salt and freshly ground pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Use approximately 2 tablespoons dressing per serving of greens.
Store remaining dressing in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   _ From The Cook's Garden catalog, (800) 457-9703.
</P>
<P>
   SOURCES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Guy Ashmore sells his salad greens at the Waynesville Farmers
Market, 8 a.m. to noon Saturdays in the parking lot of Der Dutchman
Restaurant on U.S. 42 in Waynesville. This weekend is dubbed
``Super Salad Saturday'' and Ashmore will offer tastes of some of
the unusual varieties. He also fills orders at his farm, 394 Ohio
380, Clarksville (south of Wilmington). To order, call (513)
289-3151.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Doug Siebert sells cutting lettuces and salad greens at the
Yellow Springs farm market, 8 a.m. to noon Saturdays in Kings Yard.
He also sells at the Spring Valley farm, 1560 Richland Road, but
hours are irregular except for Friday afternoon. For information,
call (937) 862- 5259.
</P>
<P>
   Both growers are certified organic.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you want to grow your own, turn to the same catalogs the
farmers use. A late August planting will provide a good crop in the
cooler days of fall. Order catalogs from The Cook's Garden, (800)
457-9703, and www.cooksgarden.com or from Shepherd's Garden Seeds,
(860) 482-3638, and www.shepherdsseeds.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
