<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0953 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-REVIEW-CLERKS-HNS &LR;      05-31 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REVIEW-CLERKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAY HELLO (AND GOODBYE) TO `CLERKS' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TIM GOODMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even with a show that reeks, that offends the senses as you
watch every pathetic minute of it, you're not completely sure of
its demise.
</P>
<P>
   That is because everybody else might like it. Look how long
``Veronica's Closet'' was around. A hit, no matter how horrible,
remains a hit. Nobody cancels shows in Hollywood just because they
are bad.
</P>
<P>
   That said, a really solid case can be made that ``Clerks,'' the
new animated series from ABC is, in effect, DOA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clerks'' is indeed a spin-off of the popular independent cult
film of the same name. Creator Kevin Smith and his band of actors
from that picture are behind this animated effort. And a brave
number of stars have lent their voices to the show, a la ``The
Simpsons.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a decent pedigree. Why then the absolute certainty that
``Clerks'' is dead? Let's enumerate.
</P>
<P>
   1. ABC decided to put the show on when the TV season was over.
Not a good sign. In fact, that's dead fish wrapped in paper,
delivered to the rival mob.
</P>
<P>
   2. Kevin Smith, upon hearing when his show _ the one he'd
labored over for a full year _ was going to debut after the season,
went into a huge rant on his personal Web page. There was much
anger and verbal stench. Word of those words leaked into the press,
and ABC, as clueless as it is most times, took notice. It's pretty
hard to get your show renewed when you assault the network.
</P>
<P>
   3. ABC is, truly, clueless. And instead of trying to cash in on
what has been a pretty lucrative market _ young males _ filled most
of its half-hour slots with shows deemed unwatchable by both
genders. Besides, this is the network that didn't know how to make
money off ``Sports Night,'' and canceled the riveting series
``Wonderland.''
</P>
<P>
   4. Animated shows are falling out of favor.
</P>
<P>
   5. ``Clerks'' essentially draws on what is a limited audience _
cult hit movie or not _ and almost no network is interested in
gambling on niche programming, much less in patiently growing the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, ABC went after ``Clerks'' in the first place because of
Smith, who has scored well with ``Chasing Amy'' and ``Dogma'' as
feature films and is revered among certain types as some sort of
alternative pop culture genius.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the aforementioned five reasons may not have
played into the future of ``Clerks'' even if it was given a
24-episode run. This animated show, centered on slackers working at
a convenience store and its neighboring video store, lacks the raw
pop of the film and relies instead on inconsistent jokes that try
to prop up premises that don't exist.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas ``Seinfeld'' got the erroneous rap of being a show about
nothing, ``Clerks'' manages to prove that you can make 22 minutes
with virtually no ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the appeal of the show, actually, is watching them
stretch to fill the time with one-liners, flashbacks and random
bits desperately thrown together.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Clerks,'' time is something that doesn't exist, and hanging
out and talking nonlinear nonsense is a breezy way to kill a
half-hour. But there's not enough to keep you interested _
particularly if you know there are only going to be six episodes
(and that's if ABC is generous). Maybe if there was a no-kill
clause to the show, you'd cut it some slack and learn to get its
vibe.
</P>
<P>
   But as it stands now, ``Clerks'' is filled with jokes that will
offend minorities. The movie didn't have a wide-enough appeal to
prepare TV audiences for this kind of 'tude, and the actions of
these animated characters aren't drawn broadly enough to present a
series of scathing offend-everyone jokes while getting away with it
by wink-winking.
</P>
<P>
   So we're left with a partially amusing, very offensive,
completely doomed summer series. For true ``Clerks'' fanatics only.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
