r l BC-FRAZZLED-PARENT-TEX     05-31 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRAZZLED-PARENT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER FINALLY COMES _ BUT AT A PRICE
</HEADLINE>
 (for use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CATHERINE NEWTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I envisioned a column about the dawn of summer. A
Letterman-esque Top 10 Reasons to be Glad It's Here, packed with
silly, somewhat ironic vignettes about the glories and challenges
of summertime when you have children. You know, lemonade stands
where you do all the work. Fire ant bites and bee stings. Constant
anxiety about listening for the ice cream truck.
</P>
<P>
   I was forming said column in my mind and planned to write it one
evening after work in the comfort of my study (otherwise known as
the room taken over by Barbie and her pink plastic prefab
township), where screened windows let gentle breezes cool the air.
</P>
<P>
   But the school year was not yet inclined to release me from its
cruel talons. I arrived home at 7 to find my friend Brittany _
temporary after-school sitter extraordinaire _ on the phone and son
Jack in tears. Apparently, he had forgotten about his fourth-grade
life science projects.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, he'd made the ant farm and had been toting the jar around
for weeks. And he'd designed, in remarkable detail, a fictional
creature that looked like a flying turtle and had all sorts of
special adaptations to nature. He had just forgotten all the other
projects, he said. All 14 of them. All due the next day.
</P>
<P>
   I thought he was joking. But the alarm in Brittany's voice was
clear as she explained the situation to me in-between brief,
staccato bits of one-sided conversations with her
encyclopedia-graced fiance, in which he informed her exactly what
you call a baby hog, a female goat and a male sheep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom already drove us around hunting for leaves,'' she
explained, pointing to a pile of leaves on the kitchen table. ``She
kept pulling over to the side of the road, and if anyone saw us she
would shout, `We're not bad people. We're just working on a little
boy's science project!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Brittany and her mother had been attacking the
project list for hours. My first instinct was to throttle my child
and go watch some season finales, but on careful reconsideration,
this seemed a bit selfish.
</P>
<P>
   I grabbed the assignment sheet. And screamed.
</P>
<P>
   There were four chapters' worth of work with 12 projects each,
and the students were assigned to do four projects from each
chapter. I decided to start at the beginning and work our way done.
</P>
<P>
   Chapter one, project one. ``Soak 20 bean seeds in one cup of
water for 24 hours. Chart how much water is soaked up.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving right along to project two. ``Grow a bean plant. Chart
its growth for about two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   This was much worse than I imagined. I scanned through the
possible projects. Grow a stalk of celery in food coloring for a
week. Observe the stages of a beetle's life. Ask your vet for
pamphlets on animal parasites. Do a vocabulary puzzle _ see your
teacher for the appropriate sheet. Do a project on traveling seeds
_ see your teacher for the appropriate sheet.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't have two weeks or even 24 hours. We didn't have any
appropriate sheets. And having recently moved and completely purged
our magazine collection in an anti-pack-rat fury, we didn't have
any pictures with which to make collages, which eliminated at least
two of the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   There were, in fact, only four projects from each chapter that
we might possibly be able to complete in one night.
</P>
<P>
   While Brittany continued to gather information on the proper
names of baby lions, female ducks and male horses, I set 6-year-old
daughter Hadley to work making rubbings of the leaves that had been
collected. While Jack drew a flower, labeling its parts _ stamen,
sepal, pollen _ I ran out to the garage to find some plant food for
which Jack could list the ingredients. Then I gingerly picked my
way through Kelly's schoolroom and Barbie's ranch to open the
screened windows before I turned on the computer.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Jeeves, my favorite cyber source: Is a bean derived from
a fruit, leaf, stem or root?
</P>
<P>
   By 8:30, Brittany and I couldn't think of the name of the 19th
and 20th grown-ups whom Jack could theoretically have surveyed to
ask if they were vegetarians.
</P>
<P>
   By 8:45, we ran out of computer paper, and Brittany tried in
vain to print out her list of carnivores, herbivores and omnivores
on a sheet of three-ring binder, lined paper.
</P>
<P>
   By 9 p.m., Brittany left to have dinner and return to her own
life's challenges.
</P>
<P>
   By 9:30, Hadley was in bed, having practiced her 10 spelling
words twice.
</P>
<P>
   And by 11, Jack was finished. We had found pictures of him to
chart his growth in the bottom of an unpacked box of books. We had
found an illustration of a colorful chameleon for him to copy, and
two kinds of penguins for him to draw. He had mapped out the life
cycle of a frog. As the 14th and final project, we would bring his
pet turtle to school the next day and he would give a report on its
eating habits and its care and how its adaptations helped it
survive.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't great work. But it was done.
</P>
<P>
   At 11:30, I sat down at my computer, felt the cool breeze waft
in, and found to my surprise that I could not think of one thing
even mildly funny about the dawn of summer.
</P>
<P>
   The One and Only Reason to Be Glad It's Summer was all I could
envision: No more homework.
</P>
<P>
   Bring on the ice cream-truck worries and the lemonade-stand
work. And if an ant bites, so what. I'm sure Jeeves can tell me
what to do.
</P>
<P>
   And the best thing is that nobody will want to know what the
male and female and baby ant are called.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 1735EDT &QL; 
