r e BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX     05-31 0404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF RELIGIOUS BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Balance of the NIV' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Kenneth Barker &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Baker, $13.99) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Think of Kenneth Barker's ``The Balance of the NIV'' as
``Goldilocks and the Three-Plus Bible Translations'': Some versions
take too many interpretive liberties, some are too wooden and
literalistic, but at least one is just about right.
</P>
<P>
   ``What constitutes a good translation?'' Barker asks in the last
installment of a Baker Books trilogy on the New International
Version. His answer: balance in its translation committee approach,
textual basis, translation philosophy, handling of tough passages,
and support resources. ``The Balance of the NIV,'' then, is
essentially an explanation and defense of the NIV's approach to
those matters.
</P>
<P>
   Barker's book often deals with scholarly technicalities, so a
passing acquaintance with the principles of textual criticism is at
least handy. ``The Balance of the NIV'' will be most helpful to
those with a serious interest in matters of biblical translation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This Mystery'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nichole Nordeman &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sparrow Records &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nichole Nordeman treats her listeners to a bit of nostalgia by
including the old Stevie Wonder classic ``As'' on this album. The
song is given some updated, Christian lyrics, but the music and the
beat are true to the original.
</P>
<P>
   The song is a pleasure, but it's also a diversion.
</P>
<P>
   Nordeman's strength is not covering other people's work, but
creating her own.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Wide Eyed,'' her debut album, Nordeman gained a reputation
as a songwriter of considerable depth. That reputation is enhanced
here.
</P>
<P>
   She has a good voice, and her music has a nice piano-heavy pop
sound, but the thing that sets Nordeman apart from the crowd is the
thought-provoking message in the music.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of ``Wide Eyed'' was personal faith. On this one, it's
the mystery of God.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 songs _ Nordeman wrote eight and collaborated on two,
including the lyrics-tweaking on ``As'' _ consider the miracles and
majesty of God, the depth and breadth of God, the questions and
doubts about God, and ultimately challenge the listener to live for
God. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Simon Gonzalez &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
