<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Palm Storage Device Makes Room for Fun
</P>
<P>
   Road warriors who get that syncing feeling with their Palm
organizers can now safely back up their data, even when there is no
desktop in sight. JKS Technologie, a German company, has created
the FlashPlug, a small device that adds 8 megabytes of storage.
</P>
<P>
   Palm owners have traditionally backed up data by syncronizing
the unit with a desktop or laptop computer via a Palm cradle
attached to it. FlashPlug users can connect the gadget to the Palm
and back up files onto the unit with the device's file manager
software.
</P>
<P>
   The lightweight FlashPlug does not require extra batteries and
will run on the Palm operating system, version 2.04 or higher. It
connects easily to most models of the Palm organizer, although the
Palm V and Vx require an adapter. Storage space on the FlashPlug
can also be partitioned. More information can be found on the
FlashPlug Web site (www.flashplug.de). The FlashPlug costs about
$120 and can be purchased in the United States from the PDA Life
Web site (www.pdalife.com).
</P>
<P>
   The FlashPlug is also being promoted as a storage drive for
large Palm databases like files containing medical reference
materials. (Files have to be copied back to the Palm before they
can be used.) Better yet, the FlashPlug might make room for the
really fun stuff, like electronic texts, games, digital maps and
graphic images, which are handy to have but are voracious space
hogs when you have only a couple of megabytes of memory.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer Fans Can Follow Euro 2000 on the Web
</P>
<P>
   For most of the world outside the United States, soccer is not a
matter of life and death _ it is much more important than that.
</P>
<P>
   The rabid _ and sometimes violent _ devotion to the sport will
be on display in Belgium and the Netherlands beginning on June 10,
the opening date for the European Championships, or Euro 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the sport can follow the 16-nation tournament, which
begins in Brussels and ends with the championship match on July 2
in Rotterdam, the Netherlands, on the Euro 2000 Web site
(www.euro2000.org).
</P>
<P>
   The site offers voluminous information in five languages:
English, French, German, Spanish and Italian. There is information
on each nation's team, a history of the tournament since its
inception in 1960, video tours of the eight cities in which the
games will be held and a video library of every goal scored in the
competition since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   A selection of events and sites on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, 9:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   www.liveonthenet.com. Nightly coverage from the Chicago Comedy
Festival, through Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY, 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   dsc.discovery.com/stories/nature/giantsquids/ask.html
</P>
<P>
   Chat with Clyde Roper, head of an expedition that is searching
for giant squid.
</P>
<P>
   Sites
</P>
<P>
   www.fourmilab.ch/earthview/vplanet.html
</P>
<P>
   Choose a longitude and latitude, and view Earth from the vantage
point of the Sun or the Moon. Or see the world from the viewpoint
of a satellite above any of a dozen cities.
www.stormkingartcenter.org/artistlisting(underscore)a.html.
</P>
<P>
   Sculpture at the Storm King Art Center in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Nomad Jukebox Holds A Hefty Store of Music
</P>
<P>
   Creative Labs has upped the ante in the MP3 sweepstakes with the
release of the new Nomad Jukebox.
</P>
<P>
   It can play music in most downloadable formats, including MP3
and WAV files and is about the size and shape of a heavy portable
CD player, but it has a hefty six gigabytes of hard drive space.
That's more than 90 times that of most smaller MP3 players.
</P>
<P>
   That means the Jukebox can hold up to 100 hours of music in the
MP3 format, which is equal to the music on 150 music CD's.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the limitations in the MP3 player market has been lack
of storage space.'' said Hector Martinez, a company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Those many audiophiles who do not believe the commonly heard
claim that MP3's produce ``near CD sound quality'' can use the
Nomad Jukebox to store less music but at higher speeds, up to 320
kilobits per second.
</P>
<P>
   The Jukebox can be plugged into a home computer through a U.S.B.
port and can be played through car stereo systems or used with
headphones.
</P>
<P>
   At a suggested retail price of $499, however, the cost matches a
hefty hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   Pump Up the Power In a Cell Phone Battery
</P>
<P>
   If the battery in your cell phone is about to die, get a grip.
That is the underlying message in a new charger called
Aladdinpower, a portable power generator that lets cell phone users
reinvigorate their batteries by squeezing a small, handheld pump.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Collins, advertising director for the Bridges Equipment
Co., an outdoor-power company in Brandon, Fla., that distributes
the chargers, said she pumps the grip while she is on and off her
cell phone and has found that the time it takes to recharge the
battery differs depending on how fast and hard she squeezes. Her
husband had a dead cell phone battery, she said, and it took him
about three minutes of steady pumping to recharge it halfway.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by Japanese engineers, Aladdinpower works by converting
each squeeze of the grip into electricity that replenishes the cell
phone battery. The brushed aluminum device weighs 11 ounces and is
5\ inches long.
</P>
<P>
   To work with the variety of cell phones on the market, it must
be used with a DC power adapter designed for your particular phone.
Cell phone users who charge their phones through their car's
cigarette lighter probably already have the adapter, Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the device is sold only through Magellan's, a travel
supply catalog (www.magellans.com), and through a branch of the
Bridges Equipment Web site (www.aladdinpower.com). Magellan's site
sells the power charger for $75, including a leather carrying case.
On the Bridges site, the charger can be purchased alone for $59.95.
On both sites, the power generator comes with a small flashlight
that can be squeezed into action in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
