<HEADER>
A0962 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-MESSAGING-SERVICE     05-31 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MESSAGING-SERVICE-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE ULTRA BUSY, ALL MESSAGES IN ONE BASKET 
</HEADLINE>
   By KAREN J. BANNAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don Damico, vice president and general manager of an industrial
holding company in New York, visits three of his company's offices,
in New York City and Pennsylvania, during the week. Even though he
carries a cellular phone, it can be difficult to get in touch with
him. Sometimes he turns off his phone for meetings, and he finds it
hard to get cell phone coverage in some places.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always have salespeople trying to find me,'' Damico said.
``With all the travel I do, it's tough to get me in one place.''
</P>
<P>
   A friend suggested that he try Messagepoint, a service that
handles voice, e-mail and fax messages. He signed up with the
service for $19.95 per month and was instantly hooked.
</P>
<P>
   Messagepoint, like other unified messaging services, gives users
like Damico individual telephone numbers they can call to check
their messages _ all their messages. Since calls to Damico's other
telephone lines are forwarded to his Messagepoint number if he does
not answer them, he has to check only one number for voice mail.
All of his e-mail and faxes also go to the same Messagepoint
mailbox, and he can check them when he checks his voice mail.
</P>
<P>
   Although Damico cannot use the phone to find out what is in his
faxes, he is notified when faxes are waiting for him. He can then
log on to the Internet to view them at a Web site. E-mail is read
to him over the phone, and he can dictate e-mail replies. That
saves him hours every month, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one of my guys has an important question for me,'' he said,
``they can send me an e-mail, and I can respond to it right away,
even if I don't have my laptop.''
</P>
<P>
   Unified messaging services have been available for more than six
years, said Megan Gurley, a research analyst at the Yankee Group, a
research firm based in Boston, but they did not catch on until
recently because there was not a real need for them. And consumers
did not understand what the services could do.
</P>
<P>
   But as more people try to keep up with home-based, office-based
and cellular phones, as well as with multiple e-mail addresses,
unified messaging may be on the verge of becoming a mass market
product. Demand for the service has also been fueled by
technological improvements in voice recognition systems.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Messagepoint, companies like General Magic,
Onebox.com, Ptek Systems and Webley Systems offer unified
messaging, and each has its own take on the service. Some let users
dial a local number to retrieve messages, while some offer the
option, for an additional fee, of a toll-free number. Some
services, like Onebox.com, are free; Onebox.com plans to make money
by licensing its technology to telephone companies and cellular
carriers. Others, like the Portico service from General Magic, cost
$9.95 per month or more and offer news and stock quotations over
the phone in addition to message services.
</P>
<P>
   Once unified messaging services catch on, free services may
become hard to find. For example, Telebot.com, a free service of
Portelco, based in Hayward, Calif., recently closed. Nader
Rahimizad, the company's chairman and chief executive officer, said
Telebot.com would reopen soon as a service designed for cellular
carriers.
</P>
<P>
   All the services let users listen over the phone to their
e-mail; the text is ``spoken'' by text-to-speech software. If a
user wants to reply to an e-mail note, that person can dictate a
response; the service will send an e-mail reply that contains an
audio file attachment with the dictated message. Anyone who gets
one of these replies can listen to the message by double-clicking
on the attachment. Since most PCs today come with the Windows Media
Player, which handles WAV files, recipients do not need any
additional software to play the messages.
</P>
<P>
   Message services let people like Damico roam without a laptop
computer and still remain connected to the office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was traveling once, and there was a decision that had to be
made on whether we could meet a certain quote for a very large
piece of business,'' Damico said. ``The client e-mailed me. I was
able to get his message and listen to it, which I wouldn't have
until later that night. I was able to work out a deal with him, and
I never saw the e-mail.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some services, like Webley from Webley Systems, Orchestrate from
Ptek and Portico, have a ``find me, follow me'' feature that
bounces an incoming call from one of the user's phone numbers to
the next until the user is located. Even if the user is found in
this way, the user can still choose to screen the calls and send to
voice mail.
</P>
<P>
   If a user listens to an e-mail or a voice mail message and wants
to respond, there are several services that can handle outbound
calls. Webley, for example, lets users dial by name or number and
connects the calls at a flat rate of 14.9 cents per minute
(expected to drop soon to less than 10 cents). Depending on the
service, the fee for outbound calls is in addition to what users
pay for calling the messaging center.
</P>
<P>
   Unified messaging can eliminate the need for a fax machine.
Senders can dial a phone number provided by the service to send a
fax to one of the service's customers. That fax is then stored as
an image file on the Web. Customers can use their computers to view
and print their faxes directly from the Web site. That feature
proved valuable to Jan Weiss, a vice president at a large
commercial bank in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss was in Washington on business when she ran into a small
problem. She was waiting for a fax from her office, but the
business center in the hotel she was staying in had already closed.
Using Onebox.com's service, she was able to receive her fax when
she needed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The documents I needed were for a conference call,'' Weiss
said. ``A client wanted an answer on something. I wouldn't have
been able to give them the answer if I didn't get that fax.''
</P>
<P>
   To sign up for a messaging service, users usually fill out an
online form and choose a toll-free telephone number. Generally, the
telephone numbers are available for use within minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The process will become even simpler in the next six to 18
months as local telephone companies and cellular carriers start
offering versions of unified messaging, Gurley said. Instead of
having customers go through the sign-up process manually, the
carriers will do all of the setup. Pacific Bell already offers its
customers the Wildfire service from Wildfire Communications, while
Bell Atlantic is also working on a unified messaging system.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the many benefits, there are several problems with
unified messaging services. For one thing, a user generally cannot
transfer a home or office number to a message service, so dialing
the service means another number to remember. Only customers who
sign up for a messaging service through a telephone or cellular
carrier can make their regular phone numbers their message numbers
(although many services let users have calls forwarded from their
regular numbers to their message services). And users may have to
give out one more number to business associates if they want things
sent via fax to services when they are out of their offices.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, none of the companies offer local telephone numbers
for customers to use to call the message center directly in all
areas of the country. So unless users are willing to take on the
added expense of having services provide them with toll-free
numbers, they may end up incurring long-distance charges.
</P>
<P>
   Users say the extra trouble is worth the result: simplified
communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely bringing things together for me,'' said Meg
Luttrell, a Onebox customer in Palo Alto, Calif. ``Right now we're
transitioning offices, and I'm moving in my personal life. Having
one number to check is a godsend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0964 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-WEATHER-ONLINE-2T     05-31 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WEATHER-ONLINE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET OFFERS ALL THE WEATHER YOU'LL EVER NEED 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: optional sidebar at end of article)  
 By BONNIE ROTHMAN MORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carey Hoffman describes himself as a weather nut.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in the last three years, Hoffman, a public information
officer at the University of Cincinnati, has taken off from work to
attend a severe-weather symposium at Ohio State University ``for
fun and entertainment,'' he wrote in an e-mail note. Since he was 9
years old and a tornado touched down one block from his house in
the suburbs of Cincinnati, Hoffman has been in hot pursuit of
information about the weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day we got cable TV was a great day,'' said Hoffman, who
saw his first radar screen displaying weather information on a
local cable channel. The debut of the Weather Channel in 1982 was
another bright day for Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the Internet that has made Hoffman and others like him
feel as if they are in weather paradise. Using several elaborate
sites, a weather fanatic can keep tabs on the temperature, the
barometric pressure, the wind speed, even the movement of storm
clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman now pursues his hobby by checking a half dozen sites on
a stormy day. He particularly enjoys exploring the Web site of the
National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (www.noaa.gov).
</P>
<P>
   NOAA, part of the Commerce Department, is the parent agency of
the National Weather Service, and its site is a favorite among
meteorologists and weather fanatics.
</P>
<P>
   On the site, Hoffman said, he finds forecasters discussing
severe storms with one another. ``It's somewhat scientific, but
they talk more openly than what they're going to tell the public,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman's obsession does not surprise those who provide weather
information. Weather, they said, is simply fascinating. ``It's a
24-hour story,'' said Joel N. Myers, president and founder of
AccuWeather, a forecasting service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. is a country that gets more different kinds of
weather than any other country in the world,'' said Dr. D. James
Baker, who is administrator of NOAA and undersecretary for oceans
and atmosphere at the Department of Commerce, who is responsible
for the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   Decker Anstrom, chief executive of the Weather Channel, said,
``The unpredictability of weather and forecasts' being wrong is
what keeps people interested in the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizations ranging from the National Weather Service to
private forecasting companies and television stations are trying to
muscle in on the Weather Channel and grab the attention of weather
enthusiasts with their Web sites. The advantage of the Internet,
the organizations said, is instantaneous, updated, personalized
weather information.
</P>
<P>
   The sites, including AccuWeather, (www.accuweather.com), Weather
Services International (www.intellicast.com) and Automated Weather
Source (www.aws/instaweather.asp), are providing more detailed,
more colorful and more graphic information. Not to be outdone, the
Weather Channel also has an elaborate site, www.weather.com.
</P>
<P>
   These sites are useful to people whose interest in the weather
starts and stops with wanting to know if they need an umbrella that
day. But for weather fanatics, the sites are the mother lode. They
show real-time satellite weather photos, current temperatures for
cities around the world, wind speeds on the ocean, tornado watches
on the plains.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike television broadcasts _ even the Weather Channel _ and
radio reports where you have to wait for a forecast, the Web sites
offer continually updated information.
</P>
<P>
   Many sites offer what has been referred to as now-casting or
personal weather views. At intellicast.com, for example, weather
reports are intended for hobbyists with weather-related interests,
like sailors, golfers and amateur astronomers.
</P>
<P>
   While National Weather Service forecasts (which can be found on
these sites as well) depict what the weather is at the airport, the
commercial sites can take microviews, zeroing in on a particular
town or a street. The sites are designed to allow users to get
information quickly; travelers, for instance, can easily find the
10-day forecast for their destination.
</P>
<P>
   One such service is AWS's WeatherBug (www.weatherbug/aws), a
free service that PC users can download onto their computers. When
severe weather has been forecast, a weather icon alerts the user.
The service is about a month old and has about 31,000 subscribers.
The average user has been clicking in 13 times a day, said
Stephanie M. Blozy, a meteorologist at AWS, formally known as
Automated Weather Source. Users of Web-enabled cell phones and
organizers like the Palm VII can download the free AWS WeatherNet
software for access to weather information on the go. A particular
favorite with weather hobbyists is weather.gov, the National
Weather Service page that says 10,000 weather sites link to it.
Here, users can scan for warnings of severe weather around the
world and check the latest satellite pictures and even 3-D images
of potential hurricanes. The site is extensive. As Hoffman found,
the deeper into the site you go, the more technical the information
becomes.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare forecasts, the National Weather Service and the
Federal Aviation Administration collect data from weather stations
at most airports and other sites once every hour. Weather
instruments _ everything from thermometers and barometers to
satellites, weather ballons and Doppler radar _ are used to gather
information. Doppler radar detects the location and intensity of
rain, snow and other forms of precipitation.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meteorologists at the National Weather Service and some
independent weather companies, like AccuWeather and the Weather
Channel, run the weather service information through computer
models that generate forecasts. Meteorologists then interpret the
data. The information is packaged and sent to media organizations
and is also put on Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Local meteorologists often gather additional information to
compile forecasts. The data is culled from instruments, including
Doppler radar owned by the broadcast stations, and from local
weather stations, including one or more of roughly 4,000 schools
set up with instruments through a program sponsored by AWS through
its School WeatherNet program.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the vast amount of information, weather forecasting is
still inexact.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average user doesn't understand the degree of uncertainty
behind this,'' said Dr. Mark S. Monmonier, professor of geography
at Syracuse University and author of ``Air Apparent: How
Meteorologists Learned to Map, Predict and Dramatize Weather''
(University of Chicago Press, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   Monmonier likened weather forecasting to a horse race where one
forecaster places all bets on one horse (one weather prediction
model) while other forecasters use different models.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Church, a longtime television meteorologist in New York,
said, ``Models of the atmosphere include wind speed, humidity, and
temperature of the atmosphere at different heights.'' One model
might indicate rain in the morning, Church said, while another
might predict rain later in the day. Accuweather.com is testing a
streaming feature called ``point-counterpoint,'' in which
meteorologists debate forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   When the forecasts are wrong, some people get angry, Monmonier
said. ``The difficulty stems from the tendency of the general
public to think that because we are spending hundreds of millions
of dollars on high tech that it will remove uncertainty,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mel Goldstein, a meteorologist, said, ``Accuracy is around
85 percent today, and it was 85 percent accurate 85 years ago.''
Goldstein is a former professor of meteorology at Western
Connecticut State University, a meteorologist at WTNH television in
New Haven and the author of ``The Complete Idiot's Guide to
Weather'' (Alpha Books, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a 24-hour forecast,'' Goldstein said.
``Most of the time it's easy to predict the weather _ you look out
the window. But during rapidly developing weather situations the
forecast accuracy falls far below that 85 percent, and
unfortunately, those are the occasions when most people are
watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Some elements of forecasts, however, have become more accurate.
A five-day forecast today is as accurate as a three-day forecast 10
or 15 years ago, said Jim Candor, a vice president of AccuWeather.
And these forecasts are far more detailed, far beyond the old
``clear and sunny tomorrow, temps in the high 60s.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker of NOAA said even more accuracy and detail are in the
offing. ``Better and more accurate data and higher speed and better
computers to take in all the data and tell us where weather will
happen'' will result in better forecasts, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, weather enthusiasts will have to choose from
the information that is already available, unless, of course, they
prefer to make their own forecasts, like Roger Perry. Perry, an
eighth grade science teacher at the Plymouth Community Intermediate
School in Plymouth, Mass., has a weather station at the school.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the standard instruments, Perry has two receivers for
NOAA weather satellite information, a live weather radar feed, five
weather stations with logs for data, lightning detection antennas
and all-day connections to the Internet. And a television in
Perry's weather station is tuned in to the Weather Channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a live weather radar image running in real time,''
Perry said. With all of this kind of data, he added, ``anybody can
make a forecast.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry and his students extend their weather activities beyond
the classroom. They serve as spotters for the weather service, a
loosely knit group of enthusiasts who watch for severe weather and
report their observations. They also offer weather information to
local cranberry growers and the nuclear power plant in town.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his interest and his equipment, Perry said he would
still like more information. To him, there can never be enough
weather information. That, he says, makes him a true weather nut.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   EQUIPMENT FOR AMATEUR FORECASTERS
</P>
<P>
   According to Roger Perry, a science teacher at the Plymouth
Community Intermediate School in Plymouth, Mass., weather
forecasting is simple, once you have set yourself up with the right
equipment and access to information.
</P>
<P>
   Perry said that ``a good Internet connection and a list of
weather information Internet sites,'' starting with weather.gov, a
National Weather Service site, can point an amateur forecaster in
the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   The following equipment is also helpful:
</P>
<P>
   _ An outdoor thermometer that will record the minimum and
maximum temperatures for the day.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wind speed and direction instruments.
</P>
<P>
   _ A barometer to measure air pressure.
</P>
<P>
   _ A 4-inch plastic rain gauge.
</P>
<P>
   _ A yardstick or meter stick to measure snowfall.
</P>
<P>
   _ A shelter to protect the instruments from heating up on sunny
days.
</P>
<P>
   _ A weather log chart.
</P>
<P>
   _ A National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration weather
radio, which can receive high-frequency weather broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Thermometers and rain gauges can be found for as little as a
dollar, but Perry suggested using sturdier equipment. These can be
found on the Web at sites of companies that sell weather
instruments, including Maximum Inc. (www.maximum-inc.com); the
Weather Store (www.wxstore.com), a folksy site offering
weathervanes and weather stations; and Davis Instruments
(www.davisnet.com), which sells home weather stations, some of
which can be linked to a personal computer. Lightning detectors are
for sale at Stormwise (www.stormwise.com), a site specializing in
these instruments.
</P>
<P>
   For the true weather fanatic, individual weather satellite
receivers and other weather information systems can be purchased
through Zephyrus Electronics (www.big-z.com), DTN Kavouras Weather
Services (www.dtn.com/weather) and Alden ELectronics
(www.alden.com), among others. These sites cater mostly to
industrial and commercial users but will sell to individuals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
