<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0968 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-JELLO0601-COX     05-31 1892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JELLO0601-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gelatin's jiggly appeal suspended in place and time
 &HT;    By Rachel Sauer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _
</P>
<P>
   Quiz:
</P>
<P>
   1. You're sick with what feels like alien torture flu. Your mom
(or spouse, or roommate) brings you:
</P>
<P>
   a. a doctor to surgically remove your throat because otherwise
it's just going to use those teeth and claws to crawl into your
head and eat your brain.
</P>
<P>
   b. down, man. You know you're sick, but it doesn't help to be
told to stop coughing.
</P>
<P>
   c. Jell-O.
</P>
<P>
   2. You're at the church potluck picnic. It's 100 percent
guaranteed that someone will bring:
</P>
<P>
   a. Uncle Ed who wears the head umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   b. a guitar and play the same three chords in different song
variations until you want to bash the instrument on something, like
John Belushi did in ``Animal House'': Learn a new song!
</P>
<P>
   c. Jell-O.
</P>
<P>
   3. You're giving a public speech and your legs feel like:
</P>
<P>
   OK, enough with the quiz. Your legs feel like Jell-O, and you
know it. Everyone else knows it, too.
</P>
<P>
   The point is this: Jell-O gelatin has 99 percent name
recognition in the United States and is found in 72 percent of
homes, according to Kraft Foods Inc. About the only other thing to
rival Jell-O in universality is TV.
</P>
<P>
   Jell-O _ and we're talking gelatin, not pudding or no-bake
desserts or whatever _ is everywhere. It's a cultural reference
point for a society that increasingly celebrates what is different
about us rather than what is the same.
</P>
<P>
   But Jell-O is the same. It's something we share, a jiggly
commonality, if you will, of similar experience. Oh, there have
been other gelatins _ Knox and Knorr and a few other forgettables _
but it's the big red letters that do something for us. Jell-O. It's
weird and mysterious, a renaissance food that you love or hate, sip
or slurp, wiggle or jiggle, or... just gimme the Jell-O.
</P>
<P>
   A SEMI-BRIEF HISTORY
</P>
<P>
   History shows that cooks through the ages have used gelatin, or
jelly, for stuff. We don't know why, and it seems like a lot of
work to look up, but trust us: There was gelatin being used.
However, it was usually made by boiling animal parts (gelatin being
nothing more than processed collagen found in the connective
tissues of animal parts, so there's a grain of truth to what you
heard in your elementary school cafeteria about Jell-O being made
from horses' hooves) (but it was later discovered there's other
stuff that gels), which was a hassle.
</P>
<P>
   In 1845, Peter Cooper _ builder of the Tom Thumb locomotive,
founder of Cooper Union, former presidential candidate, glue
factory owner _ registered a patent for ``an improvement in the
preparation of portable gelatin. He said it ``consists in making a
transparent concentrated or solidified jelly containing all the
ingredients fitting it for table use, in a portable form and
requiring only the addition of a prescribed quantity of hot water
to dissolve it, when it may be poured into glasses or molds and
when cold will be fit for use.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take off. Cooks still used sheets of prepared gelatin,
which had to be clarified by boiling them with egg whites and
shells and poured through a jelly bag before they could be turned
into molds.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of boxed, easy-to-prepare gelatin languished for 52
years until Pearle B. Wait, a carpenter and cough medicine
manufacturer from LeRoy, N.Y., wanted to enter the packaged food
business. He came up with a fruit-flavored version of Cooper's
gelatin and his wife, May, named it Jell-O. It was available in
strawberry, raspberry, orange and lemon, and for two years Wait
tried selling it door-to-door. It didn't take off.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated, Wait sold the Jell-O business for $450 to his
neighbor, Orator Francis Woodward, founder of the Genesee Pure Food
Company. The first year's sales were abysmal and Woodward tried
selling Jell-O to his plant superintendent for $35, but the offer
was refused. Woodward then looked for creative sales techniques,
including sending out a well-groomed sales force to parties, fairs,
socials and picnics, offering to supply each event with free Jell-O
gelatin.
</P>
<P>
   And that's when Jell-O took off. By 1906 sales had soared to
just under the $1 million level. By printing cookbooks encouraging
the use of molds to make fancy Jell-O salads, Woodward launched a
Jell-O juggernaut. Famous artists _ including Rosie O'Neill,
Maxfield Parrish, Norman Rockwell and Linn Ball _ were commissioned
to make art for Jell-O ads. Recipe booklets reflected the times _
the decadence of the '20s, the economy of the '30s, the patriotism
of the '40s and the renewed American spirit of the '50s. Jack Benny
and Kate Smith became Jell-O spokespeople. Bing and Dixie Lee
Crosby duetted on a song called ``A Fine Romance'' with the line,
``You take romance, I'll take Jell-O.''
</P>
<P>
   Jell-O represented a miracle of marketing: Jell-O molds and
posters and crates and creamers and figurines and dolls and aprons
and cookbooks and magnets and just about whatever you can think of.
Flavors came and went _ concord grape, apple and, in Canada, bubble
gum and root beer. The Jell-O rocket took off and still is in
orbit.
</P>
<P>
   These days, and now owned by Kraft Foods, Inc., Jell-O sales
average 854,795 packages per day purchased in the United States.
There's a Jell-O museum in LeRoy, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   All this for what essentially is a see-through food.
</P>
<P>
   A JELL-O HAIKU:
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-nine cent box
</P>
<P>
   Of jiggly, wiggly weird food _
</P>
<P>
   What's with the carrots?
</P>
<P>
   Seriously, what is with those carrot flecks floating there in
green Jell-O with something entirely unrelated, like pineapple or
marshmallows? Floating there like they're cryogenically frozen and
waiting to wake up when the world's a better place or man is living
on Mars. You can be sure there will be Jell-O on Mars.
</P>
<P>
   But back to the point: Since it was invented, people have been
inspired to put stuff in Jell-O and call it salad, or mold, or
surprise, or mousse, or delight or whatever. It's all code for
Jell-O with stuff in it, possibly shaped like a Bundt cake.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, why? Camille Rustige, public relations
representative for Hunter &AMP; Associates Inc., which does public
relations for Jell-O, wasn't sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hmmm,'' she said. ``Good question.''
</P>
<P>
   We'll just say the big ``Why did people start putting stuff in
Jell-O'' question is like Jell-O itself: a mystery. And then we'll
just go with it and say it happens. Stuff gets put in Jell-O and
taken to a potluck.
</P>
<P>
   For something interesting to do, borrow the ``Joys of Jell-O''
cookbook, printed in the late 1960s, from your mom (she calls it
``Diary of a Mad Housewife''). Thumb through the pages and pages _
87 in all! _ of molded, shaped and otherwise coiffed Jell-O
concoctions. Avocado Strawberry Ring! Citrus Surprise! Chicken
Mousse! We probably don't need to point out that not all Jell-O
creations are good.
</P>
<P>
   Kirsten Maakestad of Grand Junction has vivid memories of tomato
aspic (recipe: 1 16-ounce can stewed tomatoes, 1 small package
lemon, strawberry or mixed fruit gelatin, 1/2 teaspoon salt and 1
tablespoon vinegar or lemon juice, prepared and poured back in the
tomato can to mold) at Thanksgiving dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it was served with a dollop of mayonnaise on top,'' she
said. ``At first I thought it was Cool Whip _ it didn't occur to me
at the time how gross Cool Whip with tomatoes would be. So maybe it
would be OK, but it was mayonnaise. For two nights I had to sit at
the table until I ate it, but finally my mom said I just had to eat
a bite.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask just about anyone and they have a Jell-O memory. Marilyn
Felling described herself as a child of the '50s who grew up with
Jell-O. It was just something she and the rest of her generation
ate for dessert, fancy Jell-O molds prepared by Mom.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 years ago she started collecting anything Jell-O,
because she's a collector and because she just loves Jell-O, and
now her collection fills a room in her house and boxes in her
garage. She has Jell-O dresses and original advertising prints and
molds and figurines and just about everything else, plus hundreds
and hundreds of boxes. The license plates on her Jell-O-red car say
``JELL-O.''
</P>
<P>
   She smiled and laughed. ``There's just something about Jell-O,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom always made the green Jell-O with Cool Whip and
pineapple,'' said Raphael Allred of Grand Junction. ``It's a picnic
salad, a happy salad. And when we were sick she'd give us liquid
Jell-O. She was so young, but she always knew what to do. She had a
soothing voice and her hands were always so soft. She'd rub my face
and feed me spoonfuls of liquid strawberry Jell-O when I was
sick.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And what about those Jell-O eggs?'' added her sister, Tara
Allred of Salt Lake City. She said at Easter time the family made
Jell-O in egg molds and then their dad, Vance, would slurp them and
sing, ``Have you ever slurped Jell-O?'' to the tune of Olivia
Newton-John's ``Have You Never Been Mellow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have Jell-O and my mom would make it really fancy,''
said Kerry Glynn of Grand Junction. ``She would put it in wine cups
with a dollop of Cool Whip.''
</P>
<P>
   Glynn and Maakestad both rhapsodized about Jell-O poke cake. Oh,
those Jell-O memories.
</P>
<P>
   WHICH OF THESE HAVE YOU SAID?:
</P>
<P>
   _ I feel a little green Jell-O today (get thee to a hospital!).
</P>
<P>
   _ Eew. My abs are like Jell-O. I gotta do some crunches.
</P>
<P>
   _ It was a red Jell-O event (church potluck, kids running around
crazy, questionable potato salad).
</P>
<P>
   _ Watch it wiggle, see it jiggle, cool and fruity Jell-O brand
gelatin. Of all desserts you'll love this one, it tastes so light,
it makes such fun. It's Jell-O brand gelatin _ make some fun.
J-E-L-L-O! (Quick, where are your car keys? You can't remember, can
you? But you remember this jingle.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Glasidfasnfak nviasdnkga (Jell-O shots: a bad idea).
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, people know Jell-O. We've all been to dinners
where Jell-O salads with marshmallows and nuts were served. We've
all had mixed success making Jell-O. We joke about it. We see it in
movies. And with picnic season beginning this weekend, we can't
help but think about Jell-O.
</P>
<P>
   It enjoys periodic resurgences _ the 100th anniversary three
years ago brought renewed interest, plus the wonderful sparkling
Jell-O you make with ginger ale. Twentysomething hipsters who love
all things retro-ironic host '50s style dinner parties with Jell-O
salads. There are Web sites dedicated to all things Jell-O and
physicists who analyze the chemical composition of the fun food.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone seems to have a favorite _ or at least notable _ Jell-O
salad: the lime Jell-O with cottage cheese, the one with cherries
and cream cheese cubes, the cherry Coke one, the one with the
pretzel crust and cream cheese layer, the cranberry-and-nuts
Thanksgiving Jell-O salad.
</P>
<P>
   Jigglers have replaced molded salads, and Jell-O has adjusted
with the times to add easy-to-make salads and sugar-free products
to their repertoire. Jell-O has become a food for the family on the
go, the health-conscious, the nostalgic and the faithful who always
have made Jell-O and will keep making Jell-O oblivious to the
fickle winds of food trends.
</P>
<P>
   Bring on the marshmallows and carrot bits.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
