<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0969 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BANKS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     05-31 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE ANGEL ON THE ROOF': THE GRIT OF DAILY LIFE MEETS SPIRITUAL
EPIPHANY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes at end of review) 
 By JANET MASLIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``You! You're not mad at me like that, are you?'' asks a
character in Russell Banks' story ``Firewood.'' ``For leaving your
mother and all?'' Only a few pages later, in the next of the 31
stories in this beautifully lucid, frequently wrenching collection,
another father is asking his disaffected child essentially the same
thing. ``Was I wrong, to divorce your mother? To leave you?'' a man
asks in ``Quality Time,'' only to be spurned by an adult daughter
not interested in giving him a second chance. ``Now you've lost us
both,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   At his shattering best _ that is, in stories less easily
schematic than ``Quality Time'' turns out to be _ Banks offers
answers that are tough, honest and inevitable without being simple.
He returns again and again to the caldron of domestic life, in
which hard drinking, deep-seated strife and often the prospect of a
bleak New Hampshire winter make the walls close in. ``In those
days, women and me not finding out about them are what connected
everything in that man's life,'' one woman tells her son about his
father in ``Assisted Living.'' In ``Success Story,'' the narrator
observes that ``in some ways, my family was a civic reclamation
project _ the bright and pretty children and pathetic wife of a
brute who, nearly a decade ago, had disappeared into the northern
woods with a woman from the post office, never to be heard from
again.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Firewood,'' Banks describes a man who has had his third
drink of the day by 8 a.m. as part of a familiar pattern (``and
before he knows how it happens, it has happened again, and there he
is, being pulled off some guy and hustled out the door or picked up
off the floor and aimed by strangers toward his car'') and winds up
alone in the snow, finding it easier to stack wood than to make
sense of his life. In ``Plains of Abraham,'' as in many of the
stories here, a character registers real regret about the wreckage
in his past. ``Family life had slipped from his grasp without his
having noticed, as if, closing his eyes to drink from a spring,
he'd lost a handful of clear water and was unable afterwards to
imagine a way to regain it. The spring must have dried up. A man
can't blame his hands, can he?''
</P>
<P>
   As this book reveals, with stories dating back to his 1975
``Searching for Survivors'' and nine previously uncollected stores
from Esquire, Ploughshares and other sources, the contrasts here
between quotidian reality and spiritual epiphany have been as
central to Banks' short fiction as they have to his novels. Anyone
who first became familiar with his work through the transcendent
film adaptations of ``The Sweet Hereafter'' and especially
``Affliction,'' which is closer in eloquent, unflinching tone to
the author's writing, will find nearly as much to discover here as
in the best of his longer fiction (those novels and the magnificent
``Continental Drift'').
</P>
<P>
   What elevates these stories far above their tacitly
heartbreaking events are the vast reserves of compassion and wisdom
that Banks brings to framing tragedy. One of the most eloquent
stories in the book is ``The Child Screams and Looks Back at You,''
in which a woman witnesses the death of her son.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Angel on the Roof'' so knowingly and movingly explores
this kind of intimacy that its efforts to reveal a larger range
cast an unflattering light on some of its more marginal material.
Although this book collects work from four previously published
short story collections, almost all of the best entries come from
the 1981 ``Trailerpark,'' which features interwoven accounts of the
Granite State Trailerpark and its community of residents. Shuffling
the order of these pieces (so that ``The Fisherman'' is the first
to appear here, though it provided an ending to ``Trailerpark'' and
is best read after all its characters are already familiar) is
perhaps meant to show them off in a new perspective. But they still
stand out starkly amid more awkward conceits, like the stories
``The Caul'' and ``Indisposed,'' narrated respectively by Edgar
Allan Poe and Jane Hogarth, wife of the renowned portrait painter.
Within these stories are the seeds of ``Cloudsplitter,'' the
voluminous historical novel in which Banks reconstructed John
Brown's raid on Harper's Ferry. But far more successful and less
manipulative are the more direct, down-to-earth accounts of
ordinary lives as glimpsed by an extraordinarily wise observer.
</P>
<P>
   As a book that is not to be missed but is best read selectively,
``The Angel on the Roof'' is especially impressive for stories like
``The Guinea Pig Lady,'' a trailer park novella that builds to a
harrowing finale for its eccentric heroine, and ``Queen for a
Day,'' a stunning account of how a young boy tries helping his
mother to redefine their family. ``Lobster Night,'' previously
uncollected, begins its first paragraph this way: ``Stacy didn't
mean to tell Noonan that when she was 17 she was struck by
lightning.'' And its second paragraph starts this way: ``The night
Stacy told Noonan about the lightning was also the night she shot
and killed him.'' Among Banks' extraordinary skills, the technical
prowess and storytelling grace that hook a reader so seemingly
easily should not be overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   The story that best encapsulates Banks' cyclical sense of
domestic strife is ``The Visit,'' in which a man returns to the
scene and the memories of his father's bullying. ``It's as if
violence were a gift worth any price. Beyond the light and the
heat, it's a gift that engenders gorgeous dreams of retribution,
and they last for tens of generations of fathers and children,
husbands and wives _ it's a gift that shapes and drives fantasies
of becoming huge as a glacier and hard as iron, fast as light, and
sudden, like a volcano.'' Or of being able to articulate and
confront it as mightily as this.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   THE ANGEL ON THE ROOF: The Stories of Russell Banks
</P>
<P>
   By RUSSELL BANKS
</P>
<P>
   506 pages. HarperCollins. $27.50.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 1747EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
