<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, June 1, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A front separating chilly air near the Canadian border from
summery warmth over most of the Plains and Eastern states will be
the focus for clusters of thunderstorms Thursday and Thursday
night. The heaviest thunderstorms will occur over the northern
Mississippi Valley and western Great Lakes where a plume of humid
air from the south is forced to rise over the cool air farther
north. Some storms will have damaging winds and hail. A few of the
thunderstorm clusters will pass over ground saturated by recent
rain, posing the threat of local flooding.
</P>
<P>
   A surge of very warm air will spread across the Ohio Valley into
the Middle Atlantic states. Variable clouds and a few thunderstorms
will occur near a front as it stalls later Thursday in the interior
Northeast. The Southeast will stay mainly sunny and hot with little
chance for rain.
</P>
<P>
   Cool, unsettled weather will linger over the northern Rockies,
especially in Montana. Most of the Southwest will be hot with ample
sunshine.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: FIRE AND THUNDER
</P>
<P>
   Isolated thunderstorms are expected Thursday in parts of New
Mexico where wildfires are burning thousands of acres of forest.
But the air near the ground is also relatively dry, raising the
likelihood that raindrops falling from the some of the storms will
evaporate before reaching the ground. Without wet trees and brush,
lightning strikes could ignite new wildfires. Gusty thunderstorm
winds may also cause erratic behavior of existing fires. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
