<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-OIL-WELLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TEXAS GROUP SEEKS TOUGHER RULES FOR OIL, GAS PRODUCERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RUSSELL GOLD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A report prepared by energy industry
representatives and large landowners urges the state to crack down
on oil and gas producers who abandon wells without properly
plugging them.
</P>
<P>
   The orphaned wells threaten aquifers and force the state to bear
the clean-up costs, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   The report was delivered this week to Texas Railroad Commission
Chairman Michael Williams, who convened the group. Williams is
reviewing the recommendations and will present specific proposals
to the three-member Railroad Commission, which sets state oil and
gas policy.
</P>
<P>
   The report comes as regulators, the industry and landowners
struggle to find a new way to oversee oil and gas production in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   There is widespread agreement the current system lets too many
``bad actors'' and poorly financed companies walk away from their
depleted wells, leaving behind expensive headaches for the state.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals include letting fewer companies pay the $100
annual fee to operate. More would have to provide a larger
performance bond, lien or nonrefundable fee. Also, the report
suggested that companies should be required to either plug or
produce wells after four years, ending an increasingly common
practice of keeping them idle indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Far from fostering a consensus, the report is drawing criticism
for being too weak.
</P>
<P>
   A top commission official wrote an ``alternative proposal'' that
suggested even more aggressive action might be warranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential for pollution by those wells has continued to
increase and decisive action is necessary,'' Colin Lineberry, the
assistant director of the commission's oil and gas section, wrote
in a memorandum.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that a decade after the state created a cleanup fund to
aggressively deal with abandoned wells, the problems appear to be
worse than ever.
</P>
<P>
   The number of documented inactive wells rose 59 percent to
102,000 over the past 10 years, even as the number of wells plugged
by companies dropped 42 percent to 5,912 a year, he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   State rules require monitoring of inactive wells, but many
observers worry that as the number of inactive wells grows so does
the incidence of oil well-related contamination. An unplugged or
improperly plugged well can let extremely salty brine ruin
freshwater aquifers.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals ``are an important step in the right direction,
but more needs to be done,'' wrote A. Scott Anderson, executive
vice president of the Texas Independent Producers and Royalty
Owners Association, or TIPRO.
</P>
<P>
   TIPRO officials have expressed concern about the number of
unplugged wells, which at the existing pace will take 20 years to
plug.
</P>
<P>
   The commission cannot close abandoned wells at a faster pace
because of the limited number of available plugging contractors,
too little money in the cleanup fund and too few employees to
supervise plugging.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the commission has tried to keep wells unplugged,
even wells that produce only a couple barrels a day, because they
may have economic value in the future. Operators are allowed to pay
$100 for a one-year extension to keep an unproductive well idle
rather than going though the expense of plugging it.
</P>
<P>
   This W-1X extension program, created in 1988, is being abused,
particularly by a handful of bad operators, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real and most immediate problem is that the W-1X option is
also available to operators who have not demonstrated that they are
willing and financially able to operate responsibly,'' the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some operators are getting extension after extension without
taking steps to put the wells back into production. These wells can
end up abandoned or sold.
</P>
<P>
   In April, a plan by Commissioner Tony Garza to limit producers
to a single extension was voted down, so operators still can get an
unlimited number of extensions.
</P>
<P>
   The industry group would like to create a four-year limit, as
well as require more financial assurance, or bonding, for certain
operators.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't go near far enough, but it's so much better than
what we had before that overall I have to say I'm pleased,'' said
Ceci Wallen, mineral and land manager for the San Antonio-based
Petty Ranch Co.
</P>
<P>
   Wallen, who represented the Texas Land and Mineral Owners
Association in the group, said she was surprised state rules let
operators with a poor compliance history buy wells and idle them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept of approving a known bad actor is just bizarre to
me,'' she said, ``but that's what has been happening.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
