<SLUG> BC-CIR-ORGAN-DONORS-1090(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCHING THE WEB AS A MATTER OF LIFE AND DEATH
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Minn. , Ill., Netherlands)  By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Daniel Brown, a 32-year-old lawyer in Bethesda, Md., got the
news in February that he had chronic myelogenous leukemia and that
no one in his family had the proper genetic match to donate
life-saving bone marrow.
</P>
<P>
   The disease kills 60 percent to 70 percent of patients within
five years of diagnosis, according to bone-marrow specialists.
``Time is not on your side,'' said Brown's wife, Jolie. ``So some
families do their own bone-marrow drive, and that's what we've
done. We're not going to sit around and wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Within three weeks after hearing the diagnosis, the Browns were
calling every friend and organization they knew, printing fliers
and setting up drives to attract volunteer donors whose marrow
might provide the critical match of proteins needed for a
successful transplant.
</P>
<P>
   The family did something else, too. They got on the Internet,
establishing their own Web site, Tomorrow for Dan
(www.viaduct.com/helpdan). It is not just a plea for help; it is
also a brief primer on the disease, a family photo album and a link
to the National Marrow Donor Program (www.marrow.org) and the donor
program the Browns are working with, the Gift of Life Foundation
(www.hlamatch.org).
</P>
<P>
   Brown estimated that his family and volunteers directly sent out
at least 10,000 e-mail messages, not including those forwarded by
their recipients. ``It's clearly opened a door that didn't exist
previously, to allow you to communicate with a mass number of
people in a short period of time,'' Brown said. It gave him a huge
respect, he said, for the patients and groups that previously had
to rely on direct mail.
</P>
<P>
   Bone-marrow donor registries and the Internet have grown up
together in the last 10 years, and both have revolutionized the
potential of bone-marrow transplants when a matching donor cannot
be found in a patient's immediate family.
</P>
<P>
   Since the National Marrow Donor Program, a nonprofit
organization based in Minneapolis, began in 1986, the number of
volunteer potential donors registered with it has risen to just
under 4 million, from fewer than 100,000 at the beginning of 1990.
As of May 14, the program had been involved in 9,715 transplants of
stem cells from unrelated donors, compared with 533 by 1990. Stem
cells are what transplant patients need to make new, healthy
marrow.
</P>
<P>
   It is much harder to match types of bone marrow than types of
blood. People have about a 30 percent chance of matching with a
family member. If that fails, the next option is to search
registries of people who have volunteered to donate marrow. On
average, about 1 in 20,000 unrelated people match closely enough
for a bone-marrow donation.
</P>
<P>
   The number of registered potential donors has roughly doubled
since the first of the program's Web sites was set up in 1995.
``Originally we created a site with a target audience of
physicians,'' said Devan Shepherd, director of information systems.
``We discovered that patients and their families were using it.''
</P>
<P>
   The program's computer system manages all patient searches,
tracks detailed patient histories and maintains the
4-million-member registry. At any time, it is processing searches
for more than 3,000 patients. The donor program communicates online
daily with 350 to 400 groups around the country, including
hospitals, community groups and donor centers.
</P>
<P>
   In transplant centers, Shepherd said, new online tools provided
by the program shorten the time it takes to search national and
international registries to find matches. In some cases, the search
for a potential unrelated stem-cell donor that used to take a day
can now be done in seconds.
</P>
<P>
   There are dozens of independent bone-marrow and related
registries worldwide, and they do not share all their information.
Most, but not all, do share the basic tissue data for the more than
6.4 million people worldwide who have given samples; it is
forwarded to Bone Marrow Donors Worldwide, in Leiden, Netherlands.
That group's Web site, www.bmdw.org, is open to doctors and the
public, and includes technical data, information about how to
become a marrow donor, extensive links to more information about
the procedure and cancer treatment, and information on donor
registries worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not updated as often as some of us would like,'' said Dr.
Dennis L. Confer, the chief medical officer for the National Marrow
Donor Program. The international registry updates its list monthly.
For information other than the basic tissue types, doctors have to
write, phone or send faxes or e-mail to the individual registries,
Confer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more, the ability to access donors through online
communications is going to become the norm,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela J. Weisdorf, director of the program's office of patient
advocacy, said its Web site was being redesigned for
user-friendliness with the help of a 12-member advisory group,
including patients and their family members. ``They want
information about their disease,'' sometimes even before they know
they need a transplant, she said. ``One of the other things they
tell us is, `Please, you have to put things into language we can
understand.'''
</P>
<P>
   There is also a difference between Web language and medical
language. Take the word ``search,'' Weisdorf said. It means one
thing to most Internet users, but to patients facing a
life-or-death deadline, it means searching for an unrelated-donor
match.
</P>
<P>
   A related site, BMT Information (www.bmtinfo.org) is a
cooperative effort of the National Marrow Donor Program and the
national and international donor registries, and receives federal
financing. It has a glossary and an Ask the Expert section, with
doctors' answers to submitted questions.
</P>
<P>
   Another online resource is the Blood and Marrow Transplant
Newsletter (www.bmtnews.org), run from Highland Park, Ill. It lists
books that can be ordered online and links patients with people who
have undergone the process. It has a database of more than 250
transplant centers that can be searched by location, type of
disease treated and type of transplant offered. The newsletter also
has an online directory of specialized health care organizations
with more information, and guidance for patients with fund-raising
needs and insurance problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became apparent that a lot of people were starting to get
their information in the wee hours using their computers,'' said
Susan K. Stewart, executive director of BMT Infonet, a small
nonprofit group that sponsors the newsletter. It gets about 100,000
hits a month, she added.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With the help of the Gift of Life Foundation, which is open to
anyone but has focused on patients and donors of Eastern European
Jewish background, the Brown family organized six drives for Daniel
through early May, attracting 7,238 potential donors who had their
blood tested. (Having your tissue type determined and getting on
the registry is like having a blood test in a doctor's office, and
requires only a test tube's worth.)
</P>
<P>
   One of the 703 blood donors at the April 31 drive at the Central
Synagogue in Manhattan, David Wohl, 29, was a fraternity brother of
Daniel Brown's, but had been three years behind him and knew him
only vaguely. ``I received an e-mail from another frat brother,''
Wohl said. The news shocked him. ``I felt for Dan and his family,''
he said. ``I went to the Web site and read more.''
</P>
<P>
   Evan Cowit, 31, a lawyer and a friend of a friend of Daniel
Brown's, also donated. Without the e-mail he received, he said, he
probably would never have heard about the drive. ``I sent it around
to everyone I could think of who was Eastern European Jewish and
who hadn't already got it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In late May, the Browns were informed that at least two
potential matching donors had been identified, and those tissue
samples are undergoing further tests. Because of confidentiality
rules, they do not know whether the donors had been previously
registered or if one of them came from their family's drives for
Dan. Regardless, to Jolie Brown, their efforts were worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the thousands of people we're trying to test,'' Brown said,
``we'll surely save somebody's life, and that is a wonderful
feeling.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
