<HEADER>
A0978 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-HERSH-MCCAFFREY-HNS &LR;      05-31 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERSH-MCCAFFREY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HERSH DEFENDS HIS CLAIMS OF U.S. GULF WAR ILLEGALITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pulitzer-prize winning journalist Seymour Hersh on
Wednesday defended his controversial assertions that Army Gen.
Barry McCaffrey ordered an unprovoked assault against retreating
Iraqi troops two days after the cease fire ending the 1991 Persian
Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think McCaffrey's action was an absolute violation,
certainly of a commander's responsibility to act proportionately,
and a violation of international law,'' Hersh told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   During the Gulf War, McCaffrey was a major general commanding
the 24th Mechanized Infantry Division. He retired in 1996 as a
four-star general and is now President Clinton's drug policy
adviser.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey and representatives of the White House and the Defense
Department have denied Hersh's claims.
</P>
<P>
   President Bush announced the cease fire on Feb. 28, 1991, after
U.S. forces had routed the Iraqi military in only 100 hours of
ground combat.
</P>
<P>
   As the Iraqi troops departed Kuwait on their way north to Iraq,
McCaffrey ordered his division to stay close to the retreating
Iraqis, a move that Hersh called ``an amazing act of arrogance''
because, according to the author, McCaffrey had put his troops in
harm's way for no valid military reason.
</P>
<P>
   On March 2, according to Hersh's article, the U.S. force
attacked the Iraqi units. The American forces shelled Iraqi troops
and tanks, even though the tanks were being ferried home on flatbed
trucks. Hersh said he didn't know the extent of Iraqi casualties,
though McCaffrey told Congress after the war that there were some
400 Iraqi casualties in this engagement.
</P>
<P>
   An Army investigation concluded that McCaffrey's troops had been
provoked by weapons fire, a finding that was contradicted by the
military personnel cited in Hersh's article.
</P>
<P>
   Hersh said the original tip for his lengthy 32-page New Yorker
article came from a retired four-star U.S. officer, who, like
several other military officials, was ``enraged'' by McCaffrey's
actions.
</P>
<P>
   In the article, Hersh quotes several Army officials by name who
say that the attack on the Iraqis was unprovoked.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Lt. Col. Patrick Lamar, the division's operations
officer, told Hersh that the attack was a ``giant hoax'' in which
Iraqis who put up little or no resistance were decimated by
overwhelming U.S. force.Retired Lt. Gen. James H. Johnson Jr., who
commanded the 82nd Airborne in the Gulf War, was quoted in the
magazine as saying that ``there was no need to be shooting at
anybody'' on March 2, 1991. ``They couldn't surrender fast enough.
The war was over.''
</P>
<P>
   Hersh's article also alleged that 24th Division forces fired on
at least 380 Iraqi prisoners on Feb. 27, 1991, one day before the
cease fire. In Hersh's account, based on on-the-record comments
from eyewitness troops and an audio tape of radio conversations
during the event, U.S. forces had disarmed the prisoners and
radioed their location to other troops, who later opened fire with
machine guns on Bradley fighting vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Hersh, who broke the story of the massacre of Vietnamese
civilians at My Lai during the Vietnam War, said Wednesday that one
of the companies under McCaffrey's command was ``out of control''
and ``shooting everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Army and McCaffrey deny Hersh's allegations. The Army said
that it had already investigated the post-cease fire assault and
cleared McCaffrey and his troops of any wrongdoing on the basis
that U.S. forces were provoked by the Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the POWs, the Army said ``there was no evidence
to indicate that members of the (24th Infantry) killed or
mistreated (Iraqi POWs).''
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey attacked Hersh's article as ``revisionist history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hersh has the safe luxury of armchair quarterbacking the every
move of the 24th Infantry during the Gulf War, 10 years after the
fact. We did not have that luxury,'' McCaffrey said. ``We were out
there fighting the fourth largest army in the world, which was
armed with chemical and biological weapons .''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times and a Gulf War veteran's group have called
for an investigation into allegations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; --- &QL;
</P>
