<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0980 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-CNN-AOL01-COX     05-31 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-AOL01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TURNER AND HIS CABLE EMPIRE WILL BE STRONGER, AOL EXEC SAYS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The man who soon will replace Ted Turner as head of
the Turner cable TV empire said Wednesday its employees should not
fear layoffs or editorial meddling when the new parent company, AOL
Time Warner Inc., takes over.
</P>
<P>
   And they should ignore a recent newspaper story that suggested
Turner won't have much influence over the businesses he created,
said Robert Pittman, chief operating officer of America Online
Inc., the Internet giant that plans to absorb Time Warner Inc.,
parent company of Turner Broadcasting System.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is a 'post-Ted Turner' era'' coming after
the merger, Pittman said in a telephone interview. ``I think Ted's
going to have more influence than he had before, because I fully
expect that he'll have a say in a lot broader areas of the company
than just Turner networks and CNN.''
</P>
<P>
   Pittman added that the Atlanta-based executives who make
decisions about salaries for Turner employees, such as baseball and
basketball players, will continue to operate as independently as
they have under Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   A management reorganization plan released in May showed Turner
would no longer head the Time Warner division that includes
operations he built or bought, including CNN, TBS, TNT, the Atlanta
Braves and the Atlanta Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   But Pittman dismissed a story Friday in the Los Angeles Times
that said Turner was unhappy about not getting a formal operating
role in the immense new company. ``I thought it was so far off the
mark in terms of what Ted is in this company,'' he said. ``I
couldn't quite understand where all of that was coming from.''
</P>
<P>
   Given that shareholders still have to approve the merger of the
Internet giant and the media company, Pittman and other AOL
executives have a stake in Turner's happiness. In a merged company,
Turner would be the largest individual shareholder, with about 4
percent of the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders will vote June 23 on the proposed combination. The
world's biggest Internet service provider, AOL, will hold its
shareholder meeting in Vienna, Va., a suburb of Washington, while
shareholders of Time Warner will gather in New York.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, AOL Chairman and Chief Executive Steve Case would
become the chairman of the new company, while Time Warner Chairman
and Chief Executive Gerald Levin will serve as chief executive of
AOL Time Warner. Pittman will be co-chief operating officer, along
with Time Warner president Richard Parsons. Turner will be vice
chairman, a role without day-to-day operating power.
</P>
<P>
   The merger also has to win the approval of government regulators
concerned about concentration of power in the media. Given that the
deal is not yet done, Turner could cause trouble if he decided to
fight it.
</P>
<P>
   Pittman said he had no fears about Turner making a late effort
to derail the deal because Turner wants AOL's resources to boost
the companies he created.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just talked to Ted last week and just went over a fairly
extensive list'' of improvements that Turner wants at CNN, he said.
``I fully expect to make that (list) part of my mandate.''
</P>
<P>
   Cable viewers, too, have nothing to fear from an AOL and Time
Warner merger, such as a pullback in CNN's coverage of breaking
news around the world, Pittman said. ``They've gone global probably
better than any other TV network,'' he said. ``All we're going to
do is expand their opportunities and probably give them additional
resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Pittman said Tom Johnson ``absolutely'' will continue to run
CNN, and will do so with the editorial freedom he always has had.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Pittman has said that a combined company would be
able to save $1 billion a year. But those savings will not come
from cutbacks in staff or spending on news or sports teams, but
instead from ``synergies'' achieved primarily in advertising, he
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of (the savings) are linked to shared marketing,'' he
said. ``We spend at AOL about a billion a year on marketing. If we
re-purpose those dollars and buy from existing Time Warner
properties _ the magazine group, the Turner networks, etc. _ in
areas where we are not displacing a paying advertiser, that money
all drops to the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Pittman, 46, says he believes he has an especially close
relationship with Turner because their careers have followed
similar paths. Pittman started as a radio disk jockey in his native
Mississippi. In 1980, while Turner was creating CNN, Pittman was
thinking up another cable TV ``first.'' In 1981, he made his mark
as the programmer who created MTV.
</P>
<P>
   Under Pittman's leadership, MTV Networks grew into the first
profitable basic cable network company. He also helped create the
VH-1 and Nick at Nite cable television channels.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Pittman sold Quantum Media Inc., an entertainment
company he helped found, to Time Warner. He then went to work for
Time Warner, helping overhaul its Six Flags amusement parks. He
left Time Warner and spent a short time as chief executive of
Century 21 Real Estate Corp. In 1996, joined America Online, which
means he now has the advantage of having been an executive for both
AOL and Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   For more information: www.aol.com, www.cnn.com.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
