<HEADLINE>
&HT;     49ERS RUNNING BACK VOWS TO PLAY IN 2000 SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ As he sat in an equipment cart, his
elevated left leg in a cast, Garrison Hearst talked confidently of
returning to football despite 16 months away from the game with
what might be the most troublesome ankle injury in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   You remember Hearst. Tough guy, locker room funnyman, started
the 1998 season with a 96-yard touchdown run in overtime against
the Jets and ended it with a broken left leg in a playoff game
against Atlanta on Jan. 9, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst missed the entire 1999 season and faces more down time in
2000 after surgery in Seattle three weeks ago in which Dr. Pierce
Scranton performed a procedure that is designed to stimulate blood
flow to his ankle.
</P>
<P>
   The bone he broke 16 months ago has long since healed. The
problem is the ankle developed necrosis as a result of the injury;
the joint was dying because circulation had become compromised.
Necrosis of the hip forced Bo Jackson to retire from football a
decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst is scheduled to have the cast removed on Friday, at which
time he will be fitted with a walking boot that will aid his
rehabilitation. Still, the earliest Hearst could return if his
recovery goes well is October. There is also the possibility that
he could miss another full season as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feeling good,'' is how the San Francisco 49ers running back
described himself. ``It was four weeks in this, three weeks in a
walking boot and we'll see how things go after that. I always kept
my head up about this injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he expected of himself this season, he said, ``I
expect to play.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Hearst in uniform would be a bonus for the 49ers.
The club is prepared to play the season without him as it did last
year, when, with Charlie Garner's 1,229 yards, the 49ers led the
league in rushing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have my fingers crossed,'' coach Steve Mariucci said Tuesday
of Hearst, after the first of a four-day minicamp for rookies and
selected veterans. ``If you have Garrison with you, then it's icing
on the cake. We have to prepare to be without him, as we were last
year. We have everyone back. We should be as good or better than
last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Because it has been so long since Hearst has been able to run
unfettered, his cardiovascular condition is what he will have to
attack when and if his ankle permits. In the meantime, his work in
the weight room shows in an upper body that is thicker than it was
in 1998, when Hearst rushed for a club-record 1,570 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the hardest part,'' he said of his long recovery. ``I
see my progress every day and keep working until I reach that next
level. I feel very comfortable about the surgery. It's been rough,
but I just think positive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
