<SLUG> BC-TONYS-TV-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT SHARES CUSTODY, BUT PBS GETS THE TONYS FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 4) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jeff Folmsbee seems calmer now. ``Do You Wanna
Dance?'' is playing, and Boyd Gaines is onstage in the empty Vivian
Beaumont Theater, wooing Deborah Yates, better known as the Girl in
the Yellow Dress (but at the moment wearing a fleece top and
pants). A crew of five is filming the couple's every move as they
run through a scene from Susan Stroman's dance play ``Contact.''
The crew has already shot Stroman leading a rehearsal of dancers
and a rehearsal of the show's 18th-century girl-in-a-swing scene.
</P>
<P>
   Folmsbee, who is carrying a collection of a dozen or so
scribbled-on Playbills, was pacing earlier in the day. At this
point in early May, the Tony Awards are less than five weeks away
but the nominations have yet to be announced, so he and his team
are running around town madly filming shows they are guessing will
be nominated. This film will go into the documentary segments that
dot the first hour of the Tony Awards telecast Sunday night at 8).
You know, the hour that's on PBS before the CBS show begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people may think of us as the preshow, but we're not,''
says Folmsbee, the hour's co-executive producer, understandably
offended by the notion. This year, he hopes, that point is being
made more forcefully than before. The title of the hour is ``The
First 10 Awards: Tonys 2000'' (last year it was ``Broadway '99:
Launching the Tonys,'' which the producers concede may have
contributed to the misconception). The first-hour show is getting
equal space with the CBS show on the official posters. Rosie
O'Donnell _ who is returning as host of the overall telecast _ will
be acting as live host of the first hour, with Nathan Lane as
co-host.
</P>
<P>
   Lane put in a plug for the PBS hour on O'Donnell's daytime talk
show last Tuesday (a good thing, since the show has been promoting
the awards as ``this Sunday on CBS at 9 p.m.''). ``It's like the
early part of the party,'' he said, urging viewers to tune in.
O'Donnell chimed in, ``It's like the cocktail party _ with
awards.'' O'Donnell and Lane will open the show with a glitzy
number to the tune of Stephen Sondheim's ``Comedy Tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It will reinforce what is true,'' says Folmsbee. ``This is a
three-hour ceremony on two networks.''
</P>
<P>
   When that three-hour broadcast begins, Folmsbee and the
documentary segments' producer, Mark Mannucci, will be in black tie
but packed with other workers inside a control room on wheels, a
huge tractor-trailer truck parked near Radio City Music Hall. It's
a CBS truck.
</P>
<P>
   This strange dual-network arrangement began in 1997 after the
League of American Theaters and Producers and the American Theater
Wing, which present the Tonys, approached WNET (Channel 13), New
York's public broadcasting station. CBS _ troubled, like other
networks, by the growing and unpredictable length of awards
telecasts _ had decided it could no longer commit to more than a
two-hour show.
</P>
<P>
   The people at WNET said yes. ``I had some compassion for this,''
says Jac Venza, the station's director of culture and arts programs
and the show's other co-executive producer. In the past, he says,
when classical music shows he produced received awards, the
category was relegated to the off-air presentations.
</P>
<P>
   He does not consider the first hour of the Tonys a poor relation
to the CBS portion of the show, but he sees that attitude as par
for the course. ``Everything we've started was once thought of as
something the networks didn't want,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of the hour's loyal viewers consider the first hour
superior to the rest of the telecast. ``Oh, I love the 8 o'clock
show,'' says David F. Richardson, a theater critic for WOR Radio.
``PBS always does a fantastic job. It's one of the best parts.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Burrichter, a movie-theater marketing manager, feels the
same way. ``Wouldn't miss it,'' says Burrichter, a onetime theater
publicist. ``I just think it brings a whole different dimension to
watching the Tonys on TV. It gives the designers and the other
people behind the scenes their just due, and it nurtures interest
in the theater on the creative side, not just commercial.''
</P>
<P>
   Creatively, the show has been well received too. Mannucci, who
this year is producing five three-minute to nine-minute documentary
segments (on the musical season and on the nominated scenic
designers, lighting designers, costume designers and directors),
sees the segments as ``the heart of the hour.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You get to root for the people you saw,'' says Mannucci. ``The
stories are told from a human angle.'' There are the same humans
from the short films, sitting in the audience in evening wear,
chewing on their cuticles, accidentally applauding their own
nominations, preparing to look brave.
</P>
<P>
   The PBS hour has its critics as well. Last year, while CBS was
being lambasted for cutting a musical number from ``It Ain't
Nothin' but the Blues'' but keeping a deadly dramatic reading from
the nominated plays, WNET was being criticized for its treatment of
Uta Hagen. Hagen, who played Desdemona to Paul Robeson's Othello
and won Tonys for originating the lead female roles in ``Who's
Afraid of Virginia Woolf?'' and ``The Country Girl,'' was honored
with a lifetime achievement award. But she wasn't even asked to go
onstage. On the Oscars, a career like this would be occasion for
five minutes of film clips and a standing ovation. On the Tonys,
Hagen stood at her seat and waved. ``We got letters,'' Folmsbee
admits.
</P>
<P>
   With or without gaffes, for people who love theater, the show's
first hour has a glamour all its own. Last year the first
presenters were Alan Cumming (wearing a red shirt, a long black
jacket and what appeared to be a fishing hat), who had won for
``Cabaret'' the year before, and Audra McDonald, who has won for
``Carousel,'' ``Master Class'' and ``Ragtime.''
</P>
<P>
   The documentary segments included Kevin Spacey, on the stage set
of ``The Iceman Cometh,'' commenting on the experience of being
directed (``Sometimes you just say, `Just tell me how you want me
to say it'''), Kristin Chenoweth rehearsing her star-making
performance as Sally in ``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown'' and
Harold Prince reflecting on why there will always be theater.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night's segments will include this season's toasts of
Broadway, like Heather Headley of ``Aida,'' Stephen Dillane and
Jennifer Ehle of ``The Real Thing,'' and Philip Seymour Hoffman and
John C. Reilly of ``True West.''
</P>
<P>
   The hour's awards aren't just important; sometimes they're
historic. In 1998, after some 50 years of men having received the
best director Tonys, women were named best directors of a play
(Garry Hynes for ``The Beauty Queen of Leenane'') and of a musical
(Julie Taymor for ``The Lion King''). Both Hynes and Taymor
received their awards and made their speeches during the PBS show.
</P>
<P>
   Which, come to think of it, always ends promptly at 9 p.m. How
do they do it, while the commercial networks let Oscar and Emmy and
Grammy telecasts ramble on into Letterman-Leno territory?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have different versions of the segments _ long, short and
medium,'' says Mannucci. ``I don't want to tempt fate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
