<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0988 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NUREYEV-FILM-$ADV04-2     05-31 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUREYEV-FILM-$ADV04-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUREYEV'S PARTNER, THE CAMERA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Russia, Australia, France, Britain)  ( For release Sunday, June 4)  
 By DAVID HAY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thirty-four years ago, during the filming of his
ballet ``Le Jeune Homme et la Mort,'' the French choreographer
Roland Petit walked into Rudolf Nureyev's dressing room to check on
his star's makeup. ``He said to me, `Am I looking good?''' Petit
recalled recently. ``I said, `You're as good as Marilyn Monroe.' He
looked at me. `Is it a compliment?' I replied, `Of course.'''
</P>
<P>
   Like any star, Nureyev was anxious about his screen image. From
his early days in Leningrad, he used film to critique not only his
dancing but his curtain calls. ``The first time he saw 8-millimeter
footage which a friend shot at the end of a Kirov performance, he
became very depressed because his bows were, in his words,
`pathetic,''' said Wallace Potts, the film archivist for the Rudolf
Nureyev Foundation in Liechtenstein and the dancer's longtime
friend.
</P>
<P>
   But Nureyev's ideas about what film could do for dance extended
beyond his own personal use, in part because he developed a
sophisticated knowledge of film language. According to Potts,
Nureyev could describe the Odessa Steps montage in the classic 1925
film ``Potemkin'' ``as if he were some kind of VCR quickly playing
back the entire sequence.''
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence, Nureyev was keen to expand the scope of the
ballet film beyond preserving a particular choreography or
broadcasting a stage performance. For him, film could show off a
dancer's kinetic energy as well as provide a close-up of the
disciplined and expressive use of the body.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday through next Sunday the Film Society of Lincoln Center
is presenting ``This is Nureyev! A Weekend of Dance on Film,'' a
series of four programs that will be repeated on June 16 and 17 at
the Los Angeles County Museum of Art. Shot mostly during the 1960s,
when Nureyev was at his peak, the films provide an intimate look at
his extraordinary dancing prowess. They also bear witness to his
strong but seldom realized ambitions for the ballet film.
</P>
<P>
   The program starts with the earliest 35-millimeter film of
Nureyev dancing. In April 1958, he won first prize at the Moscow
National Classical Ballet Contest. In a voice-over to the
two-minute, black-and-white clip of his winning ``Le Corsaire''
solo, shot two days after the contest, the narrator notes that
``this artist is characterized by his hot temperament and
boldness.''
</P>
<P>
   Liuba Myasnikova, a close friend from Nureyev's student days and
now a research scientist at the Institute of the Academy of
Sciences in St. Petersburg, recalled in a telephone interview:
``His movements weren't as pure as they were later on. But he was
beside himself with joy at winning. He always wanted to be at the
top.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long after defecting to the West in 1961, Nureyev began his
legendary partnership with Margot Fonteyn. The magic of this
pairing is captured in an eight-minute excerpt of their 1965 ``Le
Corsaire'' pas de deux.
</P>
<P>
   The couple is also featured in the 126-minute filmed version of
Kenneth MacMillan's highly successful 1965 Royal Ballet production
of ``Romeo and Juliet,'' with the 46-year-old Fonteyn as Juliet.
This was supposed to have been a breakthrough in the ballet film,
because its director, Paul Czinner, placed eight cameras in front
of a sound stage at Pinewood Studios. According to production notes
from the time, this enabled Czinner to shoot ``the spectacle from
every conceivable angle.'' But the ploy did not make the experience
more intimate, and the result remains a standard theatrical
performance in which the audience is always distant from the
action.
</P>
<P>
   There was no time for cinematic experimentation during the
making of the documentary ``This Is Rudolf Nureyev'' in Spoleto,
Italy, in 1964. Never before publicly screened in this country, the
film shows Nureyev, at 26, flexing his wings as a choreographer for
the second company of the Royal Ballet, staging a production of
Petipa's ``Raymonda.'' In the 50-minute film, his persistent
attention to detail and encouragement of the company becomes a
fascinating portrait of a dancer truly obsessed.
</P>
<P>
   According to Potts, it was around this time that this obsession
with every facet of ballet led Nureyev to demand more input into
the films he was starring in.
</P>
<P>
   Being in front of the camera, however, often made this
difficult. He argued continuously with Pierre Jourdan, the director
of the documentary ``I Am a Dancer,'' begun in 1970, and finally
refused the producer's wish that only ``Rudolf Nureyev'' appear
above the title. As a way of expressing his displeasure, Nureyev
demanded that Margot Fonteyn be given equal billing, even though he
was the subject of the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I Am a Dancer'' offers a rare glimpse into the daily rigors of
Nureyev's professional life. Arriving in a leather trench coat and
a cap, a very Russian outfit, he transforms a utilitarian dressing
room into a private haven, methodically unpacking his glittering
costumes and changing into a worn leotard. This is followed by a
rigorous warm-up, in which Jourdan's camera closely observes the
dancer's extraordinarily fast and controlled footwork.
</P>
<P>
   Originally shot for French television and including such period
gems as the complete Fredrick Ashton ballet ``Marguerite and
Armand,'' the film was expanded to feature length for theatrical
release. According to John Percival, the editor of the now defunct
Dance and Dancers who wrote the narration, Nureyev insisted that
the longer version show a broader range of his work.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Jourdan included an extraordinary sequence of Nureyev and
Deanne Bergsma, their bodies often totally intertwined, rehearsing
Glen Tetley's modern ballet ``Field Figures.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was this animal instinct, almost animal movement in him,
that made him fit quite naturally into every nuance of the
choreography,'' Tetley said recently.
</P>
<P>
   But suggestions about content were not enough for Nureyev. ``He
made sure the editor took his direction for the film rather than
the ostensible director's,'' Percival recalled.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, Nureyev finally got his chance to go behind the camera.
The 103-minute ``Don Quixote,'' scrupulously restored last year by
the Australian Broadcasting Corp., was directed by Nureyev and the
Australian dancer Robert Helpmann. It features members of the
Australian Ballet, and Nureyev performs the role of Basilio and
Lucette Aldous that of Kitri.
</P>
<P>
   As director, Nureyev took the camera onto the stage. ``He wanted
it to be one of the dancers,'' said Peter McDonald, the first
assistant cameraman.
</P>
<P>
   Both McDonald and the director of photography, Geoffrey
Unsworth, had joined Nureyev's crew following their work on Bob
Fosse's ``Cabaret'' and Stanley Kubrick's ``2001: A Space
Odyssey.'' Using an aircraft hangar in the Melbourne suburb of
Essendon, Nureyev took advantage of a colorful set twice the size
of a conventional stage. It was constructed to allow the dancers to
be captured from almost any angle, and Nureyev insisted that the
camera move at the same speed as the dancers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning he came out of the wings at 40 miles per hour
and went right past us,'' recalled McDonald, now a director, who
had to rely on six burly Australian grips to push the camera.
``After that, we learned how to keep up.''
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the disciplines of ballet and film collided, Nureyev
never wavered in his loyalty to his first love. ``He would never
want to cut to a close-up because he wanted at all times to
preserve what the body was doing,'' recalled Potts, who, in 1972,
was a first assistant director on ``Don Quixote.''
</P>
<P>
   The directing role suited Nureyev's temperament. ``When Barry
Kay was making my costume, Rudi would stand there, approving of
some it and tearing off the bits he didn't like,'' remembered
Aldous, who, at 61, is senior classical-ballet lecturer at the
Western Australian Academy of Performing Arts in Perth.
</P>
<P>
   Nureyev looked through the camera before every shot, and during
the editing of the film he moved its editor, along with his
Moviola, into the bedroom of his London flat. In a review in The
New York Times in November 1973, Anna Kisselgoff called ``Don
Quixote'' ``a dance film for all audiences, an exciting,
intelligently conceived spectacle.''
</P>
<P>
   Nureyev got only one more chance to get behind a camera. In
1986, he directed the Paris Opera's television production of ``The
Nutcracker,'' shot on videotape (it is not in the festival).
</P>
<P>
   ``Ballet film productions never made any money,'' said John
Hargreaves, the producer of ``Don Quixote.'' Probably no one would
be sadder about this than the film producer and distributor Walter
Reade, who put up $750,000 to make ``Don Quixote.'' Happily, in the
Lincoln Center theater that now bears Reade's name, what was
accomplished nearly three decades ago can now be seen again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
