<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1011 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BRAZIL-ARTS-2TAKES-NY     05-31 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-ARTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOWING OFF THE PROFUSE CULTURE OF BRAZIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 4) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Nothing is ever done on a small scale here
in the largest city in Latin America's largest country. So when
cultural and business leaders gathered a few years back to plan how
to commemorate the 500th anniversary of the Portuguese colonization
of Brazil, it was preordained that they would want to make a bold,
sweeping statement about the state of the arts in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the dimensions of the mega-exhibition that opened here
in late April exceed all expectations. With nearly 15,000 objects
on display in 13 separate ``modules'' in four buildings that have a
combined area larger than the Louvre, ``The Rediscovery Show:
Brazil+500'' is, quite simply, the largest and most ambitious
display of Brazilian visual arts ever assembled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not partisans here of the notion that less is more,''
Nelson Aguilar, the exhibition's chief curator, said dryly. As a
result, the exhibition, which has a $25 million budget, ranges from
the Stone Age to the 21st century, with lingering stops along the
way to examine and admire the fusion of European, African and
Amerindian components that is the main characteristic of Brazil's
complicated cultural mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things didn't start out that way, but we would find one
important piece, which would lead us to another, and before we knew
it, the project had taken on a life of its own,'' explained Edemar
Cid Ferreira, a prominent Sao Paulo banker who is president of the
exhibition's organizing committee. ``So what we ended up with is a
panorama of Brazil that says to both Brazilians and the rest of the
world that this country has a cultural density that few others can
match.''
</P>
<P>
   The section that may most surprise the average visitor is the
one devoted to what is designated as ``Popular Art.'' Brazilians
have often looked upon the folk and ``primitive'' art produced
around them with marked disdain, reserving their admiration for
more formal manifestations of high art, but this section of the
show, which is perhaps the largest, is likely to force a
reassessment.
</P>
<P>
   Wood engravings and earthenware figures from Pernambuco, carved
figureheads for boats sailing the Sao Francisco River, ex-votos
from the churches of the Northeast, papier mache masks from
carnival and folk festivals, even homemade rudimentary toys: All
have found their way into the exhibition, mounted with respect and
affection. The sheer volume and variety of the pieces is a powerful
demonstration of the remarkable fecundity of the popular
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look at this art as something that is ours, ours
in the sense that it is not linked to any canon except our own,''
said Emanoel Araujo, the exhibition's curator. ``This is art that
comes from the very core of our being, and the objective is
precisely to show that these artists are profound in their own way,
that they are not beings from some other planet but from this
earth, expressing the strengths of this people.''
</P>
<P>
   Araujo is also the driving force behind ``Black in Body and
Soul,'' a unit that displays art both by and about blacks. It
includes objects that have little to do with Brazil _ photographs
by Robert Mapplethorpe, French colonial postcards of quotidian
scenes in West Africa in the 1930s _ as well as chains and other
``instruments of punishment'' from the days of slavery. But Araujo
said the message he wanted to convey was as much political as
aesthetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The racial question is always one and the same, with the same
ancestry, no matter where in the black diaspora you happen to be,
and that is what this exhibit is addressing,'' he said. ``I want a
positive construction of the black image, so this is not an
exposition of Afro-Brazilian art, but an exposition about black
people and how they express themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   In an exhibition whose scope is so vast, the principal
underlying concepts are obviously diversity and variety. Yet it is
possible to discern some common threads that link apparently
unrelated works from different periods, such as, for example, the
glossy feathered cape of a Tupinamba Indian chief sent to Europe in
the 1630s and the ``Tupinamba Cloak,'' a mixed-media construction
created by Lygia Pape this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a sense of continuity in Brazilian art that is very
dramatic to me, and it has to do with humor and playfulness and a
sensuality that is expressed in rhythms that are visual as well as
musical,'' said Edward J. Sullivan, chairman of the Department of
Fine Arts at New York University and an expert on Brazilian art.
``High seriousness with an undercurrent of irony is a constant
feature of Brazilian art, literature, cinema and even music.''
</P>
<P>
   The distance Brazil has had to travel in creating its own
exuberant aesthetic is perhaps best demonstrated in the weakest of
the exhibitions, that devoted to the 19th century. The paintings
and sculptures displayed are frankly imitative of conventional
French salon art of the same period, with little to identify the
works as Brazilian except for the tropical landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a module called ``The Distant View,'' which examines the
ways in which foreigners have portrayed Brazil, makes clear that
Brazil has also influenced Europe. The unit begins with the
landscapes painted by the Dutch artist Frans Post in the 1630s and
concludes with Anselm Kiefer's 1998 mixed-media series based on
photographs of the Sao Paulo skyline, with constant references
along the way to Brazil's extravagant flora and fauna and
resplendent natural light.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to make the exhibition attractive to a mass public
that does not ordinarily frequent museums, the organizers have
taken the unusual step of asking prominent stage designers from the
Brazilian theater to mount each section. That has led to a
startling diversity in ways of presenting works of art _ and to
most of the complaints about the exhibition, aside from the $5.75
admission fee, which some find too steep.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Indigenous Art'' section, for instance, is strikingly
simple and stark, with feather headdresses, masks, baskets and
fetishes suspended in glass cases with no further adornment and
sometimes even without a label, leaving the objects to speak for
themselves. The ``Baroque Art'' unit, in contrast, is a bizarre and
darkly lighted fantasy of purple and yellow paper flowers that
recalls nothing so much as the set of ``The Wizard of Oz'' and
never ceases to be distracting.
</P>
<P>
   To their credit, the organizers have also devoted a great deal
of attention to the exhibition's catalogs. There are a dozen of
them, totaling more than 3,000 pages, with gorgeous photographic
reproductions and thoughtful essays that explain, in both
Portuguese and English, the historical and social context in which
the artworks were produced and their creators lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taken as a whole, we envisioned these catalogs as a huge
encyclopedia, a vade mecum of Brazilian civilization,'' Ferreira
said. ``Brazil is a country that is not in the habit of looking
back, and so it never gets to know itself as it really is. We
wanted to remedy that both with the exhibition and the catalogs.''
</P>
<P>
   The catalogs are available in CD-ROM form as well, and some of
the works on display can also be viewed at a bilingual Web site
that will continue to function even after the show closes here on
Sept. 7: www.br500anos.com.br.
</P>
<P>
   After visits to other Brazilian cities later this year, parts of
the exhibition will begin a long overseas tour, including stops
next year in Washington and at the Museo del Barrio in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Guggenheim Museum will be selecting a few of
the works being shown here for a separate show that is to run from
Sept. 23, 2001, through Jan. 20, 2002. ``There will surely be some
overlap in terms of objects, but the two enterprises are completely
independent in terms of organization,'' said Lisa Dennison, the
Guggenheim's chief curator and deputy director. ``Our project is
highly selective, with probably 250 objects, and will focus on the
relationship between the Baroque and modernism.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Both of those periods are of course effectively represented in
the ``Rediscovery'' show, earning displays and catalogs of their
own. Modernist painters like Tarsila do Amaral and Anita Malfatti
and contemporary sculptors like Helio Oititica and Lygia Clark are
among the 20th-century standouts, while the Baroque module focuses
on polychrome woodcarvings and terra cotta works of 18th-century
masters like Aleijadinho and Francisco Xavier de Brito.
</P>
<P>
   This was one of the most extraordinary flowerings of painting,
sculpture, architecture and decorative arts ever seen in the
Americas, and very different from the Spanish sense of melancholy
you see in the Mexican or Peruvian art of this period,'' Sullivan
said. ``In general, it contains a sense of lightness and optimism
carried out in color and architectonic form that have a high degree
of theatricality, like constantly being involved in a rococo
opera.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an exhibition of modern art here in 1922 that set
Brazil's cultural agenda for the rest of the 20th century,
producing a manifesto arguing that the basis for all Brazilian
culture was a ``philosophy of anthropophagy,'' or appropriation,
amalgamation and regurgitation. With that concept now enshrined as
part of the national orthodoxy, ``The Rediscovery Show'' is making
a conscious effort to promote an updated agenda for the new
century.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are doing is opening the doors and leaving them
open,'' Aguilar explained. ``By doing that, we can break taboos,
destroy myths and completely change the perspective that people
have of themselves. It is a scandal that an exhibition like this
was not mounted 20 or 40 years ago, but important that it is
finally being done now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
