<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Thursday, June 1 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   PHONE-CHARGES (Washington) _ The Federal Communications
Commission and most of the nation's leading telephone companies
announced Wednesday a sweeping reshuffling of the telephone rates
that should reduce costs for all businesses and consumers.
Officials said the reductions amounted to the largest rate cut in
the history of federal telephone regulation and that they would
have their biggest impact on the poor and those who use their
telephones the least. For tens of millions of Americans who make
few or no long distance calls each month, the government estimated
the rates would be reduced by as much as 50 percent. By Stephen
Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT20, and a graphic.
</P>
<P>
   EMAIL-POLITICS (Undated) _ Hour by hour the e-mails arrive like
digital daggers from the presidential candidates and their parties.
Catty, pithy, weighty, gossipy, they materialize via the open
cyberfaucet of the 2000 campaign. ``Bush's Million Mom
Manipulation,'' began a message from the Democrats. ``Democrat Fat
Cat Discriminates Against Those who Flee Castro's Clutches,'' read
an e-mail from the Republicans. ``New York Honor Guard Spat on at
Clinton Nomination,'' read another. Only by extension is the target
of the computer missives the American voter. The more immediate
audience is the American journalist, who seems to pay a lot of
attention to the messages. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-JUSTICE (Moradabad, India) _ If, as the adage goes,
justice delayed is justice denied, then India's courts can be said
to customarily live in a state of denial. Some 25 million cases are
pending, a breathtaking pileup of the untried accused and
unsatisfied aggrieved. By one expert's calculation, if no new
actions are filed, 324 years would be needed to clear the dockets.
By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT16.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-U.S.-ASSESS (Berlin) _ On eve of President Clinton's
arrival in Germany, a look at U.S.-German relationship. Germans
feel that when they take a stronger role, as urged by U.S. and
others, they're being slapped down for being too aggressive. By
Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-EXECUTE (Dallas) _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas said
Wednesday that he was considering a temporary grant of clemency for
a man scheduled to be executed on Thursday so that DNA evidence in
the case could be tested. It would be the first such stay that he
has issued as governor. On Tuesday a state appeals court overruled
a trial judge's order allowing a delay for DNA testing in the case
of Ricky McGinn, who was convicted of raping and killing his
12-year-old stepdaughter. By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SYRIA (Damascus, Syria) _ The U.N.'s Middle East envoy
said Wednesday that Syria had fully accepted a U.N. report that
concluded an Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon did not require
handing over the Shebaa Farms area. (Summary from wires.) By Susan
Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   NY-TOUR-BUSES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Nine days after a double-decker
tour bus killed a pedestrian at a Midtown intersection, Gov. George
Pataki on Wednesday shut down the tour company, New York Apple
Tours, for at least two weeks, and said he will try to put them out
of business permanently. By Richard Perez-Pena.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-UNWRAPING-CANDY (Undated) _ A team of physicists has made a
giant leap in understanding the prime scourge of audiences for
opera, theater and concerts: the crinkling and crackling of candy
wrappers. But their findings will be bad news for audiences
maddened by the noise. The scientists demonstrated what plenty of
dismayed concert-goers have already intuited: the racket is
inevitable no matter how the candy is opened. By James Glanz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
