<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1016 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-THEATER-OVERVIEW-$ADV     05-31 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-OVERVIEW-$ADV04-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT ITS BEST, A SEASON THAT MADE THE LEAP INTO LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT30 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``I was wonderin' what it was like to be you.''
</P>
<P>
   Things are still more or less in control when these words are
spoken in the revival of Sam Shepard's ``True West,'' one of the
high points in the dizzyingly uneven Broadway season that just
ended. The spilled quarts of beer and sweat, the ransacked drawers,
the smashed furniture and the mutilated egos all lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
   But that simple sentence, uttered with gruff shyness by one
brother to another, is what really opens the doors to the ensuing
chaos. You have to be careful about wondering what it's like to be
someone else. It can take you into strange and slippery places.
Isn't it exhilarating?
</P>
<P>
   Imagining yourself into another existence, and then giving
physical life to those imaginings, is at the primal heart of drama.
It is what makes play-acting so incredibly glamorous to children,
and it is a large part of what keeps many of us hooked on live
theater. Much of literature may be fueled by this empathic leap of
the imagination. But what art form other than theater gives that
leap such unnerving immediacy, the sense of watching a circus
performer grabbing in midair for the trapeze?
</P>
<P>
   Books are consumed in the head, in a private dialogue between
writer and reader; movies, while often experienced communally, are
inevitably distanced by being confined to two dimensions. Theater,
taking place in the flesh in real time, is the most public and the
least lonely of the narrative arts.
</P>
<P>
   Even when it ponders the opacity of people, as it frequently
does these days, theater pulses with its vital human connection
with its audience. This may be one reason that the televised Tony
Awards ceremonies (this year's take place Sunday night) have
traditionally captured so little of what makes the theater
distinctive.
</P>
<P>
   But if the celebration that is the Tony Awards falls short of
embodying what it celebrates (and limiting itself to the parochial
professional village known as Broadway doesn't help matters), there
is much to toast in the first New York theater season to stretch
into a new century. The best offerings of the last year, at least
among nonmusical productions, reached with a heady suppleness of
both form and content to envision complete lives, to open human
minds for public display.
</P>
<P>
   The director Matthew Warchus' dynamic production of ``True
West,'' Shepard's portrait of diametrically different brothers who
unwittingly trade roles, took on a new Pirandello-like vividness
with its electric young stars, Philip Seymour Hoffman and John C.
Reilly, switching the two leads in alternating cycles of different
performances.
</P>
<P>
   To see either version is a thrill; to see both is to perceive
the very essence of the play _ which is, after all, about the
mutability of personality _ being both altered and confirmed by the
changed casting. You become newly aware of just how much an actor
is an author of any given production, and the degree to which a
play reinvents itself on a nightly basis.
</P>
<P>
   Uptown and down, the quest to peer into the consciousness of
others took varied and vigorous forms: from the avant-gardist
Richard Foreman's fragmented landscape of a philosopher's mind,
``Bad Boy Nietzsche!,'' to the director and playwright Moises
Kaufman's ``Laramie Project,'' in which a team of performers shaped
interviews surrounding the murder of a gay student in Wyoming into
a heartbreaking work of theatrical journalism.
</P>
<P>
   The best new plays to open on Broadway, Michael Frayn's
``Copenhagen'' and Claudia Shear's ``Dirty Blonde,'' summoned the
lingering presences of long-dead real-life figures _ the movie star
Mae West (``Dirty Blonde'') and the physicists Niels Bohr and
Werner Heisenberg (``Copenhagen'') _ to figure out what made them
run and how they shaped the world around them. They are
biographical mystery plays, in a sense, in which the dramatists
invite those watching to follow along as fellow detectives.
</P>
<P>
   Our feeling of being in on the process is achieved through the
actors, too. In ``Dirty Blonde,'' staged with an astonishing
fluidity by James Lapine, two characters, played by Shear and Kevin
Chamberlin, actually turn into Mae West. The transformations are
the engine of the play, a reflection of the characters' (and our)
hunger to understand West and, most ingeniously, a means of letting
us come to understand the characters.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in ``Copenhagen,'' directed with canny precision by
Michael Blakemore, who had previously staged it in London, it's a
ravenous, frustrated curiosity that propels the drama, in which the
ghosts of Bohr, his wife and Heisenberg try to pin down exactly
what did happen during a tense World War II meeting among the three
characters.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Bosco, Blair Brown and Michael Cumpsty bring a contagious
fierceness to their characters' quests, and what is effectively a
shifting dance of subjective points of view, that keeps the evening
from drifting into the ether of abstraction. The implicit
watchwords of the evening are ones we have all said from time to
time: ``What were they thinking?'' ``Copenhagen'' makes the point
that even the participants themselves couldn't answer the question.
</P>
<P>
   A spirit of wonder at the opacity of people, even those you
think you know well, infuses this year's Pulitzer Prize winner for
drama. That's Donald Margulies' ``Dinner With Friends,'' and like
most recent Pulitzer winners, it is tellingly an Off Broadway
production.
</P>
<P>
   As familiar in its shape, dialogue and sensibility as an episode
of the television series ``thirtysomething,'' the play nonetheless
has a piercing emotional eloquence that speaks directly to the baby
boom audience that has made it a long-running hit. Given a
top-drawer production by Daniel Sullivan, ``Dinner With Friends''
paints a portrait of two 40-ish couples, best friends, who come to
realize they have never understood one another at all.
</P>
<P>
   It's a cold and isolating perception, yet the production
emanates a continual warmth, generated by the four actors' loving
embrace of characters who aren't always sympathetic. The fact that
it is a live drama, staged in an intimate theater, only strengthens
its connection with middle-aged audience members just beginning to
confront their own mortality.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, demonstrating a directorial versatility matched this
season by Blakemore (who is responsible for the triumphant revival
of ``Kiss Me, Kate'' as well as ``Copenhagen''), is also the man
behind the soul-stirring Broadway revival of Eugene O'Neill's
``Moon for the Misbegotten.'' The play itself is a deeply affecting
example of an artist reclaiming unhappy elements from his own life
and transforming them into something redemptive.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Moon for the Misbegotten'' was O'Neill's elegy for and
apology to his alcoholic brother James, whose character in the play
(also named James) is granted a moment of absolution and
unconditional love before dying. Yet most previous interpretations
have been dominated by the actress playing Josie, the strapping
farm girl who prompts James' cleansing confession. Though Josie is
here ably portrayed by no less a performer than Cherry Jones, it is
Gabriel Byrne's James that makes this production a milestone.
</P>
<P>
   Byrne has an emotional transparency that allows you to see
straight to the core of James' self-lacerating guilt and to realize
how it determines his every gesture. What you are witnessing is an
extraordinary collaboration between a dead dramatist and a living
actor, a convergence of wills to come to terms with and to redeem a
given character. Byrne, turning in the richest dramatic performance
of the season, gives ``A Moon for the Misbegotten'' back to James
Tyrone, and there is no understating the significance of that
accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A contemporary play from a young writer achieved its own
transcendent transformation of autobiography. Kenneth Lonergan's
``Waverly Gallery,'' seen Off Broadway at the Promenade Theater,
was inspired by the last years of his grandmother, an enduringly
strong-willed woman sliding into dementia. The resulting work is
both harrowing and funny, suggesting how much Beckett's absurdity
is rooted in real life.
</P>
<P>
   What took the play to another level, however, was Eileen
Heckart, the fabled octogenarian actress. Playing the grandmother,
Heckart rendered senility with such limpid sharpness that even as
you lamented the character's decline, you cheered the performer's
triumph. A crystalline order emerged from the muddle that is life.
Watching Heckart serve as its chief architect, in what she has said
will be her last stage performance, was a kind of transporting
privilege that only the theater affords.
</P>
<P>
   Other productions played directly and appealingly with a
self-conscious awareness of just what the theater achieves and how
it does it. The sparkling Broadway revival of ``The Real Thing,''
Tom Stoppard's keen-witted tale of a playwright in love, makes the
case that certain things (love, for example) defy articulation.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, with the infinitely charming Stephen Dillane
playing the playwright in this import from London, even groping in
the dark acquires a glistening stylishness that is pure theater.
Dillane's co-star, the radiant Jennifer Ehle, is, by the way, the
daughter of an actress who gave another sublime study this season
in stage-savvy artifice.
</P>
<P>
   That's Rosemary Harris, whose portrayal of a great lady of the
British stage exiled to a retirement home was the touchstone of
``Waiting in the Wings,'' a 40-year-old play by Noel Coward that
received its Broadway debut only this season. Harris slyly plied,
and gently sent up, the tricks of her trade to conjure a vanished
era of stagecraft, turning them into the tools by which her
character dominated her fellow residents. There is after all, it
seems, a practical use for the skills acquired on stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Waiting in the Wings'' provided the additional pleasure of
presenting a host of actresses on the far side of 60, from Lauren
Bacall to Helen Stenborg, working as a team with contagious
delight. But the laurels for ensemble acting this season
unquestionably go to the cast of August Wilson's ``Jitney.''
</P>
<P>
   This reworking of an early play by the author of contemporary
masterpieces like ``Joe Turner's Come and Gone'' and ``Ma Rainey's
Black Bottom'' presented a slice of life, from the streets of
Pittsburgh in the 1970s, so invigoratingly fresh that you somehow
felt you had lived it yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the cast members, directed by Marion McClinton, had been
together through earlier incarnations of the play, and they wore
their roles with a deceptively easy-looking assurance. By the end
of the performance, you had the sense that you had been listening
to these people regularly for most of your life. You left the
theater with the heartening illusion that it really is possible to
know people thoroughly, after all.
</P>
<P>
   In what is becoming a dispiriting tradition, musicals did not
begin to match their nonsinging siblings in moments of revelation,
with the merciful exceptions of two envelope-pushers: ``Contact''
and ``James Joyce's `The Dead.''' The season had one glorious
pinnacle of a revival, Cole Porter's backstage musical ``Kiss Me,
Kate,'' and a charming if imbalanced new version of Meredith
Willson's all-American ``Music Man,'' courtesy of the director and
choreographer Susan Stroman.
</P>
<P>
   Less encouragingly, the trend of reinventing, and usually
flattening, movie musicals for the stage _ which seemed to have
reached a nadir with the sterile ``Footloose'' _ scraped even
deeper with the mechanical interpretation of ``Saturday Night
Fever,'' which managed to erase every vestige of sensuality and
period authenticity from the film that inspired it.
</P>
<P>
   An original musical from Disney, Elton John and Tim Rice's
``Aida,'' somehow felt as if it, too, had been translated from the
screen _ in this case, from a Disney cartoon _ though it did have
the virtue of establishing the incandescent Heather Headley, in the
title role, as a bona fide Broadway star.
</P>
<P>
   More ambitious, and hence ultimately more disappointing, were
two separate productions that adapted ``The Wild Party,'' Joseph
Moncure March's cult poem of the Jazz Age, as musicals: Andrew
Lippa's version for the Manhattan Theater Club and the current
Broadway incarnation by George C. Wolfe and the composer Michael
John LaChiusa (the latter also represented this season by the
overweening ``Marie Christine'' at Lincoln Center).
</P>
<P>
   Following a battalion of self-destructive sybarites through one
evening of dubious pleasures, both shows suffered from feelings of
arrested development. The notes of shrill unhappiness and brooding
restlessness were struck early and held for the musicals'
remainders, imprisoning their characters and scores in a frieze of
decorative decadence that never became fully animated.
</P>
<P>
   There were, however, two productions that bravely and
successfully staked out new territory for the musical: Stroman's
``Contact'' at Lincoln Center and ``James Joyce's `The Dead,''' by
Richard Nelson and Shaun Davey, which transferred to Broadway from
Playwrights Horizons. The slew of Tony nominations heaped upon
``Contact'' has caused some grumbling in the New York theater,
since the show is a dance play, with minimal dialogue and no
original music.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, its three vignettes blissfully capture what
has always been most seductive about the American musical: its
ability to lift off from everyday reality into a music-driven
empyrean, while pulling its audiences skyward with it. Boyd Gaines'
portrayal in the evening's final scene, of a suicidal urbanite who
finds his feet and his heart by learning to dance, became the
perfect metaphor for the audience's implicit participation in the
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dead,'' though less flashy, was even more innovative: a
musical that dared to be quiet. In retelling Joyce's great story of
mortal shadows at a Christmas party in Dublin, the show presented a
group of people who appeared to be performing for one another
rather for than the audience. The responses of those onstage became
as important as those who were singing or dancing for them, and a
whole other level of naturalistic character definition was
introduced to the musical form.
</P>
<P>
   No musical season in New York will ever be entirely barren as
long as the ``Encores!'' series of American musicals in concert
continues to flourish at City Center. This year the program's peak
was its final offering, a heavenly resurrection of a
never-never-land, an idealized New York City of the 1950's, in
``Wonderful Town.''
</P>
<P>
   Overseen by the prodigiously gifted Kathleen Marshall, also the
choreographer on ``Kiss Me, Kate,'' the evening provided myriad
pleasures but none quite so astonishing as those offered by its
star, the two-time Tony winner Donna Murphy. Hitherto most notable
as a performer of somber emotional intensity (``Passion,'' ``The
King and I''), Murphy turned her image on its head with a dazzling,
razor-sharp comic performance.
</P>
<P>
   Which further confirms that really good theater artists are an
enviable lot. They can, after all, turn into anyone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
