<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1020 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-AUSTIN-HOME-ART-1     05-31 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTIN-HOME-ART-1,100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEGUILED BY AN ILLUSIONIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT8,9 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Arthur Everett Austin Jr., or Chick, as he was
known from childhood, managed to have the last word on himself, by
getting the first one in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The house is just like me,'' he told critics and admirers of
the 86-foot-wide, one-room-deep, painted-wood Palladian villa with
the Venetian baroque and International style interiors. ``All
facade.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin, director of the Wadsworth Atheneum, built the striking
house here on staid Scarborough Street in 1930 at age 29.
</P>
<P>
   After 20 months and half a million dollars of cosmetic labor,
the ``pasteboard palace,'' as local grandees dubbed it, will greet
Hartford society again. The Atheneum, which now owns the Austin
house and has restored it, will unveil it to trustees June 8,
appropriately, at a party. A National Historic Landmark, it may
eventually be on view by appointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to the son of the man who lived across the street
when Chick was building the house, who was one of the founders of
the august Hartford law firm Robinson &AMP; Cole,'' said Eugene R.
Gaddis, the curator of the Austin house and author of ``Magician of
the Modern,'' a biography of Austin to be published by Alfred A.
Knopf in the fall. ``The son was in his mid-70s. `What did your
father think of the house?' I asked, and he said, `An excrescence.'
I said: `Oh, well, that's very interesting. And what do you think
of it, after all these years?' `An excrescence,' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Oh, well, that's very interesting. And what do you
think of it, after all these years?' `An excrescence,' he said.''
</P>
<P>
   But Philip Johnson, who was introduced to Austin in the 1920s by
Henry-Russell Hitchcock, the architectural historian, called the
house more important now than even its designer could have
understood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course none of us could stand his house, heavens no,''
Johnson recalled in Gaddis' biography. ``The least we could do was
copy Gropius. Today, every architect that I know under 45 wouldn't
think of building a house without going through his books of
Palladio first. And there it sits on Scarborough Street. A
postmodern house, if you please.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind Austin's legendary chain-smoking, cocktail-swilling,
brilliantined matinee-idol facade was the work of a serious
avant-gardist.
</P>
<P>
   As the director from 1927 to 1945 of the Atheneum, America's
oldest public art museum (established by Daniel Wadsworth in 1842),
Austin mounted the first comprehensive Picasso exhibition in the
United States. The evening the show opened, guests like Alexander
Calder, Isamu Noguchi, Buckminster Fuller and Clare Booth Luce sat
for the world premiere of Gertrude Stein and Virgil Thomson's first
opera, ``Four Saints in Three Acts,'' in the theater of a
Bauhaus-inspired building that was Austin's newest, personally
designed addition to the museum, the Avery Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   The young director also staged the country's first Surrealist
exhibition, featuring a Spaniard named Salvador Dali with a
painting called ``Persistence of Memory.'' With a Harvard friend,
Lincoln Kirstein, Austin sponsored the immigration of a dancer and
choreographer named George Balanchine and gave his new company its
first public appearance in America. At the Atheneum, he ran the
first film retrospective at a museum. ``The Art of the Motion
Picture'' opened with Fritz Lang's ``Metropolis.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the facade of the Modernist was an old-world connoisseur
of painting and sculpture, a curator and a collector. With his
parents, Austin had been making trips to Europe since he was 3. He
had lived in Dresden and Paris. He had studied with Bernard
Berenson. Austin's exhibition of Italian Baroque art in 1934 is
credited by scholars with rediscovering a period that had been
dismissed for 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   And behind his academic facade was a bisexual adventurer who
married a local socialite, Helen Goodwin, who happened to be the
niece of the Atheneum's board president, had two children,
sporadically pursued a second career in Hollywood away from his
family, and was fired by the museum in 1945 in part because of
uncovered financial chaos. For his next and last act, he brought a
Florida circus millionaire's museum to international prominence,
then died at home in Hartford in 1957, at 57, of an inoperable
tumor, having abandoned his male lover of 10 years to return to his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   Austin claimed he saw an angel before he slipped into a coma. No
one knows whether it was shaking its head.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the pilastered facade on Scarborough Street, he had
nothing to hide. Austin liked to show his house, bringing the
curtain up with a flourish on its stagelike, set-piece rooms. A
devotee of drama who designed several theaters and play
productions, including ``Medea'' in 1934, directed by John
Houseman, translated by the Harlem poet Countee Cullen and
choreographed by Martha Graham, Austin also appeared in Hartford as
Hamlet, challenging the loyalty of even good friends.
</P>
<P>
   The two-story, 18-foot-deep house involved every aspect of the
dilettante's interests, training and talents (he called himself an
``amateur,'' in the 18th-century sense), including a gift for
magic. Austin toured publicly as the Great Osram, a name taken from
the German light fixtures used in his new Bauhaus-inspired
bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The house's exterior was based on the Villa Ferreti in Dolo,
Italy, built in 1596 by Vincenzo Scamozzi, a student (later a
rival) of Andrea Palladio. The Austins saw it on their honeymoon.
</P>
<P>
   The interiors were an artistic showman's display of his two
great aesthetic loves: the Baroque and the Modern. ``Part of being
a Modernist, in Chick's view, was rediscovering the past,'' Gaddis
said on a recent visit, standing in the imitation Baroque dining
room, the walls of which are covered in a blue-green brocatelle
silk recreated by Scalamandre from scraps of the original that the
Austins bought in Venice. ``It created a dramatic world for his own
very Modernist existence. You go from this very 18th-century
atmosphere downstairs to the very edge of design in the Bauhaus,
upstairs. For Chick, all art was contemporary. If you understood
how it was created and why it was created, it was alive.''
</P>
<P>
   The house cost $43,000 to build. Austin's adoring mother, Laura,
paid for it. She spent her life constructing an elaborate genealogy
to prove that she and her son were royalty. After four years of
dunning letters from Adolf Loewi, his Venetian antiques dealer, for
a payment of $15,000, which was four times Austin's salary, the
furnishing bills were sent to her, too.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The house is a precociously educated pastiche. In addition to
studying with Berenson in Italy, Austin was also a student of
Federigo Ioni, a notorious restorer who was also reputed to be a
forger, copying 15th-century pictures as exercises.
</P>
<P>
   In the dining room, the carved cobweb-like boiserie that frames
the serving niche is in fact a Bavarian bed alcove. The grand
doorway that leads into the living room is taken from a massive
armoire. The harbor tableaux of fantastic voyages with pantalooned
buccaneers that form its views are the output of ``a third-rate
journeyman simulating a painting by Claude Lorrain, which hangs in
the Louvre,'' Gaddis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more or less wallpaper,'' he explained. ``Chick started
to enlarge the boat in one panel, then gave up on it. So you see,
this is not the grand Newport kind of a finished palace. It's
Chick's stage set. Many things are not of the highest quality, but
he didn't care. He wanted the aura.''
</P>
<P>
   He was also, in the tradition of the theater and the studio
arts, a do-it-yourselfer.
</P>
<P>
   There were only four walls for the five 18th-century Italian
chinoiserie painted-silk panels in the music room. Austin installed
the extra one on the ceiling. In 1935, Virgil Thomson, Aaron
Copland, Paul Bowles and George Antheil sat here and played at the
piano until 4 in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Austin marbleized and trompe-l'oeiled steps, mirror frames and
door surrounds. He mixed the house's 56 interior colors himself.
``That's the extraordinary thing,'' Gaddis said, ``the fact that
you have this house from a great connoisseur of fine arts that was
created by him personally.'' Austin was an assistant to Edward
Forbes, the director of the the Fogg Art Museum in Cambridge,
Mass., for three years before Forbes recommended the young man for
the job in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was trained in the methods and processes of Italian
Renaissance painting,'' Gaddis said, ``and he knew how colors were
created and what they did, from an artist's point of view. This
house was a painting to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Krystyn Hastings-Silver, the project manager for the
restoration, said that when carpeting was pulled up for
replacement, ``the floors looked like Jackson Pollocks _ he mixed
the colors for each room right there in the room.'' Colors were
frequently pulled from artwork: the living room's dark green copies
the storm-clouded skies in the 18th-century harbor scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings-Silver also found valuable wall fabric samples, which
she used to match for color with replicas, under baseboards that
Austin had tacked on.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could follow the line of his scissors as he cut along the
wall,'' she said. ``A professional tradesman wouldn't have left
this kind of evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of its conceit as a backdrop, the uneven quality of its
furniture and Austin's attention to decoration, the house's
backgrounds were treated as its most important historical elements,
from the rose silk taffeta draperies in the living room to the flat
planes of paint in Helen Austin's dressing room and bathroom
upstairs, which were based on Walter Gropius' bathroom at the
Bauhaus in Dessau. In it, each section of every wall is coordinated
by color to its exposure: east-facing surfaces are beige, west are
blue, north are cream and south are a deep cocoa brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the first room the painters did,'' Hastings-Silver
said of her team, which included more than 30 trades, ``and we're
so glad they didn't quit.''
</P>
<P>
   The house was given to the Atheneum by the Austin family in
1985, when Helen Austin, then in ill health, moved out. With a
bequest from her cousin, Genevieve Harlow Goodwin, the museum
started its investigations of the house, ``a place of odd
enchantments,'' as Gaddis describes it.
</P>
<P>
   Brought back, waiting for its next role, it seems more a
restoration of a remarkable spirit, with remarkable taste and a
remarkable irresponsibility to the truth, than the reconstruction
of historic rooms in an architecturally significant building.
</P>
<P>
   Fired pink and gold by late afternoon sunlight, the Austin house
showed what it knew of its creator: every incautious corner of it
grew warm with seduction, never missing a trick.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
