<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1022 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-NY-HARLEM-HOUSE-ART-N     05-31 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HARLEM-HOUSE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE LAIR OF A DOGGED CHAMPION OF HARLEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: NYT Photos 5,6,7 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By TRACIE ROZHON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The paying guests are about to arrive, and Michael
Henry Adams, a Harlem private-tour impresario, is bustling around
his apartment, lighting candles atop a fireplace mantel and laying
out tea in a porcelain pot and smoked salmon on a silver-plated
platter.
</P>
<P>
   His own basement apartment, assembled since March but looking as
if it had been that way since the Harlem Renaissance, leads off his
$100 tour, which, on any given night, might include St. Nick's Pub
or the Lenox Lounge. Most tours benefit some group. Who benefits
from this one? ``Me,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   He is certainly qualified to lead a tour: this spring, he taught
a course called ``The Harlem Community'' at City College. At the
end of the year, Monacelli Press is bringing out his architectural
compendium, ``Harlem: Lost and Found: 1765-1915.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams once wanted to be an interior designer; his last
apartment, a tiny studio room in Hamilton Heights, was featured in
a book on New York style. His current three-room apartment on 122nd
Street off Lenox Avenue (which he rents for $800 a month) is an
exotic tossed salad, with Louis XVI and a crystal chandelier mixed
up with street finds. His front room is an intimate parlor. There
is no bedroom; his daybed sits in a niche on one wall in the back
room.
</P>
<P>
   Adams is an avid preservationist, and his apartment is a prism
through which the tourist can glimpse bits and pieces of Harlem
past.
</P>
<P>
   Over his bed, for instance, is a galvanized tin frieze. ``It
came from the Marion Building at the corner of 125th Street and
Lenox _ ripped out and thrown into a Dumpster,'' he said. Over his
fireplace hangs a gilded garland, part of the demolished interior
of the Audubon Theater, where Malcolm X was assassinated.
</P>
<P>
   His decorating with Harlem's lost-and-found objects makes sense.
When he was 13, his father scoffed at his ambition to be an
interior designer, telling him, ``Only white people hire interior
designers.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, he went to the Addingham Summer School in England, and
eventually studied historic preservation for two years at Columbia
University. He gave up becoming an interior designer: too many
people told him his father was right.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, meanwhile, Adams developed a passion for
preservation that some find abrasive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would you say abrasive?'' he asked. ``I'd rather you say
`confrontational.'''
</P>
<P>
   He is most confrontational when demanding landmark status for
large chunks of Harlem. Usually, he speaks in a deliberate, low
voice. But his voice rises when he talks about the historic
buildings that have come down, and are coming down, in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Abyssinian Baptist Church is trying to turn Small's
Paradise _ the only one of the three major jazz clubs, and the only
one owned by a black man _ into an International House of
Pancakes,'' he said. ``Would they turn the Stork Club into an
International House of Pancakes?'' (Karen Phillips, president of
the church's development corporation, confirmed that negotiations
with the pancake chain are under way.)
</P>
<P>
   The best way to protect such unofficial landmarks, Adams said,
is to incorporate them into a series of historic districts, and
until that happens, he will continue to protest.
</P>
<P>
   Although the city landmarks commission has designated the Hotel
Teresa, the Mother Zion AME Church, the Abyssinian Baptist Church,
Wadleigh High School and dozens of other Harlem buildings during
the last decade, Adams contends that thousands more need
protection, among them the newly restored Lenox Lounge, the
Renaissance Casino, Blumstein's Department Store and 321 Edgecombe
Avenue, where the Mills Brothers and the Nicholas Brothers lived.
``Almost all of Greenwich Village, much of the Upper East Side and
Upper West Side and most of Park Slope and Brooklyn Heights are
landmarked,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A commission spokeswoman, Terri Rosen Deutsch, rejected Adams'
criticisms. The current commission, she said, has done more in
Harlem in the last five years than any other commission.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said that after the panel voted to protect some buildings
_ but not to create an entirely new district _ one commissioner
asked if he was grateful. He says he is far from grateful. To prove
it, he chained himself to the doors of commission headquarters in
Manhattan last year. He spent a night in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Some preservationists may be wary of Adams because of such
stunts, but Anthony C. Wood, chairman emeritus of New York City's
Historic Districts Council, says his voice is an important one in
Harlem preservation. ``You can question the wisdom of his tactics,
but you can't question his dedication,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Is Adams an outright zealot, or just zealous?
</P>
<P>
   ``In our culture, to call someone a zealot is pejorative, but to
call someone zealous is not,'' he replied. ``All I want is for
Harlem to have the same degree of protection that the other
historic neighborhoods have.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
