<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oh, the sudden joy of cooking with soy!
 &HT;    By Kitty Crider
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Three magic words in the new millennium: Deborah
Madison and tofu. This popular vegetarian author's cooking class on
tofu sold out recently at Central Market. When the waiting list
grew to 50 names, Madison added another class.
</P>
<P>
   Austin may have always had some tofu tendencies, but this is a
first on the solid soy scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been unable to make the minimum _ let alone sell out a
tofu class _ in the past three years,'' says cooking school
director Cathy Cochran-Lewis. But now soy's hot. And the
award-winning Madison, who lives in Santa Fe, N.M., has a new book,
``This Can't Be Tofu'' (Broadway, $15). Talk about timing!
</P>
<P>
   TEA OR MILK
</P>
<P>
   Nope, the cows haven't gone dry. But Promised Land Dairy, that
Floresville plant that puts milk in real glass bottles, has gotten
into the tea business. Texas Teas _ found in the refrigerated case
at local groceries _ come in 16-ounce bottles in four flavors,
including green tea with ginseng.
</P>
<P>
   It's a refrigerated product with a 45-day shelf life because it
does not contain citric acid like many shelf-stable drinks. ``We
wanted to get something that tastes close to fresh-brewed,'' says
Gordon Kuenemann, senior VP.
</P>
<P>
   Promised Land is still in the bottled milk biz, but a lot of
dairies are getting into all kinds of drinks to make things
profitable, Kuenemann says. And brewing tea has got to be a lot
easier and cheaper than milking cows.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if consumers can just remember to keep those tea bottles in
the fridge.
</P>
<P>
   FLOUR POWER
</P>
<P>
   The architect was flying back to Austin when a fellow
first-class passenger asked if that was a sack of flour at his
feet. Sure was, the architect acknowledged. But not just any flour.
White Lily, a soft wheat flour that many experts think makes the
best biscuits, shortcake, scones . . .
</P>
<P>
   It's a basic ingredient that is found everywhere in the South,
from Florida to Tennessee. But it's rarer in Austin than sushi in
Amarillo. However, Austinites who have been hauling those bags of
flour in their carry-on luggage need to know that it is now
available at Williams-Sonoma, where a 2-pound bag of the
self-rising variety goes for $2.
</P>
<P>
   FLYING HIGH WITH FAT
</P>
<P>
   eFit.com says an airline flier is worse off eating the food on
the plane than a McDonald's Big Mac, french fries and a strawberry
sundae. eFit, which is an online health and fitness network,
conducted a survey of first-class and coach meals from 15 airlines,
and found that a single airline meal contains 1,000 to 1,200
calories, 50 to 60 grams of fat and 2,000 mg of sodium. Daily
Reference Values established by the Food and Drug Administration
say that an average person should consume no more than 2,000
calories, 65 grams of fat and 2,400 mg of sodium each day.
</P>
<P>
   Items for this column are drawn from wire reports, mail,
personal observation and comments from readers. To pass on a
suggestion, call food editor Kitty Crider at 445-3656, or write to
Food, Austin American-Statesman, P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX, 78767.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
