<HEADER>
A1026 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-BKN-KNICKS-EWING-HNS &LR;      05-31 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-EWING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     KNICKS CAN'T LIVE WITH, OR WITHOUT, EWING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Patrick Ewing. Can't live without him. Can't live
with him.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, the New York Knicks are better off without Ewing
in the lineup. But that's not the whole truth. The Knicks
desperately need Ewing to have any hope of being the last team
limping at the end of the NBA playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   No, feeling strongly both ways isn't a copout. No, it's not a
sign of schizophrenia triggered by the sight of the Knicks dropping
a bunch of three-bombs on the Indiana Pacers in the Eastern
Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA playoffs are a prolonged series of games of
rock-scissors-paper. One team's patsy is another team's poison.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to playing the Pacers, Ewing is more of a
hindrance than a help. Ewing is too old a warrior to teach the new
trick of getting out of the way enough for his sprightlier
teammates to attack at the Pacers' must vulnerable points.
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, the notion of the Knicks being better off
without a member of the NBA's Greatest 50 Team is as preposterous
as Larry Johnson becoming the president of Planned Parenthood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asinine,'' Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy insists.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, coaches aren't in the habit of publicly floating
the notion that the absence of an 11-time all-star could be
addition by subtraction. For another, Ewing is the player most
responsible for allowing Van Gundy to establish himself as an NBA
head coach. Van Gundy has returned the favor with fierce loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the Knicks functioning better without Ewing means that
the whole is less than the sum of the parts. That's an indictment
of everybody involved. Ewing, for his inability to lift the play of
his teammates. The teammates, for not figuring out how to
effectively assert themselves when Ewing is on the court. Van
Gundy, for not fully meshing the talents of Ewing with the other
players.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever and in whatever proportions the blame rests, the Knicks
lost Games 1 and 2 with Ewing in the starting lineup. Ewing sat out
Games 3 and 4 with tendinitis in his right foot. The Knicks won.
His status the rest of the series is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the percentages with or without him,'' Pacers
center Rik Smits said, ``I guess I hope he comes back.''
</P>
<P>
   With Ewing, Van Gundy pulls in the reins on the Knicks. You have
to wonder: If Van Gundy had turned the Knicks loose once in a
while, could they have made shorter work of the Miami Heat in the
previous series? As it was, the Knicks averaged 81.1 points and
shot 40.4 percent against the Heat.
</P>
<P>
   The shackles _ and Ewing _ were gone the previous two games.
Latrell Sprewell and Allan Houston played free and easy in Game 3,
combining for 60 points. Johnson had a 25-point breakout
performance in Game 4, and there was still room for Kurt Thomas (16
points) and Charlie Ward (16 points) to breathe. The Knicks
averaged 94.5 points in the two games, shooting 51 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Without Ewing. With Sprewell nursing a fracture in his left
foot. With Marcus Camby hobbled by a sprained right knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter who played wasn't nearly as important as how we
played,'' Van Gundy argued. ``We play well when we share the ball
and we play inside-out.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Ewing never has been one who shared well. Sure, he's
averaging a respectable 14.4 points and 9.5 rebounds this
postseason. He's also shooting only 43 percent from the field,
averaging an assist every 98.5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have a sleeker, surer look about them lately. The
10-of-14 3-point shooting in Game 4 wasn't as flukey as it sounds.
The Knicks kept slicing through the Pacers' defense and getting
ridiculously open looks at the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a slow team,'' Pacers forward Jalen Rose said. ``We're
not an athletic team.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as clearly, the Pacers are no match for the Knicks when it
comes to steely resolve. Damning Pacers quote No. 1, from forward
Dale Davis: ``We're still in the driver's seat. We just have to
come out and play harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, what have the Pacers been waiting for, what with a spot in
the NBA Finals at stake? Damning Pacers quote No. 2, from guard
Reggie Miller: ``It is very frustrating. We felt we could come in
here, get one, possibly two.''
</P>
<P>
   A team with a champion's mentality doesn't think about
``possibly'' coming into Madison Square Garden and winning two
against the ailing Knicks. A team with a champion's mentality comes
into Madison Square Garden expecting to kick the Knicks while
they're down.
</P>
<P>
   No, the Knicks don't need Ewing now, against these Pacers. They
sure could have used him in last year's Finals against the San
Antonio Spurs' 7-footers, Tim Duncan and David Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road, where Shaquille O'Neal and the Los Angeles Lakers
lurk, the Knicks will be grateful to have Ewing on their side. If
his achy, breaking body isn't beyond repair by then. The sight of
Chris Dudley, Camby, Thomas and Johnson trying to guard The Big
Aristotle is for mature audiences only.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing. Can't live without him. Can't always live with
him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
