r l BC-SUMMER-BUGS-(1800-2Ta     05-31 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-BUGS-(1800-2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AAAH, SUMMER: SUN, FUN .... AND CREEPY CRAWLIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas: pests, Russel says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Schools, golf courses and cities responsible for controlling
ants in parks, roadways, athletic fields and public swimming
complexes pay much of the cost, Russell says.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Texans shelled out $80.6 million for repairs and
$152 million to replace electrical equipment such as swimming pool
pumps and air-conditioning units destroyed by fire ants, according
to Drees' calculations.
</P>
<P>
   Medical treatment, primarily for over-the-counter remedies, cost
Texans an additional $47.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment is aimed primarily at preventing secondary bacterial
infection, which may occur if the blister is scratched or broken.
</P>
<P>
   Most folks should clean the bite with soap and water and apply a
topical corticosteroid ointment or antihistamine cream to relieve
itching. An oral antihistamine such as Benadryl may also help
relieve itching and keep you from scratching the bite.
</P>
<P>
   If used quickly enough _ within 15 minutes of getting stung _
ammonia or diluted bleach (1:1 bleach and water) will quickly break
down the protein in the ant's venom and lessen the pain and
itching.
</P>
<P>
   The Extension Service urges neighbors to work together to treat
the whole neighborhood with a two-step program using bait and
insecticide to control fire ants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to see people take the less toxic approach and use a
pesticide bait (available at feed and grain stores, nurseries and
discount centers, such as Wal-Mart) or one of the botanical
products available, such as pyrethrin,'' Russell says. ``Beneficial
insects won't eat the bait.''
</P>
<P>
   The first step is a wide-broadcast application of a bait over
the entire yard, while the ants are out collecting food during the
early morning, cooler evenings and at night. The ants collect the
bait and take it home to eat, but it can take several weeks to
work.
</P>
<P>
   The second step is to treat individual mounds with a little of
the approved insecticides such as diazinon. Mounds also can be
treated directly with boric acid, vinegar or a citrus oil product
or by pouring two to three gallons of boiling water directly into
the middle of the mound to kill ants more quickly _ within two to
three days.
</P>
<P>
   Overuse of insecticides, especially diazinon, has become an
environmental problem, and experts say using gasoline is a bad idea
because it is extremely flammable and contaminates the
environment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FLEAS, TICKS AND MOSQUITOES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fire ants and killer bees sound more exotic and dangerous, but
in Texas, ticks and mosquitoes present a bigger health problem
during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   This year's mild winter and early summer heat are bringing out
the ticks and fleas in force, and mosquitoes can't be far behind,
says Julie Rawlings, chief of the Infectious Disease Epidemiology
and Surveillance Division at the Texas Department of Health in
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   A bite from an infected tick can cause Lyme disease, Rocky
Mountain spotted fever or ehrlichiosis, she points out. Mosquitoes
sometimes carry dengue ``break-bone'' fever and encephalitis.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Louisiana, they are already reporting equine encephalitis
in horses, and in South Texas, we have been checking on some dengue
fever cases,'' Rawlings said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's dengue fever outbreak, which continued into
December, might have been worse than a 1980 outbreak in which 63
Texans came down with the tropical disease, according to state
health officials who are continuing to review the cases.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-six dengue cases were confirmed by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no encephalitis in humans last year, but several equine
cases were reported in East Texas,'' Rawlings said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Texas reported 10 cases of Rocky Mountain spotted
fever _ up from two or three the year before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lyme disease is the state's most prevalent tick-borne
disease,'' Rawlings says. ``We have 50 to 100 cases that meet the
case definition out of 200 to 300 suspect cases each year. The
definition is very strict, and reporting is bad, and tests for it
aren't perfect, so there could be a lot more of it out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Spotted fever can be deadly, but Lyme disease can cause more
chronic, incapacitating problems, Rawlings says.
</P>
<P>
   A vaccine is available for Rocky Mountain spotted fever and is
recommended for people in Texas who are outdoors in wooded areas
for long periods, including farmers and ranchers, telephone line
workers, and Parks and Wildlife staff, Rawlings says.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are bit by ticks every day in this state. You need to
protect yourself, no matter what. Wear long pants and long-sleeve
shirts tucked into boots, and use repellents, the same type as ward
off mosquitoes. DEET does the best job,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She always carries tweezers for ``tick checks'' whenever she is
outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Families and other people outside together should check each
other for ticks every two or three hours. If you find one, grasp it
as close to its mouth part as possible and pull it straight out
with a steady motion. If you don't have tweezers, cover your
fingers with a Kleenex and pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't touch it with a hot match or cover it with petroleum
jelly, like some people recommend. If the tick gets irritated, it
can regurgitate its stomach contents and make matters worse,''
Rawlings warns.
</P>
<P>
   Pets should be examined, and ticks removed in the same way.
Several new products are available from veterinarians to kill fleas
and ticks on pets.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping your yard mowed and trimmed will help greatly to reduce
flea and tick and mosquito problems, and several new chemicals are
highly effective for treating the yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably most important is to treat everything you need to
treat at the same time,'' Russell says. ``It doesn't work to treat
animals today and the yard next weekend. Because of the life cyles
of insects, you need to treat your carpets and bedding and pets and
yards all at the same time to be effective.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
