<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1030 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-SUMMER-BUGS-(1800-2Ta     05-31 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-BUGS-(1800-2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AAAH, SUMMER: SUN, FUN .... AND CREEPY CRAWLIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Ah, the good ol' summertime, when mosquitoes
eat us alive, fire ants raise welts on our bare feet, fleas and
ticks plague our poor pets, and bees and other fearsome insects
terrorize our parks and playgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with stingers and occasionally ready to bite, the bugs of
summer start taking over the great outdoors about the same time we
foolish humans begin venturing out wearing fewer clothes _ just
daring those bugs to attack.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned? You should be. This summer, the usual pests should be
a little worse than average, because of the mild, dry winter and
the timing of spring's rains, says Paul Jackson, the Texas A&AMP;M
researcher who confirmed last month that Africanized honeybees,
better known as ``killer bees'' have indeed found their way into
North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, that's another sting of summer to worry about. An
entomologist and the state's chief apiary (beehive) inspector,
Jackson says this is a good year for swarming (good for the bees,
that is).
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had more swarm reports this year than either of the last
two, in part because of the mild winter,'' Jackson says. ``The
timing on the rains has also been good for the bees. We've had
plenty of flowers for them, blooming over a longer period than
usual. You could say Mother Nature has been kind to the bees the
past six months.''
</P>
<P>
   We're glad she's kind to some creatures. Meanwhile, here's what
you need to know about protecting yourself from the bugs that bite
in this season of stings.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICANIZED HONEYBEES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first Africanized bees crossed the South Texas border near
Hidalgo in October 1990, and Jackson had previously quarantined 119
Texas counties to help prevent the spread of the aggressive
critters.
</P>
<P>
   He quickly corrects anyone who uses the term, ``killer bees.''
</P>
<P>
   Their venom isn't any stronger, in general, and they are
slightly smaller than their more genteel European cousins, he says.
The bees get their bad rap because they swarm for a much longer
season each year and are very aggressive about protecting their
nests, Jackson says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have bred wild bees to become gentle,'' Jackson points out.
``In Texas, we've got queen breeders that have been selected and
bred for gentleness and high production for more than 100 years.
Africanized bees act like the wild bees they are _ highly defensive
around their breeding nests.''
</P>
<P>
   They are more likely to sense a threat at a greater distance,
become more upset with less reason and sting in much greater
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A domestic honeybee may sting you on the arm, and release
pheromone that will attract other bees, and 30 seconds later you
may have five stings. Africanized bees do the same thing, but 50 or
100 or 500 may come at you as soon as they sense the first sting,''
Jackson says. ``That's what we are worried about _ large numbers.
Each bee can sting only once.''
</P>
<P>
   A person may be stung hundreds of times in a few moments. In
isolated instances, people and animals have been stung to death
because they could not get away from the bees quickly enough. Some
pets and livestock were reportedly killed because they were penned
up and could not escape the bees.
</P>
<P>
   Wild bees were imported from Africa to Brazil in 1952 to
strengthen some breeding programs. They did well in hot desert
conditions, but somewhere along the way a few queens escaped, mated
with European drones and began swarming north, inbreeding their
strongest wild traits.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't distinguish them from regular honeybees just by
looking,'' says Scott Russell, the entomologist in charge of
Integrated Pest Management for the Tarrant County office of the
Texas Agricultural Extension Service.
</P>
<P>
   During a massive brood rearing period, there may be 35,000 to
40,000 bees in a colony, and when there are lots of baby bees, the
adults are highly protective. Disturb them, and they will come
after you, and they are easily disturbed. Step on a vine 20 feet
away, and the vibrations might disturb them. In the late afternoon,
casting a shadow near them may cause a disturbance, the bee experts
say.
</P>
<P>
   To escape a deadly attack, run away, and don't swat the bees.
Swatting will only make more bees want to sting you. Run inside and
shut the door if possible, Jackson recommends. If a pet is trapped
in a cage or even the back yard, open the gates so it can escape,
and turn on the sprinklers or hose. Bees stop flying when their
wings get wet.
</P>
<P>
   Pest control experts recommend calling a beekeeper to remove any
bees, or an exterminator with a high-pressure hose to kill them.
</P>
<P>
   Any time you see nests near the ground, especially under mobile
homes or in and around water meters or in holes or cracks in
building walls or tree cavities or drainage pipes or junk piles,
you should suspect Africanized bees and call an exterminator. Don't
try to spray them yourself, Jackson says.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he recommends staying away from all bees, just to be
safe. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FIRE ANTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Imported fire ants infest more than 260 million acres in the
Southern United States, where they are the No. 1 agent of insect
stings. Since the first fire ants were dumped near Houston in 1958,
they have taken over more than 80 million acres in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Those first fire ants were accidentally imported in tons of dirt
used for ballast on cargo ships coming back from South America, the
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone bitten by a fire ant develops an itchy,
localized hive or lump at the sting site, followed by a small
blister or white pustule within about 24 hours. Each ant can sting
multiple times.
</P>
<P>
   If you have been stung by any ant, chances are it was a
``Solenopsis invicta,'' the red imported fire ant, says Bart Drees,
coordinator of the Texas Imported Fire Ant Research and Management
Project at Texas A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   Fire ants are a major burden to Texans in rural and urban areas.
They cost millions of dollars annually in control and treatment and
to repair and replace equipment damaged or destroyed by the pests,
Russell says. MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 1828EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1031 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-YOGA-MUSIC-ART-$ADV04     05-31 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOGA-MUSIC-ART-$ADV04-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CHANT MASTER OF AMERICAN YOGA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT22 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (For release Sunday, May 4) 
 By ANN POWERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In yoga classes from New York to San Francisco, a
voice emanates from compact disc players, leading students through
their salutes to the sun. The tone is deep, open, American. The
music accompanying it pushes ahead like rock 'n' roll, stirred by
African rhythms or prettified by a New Age flute. But this sound is
not merely for relaxation or exercise.
</P>
<P>
   The words are Sanskrit, the ancient invocational tongue of
India, and the repetitive melodies stimulate a trancelike mental
openness. This is the gospel sound of American yoga, expressed in
the music of Krishna Das.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody loves music,'' Krishna Das, the chanting master who
was born Jeffrey Kagel in Long Island in 1947, said in a recent
interview at Les Deux Gamins in Greenwich Village. ``Here's an
offering of music that's also claiming to be a spiritual practice.
It's not heavy, it's not hard, you don't have to sit there not
moving all day as somebody beats you on the back with a stick. But
it is meditation.''
</P>
<P>
   The tuneful route to spiritual bliss is surging in popularity.
Organized chanting sessions, called kirtans, happen weekly
throughout New York. Even at gyms like Crunch, many classes begin
and end with a short chant. No longer are cries of ``Hare Krishna''
uttered only in airports by saffron-robed ecstatics. Like bindi
jewels and the writings of the Dalai Lama, yogic hymns are making
enlightenment accessible.
</P>
<P>
   Krishna Das is an unassuming icon of this trend. A practitioner
of Bhankti yoga, the devotional limb of mystical Hinduism, he has
fashioned himself into a ``kirtan wallah,'' or traveling singer,
bringing divine praises to gatherings nationwide. Yoga Journal
recently called him ``The Pavarotti of Kirtan.'' His most popular
album, ``Pilgrim Heart'' (1996), has sold nearly 50,000 copies. He
has sung with Sting and given instruction to Madonna. He tours
constantly; in May alone he led 14 events, including the keynote
address at the national ``New American Yoga'' conference at Kripalu
Yoga Center in Lenox, Mass. Triolka Records, the label he cofounded
10 years ago, has been significant in building the bridge between
world and New Age music.
</P>
<P>
   Meditation beads around his neck, cellular phone at the ready,
Krishna Das might seem to some to be a cultural interloper who has
found a way to turn his hippie ideals into a profitable venture.
Yet he remains unpretentious. It's easy to believe his claim of
doing what comes naturally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's perfectly natural that a Westerner should go to
India, soak it up and come back and then work with the forms
they've absorbed in this lifetime, which for me was Little Anthony
and the Imperials and rock 'n' roll,'' said this self-described fan
of the Clash. ``I've never formally trained in Indian classical
music, which is an extraordinarily subtle and amazing technique.
I've never had the discipline, and now I just don't have the time.
I want to sing to God, I want to sing to my own heart. And I want
to be open.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfettered enthusiasm is the source of Krishna Das' art. His
kirtans could make an atheist drop his guard. At a recent session
at the Jivamukti Yoga Center in downtown Manhattan that attracted
about 200 people, the genial leader began with a joke about missing
``The Sopranos'' and a gentle reminder that this music was not just
entertainment, but prayer. He cued his band, which included Jim
Donovan, the percussionist for Rusted Root, the Bansuri flute
virtuoso Steve Gorn and a crowd of other players and singers on
both Indian and Western instruments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll sing a line and all y'all sing along,'' he said,
beginning an invocation to the monkey deity Hanuman.
</P>
<P>
   Krishna Das pumped his harmonium, and the full band added heft
to the litanies. Although one skeptical newcomer leaned over to a
stranger and opined, ``He's the Studio 54 of chanting,'' most
attendees let the proverbial spirit take them, whether they
believed in the chants or simply relished the strong, simple
melody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to loosen people up,'' Krishna Das said later. ``This
isn't a course in how to chant. We're chanting! It's a
hootenanny.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Gannon, a founder of Jivamukti, said: ``K.D. has just
kept developing. He's like the tortoise in the story of the
tortoise and the hare. He keeps plodding along, and now he's won
the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Krishna Das' journey reflects the twisted path of yoga in
America, which evolved from a health craze to a part of the
countercultural dream in the 1960s, quietly developed in the '70s
and '80s and has returned to full force within the holistic
lifestyles of the new century. A midcareer period of retreat primed
the singer for his current, fortuitously timed comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many young people in the 1960s, Jeffrey Kagel turned to
Eastern practice out of frustration and hope. ``There was a
tremendous naivete,'' he said. ``We thought we could change the
world. A lot of people got very discouraged and felt very betrayed
by life, when things didn't change just because they took acid.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing in bands and on his own, Krishna Das sought freedom in
folk music, the blues and even heavy metal. A new route opened up
when he met Ram Dass, whose inspirational books about life under
the guidance of the guru Neem Karoli Baba had taken the
counterculture by storm. In 1970, he traveled to India.
</P>
<P>
   ``In India, they didn't see me as a failed, depressed rock 'n'
roller,'' he said. ``They saw me as a devotee of the god, and they
honored that tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   The stimulating environment and the guidance of Neem Karoli Baba
led the newly dubbed Krishna Das to a new musical challenge. ``I
sang with guys who were chanting, for hours, sometimes 10 hours at
a time,'' he said. ``When I first came, I couldn't even keep a
beat. They gave me this big cymbal. And one guy would go like
this,'' he said, clapping his hands together, ``and then he'd take
his hand away and I'd mess up. And he'd do it again. All day for
three days. At the end of a few days I had it.''
</P>
<P>
   Krishna Das lived blissfully at Neem Karoli Baba's temple until
1973, when he returned to America at the guru's behest. His teacher
called him back about a year later, but Krishna Das, who was making
money and enjoying a new romance, hesitated. Within months, Neem
Karoli Baba died.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ran over me like a truck,'' he said. ``I thought I had
blown it, and could never be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Fighting off depression, Krishna Das pursued music in Northern
California. He played in an early world-fusion band, Amazing Grace,
with Jai Uttal, another popular modernizer of kirtan. He toured
with Ram Dass, singing before the writer spoke, an activity he
continues.
</P>
<P>
   He also got into the music business with two friends, Mitchell
Markus and Paul Sloman. They founded Living Proof Records in the
late 1970s to record jazz elders they admired. The label, later
renamed Triloka, shifted toward world music with successful
releases from the sarod master Ali Akhbar Khan and the Tahitian
Choir.
</P>
<P>
   ``The label's identity came out of Krishna Das' and my
experience with India,'' Markus said by telephone from a recording
studio in Los Angeles, where the label is still based. ``The idea
is to keep intact the culture from which the music comes, and yet
make it completely accessible to a Western audience.''
</P>
<P>
   As Triloka grew, Krishna Das sequestered his own talent. He sang
only in small circles of friends. He intermittently returned to
India, seeking relief from his torment over Neem Karoli Baba's
death.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1994, living in New York, he realized that singing with
strangers might actually help him. ``I knew I was hiding stuff,''
he said. ``I had to sing with people in order to reach it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One night he attended a Jai Uttal concert at Jivamukti. He
noticed that the studio offered satsangs, or religious services.
``The next morning I got a phone call,'' Gannon remembered. ``This
man said: `Hello, my named is Jeffrey Kagel, and I also used to
chant. I know you have evening satsangs. I could do some chanting
after you talk.' He was such a nice, humble guy. I said, `OK, why
don't you come by this afternoon and we'll talk this over.' I left
for the yoga center, and when I arrived, there he was!''
</P>
<P>
   The Monday night kirtans soon drew a crowd, including musicians
and vocalists whom Krishna Das nicknamed his ``posse.'' He was
alternately pleased and bothered by his newfound fame. Back in
India in 1995, he prayed for inner reconciliation. To his surprise,
in the flash of recognition that seekers call satori, he attained
it. After that, the pieces of his vocation rapidly fell into place.
</P>
<P>
   He has released three albums since 1995, the most recent of
which is the double disc ``Live on Earth ... for a Limited Time
Only.'' Krishna Das says he can deal with such attention now,
neither recoiling from it nor letting it rule his ego.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's changed in him is what's different about a lot of us
who went over to India,'' Markus said. ``Major things like
developing a real sense of humor and an awareness of the poignancy
of any moment in your life. He's really becoming who he is, without
second thoughts about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even the peace Krishna Das has found, and his subsequent
success, has not tempered a certain melancholy within. Sharon
Gannon thinks it is the force behind his growing renown.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my teachers in India told me that for a song to be a
really good song it must have the element of sadness,'' she said.
``It has to wrench your heartstrings, that yearning. Unfulfilled
desire. Krishna Das has that. He still is the blues singer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
