<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEC-MEETINGS0601-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gators-Vols is CBS' top football pick
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DESTIN, Fla. _ CBS has made the Sept. 16 Florida-Tennessee game
the No. 1 pick for its SEC television football package for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the annual SEC spring meetings indicated that the
Florida-Tennessee game, which would be played in Knoxville, would
be broadcast at 3:30 p.m. CBS does not have the option of showing a
prime-time game this season.
</P>
<P>
   CBS gets six of the top nine preseason picks for games while
ESPN gets the other three. The other games picked by CBS were
Alabama at Tennessee, Oct. 21; Auburn at Alabama, Nov. 18; Georgia
vs. Florida in Jacksonville, Oct. 28; Auburn at Florida, Oct. 14;
and Georgia Tech at Georgia, Nov. 25. All except Georgia
Tech-Georgia should start at 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN used its top pick in the rotation to select the
Tennessee-at-Georgia game Oct. 7. That game is expected to start at
7 or 7:30 p.m. Other games picked by ESPN were Alabama at Arkansas
on Sept. 23 and Arkansas at Tennessee on Nov. 11.
</P>
<P>
   A complete television schedule will be released this summer.
</P>
<P>
   GOODBYE FOR C.M
</P>
<P>
   Technically, this will be the last SEC meetings for Kentucky
athletics director C.M. Newton, who retired earlier this year.
Newton, who is scheduled to be inducted into the Basketball Hall of
Fame, isn't sure about his future plans. Some of the league's
basketball coaches think he would be an excellent commissioner of
college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Many basketball people have complained that non-basketball
people have been making decisions for the sport, such as the recent
decision to end summer recruiting in 2001. They think that college
basketball has a unique set of problems and should have its own
governing body. Newton, who played at Kentucky and coached at
Alabama and Vanderbilt, would be the perfect person to lead that
body, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a guy like C.M. in there calling the shots,'' Alabama
coach Mark Gottfried said. ``He's been there. He knows the problems
that are unique to the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   VOTE FOR KRUGER
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky basketball coach Tubby Smith, who was thought to be a
candidate for the Hawks job vacated by Lenny Wilkens, said Atlanta
made a good choice in former Illinois coach Lon Kruger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it can be tough for college guys trying to break into
that league, but, I'm telling you, Lon is a tough guy,'' Smith
said. ``I've coached against him, and I really believe the young
guys on that team are going to be able to relate to him.''
</P>
<P>
   WORTH NOTING
</P>
<P>
   The SEC's athletics directors voted 12-0 to approve the new
football scheduling format. It will result in such games as
Florida-Alabama and Georgia-Alabama being played more often. The
league's presidents still must give final approval on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Florida is contemplating a multi-million-dollar renovation to
the press box and other facilities at Ben Hill Griffin Stadium. The
school is conducting a feasibility study. Florida's new athletic
budget was approved at more than $43 million.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi State soon will begin a renovation to Scott Field
that will raise the seating from 40,656 to more than 55,000. It is
scheduled to be completed for the 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   The football coaches discussed a new rule that would allow
quarterbacks to throw the ball away after they have break the
pocket and not be called for intentional grounding. The rule
basically is the same as the NFL's.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
