<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1037 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MARTINEZ-SPELLING-HNS     05-31 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTINEZ-SPELLING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CHRISTY MARTINEZ OF LAREDO FALLS IN FIRST ROUND OF SPELLING
BEE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Christy Lynn Martinez, an 8th grader from Laredo,
Texas, who started spelling competitively this year, stumbled over
the word philately in the 73rd National Spelling Bee Wednesday and
was eliminated after the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Christy, 13, approached the imposing black podium on the stage
where the contest was held and asked the so-called pronouncer to
repeat philately, which means stamp collecting. She then paused and
asked him to define it and use it in a sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Then she quickly tried P-H-A-L-A-T-A-L-L-Y.
</P>
<P>
   That's when she heard the dreaded bell that signals a mistake
and was ushered away from the stage into the bee's ``comfort room''
to regain her composure.
</P>
<P>
   But almost immediately she appeared smiling beside her father,
Arnulfo Martinez, an oil field worker for Chevron who measures how
much oil comes out of wells.
</P>
<P>
   Christy said ``it was scary'' when she was on stage and realized
she didn't know the word.
</P>
<P>
   But her father put a positive spin on the event. ``It's an honor
to have one of your children compete at a national level,'' said
Martinez, who grew up in Nuevo Laredo, Mexico, and became a U.S.
citizen in 1987 along with his wife Silvia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This trip is like a reward for her diligence,'' he said. ``We
never thought that we would be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Christy's mother Silvia Martinez predicted that the experience
will give her daughter new ideas about what she can become in life:
``She will be able to do anything that she wants to,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Martinez, an assistant at a company that researches
property titles and the daughter of a Mexican produce peddler,
labeled the trip to Washington ``a great experience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We got to see a lot of places we never dreamed of,'' such as
the U.S. Capitol, the Lincoln and Washington monuments, the White
House and the U.S. Holocaust Museum, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said Christy, who is always searching for a good book, was
reading ``The Diary of Anne Frank,'' a book by a Jewish teenager
who perished in the Holocaust along with her family.
</P>
<P>
   Silvia Martinez said she and her husband have always stressed
education for their four daughters, of which Christy is the
youngest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to encourage her to stay in school,'' said Silvia
Martinez, who dropped out of high school herself and later got her
general equivalency diploma.
</P>
<P>
   At home, both parents speak Spanish to their children. ``We
don't want them to lose their heritage,'' Arnulfo Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   Christy is an honors student at Crossroads Christian Institute
who volunteers as a babysitter in the nursery of her church, of
which the school is a part. Her father is an elder at the church.
</P>
<P>
   Christy, who beat 56 other competitors from Laredo area schools
last month in the regional spelling bee, said she would like to be
a pediatrician or a veterinarian.
</P>
<P>
   The National Spelling Bee, sponsored by E.W. Scripps Co.,
continues with final rounds on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address judy &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
