<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1038 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-LOTUS-KEYNOTE0601-COX     05-31 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTUS-KEYNOTE0601-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Net pioneer: E-mail needs more emotion
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ E-mail might work better in the hands of
William Shakespeare than it does for the guy in the cubicle next to
you.
</P>
<P>
   That limitation of Internet communication frustrates Mitch
Kapor, founder of Lotus Development Corp., co-founder of the
Electronic Frontier Foundation and keynote speaker at the third
biannual Harvard Conference on Internet and Society, which
continues through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Kapor thinks the future of the Internet lies in developing ways
to allow people to communicate face-to-face without actually being
in the same place. But even he, as a venture capitalist, knows
better than to put money into that.
</P>
<P>
   As a venture capitalist currently working in Silicon Valley,
Kapor says the driving force of the Net right now is focused on the
reshaping of business, leaving other pressing needs undeveloped,
unexplored and unfunded.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kapor still believes that the Net isn't just about
commerce. ``The humanist in me refuses to give up,'' he told the
capacity crowd at Harvard's Sander's Theater.
</P>
<P>
   He sees the future of the Net not in the convergence of the PC
and the television, but in the convergence of e-mail and telephony.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still communicate through text e-mail and the written
word,'' he said. That, he said, is where a great many problems
arise as Web users struggle to say what they mean and mean what
they say when they craft an e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The written word is lovely in the hands of Shakespeare,''
Kapor said. ``But most people have trouble expressing their
feelings and opinions in e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   He said part of the problem is that text-only messages strip
away body language, tone of voice and other ways that people use to
communicate.
</P>
<P>
   Kapor says he's adopted a personal rule that if his message is
crucial, he'll either use the telephone or actually seek out the
person he wants to speak to.
</P>
<P>
   However, he believes that eventually there will be a way for the
Internet to combine the personal inflections of phone or in-person
contact with traditional e-mail functions. ``What the Net lacks is
`emotional bandwidth,' '' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Does this mean all computers will come complete with Web cams so
users can see each other in real time? Kapor says no. ``Web cams
are not the answer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said he was placing his bets on the possibilities
generated by computer graphics and avatars, or representations of
people so that users can see their emotions as they communicate
their e-mail messages.
</P>
<P>
   But before e-mail can be taken to the next level, there is the
question of development and funding. Kapor worries about how this
type of development could be done in the current start-up climate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get them funded in the current angel
investor/venture capital environment,'' he said. ``These things are
very interdisciplinary, and it could be a public issue. But we need
to find the institutions who can do the basic research.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapor has a cautious optimism about the future of the Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some things about the Internet you have to love if
you have a beating human heart,'' said Kapor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a lot of speeches saying the Internet was going to make
everything better, but I was wrong,'' he said. ``The Internet will
not bring the end of civilization or herald a new utopia. It's
going to be somewhere in the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
