</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-BANKS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFTBANK MISSES DEADLINE TO ACQUIRE NIPPON CREDIT BANK 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to CORRECT name of Tokio Marine and Fire Insurance Co. in 3rd
graf.)  
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Softbank Corp., Japan's leading Internet company,
was dealt a setback Wednesday in efforts to acquire a large
insolvent bank nationalized by the government, which said it would
seek other possible buyers.
</P>
<P>
   An investment group led by Softbank had won the exclusive right
to negotiate the purchase of the Nippon Credit Bank three months
ago, in what was described at the time as a deal with far-reaching
implications for Japan's banking and Internet industries. But the
deadline for reaching an agreement, which had been extended once,
expired Wednesday with little progress made on the terms.
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Reconstruction Commission, the regulatory agency
overseeing the overhaul of Japan's troubled financial sector, said
it intends to keep talking to the Softbank-led group, which
includes Orix Corp., one of Japan's largest leasing companies, and
Tokio Marine and Fire Insurance Co. But the agency said it would
also talk to other potential bidders.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators said they could not agree with the Softbank group on
the scope of Nippon Credit Bank's bad loans and the value of the
collateral backing those and other loans. ``Those three each had an
opinion over how to estimate and deal with bad loans,'' said Shoji
Mori, a senior commission official. ``The situation at the final
meeting was that we were far from reaching an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the Softbank-led group, which had tentatively
offered 100 billion yen, or about $938 million at current exchange
rates, for the bank, said it would continue to pursue Nippon
Credit.
</P>
<P>
   Some financial analysts were betting that the Softbank group
would win the bank, one of two big banks nationalized during
Japan's financial crisis in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a credible business plan, and they want the
bank,''said Dean Perry, an analyst who tracks non-bank financial
companies at ING Barings.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials, speaking privately, said the failure to
meet Wednesday's deadline reflected political concerns over how
much responsibility the government would be forced to accept for
loans that sour after the sale.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has recently been criticized by politicians over
the terms of its deal to sell the Long-Term Credit Bank, the other
nationalized bank, to an investment group led by Ripplewood
Holdings LLC, a U.S. investment fund.
</P>
<P>
   Long-Term Credit Bank has emerged as the largest creditor of
several firms that have recently gone bankrupt or asked their
creditors for substantial debt forgiveness. Under the terms of
Ripplewood's agreement, the government must take responsibility for
bad loans that arise from such circumstances, lessening
Ripplewood's risk.
</P>
<P>
   Political concerns about the sale of these banks have come as
the country prepares for contentious parliamentary elections that
could weaken the power of the dominant Liberal Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Approval ratings for the Cabinet led by Prime Minister Yoshiro
Mori plunged to a record post-war low this week, according to a
poll done by the Asahi Shimbun.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the setback to Softbank, some analysts welcomed the
possibility that it may not acquire Nippon Credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought this was a very expensive way to buy a banking
license that came with too much legacy management,'' said Thomas
Rodes, who follows Japan's Internet industry at Nikko Salomon Smith
Barney.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The failure to reach a deal by Wednesday's deadline did not come
as a complete surprise. Japan's Internet business community has
buzzed with rumors that Softbank's ardor for the deal was cooling.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshitaka Kitao, president and chief executive of Softbank
Finance Corp., Softbank's financing subsidiary, has been openly
debating the wisdom of buying into Nippon Credit Bank with
Masayoshi Son, Softbank's founder and chief executive, who wants to
use the bank to finance the fledgling companies that have
historically lacked access to bank financing here.
</P>
<P>
   Kitao has questioned whether Softbank can assume the risk of a
bank that has a sizable portfolio of bad loans, particularly at a
time when Softbank's own financing is considered shaky. The company
has a speculative credit rating, its stock has fallen more than 73
percent since February and earnings plunged 77 percent in the
fiscal year that ended March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Son has dismissed such concerns, saying Softbank has more cash
on hand than the total of its debts due for the next eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have enough reserves to repay all debts at once if we
want,'' he told a news conference last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
