<SLUG> BC-PSA-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: PUBLIC SERVICE ANNOUNCEMENTS REQUIRE SPECIAL
CREATIVITY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALLISON FASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to public service campaigns, the goal is not so
very different from the intent of advertising for commercial goods
and services. Public service announcements, which appear pro bono
on behalf of organizations that promote safety, health and social
causes, must engage the audience and build awareness.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the producers of pro bono campaigns are working
harder than ever, it seems, to catch the attention of television
viewers and readers of magazines and newspapers. Their
unconventional creative efforts _ on issues as disparate as
Parkinson's disease, birth defects, suicide prevention and vision
impairment _ have another audience, too: the so-called gatekeepers
in the media who determine which few public service announcements
will benefit from free time and space out of the many that are
pitched.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole point of public service advertising is to get
somebody to take action,'' said Gary Scheiner, vice president and
associate creative director at McCann Relationship Marketing
Worldwide in New York, part of the McCann-Erickson World Group unit
of the Interpublic Group of Cos. ``You have got to make the most of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, McCann Relationship Marketing used the season finale
of the ABC sitcom ``Spin City'' as the vehicle for a public service
announcement for the Michael J. Fox Foundation for Parkinson's
Research. The star of the series, Michael J. Fox, who has
Parkinson's, appeared in the commercial, discussing how he was
leaving to devote his time to help search for a cure for the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got somebody like Michael, you'd be an idiot not to
use him,'' said Steve Cowles, senior vice president and group
creative director at McCann Relationship Marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Another agency, The Lord Group in New York, a joint venture of
Dentsu Inc. and Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc., took a different creative
approach _ casual humor _ to bring attention to a serious health
issue. A television campaign for the March of Dimes encourages
women to take a daily multivitamin with folic acid, which could
prevent birth defects.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding a stodgy approach that would have, say, delineated the
chemical effects of folic acid, the commercials show a live stork
arriving at an office to tell an employee she is pregnant. As the
visitor inches its way through the cubicles, employees react
differently: a woman tries to lure the stork closer with a sandwich
and a man climbs on his chair to avoid it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Humor gives it a more contemporary tone,'' said Penny Redfern,
an associate creative director at Lord, so ``you don't necessarily
realize it's a PSA.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to change their behavior,'' she added, referring to
the target audience, ``you've got to shake them up. Just giving
them the information straight, they're not going to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the same lines, Henry Hagerty, the president at the Think
Bank in New York, which represents companies that produce special
effects for advertising, created a short film meant to serve as a
public service announcement to raise awareness about suicide.
Hagerty plays the lead role in the film, called ``Easter
Clearing,'' which he said was based on a dream he had after a
friend committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The short film tells the story of a distraught man who loses
interest in his thoughts of suicide when he finds himself suddenly
trying to save a kidnapped child.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the easiest film to watch,'' Hagerty said. ``But if
you could just save one life with that film, wouldn't that be a
cool thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Easter Clearing'' can be viewed at www.atomfilms.com, the Web
site of Atom Films in Seattle. The film has also been distributed
at 340 centers of the National Mental Health Association, said
Patrick Cody, a vice president at the association, where it is used
to begin discussion groups for suicide survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Another organization trying to get the attention of a specific
audience is Lighthouse International in New York, which helps blind
people and people with partial vision lead more independent lives.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of starting a campaign to promote its cause, Lighthouse
prepared pamphlets that seek to demonstrate how contrasting colors
and more legible text can benefit readers. The goal is to encourage
agencies that produce ads and TV commercials with text on screen to
make them more readable.
</P>
<P>
   The effectiveness of print as an advertising medium is being
weakened, said Jerry Della Femina, chairman of Della Femina/Jeary &AMP;
Partners in New York, because 13.5 million Americans 45 or older
suffer some form of vision impairment even when wearing glasses or
contact lenses.
</P>
<P>
   Della Femina said he sent a memo to the art directors at his
agency, owned by top managers and the Omnicom Group, urging them to
make sure the type in the ads they create is larger and more
readable. He is also helping Lighthouse organize meetings to
educate agencies and advertisers about the guidelines and form an
advisory board to sponsor a competition of the ``best and worst''
ads in terms of readability.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good business to make type large enough for people to
see,'' Della Femina said. ``It's not just altruism, it's smart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 1838EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1043 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT01-COX     05-31 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT SETS STAGE FOR BREAKUP APPEAL
 &HT;    600&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An embattled Microsoft Corp. drew a legal road map
Wednesday of how it will contest a likely judicial decree to break
up the world's largest software company that could come as soon as
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's lawyers issued their antitrust battle plan in the
form of a lengthy response to a government proposal that would
slice the firm in two. The Justice Department and 17 states filed
their final brief last Friday at the behest of U.S. District Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft charged that the ``government's proposed final
judgment is defective in numerous respects, making the document
vague and ambiguous.''
</P>
<P>
   It suggested numerous substantive and technical changes in the
breakup document, but then added: ``No comment, or lack thereof,
should be construed as reflecting Microsoft's ... agreement with
any aspect of the government's (plan).''
</P>
<P>
   For example, it sought to delay the implementation of any
breakup for 12 months following the expiration of a stay, assuming
it lost an inevitable appeal that could go directly to the U.S.
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The federal antitrust laws were changed in the mid-1970s to make
it easier to bypass the federal court of appeals in cases of
significant national importance.
</P>
<P>
   After a widely watched 78-day trial, Jackson branded Microsoft
as an abusive monopolist that had squelched innovation in the
software industry, strong-armed its competitors and harmed
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the government's final proposal, Microsoft would be
divided into two separate companies. One would run its core Windows
operating system. The other would market its applications software,
such as Microsoft Office, as well as Internet products, such as
browsers and online services.
</P>
<P>
   But the company, claiming it has done nothing wrong, has
rejected the proposed breakup as an unjustified and extreme action
that would injure its consumers, its employees and its investors.
</P>
<P>
   Taking sharp issue with Jackson's abrupt closing down of the
landmark trial on May 24, Microsoft said it was its ``position and
understanding'' that the hearing ``was to be the beginning _ not
the end _ of proceedings on the issue of relief. Microsoft
believed, and still believes, that its position and understanding
were well-founded in both law and fact.''
</P>
<P>
   In playing its last legal card, Microsoft offered, under a
``supplemental offer of proof,'' to bring to court such top
executives as Michael Kapellas of Compaq and Jeffrey Katzenberg of
DreamWorks SKJ, who would testify to the negative effects a
Microsoft breakup would have on their companies and industries.
</P>
<P>
   But under Jackson's restricted timetable, those potential
witnesses, as well as Microsoft chairman Bill Gates, are unlikely
to ever be heard in the landmark case. The government, in its
revised filing, had called the proposed Microsoft extended witness
list a ``cynical ploy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who sat in the courtroom at the final hearing last week
had to come away with the impression that the judge wanted to the
government to give him a 'clean copy' of a final judgment so he
could sign it and get on with the appeal,'' said Rick Rule, a
former head of the Justice Department's antitrust division and a
current Microsoft legal adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, it would take the judge all of 10 minutes to
file his final judgment with the clerk,'' said William Kovacic, an
antitrust expert at the George Washington University School of Law.
``It's entirely possible we might see that later this week.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be surprised to see Judge Jackson rule by the end
of this week,'' echoed Joe Sims, an antitrust lawyer at Jones Day
Reavis &AMP; Pogue. ``He hasn't shown a lot of patience here
recently.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Salop, a professor of economics and law at Georgetown
University Law Center said Jackson ``wants to get something on the
table that could get appealed, since there is an expectation that
any remedy he orders will come back to him for refinement.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts disagreed about whether the Supreme Court would agree to
take the case directly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just any case. It's in a narrow category where
Congress has provided the option for direct review,'' said Donald
Falk, an attorney at Mayer Brown &AMP; Platt in Washington. ``It's not
a privilege that the government has abused over the past 26 years
</P>
<P>
   However, ``there are good reasons for the Supreme Court not to
take the case directly,'' said Bill Kolasky, head of the U.S.
antitrust practice at Wilmer Cutler &AMP; Pickering in Washington, D.C.
``There is a large, complicated factual record in this case that
would benefit from an appellate review.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is an above 75 percent chance that the Supremes
will not get the case immediately,'' said Richard Gray, a lawyer at
Outside General Counsel in Menlo Park, Calif. who has followed the
Microsoft case for the San Jose Mercury News. ``I think you're
looking at two years in the appeals court.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.microsoft.com
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
