<HEADER>
A1046 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-(1500     05-31 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-(1500-2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITHER THE BOY BANDS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED:eye-popping productions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With this popularity comes higher expectations. In the '60s, the
Beach Boys' Brian Wilson drew inspiration from the Beatles and gave
the world ``Pet Sounds;'' the Beatles, in turn, listened to that
record and came up with ``Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is suggesting that the 'N Sync/Backstreet rivalry will
lead to a pop masterpiece on that level, but it is obvious that
both groups are trading off their time atop Boy Band Mountain, and
that they are seeking more creative control over their music in an
attempt to be more than a passing fancy.
</P>
<P>
   The Backstreet Boys wrote a couple of songs on ``Millennium.''
They also took a step toward capturing a more mature audience in
April when they appeared on the VH1 special ``Men Strike Back,''
sharing the stage with established adult-contemporary pop/rock
stars such as Sting, as well as Tom Jones and young R&AMP;B trendsetter
D'Angelo.
</P>
<P>
   Bristling from their wrangle with Pearlman and RCA, the members
of 'N Sync made a point of trying to give ``Strings'' a grittier,
more hip-hop-flavored edge. Half the CD was written by band
members; also, they recruited noted hip-hop producers Teddy Riley
and She'kspeare, and covered Johnny Kemp's ``Just Got Paid.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to do this years ago wouldn't have worked. But this
latest revival of bouncy, bubblegum pop in the mid- to late'90s
coincided with the popularity of hip-hop. As a result, the
transition from one to the other does not seem as much of a stretch
as it would have seemed back during the days of the New Kids.
</P>
<P>
   And let's not forget about the respect a band gets from selling
millions of records _ and how it can wield that respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bigger a group gets, the more creative control they can
have,'' Rubin says. ``They have the clout to say, `I want to write
more songs' or `I want to produce.' Backstreet is writing most of
their new album together. They raise the bar and it gives them more
artistic freedom. It allows them to grow but not totally abandon
their roots.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent conference call, 'N Sync's Lance Bass and Joey
Fatone underscored this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just us,'' Bass says of ``Strings' '' hip-hop flavor.
``We wrote a lot; it's our baby. The pressure was definitely on
because everyone was going to know it was us and if anyone had any
fault with it or hated it, it was on us. But the fans love it, and
that's all we really care about.''
</P>
<P>
   The R&AMP;B/hip-hop direction was ``what we like,'' Fatone says.
``The fans like our style of music first, and their second favorite
is hip-hop and R&AMP;B. We think it's a totally different sound for us.
We call it dirty pop.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether this evolution of sound will enable 'N
Sync and Backstreet Boys to sustain their success, and to be making
records five years from now. The pop audience has always been
fickle, but, Isaak says, never so much as it is now, with new acts
debuting weekly and groups being more likely to be one-hit wonders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Longevity is a thing of the past,'' he says. ``The highway is
littered with bands and artists who weren't able to keep their
career going past one or two albums.''
</P>
<P>
   With so much money being made so quickly, there is always the
possibility that a member might leave to go solo, following in the
footsteps of Michael Jackson (the Jackson 5) and George Michael
(Wham!). But can 'N Sync or the Backstreet Boys survive intact?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way you can call it,'' Rubin says. ``The typical
life of a teen idol is four years, unless they can break out of the
mold. Ricky Nelson went from teen idol to rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is if they want to, or can, grow with the audience,''
he says. ``What people want to hear when they're 15 is not what
they want to hear when they're 20. If they can start to go there
and beyond, they might have some legs.''
</P>
<P>
   Isaak says that selling fewer CDs the next time out would not
sound a death knell for either group. Dozens of performers _ among
them Pearl Jam, Alanis Morissette, Sting, U2 and The Cure _ no
longer sell nearly as many CDs as they did in their heyday.
</P>
<P>
   But all continue to sell well enough to keep major label
recording contracts and to attract large crowds when they tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bon Jovi is still together _ they still have a career,'' Isaak
says. ``It's really hard to predict what will happen. I think it
would be healthy for 'N Sync to take on new groupings or do solo
stuff and it's likely that will be the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Change isn't a bad thing, and 'N Sync will always be able to
play somewhere, somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
