<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1054 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-3WOMEN0601-COX     05-31 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-3WOMEN0601-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Austin business travelers will soon be able to conduct business
from the airport
 &HT;    By Kirk Ladendorf
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Three Austin business women say they want to
make Austin-Bergstrom International Airport more business-friendly
by making travelers' waiting time more productive.
</P>
<P>
   At their business center, which is scheduled to open July 1,
they plan to offer conventional business center services, including
printing, copying and foreign currency exchange.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Austin Airport Business and Technology Center
plans to offer extra services for private member businesses for an
annual fee of between $42,000 and $78,000 a year. They will get
private meeting space at the airport, where they can have a drink,
conduct a private business meeting, plug in a computer to a
high-speed Internet connection and rent wireless phones. They could
even have advertising messages played on video terminals throughout
the airport.
</P>
<P>
   The business center won't be the only place at the airport with
an Internet connection. The City of Austin has struck a deal with
Austin-based Wayport Inc. to offer a wireless Internet service,
city officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Wayport, a 2-year-old startup that is still testing its service,
is among a group of companies competing to deliver wireless and
wired Internet access at hotels, airports and other public areas
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The mix of private and public services gives the new
1,800-square-foot Austin Airport Business and Technology Center a
good shot at profitability, said Stacy Rhone, its chief executive.
Her research of conventional business centers at airports showed
that many of them lose money because their services are too
limited.
</P>
<P>
   City officials agreed. The city let Rhone and her partners put
together a wider array of services to give them a better chance of
succeeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are optimistic that the services they will be providing
will allow them to have a successful business venture that will
also serve us and serve business travelers,'' said Charles Gates,
finance director for the City Department of Aviation.
</P>
<P>
   Rhone and partners Nancy Fisher and Norma Garza secured more
than $400,000 in financing from Xerox Corp. to build and equip the
center. A Xerox spokesman said the business center is an good
opportunity to showcase its products and services to business
travelers.
</P>
<P>
   They also negotiated a concession with the city. The city will
receive a guarantee of $5,000 minimum rent from the business
center. It also will receive 5 percent of the business center's
annual revenue between $50,000 and $100,000 and 7 percent of the
its revenue over $100,000. The city will also share in advertising
revenue for closed-circuit video advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The public part of of the center is under construction in the
airport ticketing lobby near the Southwest Airlines ticket counter,
while the private lounge and meeting area is being built on the
mezzanine level and is reached by elevator.
</P>
<P>
   The three entrepreneurs say they are marketing corporate
memberships earnestly to local high-tech companies and others that
want to conduct business meetings at the airport or offer services
to business travelers.
</P>
<P>
   The business center's first corporate member, United Bank of
Switzerland, wants to use the business center as a place where its
traveling bank executives can conduct meetings with local clients,
Rhone said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business people can fly in and fly out and get their business
done quickly in the right atmosphere with a variety of extra
services,'' Rhone said.
</P>
<P>
   The business center won't be the only members-only lounge and
business service center at the airport. American Airlines operates
its Admiral's Club near Gate 13, one of more than 40 Admirals Clubs
that American operates systemwide. The club, which is open to
members who pay a $400 annual fee, offers a lounge, two meeting
rooms, Internet connectivity and some basic business services,
including fax and copying.
</P>
<P>
   Continental Airlines also operates a members club at the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
