A1075 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-R-SCI-UNWRAPPING-CAND     05-31 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SCI-UNWRAPPING-CANDY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NOISE FROM THE CANDY WRAPPER IS INEVITABLE 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating to add art note)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMES GLANZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A team of physicists has made a giant leap in understanding the
prime scourge of audiences for opera, theater and concerts _ the
crinkling and crackling of candy wrappers.
</P>
<P>
   But their work will be scant help to audiences maddened by the
noise. The scientists demonstrated what plenty of dismayed
concertgoers have already intuited: the noise is inevitable no
matter how the candy is opened.
</P>
<P>
   The research, which will be presented on Friday in Atlanta at a
meeting of the Acoustical Society of America is the most detailed
examination ever of just how and why the mood-destroying noise is
generated in the kinds of materials that wrap candy.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, Eric Kramer, a physicist at Simon's Rock
College in Great Barrington, Mass., and Alexander Lobkovsky of the
National Institute of Standards and Technology in Gaithersburg,
Md., asked themselves why even the most careful, painfully
deliberate extraction of a piece of hard candy from its wrapper
does not seem to reduce the amount of sound produced as a desperate
audience member tries to relieve a dry throat, invariably just as
Tosca reaches the sublime pathos of ``Vissi d'Arte.''
</P>
<P>
   By recording crinkled wrappers as they were slowly stretched in
an otherwise silent chamber, and then digitizing and analyzing the
sound emissions on computers, the researchers found that the noise
was not continuous, but consisted of individual bursts or pops just
thousandths of a second long. Their loudness, the researchers
discovered, has nothing to do with how fast wrapping is undone.
Rather, the pops occur at random volumes as tiny, individual
creases in the paper suddenly rearranged themselves during the
overall shape change _ as the candy is unwrapped.
</P>
<P>
   The physics of wrappers turned out to be surprisingly complex,
said Kramer, who found analogues in the conformation changes of
large protein molecules in the human body and the magnetic
properties of materials in computer memories.
</P>
<P>
   But because the series of minute shape changes from wrapped to
unwrapped is unavoidable, the experiment's practical implications
were tragic news for every alas-poor-Yorick moment of great drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can follow that sequence as slowly as you want, but each
step in the sequence is accompanied by a click,'' Kramer said.
``And there's nothing you can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Broadway, where announced reminders to turn off cell phones
and beepers are accompanied by the suggestion that hard candy be
unwrapped before the curtain rises, the results may be about as
welcome as a bad review. But this parsing of the intricate behavior
of such a familiar object will find a ready audience among
scientists who study neither atomic nor cosmic realms, but rather
the physical middle ground between the very small and the very
large.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer said he no longer remembered exactly why he and Lobkovsky
began recording crinkling plastic. But he said that they became
intrigued by a fact that most people take for granted: smooth,
unwrinkled plastic has only one ``stable'' configuration, since no
matter how it is bent (as long as it is not creased), the plastic
will fall flat again. But crushed and wrinkled plastic has
innumerable stable states: deform it, and it holds the shape or
something close to it.
</P>
<P>
   So the researchers recorded the noises emitted during the slow
stretching of a common plastic that they had crushed and recrushed
many times. ``As far as we know, no one had ever looked at this
sound before,'' Kramer said.
</P>
<P>
   They were surprised to find an irregular series of extremely
brief pops with unpredictable energies that varied by a factor of a
million.
</P>
<P>
   In creating a theory of wrappers, the researchers found a
parallel in another common phenomenon, the rolling of a boulder
over a hilly, irregular landscape. Different wrapper conformations
correspond to the boulder's rolling into different depressions in
the landscape. And like a theatergoer gradually opening a wrapper,
someone might push the boulder very slowly up a hill. Nevertheless,
at some point it will tumble quickly down the other side, and, in
the case of the wrapper, emit that irritating snap.
</P>
<P>
   As homely as that process is, it has much in common a large drug
molecule that behaves differently in the body _ beneficially or
dangerously _ depending on what conformation it falls into, said
James Kakalios, a physicist at the University of Minnesota. ``If we
understood that, it would have a revolutionary impact on
everybody's life,'' since a new generation of therapeutic drugs
could be engineered, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But what does the research say about how to unwrap a piece of
hard candy when, horribly, a tickle in the throat arrives during
the final, fading bars of Tchaikovsky's ``Pathethique''?
</P>
<P>
   ``Unwrap it as quickly as possible and get it over with,''
Kramer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
