<HEADER>
A1079 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CHICKEN01-COX     05-31 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICKEN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    20 GROUPS CRITICIZE USDA OVER ALABAMA CHICKEN PLANTS
 &HT;    550&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By ELLIOT JASPIN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ More than 20 public interest groups accused the
U.S. Agriculture Department on Thursday(cq) of trying to intimidate
its own food safety inspectors and ``misrepresenting'' conditions
at two poultry processing plants in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Thomas Billy, head of the Food Safety and
Inspection Service, the groups said the department ``thwarts the
public's right to know about the quality and safety of poultry
products'' and threatens ``the effectiveness and legitimacy of
public participation.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter, which was to be delivered Thursday, was provided in
advance to Cox Newspapers by one of its signers.
</P>
<P>
   The groups said federal officials started their campaign of
intimidation after Cox published a story Feb. 6 about conditions in
two Alabama poultry processing plants run by Gold Kist Inc. of
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The story quoted federal inspectors as saying that under an
experimental inspection program that allows companies to police
themselves, Gold Kist employees were not culling out diseased
birds.
</P>
<P>
   The inspectors said carcasses with scabs, sores and pus were cut
up and made into chicken nuggets that the federal government then
purchased and distributed to school lunch programs around the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   In their letter, the groups accused Billy of warning inspectors
after the story appeared that ``there may be some risks to those
that are involved'' in the news story. The letter also said Billy
asked the Agriculture Department's Office of Inspector General
(OIG) to find out if inspectors had given ``internal agency
documents'' to a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your request of OIG constitutes the initiation of an illegal
retaliatory investigation,'' the letter says, ``because absent the
disclosures through the press, inspectors would not have been
placed under investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter said the OIG investigation was abruptly terminated
four days after it began when the Government Accountability Project
(GAP), a public interest group in Washington that defends
whistle-blowers, questioned its legality.
</P>
<P>
   The probe was also supposed to determine if adulterated food was
reaching consumers.
</P>
<P>
   But the letter said that even after learning from the OIG and
its own administrators that allegedly adulterated product was being
shipped to consumers, the agency ``misrepresented its own and the
OIG's findings'' to the public. They cited a press release by Billy
saying food from the plant was ``safe and wholesome.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter was written by Felicia Nestor, who heads GAP's food
safety program. Nestor said that she asked the heads of other
public interest groups to sign the letter. As of Wednesday
afternoon, Nestor said, representatives of 24 groups had done so.
They ranged from Washington-based Public Citizen, headed by Joan
Claybrook, former administrator of the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration, to the Western Nebraska Resources Council.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most influential food safety groups in Washington,
the Consumer Federation of America (CFA) and the Center for Science
in the Public Interest (CPSI), were not among those signing. Nestor
said Wednesday afternoon that she had not received a reply from
CSPI, and that the CFA had declined to sign. A spokesman for the
CFA was not available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Also signing the letter were the Cattlemen's Legal Fund, the
U.S. Public Interest Research Group, the Center for Environmental
Health, the New York-New Jersey Environmental Watch, Connecticut
Opposed to Waste, the Global Resource Action Center for the
Environment, the Vashon Island Growers Association, Consumers
United for Food Safety and Consumer's Voice.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Citizens Awareness Network, the Prairie Island
Coalition, the North American Water Office, Don't Waste Arizona
Inc., Earthroot Education, the Center for Food Safety, the
California Safe Food Coalition, the Aspartame Consumer Safety
Network and Pilot Hotline, the Community Nutrition Institute, the
law firm of Marler Clark, the Organic Consumers Association and the
Center for Media and Democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Elliot Jaspin's e-mail address is elliotj(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
