<HEADER>
A1092 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DAKAR-BIENNIAL-NYT &LR;      05-31 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAKAR-BIENNIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFRICAN IDENTITY? AN ART SHOW TURNS THE TABLES 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID HECHT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAKAR, Senegal _ It started in the early years of the 20th
century, when the Cubists broke down their subject matter in ways
that resembled African masks. Later Surrealists, Expressionists and
even Pop artists took visual ideas and concepts from Africa. Now
contemporary African artists are appropriating their traditions
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   That is the raison d'etre for the fifth Dak'Art, Senegal's
Pan-African biennial of art, being held here through Monday. This
former French colony, which the United Nations counts among the
world's least developed nations, has diverted almost $1 million
from basic human services and from paying off its vast foreign debt
to bring 47 artists here from 18 African countries and critics and
curators from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Development is not just about having enough to eat,'' said
Remi Sagna, director of Dak'Art, which has taken over museums and
public spaces throughout the capital. ``We are making a long-term
investment in our culture.''
</P>
<P>
   The dividend, as he sees it, is twofold. ``Art projects more
complex images of who we are than the conflict and misery shown in
the international press,'' he said. The other benefit is money:
``If African artists could command high prices, it would be a boom
to our economies.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the artworks are all an easy sell. Many of the works on
view here are highly conceptual. In a simple, elegant installation
a Senegalese artist, Soly Cisse, drapes mosquito netting, weighed
down by pillows, from a wall. Samuel Fosso, a photographer from the
Central African Republic, presents studio portraits of himself in
often unflattering outfits. The Ghanaian photographer Essien Mfon
presents images of imperfect naked African bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dak'Art is not meant to be a postcard vision of Africa,'' said
Jean-Charles Tall, an architect who is a member of the biennial's
organizing committee. ``It is a serious attempt by Africans to
reflect life through art.''
</P>
<P>
   Representation in African art has always been largely symbolic.
Giving cultural meaning to found objects, as the European Dadaists
did in the 1910s, or to raw materials, as Arte Povera did in Italy
in the 1960s, is the kind of leap of faith common in African
spiritual practices.
</P>
<P>
   But ``for Westerners, modern art is a revolt against the past,''
said the spokesman for Dak'Art, Oussanou Gueye. ``Africans don't
generally have these complexes.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, African intellectuals have long been trying to figure out
how their connection to Western modernism could be of benefit to
Africans in the real world. One of the earliest was Leopold
Senghor, Senegal's poet and first president, who lived in Paris in
the early 20th century and associated with artists there. When
Picasso once told him, ``We must remain savages,'' he replied, ``We
must remain Negroes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s Senghor became a leading member of the Negritude
movement, a heady group of French-speaking black writers affirming
traditional African culture and values and rejecting the French
policy of assimilation. He proclaimed that in the postcolonial
world order Africans would be the artists because ``emotion is
African,'' while ``reason is Hellenic.''
</P>
<P>
   When Senghor was elected president upon Senegal's independence
in 1960, he built schools for the arts, a grand concert hall, and
the Musee Dynamique for contemporary art. Senegalese schoolchildren
in the farthest-flung villages were taught African history and
culture as well as modernist art and theory. With generous
government support for the arts, many became artists.
</P>
<P>
   They produced thousands of rectangular semiabstract paintings
with colorful brush strokes that were painfully imitative and
repetitive. None of the artists became famous in the West, or even
in Senegal. When the technocrat Abdou Diouf became president in
1980, support for the arts dried up, and the Musee Dynamique was
emptied of its artworks and turned into the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes for an African ``modern'' art seemed all but dashed.
``African culture is only a raw material for the West,'' said an
official who worked at the Ministry of Culture at the time. ``It's
like cocoa, which grows in Africa, but when you try to make
chocolate from it here it melts. And that's what happened to
Senegal's dream.''
</P>
<P>
   With the first biennial in 1993, a spark again flickered, with a
difference. The artists and critics to emerge do not have the
utopian vision of Senghor's generation. ``They are less concerned
about being rooted in their culture,'' Gueye said of the Senegalese
artists in this year's Dak'Art.
</P>
<P>
   He gave the example of a sculpture by Ndary Lo consisting of a
giant iron stick figure wrapped in white thread in such a way that
it looks like a traditionally Senegalese long white gown. ``For me
the contrast of luxurious cloth against junk metal resonates with
the way toughness and refinement sit side by side in Senegal,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dak'Art grand prix is named after Senghor, and his legacy
continues. Some Senegalese artists not included in the official
biennial have built an ``art village'' of mud-and-straw huts next
to the city's giant stadium (also named after Senghor), where they
say they are creating a more authentic modern African art. They
call their exhibition ``Dak'Art Off.''
</P>
<P>
   The biennial doesn't seem to have an overall philosophy other
than including as many different types of contemporary visual
culture as possible. Since 1998 the biennials have included
sections for fabric makers and furniture designers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We no longer believe in trying to distinguish between high and
low culture in Africa,'' Sagna said. ``One way or another all art
is functional, and there is nothing wrong with it's being
popular.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the work does not have to look ``African.'' The most
successful Senegalese artist in recent years, Ousmane Sow, a member
of the show's organizing committee, is a realist sculptor whose
installations resemble theme parks; the themes are not always
related to Africa. One of his installations, shown last year in
Paris, tells the story of the Battle of Little Big Horn.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Dak'Art will be seen in the West for the first time.
It is to travel to France later this year, and organizers are
trying to persuade curators at the Studio Museum in Harlem to bring
it to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
