<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVENSYS-BAAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVENSYS TO BUY DUTCH SOFTWARE MAKER
</HEADLINE>
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Invensys PLC, a British manufacturer of factory
controls, agreed on Wednesday to buy Baan NV for $802 million,
promising to turn around the company, a Dutch software maker that
has relentlessly lost money and share value for nearly two years.
</P>
<P>
   Baan, once seen as one of Europe's most promising technology
companies, has been looking for a buyer since January, when Mary
Coleman, the chief executive, and a string of other senior managers
resigned. Lazard Freres &AMP; Co., the investment bank, was retained to
look for a buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Founded 22 years ago by two entrepreneurial brothers, Jan and
Paul Baan, the company expanded steadily until April 1998, when new
accounting rules forced it to defer revenue from licensing. The
company subsequently reported a series of quarterly losses, and its
shares lost nearly 90 percent of their value. In May, Baan shares
reached a low of 1.26 euros, or about $1.18, on fear the company
would seek bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Baan shares rose 13 percent, to 2.97 euros, or
about $2.79, on word of the Invensys deal. Investors punished
Invensys, however, driving down its share price 13 percent, to 230
pence, or about $3.45. With Wednesday's losses, Invensys stock has
fallen 32 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Invensys said it would pay 2.85 euros in cash for each Baan
share and assume $65 million in debt. The price represented an 8.8
percent premium on the Dutch company's closing price on Tuesday in
Amsterdam of 2.62 euros.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Yurko, chief executive of Invensys, said the acquisition
fitted the Invensys' ``vision to create the leading industrial
software company,'' offering products to link factories to
customers, suppliers and workers on the factory floor. He said Baan
would return to profitability within a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have turned around numerous software companies,'' Yurko
said. ``We have done it before.'' He acknowledged disappointment
about the stock market's reaction to the deal, but said the
combination represented ``the right thing for the long-term value
of the group.''
</P>
<P>
   Invensys, based in London, was created in February 1999 by the
merger of Siebe and BTR, which specialized in automation and
controls that enabled companies to monitor manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   Yurko said Baan would continue to operate under its own name as
part of a new Invensys software and systems division, expected to
generate annual sales of $2 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
