u e BC-NY-PHILHARMONIC-MEHTA     05-31 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PHILHARMONIC-MEHTA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILHARMONIC APPOINTING ZARIN MEHTA AS EXECUTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   By RALPH BLUMENTHAL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Philharmonic said Wednesday that it was
naming Zarin Mehta, who runs Chicago's prestigious Ravinia
Festival, to be its executive director starting in September.
</P>
<P>
   As the orchestra's top administrative official, Mehta will
supervise its business operations and bookings. He succeeds Deborah
Borda, who became executive vice president and managing director of
the Los Angeles Philharmonic late last year.
</P>
<P>
   The official announcement, set for Thursday, does not include
the naming of a successor to Kurt Masur as the orchestra's music
director. Riccardo Muti, music director of La Scala Opera, is the
Philharmonic's leading choice for the position, which will become
vacant in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Mehta, 61, whose brother, Zubin, was the music director of the
Philharmonic for a record 13 years until 1991, said Wednesday that
he and the orchestra's chairman, Paul B. Guenther, had met with
Muti in Milan last week and that the two looked forward to working
together as a team. ``He's very interested in the New York
Philharmonic,'' Mehta said. But he said that contract terms
remained to be worked out and that Muti's representative, David
Foster, was in Milan now meeting with his client.
</P>
<P>
   Guenther said that discussions were continuing with Muti, 58.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing imminent, but it's definitely moving in the
right direction,'' Guenther said.
</P>
<P>
   Although some orchestra members thought the two appointments
might be made simultaneously, Guenther said, ``There was never any
plan to announce them together.'' The orchestra leaves on a
European tour on Monday, and nothing will be announced before its
return on June 30, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He denied that the talks had hit a snag over salary or Muti's
commitments to the Vienna Philharmonic and the Berlin Philharmonic,
which he regularly conducts, in addition to La Scala. ``It's
proceeding in a professional fashion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Last week Muti was quoted in an Agence France-Presse article
from Milan as saying that the Philharmonic post ``is very
available'' but that ``it's me who must make a decision, and before
accepting I must find the right balance between various
obligations.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One Lincoln Center official said that the orchestra, smitten as
it was with Muti after his visits as a guest conductor, was seeking
assurance that he would continue Masur's attachment to New York
``and not just fly in and out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a strong feeling this is a marriage, not an affair,''
the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Mehta was one of 40 candidates offered by the recruiting firm of
Spencer Stuart &AMP; Associates, but he quickly topped the list,
Guenther said. ``We were told the best is Zarin Mehta, but you'll
never get him,'' he said. He called Mehta ``the best executive
director in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehta, since 1990 president and chief executive officer of
Ravinia, the open-air music festival in Highland Park, near
Chicago, the Chicago Symphony Orchestra's summer home since 1936,
said that his appointment, given his family's history, was ``an
extraordinary move for me.'' In addition to his brother's
involvement with the Philharmonic, his father, Mehli Mehta, a
violinist and conductor, studied in New York in the 1940s. A
cousin, Bejun Mehta, is a countertenor who as a boy soprano sang
for Leonard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Zarin Mehta, who was born in Bombay, entered the
music world as an accountant. Trained in England, he sought an
accounting job in New York in 1962 but was turned away for fear he
might head back to Europe or go to Canada to escape the Vietnam-era
draft. He did move to Canada to work for the accounting firm of
Coopers &AMP; Lybrand and joined the board of the Montreal Symphony
Orchestra, becoming its vice president. In 1981 he was named
managing director and served until 1990, when he took over the
Ravinia Festival.
</P>
<P>
   His musical training was nil, he said proudly. ``My parents
successfully kept me away from it,'' he said. For his
administrative duties, he said, ``accounting is better than being
an oboe player.'' He said he looked forward to working with Masur
and, if plans jelled, with Muti. ``It's a very strange marriage,
music director and executive director,'' he said. ``They're jointly
responsible. They have to be thinking along the same lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Could he have worked with his brother, Zubin? He didn't pause to
consider it. ``We would have fought tooth and nail,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for his plans for changes at the Philharmonic, he said it
would be presumptuous to speak of that yet. But he had one
priority. ``I want to attend a parks concert,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
