<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1099 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BAXTER-NAPSTER0601-CO     05-31 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-NAPSTER0601-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Napster dispute awakens debate about future
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This week a rowdy young man with headphones and an
attitude has turned up on the cover of Newsweek, official
certification of the Napster Internet piracy controversy as the
trendy story of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The bane of university computer systems operators and heavy
metal bands grown long in the tooth, Napster, a computer program
that allows users to share music over the Internet, has little
immediate relevance to most Americans. It's just a neat story,
because it involves a lot of gadgets, and because of the delicious
irony of a group like Metallica suing its fans for misbehaving.
</P>
<P>
   Like the first stories about women demanding admittance into
business clubs, however, the issues raised in the Napster story
will survive long past the bloom of trendiness.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential candidates have not had much to say on the
question of whether a college sophomore downloading a Beck album
constitutes a fundamental threat to the principle of property
rights, but Edgar Bronfman Jr., CEO of Seagram Co., which owns
Universal Music Group, sure has.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech last week in San Jose, Bronfman, who also owns the
company that produces ``The Jerry Springer Show,'' warned that the
blurring of the line between privacy and anonymity is having ``a
deleterious effect on our culture, our society and the long-term
growth of the Internet.'' He sounded a Churchillian call to arms
against the Napster pirates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will fight for our rights and those of our artists ... We
will take our fight to every territory, in every court in every
venue, wherever our fundamental rights are being assaulted and
attacked,'' Bronfman said.
</P>
<P>
   He went so far as to say the Internet, like the Soviet Union,
would ``crack, crumble and collapse'' if it goes down the wrong
path and adheres to the ``dangerous and misguided notion'' that
everything on the Internet should be free.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds bombastic, but bear in mind Bronfman's company owns the
rights to that downloaded Beck album, and he appears willing to put
his money where his mouth is to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   If the idea of grinding the Internet to a halt seems fanciful,
it's easy to see how it could be appealing to the person in control
of the world's largest record company, because of the desirability
of controlling musical tastes to insure a predictable return.
</P>
<P>
   As self-serving as it may seem for the businessman who broke the
46-year voluntary ban on television liquor advertising to rise to
the defense of culture and society, somebody was bound to do it.
</P>
<P>
   And in truth, the Napster story has more to do with the future
than the debate over whether Americans should be able to invest
their social security money in a bond fund. It raises fascinating
cultural questions, but as Bronfman has indicated, it is also
bearing down on the court system.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush seldom speaks of China without invoking the
wondrously liberating effects of the Internet, the limits on which
are what is crucially at stake in the Napster story. As the techie
vice president, Al Gore has had the chance to become well-versed in
the legal intricacies of intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
   Both of them should be expected to articulate some thoughtful
beginnings of a policy that spells out where the property ends and
how far the liberty goes. To do so probably won't matter much in
the campaign, but it could give the next president's Justice
Department a head start.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
