<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1101 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-HOME-DEPOT0601-COX     05-31 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-DEPOT0601-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home Depot Floor Store to open in July
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Home Depot's new floor-covering store in Dallas will
open in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   The retailer has dubbed the specialty concept the Floor Store,
said President and Chief Executive Arthur Blank. Atlanta-based Home
Depot announced plans for the standalone store in March but didn't
identify the name or opening date.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we've got such a strong presence in flooring, we
thought it made sense to test something like this,'' Blank said
after the company's annual stockholder meeting Wednesday. ``But let
me emphasize, it's only a one-store test.''
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot dove into carpet, rugs and floor covering in 1996 and
quickly became the No. 1 seller of those goods. It sold $2.25
billion in flooring last year, according to industry estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The Floor Store will carry about 15,000 floor, wall and window
products in a 40,000-square-foot format. About 25 percent to 30
percent of the merchandise will overlap with products Home Depot
sells at its warehouse and Expo Design Center stores, Blank said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We chose Dallas as a test site because we want to see what
kind of impact the Floor Store will have on sales at our other
stores there,'' Blank told reporters. The Dallas area has about 30
Home Depots, which focus on lower price points, and three Expos
selling high-end rugs and carpeting.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time Home Depot has tried selling such a
specialized line of products in a single store. Its other
freestanding concepts, Expo and Villager's Hardware, sell a range
of goods.
</P>
<P>
   Blank reviewed several initiatives for about 2,500 company
shareholders attending the annual meeting near Atlanta. The
initiatives included the company's planned summer launch of a
limited electronic commerce Web site, and its growing focus on
professional customers.
</P>
<P>
   The tone of the meeting was markedly more genial than in recent
years, when environmental groups staged high-profile protests of
Home Depot's sales of ``old-growth'' wood products. Last August,
Home Depot said it would start phasing out wood from endangered
forests.
</P>
<P>
   The main complaint Blank faced this year was a relatively rare
one at Home Depot gatherings. The company's stock has lost nearly a
third of its value this year, and some shareholders wanted to know
why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the same question,'' Blank said. ``Over the long haul,
the stock's going to be fine. But I have the same lack of patience
you do with the stock market. Believe me.''
</P>
<P>
   Blank blamed Wall Street's preoccupation with rising interest
rates, which tend to spook investors. Shares of Home Depot closed
at $48.81 1/4, up $1.56 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   In other business, shareholders adopted a proposal to recommend
that Home Depot reinstate simple-majority voting on all issues
subject to shareholder vote. That would eliminate current
``super-majority'' provisions requiring approval of at least 80
percent of outstanding shares for major matters such as mergers.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal still must be approved by Home Depot's board of
directors and at least 80 percent of shareholders in a future vote.
Shareholders rejected for the third straight year a proposal that
the company disclose more about the gender and racial makeup of its
232,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot reports summaries of its female and minority hiring,
but certain institutional investors want the retailer to report
detailed data within job categories by race and gender.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Home Depot's board declared a quarterly cash dividend of
four cents per share, payable June 29, to stockholders of record on
June 15.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
