<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1103 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DOW01-COX     05-31 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stocks pull back after big run-up
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bad news apparently wasn't bad enough for the stock market
Wednesday. Instead of rallying to news of economic slowing that
might curb future Federal Reserve interest rate hikes, investors
took profits instead from the market's latest gains.
</P>
<P>
   Slower home sales, reduced industrial activity and indications
of future slowing failed to prevent the market from ending a losing
month _ the fourth this year _ with a losing session.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Tuesday's strong gains, including the biggest-ever
one-day percentage gain for the Nasdaq composite index and a big
gain for the Dow Jones industrial average, made profit-taking too
tempting to pass up.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential Securities strategist Larry Wachtel said Wednesday's
stock market performance was open to interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   ``To those who felt that (Tuesday's) moon shot ushered in a
brave new world, the modest performance on Wednesday may have been
disappointing,'' he said. ``But to those who feel that the biggest
Nasdaq percentage gain in history was tough act to follow,
Wednesday was respectable.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had speculated that this week's economic news would
help investors make up their minds which way they think the Federal
Reserve will go with its policy of raising interest rates to slow
an inflationary economy.
</P>
<P>
   But apparently the market decided that one day's news was not a
trend, and not enough to convince investors the Fed is about to
reverse its anti-inflation policy.
</P>
<P>
   The most important report came from the Purchasing Management
Association of Chicago, whose index of business activity fell to
53.9 in May, on a seasonally adjusted basis, from 56.5 in April.
Economists considered it a good gauge of the national purchasing
managers' report, due out today.
</P>
<P>
   The report ``that growth in the factory sector is moderating is
good news for the Fed, but the slowing is nowhere near enough to
keep them from boosting rates further,'' said First Union economist
Mark Vitner.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department also reported that sales of new homes
tumbled 5.8 percent in April, the largest decline since last
September.
</P>
<P>
   And the Conference Board's Index of Leading Economic Indicators,
which is thought to predict activity six to nine months in the
future, declined by 0.1 percent last month.
</P>
<P>
   The market may show more reaction Friday when the government
releases its report on job growth and unemployment report, for May.
</P>
<P>
   The monthly report has become one of the most important and
watched-for economic signals.
</P>
<P>
   The April unemployment rate fell to 3.9 percent from 4.1
percent, indicating no letup in the nation's tight labor markets.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's trading, Qualcomm was blamed for leading the
Nasdaq sell-off, falling 13 percent on news that China Unicom will
not use the company's current cell phone technology. The Nasdaq
fell 1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
