<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1104 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-ACTOR-BUS-DEATH-AR     05-31 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ACTOR-BUS-DEATH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LIFE DEVOTED TO THE STAGE, ENDED BY AN ACCIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-TOUR-BUSES) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After nearly 25 years in the business, Randolph Walker knew
better than to bank on an audition. Still, when he headed home last
week after trying out for a bit part in a movie called ``Dummy,''
he could not help feeling a little hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   Life as a New York actor demands a difficult combination of
realism and optimism, and Walker had perfected it, scraping by on
the odd bits of work that define daily existence for so many people
in the profession.
</P>
<P>
   It was on his trip home to West 43rd Street last Monday that
Walker was fatally struck by a double-decker tour bus at Ninth
Avenue and 45th Street, setting off a wave of outrage against the
operator of the bus, problem-ridden New York Apple Tours.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction in theater circles was more than anger or sadness
at seeing a 71-year-old man struck down. New York's acting rank and
file, who live the rare highs and relentless lows of the city's
performing arts, had lost one of their own.
</P>
<P>
   To some workaday actors Walker was a familiar face from
countless casting calls for ``mature man, 60 to 75.'' To others he
was a gracious fellow cast member, happy to mentor and befriend
younger colleagues. To the actors who knew him as Ran, and even
those who didn't know him at all, Walker embodied their struggle: a
working actor aiming for the big break even as he tries to make
ends meet, a devoted performer willing to take roles in remote
dinner theaters or obscure downtown workshops because of a love of
the stage, a survivor who _ with the exception of a couple of
Christmases on the sales floor at Brooks Brothers _ proved it was
possible to tough it out without waiting tables or working for a
temp agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many actors who don't work at all, and here was a
guy who supported himself as an actor,'' said Todd Heughens, 38,
who became close friends with Walker 14 years ago while working on
a Boston production of ``1776.'' ``So I think he took great pride
in that.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Walker in many ways typified the life of a certain tier
of New York actor. He lived in Manhattan Plaza, the
government-subsidized apartment complex mainly for performing
artists on West 43rd Street where tenants pay 30 percent of their
income as rent, an amount adjusted annually. Generally, a friend
estimated, Walker paid about $500 a month for his 18th-floor studio
overlooking the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   He went to the theater whenever he could, availing himself of
the occasional discounts available to members of the profession.
Sometimes Walker would be invited to final dress rehearsals, known
as gypsy runs, by friends in the cast.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from playing a minor role in one Broadway show, Walker
worked at a level that included dinner theaters, which generally
pay $300 to $600 a week; print advertisements, which can pay $100
to $500; and workshop productions, which often don't pay at all.
Despite painful dry spells, Walker always got another job
eventually. His income, though, fluctuated from year to year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could land a tour and have a good year,'' Heughens said,
``but he could have a year where he earned under $30,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker had to work 20 weeks of the year to get unemployment
insurance. His main concern was reaching that cutoff _ and, with
the exception of one year, he always did. This hurdle aside, Walker
was consumed with getting auditions and then making the most of
them. Even knowing the odds, friends say, he would get his hopes up
every time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a lot of auditions but also a lot of rejections,'' said
Stephen Morello, 82, his companion of 21 years. ``You know how the
theater is _ you have to be a certain age and have a certain
look.''
</P>
<P>
   Because his survival depended on working, Walker never turned
anything down. Six foot and 165 pounds, with gray hair and brown
eyes and a resonant voice, he was generally cast in small character
parts. Butlers, undertakers and Scrooges were his bread and butter.
</P>
<P>
   In a regional production of the musical ``Annie,'' for example,
he played Drake, the head butler; in a regional ``Man From La
Mancha,'' the innkeeper. He also did a few turns on soap operas
like ``As the World Turns'' and ``One Life to Live.'' Heughens, now
an art director, described this as ``under-five work,'' when actors
are hired for the day and have fewer than five lines.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Petito, who directed Walker in plays produced by his
former Off Off Broadway acting company and now runs La Stanza
Verde, a restaurant on Theater Row, said that ``people like Ran get
lost in the shuffle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He should have been doing so much more dramatic work or
sophisticated comedy,'' Petito said.
</P>
<P>
   Walker was happy to travel to Muskegon, Mich., to play a couple
of roles in ``Camelot'' or to be a judge in a background scene in
one of the ``Godfather'' movies or to portray a man who founded an
evaporated-milk company in a television commercial or to be the
taped tour guide for the Museum of the City of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``He usually played funeral directors,'' said Michael Hartig,
Walker's agent, who represented the actor for about 20 years. ``He
had a very charactery look, right out of the movies in the '40s. If
he had gone to Hollywood, he would have had a big career.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many different union contracts for actors based on a
production's venue, and Walker usually worked at one of the lowest
pay scales. Casting directors, who ultimately send their
recommendations on to the director of a production, say that Walker
seemed to feel that nothing was beneath him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money was less important,'' said Steven DeAngelis, a
casting director at Grey Worldwide, the advertising agency, who
cast Walker in various parts. ``He was willing to audition for
every kind of job. A lot of actors' first words are: `What contract
is it? How much is it paying?' His were: `Who wrote the music? Who
is the director?'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
