<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1105 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-ACTOR-BUS-DEATH-AR     05-31 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ACTOR-BUS-DEATH-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: the director?  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What made all the anonymous bit parts worthwhile were the
occasional meaty roles Walker landed in serious plays _ even if
they were produced in out-of-the-way places for no pay. ``Ran was
the kind of performer for whom the work was the reward, the process
was the reward,'' DeAngelis said.
</P>
<P>
   Friends say that Walker was particularly proud of the
performance he gave in the Heritage Theater Company's production of
``Taking Sides'' last month at the U.S. Custom House in Lower
Manhattan, where, for $3 a day in car fare, he played Wilhelm
Furtwangler, the controversial German conductor who did not join
the Nazi party but sympathized with aspects of the totalitarian
regime.
</P>
<P>
   Walker apparently found the experience of having a leading role
disorienting. ``He hadn't done a role of that size in so many
years,'' Heughens said. ``He kept saying, `How am I going to
remember the lines?'''
</P>
<P>
   It was a workshop production for invited guests. In a letter to
the theater company's founder and artistic director, Thomas Luce
Summa, Rhoda Nathan, president of the Bernard Shaw Society, wrote:
``I thought that Randolph Walker's Furtwangler was extraordinary.
He managed to break your heart and generate skepticism about his
behavior at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker had been a charter member of the Heritage, an Off Off
Broadway company, for 30 years. Summa said his company had for the
last five years been planning to do ``The Merchant of Venice'' with
Walker in the role of Shylock, but Walker kept having to pass in
favor of projects that paid the rent. ``Every time we'd start, Ran
would get a part,'' Summa said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did so many small parts in musicals. His part in `The King
and I' on Broadway was a small part. It wasn't a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, appearing on Broadway once _ as Walker did as Sir Edward
Ramsay in the 1976 revival of ``The King and I,'' with Yul Brynner
_ can be a mixed blessing, Heughens said, ``like your career
peaked.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Hartig sent Walker out on various casting calls,
friends say Walker also hustled on his own, combing the trade
papers for auditions, keeping in touch with directors he had worked
with about whether there might be a role for him in their future
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Walker was tough on himself. ``He wished he was a little more
ambitious,'' Heughens said. ``Maybe he could have made a little
more of a name for himself or worried about money a little bit
less.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker belonged to a small circle of older men who go up for the
same parts, regularly running into one another in the waiting room
outside the casting room door. Nevertheless, the people who were
part of this group say Walker was noncompetitive in the extreme,
that he told his friends about roles he was seeking so they could
try to get them also, that he was happy for them even when they won
parts he had wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We competed a couple of times for roles,'' said Keith Perry,
69, a fellow actor who became a friend. ``We shared
disappointments. There was never a jealousy in Ran.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker also gained a reputation for mentoring younger cast
members. ``When he worked on shows, they would gravitate toward
him,'' Hartig said. ``He was kind of like Santa Claus. He always
had time to talk to them, to share his knowledge and his
expertise.''
</P>
<P>
   In large part, those who knew Walker say, this generosity
stemmed from the fact that Walker simply felt lucky to be working
in the theater after so many years of having stayed away. Soon
after his 1951 marriage to a fellow drama student he met during
freshman year at Rollins College in Winter Park, Fla., Walker left
the theater to become a banker. ``I think he realized it was almost
impossible to make a living that way,'' said Eleanor Walker, the
actor's former wife.
</P>
<P>
   The Walkers had two children, a son who died at 16 in a fire and
a daughter, Katharine Hoffman, who lives in a Chicago suburb with
her husband, Richard, and their two teen-age sons.
</P>
<P>
   After his divorce in 1976, Walker came to New York to try to
return to professional acting. ``I think he felt like his whole
life had started all over again,'' said Nagle Jackson, former
artistic director of the McCarter Theater Center in Princeton,
N.J., who in 1990 directed Walker in his adaptation of ``A Tale of
Two Cities.'' (Reviewing the play for The New York Times, Wilborn
Hampton said Walker ``presents a detestably wheedling Barsad.'')
</P>
<P>
   Although years ago he had a triple bypass operation, Walker had
a youthful spirit and seemed strong. He and Morello traveled every
year together and had been planning a trip to Venice in September.
</P>
<P>
   Although Walker did not look at his acting career as a model for
up-and-coming actors, friends say it was a shining example to many
of them nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a life you choose, and he chose this life and he was
going to make it work,'' Heughens said. ``Sure, he would rather be
doing a Broadway show, but if that didn't come his way, he wasn't
going to chuck it all, either.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
