<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1109 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GRAHAM-DANCERS-NYT &LR;      05-31 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAHAM-DANCERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAHAM TROUPE DECLINES OFFER TO PERFORM AT DURHAM FESTIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER DUNNING    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The dancers of the Martha Graham Co., which suspended
operations last Friday because of financial problems, have declined
an invitation to perform independently at the American Dance
Festival in Durham, N.C. The troupe had been scheduled to open the
festival next Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to suspend activity in the Graham company, school
and junior ensemble came during a battle between Ron Protas, whom
Graham named as her successor and who leads the Martha Graham
Trust, and board members and administrators, including the acting
chairman, Francis Mason and Marvin Preston, executive director of
the Graham company. Board members on both sides say the feud has
made donors reluctant to help the company, which has a deficit of
$500,000.
</P>
<P>
   The dancers said in a strongly worded statement on Tuesday that
``to work as a pickup company hired by individual presenters having
to license the Martha Graham ballets like any other company in the
world only profits Ron Protas and the Martha Graham Trust and not
the Martha Graham Center or the company, which Martha herself
founded and which has been in existence for nearly 75 years and in
which place lives Martha's technique and ballets.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the dancers, Protas said Wednesday that he
receives no special fees for performances. Under the terms of his
agreement with the Martha Graham Dance Center, which oversees the
school and companies, he receives $1 a year in royalties, though he
is a paid artistic consultant to the center.
</P>
<P>
   The dancers also said that accepting the offer to perform would
be short-sighted and not a solution to ``the inherent problems that
plague the inner structure of the Martha Graham Dance Company.''
Performing at the festival, they said, would ``not in any way
address the larger concerns for the future or truly answer the
question of who is responsible for bringing the company to this
tragic point or why.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The dancers wish to work cooperatively with the board and with
Ron Protas to allow the company to remain together and to continue
Martha's legacy,'' said the dancers. ``There is no justification
based on ego, pride, money or power to suspend operations of a
company of such great stature and significance as the Martha Graham
Dance Company.''
</P>
<P>
   The dancers agreed to meet Preston and Mason at the troupe's
temporary headquarters in the East Village on Tuesday, the day they
were to have begun rehearsals. Protas did not attend. When Preston
and Mason left to talk with the students, a vote on the festival
performances was taken with 13 dancers of the 17-member company
voting no. Two dancers abstained and two did not attend the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Protas, who would have had to license the dances to the festival
for the performances, also turned down the invitation to avoid
possible conflicts with the center. ``The leadership of the board
and Ron deserve each other,'' said Charles Reinhart, who directs
the festival with Stephanie Reinhart. ``Other companies and arts
institutions have financial difficulties to a greater extent than
this and are able to continue. This is a war, and the real
casualties are the dancers and the Graham public.''
</P>
<P>
   In declining the invitation, the dancers lost three weeks of
work, including rehearsals. A European tour, appearances in
California and performances at the John F. Kennedy Center for the
Performing Arts have also been canceled. The company was also to
perform at the Joyce Theater in Manhattan in November. Linda
Shelton, executive director of the Joyce, said Wednesday that the
Joyce was exploring other possibilities for the Graham dates.
</P>
<P>
   Despina Diamantopoulou, speaking for the Graham students, issued
a statement on Tuesday asking the public for emergency financing to
keep the school open. The suspension of the Graham school programs,
which have drawn students around the world, has been a particular
problem for the foreign students who make up half the annual
enrollment of about 500 students. With all employees owed a month's
pay, school administrators, class accompanists and teachers have
volunteered to keep the school going day by day during the summer
term while a search goes on for space and money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three accompanists showed up,'' Pearl Lang, a former Graham
star who teaches at the school, said Wednesday about a class this
week. ``I had an orchestra!''
</P>
<P>
   Among the offers of financial support to the school was a
promise of $1,000, enough for one day's operation of the school,
from a dancer who performed with Ruth St. Denis, Graham's teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theoretically we're closing up,'' Preston said Wednesday.
``But I say `theoretically' because we're still trying to figure
out how to start it up. Nobody wants this thing to go away. We just
have to be careful to be responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
