<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1112 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-OLY-BEIJING-COX     05-31 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BEIJING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beijing goes for the gold in 2008 Olympics bid
 &HT;    By Keith Graham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ It's ... Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   No, not exactly. No one from the International Olympic Committee
has said that. Not yet, anyway, but Li Jian has a vision.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers watching television when Atlantans heard that their
city would host the 1996 Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still remember the exuberance of your people,'' says Li, a
longtime sports reporter for China's state-controlled press.
``That's what impressed us.'' And jubilation like that is Li's
vision for the people of his city, some day in the not-too-distant
future.
</P>
<P>
   It's a vision that fits into a far grander dream. As he walks
through the site where a decade ago Beijing hosted the Asian Games,
sometimes called the ``Eastern Olympics,'' Li throws his arms wide
and says this is where the Olympic village will be built. Only it
will be 10 times as large as the village for the Asian event.
</P>
<P>
   He speaks of the city's hotels being filled with ``foreign
friends coming to Beijing and understanding the real situation
here.''
</P>
<P>
   And he sees the city itself as much grander than today: Thanks
to billions of dollars of investment in improved infrastructure,
even the hovering cloud of air pollution will largely be gone.
</P>
<P>
   Li has traded in his press pass for a post as deputy division
chief of publicity for the Beijing 2008 Olympic Games Bid Committee
and perhaps he exaggerates.
</P>
<P>
   But among the team of about 60 organizers already bustling at
work on a donated floor in the Beijing Xinquiao Hotel, the
ex-sportswriter's dream is widely shared.
</P>
<P>
   Like Li, Wang Wei, the general secretary of the committee, says
he remembers Atlanta's celebration. He predicts the eruption in his
city, if Beijing successfully lands the Games, will top any
celebration by a city yet.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the 1940s, China had dreamed of hosting an Olympics.
``But at that time the facilities were not so good,'' Wang says. In
the era of reform following the death of leader Mao Zedong, Deng
Xiaoping gave the green light for a serious effort for Beijing to
become a host city. And in 1993, when the 2000 Games were up for
grabs, Beijing came, oh, so close. It lost to Sydney by only two
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Deeply stung by that defeat, Beijing sat out the 2004 bidding,
won by Athens. But it is mounting a full-tilt effort for the 2008
Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   The city is not alone in wanting the honor. Nine other
metropolises _ Bangkok, Havana, Istanbul, Kuala Lumpur, Osaka,
Paris, Seville, Toronto and Cairo _ have submitted formal
applications to the IOC for the Games to be formally awarded in
Moscow in July 2001. In August the list is expected to be narrowed
down, but handicappers generally place Beijing as the front-runner
with Paris and Toronto as the closest competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Wang, for one, is not ready to declare his city a winner and
even adds a couple of applicants _ Osaka and Cairo _ to the list of
neck-and-neck competitors.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1993 vote, Beijing was hurt by sentiment _ then still
very fresh _ that the June 1989 massacre of human rights
demonstrators at Tiananmen Square had greatly tarnished China's
international standing. This weekend will mark the 11th anniversary
of the confrontation between troops and demonstrators in Tiananmen.
</P>
<P>
   Wang acknowledges that world perceptions about China's human
rights record could still pose a problem for the city's bid. But he
is hoping the passage of time and the greater openness of the
government in recent years will blunt those criticisms.
</P>
<P>
   ``In geographic location, in population and in cultural aspects,
Beijing leads the competition,'' he says, speaking through an
interpreter. ``Beijing is quite different from those (other)
cities.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
