<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1113 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MOORE-SPELLING-HNS &LR;      05-31 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOORE-SPELLING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MIDLAND BOY BOWS OUT OF NATIONAL SPELLING BEE IN OPENING
ROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Michael Moore, a sixth grader at Crockett
Elementary School in Midland, Tex., spelled ``septentrional''
correctly at the National Spelling Bee Wednesday, but missed his
next spelling challenge and was eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   The word that ended his run was ``negotiability.'' Michael
started spelling the word with an ``na'' instead of an ``ne.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what you get for living in Texas,'' Michael's father,
Bruce, joked, referring to the way the beginning of
``negotiability'' sounds with an accent. ``It's just the luck of
the draw,'' he concluded about the words Michael had been asked to
spell.
</P>
<P>
   Michael, 12, was younger than most of the other contestants. He
said he will continue to study spelling and will try to come back
to the national competition next year. His sister Stacey competed
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Michael, who won his first school bee in third grade, has two
years of eligibility remaining. High school students are
ineligible. He was sponsored in the competition by the Midland
Reporter-Telegram.
</P>
<P>
   He joined 247 other fifth- through eighth-grade students from
around the nation in the 73rd bee, sponsored by Scripps-Howard Co.
</P>
<P>
   His first contest word, ``septentrional'' _ defined as
``northern'' _ was taken from a list distributed to the contestants
in advance of the competition.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Pam, said she had rehearsed the word with Michael.
She said Michael had been studying since November for the regional
and national competitions.
</P>
<P>
   The words from the next round of questions were taken randomly
from the dictionary. That's when Michael was asked to spell
``negotiability.''
</P>
<P>
   First, he exercised the right of all contestants to ask for the
definition of the word. Then he asked the judge to use the word in
a sentence. Spellers also are allowed to ask for alternate
pronunciations and the word's language of origin.
</P>
<P>
   Michael characteristically thrust both of his hands in his
pockets _ ``I told him to do that (because otherwise) he hits the
microphone with his mouth,'' his mother said _ and spelled. He
missed the correct spelling by only one letter. Later, he said he
knew the root of the word was ``negotiate.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael said he would not come back to watch tomorrow's final,
but would instead enjoy the rest of the week touring Washington.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
dart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
