<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1114 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-BUDGET-N     05-31 1530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service has scheduled the following
entertainment/arts and travel articles this week for release
Sunday, June 4, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moving in `e' category)
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-OVERVIEW (New York) _ With the Tony awards just hours
away, New York Times theater critic Ben Brantley reviews the
theater season and concludes there is much to toast. (moved 5/31) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT30 sent on 5/30.
</P>
<P>
   TONYS-TV _ (New York) _ Anita Gates reports that the one-hour
preshow of the Tony Awards on Sunday night on PBS is gaining equal
footing with the two-hour ceremony on CBS. The title of the hour is
``The First 10 Awards: Tonys 2000.'' For the first time, Rosie
O'Donnell _ who is returning as host of the overall telecast _ will
be acting as live host of the first hour, and she'll have Nathan
Lane as a co-host. (moved 5/31)
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT19 sent on 5/30.
</P>
<P>
   TONYS-HERSCHER (New York) _ After a 50-year theatrical life
spanning several offstage careers _ as a general manager, a
producer, a music publisher, an agent _ Sylvia Herscher, 86, steps
into the spotlight Sunday night to receive a Tony award for
excellence. In a profile by Barry Singer, Jerry Herman, the
composer, describes her as the offstage embodiment of his greatest
leading lady, Dolly Levi. (moved 5/31) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT21 sent on 5/30.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-MUSICALS (New York) _ Wendy Wasserstein, the playwright,
believes that movie musicals defined romance and American
exuberance and are among the top ten reasons to live. She hopes
Kenneth Branagh's musical version of Shakespeare's ``Love's
Labour's Lost'' will introduce a new generation of moviegoers to
one of the best romantic comedies and some of the best songs ever
written.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-IMMIGRATION (New York) _ ``A Well-Founded Fear'' penetrates
the Immigration and Naturalization Service's confidential system of
granting or denying asylum to refugees. Samuel G. Freedman
interviews Michael Camerini and Shari Robertson, whose two-hour
documentary received its first critical acclaim at Sundance last
January, leading to its broadcast Monday night on PBS.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT20 sent on 5/30.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BARYSHNIKOV-RAINER-DANCE (Undated) _ Mikhail Baryshnikov, the
prince of Russian ballet, and Yvonne Rainer, the high priestess of
the American avant-garde, are rehearsing together for a season of
the White Oak Dance Project. How did it happen that Baryshnikov
asked Rainer, who had not choreographed a dance in decades, to
contribute to this program? Wendy Perron writes about the
commissioning of ``After Many a Summer Dies the Swan.'' (moved
5/30) With photos NYT27 and NYT28 sent on 5/30.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-FILMMAKERS (Undated) The need to discuss love and sex from
a female point of view coupled with a new freedom to do so seems to
be the launching pad for a gaggle of women-directed movies, many of
them first films, that portrays sex as both sadder and more
humorous than films made by males. Among the films that Molly
Haskell discusses are Colette Burson's ``Coming Soon,'' a female
rite-of-passage and right-to-orgasm film and ``The Virgin
Suicides,'' Sofia Coppola's recent adaptation of Jeffrey Eugenides'
1993 novel about five sisters. (moved 5/31)
</P>
<P>
   NUREYEV-FILM (New York) Friday through next Sunday the Film
Society of Lincoln Center presents ``This is Nureyev! A Weekend of
Dance on Film,'' a series of four programs that will be repeated on
June 16 and 17 at the Los Angeles County Museum of Art. Shot mostly
during the 1960s, when Nureyev was at his physical peak, the films
provide an intimate look at his extraordinary dancing prowess. They
also bear witness to Nureyev's ambitions for the ballet film. By
David Hay. (moved 5/31)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MASUR-PHILHARMONIC (New York) _ As Kurt Masur ends another
season with the New York Philharmonic Sunday night, he reflects on
his ``raw deal,'' the politics of the Philharmonic management, the
chairman's refusal to book him as a guest conductor after his
contract ends in two years and plans for a conducting tour marking
his 75th birthday in 2002. By James R. Oestreich. (moved 5/31)
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT31 sent on 5/30. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RAVE-FILM-MUSIC (Undated) ``Better Living Through Circuitry'' is
the latest of three new films, along with the recently released
``Human Traffic'' and ``Groove'' to celebrate the rave scene. A new
crop of moviemakers are attempting to portray the rave subculture
in all its optimistic blissed-out, trippy glee. By David Bahr.
(moved 5/30)
</P>
<P>
   YOGA-MUSIC (New York) _ Yoga Journal recently called Krishna Da
``The Pavarotti of Kirtan.'' His most popular album, ``Pilgrim
Heart'' (1996), has sold nearly 50,000 copies. He has sung with
Sting and instructed Madonna. ``I think it's perfectly natural that
a Westerner should go to India, soak it up and come back and then
work with the forms they've absorbed in this lifetime, which for me
was Little Anthony and the Imperials and rock 'n' roll,'' said the
artist who was born Jeffrey Kagel in Long Island in 1947. By Ann
Powers. (moved 5/31) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT22 sent on 5/30.
</P>
<P>
   HAYNES-DRUMS-MUSIC (Undated) _ Ben Ratliff profiles the drummer
Roy Haynes, 75, who has seen 50 years of change in jazz from the
best vantage point _ the back of the bandstand, the rhythm section.
He has played with practically everybody of major significance
since the 1940s _ from Louis Armstrong to Thelonious Monk to
Charlie Parker and worked with the vocalists Sarah Vaughan, Billie
Holliday and Ella Fitzgerald. A lot of that history can be heard on
his new disc on Verve/Universal called simply, ``The Roy Haynes
Trio.'' (moved 5/30)
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-EDUCATION (Cincinnati) _ Wes Craven's film ``Music of the
Heart'' and the new conservatory complex in Cincinnati tell us that
there is more to the current American classical-music scene than
empty seats and graying audiences. By David Schoenbaum. (moved
5/31)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ARTS-BRAZIL (Sao Paulo) _ In the largest city in Latin America's
largest country, cultural and business leaders wanted to
commemorate the 500th Anniversary of the Portuguese colonization of
Brazil and make a bold, sweeping statement about the state of the
arts in Brazil. They have. The megaexhibit contains 15,000 objects
in four buildings _ an area larger than the Louvre. By Larry
Rohter. (moved 5/31)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times Travel section highlights travel in New
England. The following stories have moved.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COOLIDGE-VERMONT (Undated) _ Christopher S. Wren visits
Plymouth Notch, the town known as Vermont's Brigadoon. This
community of clapboard farmhouses and weathered barns seems to have
changed little since Calvin Coolidge was sworn in here as president
on Aug. 23, 1923, at 2:47 a.m. The wood stove and the kerosene
light in his home and the modest cemetery holding six generations
of Coolidges speak volumes about the man known as ``Silent Cal.''
(moved 5/29)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-MAINE-WILDERNESS (Undated) _ Carey Goldberg asked the
question, ``How deep of a wilderness experience can be had in
Maine?'' and finds the answer. ``Pretty Deep.'' She writes of
hiking eight miles without meeting another person, flying over
lakes of pristine water, moose safaris and falling asleep in a yurt
to the sounds of ``a chorus of clacks and cheeps and peeps and
hoots ...'' (moved 5/29)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-PARKS-SMOG (Undated) _ As smog season begins, it is
likely that some of the country's most popular national parks,
especially in the east, will once again be troubled by haze and
smog rivaling the levels in crowded metropolitan areas. By John H.
Cushman Jr. (moved 5/29)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Paul Freireich answers readers' questions
on how to find a flight simulator, tickets to cricket matches in
London and botanical gardens with wheelchair access. (moved 5/30)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BARGAINS (Undated) _ Deals on travel to Japan, Los Cabos
in Mexico, barge trips in France and the Four Seasons Hotels.
(moved 5/30)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Printemps de Cahors arts festival in
France; a club style hotel in London; an online brokerage offers
frequent flier mileage; new guides to African-American sites in
North Carolina and Florida. (moved 5/30)
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ There are steps leisure travelers
can take to avoid traffic jams and noise. Among other things, Betsy
Wade advises that the practical traveler should avoid large numbers
of internal combustion engines such as the 250,000 motorcylists who
rolled into Myrtle Beach, S.C., for Harley-Davidson Week. (moved
5/30)
</P>
