<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1116 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TED-GIRLFRIEND01-COX     05-31 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TED-GIRLFRIEND01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Artist, sailor, pilot: She `has edge on Ted'
 &HT;    By Richard L. Eldredge
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   So who exactly is this woman that Ted Turner referred to Tuesday
as his ``girlfriend''? Anticipating your curiosity, Buzz spent some
time Wednesday digging up some facts on Frederique D'Arragon, the
50ish French-born artist who maintains homes in New York; Palm
Beach, Fla.; Rio de Janeiro, Brazil; and Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Porter Bibb, author of the biography ``Ted Turner: It Ain't as
Easy as It Looks,'' describes D'Arragon as independently wealthy,
intelligent and athletic.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's an artist and a very good sailor, pilot and polo
player,'' Bibb said in a telephone interview from New York. ``She's
probably the only woman who has got the edge on Ted, which
irritates him a lot. She's at least as smart and at least as good a
sailor as he is. She served on his crew on some of his
trans-Atlantic cruises in the '70s.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibb said D'Arragon (left) invited him to lunch when his book
was published in 1993 to ask for his help in setting up a gallery
showing of some of her work.
</P>
<P>
   ``She opened the portfolio, and the first thing she showed me
was a painting of Ted looking like Napoleon. The next ones were Ted
in historic poses as Admiral Nelson, Robert E. Lee and George
Washington. I asked her if Ted had seen these, and she said no. I
thought they would make great Christmas cards, but I couldn't help
her with a show. They were the kind of things you might see in Mad
magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Arragon has been on the fringes of Turner's life all during
the Jane Fonda era, Bibb said. ``They really have had this kind of
competition and friendship for more than 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibb, meanwhile, is less than convinced that a divorce is the
solution for Turner and Fonda. The author says he believes the
couple will reconcile. ``I've known Jane since she was in Vassar.
Jane is his perfect match, and Frederique is not the wifely type.
She's never been married; she's a free spirit, and she likes living
her own life.''
</P>
<P>
   Together again
</P>
<P>
   Possibly supporting that reconciliation theory, Turner and Fonda
sat at adjacent tables Wednesday at CNN's annual ``World Report''
Conference at the Omni Hotel and greeted each other cordially with
mutual cheek kisses.
</P>
<P>
   Fonda showed international journalists a 15-minute film she
recently made in Nigeria about programs that empower adolescent
girls. ``The world is not a girl-friendly place,'' said Fonda, who
founded the Georgia Campaign for Adolescent Pregnancy Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, Turner spoke to the ``World Report''
Conference, focusing on several of his favorite topics, including
nuclear disarmament, overpopulation and extinction of species.
</P>
<P>
   He said that on a recent visit to Russia, he was taken to
``Rocket Headquarters'' outside Moscow, the place where the Soviets
would have launched a nuclear attack against the United States.
Instead of a map of the United States on the wall, there was a sign
reading ``Welcome Ted Turner,'' but he was still warned by his
hosts: ``Don't push any buttons.''
</P>
<P>
   Contributing: Phil Kloer, Don O'Briant and news services. If you
have a tip, call 404-222-8503 or 404-614-2749. Or fax 404-526-5509.
Or e-mail: buzz(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   For more juicy gossip and keen commentary, see what Vixana has
to say on ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Richard L. Eldredge writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
