<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PUTIN-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUMA GIVES OK TO DRAFT OF PUTIN'S PLAN TO CONCENTRATE POWER IN
KREMLIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's lower house of parliament ignored misgivings
by political analysts and democracy advocates Wednesday and
resoundingly endorsed a first draft of President Vladimir Putin's
plan to concentrate state power in the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   The wave of support strongly suggested that Russia's upper house
of parliament, the Federation Council _ which stands to lose much
of its power to the Kremlin should the plan pass _ will be more or
less helpless to do anything about it.
</P>
<P>
   The lower house, or Duma, passed the first reading of Putin's
three-law proposal by a vote of 362-34.
</P>
<P>
   Nikolai Petrov, an expert on Russian regional political
structure at the Moscow Center of the Carnegie Endowment for
International Peace, said Wednesday night that the vote showed
Putin has control of the parliament firmly in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``His calculation was rather correct, and the Duma is clearly
backing the president in this,'' he said. ``It means it's very easy
for him to deal with the Federation Council.''
</P>
<P>
   Two more readings will occur in late June before the bills reach
a final vote, and once amendments are offered, that bloc of support
might split. But as long as the Kremlin keeps 300 votes in the
Duma, it can override any changes that the Federation Council might
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's proposals take dead aim at the governors who lead
Russia's 89 regions, a group which gained considerable independence
under President Boris Yeltsin and represents the major challenge
these days to Kremlin authority.
</P>
<P>
   His legislation would oust the governors from their guaranteed
seats on the Federation Council, where they hold 50 percent of the
vote, and also remove the local legislative leaders _often the
governors' allies _ who hold the remaining seats.
</P>
<P>
   They would be replaced by senators chosen by local legislatures
in a secret ballot.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday in the regional capital of Yaroslavl, Putin went a
step further, suggesting that a region's representation in the
Federation Council should be proportional to its contribution to
the federal till. Currently the council is composed of two
representatives from each region.
</P>
<P>
   In his proposal to parliament, Putin also seeks the authority to
remove governors if they pursue policies counter to federal law,
and to name a replacement of his own choosing. Some of these
firings would require a court hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Among other initiatives, the proposed laws would give governors
and regional legislatures the power to fire local officials who
violate laws, but give the president the right to name replacements
until new elections can be held.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has made restoring central authority a centerpiece of his
new presidency, and almost everyone here agrees, in principle. that
the Kremlin's grip on the levers of federalism is too weak. But
many are just as adamant that the latest plan moves much too far
toward making Putin or any successor not a democratic president,
but a Latin-style strongman.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin's plans are politically potent not just because they
would dilute the governors' influence in Moscow, but because they
also would give Putin powerful weapons to use against them. If the
threat of removal from office were not enough, the governors also
would lose the current immunity from criminal prosecution should
they lose their legislative seats.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Kremlin also moved this month to carve Russia into seven
federal administrative regions, each to be overseen from a regional
capital by a Kremlin appointee answerable only to the president.
</P>
<P>
   Putin called the move, which he says does not need parliament's
approval, an effort to streamline an unwieldy federal bureaucracy.
But he has staffed the regions mostly with former officials of the
military and the federal intelligence services. More than a few see
in that a plan to rebuild federal offices in the regions into
centers of authoritarian control. One of the most visible critics
has been a business tycoon and Duma member, Boris Berezovsky, who
has often been called a behind-the-scenes power broker in the
Kremlin, both in former President Boris Yeltsin's administration
and in Putin's.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview published Wednesday in the weekly journal
Argumenty I Fakty, Berezovsky characterized Putin's plans as
well-intended but potentially fatal to representative democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, almost all of us have lived the greater part of
our lives in conditions of a totalitarian regime. The most baleful
consequence of this is the development of a psychology of slaves in
people,'' he said. ``But during the past 10 years, millions of
people, as a result of new, sometimes cruel and tragic
circumstances, have learned to stop counting on anybody's help.''
</P>
<P>
   Adopting Putin's plan to re-establish a powerful center, he
said, ``will strike a crushing blow at the changed consciousness of
millions of people, this main accomplishment of recent years.''
Berezovsky voted against the legislation Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
