<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1118 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-PADRE-ISLAND-(2100-2n     05-31 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PADRE-ISLAND-(2100-2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GEM OF THE TEXAS COAST OFFERS GREAT BIRDING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH PADRE ISLAND, Texas: tanagers, kingbirds and vireos. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You'll hardly even need binoculars _ although they become
essential, once you're hooked _ to enjoy the feathered wonders seen
from the Laguna Madre Nature Trail adjacent to the island's
convention center, just north of town. (You can't miss the
building, painted with giant killer whales by the nature artist
known simply as Weyland.)
</P>
<P>
   Take a stroll on the nature trail boardwalk, which crosses a few
feet above a combination of tidal mud flat, freshwater marsh and
salt marsh _ keep an eye out for resident alligators _ and extends
dramatically a few hundred yards to the bay waters regularly called
the Laguna Madre. Along the route, you're nearly guaranteed
sightings (depending on season, of course) of deeply pink roseate
spoonbills, great blue herons, black and yellow rails, peregrine
falcons, warblers, buntings and orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as prolific as bird species and birders are places to
camp along the copious birding trails. Travelers craving more
comfort have plenty of motels and condos to choose from on the
island and in the dozen or so Valley towns. But for an
unforgettable experience combining luxury and birding, nothing
compares to a stay at the Inn at Chachalaca Bend.
</P>
<P>
   Opened in May 1999, the six-room bed-and-breakfast inn for
birders rests inside 40 acres of natural landscape at Los Fresnos,
20 miles inland from South Padre Island. Its positioning in a bend
of the peaceful and lazy Resaca del las Antonias, a saltwater oxbow
fed by other waterways that eventually flow into the Laguna Madre,
is prized for its seclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Transformed from a 1970s family home in an impressive,
million-dollar renovation, the gorgeous inn is named for the
resident chachalaca, a rather regal brush bird native to South
Texas and Mexico. You'll wake in the morning, beneath plush Laura
Ashley bedding, to the chachalaca's wild clucking, and you can hike
along a 14-acre nature trail to custom-built blinds to watch it _
and dozens of other birds _ eat at a little pond created just for
feathered friends.
</P>
<P>
   Sunrises at Chachalaca Bend are great for climbing the
observation tower to look for alligators and turtles in the Resaca,
and sunsets are perfect for sitting at the gazebo next to a large
brushy prairie's pond to watch Altamira orioles, green jays,
buff-bellied hummingbirds, great kiskadees, ringed kingfishers and
roseate spoonbills. At night, you can review the day's sightings
over a glass of wine beside one of the landscaped fire pits.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to pull away from the flagstone patios and mahogany
verandas, shaded by white-bloomed olive trees and giant palms, but
it's only a 15-minute shot north to the grand Laguna Atascosa
National Wildlife Refuge. The 45,000-acre preserve on the Laguna
Madre is the Rio Grande Valley's largest protected habitat, with
nearly 400 recorded bird species. It's open daily and has hundreds
of miles of foot and driving routes on which to see everything from
vermilion fly-catchers to long-billed thrashers.
</P>
<P>
   One more group of nature lovers is drawn to the calm Laguna
Madre: saltwater fly-fishing enthusiasts, many of whom come from as
far as Alaska and New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fly-fishing gives so much more dimension to the sport; once
you catch fish on a fly rod, you'll never fish any other way,''
says Pete Moore, a South Padre Island attorney and president and
founder of the Laguna Madre Fly Fishing Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something so aesthetically pleasing about seeing that
line when it's being cast,'' Moore says.
</P>
<P>
   Moore refers fly-fishing inquiries to such experts as Larry
Haines, owner of a fishing shop in Port Isabel and a noted
fly-fishing artist who paints commissioned works in pastels or
oils.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Haines spends perhaps 300 days each year outfitting
fly-fishing clients, teaching newcomers how to cast or serving as a
fishing guide. He says the fishing is good year-round _ with
catches ranging from redfish, trout and tarpon to snook, kingfish
and dorado _ but that fall is prime time. He likes to paddle his
kayak into the bay, a tactic that makes for easy sneaking up on the
fish.
</P>
<P>
   Haines also cites a surging interest among women in fly-fishing,
noting that even his wife wouldn't fish with him on lures, but she
goes fly-fishing all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the essence of fly-fishing that appeals to women, I
think,'' Haines says. ``You don't need strength _ it's just in
timing. It's a beautiful thing.''
</P>
<P>
   And you can be certain it's more soothing than wandering into a
tequila-shooting contest.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO STAY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For island lodging, booking well in advance is advised.
</P>
<P>
   Inn at Chachalaca Bend, Los Fresnos: (956) 233-1180, (888)
612-6800; www.chachalaca.com. Rooms are $150-$195 and include wine,
beer, snacks and a lavish breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Kingfisher Inn and Guide Service, Rio Hondo: (956) 748-4350;
new, two-room bed-and-breakfast lodging and fly-fishing guide
service. Rooms start at $70.
</P>
<P>
   Casa de Siesta Bed &AMP; Breakfast, South Padre Island, (956)
761-5656; new, 12-room adobe inn filled with Mexican and New
Mexican furnishings. Rooms start at $100.
</P>
<P>
   Brown Pelican Inn, South Padre Island, (956) 761-2722;
eight-room inn on the Laguna Madre. Rooms are $73-$115.
</P>
<P>
   New chain lodgings with good introductory rates include Super 8
Motel, (800) 800-8000; Ramada Limited, (800) 2-RAMADA; and Howard
Johnson, (956) 761-5658.
</P>
<P>
   For condo reservations, call Island Services, (800) 426-6530 or
Padre Island Rentals, (800) 926-6926.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: South Padre Island is roughly a 10- or 11-hour
drive from Fort Worth-Dallas. Direct and nonstop flights to
Brownsville and Harlingen put you within a 30-minute to one-hour
drive of the island. All major car rental agencies are available,
and shuttle services charge about $30 each way.
</P>
<P>
   Guides and tours: Fin to Feather Tours, South Padre Island,
offers birding and dolphin-watching tours daily by appointment.
Fees are typically $17.50-$22.50 per person for two to three hours.
(956) 943-BIRD; www.fin2feather.com.
</P>
<P>
   For fly-fishing, there's The Shop, Larry Haines' fly shop and
art gallery, Port Isabel, (956) 943-1785. Guides recommended by the
Laguna Madre Fly Fishing Association also include Eric Glass, (956)
761-2878; Skipper Ray, (956) 943-2798; and Scott Sparrow, (956)
748-4350.
</P>
<P>
   What else to do:
</P>
<P>
   Laguna Atascosa National Wildlife Refuge: (956) 748-3607. Open
dawn until dusk, with visitor center open seasonally.
</P>
<P>
   Sea Turtle Inc.: Founded by turtle philanthropist Ila Loetscher
_ also lovingly called the Turtle Lady _ this foundation helps
preserve and protect the Kemp's ridley sea turtle. A center is
being built just beyond the island's convention center, but a
temporary place to take turtle tours, at 10 a.m. on Tuesday and
Saturday, is at 6617 Padre Blvd. on South Padre Island; (956)
761-1720.
</P>
<P>
   Island Equestrian: Daily horseback rides on the sand are for
ages 6 and up. Look a few miles north of the convention center,
across from the county beach park, (956) 761-4677.
</P>
<P>
   Gladys Porter Zoo: Rated annually as one of the nation's top 10
zoos, this Brownsville jewel offers natural habitats showcasing
1,800 birds, mammals and reptiles from Asia, Africa, Australia,
Indonesia and other tropical areas. (956) 546-2177.
</P>
<P>
   For more info: South Padre Island Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau,
(800) 767-2373.; www.sopadre.com
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
