<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1119 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-PADRE-ISLAND-(2100-2T     05-31 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PADRE-ISLAND-(2100-2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GEM OF THE TEXAS COAST OFFERS GREAT BIRDING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JUNE NAYLOR RODRIGUEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH PADRE ISLAND, Texas _ Nearly the moment the Laguna Skimmer
pulls away from its slip at the Sea Ranch Marina, first mate
Scarlet Colley points at the sea-grass beds. There, paddling along
the water, are mother grebes, seabirds that look a lot like loons
and carry as many as three babies on their backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``And look, look!'' she adds with glee, as though she doesn't do
this every single day. ``See the red-breasted merganser? Isn't it
beautiful?''
</P>
<P>
   Colley is equally giddy over the native skimmer, with orange
legs and beak, which feeds while in flight by dropping its lower
mandible into the water. And just beyond the grasses and mangroves
that protect the shoreline, she watches for her ``babies,'' the
bottlenose dolphins that live and play in the tranquil Laguna
Madre, which separates South Padre Island from mainland Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It's a typical tour for this naturalist and her husband, George
Colley _ but it's light-years away from the human wildlife scene a
short distance down the island in spring. March, in fact, might be
the one time you'd avoid South Padre Island _ unless you're one of
the 175,000 college kids who enjoy spring break there, or you enjoy
their company.
</P>
<P>
   But, though many people associate South Padre solely with the
annual ritual of spring break, Texas' southernmost point has a lot
more going for it than tequila shots and boomboxes blaring the
latest Limp Bizkit hit.
</P>
<P>
   The other 11 months of the year are blissfully quiet around this
skinny, condo-lined spit of tortilla-hued sand, edged by a blue
bay, thick sea oats and crashing waves. And they're ideal for a
different kind of beach invader: the wildlife lover.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers can enjoy greater dolphin watching, birding and
fly-fishing than can be found anyplace else in Texas _ or the
entire Gulf Coast. The bonus, on and near the island, is a booming
choice in places to stay, ranging from upscale hotels and condo
developments to several new budget-priced motels and a quickly
growing bed-and-breakfast industry.
</P>
<P>
   Savvy travelers are finding experienced guides like the Colleys,
outfitters who take individuals or small groups onto the gentle
shallows of Laguna Madre. Calling themselves Fin to Feather Tours,
the naturalist team caters to novice watchers and skilled wildlife
photographers.
</P>
<P>
   With infectious enthusiasm, the couple share stories from five
years of filming and studying approximately 150 dolphins almost
daily. Unlike Sea World and other dolphin tours, they neither play
with nor feed the dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are wild, and we don't want to change them in any way,''
says Scarlet Colley, who, with her husband, teaches nature classes
at the nearby Pan-Am Coastal Studies Lab. ``They don't need food to
be interested in us. They're so curious, they come to us anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   In the course of a two- to three-hour tour, Scarlet and George
note with glee the surfacing of everyone from Can Opener, Natcho,
Cookie and Nipper to Titan and Baby. They've established dozens of
dolphins' identities by their dorsal fin shapes and markings, and
they easily rattle off fascinating tales, like the one about Baby,
who was orphaned before her mama taught her self-defense, and thus
lost part of a fin to a boat propeller.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the fun is watching the sleek, gray mammals in their
everyday joy. They jump boat wakes in perfect arches and often
cavort in pairs or threesomes, playing some kind of hopscotch over
one another or planting a kiss on each other midleap. They don't
need trainers; this is what they do naturally.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, watch for interaction between dolphins and birds. The
luckiest photographer might capture a dolphin tossing a fish
skyward to feed a hovering royal tern: nature in a moment of
entertainment and balance.
</P>
<P>
   The Colleys' birding tours have become as popular as the
dolphin-watching trips, Scarlet says. She has documented more than
50 bird species in Laguna Madre, which is hardly surprising when
you consider the overwhelming importance of the Rio Grande Valley
in the birding world.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of birds use the area as a refueling and resting stop
between homes in North and South or Central America. Of the
hundreds of species documented here, more than 30 are found no
other place in the United States. Experts point out that the four
Valley counties have more bird species than most states.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rio Grande Valley is the No. 1 birding destination in the
U.S.,'' says Madge Lindsay, the state parks' project leader for the
future World Birding Center. ``It's on every serious bird-watcher's
list of places to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The World Birding Center will offer classes to aid the dedicated
birder as well as help the neophyte get started. Scheduled for a
2002 opening, the WBC will cover 10 sites in the Valley, with the
headquarters adjacent to Benson State Park at Mission, and it will
offer three nature lodges for overnight stays.
</P>
<P>
   In April, birders make their own migrations south for the Great
Texas Birding Classic, the nation's longest competitive
bird-watching event. Dozens of teams _ as well as thousands of
noncompetitive ``avi-tourists,'' as the tourism officials call them
_ flock from around the United States, Canada and Europe to see the
spring flight of birds to Gulf Coast marshes, estuaries, islands
and brushy woods. In addition to superb sightings of 350 or so
species each year, the event has raised $150,000 in four years to
buy and improve thousands of acres of bird habitats.
</P>
<P>
   The birders spend nearly two weeks navigating their way up the
Great Texas Coastal Birding Trail, a route that spans the
624-mile-long Texas Gulf Coast. Distinctive brown markers along the
way make it easy for birders to log their sightings.
</P>
<P>
   And no birder can do without the Rio Grande Valley Birding Map,
available at tourism offices throughout the area. Pinpointing 80
``hot spots'' in the Valley and on the lower coast, it provides
specific directions to such places as the Falcon State Park near
Roma, Sacahuista Flats near Port Mansfield and Tres Corrales Pond
near Raymondville. Even better, the map describes specific birds
found at those spots.
</P>
<P>
   A sensible stop _ No. 73 on this giant map _ for easy birding is
the island itself. In the Black Mangrove Tidal Flat, sitting right
at the island end of the long Queen Isabella Causeway that connects
the mainland, searchers find reddish egrets and American
oystercatchers. On the jetties at the island's south end, find
loons, gannets and frigate birds. And in vacant residential lots,
which local birders have managed to keep the city from mowing,
you'll find thrush, tanagers, kingbirds and vireos. MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
