A1120 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TRANSPLANT01-COX     05-31 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRANSPLANT01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Experts exploring ethical questions in live organ gifts
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Atlantan Curt Bludworth willingly gave up a portion of his
liver to a stranger May 12, he added to the ethical complexities
confronting transplant surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, it was kidneys that relatives eagerly parted
with to save the life of a loved one. Now it's livers being shared
between strangers. What's next in this brave new world of living
organ donors, and who _ if anyone _ is overseeing it?
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored by the National Kidney Foundation and the American
Society of Transplant Surgeons, the first national discussion to
begin sorting through the ethical, medical and legal aspects of
living donation is under way today in Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   About 125 transplant surgeons, medical ethicists, social workers
and organ donors and recipients are mulling the dilemmas that have
arisen as more healthy people undergo risky surgery to donate
organs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transplant community has a responsibility to look at all
the issues raised by living donors,'' said Dr. Francis Delmonico,
director of renal transplantation at Boston's Massachusetts General
Hospital. ``The information we give our donors is critical to their
decision to proceed with the transplant or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Transplants from living donors tripled from 1989 to 1998,
according to the United Network for Organ Sharing. In 1998, there
were 4,273 living donors, and one in five transplanted organs came
from a live person. Kidneys and portions of livers and lungs are
the organs most commonly taken from a healthy person. They are
reattached inside a critically ill person who could have died
waiting for an organ from the traditional source, the deceased.
</P>
<P>
   About 68,000 Americans are waiting for an organ transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors predict living donations could radically change the
field of transplantation. Nearly half the kidneys used at leading
transplant centers are coming from living donors, most of them
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The laparoscopic technique used in kidney transplants poses far
less risk compared to living liver transplants, in which at least
one donor, possibly two, has died as a result of the lengthy and
invasive surgery.
</P>
<P>
   However, there is no federal oversight of living donors and no
private group that tracks the long-term health of living donors or
recipients. UNOS regulates only those organs coming from the
deceased.
</P>
<P>
   Transplant centers have been left to sort through the myriad
issues raised by living donors, such as assessing risk and benefit
and what constitutes informed consent.
</P>
<P>
   Only one rule is common to both kinds of transplants _ it is
against federal law to buy and sell organs.
</P>
<P>
   Most perplexing to centers is how to handle individuals such as
Bludworth, the ``good Samaritan'' donors who offer to put
themselves through surgery and recuperation for altruistic reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally, living donors have always been someone in the
family, so they received some of the benefit from the risk of
undergoing the surgery,'' says Jeffrey Kahn, director of the Center
for Bioethics at the University of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``But altruistic strangers represent a complete splitting of
this risk and benefit. ... How much risk are we willing to put a
donor through to benefit a recipient?''
</P>
<P>
   After the conference, public hearings will be conducted on
proposals. Recommendations are expected by September.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Guthrie writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
