<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1122 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-SYRIA-ART-510&AMP;     05-31 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SYRIA-ART-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYRIA SATISFIED WITH ISRAELI EXIT FROM LEBANON, U.N. AIDE
INDICATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also ISRAEL-U.N.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHABAA, Lebanon _ Syria is ready to accept Israel's retreat last
week from southern Lebanon as a complete withdrawal, a United
Nations envoy said Wednesday, perhaps easing concerns that violence
along the Israeli-Lebanese border might resume.
</P>
<P>
   After a meeting in Damascus, the envoy, Terje Roed-Larsen, said
he and Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa of Syria were in ``full
agreement on every matter'' concerning the withdrawal and could
decide soon how to deploy more U.N. peacekeeping troops in southern
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, he added, the Syrians agreed with a U.N. report
issued last week that said that Israel does not have to give up a
contested piece of territory of about 10 square miles at the far
southeastern corner of Lebanon _ land called Shebaa Farms _ in
order to comply with U.N. Resolution 425.
</P>
<P>
   That Security Council resolution dates from the 1982 Israeli
invasion of Lebanon and calls for Israel's withdrawal from land it
occupied at that time.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Shebaa Farms was occupied by Israel in 1967, after its
war with its Arab neighbors, and Israel has argued it is not
covered by Resolution 425.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement from Roed-Larsen suggested that Syria, which
exercises ultimate military and political control over Lebanon, has
decided to avoid a potentially costly escalation in tensions in the
Middle East by not challenging the United Nations over verification
of Israel's withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   But the reaction in Lebanon was confused. The government and the
armed Hezbollah militia have threatened to continue attacking
Israeli targets if Shebaa Farms is not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon's prime minister, Selim al-Hoss, issued a statement
saying that he had also talked with Sharaa and was told that Syria
supports Lebanon's claim to Shebaa Farms. The official Syrian news
agency SANA also reported that Shara called on Israel to withdraw
from Shebaa Farms, either unilaterally or in accordance with other
U.N. resolutions related to Arab land it occupied in the 1967
Arab-Israeli war.
</P>
<P>
   A Hezbollah spokesman in Beirut said the militia was not ready
to comment on the statement by Roed-Larsen.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent conflict over whether Syria does or does not back
the Lebanese and Hezbollah position is more than a matter of
semantics.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of Hezbollah, the main guerrilla movement in the south,
have said they will not abandon their war until Israel gives up
Shebaa Farms, a mountainous stretch of land at the base of Mount
Hermon in the Golan Heights, and releases all Lebanese held in
Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese government, which has permitted the Iranian-backed
Islamic militia to operate freely in the south and has lauded it as
a national liberation force, has echoed the Hezbollah threats.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, both the government and Hezbollah are
tightly tied to Syria, which has some 30,000 soldiers and an
undisclosed number of intelligence agents in Lebanon. So a Syrian
decision to accept Israel's withdrawal as full compliance with
Resolution 425 would obligate both Lebanon and the militia to
follow suit.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That Israel occupies Shebaa Farms, a stretch of land that
overlooks the Golan Heights and South Lebanon, is not in dispute.
The issue is the timing of Israel's occupation. It was seized in
1967, 15 years before the Israeli invasion of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the U.N. resolutions are concerned, Shebaa Farms is
part of the land Israel seized from Syria along with the Golan
Heights. Lebanese officials have said they want all their land
restored, regardless of when it was occupied.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials, including Roed-Larsen, have said recently that
the ownership of Shebaa Farms is a matter to be decided between
Syria and Lebanon. The two countries have never agreed on an
international border between them.
</P>
<P>
   Shebaa Farms is a rocky mountainous tract along Lebanon's
southeastern border, strategic not only because it provides a view
onto the Golan Heights but also over south Lebanon and the Bekaa
Valley that runs between Syria and Lebanon. Seven small rivers that
feed into the Jordan River before it flows past Israel all converge
in a depression of the Shebaa Farms land.
</P>
<P>
   Before the 1967 war, the land contained a series of family-owned
farms where Lebanese peasants grew wheat and grazed their
livestock. But two weeks after the June 1967 war ended, Shebaa
Farms became a new battleground, its farmers driven from their
fields and homes by Israeli soldiers seeking a vantage point to
watch for incursions by Palestinian militants operating from south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed Ali, now 75, lived through the Israeli invasion. In an
interview in his home in Shebaa, a village perched on the hillside
just west of the farms, Ali said he remembers that he and his
relatives were harvesting their summer wheat when Israeli soldiers
appeared and sprayed the fields with machine-gun fire.
</P>
<P>
   One of Ali's cousins was killed. ``Then they made everyone leave
their homes and they destroyed them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His nephew, Yehiya Ali, has been collecting deeds and other
documents from the displaced owners of land in Shebaa Farms for the
past 15 years _ an effort that so annoyed the Israeli occupation
forces in southern Lebanon that they threw him in prison in 1987
for one week.
</P>
<P>
   Ali, who moved from Shebaa to Beirut two years after his
imprisonment and returned home only last week, has now revived his
effort to reclaim his family's land. He said some 10,000 Lebanese
used to live year-round on the land, including his own extended
family, and another 1,000 families farmed plots there but lived in
the town of Shebaa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know this land is ours and it belongs to Lebanon,'' he said
Wednesday as he spread the documents out on a table in his uncle's
home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
