<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1123 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-RAUSCHENBERG-PAINTING     05-31 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAUSCHENBERG-PAINTINGS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ARTIST   SHUFFLES,   THEN DEALS   A RAUSCHENBERG 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 17 and NYT18 is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a freshly painted warehouse on a quiet street in
the Long Island City section of Queens one recent spring evening,
passersby could glimpse an odd assortment of recognizable faces.
Chuck Close was hobnobbing with Michael Ovitz. Ileana Sonnabend,
the octogenarian gallery owner, was there along with the soprano
Renee Fleming, Mike Wallace of ``60 Minutes,'' the art critic
Robert Hughes, the singer and former Talking Head David Byrne, the
choreographer Merce Cunningham, the curator Walter Hopps, Martha
Stewart, the designer Edwin Schlossberg and Mathilde Krim, the
founding chairwoman of the American Foundation for AIDS Research.
</P>
<P>
   The host was easy to spot. Clad in a cream-colored linen suit,
Robert Rauschenberg, the 75-year-old artist, was boisterously
greeting his guests. Some were old friends, he said; others he had
never met before.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people aren't friends or allies or conspirators or
comforters,'' said Rauschenberg. ``They are a group of people
picked for their diverse interests.'' At the artist's side was his
dealer, Arne Glimcher, who is chairman of the PaceWildenstein
Gallery, along with Maxwell L. Anderson, director of the Whitney
Museum of American Art. Also present were Leonard A. Lauder, the
Whitney's chairman, and Marla Prather, the museum's curator of
postwar art.
</P>
<P>
   The guests had been invited to take part in what Rauschenberg
called a game of visual gambling. But the setting looked more like
a dinner party than a casino, what with a jazz duo playing in the
background, a bar, a buffet and tables decorated with vases of
peonies. Lining the walls of the warehouse were 52 panels, each
nine and a half feet high but varying in width. All were adorned
with hand-painted passages as well as Rauschenberg's familiar
photographic images: everything from a Coca-Cola bottle to a fire
hydrant to an automobile tire.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the panels form ``Synapsis Shuffle,'' the artist's
latest work, which extends more than 220 feet and is his biggest
after ``The 1/4 Mile or 2 Furlong Piece,'' a work in progress that,
at last count, was made up of 206 panels.
</P>
<P>
   Like a deck of cards, the panels of ``Synapsis Shuffle'' are
meant to be assembled by a different group of people every time
they are shown so the work will never be seen the same way twice.
The 12 guests were the first to create a version of ``Synapsis
Shuffle'' for an exhibition opening at the Whitney on June 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the exercise,'' Rauschenberg said, is to ``share the
decisions artists have to make themselves when creating a work of
art.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the piece is really about the element of chance,'' he
added. ``At first I thought we should ask the first 12 taxi drivers
who passed the museum to put panels together. Instead, we chose
people with diverse interests to encourage as much controversy as
possible. Even though everyone can trade panels like baseball
cards, the evening may end in a fistfight. I guess this is bringing
out the devil in me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Synapsis Shuffle'' took a year to complete, and Rauschenberg
said he envisioned that it would end up in a number of different
collections. That is, until Glimcher approached the Whitney, hoping
the museum might purchase the entire work. Glimcher, Lauder and
Prather traveled to Rauschenberg's studio in Captiva Island, Fla.,
where they tried to put together ``Synapsis Shuffle'' themselves.
By the end of the visit, Lauder had agreed to buy the work, which
experts say is worth $9 million to $10 million. He has made it a
promised gift to the Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walking into Bob's studio was like walking into a fairyland,''
Lauder recalled. ``Lined up on the walls were 52 individual
masterpieces. I felt it was vital for the museum to have something
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as all the guests had been given a chance to study the
panels, Prather announced the rules of the evening: In order to
produce 12 compositions from the 52 panels in a way that was fair
to everyone, the participants _ in alphabetical order _ drew a
series of numbered tags from a silver hat belonging to
Rauschenberg; the numbers drawn indicated how many panels each
person could work with _ from three to seven _ and in what order
each would choose panels.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the participants were visibly anxious about what
numbers they would pick, Sonnabend was not, having plotted her
strategy well in advance. ``I'm going to choose the panels that are
left over,'' she said. ``For years after a show I'd always buy what
nobody else wanted. They were always the most difficult pieces, but
in the end they became the strongest.''
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz was intent on putting together as coherent a composition
as possible. The first panel he chose had a blank canvas propped on
an easel on its top portion and the image of a closed, shuttered
door below. ``I love the concept of the blank easel,'' he said.
``Now the problem is to find something to go with it.''
</P>
<P>
   As Rauschenberg predicted, bartering was inevitable. Wallace
wanted one of Close's panels because the composition worked
especially well with another he had selected. After considerable
haggling the two cut a deal: Close agreed to relinquish one of his
panels to Wallace if he would promise in writing that Morley Safer
would not be allowed to do any more art segments on ``60 Minutes''
or ``CBS News Sunday Morning.'' A sheet of paper was produced, and
the agreement was drawn up and signed. Only then was the desired
panel turned over to Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the participants had strong ideas about how they wanted
their works to look. Krim, for example, chose two of her allotted
three panels because she said they were colorful and full of life:
the images included a crowd scene, a crowded bus and a field of
flowers. But somewhere in her composition she wanted to show
desolation and emptiness to symbolize the devastation of AIDS. With
Rauschenberg's permission, she turned the panel she liked least
backward, so that it faced the wall. The back of the canvas, with
its metal stretchers, resembled a ladder, and Glimcher pointed out
that her composition was similar to a 1959 painting by Rauschenberg
called ``Winter Pool,'' which incorporates a ladder between two
panels.
</P>
<P>
   Krim wasn't the only person with a mind of her own. Once she had
selected her allotted four panels, Fleming decided they looked best
turned horizontally rather than vertically. She asked
Rauschenberg's permission. Again it was granted.
</P>
<P>
   Others made an effort to create compositions that were in
keeping with the artist's spirit. Byrne asked if he could use the
silver hat in his composition. ``It's a Bob thing,'' he said
referring to the artist's use of found objects.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   One of the quietest participants was Cunningham. He made his
selections in much the same way he said he has choreographed his
dances for the last 40 years: by tossing a set of eight-sided dice
he found in a notions store in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always take them with me when I'm on tour,'' Cunningham
said. ``Like the I Ching, I make a number of separate maneuvers
using this chance operation. It's a game, but it's a wonderful
game. Like a gambler I accept whatever comes up.''
</P>
<P>
   But the four panels in his effort _ with imagery ranging from an
Indian in full headdress to a lily pond _ seemed to belong together
in terms of their color scheme and composition.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   When ``Synapsis Shuffle'' is assembled at the Whitney _ the
museum is devoting the entire second floor to showing it _ labels
will credit each person's composition. When it comes down on Oct.
8, it will be lent to other museums. Each time it is, it will be
assembled by a different group of people invited by the artist.
</P>
<P>
   When the evening wound down and all the participants had
finished assembling their panels, Rauschenberg seemed pleased with
the outcome. Several days later he was uncharacteristically coy
when asked to critique the group's work, saying simply that ``some
did better than others.''
</P>
<P>
   He did add, however, that one day ``Synapsis Shuffle'' would
enable him to play out one of his greatest fantasies: ``to walk
into someone's home or into a museum and be able to say, `Gosh,
that's the worst Rauschenberg I've ever seen.'''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
