<SLUG> BC-DAIMLER-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHER INTEREST FORCES AUTOMAKER TO END LOW-RATE LOANS
</HEADLINE>
 By KEITH BRADSHER  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Feeling the effects of rising interest rates,
DaimlerChrysler announced on Wednesday that it would eliminate most
low-rate loans on new Chrysler, Dodge and Plymouth automobiles on
June 1 and instead offer bigger cash rebates to consumers and new
discounts to dealers.
</P>
<P>
   For most models, DaimlerChrysler currently offers customers a
choice of a cash rebate or a loan at a subsidized rate. During
June, however, the automaker will stop offering low-rate loans on a
national basis, although it will still make them available in some
very competitive regional markets, notably in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler's shift is an indication that the Federal
Reserve's six increases in short-term interest rates are beginning
to put pressure on the auto industry. Economists say that one
reason the Fed's rate increases have not had more effect on auto
sales until now is that automakers have been offsetting the higher
rates. Automakers make low-rate loans available by paying subsidies
to banks and other providers of car loans.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers say that the Fed's rate increases have begun to slow
auto sales, with the industry likely to post May results on
Thursday that will show the first drop in year-to-year sales since
the summer of 1998, when a strike crippled General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   While the drop is expected to be just 2 percent or so, and while
sales remain at a level that would have been considered extremely
strong until the last couple of years, the drop could nonetheless
be a sign that the auto market has turned.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's rate increases have led to increases in retail loans,
making it very expensive for automakers to hold down rates on auto
loans through subsidies to lenders, said Theodor R. Cunningham,
DaimlerChrysler's executive vice president for global sales and
marketing. DaimlerChrysler anticipates that short-term rates will
rise another half a percentage point to a full percentage point by
the end of this year, which could have made low-rate loans even
more expensive if the company had not switched to a greater
reliance on rebates, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of a long-term strategy of shifting to get our
investment in incentives directly into the hands of consumers
instead of financial institutions,'' Cunningham said. The new
policy on incentives will be in effect throughout June.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham said that it was not possible to calculate the effect
of the new policy on the company's total costs for discounts. The
discounts will be based on how many more vehicles each dealership
sells in June than in previous months.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler had very few incentives in May, only to see
sales plunge 15 percent in the weeks leading up to the Memorial Day
weekend. Joseph Phillippi, an auto analyst at PaineWebber, said
that while DaimlerChrysler's new approach would raise the company's
costs, it might be cheaper than a return to the discount programs
that DaimlerChrysler had earlier this year and which the Ford Motor
Co. and GM continue to offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to scratch your head and wonder what's going to
happen when we have even a 5 percent downturn, which is not that
big _ it's going to get ugly out there,'' Phillippi said.
</P>
<P>
   GM and Ford officials said that they would study
DaimlerChrysler's approach. Foreign automakers offer fewer rebates,
preferring to set prices in line with market demand instead of
setting prices high and then discounting them.
</P>
<P>
   The new DaimlerChrysler rebates for consumers are the largest
for models that have not been updated for several years and are
about to be replaced. The rebate on the Chrysler Town &AMP; Country
minivan, for example, rises to $2,000 from an already hefty $1,750.
DaimlerChrysler also announced a $1,000 rebate on Dodge Durango
sport utility vehicles with 4.7-liter and 5.2-liter engines and a
$2,000 rebate on Durangos with 5.8-liter engines.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, consumers were snapping up the biggest sport
utility vehicles. Cunningham said that rising gasoline prices had
begun to erode demand for the largest sport utilities and increased
demand for small cars, but that the Fed's rate increases had been
far more important for auto sales than gasoline prices. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
