<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAPPY FOR SMALL BLESSINGS, THE MARKET ONLY GIVES A LITTLE BACK FROM
RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After adding modestly to Tuesday's record percentage
gain, Nasdaq stock prices fell in the final hour Wednesday to
finish with a 1.7 percent loss as investors digested further
evidence of a slowing economy and girded themselves for a crucial
employment report Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index ended 58.57 points lower at 3,400.91.
Other major gauges traded in a relatively narrow range and ended
nearly unchanged. The blue-chip Dow Jones industrial average edged
down 4.80 points, to 10,522.33, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index eased 1.85 points, or 0.13 percent, to 1,420.60.
</P>
<P>
   ``The positive note is that we did not give back a lot'' of the
post-holiday rally, said Michael Strauss, a managing director of
Commonfund, an investment pool for college endowments. On the other
hand, he added, the market was pleased with reports of lower home
sales and less industrial inflation in the Midwest, ``but couldn't
do anything with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices mostly moved sideways _ and with little obvious
pattern _ except that investors seemed to welcome the opportunity
to lighten positions in high-technology concerns, while bidding up
shares of household names, like Wal-Mart, which leaped 4\, to 57|,
the biggest positive contributor to the Dow and the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the economy is going to downshift to a lower gear, you
don't want to own a whole load of technology stocks,'' said Ned
Riley Jr. chief strategist at State Street Global Advisors. Riley
examined trading blocks of at least 5,000 shares, and calculated
that retail investors accounted for 70 percent of the activity in
the top 10 Nasdaq stocks Wednesday, even though they held only 57
percent of the shares.
</P>
<P>
   Utilities and brokerage firms were among Wednesday's leaders.
Timothy M. Stevenson, a senior portfolio manager at the First
Capital Group, said the performance of brokerage firms was ``a vote
of confidence'' in the market outlook. Merrill Lynch gained 4, to
98|, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter 4{, to 71{, and Dain Rauscher 2|,
to 59|.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson was also upbeat about market breadth, with 1,719
issues advancing on the New York Stock Exchange compared with 1,287
that declined. Among the S&AMP;P 500, however, losers outnumbered
winners by 268 to 213, the biggest drags on the index being Cisco
Systems, down 2 15/16, to 56 15/16, and Qualcomm, down 10, to 66].
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard, which skidded 4 5/16, to 120 3/16, was the
biggest drag on the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
