<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1132 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-MCGINEST-BOS &LR;      05-31 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCGINEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YET ANOTHER NEW ROLE FOR A PATRIOTS' STALWART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ ``Did you know you were Adrian Klemm's idol growing
up?'' Willie McGinest was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's Adrian Klemm?'' said McGinest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team's second-round draft pick out of Hawaii, Willie. He
grew up in the Los Angeles area and idolized you as a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the guy who must be punching me in the face everyday
and holding on to my jersey,'' said McGinest.
</P>
<P>
   McGinest was kidding, we think. The Patriots' defensive
end/linebacker, whatever he is in Bill Belichick's defense, is
experiencing tunnel vision at minicamp. If he hasn't had time to
socialize with Klemm and other young teammates, you'll have to
excuse him. He's trying to learn his fifth defense since being
drafted by the Patriots in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a compliment,'' said McGinest about comments by the
rookie tackle. ``It makes me go at him a little harder. That's a
compliment, though.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a compliment to McGinest that each coach he's played
for has made him the focal point of the defense. It happened at USC
and here under Bill Parcells, who changed McGinest from a
linebacker to a defensive end. Pete Carroll then changed him into
an ``elephant'' in his defensive scheme.
</P>
<P>
   McGinest is the stud in the Patriots' front seven, responsible
for disrupting the opposing quarterback. He's been to the Pro Bowl.
He's also suffered the frustrations of being injured, a frustration
that finally ended last season when he stayed healthy for 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick is also asking McGinest to do something different. In
the role of elephant, he was a mobile defensive end who'd move in
and out of coverages and also rush the passer. Now he's at the line
of scrimmage. He's up, not down, and he acts like an outside
linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linebacker-defensive end. I don't know my title yet,'' said
McGinest. ``I'm still learning. I'm doing a lot of things to be
disruptive _ pressure the quarterback and make plays. A specific
role? A specific title? I don't really have one. I'm a linebacker,
a d-end. I'm interchangeable. Keeps guys guessing. Guys can't say
he's going to be here on a play or there. It's a little different
from elephant because I'm going to have to know what the
linebackers are doing and certain calls and checks.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, so he is a linebacker?
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't ask me. I don't know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On offense, veterans have found a resemblance to the '96 offense
when current offensive coordinator Charlie Weis worked as a
receivers, running backs, and tight ends coach. Defensive players
also see similarities to the '96 scheme, when Belichick was the
assistant head coach in charge of the secondary, although the new
head coach keeps adding wrinkles. They also see glimpses of the
Jets' defense of last season that Belichick ran.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little different,'' said McGinest. ``Some of the calls
are changed a little bit. He's added a lot. He's constantly
changing things, especially coming from another AFC team you can't
have the exact same system. It's a whole new thing for the coaches.
We're all new to it as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't watch the Jets' defense much last year because I
usually concentrate on their offense, but there have been times
I've seen the Jets bring five or six linebackers. That stuff is
confusing. If guys can take all that in, we can use it to our
advantage. The most important thing is to grasp it and go through
the motions. We have to get to the point where we don't have to
think twice about it.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinest doesn't know what he's going to find when he comes to
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows man? Right now I'm just a spoke on the wheel,'' he
said. ``We all have different roles. We're all going to have time
to get after it. I have my special plays. I was talking to one of
the guys before practice and I was just watching (Belichick). So
much stuff goes through his mind. He's constantly working. When
we're off, he's still here. You might have one defense and he might
wipe it out and have something completely different the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   You can tell McGinest's mood is changing. He was not a happy man
last year. Not when the Patriots went 2-6 the second half of the
season. He was the most vocal defensive player concerning the
team's shortcomings, especially following a humiliating loss to the
Philadelphia Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who expects to be successful and win games and be put
out of the playoffs after one game or not make the playoffs at all
shouldn't be happy or accept that,'' he said. ``We used the last
game as a steppingstone. We're just the team we were last year
until we prove otherwise. You have to go out and prove it to the
teams we're playing against that we're different now.''
</P>
<P>
   He has no way of knowing what the 2000 Patriots will look like,
except that the atmosphere has changed. The gloom and doom is gone,
at least for now. But he will never knock Carroll because his ways
``worked for him in San Francisco. Pete was a good coach,''
McGinest said. ``It just didn't work out. Just like it doesn't work
out for some players. Business decisions have to be made on that
level. All I have to worry about is what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinest says Belichick is ``business-like'' and expects things
to be done right, but ``he's not a robot. He jokes around and has
fun, too. It's not completely serious all the time,'' he said. ``He
says players need to have structure and guidance and know what
their limitations are. He sees those things in place at a time when
he feels the team needs them most.''
</P>
<P>
   Although McGinest has spent most of the offseason working on his
conditioning, he'll soon leave for California and then Vancouver so
physical therapists can help him prevent problems with his groin,
which had been troublesome to him in '97 and '98.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe when McGinest comes back, after he learns the new
defense, he can chat with Adrian Klemm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
