<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1147 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-LIFE-KAISER0601-C     05-31 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LIFE-KAISER0601-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brand new Life for Kaiser
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After sitting in the lead chair at courtside for more
than 1,000 games, Life University basketball coach Roger Kaiser
said Wednesday, ``It's time to step aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser, a Georgia Tech All-American, won four NAIA national
titles, including three in the last four years at Life. On
Wednesday, he announced his retirement as coach, but will remain at
the school as athletics director.
</P>
<P>
   ``I coached in the '60s, the '70s, the '80s, the '90s and in
2000,'' Kaiser said. ``I don't think I could've enjoyed anything
more, but it's time to put my energy into something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser, 62, coached 34 years, the last nine at Life, where he
started the program and led the Running Eagles to the 1997, '99 and
2000 NAIA national championships.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a guy from Dale, Ind., where a head count of the
town would not exceed the number of games Kaiser has coached.
</P>
<P>
   He was introduced to organized basketball in the third grade.
Former Georgia State coach Bob Reinhart was a teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob and I grew up playing together,'' Kaiser said, ``and we
played on the same team in elementary school and through high
school. He would always tell me that he was wearing his arm out
passing me the ball, and I was wearing mine out shooting it. We've
been the best of friends since those childhood days.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser, although being recruited by Indiana, Kentucky,
Louisville, Western Kentucky and Vanderbilt, chose Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser married his high school sweetheart, Beverly Hevron, after
his junior year at Tech. On the court, he played his way to
All-America status for two seasons. Tech coach Whack Hyder
eventually said about Kaiser, ``He's the best player I ever
coached.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our teams at Tech did a lot for basketball in the
South, especially the state of Georgia,'' said Kaiser, who also was
an outstanding baseball player. ``We beat Kentucky three times in
six games, and that was unheard of back then.''
</P>
<P>
   After playing in the old American Basketball Association for two
years after leaving Tech, Kaiser returned as the Yellow Jackets'
freshman-team coach for the 1963-64 season. He became head coach at
Decatur High School a year later and hired Reinhart as his
assistant.
</P>
<P>
   After a four-year high school record of 77-26, Kaiser headed to
West Georgia, where he posted a 20-year record of 381-186 and the
1974 NAIA national title. ``For what he's accomplished, he deserves
(retirement),'' Beverly Kaiser said. ``We started dating our
sophomore year in high school, and basketball has been our lives
ever since. But no matter what happened, Roger never brought it
home. He was the same _ win, lose or draw. If anything was eating
on him, he left it at the office.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What he did, more than anything else,'' Life forward Chummy
Johnson said, ``was instill personal pride in his players, and
pride in the team and in the school.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
