<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-COOLIDGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN COOLIDGE, SON OF PRESIDENT, DIES AT 93 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Coolidge, the oldest living offspring of an American
president, died Wednesday in Dartmouth-Hitchcock Medical Center in
Lebanon, N.H. He was 93.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Mr. Coolidge was as taciturn as his father,
Calvin, the former governor of Massachusetts and 30th president of
the United States, who earned the sobriquet ``Silent Cal.''
</P>
<P>
   He was an executive with the New York, New Haven, and Hartford
Railroad and president of Connecticut Manifold Forms Co., a small
manufacturer of business forms, until 1960, when he reopened a
small dairy business under the name of Plymouth Cheese Corp. in
Plymouth, Vt. The business was originally started in 1891 by his
grandfather, John C. Coolidge, and four other Plymouth farmers.
</P>
<P>
   He continued to run it well into his 80s.
</P>
<P>
   His office contained the framed first dollar he earned in his
cheese-making endeavor. Excerpts from his father's writings adorned
the walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wrote wonderful speeches, really agonized over them,'' Mr.
Coolidge once said. ``It's too bad that more people don't read
them.''
</P>
<P>
   It was in the old white clapboard family homestead up the road
from the factory that his father, then vice president, took the
oath of office to become president. He was vacationing there when
news of the death of President Warren G. Harding arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The oath was administered by the president's father, a notary
public, by the light of a kerosene lamp in the early morning hours
of Aug. 23, 1923.
</P>
<P>
   Young John Coolidge was taking summer military training at Fort
Devens in Ayer, Mass., when the oath was administered. The
following morning he was in line for breakfast when a captain asked
him if he'd seen the morning paper. ``When I told him no, he said,
`Your father is president of the United States,' young Mr. Coolidge
said, according to an account furnished by the Calvin Coolidge
Memorial Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naturally, I was surprised,'' he said, ``but nothing changed.
I guess a lot of people expected me to rush off to Washington, but
I stayed and finished training. Father wouldn't have it any other
way.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the only surviving son was a carbon copy of his
father. Modest and of a retiring nature, he was short on words but
long on Yankee conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Father brought the national debt down from $22 billion to $17
billion. That isn't bad, is it?'' he said in a rare interview
during the 1976 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Was his frugal father tight-fisted at home, too?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my, yes,'' said his son. ``He wasn't penurious or stingy,
but he knew the value of money. His father could do anything from
shoeing horses to building wagons. They believed in doing for
yourself and not spending money unless it was necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Of President Coolidge's disdain for small talk or chit-chat, his
son said this famous story about him ``could have been'' true: A
woman sitting next to the president at dinner gushed: ``Mr.
Coolidge, I bet a friend I could get three words out of you.''
</P>
<P>
   `` You lose,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   The president's son was born in Northampton, Mass., on Sept. 7,
1906. His mother, Grace (Goodhue) Coolidge, was a musical,
fun-loving woman. He graduated from Amherst College in 1928.
</P>
<P>
   In his 90s, he still occasionally shuffled from his home near
the family homestead in Plymouth Notch, Vt., to collect his mail.
Often, residents reported, he was charming and outgoing; sometimes
he was not.
</P>
<P>
   According to local legend, a neighbor once confronted him about
his shifting moods: ``Some days I take after my mother,'' he said.
``Some days, I take after my father.''
</P>
<P>
   He leaves a daughter, Lydia Coolidge Sayles of Plymouth Notch,
three grandchildren, and two great-grandsons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 2007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
