<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1155 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CRAIG-SPELLING-HNS &LR;      05-31 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRAIG-SPELLING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     REGIONAL SPELLING CHAMP MISSES NATIONAL FINALS BY A LETTER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vicki Craig, a San Antonio eighth-grader, fell
short Wednesday of the National Spelling Bee finals by one letter.
She correctly spelled ``poltroonery'' and ``synthesis'' before
misspelling ``incarcerate'' by substituting the ``i'' with an
``e.''
</P>
<P>
   Vicki, whose participation in the bee was sponsored by the San
Antonio Express-News, said the worst part of spelling competitions
is getting a word she doesn't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't know it, you really have to listen'' to the
pronunciation and look for clues about its spelling, the
14-year-old said.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki, who attends Bradley Middle School, said she had studied
``poltroonery,'' which means cowardice. The word was taken from a
list given to the contestants in advance of the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had studied it,'' she said. But ``you can't let
yourself get too overconfident.''
</P>
<P>
   She didn't, calmly asking the pronouncer for the word's
definition and asking that it be used in a sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Spellers are allowed to ask for word definitions, alternate
pronunciations, the word's language of origin and how it might be
used in a sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki asked the same questions for ``synthesis,'' defined as a
combination of parts in order to form a whole. After hearing the
answers, she clasped her hands together in front of her and spelled
it _ correctly.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with the second question, the words were no longer
taken from the list. And while Vicki knew the first random word,
she was not familiar with ``incarcerate.''
</P>
<P>
   She was one of 138 spellers eliminated from the competition the
opening day. On Thursday, the remaining 110 fifth- through
eighth-grade regional champions from around the country will
compete for a top prize of $10,000 cash from the E.W. Scripps Co.,
which is sponsoring the 73rd bee.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki's mother, Susan, a bookkeeper at Walzen Elementary School
in San Antonio, said her daughter was both nervous and excited to
be in the competition. She said Vicki had been studying words with
a teacher at her junior high school before and after class.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki said she calmed herself during the bee by spelling the
words, to herself, that were asked of the other competitors. She
said that she hoped to at least make it to Thursday's round, and
she tried her best.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki won the Express-News bee in an exhausting 59-round battle.
It was her first win in four years of competing in the regional
bee. Since Vicki will enter high school next year, she will no
longer be eligible to compete.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
dart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
