u i BC-AFRICA-BANK-NYT &LR;      05-31 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-BANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD BANK CITES ITSELF IN STUDY OF AFRICA'S BLEAK PERFORMANCE
</HEADLINE>
  By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Devastated by war, corruption and disease, people
in sub-Saharan Africa live less well today than they did in the
1960s, and aid donors have to share the blame, the World Bank said
in a comprehensive study issued Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The report, prepared jointly with the United Nations and African
development institutions, said Ghana, Mozambique and Uganda were
among a handful of African nations that have piloted a way out of
extreme poverty. But it says that with AIDS, malaria and civil
strife rising, conditions in the region as a whole are worsening.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank and the International Monetary Fund, the two
leading international lending agencies, have come under intense
scrutiny over their multibillion-dollar African aid programs.
Protesters who ran noisy demonstrations in Washington at the spring
meetings of the bank and the fund said the two institutions had
made Africa poorer through failed policies, a position that the
bank's analysis partly vindicates.
</P>
<P>
   The 280-page report acknowledges that the heavy flow of aid in
recent decades did relatively little to ignite sustained economic
growth, but the study adds that the World Bank has reinvented how
it manages aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The temptation is to retreat into pessimism,'' the bank's vice
president for Africa, Callisto Madavo, said. ``But I think if you
look at what we have been doing recently, you can see that we're
really on the right track.''
</P>
<P>
   Sub-Saharan Africa is the only major region that moved backward
in the later decades of 20th century, says the report, which
catalogs the many woes while prescribing some remedies.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1960s, African nations were widely considered more
advanced than East Asian nations. But between that time and the end
of the '90s, Africa retreated in real economic terms, while East
Asian economic output increased fourfold.
</P>
<P>
   Today, sub-Saharan Africa's 48 nations have collective economic
output that does not much surpass that of Belgium. Poland alone has
more roads. Africa's share of world trade has steadily declined to
less than 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Africa depends more on foreign aid today than ever, the report
says. Loans and grants from rich nations account for 10 percent of
total economic activity, and a heavy debt burden constrains the
ability of governments to put their fiscal houses in order.
</P>
<P>
   Infectious diseases like malaria and AIDS take more of a toll
now than at any time since the early part of the 20th century.
Africa accounts for 70 percent of the AIDS cases reported around
the world. Even if progress against the disease is made, experts
expect the disease to reduce the average African life expectancy by
20 years, erasing all the gains since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Endemic corruption and war, including the conflicts in Ethiopia
as well as western and central Africa, are the main causes of the
bleak performance, the report says. But the World Bank accepts some
blame.
</P>
<P>
   The report says the bank and its sister agencies have wasted
billions on ill-conceived projects. Even when projects were
carefully managed, they sometimes competed with national
governments, drawing talented bureaucrats and leaving nations
``project rich and cash poor,'' it says.
</P>
<P>
   The bank calls on rich countries to open their markets to
imports of African goods. Wealthy nations collectively spend $300
billion to subsidize and protect their own farmers against foreign
competition, the report says, a figure that is as large Africa's
total economic output.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 2021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1163 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-COLOROFPARADISE-     05-31 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-COLOROFPARADISE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BEAUTY, LITERALLY AND SPIRITUALLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
C.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's unlikely that every movie made in Iran is exquisitely
beautiful. But the ones successful enough to merit being imported
to America _ such as 1996's ``Gabbeh'' and 1997's ``Children of
Heaven'' _ are uniformly stunning, fablelike tales told with an
artist's appreciation of color and an almost unearthly knack for
heightening sensory awareness.
</P>
<P>
   The most extraordinary of these may be ``The Color of
Paradise,'' which was written and directed by Majid Majidi, who
also handled ``Children of Heaven.'' Like that movie, ``Paradise''
is about the passion and heart of a child, in this case 8-year-old
Mohammad. Mohsen Ramezani, a nonprofessional actor, doesn't play
the role of Mohammad so much as he inhabits it.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ramezani, Mohammad is blind, and Majidi frequently rests
the camera on him in wordless scenes where he takes in the sounds
around him, which are dominated by the chirps of birds and the
tok-tok-toks of woodpeckers that seem to be trying to tell Mohammad
something. In a captivating sequence early in the film, Mohammad
rescues a baby bird that has fallen from its nest, and Majidi
communicates the tactile joy in this: the feel of the frail
nestling, the roughness of the tree bark, the texture of an egg,
the quizzical nips of the mother bird. It's indicative of the way
Mohammad embraces life, and yet he remains frustrated by his
inability to see any of it, a cruelty that Majidi and
cinematographer Mohammad Davoodi _ whose compositions often
resemble paintings _ emphasize by making everything surrounding the
boy as jaw-droppingly gorgeous as possible.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Mohammad is Hashem, the boy's morose,
self-pitying father, a widower played by Hossein Mahjub with the
wounded look of a whipped dog. Hashem loves Mohammad, but considers
him a burden, and is continually trying to pawn him off _ on the
teachers at Mohammad's special school, on the boy's loving and
majestic Granny (Salime Feizi), on a blind carpenter (Morteza
Fatemi) who the father hopes will teach the boy a trade and make
him self-sufficient. The only thing that makes Hashem smile _ and
when he does, you think his face will shatter _ is the prospect of
marriage to a neighbor woman, but Mohammad is an obstacle to that,
as well.
</P>
<P>
   The story is deceptively simple and unabashedly sentimental,
with tears flowing so liberally in spots that ``wailing and
gnashing of teeth'' is a near-literal description. But Majidi
steers clear of blatant manipulation, preferring to seduce with the
beauty of his images: lush forests, imposing mountains, fields of
flowers, sharply hued petals turning into dyes, eerily foggy
valleys, rushing rapids, the smiling faces of Mohammad's cheerful
young sisters, the iconically lined face of his wise but saddened
grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Some might find the ending, which resolves the movie's quest for
faith, too ambiguous. But if anything, it's too literal, a slip in
subtlety from a movie that works on us from the inside. It's so
thick with beauty that the subtitles hardly seem necessary; Majidi
tells a story with pictures, and their power is enthralling. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Color of Paradise,'' in Farsi with English subtitles, is rated
PG for mild violence and adult themes. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Color of Paradise'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Score: 5 on a 1-5 scale &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Director: Majid Majidi &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Mohsen Ramezani, Hossein Mahjub &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Length: 90 min. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
