u w BC-MILLER-SPELLING-HNS &LR;      05-31 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLER-SPELLING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ALISON MILLER MOVES INTO SPELLING BEE FINALS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Alison Miller, 14, a home-schooled student from
Niskayuna, N.Y., correctly spelled three words _ saprophagous,
vendetta and carafe _ at the 73rd National Spelling Bee Wednesday
to advance to Thursday's final round.
</P>
<P>
   Alison, who competed in the bee here two years ago but did not
make the finals, said in an interview, ``I enjoy it when I get the
words right.''
</P>
<P>
   She called saprophagous a ``memorable'' word. ``It means feeding
on dead bodies. So it's pretty hard to forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Alison, who was sponsored by the Albany Times Union, joined 247
other students from around the country at the start of the 73rd bee
and was one of 110 finalists. The bee is administered by the E.W.
Scripps Company.
</P>
<P>
   Alison knew the word vendetta from reading widely, said her
father, Ross Miller, a corporate risk manager.
</P>
<P>
   A vendetta is a feud in which a wronged person seeks vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   Alison quickly spelled carafe after asking for its definition
and being told that it is a ``bottle usually made of glass.''
</P>
<P>
   Alison said she has studied languages such as French, Latin and
ancient Greek, which have helped her spell their English
derivatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty good with words,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While listening to other spellers, Alison held tightly to her
chair and rocked back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of stressful,'' she explained. ``For me the most
nervous time is when I'm waiting. When I'm up there (answering a
question) I have something to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross Miller said that before coming to Washington, Alison had
spent half an hour a day on spelling.
</P>
<P>
   Last month she also competed in the Mathcounts and USA Math
Olympiad, said her mother, Mary O'Keeffe, said. Alison finished
12th in the nation in Mathcounts and was among the top 30 in the
Olympiad, where she was one of a few eighth-graders in the
high-school-level competition. In March she won the regional
spelling bee sponsored by the Albany Times Union.
</P>
<P>
   O'Keeffe, who volunteers as a mentor in local public schools,
said she was a school spelling champion herself as an eighth grader
and that she is a descendant of Noah Webster, the famous compiler
of dictionaries.
</P>
<P>
   O'Keefe, who called Alison a ``very independent learner,'' said
she took up spelling in the sixth grade and right away made it to
the national competition. She failed in the third round of the 1998
bee by spelling the word aggrandizement with an ``s'' instead of a
``z.''
</P>
<P>
   Alison, who said she wants to be a writer, will be competing
Thursday for prizes including $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
dart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
