<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AFFIRMS OAS MOVE TO ADDRESS PERU ELECTION CONCERNS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Organization of American States agreed
Wednesday to address accusations of fraud in Peru's presidential
election when foreign ministers meet in Canada this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives adopted a cautious posture, refusing a
U.S.-backed move to formally convene the ministers on an emergency
basis.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department said it was satisfied with the outcome,
even though Luis Lauredo, the American ambassador to the OAS, had
to withdraw a motion to invoke a resolution that would have added
symbolic urgency to the response.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department spokesman said the plan to add Peru to the
agenda in Windsor, Canada, beginning Sunday showed ``this
registered as a serious problem with hemispheric implications.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department had issued mixed signals this week over
whether the allegations of fraud render invalid the re-election, on
Sunday, of President Alberto Fujimori.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Reeker, a department spokesman, said Wednesday that
Peru's ``electoral process was obviously flawed,'' but refused to
repeat a colleague's charge Monday that Fujimori could not
legitimately claim another term.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is not contemplating unilateral action against
Peru, Reeker said. President Clinton, who is traveling in Europe,
has not spoken with Fujimori, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   OAS officials and diplomats predicted that hemispheric
governments will move carefully. Some noted that electoral fraud is
a different threat to democratic rule than, say, a military coup,
and some feared inciting violence in Peru.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of stability in Peru is playing a very strong part
and has a great weight on how they will proceed,'' said one Latin
American diplomat who was active in discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Lauredo surprised some officials by sounding a vigorous defense
of democracy, considering that American anti-narcotic officials are
deeply uneasy over the prospect of losing Fujimori as one of the
region's few reliable allies on that issue. Envoys from Canada,
Costa Rica and Argentina took stands similar to Lauredo's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attacks on democracy today are more subtle than ever,''
Lauredo said. ``The thing that unites us is our common embrace of
democratic values and our shared responsibility to defend them when
they are threatened.''
</P>
<P>
   Peru's neighbors are especially wary of strong action, as were
Mexico and Brazil, officials said. Brazil's ambassador, Carlos
Alberto Leiti Barbosa, spoke of ``maintaining the necessary
delicate balance between the defense of democracy and respect for
sovereignty.''
</P>
<P>
   But Odeen Ishmael, the ambassador of Guyana, said that elections
in that small nation north of Brazil had been rigged for many
years, and that Guyana owed a debt of gratitude to OAS observers
who helped safeguard subsequent elections, Ishmael said.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomats received a preliminary report Wednesday from
Eduardo Stein, who monitored the elections for the OAS.
</P>
<P>
   The report detailed irregularities in Peru's system to compute
vote tallies, a lack of candidates' equal access to the mass media,
the use of public resources for political gain and improper
investigations into various complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Peru's ambassador, Beatriz Ramacciotti, accused Stein of
exceeding his mandate. He ``transformed himself into a political
actor,'' Ramacciotti said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
