<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1175 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BUSH-DNA0601-COX     05-31 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DNA0601-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gov. George W. Bush, a staunch defender of a state
criminal justice system under fire nationally, on Wednesday
pardoned an innocent man who spent 17 years in prison and said he
will ``more than likely'' grant his first ever 30-day reprieve to a
man scheduled to be executed tonight.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear, however, how Bush will delay the execution
because state law precludes him from intervening unless he is in
Texas. Bush is campaigning for president outside of Texas until
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   And because Lt. Gov. Rick Perry also is out of state, Democrat
Rodney Ellis, the Senate's president pro-tem, is acting governor
and must decide whether the execution occurs. An Ellis spokesman
said Bush's wishes ``would weigh heavily'' on the senator's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Both cases involve updated DNA testing. In the death row case,
Rickey Nolen McGinn of Brownwood says tests will show he did not
rape and kill his 12-year-old stepdaughter in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In the other case, Bush pardoned A.B. Butler Jr. of Tyler after
DNA tests proved Butler was not involved in the 1983 abduction and
rape of a Tyler woman. Butler, sentenced to 99 years, was released
on bond in January after the DNA test cleared him and prosecutors
recommended a pardon.
</P>
<P>
   The McGinn case is the latest to invite national scrutiny of
Texas executions. McGinn could be put to death despite the trial
judge's recommendation that he is entitled to new DNA testing. The
Texas Court of Criminal Appeals on Tuesday rejected that
recommendation. The case was pending late Wednesday in the 5th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   In a Wednesday interview prior to Bush's comments, McGinn told
The Associated Press that Bush might get some political mileage out
of delaying the execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard it would hurt him. I don't know how it would hurt
him. It would show they're trying to make the judicial system
right,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush cannot reduce a death sentence without a recommendation
from the Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles. The panel voted
unanimously Wednesday against that.
</P>
<P>
   The board also voted against delaying the execution, but that
does not prevent the governor from granting a single, 30-day
reprieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is any doubt, any outstanding evidence that
exonerates him from the rape, we ought to look at it,'' Bush said
while campaigning in Albuquerque, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not indicate whether he would return to Texas to grant
the reprieve. Spokesman Mike Jones said Bush had no plans to return
to the state to take action in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis has served as acting governor during three previous
executions, including one Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston lawmaker is a longtime critic of the Texas criminal
justice system, especially its procedures for providing attorneys
for indigent defendants. Ellis is a death penalty supporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes the decision on his own, but after close and thorough
contact with staff from the governor's and lieutenant governor's
office,'' said Ellis spokesman Jeremy Warren. ``Senator Ellis takes
this very seriously and understands and will always keep in mind
the views and positions of Governor Bush and Lieutenant Governor
Perry.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who took office in 1995, has never granted a 30-day
reprieve. One hundred thirty-one Texas death row inmates have been
executed since Bush took office and throughout the presidential
campaign he has insisted all were guilty.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, he commuted Henry Lee Lucas' sentence to life in prison
after determining that questionable evidence had been used at the
trial. Lucas once said he had committed dozens of murders, but
later recanted.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth lawyer Richard Alley, representing McGinn, said he
will ask the trial judge to further delay the execution if 30 days
is not enough time to run the tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, nobody is sure'' if McGinn is guilty, said Alley.
``It can now become conclusive. If we're not sure, let's not
execute someone until we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Alley is convinced that state District Judge Steven Ellis, who
previously could only recommend the tests, will now order them.
</P>
<P>
   Brown County District Attorney Lee Haney said there is no doubt
of McGinn's guilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oddly enough, since DNA seems to be a big deal at this point,
it was because of DNA that the trial lasted a good while,'' the
prosecutor said. ``We had experts from three DNA labs fly in to
testify, and it stretched out the trial a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Said McGinn, ``If they're so sure, what are they afraid of?
Let's do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Butler case ended Wednesday with a brief formal statement
from Bush's office.
</P>
<P>
   The case, according to Butler's lawyer, was Texas justice at its
worst.
</P>
<P>
   Butler was convicted in Smith County in the 1983 rape of a woman
abducted from a motel parking lot. Butler, then on probation for an
assault conviction, consistently proclaimed his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a black man accused of a brutal sexual assault on a
white woman,'' said Houston lawyer Randy Shaeffer, now representing
Butler. ``She identified him as the person who did it. He said he
didn't do it. A rural Texas jury, 999 times out of 1,000, is going
to believe the woman.''
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 6, Smith County District Attorney Jack Skeen Jr., who
prosecuted the case in 1983, told Bush that Butler was due a pardon
because of the new DNA testing.
</P>
<P>
   Shaeffer said his client lost 17 years to a misguided judicial
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that this is not truly a justice system. It's a system
of politics,'' said Shaeffer. ``Most of the people in the position
of authority are watching their backsides to insure they don't do
something that would stand them in poor stead with the voters or
political opponents.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaeffer said he is uncertain as to whether Bush's current
political race played a role in the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the timing looked somewhat coincidental, but I'm not
one to look a gift horse in the mouth,'' said Shaeffer. ``I welcome
the governor doing right by my client any day of the week for any
reason at all.''
</P>
<P>
   In Tyler, Butler, after a day at his dirtwork job, said he
planned to celebrate with his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no hard feelings,'' he said. ``We went through the
proper steps and here I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler said his faith, not politics, prevailed in the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prayed and asked the Lord to reach out and touch (Bush) and
make him do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
