<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1176 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-PROPAGANDA-ART-     05-31 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-PROPAGANDA-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FOOTSTEPS OF MAO, CHINA'S PRESIDENT TOUTS HIS OWN BRAND OF
PROPAGANDA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT31 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING, China _ Officials have been streaming into government
bookstores in recent days and hauling away stacks of a hot new
product: a 74-page, 50-cent booklet called ``A Great Program for
Comprehensively Strengthening Party-Building.''
</P>
<P>
   This must-read item consists of two recent speeches by the man
who is the general-secretary of the Communist Party chief and the
president of China, Jiang Zemin, and a collection of editorials
describing the ``brilliant thesis'' and ``essential compass'' that
Jiang has laid out _ a purported breakthrough in Communist doctrine
labeled the ``Three Represents.''
</P>
<P>
   To prosper in a new century, Jiang says in these speeches, the
Communist Party ``must always represent the development needs of
China's advanced productive forces, must always represent the
forward direction of China's advanced culture and must always
represent the fundamental interests of China's broadest number of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   In a classic propaganda campaign that gathered full force in
May, Jiang's supposed breakthrough has been pounded home almost
daily in laudatory editorials and televised testimonials by leaders
from every province and officially recognized social group.
</P>
<P>
   If all this sounds anachronistic for a leader who is promoting a
wider opening to the West, it reflects the enduring rituals of
power within the Chinese Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   The booklet's contents may be vague and tedious, insiders say,
but that is beside the point: Jiang is making other officials go
through the panegyrics as a show of his leadership, as a public
blow in his maneuvering to retain supreme power in the decade
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang is expected to resign as the party's general-secretary at
the 16th Communist Party Congress in 2002, when he will be 76. He
is expected to give up the presidency the year after.
</P>
<P>
   But with no strong successors in sight, Jiang, who has led the
party since 1989 and served as president since 1993, is widely
believed to want to continue pulling strings from behind the
scenes, as Deng Xiaoping did in the 1980s and 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   And so while Jiang cultivates the stature he hopes will
transcend formal retirement, officials anxious to hold on to their
own jobs loudly sing his praises.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like in ancient times, when the emperor would test his
ministers by bringing out a donkey and calling it a horse,'' said
an editor at a major party-affiliated newspaper. ``If you
maintained that it was a donkey you lost your head. If you called
it a horse, then you got a promotion.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Closely related to Jiang's effort to fortify his image, insiders
say, is his effort to secure himself a place in the Chinese
Communist pantheon, after Mao and Deng, as an important theorist.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, considering Jiang's current unrivaled
position, his ``breakthrough'' statement on the ``Three
Represents'' is garnering rave reviews and has become a staple of
high-level study sessions in provincial capitals.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``A brilliant thesis drawn from insight into the future,'' said
the party's official paper, People's Daily, on May 22 in a typical
description. ``A concentrated embodiment of the fundamental nature
of the party and the essence of socialism.''
</P>
<P>
   In other newspapers, officials have called Jiang's prosaic
statement ``pregnant with connotations and meanings,'' ``a
scientific summation of our party's nearly 80 years of historical
importance'' and ``a great program for party-building in the new
century.''
</P>
<P>
   The People's Liberation Army Daily hailed it as ``an essential
compass for military, ideological and political construction in the
new era,'' while the Federation of Trade Unions, not to be outdone,
said Jiang ``answers the question of why and how the working class
is relied on the during the process of building socialism with
Chinese characteristics.'' The China Women's News proclaimed, ``The
`Three Represents' are the criteria for women's work.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is, of course, low-key compared with the vicious
political winds of the Mao era, and much of the population today
can simply tune it out. At the popular Xinhua Bookstore in central
Beijing on Wednesday, most customers walked right past the rack up
front that featured the booklet on Jiang's speeches.
</P>
<P>
   But the booklet is a best seller at the Party Documents
Bookstore, where officials are buying it in bulk for their
colleagues, and ambitious party and government leaders can hardly
afford to ignore the new catch phrases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite apart from substance, the campaign is a test of whether
subordinates and local leaders in the provinces are staying in
step,'' the editor said. ``That's why in recent days we've seen one
local leader after another coming forward _ it's a way to affirm
their allegiance and keep their jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   This new campaign went into overdrive even before last year's
``Three Stresses'' campaign (theoretical study, political awareness
and good conduct) had fully run its course, causing complaints
about the sheer waste of time and energy.
</P>
<P>
   In that campaign, still continuing in far-flung local branches,
party and government officials have been required to spend weeks at
a time studying Deng and Jiang speeches and engaging in
self-criticism. The process was intended to spot new talent and
bring discipline to an organization seen as increasingly lax and
corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody really cares about this stuff, and people feel
disgusted when they have to study it,'' a former party propaganda
department official said of Jiang's latest ideological offerings.
``What about Taiwan or the World Trade Organization? People have
even started making off-color jokes about Jiang Zemin's love of
`threesomes.'''
</P>
<P>
   The current campaign, many believe, is just a prelude to the
probable publication this year of Jiang's collected speeches and
writings, providing a showcase for his works.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has always been the case here that the party leader is
expected to put forth his own thinking,'' the newspaper editor
said. ``Otherwise he has no prestige.''
</P>
<P>
   Party experts have noted that Jiang opened the new campaign with
speeches in the south, beginning in Guangdong province, in a
parallel with Deng's last great act, when he kicked off a new wave
of market reforms and economic growth with a celebrated southern
tour in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever his strengths as a power broker, Jiang is not regarded
as a bold theorist, and some officials are quietly grumbling about
self-aggrandizement.
</P>
<P>
   But in Jiang's defense, insiders note, he has not yet tried to
elevate himself into a Mao or Deng. Up to now, at least, he has not
granted his own ideas the official status of a body of thought, as
in Mao Tse-tung Thought, or theory, as in Deng Xiaoping Theory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
