<SLUG> BC-CD-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMINEM, KID ROCK LET THE DETROIT SIDE DOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a guy raised outside Detroit, the past two weeks were
looking promising: My fellow Detroiters Eminem and Kid Rock have
become two of the hottest acts around and were releasing CDs within
a week _ Eminem last Tuesday, the Kid this Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to report that both CDs are just fantastic, music I'll
be listening to all summer, so go plunk down your money right now.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, would be a lie.
</P>
<P>
   Eminem's ``The Marshall Mathers LP'' (all new stuff) and Kid
Rock's ``The History of Rock'' (two new songs, 12 more from earlier
records) are disappointments _ not outright terrible, by any means,
but nothing you haven't heard before, done better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Marshall Mathers LP'' is the lesser of the two, mainly
because Eminem spends so much time defending himself in light of
the success of his first major label record, ``The Slim Shady LP,''
which established him as a rap superstar and all-around pain in the
rear end for parents.
</P>
<P>
   The beats are still tough and springy, and Eminem makes some
good points about not being a role model _ see ``Who Knew'' _ but
the shock of the new has worn off. The first CD was about his life;
this one talks all too often about the reaction to his first CD.
Add some appalling misogyny on ``Kim'' and empty-headed threats on
``Kill You,'' and you have a record that pales beside the first
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The History of Rock'' is marginally better. Made up mostly of
songs from 1993's ``The Polyfuze Method'' and 1996's ``Early
Mornin' Stoned Pimp,'' it clearly shows that the Kid has always had
varied tastes (metal, old-school soul, gangsta rap, funk) and an
ability to fuse them.
</P>
<P>
   And there is some interesting material: ``Dark &AMP; Grey'' (a
previously unreleased demo) mixes Metallica-ish riffs with banjo
plucking, and the gangsta rap of ``Ya' Keep On'' is invigorating.
</P>
<P>
   But while the CD shows the Kid to be fairly innovative in
playing mix 'n' match with everyone from Too Short to Slayer to Ted
Nugent, it's also a clear indication that he hit a stylistic high
point with 1998's 9-million-selling ``Devil Without a Cause.''
These songs often sound like interesting experiments and
blueprints, nothing more. Just as instructive is 1990's more
rap-centric ``Grits Sandwiches for Breakfast,'' which was also
recently rereleased to capitalize on the success of ``Devil.'' The
Kid was always a nasty guy _ he's just gotten a lot better at it in
the past couple of years. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kid Rock &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The History of Rock'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic Records &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a 1-5 scale &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eminem &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Marshall Mathers LP'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Interscope Records &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a 1-5 scale &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman covers pop music for the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
