<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AETNA-ING-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AETNA MULLS NEW ING OFFER TO BUY 2 UNITS FOR $9 BILLION
</HEADLINE>
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aetna Inc. and the ING Group, the Dutch financial services
company, said Wednesday that they were discussing a new offer from
ING to buy Aetna's financial and international divisions. Aetna
declined to discuss the price under discussion, but some Wall
Street traders estimated it could be as high as $9 billion, only
slightly less than the roughly $10 billion ING had offered for all
of Aetna earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna shares rose $5 at midday after CNBC reported the ING
offer, and closed up $4.0625 at $66.75 on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   William Donaldson, chief executive of Aetna, said his company
was ``working with ING on their new proposal concerning our
financial services and international businesses.'' He added that
Aetna was still committed to improving its Aetna U.S. Healthcare
unit, the nation's largest health insurer. ING said in a statement
that Aetna's ``domestic U.S. health care operations are not part of
these negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson said there were ``no assurances'' that the ING deal
would close or what the terms would be.
</P>
<P>
   And he said Aetna was still ready to split the company into two
separate health and ``wealth'' divisions and spin them to
shareholders as independent publicly traded companies as it vowed
to do when it rejected ING's $9.9 billion takeover offer in March.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street traders welcomed word of the talks, which they said
cleared the way for a bidding war over Aetna's attractive financial
services business.
</P>
<P>
   ``This opens up the situation,'' said Herbert Denton, president
of Providence Capital Inc., which has Aetna holdings. ``Aetna has
abandoned its split-up plan, and it is basically in play,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very difficult to put the genie back in the bottle,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Securities analysts said $9 billion would be a high-end price.
</P>
<P>
   It would value Aetna's financial, pensions and overseas units at
20 times this year's projected earnings of about $470 million, said
Kenneth S. Abramowitz, a Sanford C. Bernstein analyst. He said
financial services companies had typically sold for 15 times
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   But ING has made no secret of its ambition to become one of the
biggest players in the North American insurance market. ING said
Wednesday that the talks with Aetna were consistent with its goal
of joining the top 10 companies in overall insurance in the United
States as well as expanding ``significantly'' in Latin America and
Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ING recently agreed to pay $5.1 billion for ReliaStar, a
Midwestern insurer, and assumed $1 billion of ReliaStar debt.
</P>
<P>
   Big European insurance companies are eager to buy U.S. insurance
companies because the growth potential for pensions and annuities
is much stronger than in Europe, said Arun Kumar, a bond analyst at
Chase Securities. ``There is more money being spent on retirement
in the United States,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other European companies that have been prospecting for
acquisitions in the United States include Aegon, another
Netherlands-based insurer, AXA of France and Allianz of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said a sale to ING could also create problems for
Aetna shareholders. Although Aetna could spinoff the financial
services and health units to shareholders without any tax
implications, a sale to ING would cause a big capital gains tax
liability for investors. Todd Richter, a Banc of America Securities
analyst, said the tax could be as high as $2 billion to $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to know how they will deal with the tax liability,''
Richter said. Another ``pivotal question,'' he said, ``is the value
of the health care business on a stand-alone basis.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Investors have been clamoring for asset sales that would result
in big stock buybacks that would bolster Aetna's share price. But
Abramowitz pointed out that Aetna also had $5 billion of debt. At
least some of that would probably have to be paid off as part of a
sale.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Cooperman, head of Omega Advisers, a hedge fund manager,
said Aetna would rather split up and avoid the tax liability, ``but
perhaps they have been offered a price they couldn't refuse. I'm
happy they are open-minded and flexible.''
</P>
<P>
   Aetna shares have bounced back to the mid-$60s over the last two
weeks, after sliding into the high $50's when Aetna's board
rejected the earlier offer from ING on March 12. ING then had a
plan to resell the big health unit to Wellpoint Health Networks,
based in California. Wellpoint said it knew nothing about ING's
latest overture to Aetna.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 2043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
