<HEADER>
A1189 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-RANDY-NEWMAN-LADN &LR;      05-31 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RANDY-NEWMAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDUCATING RANDY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If some cash-strapped Midwestern university ever decides to
offer a course in ``Randy Newman 101,'' its syllabus would be
fairly straightforward.
</P>
<P>
   Chapter 1, our hero is ``born right here'' in Los Angeles,
``November '43'', as one of Newman's self-ruminative songs puts it.
</P>
<P>
   Chapter 2, he moves with his mom to New Orleans, where the hot,
sticky musical culture of the Deep South brushes up against cold,
implacable racism.
</P>
<P>
   In chapters 3 through whatever, Newman starts taking piano
lessons (at age 6), moves back to L.A., grows up, marries twice and
raises five kids.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, incidentally, he also becomes one of the most successful
singer- songwriters of the pop-rock era, cutting a distinctive
swathe through music (``Sail Away,'' ``I Love L.A.''), movies
(``Avalon,'' ``Toy Story'') and even musical theater (``Faust'').
</P>
<P>
   Randy Newman, this is your life _ or at least it's the abridged,
somewhat sanitized version that will be put forth this summer in
``The Education of Randy Newman,'' the world premiere musical play
that opens Saturday at South Coast Repertory in Costa Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is far from a literal documentation of my life, which would
have been boring beyond belief,'' Newman says one recent morning
after schlepping from his hilltop Westside home to an SCR rehearsal
room. ``It's my life, and yet it isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   That description encapsulates a project whose authors, Michael
Roth and Jerry Patch, wanted to create something with more
emotional heft and bite than the typical Broadway-style ``greatest
hits'' revue.
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing its title from ``The Education of Henry Adams,'' the
1907 autobiographical masterpiece by the renowned New England man
of letters, ``The Education of Randy Newman'' recreates the life of
a middle-aged musician who bears a striking resemblance to its
namesake _ with some details changed to protect the guilty.
</P>
<P>
   But the show also aims to tell a bigger story about postwar
America's growing pains, through the prism of Newman's radically
skeptical, mordantly humorous worldview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given that Randy writes about the world and the people he sees
in it and how he feels in it, we decided to write the story of a
man who lived through the last half of the 20th century,'' says
Patch, SCR's resident dramaturg.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that was something that interested me because I found
myself relating to all the things this man went through,'' Patch
continues, ticking off the Civil Rights movement, the sexual
revolution, the rise and fall of the 1960s counter-culture and the
uneasy boom years of the '80s and '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like going back through a photo album and seeing all of
our lives recapitulated.''
</P>
<P>
   Now a gray-haired pop elder statesman still given to Hawaiian
shirts and blue jeans, Newman says that Patch and Roth approached
him with idea of fashioning a show from his prodigious songbook
about a year ago. He'd worked with Roth previously on the La Jolla
Playhouse's 1995 world premiere of ``Faust,'' Newman's updating of
the enduring legend about a man who sells his soul to the devil.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike ``Faust,'' which was composed of all-new material,
``Education'' includes only a couple of previously unreleased tunes
from Newman's vast 300-song catalog. The rest, spanning his
30-plus-year recording career, are a mix of familiar and
less-familiar numbers sung by a cast of seven and backed by a
seven-piece band. Scott Waara, a Tony Award winner for the Broadway
revival of ``The Most Happy Fella,'' portrays the Newman character.
</P>
<P>
   For Newman, the rehearsal process has been, well, educational.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's been basically a good experience,'' he says.
``They (the songs) benefit by having a theatrical context
sometimes. You know, I always understand what I'm talking about,
but other people don't. And when it's clear, or it's someone with a
traditional good voice, who can hold a note, it's got a different
thing to it. And they (the songs) are easier to understand. You
know, irony in pop music, coming out of a radio, as you're driving
down the freeway.... I mean, I don't know that I get it myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironic self-deprecation comes naturally to Newman, as it did for
Adams. It's part of a dualistic personality capable of penning the
warm and fuzzy ``You've Got a Friend in Me'' (from ``Toy Story''),
then turning around and writing ``Life Isn't Fair,'' a trenchant
2-minute parable about tarnished ideals from Newman's 1999 studio
release ``Bad Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Newman admits that some of his purportedly autobiographical
songs like ``Dixie Flyer'' (included in the show) are partly
apocryphal, and that his songs' first-person narrators, despite
their apparent candor, are notoriously untrustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he also exposes himself and his shortcomings mercilessly
through song. The Newman narrative persona may be shifty, but the
sentiments behind it tend toward the painful truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing about my life that I wouldn't expose to get a
song out of it,'' he asserts. ``There isn't anything more important
to me. Well, almost nothing. I wrote a love song to my first wife
on my last record, while I'm married to my second wife. Not
without, you know, some repercussions. And I'm not saying this like
`Oh, what a ruthless writer, he must be good!' I'm saying it
because it is true.''
</P>
<P>
   Newman's only other foray into musical theater besides ``Faust''
was the 1981 revue ``Maybe I'm Doing It Wrong.'' Though he has
learned to like the genre, he admits to walking out on both ``Les
Miserables'' and ``Cats,'' ``which may be just California
vulgarity, but I think we were right.''
</P>
<P>
   Patch credits Newman's ability to write in many musical idioms
to his protean, ``suburban blueslinger'' personality. Despite
growing up in a privileged environment _ the son of a doctor and,
more significantly, the nephew of legendary Hollywood film
composers Alfred Newman and Lionel Newman _ Randy Newman's
anti-romantic songs often adopt the perspective of misfits and
losers, characters with distinct voices and attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   And his conceptual albums ``Land of Dreams'' (1988) and ``Bad
Love'' possess strong narrative through-lines, playing almost like
mini musicals.
</P>
<P>
   `I think most pop songs are written with a lack of specificity,
even good pop songs,'' Patch says. ``If you take Beatles songs like
`I Want to Hold Your Hand,' that's the sentiment and anybody can
sing it. Not everybody can sing `Rednecks.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So what does Newman's stage alter-ego finally learn?
</P>
<P>
   ``He decides that life is all right,'' Newman says. ``Which I
do, simplistic and stupid as it seems. For me to think that is not
a small thing. It's comin' a little way to think that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought that life is like a (Charles) Bukowski
novel,'' he continues, referring to the down-and-dirty L.A. author
of ``Barfly.'' ``I never believed in `the world is a cesspool'
theory of art, and `you're just alone and it's a gutter' kind of
thinking. I always felt that people are pretty decent one on one.
You sit next to somebody on a plane, and usually they're all
right....''
</P>
<P>
   Newman hesitates a beat, a smile stealing over his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you're not in First Class, of course.'' &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
What: ``The Education of Randy Newman.''
</P>
<P>
   Where: South Coast Repertory, 655 Town Center Drive, Costa Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   When: Saturday through July 2. Performances at 8 p.m. Tuesdays
through Fridays; 2:30, 8 p.m. Saturdays; 2:30, 7:30 p.m. Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: $33-$52. Call (714) 708-5555. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
