<HEADLINE>
PALM INC. TO ACQUIRE INTERNET CALENDAR COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The leading power in palm-based computing is acquiring a
Cambridge, Mass., Internet firm to extend its online presence.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Inc., maker of the popular Palm Pilot handheld devices,
will pay $80 million in cash and stock for AnyDay.com Inc., which
operates a popular Internet calendar and appointment book service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is supposed to provide detailed and streamlined
services, and not just be an entertainment medium, and that's what
we're going to do with AnyDay,'' said Bill Maggs, Palm's chief
technology officer.
</P>
<P>
   Palm is upgrading its entire line of PalmPilots to support
wireless Internet access, and the firm plans to build a suite of
Internet information management services around AnyDay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the center of their Internet strategy,'' said AnyDay
founder and chief executive Steve Watts.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition is the first Santa Clara, Calif.-based Palm has
made since being spun off earlier this year from parent 3Com Inc.
There are about six million users of Palm devices, lightweight data
managers busy people can use to keep their lives organized.
</P>
<P>
   But at a time when the Internet has become the most important
tool in computing, only one of Palm's devices has built-in Internet
access, through a wireless modem. Maggs said this is going to
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the end of the year, every single Palm is going to be
connectable to the Internet,'' he said. The company plans to offer
a variety of add-on devices that will add Internet access to
existing Palms.
</P>
<P>
   The AnyDay acquisition will give Palm users a central online
repository for personal and business information, one that can be
kept constantly up to date.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1998, AnyDay has 1.7 million registered members.
Their free Web site features a calendar, address book, and to-do
list. The service can also be programmed to notify the user about
important events _ a baseball game between the Yankees and Red Sox,
for example, or the opening date of the latest Mel Gibson movie.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, an AnyDay user can post a public version of his
calendar on the Internet, where it can be seen by colleagues or
family members.
</P>
<P>
   Privately held AnyDay had begun seeking its third round of
venture capital when Watts learned Palm was interested in the
company. ``They were missing the Internet,'' he said. ``That's what
we bring into the fold.''
</P>
<P>
   AnyDay will remain in Cambridge; Watts said the firm will serve
as 3Com's main office in the eastern United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
