u s BC-TEN-COLLINS-BOS &LR;      05-31 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVENPORT LOSES IN FRENCH OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ They looked like Les Miserables, the homeless of Paris,
30,000 soaked and sodden lost souls huddled at Stade Roland Garros,
waiting for the rain to stop Tuesday. It never did. For the only
time in the 75-year-old French Championships, not a single tennis
ball was smacked.
</P>
<P>
   Rain had often interfered, but never triumphed. However, after
nine hours the long-suffering were liberated, sent home clammy and
coughing, and promised refunds. The proprietor, the French
Federation, collected $1 million in a rain insurance payoff, and
five champions slept soundly, probably never dreaming it would be
their last night in town. For three it was.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday appeared cold and shrouded in gray, ominous for the
names _ Carlos Moya, Sergi Bruguera, Lindsay Davenport _ who had
ruled major citadels. But hopeful for no-names, too, such as Erika
de Lone, who had ``waited 11 years'' for such a day: ``my first win
in Paris.''
</P>
<P>
   And for a scrawny Belgian named Dominique Monami Van Roost, so
distraught at her mother's death three months ago that she didn't
want to continue playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am crying and laughing,'' Dominique said after celebrating
her 27th birthday by overcoming the Wimbledon and Australian Open
champ, No. 2 Davenport, 6-7 (5-7), 6-4, 6-3. ``Usually I cry just
when I lose. But I think this was a wonderful victory mentally,
because I fought within myself these last months. I was not sure I
would start playing again.''
</P>
<P>
   It was one of a panoply of 79 matches spread across 22 crimson
dirt courts from morning till nightfall as the strivers threatened
the mighty, and an anonymous unshaven Frenchman, wild card Anthony
Dupuis, No. 108, thought, wrongly, that he was surely beating the
reigning champion, Andre Agassi. His victory dance was premature.
</P>
<P>
   The jigging Dupuis believed he had taken the opening set
tiebreaker on an ace as his serve whizzed past Agassi. But it
grazed the tape: a let. ``I knew it would be a let as soon as he
served it,'' said Agassi, who, well within himself, debuted with a
7-6 (9-7), 6-3, 6-4 win. ``But the guy told me afterwards that he'd
wished for 10 years to be on a court with me. That was nice.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the gallant Davenport, grimacing in pain and hobbled by
back spasms, could consider herself a spiritual winner after a
losing struggle of 2 1/4 hours, the never gallant _ though gifted _
Chilean, Marcelo Rios, once No. 1 for a few fleeting minutes two
years ago, presented a stark contrast on a nearby court. He
surrendered after two listless sets and 66 minutes against Tommy
Haas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's good to quit after two sets if you haven't
been hurt,'' said Haas, the young German trained at Nick
Bollettieri's boot camp in Florida. ``But I think we all know how
Marcelo is. I don't think he really cares what other people
think.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans who watched Rios splash unprofessionally twice at the US
Pro know what Haas means. Rios said his legs were sore _ ``I think
I'm not here to win one match. I'm here to try to win the
tournament. If I'm not feeling good it makes no sense to play.''
</P>
<P>
   It made sense to do-or-die Davenport, who strained her back at
the Italian Open and ``probably came back a week too soon. I was
feeling pretty good until the last game of the second set when I
hit a serve, and my back went into spasms again, which has been the
problem the last couple of weeks. Then I had trouble reaching up
for the serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough call about retiring or trying to play through it.
Dominique was playing well. She might have beaten me if I'd been
100 percent. It's the first time I've played a major with something
really wrong. But I really wanted to play. I've never quit a
match.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport was the first No. 2 to fall in the first round since
Virginia Wade was beaten by Louisianan Linda Tuero in 1971. ``I'm
just going to rest,'' Davenport said, ``and I'm sure I'll be ready
for Wimbledon.''
</P>
<P>
   Gone was her shot at this year's Grand Slam. ``The French has
been my goal since I've won the other three majors,'' she said.
``But my mind-set was to just survive out there today.'' That she
did, in reputation as a true-blue champ.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay's conqueror, No. 20 Van Roost, was nursed back to mental
stability by her live-in coach, husband Bart Van Roost, after her
mother's long ordeal with cancer. ``We had to work hard, very hard
for me to get back,'' she said. ``Down deep I felt I didn't want to
be hurt again. But everything came together two or three days ago.
I have a lot of luck to have a husband like Bart, a real support.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominique and Bart were the Juliet and Romeo of Belgium when
they married to the tune of great ``political disapproval,'' she
said. She is Walloon, he Flemish. ``For many Belgians it is a no-no
to mix the two. But people get over that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish kings of France, Bruguera (1992-93) and Moya (1998),
were chased by peasants named Juan Balcells, a No. 97 qualifier,
and Hernan Gumy, No. 88.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, he's a cuddly Gummy bear,'' proclaimed a female viewer as
the handsome Argentine outlasted Moya, 7-6 (7-4), 6-2, 4-6, 3-6,
6-3, in 3 hours 37 minutes. ``Just a warmup _ remember '98?'' said
Gumy, who lost the most unending of French jousts, to Alex Corretja
in 5:31 two years ago. Balcell's act of lese majeste against
Bruguera _ 6-3, 5-7, 6-2, 1-6, 6-0 _ was even more pronounced since
he, too, is a Spaniard.
</P>
<P>
   But two endangered kings escaped. Michael Chang, the prodigy at
17 in 1989, is spinning his once-marvelous wheels these days, but
won his second-rounder over Swede Thomas Johansson, 7-6 (7-2), 7-6
(7-5), 2-6, 6-3. Russian Yevgeny Kafelnikov, victorious in 1996,
and tied with Rios in the sourness league, finished sweetly enough
over yet another of those rising Argentines, Mariano Zabaleta, 6-2,
3-6, 6-7 (6-8), 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe none of them felt better than the young woman playing for
a gathering 43 of the day's 32,229 patrons, way out in the boonies,
Court 20. That was dauntless campaigner de Lone of Lincoln, Mass.,
with ``the best win of my life'' _ 6-3, 6-2 over the sturdy
Austrian lefthander, Barbara Schwartz, who toppled Venus Williams a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I waited a long time for my first win in Paris,'' said de
Lone. ``Eleven years. I usually lost in qualifying. But I did
qualify twice, but then didn't win. But I didn't have to do that
this year with my No. 75 ranking.''
</P>
<P>
   As she hooked a troublesome serve on match point, her
stepfather, John Plukas, murmured, ``Now I can breathe again.''
</P>
<P>
   So could the French Open, recovered from the Tuesday deluge.
</P>
<P>
   Bud Collins is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
