u f BC-INTERNET-FUTURE-BOS &LR;      05-31 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-FUTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN SOME OF WEB'S BIGGEST FANS ARE FEELING THE BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ The Internet Blahs are upon us.
</P>
<P>
   The bursting Net-stock bubble has imploded the Nasdaq stock
index. Half of all e-retailers will be dead in a year, reputable
analysts predict. Online shopping and Web surfing feel more and
more like a giant conspiracy to reduce people to narrowly
pigeonholed targets for banner ads and spam mail.
</P>
<P>
   And the recent news that the World Wide Web now counts over 1
billion pages seemed no milestone in human wisdom. Just more
useless material to clog up our search engines when we simply want
to find a good recipe for marinara sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of the Internet's biggest champions are feeling the
blues these days, if the mood at the opening of Harvard
University's third conference on The Internet and Society Wednesday
was a good barometer.
</P>
<P>
   As dozens of leading academics and business people flocked to
Harvard for three days of symposia on how the Net can reshape
everything from education to medicine to urban design, Wednesday's
opening sessions on the future of the Net were dominated by
lamentations of what has gone wrong so far _ with only a few
glimmers of hope for recovering the golden-promise days.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's almost a backlash right now, sort of an enormous
hangover and a retreat from the kind of giddy euphoria'' that
dominated the early and mid-1990s view of the Net's possibilities,
Lotus Development Corp. founder Mitch Kapor said in a speech he
dubbed ``the confessions of a recovering technological utopian.''
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, in the years after he discovered an early e-mail
community in the San Francisco Bay area, ``I made a number of
speeches in which I said the Internet was going to make everything
better. As we know, that didn't exactly happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard president Neil L. Rudenstine, meanwhile, rejected
suggestions that long-distance learning over the Net will some day
replace traditional colleges and universities. Despite all the ways
the Net has enhanced traditional higher education, in-person
teaching is still ``the most powerful'' mode of education, he said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 Harvard courses now have extensive Web sites,
Harvard's business school is pioneering new Web-based midcareer
development programs for executives, and e-mail has revolutionized
communications among students and teachers at every school,
Rudenstine said.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Net has enhanced old-line colleges and
universities, ``campus-based residential learning, at least for the
undergraduate and first-degree graduate level, is here to stay,''
Rudenstine said. He said there are too many aspects of college
education, such as learning to appreciate diversity, that ``it's
hard to imagine could be carried out online.''
</P>
<P>
   Pattie Maes, an associate professor in the Media Lab at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, said she once believed the
Net would usher in four world-changing trends: leveling the playing
field for small businesses to compete against the large, bringing
``power to the people,'' offering highly personalized information,
and serving as the ``collective mind'' of curious humans
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't exactly say that all these visions have become
reality,'' Maes said. ``Maybe they are becoming delusions.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea the average person could sell cookies from her kitchen
over the Net, Maes said, has given way to the reality that the
e-commerce world is dominated by ``whoever spends tons of millions
of dollars on advertising.'' One example is the music industry
which, by trying to squelch the Napster music-pirating software, is
showing the Net is not necessarily liberating the proletariat.
</P>
<P>
   Maes said using the Web to get personalized information now
seems like a sure route to mailbox-clogging advertising spam or an
uncomfortably high level of disclosure about people's hobbies and
interests.
</P>
<P>
   And rather than bringing people into a wealth of global
knowledge, Maes said, ``We all suffer from this so-called
information overload. It's extremely hard to find quality
information'' on the Web now.
</P>
<P>
   In each of the four areas of failed promise, Maes said,
specialists at the Media Lab and elsewhere are working on
solutions, with daunting titles such as ``communityware'' and
``collaborative ontology editors.''
</P>
<P>
   Maes's description gave no suggestion a silver bullet is in the
works to solve the Net epidemics of overcommercialization, hype,
and infogarbage. But, she said, ``We're basically all idealists. We
want to make sure this medium will change society for the better.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the pessimism was hardly monolithic. Even Kapor
said, ``There are things about the Internet you have to love if you
have a beating human heart.'' He cited a recent news account of
fishermen in India who now get life-saving weather forecasts for
the Bay of Bengal from a US Navy Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is very much like the cooking business,'' said
Esther Dyson, chairman of EDventure Holdings and interim chairwoman
of the international governing body that assigns dot-com and
dot-net names.
</P>
<P>
   News accounts are dominated by what's happening at the online
equivalents of McDonald's or the fanciest restaurants in Boston and
New York, Dyson said. ``But even as you read about these things,
there's a huge amount of home cooking going on that you never read
about. That's what's really going on on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Berners-Lee, who invented the World Wide Web in 1989 and now
holds a research chair at MIT's Laboratory for Computer Science,
dismissed a question about the proliferation of irrelevant pages on
the Web, saying that the good sites ``are still there. You just
have to have the presence of mind to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapor said he senses, everywhere from the capital markets to the
community of Web surfers, that ``the pendulum is now swinging back
to the middle, having been at the extremes of Internet hype.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
