<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1198 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-PHONE-CHARGES-ART-940     05-31 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONE-CHARGES-ART-940(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATORS CLEAR WIDE-RANGING CUTS IN TELEPHONE FEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo _ NYT20 _ is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal government and many of the nation's
leading telephone companies announced an agreement on Wednesday for
a sweeping reshuffling of phone rates that would dramatically
reduce the bills of tens of millions of less affluent consumers and
lead to less significant cuts for other consumers and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the reductions, part of an agreement and an order
by the Federal Communications Commission, amounted to the largest
rate cut in the story of federal telephone regulation.
</P>
<P>
   They said the cuts would have their biggest impact on the poor
and those who use their phones the least. Rates would be reduced by
as much as 50 percent for Americans who make few or no
long-distance calls.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers and businesses that make more long distance calls,
the government predicted reduced costs, although some consumer
groups and Wall Street analysts disagreed with the government's
estimates, suggesting they were too rosy.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said that they had a commitment from the
long- distance companies to pass on to consumers the benefits of
$3.2 billion in savings from a reduction in the access payments
they make to local telephone companies.
</P>
<P>
   And officials said that experience had demonstrated that when
access charges were last reduced three years ago, the long-distance
companies began engaging in a price war that dramatically lowered
overall phone rates.
</P>
<P>
   But critics and analysts said long-distance companies had been
slow to pass on all of the savings when access charges had been
cut, and that the benefit to consumers from the price wars had been
offset by new fees tacked onto their bills.
</P>
<P>
   Critics and officials agreed, however, that Wednesday's action
would fundamentally reshape the economics of the telephone industry
and marked another major step towards deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   It also is part of an evolution towards a new pricing structure
in which long-distance rates will ultimately be like wireless and
Internet service rates _ either a flat monthly fee or a fee that
entitles the customer to a bundle of minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's announcement is a giant step forward in rationalizing
pricing,'' said William E. Kennard, chairman of the FCC. ``This is
the most dramatic reduction in telephone service prices in the
history of this agency.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennard said the price changes would take effect in July and
that the order was an effort to accelerate competition by ending
several implicit subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement and order is the product of more than a year of
intense negotiations between local and long-distance companies and
federal regulators on issues that have divided the local and
long-distance providers from the moment they were created with the
breakup of AT&AMP;T 16 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone executives from most of the nation's top companies
also applauded the order.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the results of today's action start showing up on
customer bills in a month or so, consumers will see that the total
cost of local and long-distance telephone service will be down,''
Duane Ackerman, chairman and chief executive of Bell South, said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time,'' he said, ``those customers who live in
rural areas that are expensive to serve and those people who need
help paying their phone bills will be ensured affordable service
well into the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that ultimately the companies reached an
agreement with each other and regulators because of a variety of
important trends, including the blurring of lines between local and
long-distance companies, the competitive threats posed by the
emergence of telephone service on the Internet, and the heavy
pressure put on regulators by a Republican Congress to reduce
regulations and let the marketplace play a greater role in setting
prices.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the agreement, AT&AMP;T said it would eliminate the $3
minimum monthly fee that it charges to millions of customers who
make few or no long- distance calls.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with other changes announced on Wednesday, a typical
monthly bill for an AT&AMP;T customer who makes no long-distance calls
would be cut in half, to $4.68 from $9.39. A customer who made 10
minutes of long-distance calls would have total monthly charges
decrease by 27 percent, from $9.39 to $6.87.
</P>
<P>
   The order simplifies telephone bills by folding two separate
charges _ one for the cost of telephone lines and the other a
special access charge _ into one. It reduces an earlier announced
rate hike for the combined items by 66 cents a month.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the agreement, spelled out in the summary of
an order that will soon be issued by the commission, reduces by
$3.2 billion the access charges that long-distance companies such
as AT&AMP;T and Sprint pay to local telephone companies such as Bell
Atlantic in order to use their lines at the beginning and end of a
call. The reduction amounts to about a 25 percent cut in access
fees paid to the local companies.
</P>
<P>
   Commission officials said they could not precisely quantify how
much heavy long-distance callers might save, and some analysts and
consumer groups said they doubted that many of the savings would
result in dramatically lower bills. ``We hope that the FCC will
monitor this process to ensure that the $3.2 billion in
long-distance company savings are translated into demonstrable
price reductions for consumers,'' said Gene Kimmelman, co-director
of the Washington office of Consumers Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's decision is a clear benefit for people who make few or
no long- distance calls,'' he said. ``But it still leaves consumers
paying inflated monthly charges.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Scott C. Cleland, a telecommunications analyst at the Legg Mason
Precursor Group, said that experience had shown that the companies
had not passed on savings from reductions in access charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The companies have a fiduciary responsibility to their
shareholders to not necessarily pass them on,'' Cleland said. ``To
the extent that prices don't fall, these savings increase
long-distance profits. The companies may pass them on, but it will
be over time.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry executives said that the decision was part of a trend
that will inevitably lead to long distance fees resembling the fees
now charged by Internet companies and cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pricing structure that these rules permit allows us to
moev more in the direction that will ultimately lead to Internet
pricing or wireless pricing in the long-distance market,'' said
John Nakahata, a former top official at the FCC and spokesman for
the coalition of telephone companies that signed the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the fee changes, local telephone companies stand
to see a short-term shortfall of as much as $500 million over the
next year. But industry executives and analysts said that lower
prices should increase demand more than enough to offset the
shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This industry is growing at a rapid rate and we're all
realizing significant cost reductions,'' said Frank Gumper, vice
president of regulatory and long-range planning at Bell Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   In a partial dissent to Wednesday's order, one commissioner
accused the staff of the FCC of making improper side-deals with the
telephone industry in order to gain its support for the order.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner, Harold Furchtgott-Roth, said that in exchange
for the industry's support, the staff had agreed waive certain
onerous depreciation rules and rule favorably in a separate access
fee proceeding. Both proceedings involve billions of dollars to the
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be clear, I do not believe that any employee of this agency
acted in bad faith'' Furchtgott-Roth wrote. ``But I cannot escape
the conclusion that the process by which this notice has been
promulgated falls short of certain fundamental principles that
govern the behavior of administrative agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Both industry lobbyists and staff officials denied that any
separate deals had been reached.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
