<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1201 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-MENTAL-HEALTH-AR     05-31 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-MENTAL-HEALTH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE EXPLAINS HIS MENTAL HEALTH POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
 (With MRSGORE-MENTAL-HEALTH) 
(ART ADV: Photo NTY23 has being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRIENDSHIP HEIGHTS, Md. _ Pledging to make mental health care a
priority in his administration, Vice President Al Gore on Wednesday
called for legislation that would force insurance companies to
provide children with comparable coverage for mental illnesses as
for physical ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing with his wife, Tipper, before a group of mental health
professionals and advocates in suburban Washington, Gore described
his proposal for children as a first step toward eliminating
disparities in mental health coverage for adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``People still have insurance plans that actively discriminate
against mental health,'' he said. ``They still don't recognize it
as a treatable illness, just like diabetes or high blood pressure
or heart disease.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was part of a package of mental health programs,
some of them not new, that Gore outlined on Wednesday. Those
measures included training teachers and police officers to identify
mental illness, expanding community mental health services and
creating a $3,000 tax credit for families to pay for long-term
care, including in mental institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Achieving parity in insurance benefits for mental and physical
illnesses has become a legislative goal of mental health advocates,
who contend inadequate insurance coverage has discouraged many sick
people from seeking treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1996 law, group health plans are forbidden to set annual
or lifetime dollar limits on mental health care that are lower than
the limits for general medical and surgical services. But a
congressional report released two weeks ago found that thousands of
companies were violating the law.
</P>
<P>
   Some insurance companies have also skirted the law's
requirements by simply replacing the old dollar limits on mental
health care with numerical limits on outpatient visits, treatment
sessions or days in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation with bipartisan support in Congress would try to
close such loopholes by prohibiting insurers from setting limits on
the number of outpatient visits or days in the hospital for
treatment of mental disorders that are more stringent than those
for the treatment of physical illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Wednesday, Gore suggested he would support a
version of that legislation, but focused only on children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to close any loopholes that allow insurers to shirk
their obligations under the law,'' he said. But he did not offer
specifics.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's Republican presidential opponent, Gov. George W. Bush,
signed legislation in Texas in 1997 requiring health insurers to
provide comparable coverage for mental disorders as for physical
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   But Dan Bartlett, a Bush spokesman, said the governor has not
said whether he would support similar federal legislation. Bartlett
added, ``Governor Bush understands the importance of mental health
parity.'' Opponents of Gore's proposal, including many business
groups, argue that it would significantly increase the cost of
health insurance, potentially causing some employers, particularly
smaller ones, to drop their policies. Gore estimated that his plan
for children would increase premiums by less than 1 percent, but
the opponents said the figure could be five times that much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you increase costs, you cause people to drop
coverage, and the end result is more people without insurance,''
Frank Coleman, vice president for media relations for the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce. ``The question is, do we want Cadillac
coverage, or do we want to find ways to insure the 40 million
people without coverage, who mostly work for small businesses?''
</P>
<P>
   But mental health advocates heralded Gore's proposal as a
crucial step toward eliminating discrimination against the mentally
ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's put his finger on a major problem,'' said Laurie Flynn,
executive director for the National Alliance of the Mentally Ill, a
nonprofit group. ``The lack of adequate coverage brings enormous
economic hardships to families. They can quickly run through
savings, forcing them to re-mortgage houses and dip into college
funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore refrained from criticizing, or even mentioning, Bush at
Wednesday morning's event. Indeed, in sharp contrast to his gloomy
attacks on Bush, Gore was almost relentlessly upbeat, repeatedly
describing the current times as ``exciting,'' ``optimistic'' and
``hopeful'' for people with mental illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly believe there has never been a more hopeful time for
mental health care in America,'' Gore said. ``We are on the very of
a new era that will bring revolutionary change.''
</P>
<P>
   But the vice president did not hesitate to ask the crowd to
support him, saying that he wanted a ``mandate'' to make mental
health a priority in his administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what elections are all about,'' he said. ``Deciding
among ourselves the kinds of changes that we're willing to fight
for, that we are willing to make a priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the shootings at Columbine High School last year
provided evidence that the federal government needs to help schools
train teachers to identify mentally ill students and to hire mental
health counselors.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Columbine taught us, we can't wait until tragedy strikes to
reach out effectively to troubled young people and give them help
and hope,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
