u f BC-LAWSUIT-MARKETPLACE-N     05-31 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWSUIT-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: KLEIN LAWSUIT PUTS WARNECO IN A BIND 
</HEADLINE>
   By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Calvin Klein Inc. has filed suit to break a licensing
pact with the Warnaco Group Inc., which makes its underwear and
jeans brands, in what many industry insiders consider an act of
vengeance against the flint-tough chief executive of Warnaco, Linda
J. Wachner.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, Klein and his long-time partner Barry Schwartz
engaged the investment firm of Lazard Freres to find a buyer for
their private company. Tommy Hilfiger Inc., Liz Claiborne and
Warnaco were among the companies that expressed interest. But none
was willing to bite at Klein's asking price, said to be $1 billion.
Part of the problem was that the brand was already highly exposed _
Klein's name appears on everything from sunglasses to bed linens _
and therefore did not offer prospective buyers an obvious path for
dynamic future growth.
</P>
<P>
   But Klein's long-term licensing deal with Warnaco complicated
the picture as well. Warnaco accounted for some $1 billion of the
$2.5 billion in Calvin Klein products sold wholesale in 1999, and
Wachner has pressed for more control of design and distribution.
While Klein insists that he could have sold the company if he
wanted to and that the new lawsuit is unrelated, he says that
Wachner scared off prospective partners. ``People have told us that
they were hesitant to have a relationship with Linda Wachner,'' he
said in an interview Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Wachner insists that Klein's lawsuit, filed in U.S. District
Court in New York on late Tuesday, was a complete surprise and that
she first learned of it Tuesday night by phone call while in a
design meeting in the offices of Calvin Klein Inc. ``One must
wonder why having tried and failed to sell their business that they
have adopted this tact now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   David Wolfe, creative director of The Doneger Group, a retail
consulting firm, and one of the many people in New York's Garment
District enjoying the fight, put it bluntly: ``This is about
Calvin's failure to cut a deal. He is kicking her while she is one
the defensive. He grew up in the Bronx. He is a streetwise kid. It
will really be fascinating to watch it play out.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks to terminate Warnaco's long-term license to
make Calvin Klein jeans on the grounds that the company has
breached its fiduciary duty by ``diluting''the quality of Klein's
image. Among the specific infractions cited is selling new products
through unauthorized mass-marketers like Costco and B.J.'s. and
affixing the Klein name to products made by other designers or
products designed by Klein but altered without his consent.
</P>
<P>
   Klein and Schwartz insist the suit is an instrument of last
resort, after years of complaints through letters, personal
meetings and lawyers. Schwartz said the issue came to a head in
March when Warnaco handed over a list of its retail clients, and
the top six, which accounted for over $200 million in sales in
1999, were unauthorized off-priced outlets. ``It was clear to us
then that this was a pre-meditated strategy to destroy the
trademark,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wachner says she is baffled by Klein's allegations. ``I am not
going to respond to a lawsuit I have not yet seen,'' said Wachner,
`` but it is without merit.'' She added that all Warnaco's
licensing and royalty agreements have been clearly known to the
Klein partners since last fall, when they requested the information
to share with perspective buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is a liar,'' Schwartz responded. ``She can say anything
she wants to the press, but let her say that in court.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the merits of the suit, the timing could not be more
devastating to Wachner. Warnaco, which produces underwear and
clothing under numerous names beside Klein's, has seen its stock
price plunge for almost a year, as the company has repeatedly
missed earnings estimates. Wednesday, the news of Klein's suit
pushed the stock to a 52-week low of $6.688, down from a high of
nearly $30 a share last June. Wachner, whose compensation ranks
among the top chief executives in the nation despite her company's
dismal performance, is already a target of irate shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint singled out Wachner as the source of friction
between the companies. It called her ``abusive and
unprofessional,'' a topic Klein angrily expanded on in an
interview. ``She runs it like a monarchy,'' Klein said of Wachner's
performance at Warnaco. ``She is abusive to our people. Verbally,
the language is disgusting.''
</P>
<P>
   At least in the short term, the Klein suit will surely put the
already cash-strapped Warnaco into more of a bind. ``No one is
going to step into the gap and be by her side financially,'' said
Josie Esquivel, who is a stock analyst at Morgan Stanley. However,
the long-term effect will depend on how the court rules, and
long-time Wachner watchers don't count her out. ``She has shown
great wherewithal,'' Esquivel noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
