<SLUG> BC-MRSGORE-MENTAL-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIPPER GORE STEPS INTO THE SPOTLIGHT AT MENTAL HEALTH FORUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (With GORE-MENTAL-HEALTH) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRIENDSHIP HEIGHTS, Md. _ After having kept a low profile on the
campaign trail in recent months, Tipper Gore, the wife of Vice
President Al Gore, emerged Wednesday in the kind of setting where
she clearly feels most comfortable: a forum on mental health
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Tipper Gore has never seemed to relish the campaign trail,
trying to maintain her privacy beyond the glare of the public
spotlight trained on her husband. ``I think the way for people to
understand me the best is for you to understand that I'm not really
of the political milieu,'' she told a reporter last year.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore has also taken an increasingly public role as an
advocate for mental health care, serving as an adviser to President
Clinton and helping to organize the first White House Conference on
Mental Health last year.
</P>
<P>
   So Wednesday's appearance before a group of mental health
professional in suburban Washington, where she shared a stage and a
microphone with her husband, offered the perfect blending of
politics and policy, an opportunity to promote her pet issue and
her husband's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a president who understands the importance of health
care and mental health care,'' she told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, she added, did not just care about mental health in
the abstract. ``He has lived it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That was a reference to her own battle with depression, which
she disclosed in a newspaper article a year ago. In that article,
Gore said she had been treated for depression after the couple's
6-year-old son was severely injured in an automobile accident in
1989. Her aides say she is no longer under treatment.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Gore _ who earned a master's degree in
psychology from Vanderbilt University _ described the disclosure of
her depression as a liberating experience. Since then, people
ranging from airline stewardesses to Congressmen have told her that
she had helped them discuss their mental problems openly, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I've been treated differently,'' she said, ``is people
approaching me, being happy, being joyful and open, saying, `Thank
you, thank you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's appearance Wednesday fit neatly into efforts by her
husband's campaign this week to cast the vice president _ who has
come under criticism from some Democrats as overly negative on the
stump _ in a more positive, family-oriented light. But both Gores
bristled at the suggestion that Wednesday's event was in any way
choreographed by his advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This event's been planned for months,'' the vice president
said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Wednesday's event, and then during the joint
interview, the Gores were a picture of mutual solicitousness,
stepping out of each other's way in answering questions and
praising each other's commitment to the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should know that I agree with everything she says,'' the
vice president said in the interview. Without missing a beat, his
wife replied, ``But he sets the policy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 2106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0361 </DOCNO>
