<HEADER>
A1210 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-RANGERS-NYT &LR;      05-31 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SATHER APPOINTMENT EXPECTED TO USHER IN NEW RANGER ERA 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After nearly a month of negotiations with Madison
Square Garden President Dave Checketts and Cablevision boss James
Dolan, Glen Sather will be formally introduced Thursday as the New
York Rangers' new team president and general manager at a Madison
Square Garden news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Several National Hockey League officials confirmed that Sather
had agreed to a five-year contract believed to be worth $15
million, including stock options in Cablevision.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely got complete control,'' a league official said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 56-year-old Sather, who flew to New York from his La Quinta,
Calif., home Wednesday with his wife, Ann, was customarily coy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now why do you think they're having a news conference?''
Sather asked with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Sather's first assignment would be to try to persuade Kevin Lowe
to coach the Rangers. One person close to Sather said that he had
asked Lowe, who was Sather's head coach in Edmonton last season, to
meet him in New York Wednesday, so that he could introduce him as
the Rangers' new head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe, the person said, declined because he needed more time to
make a decision. Edmonton's 37-man ownership group has asked Lowe
to succeed Sather as general manager. Lowe said he would probably
make up his mind early next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see it going much longer than that,'' Lowe said
Wednesday. ``It's 50-50 either way. But more so, it's do I want to
be a general manager or a coach, rather than New York or
Edmonton.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision for Sather was simpler. He set it in motion himself
when he chose to resign his posts as team president and general
manager in Edmonton, May 19, after 24 years in the Oilers'
organization, the last 21 as general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Sather had grown tired of having to answer to 37 owners,
especially after Cal Nichols succeeded Sather's good friend, Jim
Hole, as chairman of the Edmonton ownership group. In New York,
Sather will still have to answer to Checketts, a league official
said. But Sather will also be given a wide berth within which to
work in his new role.
</P>
<P>
   Once Sather indicated to The New York Times, on April 19, that
he would listen to offers from other teams, it became immediately
apparent that he was the Rangers' first and only choice to succeed
Neil Smith. Smith was fired as Rangers' president and general
manager, March 28, along with Coach John Muckler.
</P>
<P>
   Sather, Checketts and Dolan first met in the first week of May
and have met and spoken several times since. There is a certain
irony in Sather's acceptance of the Rangers' offer, however. For
years, in Edmonton, he was the outspoken champion of small-market
Canadian teams, a fiscal conservative who routinely criticized the
free-spending ways of teams like the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   And now, Sather is taking over a team with a seemingly unlimited
budget _ a league record $61.2 million last season _ and attempting
to lure Lowe to come with him, presumably with the just the kind of
offer that incensed Sather when he was in Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers do represent a very different sort of challenge for
Sather, who played left wing for the Rangers for parts of four
seasons from 1970-73. As a coach and general manager, Sather
assembled the Oilers' dynasty that won five Stanley Cups. But the
Oilers, mired in fiscal constraints, won their last cup in 1990.
This is Sather's chance to prove that, given the resources, he has
not lost his touch.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have not qualified for the playoffs the last three
seasons, since Mark Messier left the team in a messy divorce in the
summer of 1997. Sather's hiring is the surest sign yet that
Messier, who led the Rangers to their first Stanley Cup in 54 years
in 1994, will return to the Rangers this summer and be allowed to
finish his career in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Messier, who will become a free agent July 1, if Vancouver does
not pick up the $6 million option on his contract, was the
unquestioned leader of all five of Edmonton's cup winners, and
their captain in 1990. Lowe was Messier's teammate on all five of
those cup-winning teams in Edmonton, and again with the Rangers
when they won in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Those Rangers were known as Edmonton East. The Rangers have been
looking to the Oilers' organization to right their ills ever since.
</P>
<P>
   And with all the Rangers have to offer Lowe financially, could
Lowe be far behind?
</P>
<P>
   Lowe made $450,000 in Edmonton this season, and will make
$625,000 next season. Sather could easily double the likely
$700,000 the Oilers are believed to be offering him to become their
general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in the process of negotiating,'' Nichols said
Wednesday. ``We mutually are intending to get somewhat close if we
can by the weekend. And even if we don't have an agreement, we hope
to have enough to say we think we're there. That's our intention.''
</P>
<P>
   Sather obviously has very different intentions. And Nichols has
indicated many times in the last two weeks that he would not ask
the Rangers for any compensation if Lowe accompanies Sather to New
York. Both Lowe and his assistant coach, Craig MacTavish, became
free agents once Sather resigned.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if it comes down to that,'' Lowe said, meaning that he
chooses to continue coaching, ``I would be happy to accept the
challenge. I would love to come back to New York. But let's cross
that bridge when we come to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 2107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1213 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-R-EMAIL-POLITICS-ART-     05-31 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-EMAIL-POLITICS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-MAIL'S EMERGENCE TURNS BUSH-GORE RACE INTO CYBERWAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending to add art note)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Gore Coverup Revealed!'' read the headline on the e-mail
message from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The five-paragraph missive, beamed into electronic mailboxes of
reporters across the country last week, was another swipe at Vice
President Al Gore by the Republican National Committee. But it was
not a suggestion of political corruption or obstruction of justice
that had prompted the official Republican bulletin. It was a report
that Gore wore makeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can't be Naomi Wolf's idea of an alpha male!'' the
message quoted Jim Nicholson, the Republican national chairman, as
having joked about a recent article in People magazine that said
Gore used spray-on cosmetics.
</P>
<P>
   Hour by hour, the e-mail arrives like digital daggers from the
candidates and their parties. Catty, pithy, weighty, gossipy, the
messages materialize via the open cyberfaucet of the 2000 campaign.
``Bush's Million Mom Manipulation,'' began a message from the
Democrats. ``Democrat Fat Cat Discriminates Against Those Who Flee
Castro's Clutches,'' read one from the Republicans. ``New York
Honor Guard Spat On at Clinton Nomination,'' read another.
</P>
<P>
   Only by extension is the target of the computer missives the
American voter. The more immediate audience is the American
journalist. ``Day 52: Reporters Held Hostage!'' screamed the
headline of e-mail from the Republican National Committee in April.
One of a series of such messages from the committee, it was
intended to remind the press that the vice president had not held a
news conference in 52 days. Under an illustration of political
writers from Newsweek and The Washington Post in the stocks, it
implored, ``Mr. Gore, please let these reporters go!''
</P>
<P>
   Campaigns, of course, have always whispered nasty little
nothings about the opposition into reporters' ears. But just as
e-mail has ushered in a new era of epistolary ease and
connectedness for the world at large, it has also created a
hyper-efficient form of press release, a paperless document that
not only links the political world to the nation's assignment
editors, columnists and news anchors in seconds, but also allows
the campaigns to fire at each other at will, all day long.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, a presidential campaign is no longer so much a
series of stops as an endless wave. Gaze at the laptop screen of
any political reporter on the road these days and see how rapidly
campaign e-mail accumulates: the Message of the Day has given way
to the Message of the Last 10 Minutes. And, not surprisingly, in
the proliferation of messages comes all manner of information:
useful, irrelevant or irreverent.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson's alpha-male crack, for instance, made it onto the
Perspectives page of the current issue of Newsweek, and the
``reporters held hostage'' messages were noted by several
newspapers and television commentators in April. (Late that month,
after the count had passed 60 days, Gore held a news conference.)
</P>
<P>
   The ability to express so much is transforming campaign
back-and-forth into a kind of online bile duct.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything keeps speeding up, and becoming less profound in
the process,'' said Howard Fineman, a political analyst for
Newsweek and MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Like many reporters, Fineman is ambivalent about all this
e-mail, perplexed by the tone and the volume but anxious about the
consequences of not receiving it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have several e-mail addresses,'' he said, ``and I just keep
establishing new ones to get away from the old ones. And maybe once
a week, I manfully press the `control-A' combination, which
highlights all of the e-mail, and then I hit the delete button.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' he added, ``in the spirit of confession, I have
to say that when I found that I wasn't on the latest version of the
Gore campaign's e-mail list, I called them up and gave them a piece
of my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Any political operation of any importance today is online with a
vengeance, and e-mail has become the baseline conveyance that the
telephone and the fax machine once were. (Mention old-fashioned,
Postal Service-type mail to campaign press secretaries, and they
burst into laughter.)
</P>
<P>
   The message via computer is equal parts invasive and discreet.
``Right now, people take it more like a phone call than a press
release,'' observed Clifford D. May, director of communications for
the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is, it's a phone call that's not in real
time,'' he added. ``So I may e-mail to financial columnists that Al
Gore says he owns no stocks whatsoever: `Either he's not telling
the truth or he's a financial dolt. Don't you think you should
write about it?'''
</P>
<P>
   The advantage? ``You're not interrupting someone on deadline. I
suppose you could do that on a voice mail, but on e-mail you can
take your time to compose the message, to make it as persuasive as
you possibly can.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporters are by training disposed to discount the persuasion of
the press release. But the campaigns and their allies insist that
e-mail has made it easier to get their story into print or on the
air faster. Jennifer Backus, press secretary for the Democratic
National Committee, said that as the first round of news-agency
accounts was transmitted during Republican presidential debates in
the primary season, her staff would immediately respond to those
accounts by sending e-mail to the writers _ and could see the
results as quickly as the next cycle of reports that evening. By
then, she said, the reports were reflecting the Democrats' own
assessment of the Republican debate.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And in the game of rapid response _ getting your message out
before your opponent's can make an impact _ e-mail delivered with
surgical precision can pre-emptively alter the flow of a major
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was funny,'' said Craig Crawford, editor in chief of the
online political digest Hotline. ``My e-mail sound file is from
`2001: A Space Odyssey,' and early one morning HAL goes, `You have
received a message.' It was Al Gore's people with a response to the
Social Security plan that Bush put out.''
</P>
<P>
   The oddity was that the message arrived before Gov. George W.
Bush held the news conference where he formally unveiled his
proposal to partly privatize Social Security. ``Before the sun was
up, I had Bush's plan and Gore's response,'' Crawford said.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, press secretary for the Gore campaign, says the
strategy, which he calls ``pre-buttal'' _ had the desired effect;
the degree to which major newspapers reflected Gore's objections
surprised even Lehane. Normally, he said, as much as 90 percent of
the content might be devoted to the candidate making the proposal.
With the rapid response, he said, ``my sense is you get 60-40
play.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a rollicking tabloid gusto in the tone of campaign
e-mail, whether the Bush campaign is reinforcing the idea that Gore
stretches the truth (in its continuing series ``The Gore
Detector'') or the Gore campaign is hammering away at Bush's record
in Texas (``one of the dirtiest states in the nation'').
</P>
<P>
   In a message posted last Friday, the Democratic National
Committee renewed its daily efforts to get under Bush's skin with
the suggestion that his campaign was trying to conceal a deeply
conservative agenda. ``Today marks eight days that George W. Bush
has refused to release a tape copy or a transcript of remarks he
made to a far-right conservative organization last October,'' the
message said.
</P>
<P>
   It arrived minutes before a Bush campaign bulletin intimating
that Gore was not telling voters the truth about his Social
Security plans, that he would either raise taxes or cut retirement
benefits. Earlier in the day, the Gore campaign went online to say
Bush had spoken to the Catholic Press Association ``without
mentioning his very public embrace of anti-Catholic Bob Jones
University during the Republican primary.'' Which came on the heels
of Bush e-mail that summed up the week's events as ``Bush Leads,
Gore Flounders.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only can e-mail circulate instantly, its recipients can
forward it instantly: the virtual equivalent of stuffing fliers
under thousands of windshields simultaneously. Campaign spokesmen
say this can make the technology a useful way to talk to their rank
and file as well as to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The parties and the campaigns maintain that so far, e-mail to
those supporters has been used as a means of circulating favorable
news articles and marshaling the troops rather than as a tactical
weapon against an opponent. ``When Gore was going to a specific
part of the country,'' Lehane said, ``we used e-mail to recruit
volunteers to go.''
</P>
<P>
   It can also be just plain fun. Along with posting presidential
candidate schedules (``The vice president remains overnight in
Memphis'') and innocuous news tidbits (``Wisconsin Veterans Back
Bush''), the campaigns engage in an endless cyberspace version of
trash talk.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee, in installments of a feature
called ``Bush Lite,'' makes merciless sport of Bush's semantic
gaffes and failures to communicate. ``Bush Confused Canadian Prime
Minister With Canadian Cheese Curd Snack Treat,'' read an item that
the Democrats posted on April 24.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee replies with a daily watch of
Gore's lack of formal endorsement by former Sen. Bill Bradley.
``Missing,'' says the mock-up of a milk carton with the likeness of
Bradley and the words ``Got endorsement?'' emblazoned on the side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sophomoric humor is a huge piece of this,'' Lehane said.
``It's got to go so over the top that people pay attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Short attention spans are, after all, another hallmark of the
age of instant media gratification, an age when the saddest fate to
befall a short and punchy computer message is that it be ignored. A
fate that is alas inevitable for some electronic mail when messages
are arriving in batches faster than you can say ``download.''
</P>
<P>
   As May, the Republican spokesman, himself acknowledged, ``I have
188 unread e-mails in my queue at the moment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
