<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-EXECUTE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PLANNING TO GRANT TEMPORARY REPRIEVE TO DEATH ROW INMATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: The 2nd take is scheduled to move by 9:45 p.m. ET) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr. with FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas said Wednesday that he was
``more than likely'' to grant a temporary reprieve for a man
scheduled to be executed on Thursday so that DNA evidence in the
case could be tested. It would be the first such stay Bush has
issued as governor.
</P>
<P>
   The case of Ricky Nolen McGinn, 43, who was convicted of raping
and killing his 12-year-old stepdaughter in 1993, has slowly and
quietly been working its way through the Texas legal system. But
with Bush, a vigorous supporter of the death penalty, now the
presumptive Republican presidential nominee, the case has begun to
take on political significance. Bush made his statements about the
case a day after the Texas Court of Criminal Appeals, the the
state's highest criminal court, refused to accept the
recommendation of a lower court that the execution be delayed so
sophisticated DNA tests could be conducted. The appeals court gave
no reason for its refusal.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush told reporters covering his campaign that he was
inclined to grant a 30-day reprieve so that McGinn could ``have his
full day in court.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that DNA can help in innocence or guilt,
particularly in death penalty cases, but in all cases, I think
that's very valid, very important,'' he said at a news conference
in Scottsdale, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he was telegraphing his intentions before making a
final decision, he said: ``I believe this is a case where it's
important for me to send a signal about what I may do because it's
a case where we're dealing with a man's innocence or guilt.'' As
Bush was talking about the case, the state's Board of Pardons and
Paroles, whose members he appoints, voted 11-7 against recommending
a reprieve. But the governor is not bound by it. At McGinn's trial
five years ago, DNA tests of hair and semen samples taken from the
body and clothing of the victim, Stephanie Rae Flanary, were
inconclusive. But lawyers for McGinn, who says he is innocent, say
advances in DNA testing could now yield conclusive results if the
evidence were retested.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office, Bush has overseen 130 executions _ more
executions than any other governor in the nation _ and has made
speeding the pace of executions a priority. He has backed
legislation in Texas curtailing attempts, as he has described it,
by convicted murderers ``to endlessly delay justice by repeatedly
filing court appeals.'' He maintains that every one of the
prisoners executed during his tenure were guilty and had
appropriate access to the courts.
</P>
<P>
   But speaking via teleconference to a gathering of Catholic
journalists in Baltimore last week, he said he supports DNA testing
to ``erase any doubts'' about a condemned prisoner's guilt. Bush
aides also note that the governor has pardoned two convicted sex
offenders including an East Texas man pardoned Wednesday after DNA
tests proved their innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Under Texas law, the governor only has the ability to grant a
one-time 30-day reprieve to a condemned prisoner; he can commute a
death sentence, as Bush has done once, but only if the Texas Board
of Pardons and Paroles recommends that action.
</P>
<P>
   Since Bush is traveling out of the state, and Lt. Gov. Rick
Perry is out of the country, the decision on whether to act in
McGinn's case technically falls to the state senate's president pro
tem, Rodney Ellis, a liberal Democrat from Houston who in the past
has clashed with Bush over criminal justice legislation. A
spokesman for Ellis said Wednesday that he had not yet decided what
to do in McGinn's case, but virtually no one expects him to allow
the execution to take place under the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon, Bush told reporters he had contacted Ellis'
office to say he was leaning toward a reprieve. ``I'll make a
decision tomorrow morning,'' Bush said. ``I have the authority to
recommend to the chain of command'' what to do, he said.
</P>
<P>
   McGinn's lawyers have filed 11-hour motions with the 5th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans, and Bush said he would
await that court's decision before acting. Should the courts not
halt the execution, ``I'm more than likely to grant the 30-day
reprieve,'' he said, adding that his staff is reviewing how to
ensure that the DNA evidence gets retested. ``We're now researching
the procedure to make sure the DNA gets evaluated.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
