<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-EMISSIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS GOES WITH FEDS ON STANDARDS FOR CLEANER CARS &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BILL DAWSON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   (Undated) State officials' long-awaited decision on how to bring
cleaner cars to Texas drew praise Wednesday from Gov. George W.
Bush, U.S. officials and automakers.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists mixed their applause with criticism for
the action by the three Bush-appointed members of the Texas Natural
Resource Conservation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the commissioners voted unanimously to keep Texas
on the list of states where new federal rules will dictate the
introduction of less-polluting cars and light trucks, starting with
the 2004 model year.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials estimate these regulations will boost the
average new vehicle price by about $200.
</P>
<P>
   With their decision, the TNRCC commissioners declined to choose
the only option available under federal law _ adopting an
alternative set of California emission rules for new vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Bush urged the commissioners to consider adopting
the California rules, favored by many environmentalists, as they
developed new smog-reduction plans for Houston and other areas this
year.
</P>
<P>
   His message was widely interpreted as a thinly veiled hint that
he preferred the California option to the federal rules, which were
negotiated with automakers by the Democratic administration of his
expected presidential opponent, Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, however, a spokesman for the Republican governor
expressed no disappointment at the decision to keep Texas in the
federal program.
</P>
<P>
   Bush asked the TNRCC commissioners to select ``the best solution
for Texas'' and ``it appears they came up with a plan with some of
the best ideas from both the federal and California plans,''
spokesman Mike Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Both the federal and California rules will require automakers to
phase in the sale of models with much lower emissions from cars and
light trucks.
</P>
<P>
   TNRCC officials concluded the two sets of regulations would be
roughly equivalent in reducing nitrogen oxides, the combustion
byproducts targeted in new smog-reduction plans for Houston, Dallas
and other Texas cities.
</P>
<P>
   Talks leading to the commissioners' action, however, focused
largely on other pollutants _ smog-forming chemicals that evaporate
from vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   These negotiations led to promises by automakers to include
tighter controls for these gasoline fumes, required only by the
California rules, on the vehicles they sell in Texas and other
states under the federal program.
</P>
<P>
   With those pledges in hand, TNRCC officials claimed credit
Wednesday not only for taking steps to clear the air in Texas _ a
huge automotive market _ but also nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we accomplished is that we got the automakers to do this
for 49 states,'' Commissioner Ralph Marquez said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom ``Smitty'' Smith, Texas director of Public Citizen, an
environmental and public interest group that urged adoption of the
California rules, said the commissioners ``should be complimented
for having negotiated a deal with the automakers that will probably
lead to the California (vapor) standard for the whole country.''
</P>
<P>
   But Smith said he still has ``grave concerns'' about the
agreement, because Texas officials have no power to enforce it.
</P>
<P>
   On another key issue, Marquez said he never got the level of
assurance he wanted from automakers and the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency that the federal rules will guarantee the
availability of large numbers of extra-clean ``alternative
vehicles'' in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'll confess to you, I think this is the best we can work
out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides mandating much cleaner models powered by conventional
engines, the federal and California rules both aim to bring
``alternative'' models to the market _ but by different means.
</P>
<P>
   California's rules require the sale of a certain percentage of
these vehicles, which are expected to include electric,
gasoline-electric and fuel-cell models.
</P>
<P>
   The federal rules, adopted last December by the Clinton
administration, instead require each manufacturer's fleet to meet
an average emission level.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Bergquist, spokeswoman for the Alliance of Automobile
Manufacturers, said the federal approach will ``essentially
require'' that citizens of Texas and other states have the same
access to ``alternative'' vehicles that California residents have.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Cooke, Dallas-based regional administrator of the EPA,
said its officials are convinced the federal rules will result in a
``fleet mix'' including ``alternative'' models.
</P>
<P>
   Smith remained unconvinced, however, charging that the federal
approach will not do as much to force the development of new,
cleaner automotive technologies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
