<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAME 1 LOSS WAS JUST PLAIN EMBARRASSING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Logic says the Stars will have at least
a Stanley Cup-runneth-over of motivational factors for Game 2 here
tonight. And embarrassment would seem to be a good place to start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too late for that,'' Ken Hitchcock said. ``Embarrassment
won't work once you've advanced this far \Rin the postseason\S.
Basically, both teams got to this point by being able to
psychologically write off a loss, adjust, and come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Beg to differ, Hitch. That 7-3 thing. That was embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``What difference does it make _ tough loss or embarrassing
loss?'' answered the Stars coach following yesterday's practice,
which came 12 hours after Tuesday night's Game 1 shell-shocking.
``You still have to write it off and go adjust for the next game,''
Hitch added.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Hitchcock's players automatically fall in step with his
public opinions, but defenseman Richard Matvichuk, one of many
Stars who won't hesitate to think independently from the coach, was
mostly in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, I don't know about embarrassment,'' Matvichuk said,
``except that Eddie \RBelfour\S has been there for us all season,
and then we leave him hanging out there like we did. Now that is
embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, moving right along to the next motivation point following
7-3. What about pride?
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, you're on to something,'' Hitchcock said. ``Pride is a
much bigger factor for the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   What then is the difference in pride and embarrassment?
</P>
<P>
   ``Pride involves your own play, and in using all the elements
that got you here as a team,'' Hitchcock said. ``\RGame 1\S was not
about what they did, it was about what we didn't do. This series
won't be about what they are doing. It will be about what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Then why have the Stars had these playoff games in each round
thus far where what they do is nothing short of, well,
embarrassing?
</P>
<P>
   Matvichuk: ``I'd love to know the answer to that. If I knew,
then we wouldn't be having those kind of games. We all hate it when
we play like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hate? Isn't that another possible motivational point for Game 2?
</P>
<P>
   ``They scored seven goals on us. I hate them for that,''
Matvichuk said. ``We had played three straight series \REdmonton,
San Jose and Colorado\S where the hate just came natural. But there
was no good reason to hate New Jersey. Then came those seven goals.
We learned to hate these guys in a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe even Hitchcock did, too. Why else was he heaping praise
upon the Devils' speed and quickness with their forwards
immediately after Game 1, but yesterday simply gave a hand wave to
dismiss that as a factor?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played against that kind of speed before, and we've
played against a lot of good lines,'' he said, doing a 180-spin
from his postgame comments. ``If we get our game going, from the
goalie to the puck movement, then we'll be where we want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   And then the Hitch who had said after Game 1 that the emotional
and physical transition from the Game 7 against the Avalanche was
no excuse for what happened here, added this: ``I wasn't surprised
by what happened \Rin Game 1\S. We were a couple of days behind
them, energy-wise. We've got to get caught up.''
</P>
<P>
   What's this? Hitch hinting at a excuse for that embarrassment in
Game 1? Which is the same question for Belfour when he talked after
Game 1 about medication for a head cold making him sluggish in
goal. An excuse best kept private?
</P>
<P>
   ``With Eddie it wasn't an excuse, it's just a fact,'' Hitchcock
said. ``When I saw him that afternoon before the game I knew he
wasn't himself. He didn't react like himself on the first goal,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe on the next five. Hmmmmm. Motivational factors would
seem to be in the Stars' favor for tonight, but the excuses, if
that's what they were, sounded cheap yesterday. All that really
matters, however, is the Stars having so much to prove tonight, and
improve on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can promise this will be a very physical game,'' added
Matvichuk, who plays a lead role in such things. Matvichuk acted
surprised to hear and read the ESPN and New York media lauding the
Devils for winning all the physical battles in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing physical about that game at all,'' said
Matvichuk, ``and that's the reasons we looked like we did. Being
physical is the key to how we play. That starts with Derian
\RHatcher\S and myself, and I think he'd agree neither one of us
did our job. That will change immediately. It's going to have to
become a war. After us giving up seven goals, what else can it
become?''
</P>
<P>
   Despite denials all around, Matty was sounding as if
embarrassment would indeed be a motivational factor for Game 2.
Embarrassment and then hate, too. If so, maybe the Stars are
finally ready to begin play in the Stanley Cup Finals.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 2122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
