<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0367 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1221 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-STARS-TEX     05-31 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ This is the Stanley Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was the Stanley Cup Finals with the goalie on
prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Any questions?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not. Game 1 was pretty self-explanatory. Stars goalie
Ed Belfour wasn't feeling good after taking a decongestant
prescribed for his cold symptoms. He didn't play well, allowing six
goals on 18 shots. And without Belfour at his best, the Stars
didn't stand a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we learned \R Tuesday\S is when Ed Belfour is
average or even below average we are not a very good team, and I
think we need Eddie to be a great player,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said. ``Our goalie was able to cover up for some of the
mistakes we were making. For one night, he didn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   And as a result, the Stars fumbled, bumbled and stumbled through
an embarrassing 7-3 loss.
</P>
<P>
   This was the Stars in Game 1. We're about to see the Stars after
a strong dose of humiliation when Game 2 begins at 7 tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's embarrassing for all of us,'' Belfour said. ``It's not
easy for us to put it out of your minds, but it definitely
motivates us.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, they have a tendency not only to bounce back, but to
bounce back better after getting humiliated.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A: Dallas played abysmally in Game 1 against Colorado,
losing, 2-0, and being outplayed in almost every aspect. In Game 2,
the Stars answered with an angry, physical and mean game and won,
3-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hate to lose,'' Stars defenseman Richard Matvichuk said.
``You wake up and say we're not going to let that happen to us
again. We don't ever want to lose two in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars haven't lost back-to-back games in this year's
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   A big reason has been Belfour. In Games 3 and 4 against
Colorado, he stopped 76 of 79 shots and helped Dallas escape with a
split.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave him no support,'' Stars captain Derian Hatcher said.
``We got to help the guy. They had a lot of chances right
point-blank, and that's tough on a goalie. We definitely have to
give him more support than we gave him'' Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' defense needs to do better against New Jersey's line
of Petr Sykora, Jason Arnott and Patrik Elias. The good news is
that Hatcher, who missed the second half of the third period with a
hyperextended right knee, is healthy and expected to play.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars need to do a better job of counteracting New Jersey's
speed. As Devils winger Claude Lemieux said: ``You can only chop
and hit what you can catch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' offense needs to generate more than one or two good
scoring chances a period.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, the Stars' goaltender needs the Stars to play better in
front of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie has been there for us all year, and we left him out
there,'' Matvichuk said of Game 1. ``That's what's embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour said he started getting sick before Game 7 against
Colorado and started taking the decongestant. He had taken this
particular prescription medication before without any ill effects.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, when he talked to Hitchcock before Game 1, he wasn't
feeling well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a thing with Eddie where we kind of communicate with
him earlier in the day, because, really, from noon on, he's not a
guy you really want to talk to,'' Hitchcock said. ``We always ask
him the question `How are you feeling?' And he gives you the answer
`Good,' then we walk away. That is the end of the conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   But a single word dragged into 10 minutes as Belfour explained
that he wasn't feeling all that good.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said he knew there was a possible problem that
afternoon but thought Belfour would be able to get through.
Hitchcock said he realized the situation was ``dicey'' a couple of
shots into Game 1 but decided to stay with Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock quickly dismissed speculation that Belfour had used
his cold as an excuse for his poor play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to use things like that as an excuse,'' Belfour
said. ``I didn't play my best game. I know our team didn't play our
best game, and they know it. Regardless, whether I am on medication
or not, I have to play better, and I know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour said he didn't feel energetic at practice yesterday but
hoped to be better this morning. He says he will play tonight. He's
no longer taking the medication, which he said threw off his
balance and equilibrium.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour said that if he had been healthy he would have stopped
at least half of the six goals he allowed, Devils defenseman Scott
Stevens' slap shot, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it was something, because it wasn't that hard of a
shot,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   How bad were things for Belfour and the Stars in Game 1?
</P>
<P>
   Devils goalie Martin Brodeur said he felt himself feeling sorry
for Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, for sure, because you never know when it is going to
happen to you,'' Brodeur said. ``Unfortunately, it happened for
him, but it's fun for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were forced to sit and watch the celebration. Every
time they looked at the scoreboard, they were reminded of how badly
they were getting beat.
</P>
<P>
   Which might be just what the doctor ordered for the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, we need a good kick in the butt to start playing,''
Stars forward Guy Carbonneau said. ``If you look at the game last
night, a lot of those goals were little things we could have done
better _ being outbattled in the corner, just a step behind coming
back in front of the net.''
</P>
<P>
   And did Game 1 provide that kick in the pants?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope so,'' Carbonneau said. ``This is the Finals.''
</P>
<P>
   Any questions?
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
