<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1223 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBC-GATECH-CATCHER060     05-31 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-GATECH-CATCHER0601-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jackets' rise coincides with ascension of Prince
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A year ago, Bryan Prince was a part-time bench-sitter,
part-time designated hitter, full-time rah-rah guy on Georgia
Tech's baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   Prince was willing to do anything to get playing time. He was
hoping for a chance to catch a game or two in relief of starter
Eric McQueen and maybe play a little first base.
</P>
<P>
   After two seasons at Tech, the highly regarded high school
recruit somehow had managed anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Prince is a first team All-ACC catcher, fresh from being
named the MVP in last week's NCAA Atlanta regional. He also is one
of 10 semifinalists for the Johnny Bench Award, presented to the
best catcher in college baseball.
</P>
<P>
   A case can be made that Prince is the player most responsible
for the success of this year's Georgia Tech team, which is just two
victories away from a trip to Omaha for the College World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Third-sacker Mark Teixeira was named first team All-American, is
hitting .422 and has slugged 18 homers. And second baseman Richard
Lewis, a second-team All-American, batted over .400 all season and
has made himself into one of the best leadoff hitters in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   But Prince is one of the reasons Teixeira has knocked in 80 runs
and has carried a high average all year. The catcher, who bats
clean-up behind Teixeira, is hitting .395 with 77 RBIs and made
teams pay dearly when they chose not to pitch to Teixeira.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were playing FSU, and they decided to pitch around
Teixeira,'' Tech coach Danny Hall said. ``(FSU third baseman)
Marshall McDougall asked me if a lot of people were doing that. I
told him some had, but the next guy in the lineup had made them
sorry a lot of the time. Bryan immediately doubled, and McDougall
said, `I see what you mean.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Prince is allowed to call his own game when ace Cory Vance is
pitching, and the junior left-hander has compiled a 13-2 mark.
</P>
<P>
   He is the epitome of a catcher _ 6 feet 2, 200 pounds, dirty
uniform, scrapes and scratches and scabs everywhere, a candidate
for a Band-Aid commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Catching takes a special mentality, almost a football attitude,
Prince said. ``Absolutely. I think there is a different mindset,
but I love being involved in every pitch of every play. I think I'd
be bored playing anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Prince was having a hard time getting Tech starter Rhett
Parrott settled down against Georgia Southern. The catcher blocked
at least half a dozen pitches before one bounced up and struck him
in the throat. He went down, got a quick visit from the trainer and
immediately went back to work. ``I'd much rather have the pitches
there than about belt-high out
</P>
<P>
   over the plate,'' he said. ``I don't mind if our pitchers bounce
them up. Just don't throw it down the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   The native of Fort Oglethorpe was recruited by two dozen major
schools and visited Clemson, Tennessee, Georgia and Miami before
choosing Tech. ``This'' _ the NCAA playoffs _ ``is the reason I
came here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prince is one of the Jacket tri-captains, with Teixeira and
reserve Jahmal Overton, and is one of the team leaders on and off
the diamond.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my job to keep our pitchers focused,'' he said. ``If one
of the pitchers is having a problem, I go out there and talk, try
to settle him down. I'll tell him something funny somebody in the
stands said, or say something about one of the umpires or anything
to get his mind off of the problem and to get him to focus on me.
It's my job to keep him focused, not to let him worry about
whatever's happening.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the ultimate team player,'' Hall said. ``This year he has
done everything and anything he could do to help us win. He's a
great defensive catcher, he's a team leader, and he's caught almost
every game and has been beaten up a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking punishment comes with the job, Prince said. ``There are
days when you sit in the whirlpool a long time, but winning takes
the pain away,'' he said. ``In the ACC tournament, I caught five
games in four days, but when we won, I didn't feel any pain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bryan's done a lot this year,'' Hall said. ``There's no doubt
he's the unsung hero of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
