<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1224 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-U.N.-ART-2TAKE     05-31 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-U.N.-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL'S BITTERSWEET MOMENT: ONE STEP OUT OF ISOLATION AT U.N. 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT24 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ When the Europeans last week offered Israel a
way out of its painful isolation at the United Nations, the move
caused a cheer among Israeli diplomats here and American Jewish
leaders, who campaigned for this prize for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   But decades of slights and assaults have taken a toll on Israeli
confidence in the United Nations, so there was hesitation until
almost the last minute among the Israelis about whether to accept
the offer.
</P>
<P>
   The urgings of European friends and the intercession of
Ambassador Richard C. Holbrooke with Israel's foreign minister,
David Levy, led Israel to take less than it wanted, hoping to get
the rest later.
</P>
<P>
   An important factor, diplomats said, was a determination by
Prime Minister Ehud Barak to put a higher priority on a full role
for Israel in the United Nations, a goal not given much importance
by his predecessor, Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   What was formally offered to Israel last Friday night, and
formally accepted on Tuesday, was temporary membership in a
regional caucus, the Western European and Other Group, known in
United Nations jargon as WEOG. Without membership in a regional
group, a country can never hope to be elected to important councils
and committees in the U.N. system.
</P>
<P>
   Until last week, Israel, a member of the United Nations since
1949, has been barred from the Asian caucus, which includes the
Middle East, since regional groups were organized in the 1960s. It
was the only country banned from any group.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's eventual victory was bittersweet, however. It has been
asked to forgo the chance to hold the most influential seats,
including on the Security Council, at least for the foreseeable
future. And the invitation did not include the right to take part
in European caucuses in Geneva, the United Nations' European
headquarters, or in centers in Vienna and Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   Geneva is particularly important, Yehuda Lancry, Israel's
ambassador to the United Nations, said in an interview on
Wednesday. The United Nations Human Rights Commission, a perennial
critic of Israel, meets there, and several important U.N. agencies
have their headquarters in Geneva. Of all the concessions Israel
had to make, ``that one constituted a problem for us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand that our membership is on a temporary basis, and
we accept that,'' Lancry said, adding that Israel still has hopes
of entering the Asian bloc when peace efforts succeed in the Middle
East. And, he said, membership gives Israel the ``ability to
express itself among the family of nations, to be able to channel
its creativity, its energy, its spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Lancry said that he was advised to seize the moment. ``Taking
into consideration that we were out for more than four decades of
the spheres of influence, the opportunity was rare and precious and
the decision had to be made, and we made it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lancry said that he had to counter strong pressures on the
Europeans from Arab and other Islamic nations, whose leaders wanted
Israel's membership in the European group _ which also includes
Canada, New Zealand, Australia and sometimes the United States _
held hostage to Palestinian and other regional demands.
</P>
<P>
   Arab reaction to the move to admit Israel to the European group
has been muted in recent days. At a lunch on Wednesday that
Holbrooke gave for Sen. Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania, three envoys
from Islamic nations congratulated Yancry. Diplomats regard this as
at least a truce.
</P>
<P>
   David Harris, executive director of the American Jewish
Committee, which has led the campaign on behalf of Israel since
1993 through quiet diplomacy at the United Nations and European
capitals said on Sunday that the fight is not over, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major step forward, but no one should engage in
self-deception,'' said Harris, who returned on Wednesday from
Geneva, where he was elected the new head of U.N. Watch, a private
monitoring group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel remains still unequal, and the conditions imposed on
Israel reveal that fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger here is that people will conclude that Israel's
problems have been solved totally, when in fact they have not.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel's drive for membership in a regional caucus within the
United Nations and the consequent chance to take part more fully in
the organization's work has been a goal of Israeli governments for
decades. During the cold war, however, Israel became the target of
a General Assembly majority of leftist, Third-World and Islamic
nations.
</P>
<P>
   The nadir of Israel's relations with the organization came in
the mid-1970s, when the General Assembly voted to equate Zionism
with racism, a move that alienated many American intellectuals from
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Although the end of the cold war enabled President George Bush
to have the Zionism resolution rescinded by the assembly, a
changing world atmosphere did little to help Israel generally in
the United Nations until very recently, when the Barak government
came to power and accelerated efforts to settle with its neighbors
and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The Europeans spent the last decade blaming each other,'' an
American official said on Wednesday. Just when one country would
lift objections to Israeli membership, another would find a reason
to block it. Belgium, Germany and Sweden were Israel's strongest
friends and supporters, while objections came from Ireland, Italy,
Portugal, Spain and sometimes France.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a breakthrough occurred, diplomats said, when France
_ where Lancry was Israel's ambassador at the time _ swung around
to support of Israel. At the same time, the Clinton administration
began to lobby European leaders at the highest levels, including
King Juan Carlos of Spain, whose country proved to be the last
holdout.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright spoke to European foreign
ministers and at the United Nations Holbrooke began to tackle
envoys.
</P>
<P>
   Then help came from an unexpected quarter. In speeches,
Secretary General Kofi Annan began to call attention to Israel's
isolation in strong terms. In a speech in New York in December,
Annan said that ``it sometimes seems that the United Nations served
all the world's people but one: the Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Annan welcomed the European decision, saying that
it ``rectifies a longstanding anomaly.''
</P>
<P>
   But Harris emphasized that it was important that Barak's
government finally decided to give a clear signal to the European
Union. ``At some point, Israel got off the fence,'' he said.
``Until they decided to go for it, it wasn't even clear to many of
the WEOG members whether this was important enough to Israel to
pursue.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel's cold feet did not finally warm until last Monday,
however, diplomats said on Wednesday. Levy, the Israeli foreign
minister, was still concerned that Israel could be making a mistake
by taking only a limited offer. The problem was Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   The United States made one more promise, and added a warning,
diplomats said. If Israel accepted the European offer, the American
ambassador to the United Nations in Geneva would be put to work
immediately to extend Israel's participation there. If the Israelis
faltered now, they were told, a window provided by the Dutch as
chairman of WEOG in New York could close because of some unforeseen
event in the Middle East or Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Peter van Walsum, the Dutch ambassador, told his
fellow WEOG members by letter that he was making the offer to
Israel and they had until Friday to object. There were no
objections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
