r a BC-PRISON-ESCAPE-TEX     05-31 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISON-ESCAPE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVICT USES WIRE, TOOTHBRUSHES, TOOTHPASTE IN ESCAPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CRYSTAL YEDNAK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRANBURY, Texas _ With toothpaste, two toothbrushes and a piece
of wire, a slippery Hood County prisoner completed his own Mission
Impossible by slithering out of his cell, through an air duct and
out of jail, becoming the first to escape the 6-year-old facility.
</P>
<P>
   Police identified the escapee Wednesday as burglary suspect
Collin Michael Littrell, 25, of Granbury who has been on the run
since early Friday.
</P>
<P>
   So far, he has eluded bloodhounds, tracking teams, a roadblock
and a helicopter, the sheriff's office said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, a man matching Littrell's description was seen
stealing a blue minivan in the Erath County town of Dublin, 60
miles to the southwest.
</P>
<P>
   The lanky prisoner, who was awaiting trial on eight burglary
charges, apparently yanked a piece of wire from an air duct in his
cell. Stringing it between two toothbrushes, he fashioned a
makeshift hacksaw and, slowly and patiently, he sawed for weeks at
a white bar blocking the duct entrance, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   After sawing for hours each day, Littrell apparently used white
toothpaste to mask the groove in the metal, sheriff's investigator
Larry Goin said.
</P>
<P>
   An alert jail employee noticed that the steel bar had been
tampered with about two weeks ago, Hood County Sheriff Allen Hardin
said. A work order was issued but not acted upon, and neither
Littrell nor any of his 14 cellmates was moved to another cell.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't consider someone going through an exhaust fan,
unless they're just a plain idiot,'' Goin said of the jail staff.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime early Friday, Littrell finished cutting through the
white bar. Possibly with help from one or more cellmates, he lifted
his 5-foot-9-inch, 145-pound frame into the air duct, Hardin said.
</P>
<P>
   In his bunk, Littrell left behind a dummy; a water-filled trash
bag inside a laundry sack formed the head and two pillows formed
the body, officers said.
</P>
<P>
   As Littrell wriggled through the duct, he had to remove a
chain-link barrier and slip between the large but unmoving blades
of a fan, police said. Then he had to force open a door to the
roof.
</P>
<P>
   No one else escaped, but deputies are investigating the
possibility that his cellmates were involved.
</P>
<P>
   Once free, Littrell stole a car from an unincorporated area of
Hood County near Strouds Creek, about two miles north of the jail.
He then drove to the Brazos River Acres subdivision, about six
miles to the south, to see his infant daughter, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of his child, a former girlfriend, called the
Sheriff's Department about 4 a.m. Friday to find out why Littrell
was free and at her front door.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that was the first we knew he was out,'' Goin said.
</P>
<P>
   The escapee abandoned the car, apparently because he could not
get it started again without a key, Goin said. Some of his
belongings were recovered.
</P>
<P>
   For days, neither a roadblock, bloodhounds, a helicopter nor
tracking teams turned up anything else.
</P>
<P>
   About 4:30 a.m. Wednesday, a blue Plymouth Voyager minivan with
license plate DBK41F was stolen in Dublin, Texas. Witnesses'
descriptions closely match Littrell's, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Because Littrell is said to have carried firearms during some
burglaries, Goin described him as potentially dangerous. Littrell
has brown eyes and brown hair, with the top bleached blond. He has
used the alias Mika V. Finch, according to authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the eight burglary charges in Hood County, Littrell
has ``at least that many pending'' in Parker and Erath counties,
said Hood County District Attorney Richard Hattox.
</P>
<P>
   Littrell was on parole after a 1993 Denton County forgery
conviction when he was arrested Jan. 28 after an investigation by
Hood, Parker and Erath county deputies, according to Hattox and
state records.
</P>
<P>
   Deputies from the three counties had been keeping his house
under surveillance after receiving a tip that tied Littrell to a
motor vehicle theft in Parker County, Hattox said.
</P>
<P>
   While watching his home, deputies heard a radio call describing
an Erath burglary. Littrell then drove up in a car matching the
description of the auto used in the break-in, and deputies arrested
him, the district attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the breakout worthy of a TV adventure series, the sheriff
said it could have been prevented if his staff had replaced the
half-sawed bar in time. ``If maintenance had been doing its job, it
wouldn't have happened,'' Hardin said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   .MDSD/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
