<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EUROPE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AND EUROPEAN OFFICIALS MAKE NO PROGRESS IN TRADE TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (subs 22nd graf for clarification on Airbus)   
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LISBON, Portugal _ President Clinton and senior European Union
officials met Wednesday on four major trade disputes dividing them
but did not make any progress, a senior administration official
said .
</P>
<P>
   The trade issues were apparently so difficult that Clinton,
Romano Prodi, president of the Union Commission, and Prime Minister
Antonio Guterres of Portugal, who currently holds the rotating
European Union presidency, did not even make a serious attempt to
resolve them.
</P>
<P>
   They spent 20 minutes of their 75-minute working meeting at the
Queluz Palace, an 18th century small-scale version of Versailles
outside of Lisbon, on trade. The rest was devoted to Russia and
security issues like Kosovo and European defense. Their hour-long
working lunch focused on economic issues like commerce on the
Internet and infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusually blunt public assessment for such a high-level
meeting, Lael Brainard, the deputy national economic adviser, made
no effort to put a positive spin on it.
</P>
<P>
   Briefing reporters, she described the trade talks as ``a lively
and frank exchange on areas where our views differ.'' Asked
specifically whether any progress had been made on any outstanding
issues, Brainard said, ``There was no progress at this meeting.''
Wednesday's meetings, on the first stop of Clinton's last scheduled
trip to Europe as president, underscored how little time Clinton
has to shape foreign policy before he leaves office in eight
months.
</P>
<P>
   A joint news conference was held in the formal garden of the
palace after the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In his opening remarks, Clinton struck a retrospective note,
saying he wanted to put Wednesday's meeting into ``some historical
perspective.'' He listed what he called Europe's achievements in
promoting democracy and economic prosperity during the past eight
years. ``I thank all of those who have supported those
developments,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In emotional words of his own, the effusive Prodi said that he
wanted to ``pay tribute'' to Clinton's support of the European
Union during his administration. Italy's former prime minister said
it was fitting that Clinton would receive the Charlemagne Prize
later this week, an award given to those who promote Europe's
goals. Clinton is ``a European,'' Prodi said, adding, ``You belong
to our family, really.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was the blinding sun in Clinton's eyes that made him
blink as Prodi spoke. In the afternoon, Clinton played golf for
several hours with his national security adviser, Sandy Berger, on
a world-class golf course just outside of Lisbon.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the news conference, Clinton spent most of his time fielding
questions on subjects other than trade.
</P>
<P>
   In his most extensive remarks on the withdrawal of Israeli
troops from Lebanon, Clinton called the withdrawal decision by
Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel ``daring.'' He added, ``It
changed the landscape.'' But Clinton also warned that the
withdrawal ``imposes a much greater sense of urgency'' on all the
parties to agree to a blueprint that is supposed to lead to a
permanent peace agreement by mid-September. Israel and the
Palestinians are still grappling with unresolved issues like the
fate of Jerusalem, Jewish settlements on occupied land, borders and
the future of around 4 million Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is both greater potential for something happening and
also greater tension in the atmosphere,'' Clinton said, ``which is
causing a ripple effect in the relationship between the Israelis
and the Palestinians.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton confirmed that a private meeting he will have with
Barak, originally scheduled for Berlin, had been switched to Lisbon
on Thursday morning at the request of Barak, who, in the face of
domestic opposition, decided he needed to be in the country for a
state ceremony marking Jerusalem Unification Day.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who is scheduled to leave for Germany later on
Thursday, also spoke by telephone with the Palestinian leader,
Yasser Arafat. ``President Clinton emphasized a commitment to do
everything he can to move the process forward,'' a senior
administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Asked at the news conference about a U.S. plan to develop a
limited missile defense, which has been much criticized by
America's European partners, Clinton reiterated his view that the
United States faces a new nuclear threat and would be willing to
share its technology with other ``civilized nations.''
</P>
<P>
   If the technology for such a system is developed, Clinton said,
``it would be unethical,'' for the United States to hoard the
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's proposal to modify the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile
Treaty to allow for the deployment of a limited missile defense
system as well as Russia's conduct in the war in Chechnya will be
at the top of the agenda when he meets during the weekend in Moscow
with Russia's president, Vladimir Putin, for the first time. Putin
has vociferously opposed amending the treaty, a landmark of cold
war arms control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done a lot of information sharing already with the
Russians,'' Clinton said. ``We've offered to do more.''
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans are not sanguine about a modification of the
treaty either.
</P>
<P>
   Guterres, Portugal's prime minister, said Wednesday that any
move toward a missile-defense system would have to be agreed to
``by everybody'' and would have to take into account ``everyone's
preoccupations in this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, President Jacques Chirac of France said he was
worried that the missile defense system would spark a new global
arms race.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton played down the prospects for any major breakthrough in
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be surprised if we bridge all of our differences on
Chechnya, and I would be surprised if we resolved all our
differences on the question of missile defense, although we might
make more headway than most people expect,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As for trade, trade between the United States and the 15-member
European Union represents more than 40 percent of the world's
share, but the two sides are locked in a protracted and public
struggle over a series of conflicts in which neither side has shown
much willingness to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. side objects to European restrictions on the
importation of bananas, a ban on U.S. beef produced with growth
hormones and subsidizing by European governments of a new
double-deck passenger jet built by the European consortium Airbus
Industrie.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the European Union has objected to a tax break
that the United States grants to major corporations that set up
operations in offshore tax havens like the Virgin Islands and
Barbados. These companies are not required to pay U.S. sales tax
and duties _ from 10 to 30 percent _ on their exports. The European
Union argues that the tax relief that benefits 6,000 exporters,
including such corporate giants as Boeing, General Motors and
Microsoft is a form of subsidy that will amount to about $25
billion to U.S. companies during the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the European Union's position on bananas and beef,
the World Trade Organization has allowed the United States to
impose more than $300 million in import penalties against the
European Union. The Europeans are infuriated by the U.S.
retaliatory import tax on goods such as Roquefort cheese and foie
gras.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
