<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS.CLINTON PLEDGES A RACE OF `ISSUES NOT INSULTS'
</HEADLINE>
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With her Republican opponent now confirmed, Hillary
Rodham Clinton took an aggressively combative tone on Wednesday,
criticizing Rep. Rick Lazio for operating what she said was a
campaign based on insults and asserting that her positions better
reflected the views of mainstream New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``While my opponent tells you where he's from, I'm going to tell
you what I'm for,'' Clinton told about 300 supporters at a noon
rally at the lower Manhattan headquarters of the United Brotherhood
of Carpenters and Joiners of America. ``This is not about who's
from New York. This is about who will fight the right fights for
all New Yorkers.''
</P>
<P>
   The rally was held one day after the Republican Party officially
nominated Lazio at its convention in Buffalo, where speakers
criticized Clinton's decision to move to New York and to run for
the U.S. Senate seat being vacated by Daniel Patrick Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Republicans extolled Lazio as a
born-and-bred product of the state and a candidate with moderate
positions on issues. Indeed, the Republican candidate himself
suggested in his acceptance speech that Clinton was at a
disadvantage because she was not a native New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opponent may be new,'' Clinton told those at Wednesday's
rally, ``but the issues that New Yorkers care about remain the
same. And the issues I care about remain the same. I pledge to run
a campaign based on issues, not insults, and about the real
differences between us.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 30 years, I have fought for children and families, for
women and workers,'' Clinton told the audience of union workers and
political activists. ``And in this campaign, I've stood up for New
Yorkers who needed a voice. I'm not afraid of the tough fights.''
</P>
<P>
   She then discussed several issues that have become common themes
in her speeches: her support for mandatory handgun registration and
targeted tax cuts, such as tax deductions for college tuition, and
the need to modernize New York's school buildings.
</P>
<P>
   As she has since Lazio emerged as the likely Republican
candidate in place of Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani, Clinton
highlighted her support of handgun registration, a position on
which she differs with Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every teen-ager who wants to drive a car has to get a license
and register their car,'' she said. ``I think it's time we license
every handgun owner and register every new handgun.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's aides said that the congressman favors many forms of gun
control, but not registration.
</P>
<P>
   Following the rally, Clinton flew to Buffalo, the city where
Lazio was nominated just 24 hours earlier, to visit a school and to
emphasize her support for a bill in Congress to defray the interest
on school construction bonds.
</P>
</TEXT>
