<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVENPORT IS OUSTED AS VAN ROOST PREVAILS 
</HEADLINE>
  By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ ``Usually, I cry when I lose,'' Dominique Van Roost said
through tears on her 27th birthday after beating Lindsay Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   It was a day for the unusual at the French Open. A day when a
record 80 singles matches had to be crammed into the schedule at
Roland Garros stadium to make up for the rain that washed out play
completely on Tuesday. A day when the former clay-court masters
Carlos Moya and Marcelo Rios were sent skidding out of the
tournament in the first round. A day, above all, when Davenport,
one of the two women who have dominated the game in 2000, was
beaten by the unseeded but hardly unmotivated Van Roost, 6-7 (5),
6-4, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport had not lost her opening match at a Grand Slam event
since 1993, and she had a valid excuse in the injured back that
forced her to withdraw from the Italian Open two weeks ago and
began bothering her significantly again late in the second set
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to play here, and I gave it my best effort,''
Davenport said. ``You know that's bad timing and bad luck.''
</P>
<P>
   It was left to others to reinforce some order on the day. Venus
Williams, who missed the first four months of the season with
tendinitis in both wrists, fared better Wednesday, beating Jana
Kandarr of Germany, 6-0, 6-3. The defending men's champion Andre
Agassi also advanced, shrugging off three set points in his
first-round match against the Frenchman Anthony Dupuis, winning by
7-6 (7), 6-3, 6-4. In the second round, Yevgeny Kafelnikov downed
the Argentine Mariano Zabaleta, 6-2, 3-6, 6-7 (8), 6-4, 6-4;
Michael Chang defeated Thomas Johansson in four sets to earn a date
with Gustavo Kuerten, and Mark Philippoussis, who beat Pete Sampras
in four sets on Monday, eliminated the American Paul Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
   The second-seeded Davenport was gracious in defeat, conceding
that Van Roost's spirited baseline play had a great deal to do with
the outcome. ``It's a tough call to make about retiring or trying
to play through it,'' said Davenport, who cannot recall retiring
from any match. ``She was playing well. I could have been a hundred
percent healthy and still lost. You never know.''
</P>
<P>
   One month ago, Van Roost, distraught by the death of her mother,
Louise Anne, from cancer on March 26, was not sure she wanted to
play the game anymore. ``I was mentally struggling,'' she said. ``I
had many questions going through my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   A former member of the top 10, her ranking dropped to 20 after
early losses in Rome and Strasbourg, and her draw in Paris did not
lift her spirits. ``I arrived here and said, `Well, God is not
really nice with me in this moment,''' Van Roost said.
</P>
<P>
   But Van Roost's confidence and game plan began to evolve. Like
Davenport, she does not particularly enjoy playing on clay, but she
knew that if she could get enough first serves in play and keep the
Californian off balance by mixing flat, deep groundstrokes with
drop shots she had a chance. By the time the match reached its
critical phase, with Davenport moving gingerly and wincing on most
shots, Van Roost's chances had grown immensely.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the slender Belgian was in perfect shape herself. She
received treatment for cramps in her right forearm and legs three
times in the final set. ``I must admit that I could see she was not
moving all that well, but I was not moving very well at the end
either,'' Van Roost said.
</P>
</TEXT>
