<HEADLINE>
THOMAS SKUTT, MUTUAL OF OMAHA CHIEF, DIES AT 69  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Neb., Conn.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thomas J. Skutt, a retired chairman of the Mutual of Omaha
Companies, died on Monday at Methodist Hospital in Omaha. He was 69
and lived in Omaha.
</P>
<P>
   He suffered a cerebral hemorrhage, said Jim Nolan, a spokesman
for Mutual of Omaha, the big insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   Skutt, who joined Mutual of Omaha in 1969 as secretary and tax
counsel, was its chief executive from 1984 to 1986 and its chairman
from 1986 until he retired in 1998. In both posts he succeeded his
father, Vestor Joseph Skutt, known as V.J., who died in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Under Thomas J. Skutt's leadership, Mutual of Omaha diversified
its product offerings and entered additional markets.
</P>
<P>
   Skutt was born in Omaha, grew up there and received a bachelor's
degree in 1952 from Yale. He was an Army lieutenant in Korea in the
early 1950s and received a law degree in 1957 from Creighton
University in Omaha.
</P>
<P>
   He was also a civic leader in Omaha.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife of 44 years, the former Jeanne
Cecille Plunkett; two daughters, Kimberly Davis and Mary Elizabeth
Sutton, known as Lissa, both of Omaha; a son, Thomas, Jr., also of
Omaha; eight grandchildren; and a sister, Sally Skutt of Lincoln,
Neb.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
