 &UR; HP _ &LR;  Hewlett-Packard rang up a victory on multiple fronts
yesterday with a deal that makes it the ``primary Internet
infrastructure provider'' for e-commerce giant Amazon.com.  &UR; BY &LR; 
 &UR; HENRY NORR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; PARENTAL _ &LR;  Summer vacation is coming. Do you know where your
children are? Of course you do. They're on the Internet. In the
summer, kids explore and inevitably get into some things they
shouldn't. It's no different on the Internet, where children ages 2
to 17 now make up about 20 percent of users, according to Media
Metrix.  &UR; WITH SIDEBAR. BY CARRIE KIRBY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ASKJEEVES _ &LR;  Emeryville, Calif., Internet search firm Ask Jeeves
said Wednesday that Ted Briscoe, the company's president and chief
operating officer, has resigned after serving for only two months.
 &UR; BY VERNE KOPYTOFF &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; EXCITE _ &LR;  ExciteAtHome, the Redwood City, Calif., firm best known
for providing zippy Internet access over cable television lines,
has come up with a new way to boost revenue: give some Web site
operators preferred access to its network so that those sites seem
even faster to its 1.5 million cable modem users.  &UR; BY TODD &LR; 
 &UR; WALLACK &LR;
</P>
