 EXCITEATHOME OFFERS PREFERENTIAL WEB TREATMENT  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ExciteAtHome, the Redwood City, Calif., firm
best known for providing zippy Internet access over cable
television lines, has come up with a new way to boost revenue: give
some Web site operators preferred access to its network so that
those sites seem even faster to its 1.5 million cable modem users.
</P>
<P>
   Executive Vice President Mark O'Leary predicted the new business
would be worth in the ``double-digit millions of dollars'' next
year and grow at between 400 to 600 percent per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be the fastest-growing part of our commercial
business,'' O'Leary said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of that strategy, ExciteAtHome said Wednesday that it
has signed pacts with three so-called ``content distribution
networks'' (Akamai, iBeam and Microcast), which all help Web sites
zip information faster over the Internet. Akamai distributes
multiple copies of Web sites around the world, iBeam uses
satellites and Microcast has deals to locate its equipment closer
to telecommunications companies.
</P>
<P>
   In April, ExciteAtHome also announced plans to work with
Equinix, which is building dozens of fortified bunkers for
companies to exchange Internet traffic so other Internet companies
can more easily tie into ExciteAtHome's network.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, ExciteAtHome reaches only a tiny fraction of
Internet users. America Online, for instance, has 22 million
customers.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary, the ExciteAtHome executive who is spearheading the
strategy, said Web operators are especially eager to reach
ExciteAtHome's users because they all have fast Internet
connections, and are more likely to try to watch movies and
download songs and other bandwidth-intensive tasks. ExciteAtHome is
the Internet service provider for a majority of U.S. homes with
high-speed access, typically dozens of times faster than a
conventional 56K modem.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real compelling value here,'' O'Leary said.
</P>
<P>
   ExciteAtHome could potentially work directly with some major Web
sites, like Yahoo's Broadcast.com. But yesterday's deal shows that
it is first interested in working through middlemen, such as Web
hosting companies, Internet service providers and companies like
Akamai that specialize in working with Web sites to reduce lag
time.
</P>
<P>
   Akamai makes copies of popular Web pages on sites like Yahoo,
scatters them around the Internet, then directs users to the copy
that it can access with the smallest delay. By letting Akamai put
copies of the Web pages even closer to ExciteAtHome's customers,
the company could further reduce waiting time for users when they
sign on to customers like Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
