 AMAZON DEAL LIFTS HP IN RACE AGAINST SUN  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Hewlett-Packard rang up a victory on multiple
fronts yesterday with a deal that makes it the ``primary Internet
infrastructure provider'' for e-commerce giant Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, HP will supply 90 percent of Amazon's
computing needs, including high-powered Web servers, data-storage
systems and desktop PCs, as well as support services. Amazon, which
saw its net sales jump 95 percent to $594 million in the first
quarter, now relies primarily on hardware from Sun Microsystems and
Compaq Computer.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, HP said, instantly makes Amazon one of its five
largest customers.
</P>
<P>
   Although neither company would provide financial details, the
agreement is an important step in HP's efforts to rebuild its
server business, which until recently was steadily losing ground,
especially to Sun.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, because of Amazon's high profile as an e-commerce
pioneer, its endorsement is bound to lend credibility to HP Chief
Executive Officer Carly Fiorina's campaign to position her company
as a key player in the online economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they manage it right, HP could parlay a high-visibility
agreement like this to grab the attention of other dot-coms,'' said
analyst Lee Kroon of the D.H. Andrews Group. ``If they were smart,
they probably gave very good terms to Amazon to create some
`whisper' in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To a great extent this is a commodity marketplace,'' Kroon
added, ``and when you're up against tough competitors like Sun, you
have to make an investment to buy back market share.''
</P>
<P>
   Sun isn't HP's only rival in the server market, though _ IBM and
Compaq have also been scrambling to boost their presence,
especially in the fast-growing market for Internet servers. Sun
grabbed an early lead in that category, largely because it
recognized the potential of e-commerce before its rivals did.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Sun's competitors have regained some ground,
according to analysts, in part because a new Sun chip called the
UltraSparc III has been delayed.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Sun continues to score major wins in the
server race. Just two weeks ago, eBay, the giant online auction
house, reaffirmed its commitment to Sun as its premier supplier of
servers, software, storage and professional services. That
announcement represented an important endorsement not only because
of eBay's size and prominence, but also because some company
officials had blamed Sun for a series of outages on its site last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's Amazon-HP agreement also makes the Palo Alto,
Calif., computer company an ``anchor tenant'' in Amazon's online
electronics store _ a provision that should help HP expand its
already fast-growing share of the PC market.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon sells HP printers, scanners, storage devices, supplies
and other products, but not its desktop or notebook PCs.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter of this year, HP passed IBM to take the No.
3 market position in worldwide PC sales, according to preliminary
estimates from International Data Corp. HP's PC sales were up 56
percent compared with the first quarter of 1999 _ a rate of growth
nearly three times that of the PC industry overall.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
