<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-BREAKUP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MICROSOFT TAKES ITS LAST SHOT  &HT;     By KELLY ZITO 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In its last filings before a federal judge signs
an expected breakup order against the company, Microsoft offered
additional testimony yesterday against such an ``excessive'' plan.
</P>
<P>
   The company also grudgingly suggested a longer timetable for
dividing the company in two.
</P>
<P>
   In a 37-page rebuttal to the Justice Department's proposal to
cleave the world's largest software company into two pieces,
Microsoft asked that it be given 12 months, instead of four, to
craft a blueprint for the breakup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The forced breakup of a unitary company like Microsoft is
unprecedented, and dividing the company in half would be an
enormously difficult task,'' the filing stated. ``Four months is
not remotely enough time to formulate a plan for attempting such an
undertaking.''
</P>
<P>
   The company also made minor changes, such as crossing out the
government's term ``reorganization'' throughout the proposal and
replacing it with ``divestiture.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, the judge
overseeing the case, could sign off on the final remedy early as
today, thus ending an important chapter in the landmark antitrust
battle. Microsoft has signaled it will appeal the case, ensuring it
will be played out during the next year or two.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate brief also filed yesterday with Jackson, the
company focused on its longtime argument that breaking up the
company would be detrimental to the high-tech industry and the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft offered several high-profile executives, including
Jeffrey Katzenberg, co-founder of DreamWorks SKG, and Michael
Capellas, chief executive of Compaq, who the company said would
testify to that effect.
</P>
<P>
   The ``supplemental offer of proof'' follows on the heels of
another brief filed last week, shortly after Jackson abruptly
wrapped up the only hearing in the remedy phase.
</P>
<P>
   In that hastily filed document, Microsoft had proffered the
testimony of Chairman Bill Gates and chief executive Steve Ballmer.
The government, in its revised remedy, called the measure a
``cynical ploy'' designed to distract from the remedy proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The briefs, though unlikely to sway Jackson, may help lay the
foundation for the company's planned appeal _ which could drag the
case out for another year or two.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department issued a statement late yesterday calling
the company's filing ``another effort to posture for appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of Microsoft's submission is patently irrelevant to the
question before the court,'' the department said. ``The filing does
not come to grips with the fact that Microsoft has been found to
have repeatedly engaged in serious legal violations, and serious
remedies are required to restore competition and prevent similar
violations in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 3, Jackson found that Microsoft used its monopoly in
the operating systems market _ the firm's Windows operating system
powers about 95 percent of the world's personal computers _ to
crush rivals, therefore squelching the number of choices in the
marketplace and thereby hurting consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Though Jackson is free to draft his own remedy plan, many expect
him to follow closely the proposal of the Justice Department and 17
state attorneys general. That plan, filed on Friday, calls for
snapping the Seattle company into two separate firms: one
controlling the Windows operating systems and another comprised of
Microsoft's other software and Internet holdings _ including the
popular Office suite, Internet Explorer and MSN.
</P>
<P>
   The company vehemently opposes a breakup and has denied breaking
the law. It did, however, acknowledge the plan's impact on the
company in an indirect way last week.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the same day the government handed the judge its
final remedy plan, Microsoft postponed an important conference on
its ``Next Generation Windows Services'' initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Though employees will still receive a briefing on NGWS today,
media and analysts will have to wait until June 22 to hear about
the multibillion-dollar push to make its software available on
non-PC devices such as cell phones and Palm-type organizers.
</P>
<P>
   The project ``will be doomed to failure at the outset if
Microsoft is split along the arbitrary lines proposed by the
government,'' Gates said in a court filing last week.
</P>
<P>
   In yesterday's filing, Microsoft continued to assail the plan as
fundamentally ``defective'' and one that would have far-reaching,
negative effects on partners and customers.
</P>
<P>
   However, those who have followed the case closely are divided on
the merits of Microsoft's latest objections.
</P>
<P>
   Berkeley economics Professor Richard Gilbert, the former chief
economist for the Justice Department's antitrust division, said the
company may need additional time to formulate a breakup plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft raises a number of important issues, like how to
exchange the intellectual property needed to implement the
divestiture and how do you deal with issues in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't just snap your fingers and break apart a company,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
   Others called yesterday's filings weak.
</P>
<P>
   ``This filing really looks like Microsoft took out a 12-gauge
shotgun and pointed it at their foot,'' said Rich Gray, a Silicon
Valley attorney.
</P>
<P>
   In the offer of proof, ``their main argument is `Our customers
are going to be upset if the operating systems and applications are
going to be separate,''' he said. ``They should have made the point
that the world is moving away from the desktop PC to other
devices.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kelly Zito at  &LR; kzito(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
