<SLUG> BC-PARENTSIDE-SIDEBAR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 A WORLD OF SAFE HAVENS IN THE CHAOS OF CYBERSPACE  &HT;     By CARRIE KIRBY 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An alternative to trying to control what kids do
on the Internet is directing them to safe online spots where
they're less likely to run into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Safe Worlds
</P>
<P>
   For very young children, there are several closed networks where
little ones can't be lead astray because they're not on the
``real'' Net.
</P>
<P>
   One such ``walled garden'' is Your Own World
( &LR; www.yourownworld.com &LR; ), a free program released in February.
Parents install the software, then set it to regularly connect to
the Internet and download new material. Kids play games and read
age-appropriate content provided by Time (magazine) for Kids,
Muppets.com and other sources. Your Own World is advertised for
children under 12, but its cuddly cartoon characters look like they
would be most appealing to younger kids.
</P>
<P>
   JuniorNet ( &LR; www.juniornet.com &LR; ), another walled garden, is
subscription based, costs $9.95 a month, and offers similar content
from magazines including Highlights for Children and Ranger Rick.
</P>
<P>
   Similar to walled gardens are Web sites for kids that contain
links only to a preapproved list of partners. Lycos Zone, part of
the leading portal Lycos, links to sites providing homework help or
activities like sing-alongs. The site also has a filtered search
engine.
</P>
<P>
   However, if the garden is on the real World Wide Web, don't
expect its wall to be without gaps. Although Lycos' kids' search
engine _ and others such as Ask Jeeves for Kids ( &LR; www.ajkids.com &LR; )
and Yahooligans ( &LR; www.yahooligans.com &LR; ) _ lead to only
age-appropriate sites, some of those sites contained ads for
mainstream e-tailers. By following an ad on Lycos Zone for
FreeShop.com, a site that aggregates free offers such as trial
magazine subscriptions, it's possible to land (within two clicks)
in an Internet casino that takes MasterCard and Visa.
</P>
<P>
   Supervised Communities
</P>
<P>
   Chatting, instant messaging and e-mail are all extremely
attractive to kids who want to reach out to one another and make
friends in distant parts of the world. But with good reason, these
applications are at the top of many parents' lists of anxieties
about the Internet. Even adults can be fooled about who they're
talking to online _ a former executive for Disney's Go.com, Patrick
Naughton, was tricked by an undercover police officer into thinking
he was chatting with a 13-year-old girl for months. If an Internet
executive can't tell if he's chatting with an adult or a child, how
could the average 9-year-old?
</P>
<P>
   One solution is to use a filtering program to make chat, instant
messaging and e-mail unavailable; another is to be present whenever
a child is using these tools.
</P>
<P>
   But a more fun option has been presented by Surf Monkey , a
kids' community site that provides free e-mail accounts and chat
rooms, all supervised by adults. Using Surf Monkey e-mail, kids can
only send and receive messages to friends on a buddy list that
parents have approved. Kids can chat with anyone in the monitored
chat rooms, but all the information typed is reviewed before
posting, with personal details stripped out. Kids can meet in an
unmoderated chat room only with people on their buddy list.
</P>
<P>
   Surf Monkey also offers a free browser that provides some of the
functionality offered by retail filtering software.
</P>
<P>
   The buddy list rule eliminates the risk of kids finding surprise
XXX-rated advertising in their in-boxes.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carrie Kirby at  &LR; ckirby(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
