<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1251 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TEXAS-MINERAL-RIGHTS-     05-31 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-MINERAL-RIGHTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DISPUTE OVER MINERAL RIGHTS ON TEXAS ISLAND
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
 By ROSS E. MILLOY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROWNSVILLE, Texas _ It is a case that has all the elements of a
Charles Dickens novel: an aspiring young lawyer with a helpful
uncle and great expectations; a raft of poor relatives hoping to
reclaim their inheritances; and a tangled legal snarl that would
make the Jarndyce vs. Jarndyce lawsuit of ``Bleak House'' seem as
uncomplicated as a parking ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Concepcion Sauceda vs. Gilbert Kerlin et al. _ the case that
began on Wednesday in Texas District Court here _ pits 500
relatives of Padre Jose Nicolas Balli, an 18th-century Roman
Catholic priest, against a 90-year-old New York lawyer named
Gilbert Kerlin.
</P>
<P>
   The Balli family members say Kerlin, described even by the
opposing counsel as ``a brilliant lawyer,'' cheated some
unsophisticated rural Hispanic families out of as much as $11
million in mineral revenues for ancestral lands he obtained from
them more than 60 years ago. Kerlin says the lands, on Padre Island
near here, were never theirs to begin with and he never needed to
pay them any revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Once a desolate spit of sand and scrub brush, the 120-mile-long
island is rich in oil and gas and is now home to dozens of
high-rise condominiums, hundreds of residents, and the resort city
of South Padre Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing to see but a Coast Guard station at the
south end and a fishing shack that had been knocked apart by
storms,'' recalled Kerlin in a 1996 deposition about the first time
he saw Padre Island. ``Otherwise it was just a barren barrier reef
with nothing out there but an occasional fishing expedition.''
</P>
<P>
   That was in 1938, and Kerlin, fresh out of Harvard Law School,
had just been hired by a rich uncle, Frederic N. Gilbert, to buy
the island after hearing about it from a Brownsville lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The island is named for Padre Balli, who received the title to
the land from King Carlos III of Spain for his work managing church
funds. Padre Balli died in 1829, leaving most of the land to a
nephew, Juan Jose Balli, and his descendants.
</P>
<P>
   In 1830, Juan Balli sold the land to Santiago Morales for $700,
but Morales apparently suffered buyer's remorse and soon wanted his
money back. Juan Balli repaid the $700, but the reversal of the
sale was never officially recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 100 years later, Kerlin set about trying to buy as much
of the land as he could for his uncle, though in the intervening
century, the island had been split into many smaller parcels as
members of the Balli family married and died.
</P>
<P>
   Kerlin hired a member of the family, Primitivo Balli, to
reconstruct the family tree and eventually signed 11 contracts with
various Balli descendants and others in which they gave Gilbert
60,000 acres of Padre Island and the Laguna Madre, a strip of water
that separates the island from the mainland, in exchange for a
share of any revenues from oil and gas wells, according to court
records.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1950s Kerlin acquired the Padre Island interests of
his uncle, who has since died.
</P>
<P>
   The families may also have received some cash for the deeds, but
the heirs are unsure how much. Kerlin's lawyer, M. Steve Smith,
told jurors Wednesday morning only that Gilbert and his partners
had lost $80,000 in the transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan Balli had sold his share of Padre Island to Santiago
Morales in the 1800s,'' Smith said. ``The Ballis sold Kerlin
nothing in 1938 because they had nothing to sell. Their deeds are
worthless.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was fraud and deception here all right, but it was on
the part of the Ballis.''
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs angrily disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``They stole that land,'' said Bertha Reyes, 56, who married
into the Balli family, as she waited outside the courtroom. ``Those
poor people they got the deeds from couldn't even read and write
English, much less understand a legal contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Court records are filled with examples of Balli family members
questioning Kerlin about the original deal and about whether or not
any oil and gas revenues were due them, but for more than six
decades he has managed to put them off, arguing that their titles
to the land were questionable.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the Balli descendants produced evidence on
Wednesday, however, that Kerlin had used the titles at least twice
in earlier court cases to defend his rights to the property.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith told the court that Kerlin had used other subsequent
transactions perfected with ``superior titles'' to prove his claim
to the land over the years.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the judge in the case, Pat McDowell of Dallas,
ordered lawyers and plaintiffs not to discuss the lawsuit, and
outside the courtroom on Wednesday both Kerlin and Smith said they
did not have time to talk about the case.
</P>
<P>
   But Reyes, whose mother-in-law is a direct Balli descendant, was
outspoken. She said her mother-in-law told her that the family
``owned Padre Island and they were to be paid $50 a month rent for
their land.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all they thought they were doing, renting the land,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Family members say they never received any oil or gas revenues
from Kerlin, and one branch of the family filed a lawsuit in 1993
to collect at least $11 million in oil royalties they believe they
are owed.
</P>
<P>
   As news of that lawsuit spread, other family members began
questioning the terms of the deeds and filed other suits that were
combined into the single court case now being heard in Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   Kerlin sold most of the surface rights in 1971, according to the
Balli family lawyer, Britt Monts, but kept the mineral rights and
continues to earn money from them.
</P>
<P>
   After describing Kerlin as ``a charming man, and sharp as a
tack,'' Monts told jurors: ``He has been paid substantial sums of
money from oil wells on that property that he should have shared
with the Balli family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
