<HEADER>
A1252 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PARENTAL-INTERNET-SFC     05-31 1483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARENTAL-INTERNET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WEB GUARD ON DUTY  &HT;     By CARRIE KIRBY 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Summer vacation is coming. Do you know where
your children are? Of course you do. They're on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer, kids explore and inevitably get into some things
they shouldn't. It's no different on the Internet, where children
ages 2 to 17 now make up about 20 percent of users, according to
Media Metrix.
</P>
<P>
   Technology is available _ for $50 or less _ that lets parents
track their children's every move online and limit their travels to
proscribed paths. The software is in most cases easy to use.
</P>
<P>
   The difficult part is deciding whether to use it. Parents are
whipsawed by two veins of media sensationalism: On one side are
accusations from the American Civil Liberties Union and other
groups that filtering programs inadvertently deny access to many
innocent sites, deliberately block sites whose politics the
softwaremakers don't agree with and violate children's right to
free speech. On the other are stories about kids addicted to online
porn and child molesters marauding through chat rooms while posing
as kids.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that it's not all or nothing _ tools for
supervising computer use come in a variety of forms, and most
software packages let parents turn off functions they find too
restrictive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest risk that kids face on the Internet is being
denied access,'' said lawyer Parry Aftab, author of ``The Parent's
Guide to Protecting Your Children in Cyberspace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to use just one (tool),'' Aftab said. ``You can
take one from column A and two from column B. And it will change as
the kids get older.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are the basic tools available for parents:
</P>
<P>
   Filters
</P>
<P>
   Filtering programs, such as Net Nanny, SurfWatch and Cybersitter
block out inappropriate sites in two ways: by blacklisting Internet
addresses known to lead to porn, violence and the like, and by
``reading'' the content of Web sites as they are accessed and
blocking them if they contain objectionable terms.
</P>
<P>
   To keep up with the new pages added to the Internet daily, most
filtering programs offer regular updates of new blocked sites that
can be downloaded from the company Web site. Some charge a
subscription fee; others provide the updates for free.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to find problems with filtering software: Besides the
fact that some programs seem to have hidden political agendas, what
the software's manufacturer deems offensive may not be what parents
are concerned about.
</P>
<P>
   While most filters block almost all sexual content, the Center
for Media Education found that they're not as good at filtering out
material about cigarettes and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found only one (SurfWatch) was effective at blocking over
50 percent of alcohol and tobacco promotional sites. Some filters
were blocking as little as 3 percent,'' said Charlene Simmons, CME
research associate. Fortunately, filters give parents the option to
adjust the parameters.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a parent concerned about online beer buying can ban
all URLs that include the word ``beer.''
</P>
<P>
   The reverse also works if a parent wants to permit kids to
access URLs or phrases that the software bans.
</P>
<P>
   Not all filters make their lists of blocked sites public. Net
Nanny provides a list of blocked sites along with the software, and
Cyber Patrol provides a search engine on its Web page where one can
type in a URL and find out if it's blocked. But others keep those
lists secret.
</P>
<P>
   Not all filtering software blocks the same categories of
content; while Cyber Patrol blocks cult material, Net Nanny
doesn't. Aftab suggests that parents examine their own priorities
and choose the filtering product that most closely matches those
values.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain parents are concerned about sex, others are concerned
about hate and violence,'' Aftab said. If after adjusting the
parameters, the filter is still getting in the way of a homework
project or curiosity, parents can always temporarily shut it off.
</P>
<P>
   Cyber Patrol and Net Nanny allow parents to set up user profiles
for different children in case they want to allow relatively
unimpeded access to a high-school student while keeping his
grade-school sibling on a shorter leash.
</P>
<P>
   Several Internet service providers, including America Online,
provide Net access that's filtered right from the source,
eliminating the need to install filtering software. However, many
children's online safety experts discount ISP-based services
because they are too limited. ISPs generally don't filter what
children type in chat rooms or e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``They only filter what's coming into your home,'' said Mark
Brasche of Southington, Conn., author of ``Child Safety Net'' and
Webmaster of  &LR; www.surfsafely.com &LR; , both resources for parents
looking for online safety tips.
</P>
<P>
   The major filtering software products (except SurfWatch) offer
the option of filtering any message a child sends out to the
Internet, using e-mail, chat rooms or instant messaging. Parents
can specify exactly what information the child should not reveal;
the standards are full name, home address and credit card number.
If the kid tries to type a forbidden word or number, Xs appear
instead of the characters.
</P>
<P>
   However, while incoming filtering is difficult to circumvent
without knowing the parents' password, it's relatively easy to
thwart outgoing filtering if the child really wants to. If the
parent blocks the name ``Jane Smith,'' little Jane could still tell
people that her name is spelled ``J-a-n-e S-m-i-t-h'' or ``Ja ne
Smi th'' and the computer will probably not catch it. But this
feature effectively stops kids from ``blurting out'' their names or
numbers by accident.
</P>
<P>
   Time Control
</P>
<P>
   Some parents worry that the Internet has become the new TV,
wasting summer days and keeping kids from playing outside. Others
want kids to stay offline whenever a parent can't be there to
supervise. Recognizing this, all the major filters let parents
dictate when the Internet can be used, and for how long.
</P>
<P>
   For some kids, limiting Internet time may be the key to avoiding
online trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as you get over an hour and a half a day, there's a
much higher risk of them getting into dangerous activities,'' Aftab
said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Monitoring
</P>
<P>
   Depending on how you look at it, monitoring kids' online
activities can be the most intrusive or the most liberal way to go.
Knowing that every keystroke they enter and every page they visit
is being recorded is a powerful incentive for kids to behave
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let kids know that you know what they're doing,'' said Warren
Buckleitner of the Children's Software Revue. Buckleitner prefers
monitoring to filtering because it gives kids a chance to obey the
rules before slapping down restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Monitoring can be as low tech as always being in the room when
kids are online, or periodically checking Netscape or Internet
Explorer's history file, which lists every site the browser has
visited recently. (Hitting control H on either browser will reveal
the history.)
</P>
<P>
   Some filters provide lists of URLs visited and chat transcripts,
but to see each keystroke typed and each image viewed requires
heavy artillery: a surveillance program such as Spector.
</P>
<P>
   Spector is also marketed to employers who want to see what
workers are doing with their office Internet connections. The
software takes screen shots every few seconds and allows the parent
to replay a whole day or week's computer use, screen by screen. The
software can record the transcripts of chat sessions and e-mail
messages.
</P>
<P>
   Spector can be run on stealth mode, which means that unless they
are warned, the kids have no way of knowing that the software is
installed on the computer. In stealth mode, no Spector icon appears
on the toolbar, and searching the computer for the word ``Spector''
turns up nothing. However, kids who know their way around a
computer can dig up the files Spector is saving with their screen
shots.
</P>
<P>
   Spector offers an even more cloak-and-dagger product called
eBlaster, which e-mails the computer-use reports to the parent,
boss or CIA agent wherever they are.
</P>
<P>
   This all sounds very ``1984,'' but used sensibly, monitoring can
be the best way to protect kids _ especially teens who know better
_ from getting into trouble with the computer.
</P>
<P>
   With one caveat: Forget the stealth stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to tell the kids ahead of time,'' Aftab said.
</P>
<P>
   After selecting the tools _ if any _ to use to keep the kids
safe on the Internet, Buckleitner suggests one more utility:
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need to fly off the handle if you discover that your
child has seen an X-rated site,'' Buckleitner said. ``Understand
that some exploration is perfectly normal. It's part of being
human.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carrie Kirby at  &LR; ckirby(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
