 ASK JEEVES LOSES PRESIDENT AFTER 2 MONTHS  &HT;     By VERNE KOPYTOFF 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Emeryville, Calif., Internet search firm Ask
Jeeves said Wednesday that Ted Briscoe, the company's president and
chief operating officer, has resigned after serving for only two
months.
</P>
<P>
   Briscoe is leaving to become chief executive of Play Streaming
Media Group, a private Internet broadcasting company based in
Rancho Cordova, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   During Briscoe's tenure, Ask Jeeves' stock declined sharply
along with the rest of the Internet industry. The stock closed down
$1.63 Wednesday at $20, near its all-time low.
</P>
<P>
   When Briscoe became president in March, the stock was around
$80. It had been as high as $190 in November 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Ask Jeeves, which offers question-and-answer
Internet searches, has gained users faster than most of its
competitors. It has gone from being the 124th-ranked Web site in
March 1999 to the 13th-most-visited Web site in April, according to
Media Metrix, the online research company.
</P>
<P>
   Briscoe, who will remain at Ask Jeeves for several weeks to help
with the transition, joined the company as chief of marketing in
1999. Ask Jeeves, which has about 635 employees, said the
president's job will be eliminated and that other executives will
assume Briscoe's duties.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Verne Kopytoff at  &LR; verne(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
