<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIAS WAS DEVILS' TOP DEMOLITION MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Patrik Elias was one of the architects
for the Devils in the demolition of the Dallas Stars in the opening
game of the Stanley Cup finals. Elias' passing skills helped Jason
Arnott and Petr Sykora, his partners on the Devils' premier line,
score two goals each in the 7-3 rout Tuesday night. And Elias
helped get the Devils to this stage as he produced both goals in
the deciding game against the Flyers in the Eastern Conference
finals.
</P>
<P>
   Elias starred in the regular season as well, posting career
highs in goals (35) and points (72), leading the team in both
categories despite missing 10 games at the start of the season
because of a contract dispute. The crafty and elusive left wing has
simply picked up in the playoffs where he left off in the regular
season, leading the team in points with 18, one more than Sykora
and two more than Arnott.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're clicking well right now,'' Elias said Wednesday after a
team meeting to plan strategy for Game 2 against Dallas on Thursday
night. ``None of us shy away from the puck,'' Elias said, sharing
credit with Arnott and Sykora.
</P>
<P>
   Elias has shown a remarkable ability to mesh with Sykora, his
countryman from the Czech Republic, and his pass for Sykora's first
goal in the victory over Dallas in Game 1 had his teammates in awe.
</P>
<P>
   Collecting the puck on the left flank, Elias went behind the
goal and seemed headed to the opposite side, but he surprised
everyone by back-passing the puck to Sykora at goalie Ed Belfour's
right doorstep for Sykora's first goal of the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps from the way we're raised and from the style of
hockey we've played,'' Elias said of his combining with Sykora.
``On that play, I just happened to pass it to the near post and
Petr was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Slava Fetisov, the former defenseman who is now an assistant to
Coach Larry Robinson, has been particularly impressed by Elias.
</P>
<P>
   ``He reminds me so much of Sergei Makarov,'' Fetisov said of his
former teammate on the Soviet national team. ``He's an extremely
intelligent hockey player.''
</P>
<P>
   Elias combined with Arnott and Sykora to produce the kind of
numbers expected from Brett Hull and Mike Modano of the Dallas
Stars. The Devils' threesome combined for 11 points from four goals
and seven assists.
</P>
<P>
   But the Devils do not want to look back.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Holik spoke for nearly everyone when he said: ``Forget
yesterday, it's done. We have another game tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Holik and others on the Devils said there was no overconfidence
after knocking Belfour out of Game 1 and keeping the Stars' top
line off the scoring sheet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know they didn't play their best game and they are capable
of raising it a notch or two,'' Holik said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing for us is to play our game,'' Holik added,
referring to the Devils' penalty-free performance.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Brodeur said the Devils were determined to capitalize on
their chances the way they did in the first game. ``It seems that
everything we threw at them went in,'' Brodeur said. ``We started
with the home-ice advantage and if we don't win tomorrow we lose
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Claude Lemieux said the Stars would be more physical in Game 2
and he did not expect another lopsided victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they don't want to disappoint themselves two games in
a row, but we're desperate, too,'' Lemieux said. ``What matters is
that you're ready for the next game and you stick with the game
plan. The plan is to get the puck in deep and do the things we can
do best. Puck movement and skating has been the key for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
