<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BELFOUR, MEDICINE WAS A CULPRIT IN LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Will Eddie Belfour still be dazed and
confused? That is the main question facing the Dallas Stars when
they play Game 2 of the Stanley Cup finals Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour allowed six goals on only 18 shots before he was pulled
early in the third period of an embarrassing 7-3 loss to the Devils
Tuesday night in Game 1 at Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The moody goaltender complained afterward that he was taking a
decongestant and had experienced problems with ``balance and
equilibrium'' during the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been told to get off it,'' Belfour said Wednesday, when
asked if he was still taking the prescribed medication.
</P>
<P>
   As the goaltender who anchored the Stars to the Stanley Cup
championship last season and through the playoffs this season,
Belfour is by far the team's most important player. Coach Ken
Hitchcock confirmed that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we learned last night is this: When Ed Belfour is
average or even below average, we are not a very good team,''
Hitchcock said. ``I think we need Eddie to be a great player. But
it also shows me how valuable this guy has been to our group. We
have made the same mistakes in other games and he saved our bacon.
Last night, for the first time maybe, he didn't do those things.''
</P>
<P>
   But, because Belfour, who still looked a little woozy Wednesday,
came out and blamed his poor performance on cold medication, it is
inevitable that some people will accuse the sometimes irascible
goalie of making up an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't an excuse; it was the truth,'' Hitchcock said. ``But
sometimes when Belfour says something, everybody thinks it's an
excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   After participating in an optional off-day skate Wednesday,
Belfour said: ``I don't like to use things like that as an excuse.
I didn't play my best game. I didn't have a lot of energy today.
But it was a chance to get a good sweat. And regardless of how I
feel tomorrow, I have to find a way to play my best game. I've
played with something like this before. Regardless, you have to
find a way to win, no matter how you feel out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock was asked why Belfour was even playing while taking a
decongestant that made the goalie feel off balance.
</P>
<P>
   How could he be expected to face 100 mph pucks?
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' Hitchcock said, ``he is the horse that has gotten us
this far, and we are going to ride him all the way through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
