<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO TAKES MESSAGE BY BUS TO VOTERS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT30 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BINGHAMTON, N.Y. _ Rep. Rick Lazio sought to build momentum in
his campaign for the Senate on Wednesday, riding his newly
christened ``Mainstream Express'' across upstate New York as he
greeted supporters and stepped up criticism of his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh from the Republican Party's state convention on Tuesday at
which he was named the Republican nominee to face Hillary Rodham
Clinton in November, Lazio strolled with his wife, Patricia,
through a winery and a glass museum and along a downtown street in
rustic Watkins Glen.
</P>
<P>
   He made five stops, traveling from Syracuse to Binghamton and
stopping overnight in Newburgh, from which he will continue a tour
that will travel through the New York metropolitan area before
ending Friday on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said the title of the bus was meant to emphasize what he
considered his mainstream voting record in the House and ``to
reinforce this is a grass-roots campaign, that we are going to be
out and open and among the people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be answering your questions like I am right now
at every stop,'' he told reporters. The campaign, he added in a
reference to the tight security around the first lady, ``should not
be about rope lines and checking credentials and scripted
responses.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio seemed unaware that his own campaign staff had issued
credentials to reporters to ride on the bus trailing his, which is
modeled after Sen. John McCain's ``Straight Talk Express'' used
during this year's presidential primary season, though Lazio is not
granting reporters the same freewheeling access as the senator had.
</P>
<P>
   And Lazio's penchant to answer questions at stops meant for
meeting and greeting people appears to grate on his staff. ``Guys,
no more walking avails,'' a campaign aide cautioned reporters,
using jargon for news conference. This came after reporters jostled
for space and access to Lazio after he toured a crammed milk
bottling plant in Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   And despite his pledge of a less-structured campaign style,
there were ample signs that Lazio's appearances were as scripted as
any other candidate.
</P>
<P>
   At the stop in Watkins Glen, a teen-age volunteer from the
office of U.S. Rep Amo Houghton told supporters who had been
rounded up by phone, ``You just follow me when I start cheering,
OK,'' before Lazio's bus pulled up.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio also repeated variations of what sounded like a stump
speech that he had been offering for the last week, talking about
the ``need to earn this'' and to find ways to stop a brain drain of
young people to other states that amounted to ``exporting our
children from this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's staff issued a statement on Wednesday, taking issue
with Lazio's criticisms of ``scripted responses.'' The statement
said the prepared text of Lazio's convention speech at one point
contained a note ``(smile)'' as if to remind him to do so when he
commented on the ``low wages'' his father paid him for helping out
in the family store. Lazio did smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Candidates in glass buses shouldn't throw stones,'' Howard
Wolfson, Clinton's campaign spokesman, said. ``Once again, Rick
Lazio's rhetoric doesn't match reality.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of a series of 15-minute interviews that he has begun
granting, Lazio said he was speaking from the heart and denied that
he had a prepared speech, challenging reporters to watch for one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to sort of depend on you guys to set the record
straight because you are out there and you've seen what's real,''
Lazio said. ``If you think I'm reading questions and reading a
stump speech every time I go out, then I think you have cause for
making a point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
