<SLUG> BC-BBC-UCLA-SCOTT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S SCOTT HAVING BIG YEAR, NO MATTER WHAT SCOUTS SAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS COCOLES  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ His wrist has bothered him, the scouts have
criticized him. But Bill Scott is having a good time playing
baseball for UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   And having a record-breaking season. The junior left fielder
from Alemany High of Mission Hills, Calif., is batting .430 with 21
homers and 75 RBI and was named All-America by USA Today and
Collegiate Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The fun continues on Friday, when Scott and the Bruins play at
LSU in a NCAA Super Regional opener. The winner in the
best-of-three series advances to the College World Series in Omaha,
Neb.
</P>
<P>
   Scott is just the third Bruin (Troy Glaus was the most recent)
with at least 20 homers and 100 hits in a season. A 4-for-5
performance in Sunday's regional championship win over Oklahoma
gave Scott 111 hits, breaking Glaus's single-season record of 108.
</P>
<P>
   Should he remain hot in the Super Regionals, Scott is on pace to
surpass Don Slaught's 21-year-old school record for highest batting
average (.428) in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Helping UCLA reach the College World Series is his primary goal
this weekend in Baton Rouge. But Scott is now eligible for Monday's
first-year player draft and can't help but think about it.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball America was impressed enough to rank him 22nd in the
publication's preseason rankings of draft-eligible collegians.
</P>
<P>
   But his outfield defense and arm strength Scott had surgery
during high school have been questioned. When Baseball America
recently released its latest Top 100 high school and college draft
prospects, Scott was omitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've made up their mind. They're not going to change their
minds in the next week,'' he said of the scouts who flocked to
Jackie Robinson Stadium throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no control where I go in the draft. ... You've done all
you can do and you hope you've done your best. Everybody has to
take a little criticism. Scouts say stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Adams, who has coached 10 first-round picks in 26 years at
UCLA, knows what prospects such as Scott go through as draft day
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so much pressure. Everyone dreams about playing in the
major leagues,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott is no different. He understands his defense needs work and
he could eventually play first base. But he's confident he can work
on his weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   No one doubts his bat. As a sophomore, he smacked 28 home runs,
but the seven fewer homers this year is more than balanced by a
50-point jump in batting average. Plus, he has just 29 strikeouts
in 258 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a power hitter that doesn't strike out. A pitcher can
have two strikes on him and he's willing to go the opposite way
instead of trying to hit a home run,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's hot, he's really hot. And he's never cold. You know
he's going to be consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   His steady play has come in a year when Scott has been banged
up. He sprained his ankle during the final weekend of the regular
season at Stanford two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   His right wrist injury, suffered while swinging, was much more
serious, though Scott started 61 of UCLA's 62 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The injury) was really impinging my swing. ... It was hard to
get the bat through the zone on outside pitches,'' Scott said. ``I
tried to deal with it the best way I could.''
</P>
<P>
   His numbers would say Scott did a pretty fair job of dealing
with it.
</P>
<P>
   In three UCLA regional wins in Oklahoma City, Scott hit .533 (8
for 15) with four doubles, four RBI and five runs scored to earn
all-region team honors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take what he's doing right now. He's driving in runs.
He's doing it with singles, doubles and home runs,'' Adams said.
``Despite those injuries, he's put together another great year.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 2213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
