<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-BLAZERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LAKERS JUST SHRUG AND SAY THEY'RE READY FOR GAME 6
</HEADLINE>
  By TOM SPOUSTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They claimed a sense of urgency, not a feeling of
panic. As Glen Rice and A.C. Green engaged in a loose post-practice
shooting drill and teammates casually heaved half-court shots
around them, the Lakers gave the impression Wednesday that their
Game 5 freeze had already thawed.
</P>
<P>
   Green and Rice took turns running at each other while shooting
jump shots in an effort to simulate the Portland defense that
suddenly became nasty during the Trail Blazers' 96-88 victory in
Game 5 on Tuesday night. Despite playing at home, the Lakers had
their lead cut to 3-2 in the best-of-7 Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, Robert Horry and Kobe Bryant in particular were harassed
in Game 5 and missed a combined 24 of 32 shots. Coming off 21
points on 7-of-11 shooting Sunday, Rice was 1 of 8 Tuesday night.
Horry was 3 of 11. Bryant, who played on a right foot sprained in
the first quarter and who battled foul trouble throughout, was 4 of
13.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But in a series of wild momentum swings and two victories by
each team on the other's home court, the Lakers did not seem
concerned about shots not falling Friday night at the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant shook off his cold hand and tender foot and pronounced
himself fit for Game 6 in Portland. Rice shrugged off his
inaccuracies, saying the ball sometimes just doesn't go in the
basket. Horry, who has made only 8 of 24 attempts in the last four
games, believed the Lakers spent too much time forcing 3-point
shots; they tried 27, but made only six.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had a lot to do with Portland's defense,'' Rice said.
``They didn't allow us to get in our offense as easily as we did in
previous games.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal said: ``We were so anxious to put this team
away, we didn't take care of our business properly. We're going to
be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Lakers coach Phil Jackson attributed the loss to little mistakes
magnified by the Trail Blazers' aggressive play and their
desperation not to be eliminated. He pointed to the third quarter,
when the Lakers shot 60 percent and Portland's eight-point halftime
lead grew to 13 points heading into the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson offered at least one excuse for his team's 38 percent
shooting. Before Game 5, Jackson held the Lakers' shoot-around at
their training facility in El Segundo near Los Angeles
International Airport, before going downtown to the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little stuff like that,'' Jackson said. ``Portland looked more
comfortable on our court than we did.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers were more determined from the start. Led by 22
points each from Scottie Pippen and Rasheed Wallace, Portland
dictated a pace that was fast and physical. The Lakers never
adjusted, especially to Pippen, who was quicker afoot and lighter
in the wallet for Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen had been fined $10,000 by the NBA for his forearm to the
back of John Salley's head with 52 seconds left in Game 4, an
incident that Jackson complained should have resulted in a one-game
suspension. Despite dislocating two fingers in the first quarter
Tuesday night, Pippen also delivered six rebounds, six steals and
four blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know in our hearts we can outplay this team,'' Pippen said.
``We have throughout this series, but we haven't completed it in
the games. We feel like we're going to outplay them every time out
on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   With a victory Friday night at Portland, the Lakers can advance
to the NBA finals for the first time since 1991, when they lost to
the Chicago Bulls. Should the Trail Blazers win, Game 7 will be
Sunday at the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Rice said: ``They have a little more life. It's 3 to 2. They
have everything to be confident about. But so do we. They know they
haven't beaten us up there yet in this series.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
