<HEADER>
A1262 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-HOTEL-FEUD-NYT     05-31 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOTEL-FEUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RULES IN FAVOR OF PAKISTANIS IN HOTEL DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
  By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Milstein real estate family has lost a bruising
battle with Prince Faisal ibn Khalid of Saudi Arabia and Pakistan
International Airlines over the historic Roosevelt Hotel, near
Grand Central Terminal.
</P>
<P>
   The Milsteins must repay the prince and the airline $23 million
of the $59.5 million they paid for the 1,013-room hotel on Madison
Avenue in 1999, according to a decision in state Supreme Court last
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Ira Gammerman ruled that the Milsteins must adhere to
their 1979 agreement to sell the hotel to the investors for $36.5
million, which is one-seventh of its current value, hotel analysts
say. The Milsteins had forced the airline to pay off a $23 million
mortgage on the hotel before they would agree to the sale.
</P>
<P>
   It was a good deal gone bad for the Milsteins and a windfall for
the Pakistanis, who had lost money on the hotel nearly every year
since they took it over in 1979, under a lease with an option to
buy in 20 years. They now own a major hotel at one of Manhattan's
best corners, Madison Avenue and 45th Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a battle,'' Aslam R. Khan, managing director of
Pakistan Airlines Investments, said Wednesday. ``They didn't want
to let it go. I'm grateful that justice prevailed.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwin V. Petz, general counsel for Milstein Properties Corp.,
declined to talk about the decision. ``We expect to appeal,'' he
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   To press his case, Khan had hired Chadbourne &AMP; Parke, the law
firm that represented the airline in the original deal with the
Milsteins.
</P>
<P>
   In his decision last Friday, Gammerman said that he was left
with the impression that the litigation was ``the culmination of
the Milsteins' efforts to find a loophole in the lease in the hope
of escaping an agreement which, with the passage of time, appeared
to be less favorable than originally anticipated.''
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1924 by a predecessor of the Penn Central Railroad to
serve passengers at Grand Central Terminal, the 20-story Roosevelt
was one of the first hotels in the world to offer a health club,
child care and a kennel for guests' dogs. In its heyday, Guy
Lombardo broadcast ``Auld Lang Syne'' over the radio from the
Roosevelt Grill.
</P>
<P>
   But the hotel and Penn Central had fallen on hard times by 1978,
when the Loews Corp. bought the Roosevelt, as well as the Barclay
and the Biltmore Hotels, for $55 million. Loews promptly resold the
Roosevelt to Paul Milstein, a major New York developer, for $30
million.
</P>
<P>
   Milstein leased the hotel to the Pakistani airline for $2.7
million to $4 million a year. He also gave it an irrevocable option
to buy the hotel, court papers show. The city was wracked by a
fiscal crisis, so it seemed a good deal for the Milsteins.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Pakistanis moved to buy the hotel in 1999, a real
estate boom was under way. The 1979 agreement had specified a sale
price of $36.5 million. Paul's son, Howard Milstein, was no longer
eager to sell a hotel that was now worth more than $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Faisal, who had invested in the original deal,
and the airline had lost more than $70 million operating the hotel,
where the carpets were threadbare and the brass was tarnished. The
Pakistanis closed the hotel in 1995 for a $65 million renovation
and hired a new management company, Interstate Hotels. The hotel
reopened in 1997 and began making money in the next year, when the
investors moved to buy the hotel for $36.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Milstein family stalled, and later demanded that the airline
also pay off a $23 million mortgage, which the Milsteins had taken
out. At the same time, building, fire and health inspectors swarmed
over the hotel, issuing citations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were putting out fires every day,'' Jim Heineman, a former
manager of the Roosevelt, said in an interview last fall. ``We
certainly felt there was pressure on us.''
</P>
<P>
   The airline bought the hotel for $59.5 million last year and
went to court. Last week, Gammerman said he found most of the
testimony on behalf of the Milsteins ``to be contrived or lacking
in meaningful detail,'' and ordered the real estate family to
reimburse the investors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 2218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
