<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NUKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NEXT GENERATION OF WEAPONRY' WILL NEED BILLIONS, BUSH SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. _ George W. Bush said Wednesday that the
United States, while considering reductions in its nuclear arsenal,
also must commit billions of additional dollars to technological
research to develop new ``peacekeeping'' weapons for the future.
</P>
<P>
   The likely Republican presidential nominee said that he will
urge Congress to increase spending on defense research and
development by $20 billion over the next five years. And he
promised to direct that 20 percent of the defense procurement
budget be used to purchase the ``next generation of weaponry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not enough to make incremental improvements on existing
(weapons) systems,'' Bush told a sun-baked crowd of several hundred
at an outdoor veterans memorial park on the second day of a
campaign swing through the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mission is to design and develop quantum-leap weapons,
weapons that will dominate the battlefields of the future, weapons
that will allow America to redefine how war is fought and won, and
therefore allow this great nation to redefine how the peace is
kept,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Texas governor proposed a reduction in American
nuclear warheads and an expansion of a missile defense system to
help protect national security and keep the peace in the post-Cold
War era.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, speaking in a state where the Los Alamos and
Sandia research facilities would likely play a key role in the
development of futuristic weapons, Bush said major changes in
military preparedness are essential.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's military is organized more for Cold War threats than
for challenges of the new century,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``America's forces in the next century must be agile and lethal,
readily deployable and require a minimum of logistical support. We
must be able to project our power over long distances in days and
weeks, rather than months.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush admitted that ``transforming our military is going to be a
massive undertaking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But we have no choice,'' he added. ``The choices we make now
in the quiet days of peace will determine the world as we head into
the 21st century. I look forward to seizing the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier in Denver, Bush had criticized President Clinton
and Vice President Al Gore, saying they had allowed the U.S.
military to fall into a sorry state of poor morale and low
preparedness. Gore is the probable Democratic presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   That provoked a response Wednesday from Gore's campaign, saying
Bush should look to his own service as a state commander-in-chief
before leveling criticism elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just one more example of where the governor's rhetoric
does not match the record in Texas,'' said Gore spokesman Chris
Lehane. ``He's spent the last several days talking about the state
of readiness of the United States military, when in fact some of
the same issues he's raising exist in the Texas National Guard,
where he's commander-in-chief.''
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Chronicle in 1997 and 1998 reported widespread
allegations of racism and sexual misconduct in the Texas State
Guard, a state militia that falls under the control of Brig. Gen.
Daniel James III, a Bush appointee. There also were admissions that
the Texas Army National Guard and Air National Guard had a low
state of military readiness.
</P>
<P>
   James, who oversees all three forces, told a state House
committee in 1998 that he was attempting to address personnel
problems within the State Guard. He blamed the preparedness
deficiencies in the National Guard units on funding cutbacks by the
Pentagon, acknowledging, ``we're not as ready as we've been in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   But James' spokesman, Lt. Col. John Stanford, said Wednesday the
Texas guard units have taken on major military roles, despite
receiving less funding than goes to other state guards.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford said 700 members of the 49th Armored Division of the
Texas National Guard make up the headquarters command of the
multinational forces in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford said personnel problems within the State Guard unit
were resolved two years ago. Stanford said he knows of no current
sexual harassment cases pending in the state militia.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail in New Mexico, Bush said that he is well
satisfied with the Texas State Guard and National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this the mode of the campaign, when the vice president says
`I'm going to campaign positively'?'' he said. ``Danny James has
done an excellent job as the adjutant general, and people who
follow the guard in Texas know that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
