<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1268 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-TOUR-BUS-320&AMP;ADD-N     05-31 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TOUR-BUS-320&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI ORDERS TOUR BUS LINE OFF THE STREETS 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Nine days after a double-decker tour bus killed a
pedestrian at a midtown Manhattan intersection, Gov. George E.
Pataki on Wednesday shut down the tour company for at least two
weeks, and vowed to put it out of business permanently.
</P>
<P>
   The governor had the state Department of Motor Vehicles suspend
the vehicle registrations for all 63 buses run by New York Apple
Tours, after an investigation by an array of city and state
agencies found hundreds of violations of state laws. Those
violations could result in hundreds of thousands of dollars in
fines against the company, and possible jail time for some of its
employees.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which has repeatedly run afoul of city, state and
federal authorities, can contest the suspensions at a DMV hearing
on June 13. If it fails, the buses will be off the road
permanently.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't tolerate an operation that ignores the regulations
and flouts the law,'' Pataki told reporters in Albany. ``They
should be, in my view, put out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's double-decker buses have become a ubiquitous
presence on city streets in recent years. But as the buses have
proliferated with the city's tourism boom, they have also drawn
angry criticism in residential neighborhoods for clogging and
polluting streets, as well as for posing safety threats.
</P>
<P>
   The death of a pedestrian last week heightened pressure for
stronger action against the company.
</P>
<P>
   While the company could, in theory, resume operation with a new
fleet of buses, state officials said the Department of Motor
Vehicles could make it very difficult for New York Apple to receive
new vehicle registrations.
</P>
<P>
   The administration of New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has
already moved to revoke the company's operating license, and
Wednesday an administrative judge temporarily sided with the city,
suspending its license until full hearings into the matter are
completed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The state order was served on the company Wednesday morning,
state officials said, and should have been effective immediately,
but New York Apple's readily recognizable bright red double-decker
buses continued to run throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani released a statement saying that ``commuters and
visitors will be safer'' because of the governor's action.
</P>
<P>
   The tour company refused requests to interview its officials,
but it issued a statement in which it said it was ``shocked and
surprised'' by the state's action and contended that the company
had been treated unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are dismayed by this administration's rush to judgment
without granting us our day in court,'' the statement said. ``We
deserve better. We look forward to defending and clearing our good
name and serving the visitors of the greatest city in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, opponents of the company praised the governor's
action, but said the city and the state should have moved against
the company long ago. ``I'm only sorry that someone had to die for
us to get this kind of response,'' said state Sen. Thomas K. Duane
of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   While the city had been moving for a month to shut the company
down, it was the death of Randolph Walker, a 71-year-old actor, on
May 22 that brought matters to this point.
</P>
<P>
   Walker was strolling home from an audition when he was hit at
the intersection of Ninth Avenue and 45th Street, where, the police
said, he was crossing with the right of way. They said the bus
driver, Howard Scott, 41, was not licensed to drive a bus.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said that after Walker was killed, he ordered an
immediate audit of the company, and he and Giuliani arranged for a
full-court press by a variety of agencies, looking into every
aspect of its operations.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the state audits the operation of bus companies every
three years, and New York Apple was due for an audit next year.
</P>
<P>
   The new state audit, by the motor vehicle department and city
and state transportation agencies, found 625 violations of state
laws, triple the number that were found in a 1998 audit. Pataki
said the company's disregard for the law had become ``significantly
worse'' in two years.
</P>
<P>
   New York Apple, which also operates tours in Brooklyn, has been
cited by the city and state for a wide range of misdeeds, like
switching license plates on buses to avoid inspections, violating
building and environmental codes at its garage and driving off its
authorized routes.
</P>
<P>
   The company's drivers have received 1,400 traffic summonses,
including many for reckless driving, and have been involved in 140
accidents, according to city officials.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the company admitted lying to the federal government
about the age of the buses it was importing from Britain to
circumvent emissions standards, and paid an $800,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   A study found that its buses, many dating from the 1970s,
created 25 times as much pollution as new buses.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 and 1999, safety inspectors from the state Department of
Transportation gave failing grades to 42 percent of the company's
buses, often for faulty brakes.
</P>
<P>
   In the new audit, the company was cited 245 times for failing to
notify the Department of Motor Vehicles every time it hired or
fired a driver, 205 times for failing to maintain complete records
on its drivers, and dozens of times each for failing to check
drivers' driving records before hiring them and for failing to give
them physicals.
</P>
<P>
   In a parallel investigation, the State Department of
Environmental Conservation said it found several violations of
environmental laws at its depot in the Greenpoint section of
Brooklyn. Two of those are misdemeanor crimes that could mean a
year in jail for company officials: failure to register a waste oil
tank with the state, and failure to take adequate measures to keep
that tank from leaking.
</P>
<P>
   The department found that the company had illegally disposed of
used motor oil and allowed oil to contaminate the groundwater.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said that the State Department of Insurance had
subpoenaed company records to see whether it had complied with laws
on liability coverage.
</P>
</TEXT>
