A1273 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GLF-GOLF-CARTS-NYT &LR;      05-31 0451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF-CARTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUR TO APPEAL RULING ON CARTS TO HIGH COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARCIA CHAMBERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ending weeks of speculation, the PGA Tour has decided to appeal
to the U.S. Supreme Court a federal appeals court decision that
allows Casey Martin to ride a cart in PGA Tour events, a lawyer for
Martin said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The tour asked Justice Sandra Day O'Connor two weeks ago for a
60-day extension to file a petition to the court seeking a review
of the case. O'Connor, herself a golfer, granted the tour an
extension until July 5.
</P>
<P>
   Roy L. Reardon, Martin's lawyer, said: ``We opposed the tour's
petition. They have seen Casey perform in a cart on both the Nike
and PGA Tour. They can see he has no advantage over other
players.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the tour said Wednesday that the board of
directors had discussed the Martin case at a meeting last week, but
that the tour would make no immediate announcement on the matter.
The tour's plans to appeal to the Supreme Court were first reported
Wednesday in The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   The tour cited a recent conflict between two federal appeals
court decisions about golfers seeking to ride carts in professional
competitions. ``These unsettled issues are substantial and of
potentially widespread significance,'' the tour's lawyers wrote in
seeking the extension. Although the Supreme Court takes only a
small percentage of cases for review, one criterion for acceptance
is a split in the circuit courts.
</P>
<P>
   The 9th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals in San Francisco upheld a
lower federal court decision in March, giving Martin the right to
ride a cart. Martin, 27, has Klippel-Trenaunay-Weber syndrome, a
rare circulatory disorder, in his right leg. His lawsuit became the
first to be filed by a professional athlete under the Americans
With Disabilities Act. The tour mounted a vigorous challenge
primarily on the grounds that walking is an essential part of
high-level golf competition.
</P>
<P>
   As Martin's case went through the courts, Ford Olinger, a club
pro from Indiana who has a degenerative hip, filed a lawsuit
against the U.S. Golf Association seeking to use a cart to play
qualifying events for the U.S. Open. Unlike the court in
California, a three-member panel of the 7th Circuit U.S. Court of
Appeals in Chicago ruled for the USGA.
</P>
<P>
   Olinger, 33, has appealed his case to the entire 11-member
Seventh Circuit court. If he loses, his lawyer, John C. Hamilton,
has said he will appeal to the Supreme Court as well.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a third case involving a Texas golfer seeking to use
a cart to qualify for the U.S. Senior Open is now before the 5th
Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals in Austin, Texas.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
