<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HATCHER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HATCHER, STARS' DEFENSE PLAN TO PLAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ It wasn't Theisman-esque, but the sight
of Stars defenseman Derian Hatcher's right knee buckling on a hit
against New Jersey's Alexander Mogilny was chilling on slow-motion
replays.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher hyperextended the knee on the third-period hit and did
not return. He plans to play for tonight's Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would almost guarantee it,'' Hatcher said. ``I haven't
skated yet. Last night it didn't get any worse, and usually, if
it's serious, throughout the course of a night it gets worse. So,
for the most part, it feels pretty good. I rode the bike a little
today and for the most part it feels pretty good, so I'm sure it
will feel good tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   While Hatcher says his right knee is OK, the rest of the team,
and defense, is still smarting after the Game 1 ambush, where they
surrendered seven goals, the total given up in their four previous
playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was because of blown assignments, poor puck play or
poor positioning, the Stars' defensemen are convinced Game 2 will
not be a repeat of Game 1. Without making any major adjustments,
they are convinced they can contain a top line that scored 11
points and physically neutralize a team that skated and scored all
over them in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive pair going against the Devils' top line of Jason
Arnott, Petr Sykora and Patrik Elias is expected to change. In Game
1, Darryl Sydor and Sergei Zubov went against that line, and it
finished with four goals.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher and Richard Matvichuk expect to be going against that
line tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hatcher and I have to take it as a personal challenge to shut
down those guys,'' Matvichuk said. ``Hopefully, starting
\Rtonight\S, we'll get what we want and that's to play against that
line knowing we've been pretty successful shutting down top
lines.''
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the rest of the Stars defensemen trying to contain
an offense that outshot them, 26-18. Considering that the Stars
have been outshot by wider margins this postseason, that's not too
alarming.
</P>
<P>
   What's more encouraging is the Stars' history of playing
physically more aggressive on the heels of a defeat. But against
the Devils, being more physical isn't always a matter of finishing
checks or hitting players. It's about being selectively physical.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a game where you are physical when you can be,'' Stars
defenseman Dave Manson said. ``You don't want to be out of position
to be physical, because then you end up getting that stuck right
back down your throat, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, the Stars are the ones expected to do the shoving down
throats. And the Devils know it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect a lot more from the next game,'' Devils defenseman
Scott Stevens said. ``We have to come out hard and go right after
them and put them back on their heels.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars don't expect this. Precedent suggests they shouldn't.
They haven't lost consecutive games in the playoffs this season.
The last time they lost consecutive playoff games were Games 4 and
5 of the 1999 conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``\REverybody\S talks about how great we are after a loss,''
Matvichuk said. ``After the loss we took \RTuesday\S last night, we
better be great.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
