<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS EXPECT COUNTERATTACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J. DOUGLAS FOSTER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Call it a hurricane. Maybe a typhoon.
Even an Avalanche, for a more fitting hockey reference.
</P>
<P>
   Some sort of natural disaster is likely the best analogy for
what most people following this year's Stanley Cup Finals expect
from the Stars in Game 2 tonight. After watching the speedy Devils
skate past the Stars repeatedly in a 7-3, Game 1 loss, odds are the
Stars will open with one of their most desperate and aggressive
first periods tonight at the Continental Airlines Arena.
</P>
<P>
   And nobody knows that better than the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're probably a little ... embarrassed,'' New
Jersey center John Madden said. ``I would be. I think they'll come
out real hard in the first 10 minutes of the game. It will be
important for our team to rise to the challenge and weather the
storm. Those first 10 minutes will be vital.''
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made of the sound thrashing New Jersey gave the
Stars and goaltender Ed Belfour in Game 1, and rightfully so. The
Devils scored six goals in a little more than two periods, chasing
Belfour from the ice for backup Manny Fernandez before eventually
scoring on him as well.
</P>
<P>
   It's not supposed to be this way. The defending Stanley Cup
champions are supposed to embarrass others, not get embarrassed.
Dallas is supposed to grind and punish teams into submission, not
sit back and watch teams throw pucks past Belfour as if he were
woozy on cold medicine.
</P>
<P>
   But that's what happened. And expecting the same in Game 2 is
the last thing on New Jersey's minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going to come out really angry and really hungry to
win that hockey game,'' Devils goaltender Martin Brodeur said.
``For us, we've got to make sure that we are really disciplined in
the early going of that game and make sure we stay physical and try
to make them think about Game 1 ... try to bury our chances when we
have them.''
</P>
<P>
   Staying disciplined amid Dallas' attempt to force its way back
into this series is extremely important. In Game 1 New Jersey
wasn't called for a penalty, and expectations are that the Stars
will try to create more special-teams chances by bringing more hits
and physical play to Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   What the Devils can't do, they said, is underestimate Dallas.
The Stars are, after all, the defending champions. And it's not
like this is new territory for coach Ken Hitchcock's bunch. Dallas
has lost the first road game in each of its three playoff series
this season only to emerge victorious. And in the past two seasons,
the Stars have lost Game 1 of both conference finals series and
both Stanley Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars won the first three series. The Devils know they can
still win the fourth in spite of Tuesday's score.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter whether we won 2-1, 7-3 or 4-3,'' Devils
center Bobby Holik said. ``Tomorrow it won't help us at all.
Nothing is going to help us but this team being ready to play like
we were.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
