r s BC-HKN-DEVILS-SPEED-TEX     05-31 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-SPEED-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS HOPING TO PUT CLAMPS ON SPEEDIER DEVILS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The New Jersey Devils were quicker to
loose pucks, quicker up and down the ice and quicker out of the
gate in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the Stars, who lost to the Devils, 7-3, on Tuesday
night, enter tonight's game playing catchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have quick forwards with a lot of speed,'' Stars center
Guy Carbonneau said. ``They like to control the flow of the game,
and that's exactly what we gave them \RTuesday\S night. We're known
as a team that plays tight defense and plays tight in the neutral
zone. \R Tuesday\S night, we didn't do that. We didn't start the
way we wanted to play, and they took advantage of all the
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Avalanche, which lost to the Stars in the Western
Conference Finals, are fast. The Devils are faster.
</P>
<P>
   As the Stars have discovered, speed can kill.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a fast team, but they were opportunistic on the
chances they had,'' Stars defenseman Sylvain Cote said. ``We have
to have better positioning, no doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the game, coach Ken Hitchcock said his team
had ``struggled'' in its own end and blamed the Stars' mistakes on
the speed of the Devils' forwards. Less than 24 hours later,
Hitchcock was back-tracking.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the game, I kept thinking that they were coming at us,
coming at us,'' Hitchcock said, ``but then when I looked at the
tape \Ryesterday\S, the reason they were coming at us is because of
the mistakes that we were making that gave them that opportunity.
We were giving them odd-man rushes, because of us turning the puck
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you negate speed by being better with the puck. You
can stand in position defensively all you want, but if you are not
good with the puck and you are not strong in those areas and
determined to get the job done, then you are going to constantly be
looking at speed coming at you. That is the area that has got to be
better for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars said they aren't as slow as they looked. Instead, they
claim it was neutral-zone turnovers that helped the Devils get
ahead in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got speed, but we had so many puck mistakes that it
created a lot of opportunities for them,'' Stars defenseman Darryl
Sydor said. ``We've got to clean up our neutral-zone turnovers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils' first line of Jason Arnott, Petr Sykora and Patrik
Elias had four goals and seven assists. Either Sydor or his
defensive partner, Sergei Zubov, was on the ice for all of the
game's 10 goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really skate to the puck well down low,'' Sydor said.
``They've always got a guy in front, and they don't seem to look.
They just try and throw the puck in areas where they believe guys
are. When you play together for a while, you know where guys are
without even looking. That's what they're doing right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to stop their cycle. Obviously, you've got to pin
and seal. You've got to get the first guy stopped up and try to get
them not moving. We basically have to shut them down physically.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
