<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-LINES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' HITCHCOCK MIGHT HAVE TO AD-LIB LINES FOR GAME 2
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Jamie Langenbrunner remains a scratch.
Guy Carbonneau is grinding his teeth into sand for a crack at
checking the Devils' explosive top line. And Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock is giving the outside world _ and the Devils _ no
indication of how he will construct his lines for tonight's Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because he isn't sure yet himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got our challenges,'' Hitchcock said the day after
adjusting and readjusting all four lines throughout the Stars' 7-3
loss in Game 1 of the Stanley Cup Finals. ``They \Rthe Devils\S
don't present anything different. I'm more concerned with the
challenges we're creating for ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have become a 20-player jigsaw puzzle at the worst
time. Much of the shuffling in Game 1 was due to the Devils'
domination and Hitchcock's search for a spark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you try to shake up things,'' Carbonneau said.
</P>
<P>
   A major blow is the loss of Langenbrunner, who Hitchcock said
will not play in Game 2. As long as Langenbrunner, who has a
sprained knee, is out of the lineup, mixing and matching and
adjusting lines during the game could become a regular occurrence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have time to experiment, we have to find the right
combinations for \Rtoday\S and throw them together,'' Stars forward
Kirk Muller said. ``Everyone has had lots of opportunities to play
with each over this year. More important is that we can play a
stronger game. We all know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau wants the opportunity to battle Petr Sykora, Jason
Arnott and Patrik Elias, who combined for four goals and 11 points
in Game 1. With the Devils owning last change, they are able to
keep Carbonneau of that line much of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously,'' Carbonneau answered when asked if he wanted to go
head-to-head with the Devils' highly skilled line. ``It's tough on
the road, but I will when we go back to Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner's absence provides the biggest challenge in
constructing a potent second line. He and center Joe Nieuwendyk
seem to find instant chemistry on the ice together. With power
forward Scott Thornton opposite Langenbrunner, that line had hit a
groove. Since Langenbrunner went out in Game 5 against Colorado,
Nieuwendyk and Thornton have no points.
</P>
<P>
   The seriousness of Langenbrunner's knee sprain is beginning to
draw speculation. The Stars said they expected him back for Game 2,
but yesterday Hitchcock said Langenbrunner is not ready to play.
His absence for a fourth consecutive game sends shock waves through
the lines.
</P>
<P>
   Without Langenbrunner, Hitchcock said he prefers to insert
winger Jon Sim, who spent most of the season playing for the Stars'
minor-league affiliate, instead of checking forward Blake Sloan,
who spent most of the year on the checking line with Carbonneau and
Mike Keane. Aaron Gavey, who hasn't played since Game 3 of the
Western Conference Finals, is also a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it hurts us to a certain point,'' Keane said. ``Joe
and Jamie play very well together. It's something where whoever has
to play for Jamie has to play well. The first two lines are the
most important, three and four kind of work themselves out. You
want your best players playing on the No. 2 line.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
