<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-PENN-STATE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELL-BALANCED PENN STATE NOT TO BE TAKEN LIGHTLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the sun rose over Upper Montclair, N.J., on Sunday, the Penn
State Nittany Lions were in a fix: To survive the Rutgers regional
and advance to the Super Regional round, they would have to beat
North Carolina ... twice.
</P>
<P>
   A daunting prospect, since at that moment they stood 0-3 on the
year against the Tar Heels, including two early-season losses and a
14-5 pasting in the regional opener.
</P>
<P>
   But just as gloom began to settle, the Lions suddenly received
the spark necessary to propel them to victory, helpfully provided
by the Tar Heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were taking us lightly, they only had to win once, and
they figured there wasn't going to be a second game,'' Penn State
pitcher Pete Yodis said. ``We heard they had tickets to the Yankees
game that night. That fired us up.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Nittany Lions _ playing in the NCAA regionals for the
first time since 1976 _ swept two from the Tar Heels and are on
their way to Austin, where they will face Texas at 7 p.m. tomorrow
at Disch-Falk Field in the opener of the best-of-three Super
Regional. The second game is scheduled for 7 p.m. Saturday and the
third game, if necessary, for 2 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions come well-armed and powerful.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State (45-17) is hitting .344 as a team after closing the
regular season at .358, best in the nation. ]Leading the way is
outfielder Michael Campo _ a recent first-team All-America
selection _ who carries a .439 average and a 41-game hitting
streak. On the power side, there is third baseman Shawn Fagan, with
15 home runs and 80 runs batted in. Eleven players are hitting more
than .300, including eight regulars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've hit well,'' coach Joe Hindelang said, ``but I'm really
more proud of what we've done on defense _ we're at .970, and
that's been a big factor. Sometimes your hitting goes south on you,
but the way you win is with solid defense and pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   While Penn State's pitching (4.63 team earned-run average) is
far less gaudy than that of the Longhorns (3.18), the Lions have
had their moments recently and boasts a key strength _ depth _ that
was evident Sunday against North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``North Carolina used Eric Henderson, one of their big starters
in the first game, but after we knocked him out, the game began to
turn in our favor and we won, 6-5,'' Yodis said. ``They had no one
left and used their closer to start the second game, and we won,
10-3.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Penn State had an unsung ace in the hole _ freshman
Kevin Damiano, who had pitched 19 innings all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to the pitching coach,'' catcher Joe Puliafico said,
``and pointed out that we had some fresh arms that hadn't thrown
lately, and we should use them instead of the guys we'd been
pitching all weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   So Damiano became the hero _ closing the first game and starting
the second _ pitching a total of nine innings and picking up both
victories. He even survived a piece of backfired strategy straight
out of ``Bull Durham''.
</P>
<P>
   ``After he looked so strong finishing the first game, we decided
to start him in the second while he was still warmed up,''
Puliafico said. ``It seemed like he finally began to lose some
steam in the fifth, so I went to the mound and I said, `Just make
sure you don't walk this guy ... Throw it over the plate _ I don't
care if he hits a home run.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So Kevin throws a changeup and the guy hits a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, it seems, the Nittany Lions can overcome anything. This
weekend they'll be asked to overcome the loss of their coach, who
will not make the trip. Hindelang was admitted to Hershey (Pa.)
Medical Center yesterday with acute chest pains and is being held
for more observation.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, Penn State overcame the loss of three starters,
catcher Chris Netwall (ankle), first baseman Chris Wright
(mononucleosis) and shortstop John Richmond (stiff neck), to move
on. Penn State officials are hoping all three will be ready this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Puliafico likes his team's chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure there's no pressure on us ... we're lovin' it,'' he
said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
