<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1283 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-SIERRA-TE     05-31 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-SIERRA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIERRA HAS A CHANCE _ SOMEWHERE ELSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Ruben Sierra could be returning to the major leagues
soon. It probably won't be with the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Doug Melvin said yesterday he is getting
inquiries about the Rangers' former superstar, who is showing signs
of a comeback at Triple-A Oklahoma after his career was all but
extinguished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a couple teams talk to me about him,'' Melvin said.
``There's a little interest. He's proven he could play at that
level. He could be a productive part-time player for somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Rangers, Melvin said, ``I don't think he would be a
fit for us at this time, not unless we had a bunch of injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Sierra,, going into last night's game, was hitting .356 in 27
games with 22 runs scored, five home runs and 20 runs batted in.
His defense still isn't the best but Melvin said, ``That's not
what's going to get him to the big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Sierra, 35, was once considered one of the best to play for the
Rangers. He finished second to Milwaukee Brewers Hall of Famer
Robin Yount in the 1989 American League Most Valuable Player
balloting after hitting .306 with 29 home runs and a league-leading
119 RBI. But he was traded to the Oakland Athletics on Aug. 31,
1992, and his career steadily declined.
</P>
<P>
   He attributed his decline to doing too much weightlifting that
ruined his swing. But he said he has stopped that and recently told
the /Daily Oklahoman/, ``I've finally come back to swinging the bat
like I used to. I feel much better now. I know I don't need to lift
weights because I can hit the ball out of the ballpark without
lifting weights.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, with Gabe Kapler out until early next week with a
strained hip flexor, could have used help in right field the past
month. Chad Curtis is playing there but the Rangers' right fielders
have combined to hit .198 this season with six home runs and 24
RBI. That's the lowest batting average at the position for any
American League team.
</P>
<P>
   Scarborough Green and Jason McDonald were sharing the position
before Curtis moved over from left field, when Rusty Greer came off
the disabled list. They remain on the team as reserves, and Melvin
said the Rangers still prefer what they have on the roster over
Sierra.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a better fit for us because of their speed and
defense,'' Melvin said. ``They both play good defense and we
probably have a need for somebody to pinch run more than anything.
Our offense has been good enough where I don't see Ruben being a
good fit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also have roster concerns. Both McDonald and Green
are out of options, meaning they would have to go through outright
waivers before being sent to the minor leagues and could be claimed
by another team. One of them will have to go through waivers when
Kapler comes back. The Rangers don't want to risk losing both by
experimenting with Sierra.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get Gabe back, have Chad as our fourth outfielder
and have the guys we had at the start of the year,'' Melvin said.
``Then we'd probably make a decision between Green and McDonald.''
</P>
<P>
   So Sierra stays at Oklahoma and waits. But there is hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``As time goes by, more clubs will be calling,'' Melvin said.
``I've been asked about him. One of the problems clubs are having
is they have so many injuries, they're starting to look at Triple A
for help. It looks like he's still able to hit and may have
something left. I won't stand in his way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 2237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
