<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODRIGUEZ TOPS AL VOTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The drama is over. It usually is when the first
release of the All-Star voting is announced. Rangers catcher Ivan
Rodriguez is headed toward his ninth consecutive All-Star Game and
his eighth consecutive starting assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez led all American League players regardless of position
with 455,486 votes, more than twice as many as his nearest
competitor at catcher. That would be Jorge Posada of the Yankees,
who has received 201,665 votes in the first voting release
announced yesterday. Cleveland Indians second baseman Roberto
Alomar is second among all American League players with 386,062
votes.
</P>
<P>
   From the Rangers, Rafael Palmeiro was fifth among first basemen
and second baseman Luis Alicea and shortstop Royce Clayton were
ninth at their positions. No Rangers outfielders were listed in the
top 20. Detroit's Juan Gonzalez is 12th, far behind the three
leaders, Kansas City's Jermaine Dye, New York's Bernie Williams and
Cleveland's Manny Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   All-Star voting continues through June 25. The starting teams
for both leagues will be announced July 4. The pitchers and
reserves will be announced July 5.  &QL; 
Gonzalez needs MRI
</P>
<P>
   Juan Gonzalez was not in the Tigers' starting lineup last night
and is scheduled to undergo an MRI exam on the strained tendon in
his left heel today. The Tigers are concerned because the swelling
hasn't gone down, and Gonzalez is still in considerable pain. The
disabled list is a possibility.  &QL; 
Kapler getting close
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Gabe Kapler, on the disabled list with a strained hip
flexor, could be activated by the Rangers on the upcoming
homestand, probably either Sunday or Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler tested the injury yesterday afternoon by running the
bases and said he only felt the injury once. He is planning to take
today off, then run the bases again tomorrow at The Ballpark in
Arlington. If that goes well, he could be sent out on a second
medical rehabilitation assignment on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   That may be just a one- or two-game assignment but both Kapler
and the Rangers want to make sure he is healthy before he is
activated. He reinjured the muscle in his last rehabilitation
assignment, which further delayed his return.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler said yesterday, ``The muscle was as good or better than
the first time I went out on assignment. But I'm not going to
\Rreinjure it\S again. I'm going to be smart about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapler has been on the disabled list since May 2 after suffering
the injury running the bases during a game against the Tampa Bay
Devil Rays.  &QL; 
Minor-league notes
</P>
<P>
   Cuban refugee//second baseman Jorge ``Spider'' Diaz has been
activated and assigned to Class-A Port Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Savannah (Ga.) SandGnats infielder Hank Blalock and pitcher Matt
Kosderka have been selected to the South Atlantic League Southern
Division All-Star team.
</P>
<P>
   Double-A Tulsa first baseman Carlos Pena continues to thrive in
the Texas League. Pena, the Rangers' No. 1 pick in 1998, is hitting
.335 (10th in the league) with 15 home runs (third) and 57 RBI
(second).  &QL; 
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are expected to eclipse the 1 million mark in
attendance during tomorrow's game against the Arizona Diamondbacks.
The Rangers are 27,356 fans shy of the mark.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Mike Munoz, on the disabled list with tendinitis in his
left elbow, is scheduled to pitch batting practice for the first
time tomorrow. Trainer Danny Wheat said Munoz would probably throw
batting practice two or three times during the six-game homestand,
then possibly go out on medical rehabilitation assignment while the
club is on the next road trip to Colorado, Baltimore and Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have a day off today, one of 11 scheduled before the
All-Star break. They have just six scheduled after the break and
one is being used to make up the April 11 rainout with the New York
Yankees. Said manager Johnny Oates, ``I wish the off-days were more
evenly spread throughout the schedule.''
nn
</P>
