<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. and Phone Companies Agree to Some Rate Cuts
</P>
<P>
   The federal government and many of the nation's telephone
companies agreed to a reshuffling of phone rates that would reduce
the bills of tens of millions of less affluent consumers and lead
to less significant cuts for other consumers and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the reductions, part of an agreement and an order
by the Federal Communications Commission, amounted to the largest
rate cut in the history of federal telephone regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Daimler Ending Low-Rate Loans
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler said it would eliminate most low-rate loans on
new Chrysler, Dodge and Plymouth cars and instead offer bigger cash
rebates to consumers and new discounts to dealers.
DaimlerChrysler's shift in strategy shows that the Federal
Reserve's six increases in short-term interest rates are beginning
to put pressure on the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Kmart Names New Chief Executive
</P>
<P>
   Kmart, which has been struggling to revive its sagging sales and
stock price, reached outside the company for a new chief executive,
selecting Charles Conaway, 39, the president and chief operating
officer of the CVS Corp., the drugstore chain. He succeeds Floyd
Hall, who is stepping down after a search for his replacement that
Kmart announced a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Gains Early but Ends Lower
</P>
<P>
   After adding modestly to Tuesday's record advance, the Nasdaq
composite index turned lower in the final hour and finished down
58.57 points, or 1.7 percent, to 3,400.91. The Dow Jones industrial
average edged down 4.80 points, to 10,522.33, while the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index fell 1.85 points, or 0.13 percent, to
1,420.60.
</P>
<P>
   Softbank Has Setback in Bank Bid
</P>
<P>
   Softbank, Japan's leading Internet company, was dealt a setback
in efforts to acquire Nippon Credit Bank, which was nationalized by
the government, after a deadline for reaching an agreement passed.
The Financial Reconstruction Commission said that it intended to
keep talking to Softbank but that it would also talk to other
potential bidders.
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai Founder Vows Revamping
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai Group's chairman announced radical changes that will
severely diminish his family's management role and help South
Korea's biggest conglomerate repay billions of dollars in debt
through asset sales. But the announcement was nearly overshadowed
by the refusal of the chairman's son to relinquish control of
Hyundai's automaker.
</P>
<P>
   New Home Sales Slide 5.8 Percent
</P>
<P>
   New home sales fell 5.8 percent in April, to an annual rate of
909,000 units. Purchasing managers in the Chicago area also
reported that their factory index fell this month, and the
Conference Board's index of leading economic indicators dropped in
April for the second time in three months.
</P>
<P>
   Invensys to Buy Software Maker
</P>
<P>
   Invensys, a British manufacturer of factory controls, agreed to
buy Baan, the Dutch software maker, for $802 million, promising to
turn around the company, which has lost money and share value for
nearly two years.
</P>
</TEXT>
