<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TOUR-WORKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUR BUS WORKERS SHOCKED AT SUDDEN JOB LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUAN FORERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They knew their company had been under intense
scrutiny, but employees of New York Apple Tours still shook their
heads in disbelief Wednesday after hearing that the state had
ordered the operator's double-decker buses off the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Some workers quietly agreed that the city had a right to
investigate the company's environmental and safety record,
especially after a pedestrian was struck and killed by an Apple
Tours bus last week. But they wondered if the state might have had
other options. Without a job, the workers asked, how would they
feed their children and pay their bills?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very surprised,'' said Amadou Sabi, 45, an employee of
Apple Tours for eight years, moments after hearing the news
Wednesday afternoon when he arrived at the company's visitor center
at Eighth Avenue and 48th Street
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they were going to give us some time,'' said Sabi,
who was a ticket seller. ``I don't know what to do. I have a wife,
two kids, a family to support.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Martin, 35, who also sold tickets and had been with the
company five years, said she felt like a member of her family had
died. ``I love the work and I love the family,'' she said. ``It's
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The temporary shutdown order was also hard on hundreds of
tourists who had bought tickets for a tour of Manhattan aboard
Apple Tours' red buses Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Field, a visitor from Australia, said she had ridden one
block aboard a bus when a guide said about 1:30 p.m. that the tour
was over. ``Sorry, folks, but we've been closed down,'' the guide
told the bus of tourists, Field said,
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very angry,'' said Field, who arrived in New York with her
husband. ``This is our first day here and this is what we're
confronted with.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of tourists demanded refunds and stormed off after Apple
Tours employees told them none would be given. Later in the
afternoon, other tourists were told their tickets would be honored
by Apple Tours' competitors, Gray Line and New York Double-Decker.
</P>
<P>
   Craig P. Heard, president of New York Double-Decker, confirmed
that his company would accept Apple Tours tickets. Lee Gelber,
manager of tour services for Gray Line, said the company would
honor tickets bought from tourism companies that do business with
Gray Line. But he said his company would not accept tickets bought
from other operators or directly from Apple Tours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apple has collected all the money, and there's no way they're
going to pay it to us, not that we can envision,'' Gelber said.
</P>
<P>
   The 300 workers of Apple Tours, meanwhile, passionately defended
the right of their company to operate. By evening, dozens had
gathered in front of the visitors center, saying the city's charges
were ``bogus'' and a ``set-up.''
</P>
<P>
   A tour guide, Eva Lee, screamed that the company was being
unfairly maligned.
</P>
<P>
   In private conversations throughout the afternoon, some workers
were more circumspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should put restrictions on us if they want, more point
checks, but they shouldn't shut us down,'' said Juan Gonzalez, a
dispatcher and a five-year veteran of Apple Tours.
</P>
<P>
   Lorenzo Smith, 23, a driver who said he was ticketed last week
for driving a bus without the proper license, said the temporary
shutdown was probably a good thing for him. ``This is what I needed
to get out of here,'' he said. ``I needed a little more stability,
and this company wasn't doing it for me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
