<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PARDON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH FAVORS DELAYING INMATE'S EXECUTION FOR DNA TEST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Editors: resend for all needing) 
 
 
By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
and EVAN MOORE 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In a case involving DNA evidence, Gov. George W.
Bush said Wednesday he would delay an inmate's execution Thursday
if the courts don't step in to block it.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-day reprieve, which only the governor can issue, would be
Bush's first during his five years in office.
</P>
<P>
   And, in a second case involving DNA evidence, Bush on Wednesday
issued a rare pardon to a Tyler man who served 17 years in prison
for a rape that DNA testing proved he did not commit.
</P>
<P>
   A reprieve would allow sophisticated new DNA tests on crucial
evidence in the 1993 rape and murder case of Ricky Nolen McGinn of
Brown County. With Bush and Lt. Gov. Rick Perry out of state
Thursday, the relief for McGinn could only be issued by the acting
governor, state Sen. Rodney Ellis, D-Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his staff informed Ellis that if other last-minute
legal appeals don't stall the execution, the governor expects Ellis
to carry out his wishes. A final petition is pending in the 5th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they (courts) don't cause the DNA to be reviewed, I'm more
than likely to grant the 30-day reprieve,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's pardon for 46-year-old A.B. Butler came three weeks after
the Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles recommended it. Butler was
convicted of the kidnapping and rape of a 25-year-old woman in 1983
and given two, concurrent 99-year sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Butler is the third Texas convict to be freed as a result of DNA
findings. The other two also went to inmates exonerated by DNA
testing. Kevin Byrd of Houston spent 12 years in prison before
being freed in 1997. Ben Salazar of Austin was freed while serving
a 30-year sentence for a 1992 rape.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has issued 15 pardons since he took office in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Butler began seeking a DNA comparison in 1987 and eventually
contacted Houston attorney Randy Schaffer, who obtained court
orders for the tests.
</P>
<P>
   Schaffer had one test conducted that proved inconclusive. A
second test, however, showed Butler was not the rapist and Schaffer
began requesting a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Schaffer eventually was granted a hearing on that test by state
District Judge Cynthia Kent and, on Jan. 7, Butler was released on
bail.
</P>
<P>
   Both Schaffer and Smith County District Attorney Jack Skeen
joined in requesting a pardon.
</P>
<P>
   Kent, however, ordered a new trial. Schaffer said Wednesday's
pardon negates that order.
</P>
<P>
   Bush agreed to the pardon because the case met his requirement
that such test results be reviewed by the prosecution, defense
attorneys, trial judge and the court of criminal appeals and all
agree that the test constitutes valid new evidence of innocence.
</P>
<P>
   The pardon makes Butler eligible for $25,000 from a state fund
in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in New Mexico campaigning for the Republican presidential
nomination, issued a statement saying ``all the parties concluded
that the test results constituted new, valid evidence of Mr.
Butler's innocence when reviewed in context with other evidence in
the case.''
</P>
<P>
   In comments recorded for MSNBC-TV's ``Hardball'' program, Bush
said the DNA retesting in McGinn's case was unlikely to offset
evidence that he committed the murder, though it might prove he
didn't rape the victim, Stephanie Rae Flanary, his 12-year-old
stepdaughter. If exonerated of the rape, McGinn would not be
executed but would remain behind bars for murder, Bush noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``My attitude is, if there's any doubt, we ought to be looking
at that evidence. If there's any doubt as to whether or not he
committed the rape, that evidence ought to be reviewed,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see what the courts say and see what the Board of
Pardons and Paroles says. And then I'll make up my mind,'' Bush
said. ``I want to make sure the man has his full day in court.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush made those comments, the parole board voted
overwhelmingly against McGinn's requests for a 30-day reprieve and
commutation of his death sentence. Parole board chairman Gerald
Garrett said the board voted 18-0 against recommending to Bush that
he commute the death sentence to a lesser penalty. They split 11-7
against the reprieve, Garrett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the members had any doubt as to his guilt. The facts
that are before us at this time clearly indicate that he's
guilty,'' Garrett said. He was referring to blood and hair evidence
that prosecution experts said tied McGinn to the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. McGinn and his supporters, at the 11th hour, introduced a
new issue and I believe the membership took a close look at that,''
Garrett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board has rendered its decision on this matter, so that
leaves the governor only the option of granting a one-time, 30-day
reprieve,'' Garrett noted.
</P>
<P>
   If Ellis grants the reprieve that Bush favors, McGinn can prove
or disprove his culpability in the rape and murder, one of his
lawyers said. Specifically, the defense teams want to conduct new
types of tests on semen stains found on the victim's clothes and on
a pubic hair _ previously identified as probably from McGinn _
found on the girl's body.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Barry Scheck, the DNA expert who defended O.J. Simpson,
derided as ``junk science'' the microscopic hair comparisons
conducted on the pubic hair. He said Bush should grant the reprieve
as ``a matter of common sense and basic decency.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how anybody could oppose this. Not only could we
prevent the execution of somebody who might be innocent, but it
could also lead to the apprehension of the real perpetrator,''
Scheck said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of the 72 post-conviction DNA exonerations in North
America, 16 times it has led to the identification of the real
perpetrator, and that's going to happen more and more with these
DNA databases,'' Scheck said.
</P>
<P>
   But on Fox News, McGinn's prosecutor said further DNA testing is
unnecessary and wasn't sought on a timely basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, unlike before the trial, Mr. McGinn is not
presumed to be innocent but is in fact presumed to be guilty
because that's what a jury found,'' said Brown County District
Attorney Lee Haney of Brownwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even this evidence would not overcome the tremendous amount of
other evidence that was involved at the trial. ... There's DNA
evidence, scientific evidence and circumstantial evidence tying him
to the murder of this young girl,'' Haney said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
