<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-JONES-SEC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW JONES CRITICIZES CORPORATE NEWS PROPOSAL
</HEADLINE>
 By FELICITY BARRINGE R  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dow Jones &AMP; Co. has complained to the Securities and
Exchange Commission that a proposed rule intended to prevent
companies from giving information to a hand-picked group of
investors would result in ``less informative, less objective and
less timely reporting.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless the proposal is amended, wrote Peter G. Skinner,
executive vice president and general counsel of the company that
owns The Wall Street Journal, Barron's and Dow Jones Newswires, it
could increase timidity among executives afraid of running afoul of
the rule, and end up ``choking the flow'' of information.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC proposed the rule in December, after the issue had been
championed for months by the commission's chairman, Arthur Levitt.
In a speech in October, Levitt said: ``The behind-the-scenes
feeding of material nonpublic information from companies to
analysts is a stain on our markets. In a time when instantaneous
and free-flowing information is the norm, these sort of whispers
are an insult to fair and public disclosure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Journal's opposition highlights the increasing scrutiny
given to how, and to whom, companies provide information in an era
when new technologies and hair-trigger markets have made
information a more valuable and sensitive commodity.
</P>
<P>
   The view that the proposed rule could have the unintended
consequence of restricting the flow of financial information,
however, is hardly universal. While critical comments were filed by
Dow Jones and some members of the Society of American Business
Editors and Writers, other news organizations largely remained
silent.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg News, a financial service that is a competitor of Dow
Jones', published a news report on Wednesday highlighting its
rival's decision to criticize the proposed rule. Dow Jones,
Bloomberg reported, was arguing that the proposal ``could dry up
scoops at its flagship Wall Street Journal newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkler, Bloomberg's editor in chief, said: ``There isn't a
great story that has come from a handout. Ever.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``The best stories come from good old-fashioned
enterprise. I say that as a former Wall Street Journal reporter. I
don't understand what the fuss is about.''
</P>
<P>
   Dow Jones' comments, filed as the designated period for reaction
was ending last month, sought to make the proposed rule
inapplicable to information released ``to bona fide news
organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial journalists are not the only group split on the
proposal, which is in general disfavor with most analysts but
appears quite popular among small investors, whose numbers have
expanded exponentially.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel J. Kramer, a partner at the law firm of Schulte Roth &AMP;
Zabel, says he believes that the key question in analyzing the new
rules is ``whether they will result in an information brownout, and
result in less information being available to the public rather
than more.''
</P>
<P>
   The high profile given to the practice of selective disclosure,
however, has had some impact. A 1998 study by the National
Investors Relations Institute, cited by Kramer, found that while
the majority of the 163 companies surveyed preferred to discuss new
information with analysts on conference calls, 29 percent invited
individual shareholders, and 14 percent invited the media.
</P>
<P>
   Three months ago, a report from the investor relations' group
showed that 82 percent of companies let individual investors in on
their conference calls and 74 percent let journalists participate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 2243EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0424 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1289 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-CHILD-DEATH-340&AMP;AD     05-31 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHILD-DEATH-340&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER'S ABUSE OF BABY IN '86 MAY BE LINKED TO HIS DEATH THIS
YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The authorities said Wednesday that they were
considering filing manslaughter or perhaps murder charges against a
Queens woman whose son died this spring from injuries she inflicted
on him 14 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The case is an extremely rare instance in which a long-ago
assault becomes fodder for a homicide investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The city medical examiner said Wednesday that Joshua Slaughter,
14, died on April 11 from complications related to injuries he
received during his first weeks of life, when his mother, Mitzi
Slaughter, aggressively shook him in their home in Jamaica, Queens.
Because of the shaking, police said, the boy suffered a brain
injury, developed cerebral palsy and required continuous care.
</P>
<P>
   Mitzi Slaughter, now 36, pleaded guilty in 1988 to second-degree
assault and endangering the welfare of a child. She was sentenced
to six months in prison and five years' probation, and lost custody
of her son. She appeared to have fully served her sentence for a
crime she committed as a young mother.
</P>
<P>
   But the case against her was revived last week when the medical
examiner, after rounds of tests, determined that Joshua died of
bronchial pneumonia, blood poisoning and neurological disorders
related to shaken-baby syndrome. ``The complications that occurred
are a consequence of the shaking that occurred in 1986,'' said
Ellen S. Borakove, the medical examiner's spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Slaughter was being questioned Wednesday night by investigators
at the 103rd Precinct in Jamaica, where the authorities said they
were considering filing fresh charges against her. ``We're
conferring with the Queens district attorney to determine
charges,'' said Sgt. Brian Burke, a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The state's criminal procedure law allows for renewed
prosecution of assault cases when injuries received in the assault
later cause the victim's death. Mary DeBourbon, a spokeswoman for
the Queens County district attorney, said that if the investigation
found grounds, the prosecutors could file charges.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``It's not impossible,'' she said. ``It's legally permissible.''
</P>
<P>
   But DeBourbon also said Wednesday that prosecutors were still
gathering records from the 1986 case and had not reached a
decision. Slaughter's circumstance is rare but not unprecedented.
In a similar case last year, the Bronx district attorney, Robert
Johnson, considered but ultimately declined the bringing of new
charges against a woman who attacked Rodney Irby, a Bronx man who
died 25 years after being shot and stabbed in a dispute over drugs
in the South Bronx. Irby was left a paraplegic by the assault.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities said the attack against Joshua Slaughter had
caused brain injuries and palsy disabling enough to eventually
require institutionalization. Cerebral palsy is a chronic condition
affecting body movement and muscle development. Most cases are
caused by damage to a fetus' brain, but injuries to an infant's
developing brain _ like those from violent shaking _ can also cause
the condition, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Banks, a spokeswoman for the Administration for
Children's Services, said that Slaughter had lost custody of Joshua
after she attacked him. The boy was placed in foster care and under
the administration's supervision from 1986 to 1997. During that
time, Slaughter remained in contact with her son and sometimes
spent time with him. ``The record indicates that the mom did visit
periodically,'' Banks said.
</P>
<P>
   She said that in 1997, the agency had transferred Joshua to an
institution run by the city's Department of Mental Health. The boy
also received treatment from the United Cerebral Palsy center in
Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Wednesday that on the evening of April 11 Joshua was
taken to Mary Immaculate Hospital from the United Cerebral Palsy
center at 110-35 164th Place in Queens. He died shortly after
arriving.
</P>
<P>
   United Cerebral Palsy declined to comment Wednesday. A spokesman
for the city's Department of Health, reached late in the day, said
the agency was unable to immediately locate records on Joshua 's
case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
