<HEADLINE>
INSTEAD OF ATTACKING HIS FOE, GORE TALKS OF FAMILY MENTAL HEALTH
ISSUES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHEVY CHASE, Md. _ With his wife, Tipper, by his side, Al Gore
spent Wednesday morning in a suburban Washington community center
sharing his family experiences with mental illness and his ideas on
how the federal government can better guarantee treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Absent from the vice president's address to the roomful of
mental health experts and advocates was his standard denunciation
of Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush's record on the
issue in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Gore related to the crowd how much he learned from
Tipper, who has acknowledged being treated for clinical depression
after their son, Albert III, was hit by a car in 1989. He had a
lengthy but complete recovery from his injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mental illness is nothing to be ashamed of,'' the Democratic
presidential candidate said. ``But stigma and discrimination shame
us all.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore proposed requiring insurance companies to cover mental
health services for children in the same way they cover other
health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the softer side of Al Gore. After weeks of playing
the attack dog, the vice president has decided to ease up and talk
more about his own life experiences to show voters he relates to
the family issues they face.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week he spoke to veterans about his experience in
Vietnam and how it made him understand the problems of military
families.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday evening he scheduled a town hall style meeting in
Macon, Ga. Thursday he travels to Emory University Medical Center
in Atlanta to talk about protecting privacy and treatment rights of
cancer patients. Gore's sister, Nancy, died of lung cancer in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   And on Friday he will talk about fatherhood and the need to
fine-tune welfare reform to ensure that men play a greater role in
raising their children.
</P>
<P>
   The latest campaign strategy appears aimed at improving his
image among voters, who find Bush more likable than the vice
president, according to polls. Indeed, as Gore has escalated his
attacks on the Texas governor over the past few months he has
slipped behind Bush in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear the more he attacks Bush the more reactive and
negative he looks and therefore less presidential,'' said political
analyst Stuart Rothenberg. ``He wants to get rid of the petty
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's latest tack may be aimed at gaining an advantage among
women voters, who traditionally have been Democrats' strongest
supporters but who have been drawn to Bush's emphasis on education.
Polls show women split among the two candidates while men heavily
favor Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Gore takes a break from blasting Bush, he is still
relying on his campaign and surrogates to keep up the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not going to be a retreat in discussing his mess in
Texas,'' said Gore campaign spokesman Chris Lehane.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, when Gore received the endorsement of the
League of Conservation Voters, he left it to the environmental
group's president, Deb Callahan, to criticize Bush's record on
pollution in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   And a Gore campaign aide referred reporters to Sen. John Kerry,
D-Mass., for comment on recent allegations that Bush did not report
for training for a year during his Texas Air National Guard service
in the early 1970s. Bush says he fulfilled all of his training
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokesman Scott McLellan scoffed at Gore's newest
campaign shift. ``How many times is the vice president allowed to
reinvent himself?'' McClellan asked. ``Al Gore's latest strategy is
to hide behind his surrogates.''
</P>
<P>
   However, in using others to assault his opponent, Gore appears
to be taking a page out of Bush's playbook. For the most part the
governor has chosen to take the high road while leaving the
attacking to others, including members of Congress, the Republican
National Committee, and conservative political groups.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
