<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.D., N.M., Calif.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INQUIRING MINDS WANT TO KNOW
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two Senate Democrats jumped into the debate over Social
Security Wednesday, writing to Gov. George W. Bush of Texas for
more details on his proposal to create individual investment
accounts ``so that the American public, elected officials and other
policy-makers can evaluate your proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter, circulated by Sens. Charles Schumer of New York and
Byron Dorgan of North Dakota, asked questions intended to show some
of the hard choices that might be involved in reshaping the
retirement system. Among them: Would the government do anything to
limit investment choices to minimize risk? Would the proposal cut
Social Security benefits? Would the cuts have a disproportionate
impact on women?
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel strongly that as we debate any change to our Social
Security system, the public needs the full details of any
proposals,'' the Democrats wrote. Ari Fleischer, Bush's spokesman,
said Bush welcomed bipartisan input and supported a proposal by a
bipartisan group of senators to have a commission study changes to
the retirement system.
</P>
<P>
   KNOWING NOTHING, TELLING ALL
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush often revels in not being a know-it-all, but
when Gov. Gary Johnson of New Mexico tried to join in that
celebration on Wednesday, he may well have taken it just a tad too
far.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``I'll tell you a story,'' Johnson said to scores of people who
had turned out to meet Bush in Albuquerque. ``At one of these
governors' conferences, George turns to me and says, `What are they
talking about?' I said, `I don't know.' He said, `You don't know a
thing, do you?' And I said, `Not one thing.' He said, `Neither do
I.' And we kind of high-fived. And my point here is _ is that _
when it comes to politics, it's really hard to find somebody who
will rather admit _ or rather talk about _ the things they don't
know and make that really evident.'' Bush has certainly been known
to do that.  &UR;  &LR; DELIVERING VENOM
</P>
<P>
   Bob Mulholland, a consultant to the California Democratic Party,
is celebrated for his unsparing verbal assaults on Republicans. But
last week, in a gesture that seemed over the top even for him, he
sent former Speaker Newt Gingrich and his fiancee, Callista Bisek,
a $12 gift from their online wedding registry at Williams-Sonoma: a
half-dozen dish towels and a cheery note.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newt: Here's a set of dishcloths to clean up the mess with
your second wife,'' Mulholland wrote, adding: ``Callista: In 5
years he'll be w/another younger woman. That's his pattern.'' That
was too much for the California Republican chairman, John McGraw,
who issued a statement calling on the state Democratic chairman,
Art Torres, to dismiss Mulholland, and sent along a can of Lysol to
disinfect Mulholland's office. ``Your flunky's latest despicable,
hate-filled act of venom sinks lower than a snake's belly in Death
Valley,'' McGraw wrote. Mulholland was unfazed. ``I'm happy to see
the California Republicans defending Newt Gingrich,'' he said.
``This man is despicable. He owes an apology to the American people
for attacking Bill Clinton while he was carrying on his own
affair.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Sand Harbor State Park, Nev., and Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Atlanta.
</P>
