A1306 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-LAZIO-N     05-31 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-LAZIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: REPUBLICANS FIND COMFORT WITH RICK LAZIO 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELEANOR RANDOLPH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The dominant emotion at this week's New York State Republican
convention was relief that Rep. Rick Lazio has stepped in to
replace Mayor Rudolph Giuliani as the party's Senate nominee.
Sometimes this relief was unspoken, but in a surprising number of
cases, top Republicans expressed it openly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you there was a lot of nervousness two weeks ago,''
said Georgette Mosbacher, a prominent fund-raiser. ``Under
everyone's breath we were saying, my God, can Rick raise the money?
Are we too late? But no, the segue from Rudy to Rick was absolutely
seamless.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not absolutely seamless. In a hastily scripted
two-hour event there were enough miscues to remind most seasoned
viewers that this was a campaign still suffering through its
toddler stage. The text of the speech handed out to the media, for
example, was still titled ``Draft 13.'' The unlucky rewrite
contained stage directions for how Lazio was to punctuate a story
about learning the value of labor from his father, who made the boy
earn money for a baseball glove by working in the family store.
``At pretty low wages, I remember,'' the text read, then added in
parentheses, ``(Smile).'' Lazio did.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate's boyish smile, of course, was a bit lopsided
after the fall on Monday that left him with a stitched lip. He
probably won some points for campaigning gamely along, but a more
seasoned staff would have thought to reposition the media platforms
so that the cameras were not forced to focus on the swollen side of
the candidate's face. And when Lazio's speech strayed past 5 p.m.,
he was suddenly competing with seven television personalities
brazenly doing their live stand-ups so loudly that it became
difficult to hear the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   These are the kinds of rough spots that political reporters are
trained to notice and the party faithful are conditioned to ignore.
In the main, you could feel the 2,000 Republican leaders gathered
in Buffalo settling into their comfort zone, sighing about how
scrubbed and energetic their candidate is, how clean-cut he is, how
home-grown. In fact, the whole idea of Lazio's nomination seemed to
be that he is the only insider here, the outsider being Hillary
Rodham Clinton, who moved to Westchester County last year from the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   The Erie County executive, Joel Giambra, fed the party line by
noting that it was time to elect a senator who ``played little
league football in this state.'' A colleague offered the contrast
that Lazio has paid taxes in New York state for many years. And
Gov. George Pataki summed it up by saying, ``Rick Lazio is one of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Such was the zeal to embrace the carpetbagger strategy that no
one seemed to consider that ``one of us'' can be a loaded political
message, especially coming from a convention that had about as many
blacks and Hispanics as your average private golf club. More
important for Lazio, there are a lot of voters in New York state
who may not be as new to the state as Clinton but still do not
qualify as ``one of'' a party that has already maxed out its
support among white suburbanites.
</P>
<P>
   Even some Republicans, like Giuliani, do not fit easily in this
upstate conservative clubhouse. The mayor, who had the good sense
not to appear in Buffalo and muddy Lazio's message, is still known
in this crowd as the man who endorsed Mario Cuomo. That Giuliani is
allowed to call himself a Republican is a source of amazement to
some GOP insiders, not a few of whom work for Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani departure clearly pleased some on the Pataki team,
but it also sets up a key test of the governor's power. If Rudy
Giuliani ran against the first lady and lost, Pataki could shrug it
off as the mayor's problem, not his or the party's. If Lazio loses,
some of the blame will settle on his coach in the governor's office
and on this convention's us-versus-them message.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, though, Republicans seem united in celebrating a
candidate who is not only the anti-Hillary but also the non-Rudy.
The GOP leadership is betting that as a candidate who lacks the
polarizing features of both Clinton and Giuliani, Lazio can command
broad if bland swatches of the middle ground. Hence the
concentrated effort by so many speakers to depict the first lady as
an invading Nurse Ratched. That may work, but a campaign to make
Clinton into a fearsome outsider could also turn Rick Lazio into
Ricky Nelson. In such a match, some of those swing voters might
wind up going for the more forceful character after all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
