u i BC-CLINTON-EUROPE-HNS &LR;      05-31 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EUROPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON VOWS TO SHARE ANTI-MISSILE TECHNOLOGY 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LISBON, Portugal _ President Clinton pledged Wednesday to make
any U.S. missile-defense technology available to allies, including
Russia, and held out the prospect of unexpected progress on arms
control when he meets President Vladimir Putin this weekend in
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in the first news conference of his weeklong European
trip, said it would be ``unethical'' to withhold effective
anti-missile know-how from any allies working to stem nuclear
weaponry, including America's old Cold War adversary.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has set a midsummer deadline for deciding on
whether to go ahead with the anti-missile system, said the United
States has ``done a lot of information-sharing already with the
Russians.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that we could ever advance the notion that we
have this technology designed to protect us against a new threat
... and not make it available to them,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic president seemed to be moving toward the position
taken recently by Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive
Republican presidential nominee, but top Clinton aides resisted
that interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's always been my position,'' Clinton said, a sentiment
echoed by White House spokesman Joe Lockhart in a subsequent
briefing.
</P>
<P>
   However, last month, after Bush said ``a missile defense system
should not only defend our country, it should defend our allies,''
Lockhart told a White House briefing, ``We have a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pursuing a policy of a limited, 50-state national
missile defense to protect against the emerging states like Korea,
Iraq. We believe that's the most effective way to move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart criticized Bush for turning down a briefing by Pentagon
top brass on the Clinton administration's work to date on the
prospective missile shield.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed anti-missile system has been criticized as a
potential offensive measure by Putin and is expected to be a key
point of contention in the two presidents' first direct talks
Saturday and Sunday in the Russian capital. Clinton contends the
missile shield is intended only to protect the United States from
undependable nations, such as North Korea, or their terrorist
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Although White House aides have worked for the past two weeks to
play down expectations of the U.S. president's initial summit with
Putin, Clinton told a news conference more progress might be in the
offing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be surprised if we resolved all of our differences on
the question of missile defense, although we might make more
headway than most people expect. I'm just not sure yet,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments came at the end of a joint meeting between
U.S. government leaders and chiefs of the 15-nation European Union,
a one-day session that produced no discernible progress on the
trickiest trans-Atlantic trade disputes, including the EU ban on
U.S. hormone-treated beef.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton planned to confront another international flash point
Thursday before leaving the Portuguese capital for Berlin. He
rearranged his schedule for a morning session with Prime Minister
Ehud Barak of Israel. Clinton spoke by telephone for 20 minutes
Wednesday with Palestinian leader Yassir Arafat about recent
developments, including the withdrawal of Israeli military from
Lebanon, affecting Israeli-Palestinian plans for a final peace
agreement by fall.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's statements about making more progress on arms control
with Putin left senior White House aides scrambling to describe
what breakthroughs to which he might be referring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you what he's talking about,'' Tony Blinken, the
National Security Council's senior director for European affairs,
said in a burst of candor.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said Clinton was talking about nothing more than a
previously anticipated move by both nations to dispose of 34 tons
each of military-grade plutonium.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not hinting at anything other than a few things that
we've got going,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Berger, Clinton's national security adviser, said last
week in Washington that the United States and Russia had made
``significant progress'' to get rid of weapons-grade materials and
expressed hope that the plutonium agreement would be ready for the
leaders to sign off on in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an enormously important agreement if we're able to
finalize it,'' Berger said. It was a major point not only in the
U.S.-Russia bilateral relationship but also on the broader nuclear
nonproliferation front, he added. Smaller, non-nuclear nations have
been increasingly critical of what they see as U.S. foot-dragging
in scaling back its warhead-making arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton defended his upcoming meeting with Putin even if the
results are limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in the areas where we may not have an agreement, in some
ways that may be the most important reason for the trip of all,''
Clinton said. ``We shouldn't only do these trips and these
dialogues when we know we've got a guaranteed outcome. Sometimes
it's most important to be talking when there's still unresolved
differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke during a joint news conference with Portuguese
Prime Minister Antonio Guterres, whose nation currently holds the
rotating presidency of the European Union, and Romano Prodi, the
former Italian prime minister who is chairman of the EU Commission.
They appeared before a gathering of international reporters in a
sunny plaza at the Que Luz palace outside Lisbon.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, whose sightseeing bug has been little served while in
Portugal, later went for a round of golf near Sintra.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who insists he has not made up his mind about going
forward with the missile defense system, went over the criteria he
says will guide his thinking.
</P>
<P>
   The first is whether ``there is a threat that is new and
different.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer to that, it seems to me, is plainly, yes, there is
and there will be one,'' Clinton said, referring to development of
nuclear capabilities by nations not part of international arms
control and nonproliferation pacts.
</P>
<P>
   The other criteria are whether the technology works, whether it
is cost effective and what will be the effect of the system on
``our overall security interests, included but not limited to arms
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington's European allies have objected to the missile
defense proposal, in part because they fear it would leave them
undefended.
</P>
<P>
   Guterres said that although there is no official EU position
opposing the missile defense, ``we have ... a main concern'' that
trans-Atlantic security proposals remain ``as comprehensive as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
