u k BC-EDIT-PHONES-NYT &LR;      05-31 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PHONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PHONE RATES HEAD DOWNWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, June 1:
</P>
<P>
   Telephone customers will soon begin to save money on their
long-distance calls, courtesy of decisions made on Wednesday by the
Federal Communications Commission. Families that make few
long-distance calls will save the most under the commission's
intricate ruling, as much as 50 percent _ a nice touch that brings
the benefits of deregulation to low-income families. But buried
among the regulatory rulings is something that should prove even
more important to most customers in the long run. The commission
wrung subsidies out of regulated rates that have kept prices too
high and have stymied the outbreak of competition that Congress
promised when it passed the 1996 Telecommunications Act.
</P>
<P>
   The issue the commission partially resolved on Wednesday
concerns access charges _ regulated fees that local phone companies
like Bell Atlantic are permitted to charge long-distance carriers
like AT&AMP;T for their use of the wire loops that Bell Atlantic runs
into nearly everyone's home and business. The regional Bells and
long-distance carriers have been fighting over access since the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the access charges cover the costs that rise as the
length of individual calls rises. The most important decision the
commission made on Wednesday was to cut these per-minute fees by
about $2 billion a year _ roughly 4 percent of annual long-distance
charges. This would bring these charges down from about five cents
three years ago to about one penny per call, a level close to the
actual costs that local companies incur when their loops are used.
</P>
<P>
   That, in turn, should allow the price of long-distance service
to fall sharply, assuming the carriers pass the savings on to
consumers as they have said they will. By matching prices to costs,
the commission is doing all it can to create markets where the
low-cost provider captures the most business.
</P>
<P>
   Another access charge covers the fixed cost of providing the
loops _ costs that remain the same no matter how many calls are
processed. Here the commission did little more than simplify
billing. These charges currently appear on both local bills and the
long-distance bills. But in the future the two will be combined
into one charge on the local bill. Families will pay less to their
long-distance carrier, but more to the local company. The total
will not change very much, causing consumer groups to criticize the
commission for not making significant cuts. But the commission
pledged to do a careful economic study in two years that will
determine exactly how much customers need to pay to cover the true
costs of maintaining the loops.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest winners on Wednesday will be families that in a
given month make no or very few long-distance calls. Typically,
carriers charge $3 a month for long-distance calls no matter how
few are actually made. As part of the deal, some long-distance
carriers promised to waive these minimum fees.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 Telecommunications Act invited long-distance carriers
into local service and local carriers into long-distance service.
But so far, customers have reaped only modest benefits. Part of the
problem has been a complicated regulatory system. On Wednesday the
commission simplified billing, brought charges in line with costs
and provided a special boost to low-income families. Nothing
dramatic will result from these steps for now. But over time they
should foster competition, and the savings should mount.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 2320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000531.0430 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1446 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-HUNDLEY-L     05-31 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-HUNDLEY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDLEY PLACED ON 15-DAY DISABLED LIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Todd Hundley spent the offseason working
vigorously to prove he could return to all-star from, and he was
heading in that direction until, while running the bases, he spun
quickly to see where a ball landed.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley strained the oblique muscle in the right side of his rib
cage in Tuesday night's game. He went on the 15-day disabled list
prior to Wednesday's game against the Mets, but he admitted the
healing process is probably longer. His place on the roster was
taken by infielder Alex Cora, who was recalled from Triple-A
Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things, usually on the average, are three to six weeks
until you feel 100 percent,'' Hundley said. ``The only thing about
it is it's not the cartilage between the ribs. It's really a
delicate thing, and for the next two weeks the trick is not to
aggravate it so you have to start over.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Chad Kreuter steps into the starting spot. Kreuter has
built his career around being a strong defensive catcher, but the
loss of Hundley could have a profound effect on the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter and Hundley switch-hit, but Hundley's bat is more
potent. He's hitting .290 with 13 homers and 33 RBI, mostly from
the sixth spot in the order, and has provided better pitches for
Eric Karros, Gary Sheffield and Shawn Green. The four have combined
for 52 homers and 157 RBI and are the major reasons the Dodgers are
fourth in the National League with 296 runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley joins starters Devon White and Adrian Beltre on the
disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you take out him and Beltre, it's a little different look
in the lineup,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``(Hundley's)
been feeling so good. Whether he's catching or whether he's
hitting, and he's hit well right-handed and left-handed, he's a big
part of our success.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley was injured during Tuesday's brutal 10-5 loss to Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't breathe,'' Hundley said. ``It felt like someone
punched me and stabbed me with a knife at the same time. It knocked
the wind out of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Team physician Dr. Ralph Gambardella examined Hundley on
Wednesday. It's similar to the injury Todd Hollandsworth
experienced last season. Hollandsworth missed 22 days with his
strained oblique.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley vowed to work twice as hard to recover from this injury
as he did during the winter, when he worked out six days a week to
get his body and right arm in shape for spring training. He's
highly regarded in the clubhouse as an intense worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody on this team works harder than him,'' Sheffield said.
``He comes in and works on the elbow, when he's finished with that
he works on his back, and when he's finished with that he working
on his catching.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
