<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ISRAEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PRESIDENTIAL SUCCESSION IN ISRAEL 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, June 1:
</P>
<P>
   Ezer Weizman is justly admired for his many contributions to
Israeli public life, including crucial support for peace efforts
with Egypt and the Palestinians. But a withering government report
detailing his receipt of more than $300,000 from two businessmen a
decade ago left him little choice but to resign from the largely
ceremonial office of president effective July 10. Appropriately,
the leading choice to succeed him is another man closely identified
with the quest for Mideast peace, former Prime Minister Shimon
Peres.
</P>
<P>
   Weizman's downfall brings a notable career to a sad end. As air
force commander he helped lead Israel to victory in the 1967 war.
Entering politics, he joined Menachem Begin's conservative Likud
government as defense minister and played a major role in the
diplomacy leading to the Camp David agreement and the 1979 peace
treaty with Egypt, Israel's first with any Arab nation. He later
joined the Labor Party and, with its support, became president in
1993. Stretching the limited powers of that office, he became an
independent-minded advocate for peace, challenging the policies of
Labor as well as Likud governments and becoming popular with the
Israeli public.
</P>
<P>
   But it turns out that Weizman was not quite as independent as he
seemed. The illegal political contributions he secretly accepted
were, by his own acknowledgment, efforts to buy influence with a
rising political star. Had the statute of limitations not run out,
Weizman could have faced criminal charges of bribery.
</P>
<P>
   Peres would make a worthy successor, given his broad experience
and his close personal identification with the peace process.
Awarded a share of the Nobel Peace Prize for his role in
negotiating the 1993 Oslo peace agreements, he became prime
minister after the assassination of his fellow laureate Yitzhak
Rabin in 1995. Since then Peres has sometimes been seen as an
intra-party rival to Prime Minister Ehud Barak. But Barak was smart
to pick him as the candidate of his majority coalition when
Parliament chooses a new president on July 31.
</P>
<P>
   The move will help reinforce the coalition's unity for the
challenging months ahead. Israel must find ways to stabilize its
border with Lebanon in the wake of its rushed withdrawal last week
and the movement of Iranian-backed Hezbollah guerrillas to the
international frontier. It also faces possible new tensions with
Syria over Lebanon and the Golan Heights while trying to meet a
September target date for negotiating a final peace agreement with
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Barak will discuss all three of these peace issues with
President Clinton when the two meet in Portugal today. The
questions still to be resolved with the Palestinians and Syria are
difficult but have by now been clearly defined. With enough will on
all sides, they can be bridged. It would be fitting for Peres, as a
newly installed president, to participate in completing the peace
agreements he envisioned and helped design. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 2326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
