<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1449 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-1     05-31 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT FILES TECHNICAL CRITIQUE OF GOVERNMENT BREAKUP PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 18th graf starting: Along with the, etc., to make it read:
Capelles of Compaq xxx)  By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ignoring the judge's assertion that he wanted no
more briefs, Microsoft filed a detailed criticism of the
government's breakup plan Wednesday, the last filing for the record
before the judge rules on how to deal with the company's antitrust
violations.
</P>
<P>
   The company's proposal significantly modifies nearly every
element of the government's remedy plan, lengthening the amount of
time the company would have to comply with the order and scaling
back many proposals.
</P>
<P>
   The government proposal ``is defective in numerous respects,
making the document vague and ambiguous'' and therefore ``void and
unenforceable,'' the company's brief said.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier brief, filed on May 10, laid out Microsoft's broad
objections to the remedy proposal. This one is a technical
critique, attacking individual points in the plan, including e-mail
retention rules, joint-venture restrictions and a requirement that
Microsoft's senior managers be required, within 90 days, to certify
that they have read and understood the remedy ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to the Microsoft filing Wednesday evening, the Justice
Department said: ``This is another effort to posture for appeal.
The filing does not come to grips with the fact that Microsoft has
been found to have repeatedly engaged in serious legal violations,
and serious remedies are required.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft says it intends to appeal as soon as Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson rules on the remedy, a ruling that is expected
Thursday or Friday. The judge has already suggested that he is
inclined to accept the government's recommendation that the company
be broken up.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the Microsoft filing was a justification for the
company's decision to place a long document called an ``offer of
proof'' in the record during a court hearing on May 24, just before
the judge ended the proceedings. The document included statements
from witnesses that the company would have called or quoted, had
the judge held on a hearing on remedies, as Microsoft requested.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department, also ignoring the judge's no-more-briefs
edict, argued in a brief filed last Friday that the offer-of-proof
filing was cynical and irresponsible. On Wednesday Microsoft called
the government's accusations baseless and submitted an additional
offer of proof.
</P>
<P>
   The latest offer includes statements from seven academic experts
and corporate leaders who say they oppose the government's breakup
plan and related remedy proposals. Among them are Michael Capellas,
the chief executive of Compaq Computer; Jeffrey Katzenberg, founder
of the DreamWorks motion picture studio; Tom Nicely, chairman of
Geico, the insurance company; and John Whitacre, chief executive of
Nordstrom Inc., the department store chain based in Seattle,
Microsoft's hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Among Capellas' complaints is the general concern that Microsoft
would not be allowed to accord Compaq special treatment in pricing
and partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compaq is several times the size of the 20th largest''
manufacturer, he wrote, and ``there is no reason why Compaq should
not receive more resources from Microsoft, given our greater
investment in testing, distributing and promoting Microsoft's
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg wrote: ``If Microsoft were broken up _ as the
government proposes _ Microsoft's operating systems, applications
and other products over time would become less and less compatible,
both with each other and with the various hardware products used by
DreamWorks.''
</P>
<P>
   Before it critiqued the government's remedy proposal, Microsoft
stressed once again that ``the relief requested by the government
is extreme and unjustified.'' But while the company objected to the
proposal in its entirety, it also picked apart nearly all of its
parts, beginning with the first paragraph.
</P>
<P>
   There, the government gave Microsoft four months after the
judge's ruling to submit a plan for breaking the company into two
parts (though the actual breakup would be stayed until legal
appeals are complete). Microsoft countered by lengthening the time
to 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   The company notes that numerous federal agencies and foreign
governments, in places where Microsoft has subsidiaries, would have
to approve the breakup plan, and ``obtaining such approvals would
be a time consuming process.''
</P>
<P>
   The government plan would create two new companies; one would
hold the Windows operating systems, the other everything else,
including the Office suite of programs like Word for word
processing and Excel for spreadsheet calculations.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, the applications company would have rights to
Internet Explorer, the company's Web browser, and could license it
back to the operating system company. But in Wednesday's brief,
Microsoft makes the same argument it has put forward since 1997,
that there is no such thing as a Web browser; Internet Explorer is
merely a feature in Windows. Jackson forcefully rejected that
argument in his rulings.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the breakup plan, the government has proposed a long
list of rules that would modify Microsoft's conduct. The company
picked those apart, too. For one, it deleted a provision
prohibiting Microsoft from making special marketing deals with
computer makers _ the provision Capellas of Compaq also opposed.
During the trial, the government showed that Microsoft sometimes
used the special deals to reward companies that followed
Microsoft's lead on issues of importance to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Among other changes, the company proposed to charge other
companies ``a reasonable royalty'' for access to technical data
about Windows needed to design programs that run with the operating
system.
</P>
<P>
   The company also deleted a requirement that it retain all of the
e-mail written by senior company managers for four years, calling
the proposal ``overly broad and unduly burdensome.'' It was e-mail
from company managers, including Bill Gates, the chairman, that
formed the basis for the government's successful suit against
Microsoft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
