<HEADER>
A1451 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-PHONE-CHARGES-1STLD-W     05-31 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONE-CHARGES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-790(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATORS CLEAR WIDE-RANGING CUTS IN TELEPHONE FEES
</HEADLINE>
 (Subs for complete rewrite with additional information; ADDS 150
words)  
(ART ADV: Photo _ NYT20 _ is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal government and many of the nation's
leading telephone companies agreed Wednesday to a reshuffling of
phone rates that would reduce the bills of tens of millions of
less-affluent consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The reductions, described by fficials of the Federal
Communications Commission as the largest rate cut in the history of
federal telephone regulation, should lead to less-significant cuts
for other consumers and businesses. And the changes could
ultimately lead to a flat rate for long-distance service, much like
fees paid by mobile phone users.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said they had a commitment from the
long-distance companies to pass on to consumers the benefits of
$3.2 billion in savings from a reduction in the payments they make
to local telephone companies to connect calls to customers, known
as access charges.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the cuts would have the biggest effect on the
poor and those who use their phones the least. Rates would be
reduced as much as 50 percent _ to $4.68 from $9.39 a month in a
typical case _ for Americans who make few or no long-distance
calls.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers and businesses that make more long-distance calls,
the government predicted reduced costs, though some consumer groups
and Wall Street analysts disagreed with the government's estimates,
suggesting they were too rosy.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer groups and analysts questioned whether the
significant savings recognized by the long-distance companies would
ultimately be passed on to consumers. They also said that the
government could not force the companies to pass the savings on to
the consumers, who would have to rely on the good faith of the
long-distance companies.
</P>
<P>
   But officials said that when access charges were last reduced
three years ago, the long-distance companies began engaging in a
price war that drastically lowered overall phone rates.
</P>
<P>
   The critics and analysts said, however, that long-distance
companies had been slow to pass on all of the savings when the
access charges were cut and that the benefit to consumers from the
price wars was offset by new fees tacked on to their bills.
</P>
<P>
   Critics and officials agreed that Wednesday's action would
fundamentally reshape the economics of the telephone industry and
that it was another big step toward deregulation. It is also part
of an evolution toward a price structure in which long-distance
rates will ultimately be like wireless and Internet service rates _
either a flat monthly fee or a fee that entitles the customer to a
bundle of minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's announcement is a giant step forward in rationalizing
pricing,'' said William Kennard, the chairman of the FCC. ``This is
the most dramatic reduction in telephone service prices in the
history of this agency.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennard said the price changes would take effect in July. He
said the commission's action was an effort to accelerate
competition by ending several implicit subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's moves involved an agreement and an order by the FCC.
They were the products of more than a year of intense negotiations
among local and long-distance companies and federal regulators on
issues that have divided the local and long-distance providers from
the moment they were created with the breakup of AT&AMP;T 16 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone executives from most of the nation's top companies
applauded the order.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the results of today's action start showing up on
customer bills in a month or so, consumers will see that the total
cost of local and long-distance telephone service will be down,''
said Duane Ackerman, the chairman and chief executive of BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time,'' he said, ``those customers who live in
rural areas that are expensive to serve and those people who need
help paying their phone bills will be ensured affordable service
well into the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that the companies had ultimately reached an
agreement with one another and regulators because of several
important trends, including the blurring of the lines between local
and long-distance companies, the competitive threats posed by the
emergence of telephone service on the Internet and the heavy
pressure put on regulators by a Republican Congress to reduce
regulations and let the marketplace play a greater role in setting
prices.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the agreement, AT&AMP;T said it would eliminate the $3
minimum monthly fee that it charges to millions of customers who
make few or no long-distance calls.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with other changes announced Wednesday, a typical
monthly bill for an AT&AMP;T customer who makes no long-distance calls
would be cut in half. For a customer who made 10 minutes of
long-distance calls, total monthly charges would decrease 27
percent, to $6.87 from $9.39.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The order simplifies telephone bills by folding two separate
charges _ one for the cost of telephone lines and the other a
special access charge _ into one. It reduces an earlier announced
rate increase for the combined items by 66 cents a month.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the agreement, spelled out in the summary of
the order that will soon be issued by the commission, reduces by
$3.2 billion the access charges that long-distance companies like
AT&AMP;T and Sprint pay to local telephone companies like Bell Atlantic
to use their lines at the beginning and end of a call. The
reduction amounts to a cut of about 25 percent in access fees paid
to the local companies.
</P>
<P>
   Commission officials said they could not precisely quantify the
reduction for heavy users of long-distance services, and some
analysts and consumer groups said they doubted that many of the
savings would result in significantly lower bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that the FCC will monitor this process to ensure that
the $3.2 billion in long-distance company savings are translated
into demonstrable price reductions for consumers,'' said Gene
Kimmelman, co-director of the Washington office of Consumers Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's decision is a clear benefit for people who make few or
no long-distance calls,'' he said. ``But it still leaves consumers
paying inflated monthly charges.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott C. Cleland, a telecommunications analyst at the Legg Mason
Precursor Group, said that experience had shown that the companies
had not passed on savings from reductions in access charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The companies have a fiduciary responsibility to their
shareholders to not necessarily pass them on,'' Cleland said. ``To
the extent that prices don't fall, these savings increase
long-distance profits. The companies may pass them on, but it will
be over time.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry executives said the decision was part of a trend that
will lead to long-distance fees' resembling the fees charged by
Internet companies and cell phone providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pricing structure that these rules permit allows us to
move more in the direction that will ultimately lead to Internet
pricing or wireless pricing in the long-distance market,'' said
John Nakahata, a former top official at the FCC and spokesman for
the coalition of telephone companies that signed the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the fee changes, local telephone companies stand
to get a short-term shortfall of as much as $500 million over the
next year. But industry executives and analysts said that lower
prices should increase demand more than enough to offset the
shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This industry is growing at a rapid rate, and we're all
realizing significant cost reductions,'' said Frank Gumper, vice
president for regulatory and long-range planning at Bell Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Traders on Wall Street shrugged off the announcement of the rate
changes. There was no uniform movement in the stock prices of
telephone companies, and changes were modest.
</P>
<P>
   In a partial dissent to Wednesday's order, a commissioner
accused the FCC staff of making improper side deals with the
telephone industry to gain its support for the order.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner, Harold Furchtgott-Roth, said that in exchange
for the industry's support, the staff had agreed to waive certain
onerous depreciation rules and rule favorably in a separate access
fee proceeding. Both proceedings involve billions of dollars for
the companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be clear, I do not believe that any employee of this agency
acted in bad faith'' Furchtgott-Roth wrote. ``But I cannot escape
the conclusion that the process by which this notice has been
promulgated falls short of certain fundamental principles that
govern the behavior of administrative agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Both industry lobbyists and staff officials denied that any
separate deals had been reached.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-00 2340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
