<HEADLINE>
WHY WASTE GREAT ONE ON HOCKEY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News  Service clients)  
 BY E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush and
U.S. drug czar Barry McCaffrey were in town Wednesday for what I
can only presume to be the obvious reason: meeting Wayne Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks now, Gretzky has been on the front page of the local
papers and on the TV news programs, always pre sented lovingly, as
if all of the report ers, politicians and businessmen in town were
auditioning to play Romeo to Wayne's Julietzky.
</P>
<P>
   Then, finally. it happened.
</P>
<P>
   The Great One (as he's known to hockey fans and TV anchors)
saved Phoenix and perhaps the world by agreeing to join in the
ownership of the Phoenix Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable. This is the best thing in the entire
world,'' Coyotes captain Keith Tkachuk said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wayne is just absolutely a fine, fine man,'' said Phoenix
developer Steve Ellman, who heads the group pur chasing the Coyotes
and redevelop ing Los Arcos Mall into a hockey arena. ``I hope
people understand the magnitude of what this means for all
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Like so many others in town, I didn't completely understand the
magni tude of the event, for which I am full of regretzky.
</P>
<P>
   I understand now.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes after Ellman an nounced that Gretzky would join
the Coyotes ownership team, Ellman be gan receiving $1 million
offers from potential investors.
</P>
<P>
   The organization has also seen a big boost in season-ticket
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Before you know it, the struggling Coyotes will be out of
debtzky.
</P>
<P>
   All because of Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   For this reason, I figure Bush jetted into Arizona to interview
Gretzky as a possible vice presidential candidate (figuring
Republicans in Congress _ except John McCain, of course _ will
overlook the rule prohibiting Canadi ans from holding office in the
United States, at least until the Great One draws more of those
million-dollar ``investors.'')
</P>
<P>
   As for McCaffrey, maybe he's trying to find out if Wayne would
be willing lend the magic of his name in support of our unending
war on narcotics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrible threatzky,'' McCaffrey might say.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for them, Gretzky's not here yet. He changed his
plans and won't be in town until Friday.
</P>
<P>
   By then, hopefully, Arizona Gov. Jane Hull will have convinced
Gretzky that his talents can serve higher purposes than
professional hockey or presiden tial politics.
</P>
<P>
   Education, for example, for which Ar izona consistently ranks at
the bottom of the funding list, causing local par ents to fretzky.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps Gretzky can solve the growing problem of illegal
immigra tion.
</P>
<P>
   Or advise the Legislature on how to spend the billions of
dollars in lawsuit settlement it's receiving from compa nies that
produce cigarettezkys.
</P>
<P>
   The health care crisis Arizona's chil dren face could certainly
use a Great One.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the drought? And the ensuing fires? Would Wayne
have ways to make us all wetzky?
</P>
<P>
   We'll make it worth his while. We'll feed him crepes suzettezky.
Sculpt a statuettezky. Do a pirouttezky. Even give him a
Corvettezky.
</P>
<P>
   He's worth it. You'll see on Friday, when he is mobbed by the
press and the temperature is 105, and for the Great One it's no
sweatzky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
