<HEADER>
A1457 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-WENDYS-SUSPECT-ART     05-31 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WENDYS-SUSPECT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIND OF A KILLER IS STILL A CLOSED BOOK
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT21 has being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For eight hours after his arrest last week, John
Taylor sat with investigators in a second-floor squad room at the
111th Precinct in northern Queens, unwinding the spool of his life,
from his childhood in a Brooklyn housing project to his role in the
execution-style slayings of five people in the basement of a
Wendy's in Flushing.
</P>
<P>
   In a voice devoid of emotion, Taylor detailed the killings,
explained how he had acquired the gun, a .380-caliber bought on the
streets, and traced his escape route home, cab by cab,
investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   But they said he never came close to answering the question that
hung in the interrogation room all night: how a 36-year-old man who
once displayed a devoted work ethic, a love for his children and an
engaging smile had evolved into someone capable of the carnage that
ended an armed robbery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke to a psychiatrist this afternoon, and even with all
the information we have, who can say?'' an investigator said.
``Maybe he thought there was an easier way than working.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as police and prosecutors amass what they characterize as
an overwhelming volume of evidence against Taylor and his
accomplice, Craig Godineaux, law enforcement officials acknowledge
that they have gained little insight into what motivated the
viciousness of the murders, aside from the pair's concession that
they had sought to eliminate all witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   John Taylor's previous crimes, one burglary and a few robberies
that the authorities say he admitted to, were brazen, but never
violent. The law-breaking began only a few years ago, after Taylor
had built a reputation as a dutiful manager who spent 14 years
working in the same McDonald's franchise in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators acknowledged that perhaps no amount of
psychological theorizing could ever make sense of what happened in
the Wendy's last week. But they said the involvement of Taylor, who
is thought to have planned the crime, is particularly baffling. By
all appearances, his crimes had been aberrations in an adult life
unaffected by mental illness, drug addiction or grudges.
</P>
<P>
   He filed his income taxes. He paid Social Security taxes for his
baby sitter. He took an accident prevention course last year
sponsored by the New York Department of Motor Vehicles. He was
known around his former home in Lefrak City as the sort of person
who took his four children, two boys and two girls, 5 to 13 years
old, to the video store to rent movies like ``The Big Green,'' a
family soccer story; and Jackie Chan's latest high-action thriller.
</P>
<P>
   ``John seemed like the kind of guy you would trust with your
kids,'' said Edward Wills, who supervised him for eight of the 14
years that Taylor worked as an assistant manager at a McDonald's in
Midtown. ``I don't think this is the same John.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who worked with Taylor in five restaurants said he had
grown sullen and withdrawn, with few friends. They said he became a
strict manager, intolerant of small mistakes, even as he was
accused several times of filching cash.
</P>
<P>
   But, as the Queens district attorney, Richard A. Brown, tries to
decide whether these killings warrant the death penalty, several
investigators said they were most struck by Taylor's chilling
ability to distance himself from the crime. On the day after the
killings, for example, he went to work at a clothing store, where
he was a salesman. That afternoon, he called a 26-year-old woman he
had begun courting.
</P>
<P>
   Although authorities have said that Taylor has confessed to
shooting one of the seven people shot that night, he has yet to
enter a formal plea. A trial to determine his guilt is months away.
</P>
<P>
   John Benjamin Taylor, who often uses the nickname Benji, was
born March 10, 1964, the first of four children of John and Audrey
Taylor. He, his younger brother, Vaughn, and two sisters were
raised in an apartment in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   His parents, who divorced in 1993 after being separated for at
least 10 years, declined to be interviewed for this article, as did
Taylor's lawyer, John Youngblood.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's mother, who now uses her birth name, Audrey Saddler,
had recognized the Wendy's on the news as the place where her son
had worked, said Roy Earl, her boyfriend. Within hours, she was
confronted by detectives seeking to question Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   After his arrest, Taylor spent hours talking to Detectives Louis
Pia, Brian Quinn and Elizabeth Curcio. By his own account, Taylor
has always been closer to his father. He moved from his mother's
apartment in Brooklyn to his father's apartment in Queens in 1982
after graduating from East New York Vocational High School.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor told detectives that the move was prompted by an argument
with his mother, who feared he was involved in gang activity and
might lure his younger brother into trouble. But residents recalled
that, during an era when gang violence in the projects was growing,
John Taylor was routinely seen walking off to work in the uniform
of a fast-food worker.
</P>
<P>
   For years, John Taylor seemed to be the more stable of the two
brothers. While John was working as an assistant manager at a
McDonald's in Manhattan, his brother, Vaughn, was being arrested
for minor crimes in Suffolk County, where he lived.
</P>
<P>
   John Taylor's relationship with both of his parents has
deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, when he left jail after his arrest on a robbery
charge, Taylor filed a complaint with the police, accusing his
father of stealing the furniture from his Lefrak City apartment.
</P>
<P>
   In the fast-food industry, in which workers often change jobs
frequently, Taylor was a study in permanence, commuting daily for
years from Queens to his job as an assistant manager at a
McDonald's in midtown Manhattan. He was punctual and polite, and
several friends recalled that he talked often of owning his own
store.
</P>
<P>
   But something seemed to change in 1996. There were whispers
among co-workers that Taylor had placed ghost employees on the
payroll. He was transferred to another location, although Wills
said the only problem had been that Taylor's performance had
slumped a bit and he wanted to give him a new challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Several months later, Taylor was discovered at the back at the
midtown store at 6 a.m., trying to break into the safe. Taylor, who
said he needed the money for his children, was sentenced to five
years' probation. It was his first offense.
</P>
<P>
   By 1998, he was working as an assistant manager at the Wendy's
in Flushing. Some former employees said he was pleasant, but
authorities said he was caught stealing in May 1999 and transferred
to another Wendy's for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the police say they believe that Taylor, armed
with a starter's pistol, embarked on a spree in which he robbed or
tried to rob five restaurants in Queens, beginning with a Burger
King. In that incident, on June 15, a supervisor went for the phone
to call police and the robber ran off.
</P>
<P>
   Eight days later, Taylor was arrested, the police said, after he
robbed a McDonald's for the second time in four days. He was held
until August, when he posted $3,500 bail and returned home to
Lefrak City to find that his apartment had been emptied of
furniture, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said he still had a job, however, as a manager at a
Wendy's in Elmhurst. One neighbor, George Gross, said Taylor helped
his daughter get a job at the same store, but she soon found him
unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   ``She never complained about anybody the way she complained
about him,'' he said. ``She just said: `He's not right. He is too
serious.'''
</P>
<P>
   Last October, within a few weeks, Taylor was evicted from his
apartment and was fired from his job, the authorities said. At the
same time, out on bail in his robbery case, in which prosecutors
were pushing for a 12-year prison sentence, he failed to show up
for court.
</P>
<P>
   He then hid in plain sight, taking a room at $85 a week in a
private house in Jamaica, only three miles from Queens Supreme
Court, where a warrant had been issued for his re-arrest.
</P>
<P>
   He found work a few blocks away, first at a leather goods store
and later as a salesman at SC&AMP;R Clothing, Taylor told detectives.
He and Godineaux were both working at the store last week when, the
police say, they robbed Wendy's of $2,400 and left seven people for
dead in the basement.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Thursday, Taylor showed up for work, leaving at
7:30 p.m. to watch the Knicks game.
</P>
<P>
   The following morning, according to Taylor's statement to
police, he heard his name on television as a suspect in the
killings, and he decided to flee.
</P>
<P>
   But first, in an unusual move, he called in sick at the clothing
store, said the owner, Anna Biton. She said he told her his father
had died and he had to bury him in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   He then went to the home of his brother's wife in Brentwood,
N.Y., where he was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   On the way back to Queens, Taylor began telling the first of
several accounts of the killings, a law enforcement official
recalled. It was a story full of facts, but one that shed little
light on how Taylor had come to participate in such violence, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Another investigator said he could not imagine any account that
would adequately explain the killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could think and understand how someone could do something
like that,'' he said, ``then it's time to quit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
