<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-OAKLAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONE FALTERS AS YANKS LOSE TO ATHLETICS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Cone's right hand was locked on his hip, his
eyes were focused on the grass and his mind was probably on what he
could do to emerge from this predicament. It was only the first
inning and the New York Yankees merely trailed the Oakland
Athletics by three runs, but Cone already looked deflated.
</P>
<P>
   The body language of slumped shoulders, frustrated expressions
and deep exhales told as much of a story about Cone as the numbers
dotting the scoreboard. It was an awful evening for Cone, who knew
that he did not have an effective repertory of pitches and quickly
discovered that he could not trick the Oakland batters either.
</P>
<P>
   Long after he was gone, the Yankees had stumbled to an 8-7 loss
at Yankee Stadium that left Cone with a 1-5 record after the
season's first two months.
</P>
<P>
   Cone was gone by the fourth inning, battered and bruised because
he could not summon a decent fastball, a decent slider or a decent
anything. The 37-year-old pitcher allowed six earned runs on six
hits and four walks in 3 1/3 innings, and he jogged to the dugout
amid cheers and boos. He had a look of resignation across his
reddened face. The Yankees were mystified.
</P>
<P>
   ``He leaves nothing in the bag,'' said manager Joe Torre, before
the game. ``He bares his soul. I don't want to say anyone wants to
win more for him. But they know what he's going through. They feel
that responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone said: ``I just didn't have it. I have no excuses. It was
just a poor effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Posada, the Yankee catcher, said: ``He couldn't throw a
strike. He was angry with himself. You could see a little
frustration. He tried everything. Today, it didn't work out.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The panic button is never too far in George Steinbrenner's
world, even if the two-time defending World Series champions have a
winning record. But the Yankees have now lost four of their last
six games and they are about to begin a treacherous stretch in
which they will play seven straight series against teams with
winning records, starting with the Braves Friday night in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the Yankees are aggressively pursuing someone to
help improve their underachieving offense. They have had
discussions with the Houston Astros about Moises Alou and they are
still talking to the Cincinnati Reds about a trade that would
involve Dmitri Young and Ramiro Mendoza.
</P>
<P>
   The more the Yankees falter, the more anxious Steinbrenner will
get to make a change, although Rickey Ledee, the owner's scapegoat,
helped the Yankees climb back into Wednesday night's game twice
with a three-run homer and a run-scoring double.
</P>
<P>
   Cone needs to make some changes soon. With two out in the first,
he gave up a single and a walk and then Matt Stairs lined a
three-run homer into the first row of seats in right field. Eric
Chavez walked and scored in the second, but Chuck Knoblauch's
three-run homer off Gil Heredia made it 4-3 after two.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cone labored. He walked two more in the third and was
fortunate to emerge unscathed, but he could not pull off another
Houdini act in the fourth. Chavez bashed a homer to put the A's
ahead, 5-3, and, after two more hard singles, Torre burst out of
the dugout to end the fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   Both runners scored off Allan Watson, the first on a sacrifice
fly and the second on Posada's throwing error, to increase
Oakland's lead to 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   After Ledee's homer cut the deficit to 7-6, the Yankees botched
a chance to tie the score when Scott Brosius was caught stealing. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
