<HEADLINE>
NASCAR DRIVERS STRUGGLE WITH TIME CRUNCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Total access, or a reasonable facsimile thereof, has helped
transform most NASCAR Winston Cup drivers into household names, and
the series into a runaway success.
</P>
<P>
   But Cup drivers are finding it increasingly difficult to balance
what they need to get accomplished on the racetrack with the
never-ending demands being placed upon them by fans, sponsors and
the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a Winston Cup driver, you sell your privacy forever.
It's gone. That's it,'' said Mark Martin, 41, a perennial
championship contender and therefore, a garage-area celebrity. ``I
sold it \Rhis privacy\S down the river, you know, to do this. I
didn't know it when I did it, but I knew after I did it. And it
will not ever, ever be the same again.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the once-simple courtesy of signing an autograph can become
a chore, Martin said, who recalled the days before his NASCAR
career when he raced before perhaps 3,000 people in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we have 3,000 people in the garage,'' said Martin, driver
of the No. 6 Valvoline Ford Taurus and ace of Jack Roush's five-car
stable. ``Times have changed, racing has changed and we can't
service everybody that wants what they want. And so, that's
frustrating for the fans and that's frustrating for the drivers,
because no matter what we do, we can't do enough. And it's not that
we don't want to, it's that you can't.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got 30 seconds and you've got 100 people standing
there, what do you do? Do you do one? Do you do 10? Or do you just
do none? I mean, you don't have a good choice left in situations
like that. I don't know what to do. Sometimes, I just do the kids.
Sometimes I can't even do that. Sometimes I do the kids and the
parents swear at me. You can't win. It's physically impossible for
us to do the exact right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin said there are nights he goes to bed sick to his stomach
_ or just plain mad _ because he was unable to fulfill everyone's
request for his signature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I go to bed brokenhearted,'' Martin said, ``because
I think it wouldn't have taken that much more out of my time to
have done that, and that would have touched their lives forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best driver never to have won a Cup championship,
Martin noted that his 7-year-old son, Matt, is a budding racer who
could compete in NASCAR some day.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son already signs autographs, you know,'' said Martin,
whose youngster is in his second season of racing in Florida. ``I
tell him all the time, `You've got to be nice to the fans. You've
got to realize that the fans are what makes this sport go round.' I
work on him regularly.''
\Nsubheds:PIT STOPS On the Juan watch
</P>
<P>
   Where's Juan?
</P>
<P>
   When last sighted, reigning Indianapolis 500 champion Juan
Montoya was throwing a baseball over the backstop at Yankee Stadium
on Tuesday night. Another Mariano Rivera, he's not.
</P>
<P>
   And don't look for Montoya and his Target/Chip Ganassi Racing
team to try to reprise their effort at the Indianapolis Motor
Speedway during the Casino Magic 500 night race at Texas Motor
Speedway on June 10.
</P>
<P>
   Entering a second Indy Racing League event this season never was
part of car owner Ganassi's game plan, team spokeswoman Jana
Griffith said yesterday. Budweiser gave Ganassi $3 million in
additional sponsorship budget to run Indy, an amount that
reportedly doubled if either Montoya or teammate Jimmy Vasser won.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya, reigning Championship Auto Racing Teams FedEx Series
champion, is scheduled to make a promotional appearance at
Ganassi's Chicago Motor Speedway on June 10. CART's Target Grand
Prix is scheduled there on July 30.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Gossage, executive vice president and general manager of
TMS, said he left a congratulatory message on Ganassi's cellphone
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reminded him the door is open \Rat TMS\S,'' said Gossage,
who since 1997 has built promotion of this race around the new Indy
500 champion. ``To me, it's the cars and stars of the Indy 500
coming. I thought Juan Montoya was absolutely unbelievable on
Sunday. I said going in they're the favorite _ best driver, best
crew, best resources, best owner in the business. No surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real question is, since he's never run on a high-speed,
high-banked oval of this nature ... could he do it here? And I
think not, to be perfectly honest. But it's like any IRL race, the
Indy 500 included. The door is wide open for them to run here.''
\Nsubheds:Road-course plans ready Construction on the permanent
road course in the infield of Texas Motor Speedway is scheduled to
begin June 12, the Monday after the IRL race in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Gossage, TMS executive vice president and general manager,
said IRL driver Davey Hamilton, American Le Mans Series regular
David Brabham and three-time Indy 500 champion Johnny Rutherford of
Fort Worth contributed to the design of an infield layout measuring
1.17 miles and featuring six turns. All but approximately 160 feet
of the 1.5-mile quadoval also have been incorporated into the
design, which will make the total approximate length at 2.6 miles.
</P>
<P>
   The course will be used for the first time on Labor Day weekend,
when the ALMS and BFGoodrich Trans-Am Series compete in the
inaugural Grand Prix of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're also very close to landing a top-notch
internationally known driving school for better than 100 days a
year on the road course,'' Gossage said. ``That's pretty strong.''
\Nsubheds:The last word ``He didn't build it because he loved us.
He just got some free concrete.''
</P>
<P>
   _ NHRA Funny Car champion John Force, on Billy Meyer's decision
to make the Texas Motorplex quarter-mile all-concrete.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
